<HEADLINE>
HOT PATRIOTS STEAM THROUGH ARIZONA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Their charter flight arrived here five hours
later than expected Saturday because of mechanical problems. Then
they had to play in 90-degree-plus heat, many, many miles from
their home turf.
</P>
<P>
   Those could have been easy excuses, but instead the Patriots
took it out on the Cardinals Sunday, 27-3, and head into their off
week at 6-2. Drew Bledsoe threw for four touchdowns and helped the
offense gain 386 yards, while the defense held an Arizona attack
led by backup quarterback Dave Brown to 166 total yards.
</P>
<P>
   When the Patriots return to action they'll host the New York
Jets, now 1-6, and the Tuna, Bill Parcells. Another overmatched
foe?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to be able to stand on the sideline in the fourth
quarter and chew the fat with Drew more often,'' offensive lineman
Bruce Armstrong said with a smile. ``We got those early points up
there, and that's what we can do when we have some things clicking
in our favor. That's what we should do. It's a good feeling to have
a game like this where we go out in front and then we hold on and
win. But now we have to take the next week to get healthy and then
come out with the same attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe's four-TD game was his second of the season and the
eighth of his career. Two of the scores went to Shawn Jefferson,
helping build a 20-0 halftime lead. Jefferson's 64-yard
catch-and-run was the longest touchdown reception of his career.
His other was a 36-yard over-the-shoulder catch in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shawn's a great receiver, and it was great just to be able to
get him the football,'' said Bledsoe, who got to take a
late-fourth-quarter breather in favor of John Friesz. ``He's a guy
I really appreciate out there and I'd love to spend the rest of my
career throwing it to him. We haven't got him the ball lately, but
today I was able to see him open and we were able to connect.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight week, Bledsoe threw it only 22 times,
completing 14 passes for 276 yards and no interceptions. The
Patriots ran the ball even more than they did in last week's win
over Denver, rushing a season-high 43 times for 142 yards (3.3-yard
average). Terry Allen carried 21 times for 88 yards (4.2), and
Kevin Faulk chipped in with 17 carries for 42 yards (2.5).
</P>
<P>
   The defense got a lot of pressure on Brown, sacking him three
times and intercepting him twice (Ty Law and Kato Serwanga). The
Patriots held the Cardinals to eight first downs, 76 yards rushing,
and only 3-for-16 success on third-down conversions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went out there and wanted to go right at them with our
defense and make something happen,'' said Chris Slade, who had five
tackles, one sack, and a pass defensed. ``It's great to be 6-2, but
we have to keep going with this. We can't let up.''
</P>
<P>
   Running backs had only 37 of the team's 150 receptions before
Sunday, but Bledsoe went to them early. On the Patriots' first
scoring drive, their second offensive possession of the game,
Bledsoe threw down the left sideline on a 38-yard toss to Allen,
then found an uncovered Lamont Warren for a 3-yard pass in the
right corner of the end zone with 8:56 remaining in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots added to their lead with another score with 1:13
remaining in the quarter. Bledsoe took a three-step drop and fired
a quick slant over the middle to Jefferson, who put a fake on free
safety Kwamie Lassiter at the 35. Jefferson ran it in the rest of
the way to complete a 64-yard hookup, and it was a 14-0 game after
Adam Vinatieri's extra point.
</P>
<P>
   With Arizona using a makeshift offensive line, the situation was
ripe for the Patriots to make a big play or two defensively, too.
The first came early in the second quarter when Brown dropped back
for what was supposed to be a dump pass to a back. But the ball was
tipped at the line of scrimmage by Ferric Collons into the arms of
Law at the 45.
</P>
<P>
   Law fumbled at the 50, where Chris Carter jumped on the loose
ball. But the offense went three and out when defensive end Simeon
Rice sacked Bledsoe, who held the ball too long, for a 1-yard loss.
Rice sacked Bledsoe twice on the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe's protection began to erode midway through the quarter,
getting him so frustrated that he stormed off the field after being
sacked by Rashod Swinger on third and 5 from the 40. Bledsoe was
irate as he went to the sideline, and teammates had to settle him
down.
</P>
<P>
   But things were better on the next series, when Bledsoe
engineered a six-play, 61-yard drive that featured a 19-yard
sideline pass to Vincent Brisby, followed by a 35-yard touchdown
pass to Jefferson. That came on a post route down the middle on
which Jefferson outran strong safety Tommy Bennett, making it 20-0
with 4:45 remaining. Vinatieri's extra point attempt was blocked,
ending a string of 117 straight successes.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, who have made second-half adjustments well this
season, had to protect a 20-0 halftime lead. And it didn't appear
they were quite ready to do that at the start of the second half,
as Adrian Murrell went for 31 yards and Brown completed a 22-yard
pass to David Boston to get Arizona's first drive going.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots finally stiffened near the goal line, stuffing
three straight runs and forcing a fourth down. Brown tried to draw
the Patriots offside with his cadence, but the defense didn't bite.
Brown called a timeout and returned to more confusion, when his
offensive line drew an illegal motion call that forced Arizona to
go to Chris Jacke to kick a 24-yard field goal, making it 20-3.
</P>
<P>
   The nail in the coffin came with 14:20 remaining when Bledsoe
flung it downfield to a wide-open Terry Glenn for a 36-yard
touchdown pass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
