<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITCHCOCK, SELZNICK HOLLYWOOD ODD COUPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Michael Epstein told people he wanted to make a dual
biography of Alfred Hitchcock and David O. Selznick, everyone
recognized, of course, the former.
</P>
<P>
   And the latter?
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of blank stares,'' Epstein said from his home
in Brooklyn. ``But when I said he was the producer of ``Gone With
the Wind'' _ `Oh, sure, I know who he is!' All of a sudden, it kind
of came back.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, Selznick is spinning in his grave. And Hitchcock is
chuckling.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Masters: Hitchcock, Selznick and the End of''
``Hollywood'' brilliantly captures the complicated relationship
between the two men _ a relationship that produced such classics as
``Notorious'' and ``Rebecca'' _ and how that relationship came to
symbolize the destruction of the Hollywood studio system. The
90-minute film uses key footage from both men's movies, as well as
interviews with those who knew and worked with them, to chronicle
the rise of the director's role in Hollywood _ at the expense of
the omnipotent producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was sort of, in one man, I thought, a pretty close
representation of the studio system where the producer is king,''
Epstein, the executive producer of the film, said of Selznick.
``Everyone is under a seven-year contract and they kind of are
horse-traded like cattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitchcock comes to represent an entirely new era. He is in
many ways the first director who is also a celebrity. . . . As
successful as somebody like Billy Wilder or Howard Hawks was,
(movie fans) would have no clue who he is. But Hitchcock was
different.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't start out that way. Hitchcock made a name for himself
in England, but yearned to come to America. In 1939, Selznick
signed him and brought him over. Sixty years later, Hitchcock is
far more famous, but not then.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, when Hitchcock first came over, David Selznick was
much, much more of a name, and in a lot of ways much more of a
celebrity,'' Epstein said. ``And I think probably, truth be told,
more of a filmmaker, at that moment. At least as Hollywood
perceived filmmakers.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the Hollywood of interchangeable directors, directors
hired simply to carry out the technical details of the producer's
vision. Selznick was busy whipping the cast and crew of ``Gone With
the Wind'' into the shape of that vision and _ perhaps
unfortunately _ it paid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gone With the Wind'' was a legendary triumph, both critically
and commercially. Selznick took home the Oscar for Best Picture;
the success validated his megalomaniacal methods of moviemaking.
</P>
<P>
   He tapped Hitchcock to direct his next feature, ``Rebecca.''
Sparks flew from the start.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble stemmed from the two men's vastly different methods
of making a movie. Selznick liked for directors to shoot everything
_ all the angles, all the scenes, all the takes, everything _ and
then he would piece together the movie he wanted in the editing
room.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock worked a little differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father literally cut the picture before he shot it,''
Hitchcock's daughter, Pat, said from her California home. ``By the
time he got on the set, he knew exactly what that picture was going
to look like.'' That meant shooting only what was needed, nothing
more _ a method Selznick rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Selznick was far more powerful at the time, and his vision won
out _ literally. ``Rebecca'' won the Oscar for Best Picture, the
only time a producer has won in consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
   (Hitchcock didn't go without small victories. Epstein told the
story, which didn't make it into his film, of Hitchcock discovering
that one of the secretaries on the set was a Selznick spy. He
figured out who, and from then on ``only uses the foulest
language'' around her until she broke down and quit.)
</P>
<P>
   But it was the beginning of the end for Selznick. The pressure
of competing with ``Gone With the Win''d's success built until he
stopped making movies; instead, he packaged projects and sold them
to other studios. He lost millions gambling. But he rebounded a bit
after undergoing successful psychotherapy, which he loved because
the visits were like story sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an egotist's dream,'' David Thomson, a Selznick
biographer, says in the film.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock, meanwhile, was lent to other studios and began
building a reputation and power. When the time came to make
``Notorious,'' he was on more equal ground.
</P>
<P>
   Selznick's name is nowhere to be found on that movie, but it is
their greatest work together. (In an effort to raise money for his
own rather notorious movie, the ill-fated ``Duel In the Sun,''
Selznick sold ``Notorious'' to another studio, allowing Hitchcock
to produce and direct.)
</P>
<P>
   Selznick came up with many of the most successful parts of the
film, including the party scene. And he instructed Hitchcock and
writer Ben Hecht to rework the ending _ originally, they killed off
Cary Grant's character; in another rewrite they did the same to
Ingrid Bergman's. Selznick wouldn't stand for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's, to me, real collaboration,'' said Epstein, who calls
``Notorious'' ``a nearly perfect movie.'' He added, ``But that's
not being a creator.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in life, as Selznick floundered and Hitchcock flourished,
the two men were more civil toward one another. In fact, Pat
Hitchcock claims, the two men got along fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't as bad as everyone is trying to make out now,'' she
said, ``because now it's a big story. . . . They both had respect
for each other, and that was the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Epstein contends it was much more of a struggle. Whatever the
case, while making his film Epstein found what he thinks of as a
classic Hitchcock joke, which he discovered while studying the
killer Raymond Burr plays in ``Rear Window.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got his white hair and he's got his thick glasses and
he's chain-smoking all the time and he's a little overweight,''
Epstein said. ``I'd been looking at all these Selznick pictures and
it just hit me _ this is David Selznick!''
</P>
<P>
   Not officially, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could never confirm that it was done on purpose,'' Epstein
said, ``but, at least in my mind, it strikes me as perfect
Hitchcock. That, in a lot of ways, is the essence of his humor and
the essence of his personality.''
</P>
<P>
   And the essence of a relationship that helped change Hollywood
forever. &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8974, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
