</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS HEADED IN RIGHT DIRECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ The Patriots played a home game in Tempe Sunday,
which is what happens sometimes when you're on your way to
controlling your destiny and your opponent is on its way to
oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the directions the New England Patriots and Arizona
Cardinals seem headed today as the season approaches its midpoint,
and much of that feeling stemmed from Sunday's 27-3 thrashing of
the Cardinals at Sun Devil Stadium, a win that sent New England
gliding to its off week with a 6-2 record and a new address:
</P>
<P>
   New England Patriots
</P>
<P>
   Catbird's Seat
</P>
<P>
   Foxboro, MA 02035
</P>
<P>
   This address was reflected in many ways, not the least of which
was that a third of the 55,830 people on hand were wearing Patriot
jerseys and cheering every move New England made. Those brave,
sweltering, pale-skinned refugees from the East Coast had much to
cheer about, including a four-touchdown passing day from Drew
Bledsoe, explosive receiving games from Shawn Jefferson and Terry
Glenn, another solid rushing effort out of Terry Allen, and a
defense that limited Arizona to 2.7 yards per offensive play.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say the Patriots are without problems this
morning, but as they survey the AFC East from near the top of the
divisional ladder, what they see is the best a team can hope for at
this point in a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our own destiny in our hands,'' said six-time Pro Bowl
tackle Bruce Armstrong, who spent many years not only not in that
position but on teams that by now had their destiny decided. ``Even
the Super Bowl year we had to have things happen for us. We needed
to get streaky and have other people get beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time we're 6-2. We could have been 8-0, but we could have
been 3-5, too, so I'll be happy with this. It's been years since
this team was 6-2.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it has. Nineteen, to be exact. Not since Ron Erhardt's
1980 squad have the Patriots rushed off to such a fast start. What
it means is that they not only control their own destiny but will
come off their week of rest with a chance to knock their
competition out in a three-week stretch in which all their
opponents will be playing with lineups weakened by significant
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   While New England has some minor injury problems at linebacker,
its problems pale in comparison to the Jets and Dolphins, who are
both without their starting quarterbacks and hence are struggling
to keep their heads above water. New York's season was finished
long ago, and when New England comes back off vacation it will be a
well-rested team hosting a battered one in the Jets. Difficult as
Bill Parcells always seems to make it on his old team, this is the
perfect scenario for the Patriots to begin a critical stretch of
games.
</P>
<P>
   Following the Jets, the Patriots travel to Miami to try and
avenge the stunning 31-30 loss backup quarterback Damon Huard put
on them, but the Huard they will face is not the same one who so
boggled New England's minds in his debut for the injured Dan
Marino. Huard has struggled since that game and although his team
won again Sunday and is 6-1, there is little chance Marino will be
back by then, and even if he is he will not be the real Marino.
</P>
<P>
   Huard is beginning to suffer as all untested quarterbacks do,
and so is his team's offense. Marino may no longer be the remedy
for that because he is now a 38-year-old shadow, a quarterback not
aging gracefully who survives more by his wits and his defense than
by what his once marvelous arm could do. Miami can win with either
of them because of its defense, but it is a struggle now and will
be Nov. 21, as well.
</P>
<P>
   After that trip to Florida comes one to Buffalo, where the Bills
will be dangerous. But they also likely still will be without their
best receiver, Eric Moulds, who is out 4-6 weeks with an injury.
Without Moulds's deep threat, Buffalo's offense has struggled,
allowing defenses to put more pressure on Doug Flutie. What has
resulted is eight interceptions in Flutie's last three games, and
an offense bogged down without much of a running game all season
now finds itself without much of a passing one either.
</P>
<P>
   There is a chance Moulds could be back by Nov. 28, but this
seems to be a season so far in which things are breaking right for
the Patriots, so don't count on it. Sunday was a case in point.
When the season began, this appeared to be a difficult game played
in high heat far from home against a team with a hot young
quarterback and a predatory defense.
</P>
<P>
   But by the opening kickoff, the Cardinals came into this fiasco
without quarterback Jake Plummer, their best offensive weapon even
on his bad days, and with a revamped offensive line in which the
only player in the same position as when the season began was
center Aaron Graham. This allowed New England's defense to harass
backup quarterback Dave Brown into submission and stuff the
Cardinals' running game by attacking the new faces at the line of
scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   It has been like that since the start of what thus far has been
a dream season that comes only one year removed from a nightmare.
Where last year they were the walking wounded, this season New
England is walking on air.
</P>
<P>
   Eight minutes into the new year and Vinny Testaverde is lost for
the season without even being hit. Patriots win. Jets die.
</P>
<P>
   The young Colts are improved, but by Week 2 their rebuilt
defense has not yet learned everyone's name, let alone how to play
together. New England rallies. Colts lose.
</P>
<P>
   Then came two gimme putts from the Giants and Browns before the
Patriots' only two losses, games decided, like most in the NFL this
year, by 2 points or fewer. Normally that two-game losing streak
could have turned into a disaster with the arrival of Denver the
following Sunday. New England had not beaten the Broncos since the
Johnson Administration _ Andrew Johnson _ and there would have been
panic in the air and blood on the water under normal circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   But little has been normal about this NFL season, and the
Broncos who limped into Foxborough a week ago came with two
straight Super Bowl championships but without John Elway, Terrell
Davis, and Shannon Sharpe. In other words, they came without their
offense, and New England survived _ barely _ thus setting the stage
for a high-octane start to a potentially high-hopes season.
</P>
<P>
   This still all could end in desperation, disaster, or another
mad scramble to the playoffs of course, but this time it should
not. Not after a first half that could not have gone much better
for the Patriots in terms of their record, their health, and the
battered nature of their chief rivals in the AFC East.
</P>
<P>
   They open the second half of their playoff run with four
division games in five weeks and would seem to have clear
advantages in the first three if all things remain intact _
including the limbs of the New England players. If they do, it will
be up to the Patriots where they end up, just as it was up to them
Sunday how big a victory margin they would post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along if we have our key guys _ and that starts
with the quarterback and the receivers _ we can play with anybody
in this league,'' Armstrong said. ``Today we have them, and they're
still healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   With half a season gone, so are the hopes of his team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
