<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALLAS BOOSTS GRAHAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Rob Tallas knows exactly how John Grahame is feeling
right now. In his first year with the Bruins in 1994-95, Tallas
came into training camp with no contract and dazzled management
enough to win one. He spent that year mostly in Charlotte, in the
East Coast League, and played two games in Providence.
</P>
<P>
   For the next three years, Tallas split his time between
Providence and Boston. Whenever there was a decision about who
would be demoted as the Bruins brought in a cast of goaltender
candidates, Tallas was odd-man out.
</P>
<P>
   This season, though, Tallas will be in Boston to play his second
full season in the NHL, behind Byron Dafoe, and Grahame, despite
how well he's performed, will head down to Providence.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a player, you never want to be put in that situation,''
said Tallas. ``He's done everything in his power to show that he
can play and that's all you can ask from a guy like that.''
</P>
<P>
   It is ironic that Grahame earned his first NHL shutout Saturday
night in a 3-0 victory over the Buffalo Sabres and now faces
demotion as the victim of a numbers game _ Tallas would have to
clear waivers to be sent down and it's obvious some other team
would grab him. With two new teams coming into the league next
June, the Bruins can't afford not to retain Tallas, who is likely
to be exposed for the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he handled himself awesome (Saturday night),''
Tallas said about Grahame. ``There was a lot of pressure in the
game with the Byron situation. He's a calm and relaxed guy. He
needs to know that he did everything right. If that's the case
(that he is demoted), everyone here will pat him on the back and
he'll be back here in no time. He's got a bright future.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallas said there were several times early in his career when he
felt he deserved better. However, because of contractual situations
or waiver considerations, he wasn't always given a reward
commensurate with his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember three years ago, it was the same thing when Jim
Carey was here,'' said Tallas. ``I felt I had a great training
camp. I think I won every game. But the numbers really didn't
reflect on the situation and I had to go down and work hard. I'll
talk to John; he's a good guy and he has a positive attitude. It's
hard not to look at it as a step back and you're definitely going
to go down there and be frustrated for a little while, and
rightfully so. Everything he's done up here has been positive since
Day One of training camp.''
</P>
<P>
   As sympathetic as he is, though, Tallas believes he's earned his
stripes. He admits to being insecure while coach Pat Burns was
rotating netminders until Dafoe was signed. Rather than sit out a
few games because of painful injuries (a bad ankle against Los
Angeles and Anaheim, a bad thumb and shoulder against Tampa Bay),
Tallas played because he didn't want to lose his spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to miss games,'' he said. ``That was the biggest
thing. A couple of games, maybe I shouldn't have played. I just
thought I had to play no matter what. I wanted to go out there and
prove to Pat and everybody that my heart is as big as it always has
been. I try to go out there every night and play with every amount
of emotion that I can and I wanted to show that. And I'll do that
at any time of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallas didn't bother to fill in Burns with the details of his
ailments. The goalie said when Burns asked if he could play, he
wanted a one-word answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think (Burns) really knew (the extent of the
injuries),'' Tallas said. ``Every time he asked me, I looked him in
the eye and said, `I'm playing.' I think maybe he didn't want to
know. It was a yes-or-no question and I was giving him `yes' all
the time. I think once he talked to the trainers and realized I had
to go in and get a (cortisone) shot that it was a little bit more
sore. Pat is an old-school guy. He likes guys who will fight
through the weather. I didn't want to take myself out of the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Dafoe earned the bulk of the workload, and with the
Bruins fighting for a playoff spot, Tallas was on the sidelines
more than he would've liked. When he did get a chance to play, it
was usually in a rough situation with the Bruins playing their
third game in four nights or facing a team that had been sitting
home waiting while the Bruins were wrapping up a long road trip.
Such is the lot of the backup goalie, but Tallas has the mentality
for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always looked at the positive in every situation,'' he
said. ``I think at Christmas (last year), I might have had five
games. There are still two more months to go and I have a game in
hand. I got off to an early start and got some games right away and
there will be games coming up and that's healthy for me. I think
one thing that helps, too, is the relationship me and Byron have.
Up to now, we've been rotating, but at this level, we do need a No.
1 goalie and you do need a backup. It's hard to do a rotation
system.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears the rotation is over. It's likely Dafoe will make his
season debut against New Jersey Thursday, or against Atlanta
Saturday at the latest, which means Grahame will be toiling in
Providence by then.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough time,'' said Tallas. ``But he's 24 years old.
Next year, who knows what is going to happen with expansion, and
there's still a lot of season left here. It's tough but he
definitely has to deal with it. He's done a great job. I can't find
the words to cheer someone up in that situation. I know tears will
be shed, absolutely; it's an emotional sport. But rightly so, he's
done everything he could do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
