<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COATES: CLOUD ON HORIZON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Ben Coates Sunday did not have a reception for
the second game this season and was irate afterward, charging he's
been excluded from the game plan and saying he wants out if he
doesn't receive a bigger role.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing I can do about it except try to get the hell
out of here,'' Coates said after the Patriots' 27-3 win over the
Arizona Cardinals at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's this, the second or third game where I haven't caught a
(expletive) ball?'' Coates said as he packed his bags for the trip
home. ``There's nothing to talk about. If this is the way they want
it, what's there to say? Just release me. Be my guest. Do whatever
you want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Coates has not caught as many passes since Ernie Zampese took
over as offensive coordinator two years ago. Once a favorite target
of Drew Bledsoe, having caught 45 touchdown passes from the
quarterback since 1993, Coates said, ``It's definitely changed.
(Zampese) wants to do things his way, and the tight end isn't that
important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be a decoy and run around and allow everyone
else to get open. All I do is block. They can get anybody to block.
Anybody. I have a lot of football left. I haven't slowed down any.
What it is is I just can't do it here anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Coates's anger had been building for some time. After averaging
4.1 catches per game in 1997 and 4.7 in 1998, he is averaging 2
this season. Sunday he had just two balls thrown to him, both into
double coverage. By the end of the game, with the score so
lopsided, Coates was on the bench and Rod Rutledge in the game.
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation Coates has been bothered by a sore
left knee and ankle, which were further tweaked when they were
twisted by linebacker Bill Romanowski in a 24-23 win over Denver
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fine,'' he said. ``My health has been as good as it's been
in a long time. That's (expletive). I'm sick of what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Coates said he was going to fly home to North Carolina during
the three-day break the Patriots earned with the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``And maybe I won't come back,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
