<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON READY FOR FUN-AND-GUN CELTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. _ There are fewer than 48 hours left before the
start of the NBA season. The roster is set. Training camp's over.
Ditto the exhibition season. What else can the Celtics do to
prepare, to make certain they advance to the playoffs for the first
time since 1995?
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Anderson said Sunday the key word is mindset.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to keep this game of basketball . . . something I
enjoy,'' said the starting point guard, ``because all the other
off-court (stuff), and all life has a lot of (expletive) involved
in it. When I come here and I play, this has to be my outlet. This
has to be something I enjoy.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said he worked with a trainer during the offseason and
is as healthy as he's been since he signed with Portland in 1996.
He said he will attempt to make this year one in which
off-the-court problems don't interfere with winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a good group of guys here. All in all, it's a
positive thing,'' he said. ``We just want to win now.''
</P>
<P>
   Such talk should be music to the ears of third-year coach Rick
Pitino, who guided a team that had gone 15-67 in 1996-97, its worst
record ever, to a 36-46 mark in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted much enthusiasm entering last year, but the
Celtics were a disappointing 19-31 in a strike-shortened campaign,
and among the issues the team faced was a questionable chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot my first year. I didn't learn anything last
year,'' said Pitino, whose team opens its season Tuesday at
Toronto. ``I didn't enjoy it. I didn't learn anything. In fact, it
was not a pleasant year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this year, what we will learn more than anything else is
that our chemistry has to be great in order for us to, as a young
team, try and make the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   During the offseason, former Celtics have come to the aid of the
franchise. Bill Russell worked with the team on establishing a
winning mindset. Dave Cowens was at practice Sunday working with
post players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russell, I wish I had around every second, to get inside the
players' heads,'' said Pitino.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russell constantly gets them to think of the team, winning
ahead of losing, passing over shooting, rebounding over selfish
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets into their heads, and Dave gets on the court and shows
them things as a post basketball player. And let's face it: Vitaly
Potapenko, Tony Battie, and Danny Fortson are undersized for their
position, and so was Dave Cowens. So, all the little tricks Dave
could pull off as a player he can give insight to their game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics finished 3-5 in the exhibition season. They were
swept in two games by Charlotte and split against Washington,
Atlanta, and Utah. Paul Pierce led the team in scoring in three
games.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino said outside of the last exhibition game, a loss to
Washington at the the Springfield Civic Center, the Celtics' shot
selection was good. The team shot 43 percent from the floor in the
exhibition season but finished tied for sixth with Charlotte in
points per game (102.6). Celtics opponents averaged 100.6 points
per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got an excellent chance of winning. We're prepared and
we're making strides,'' said Pitino. ``We're going against one of
the most athletic teams in the league with the Toronto Raptors. We
have to match that athleticism on the backboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do that, hopefully going into the fourth quarter it will
be a close game, like I think most of our games will be this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said Pitino hasn't changed much; he's very demanding.
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``We don't need to change. We just have to win
games. We have to listen to details better. Rotate quicker. Know
our assignments on defense. Know what plays to run. With our
talent, we can win games, and everything will be all right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until then, you can make all the excuses you want. You still
have to win games. If he's going to be demanding, he's going to be
demanding. Winning changes everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
