<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC BOWLED OVER BY WINNING FEELING 
</HEADLINE>
 COLLEGE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ Boston College coach Tom O'Brien stood in a
hallway outside the visitors' locker room in the bowels of the
Carrier Dome when his defensive coordinator, Frank Spaziani, and
his offensive line coach, David Magazu, wearily approached.
</P>
<P>
   Before he made his postgame comments to the media, O'Brien
paused and hugged both men.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien's rare display of public affection illustrated just how
much emotion there was to BC's 24-23 victory over Syracuse Saturday
at the Carrier Dome. It showed just how much it meant to the Eagles
(6-2, 3-2 Big East) and to the men who coach them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good win,'' said O'Brien, whose players are off next
week before resuming action Nov. 13 by hosting West Virginia. ``Now
we've got a winning record in October (3-2). We had one in
September (3-0), and now we've got to find a way to get a winning
record in November.''
</P>
<P>
   BC's sixth victory of the season _ and first at Syracuse since
1993 _ guaranteed O'Brien his first winning season with the Eagles
after back-to-back 4-7 campaigns. It also made BC bowl eligible for
the first time since 1994, when the Eagles last had a winning
regular-season record (6-4-1) to earn a berth in the Aloha Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   One week ago, the Eagles seemed to ruin their hopes for a
winning record and bowl bid in a 31-28 loss to Miami, but BC
resuscitated its hopes by surviving a topsy-turvy thriller that
wasn't sealed until a final Syracuse drive stalled in the last
minute. BC had taken the lead when John Matich converted a 34-yard
field goal with 2:57 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Eagles could be headed for any number of bowl
destinations.
</P>
<P>
   BC could be in line for a spot in the Aloha/Oahu Bowl
doubleheader Dec. 25 in Honolulu as an at-large opponent for either
the Pac-10's No. 4 or No. 5 team; the Motor City Bowl Dec. 27 in
Pontiac, Mich., as an at-large team against the Mid-American
Conference champion (Marshall); the Music City Bowl Dec. 29 in
Nashville as the fourth Big East representative, matched against a
Southeast Conference opponent; or, quite possibly, the Insight.com
Bowl Dec. 31 in Tucson against the Big 12's No. 5 team.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles can improve their postseason position with a victory
against a West Virginia squad that first faces the unenviable task
of hosting Virginia Tech after blowing a 13-0 halftime lead in a
28-20 loss Saturday at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get the next one,'' said senior linebacker Frank
Chamberlin, who made a staggering 24 tackles, including a
game-saving shoestring grab of quarterback Madei Williams that
stopped him 1 yard shy of converting a fourth-and-13 play on the
Orangemen's last drive. ``We have a winning season, but we're not
finished. We don't feel like that's the pinnacle of our season.''
</P>
<P>
   After surviving a game that was full of as many big plays as
infuriating mistakes, O'Brien gave his players a well-deserved week
of liberty.
</P>
<P>
   It will give senior strong safety George White (hamstring) and
redshirt freshman defensive end Derric Rossy (shoulder) time to
heal from injuries sustained Saturday. In addition, it will give
freshman running back William Green (groin pull), freshman wideout
Keith Hemmings (hamstring), junior linebacker Steve Martin (neck),
junior cornerback D.J. Sutton (ankle), and redshirt freshman
defensive tackle Frank Misurelli (ankle) _ all of whom missed the
trip to Syracuse _ time to recuperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty beat up, we're sore, and we're tired,'' O'Brien
said. ``We need the time off. I'm not sure how much we had left at
the end of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore DuJuan Daniels got the game off to a roaring start
when he returned the kickoff 100 yards to give BC a 7-0 lead. It
was another in a series of amazing firsts for Daniels, who scored
on his first varsity play in high school at Bishop Chatard in
Indianapolis and, after being switched from cornerback to wide
receiver, scored on his first collegiate play on offense, hauling
in a 64-yard pass from Tim Hasselbeck in BC's 14-10 victory at
Navy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to find something else for him to do first,''
O'Brien joked. ``He scores the first time he catches (one) and the
first time he runs a kickoff return. We may have him return a punt
next week. First time he does something, he scores.''
</P>
<P>
   How big was the win?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no clue,'' O'Brien demurred, as he ducked into the
coaches' locker room. ``Let's wait and count 'em up at the end of
the season.''
</P>
<P>
   While it was an attempt to downplay the win, O'Brien's actions
still spoke louder than his words.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
