<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'BRIEN HAD EAGLES FLYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ While the Boston College players deserve most of the
credit for their 24-23 win over Syracuse Saturday, coach Tom
O'Brien also deserves some praise.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien faced the monstrous task of getting his team mentally
prepared after last week's 31-28 loss to Miami. How do you convince
a team that blowing a 28-0 lead in the second half makes it a
decent squad? Especially when you are hitting the road against a
Syracuse team that had two weeks to digest a 62-0 loss to Virginia
Tech?
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien asked his team this: If someone had told you that with
three minutes to go in the Miami game the score would have been
tied at 28, how would you have felt? The answer would have been
pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien told his team all week it should learn from blowing the
lead, but also that since it could play with Miami, it could do the
same against Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Against Miami, the Eagles played 58 minutes when they needed to
play 60. Against Syracuse, they played an entire game against a
good opponent and won a game almost no one gave them a chance to.
</P>
<P>
   BC has come out flat for games in the past, and O'Brien and his
staff have been criticized for it.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the Eagles came out flying, proving they are a Top
25-caliber team. With six wins, they also proved to be bowl worthy
and almost certainly will be playing somewhere in the postseason,
perhaps Hawaii, Nashville, Tucson, or Pontiac, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   The players deserve the praise they are receiving. They just as
easily could have been 8-0 right now.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Brien and his staff deserve as much praise for guiding the
team through turbulent times.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bizarre story of the season, and maybe of the century,
involves Arizona State running back J.R. Redmond. Redmond did not
play in Arizona State's 20-17 loss to Oregon, serving a one-game
suspension because he received what the NCAA ruled were extra
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   No big deal there. But these were the extra benefits: Redmond, a
potential first-round NFL draft pick, was dating a student who also
worked part time in the ASU athletic department. During the
courtship, Redmond rang up more than $400 in charges on her cell
phone. His fiancee informed him that was an NCAA violation, and
unless he married her, she would turn him in.
</P>
<P>
   So he did. Now he wants out of the marriage, but his wife has
hired an attorney and is asking for a portion of his potential NFL
earnings as part of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in disbelief,'' said athletic director Kevin White about
the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a good theme for the next ``Jerry Springer Show.''
``How I Blackmailed My Husband Into Marrying Me And How I Hope To
Strike It Rich.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina is 1-7 after a 28-3 loss to 7-1 Furman. What's
the big deal? Furman is a Division 1-AA team, albeit a very good
one, and it marked the first time North Carolina had ever lost to a
1-AA team. It was also Furman's first win over a 1-A opponent in 14
years . . . Stanford lost its first Pac-10 game of the season when
Washington came from behind for a 35-31 victory. The Cardinal
entered the game ranked 111th (out of 114 teams) in defense and
allowed Washington quarterback Marques Tuiasosopo to have a career
day. He gained 509 yards in total offense, which included 19 of 32
for 302 yards and 1 TD passing, and 22 carries for 207 yards and 2
TDs rushing . . . Kansas and Navy fans can share the misery of
their latest losses. Navy had Notre Dame beaten, but a generous
spot on a fourth-down play gave the Irish one more chance and they
took advantage of it, pulling off a 28-24 come-from-behind win.
Kansas led Nebraska, 9-0, at halftime and was tied at 17 late in
the fourth quarter before losing, 24-17 . . . Southern Methodist
players will wear decals on their helmets to recall two-time US
Open champion Payne Stewart, a 1979 graduate killed in a plane
crash last week. Knowing the NCAA, the Mustangs likely will be
forced to take them off since it probably isn't an approved decal .
. . Coaches always say it takes a solid running game to win. Not so
with Duke. The Blue Devils had a total of minus-5 yards rushing and
still beat Maryland, 25-22. To make matters worse, Maryland's
LaMont Jordan ran for 227 yards and the Terps still lost . . . The
'Canes didn't show up for a first half in the last two games,
against BC and West Virginia, and wound up winning both. Against BC
they overcame that 28-0 deficit; against West Virginia they
trailed, 13-0, at halftime and won, 28-21. Maybe coach Butch Davis
should bring his team to the stadium seven hours before kickoff
instead of the normal 2 1/2-3 when it takes on Pittsburgh next
week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
