<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS DEFENSE HAS LINE ON VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ The future is not now for the Arizona Cardinals,
who could not overcome the mistakes of their young offensive line
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can run the ball even this much,'' said Cardinals
general manager Bob Ferguson before the game, spreading two fingers
about an inch apart, ``then we could do OK today. We've got an
entire line of rookies. Either they are legitimate first-year guys,
or they were with us a year ago and didn't play. This will be their
first game together, and we plan to have them as a group for the
next five years.''
</P>
<P>
   They're sure to have better days than the one they had against
the Patriots. The New England defense manhandled them, limiting
Arizona to a total of 166 yards, and never giving the Cardinals a
chance to get in the game once the Patriots claimed a 14-0 lead in
the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's offensive line was so bad in its first six games it
was completely revamped when the team had a week off.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots felt good about their defensive game plan going in.
They would attack Dave Brown, the Cardinals' backup quarterback who
was working in place of star Jake Plummer, out with a broken finger
on his passing hand.
</P>
<P>
   A defense has to respect Plummer when he plays. He has great
mobility and creativity. Brown does not. He is stationary, and the
Patriots' rushers knew they could find him in the pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Steve Sidwell wanted to force Brown into
throwing situations, then pressure him into making mistakes.
Arizona entered the game with more turnovers (20) than any other
team in the league, and the Patriots wanted to take advantage.
</P>
<P>
   New England also anticipated that Arizona would protect Brown by
having him take a three-step drop and get rid of the ball on
shorter pass plays. The way the Patriots got around that was to
have cornerbacks Ty Law and Steve Israel play the receivers tight
off the line of scrimmage, making Brown hold the ball longer than
he wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme worked well in the first half. Arizona had just four
first downs and 77 yards of total offense and never got the ball
inside the New England 45.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, Arizona is decent, a gambling unit that likes to
attack an offense with blitzes. The Cardinals usually enter a game
with two or three blitzes the other team hasn't seen before.
</P>
<P>
   Thus they live or die by the sword, and Sunday they cut their
own throats. They got to Drew Bledsoe several times in the first
half, sacking him three times, and he wasn't happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   But Bledsoe got his revenge. On each of the first three New
England scoring drives, he made big plays through the air. The play
that set up the first touchdown was a 38-yard pass to Terry Allen
down the sideline to the Arizona 10. The Patriots surprised
Arizona's defense by going to the no-huddle, and operating from the
shotgun formation, on second down, not allowing Arizona time to
substitute. The Cardinals' strong suit on defense is when they
bring in a defensive package with extra backs. Allen is rarely used
on longer pass routes, but he got behind the defender easily.
</P>
<P>
   On their next possession, the Patriots scored again, catching
Arizona gambling. Bledsoe went behind center with no running backs
behind him. He had four wide receivers deployed along with tight
end Ben Coates. At the snap, Shawn Jefferson, set right in the
slot, ran five strides to his right, then broke sharply up the
field. Bledsoe got the ball out of his hand quickly. Cornerback Tom
Knight dived to intercept it and missed. Jefferson caught the ball
in stride heading straight up the field, froze safety Kwamie
Lassiter with a head fake to the right, and ran right past him for
the score.
</P>
<P>
   For all intents and purposes, Arizona was cooked. The Cardinals
had been averaging 11 points a game for the previous five weeks and
ranked 29th on offense _ with Plummer in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe dropped another bomb on them in the third period to put
the game away. He floated a 36-yard pass for Terry Glenn to run
under at the goal line, and Glenn stepped into the end zone without
a defender within 5 yards.
</P>
<P>
   It was a hit-and-miss day for the New England offense, however.
Bledsoe was sacked five times and knocked down at least five more.
Late in the second quarter, after taking his third sack of the
quarter, he was upset when he went to the bench, and he let the
coaches know about it. A couple of teammates moved in to nudge him
away. For a good three minutes he walked up and down the sideline,
venting his frustration.
</P>
<P>
   During the off week, the Patriots should tinker with their
offense to get someone open quicker to allow Bledsoe to get rid of
the ball under pressure rather than taking hits. Entering the
weekend, only Charlie Batch of Detroit had been knocked down more
than Bledsoe. It is something the coaching staff must remedy if the
team is to make a playoff run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
