<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEFFERSON SEIZES PASSES, NOT PRAISE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ If you were a New England Patriot, the entire day
was fun, fun, fun and Daddy never even threatened to take the
T-Bird away.
</P>
<P>
   And if you didn't know any better, you'd have thought this 27-3
dispatch of the impotent Arizona Cardinals was a home game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was obvious the whole day,'' beamed Pete Carroll, now coach
of a 6-2 team. ``It was a tremendous showing by our fans. I don't
know where they came from, but it seemed there were as many
Patriots fans here as Cardinals fans, and certainly they were much
louder.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots gave them a lot to cheer about. They built
themselves a comfortable 20-0 halftime lead. The only decent
Arizona offensive thrust turned into an embarrassing field goal.
Drew Bledsoe threw four touchdown passes, three of them certifiably
Long Distance, and two of those to Shawn Jefferson, a.k.a. the
Great Angler.
</P>
<P>
   You might recall that Jefferson got himself in the news not too
long ago by latching onto a 488-pound tuna. (No, not him. A real
one.) This makes him the only NFL wide receiver who must be asked
the following question: ``OK, so is it more fun to catch a
488-pound tuna or catch two touchdown passes against the hapless
Arizona Cardinals?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Catching the tuna,'' he claimed. ``You're out there with a
chance to see Mother Nature in her rarest form.''
</P>
<P>
   Catching the kind of passes Bledsoe threw Sunday might qualify
as hauling in NFL aerials in some quarterback's rarest form, but
for Bledsoe it was just another routinely great 1999 office visit.
It was his second four-touchdown performance in what is shaping up
to be his greatest season.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson was in no mood to gloat, celebrate, or otherwise
acknowledge he had done much of anything. That's very noble, coming
from a man whose three receptions were good for 113 yards and those
two TDs.
</P>
<P>
   Touchdown No. 1 came on a third-and-6 at the Patriots 36. The
Cardinals had the foolish notion of blitzing the increasingly
unblitzable Bledsoe, who found Jefferson in some delectable
one-on-one coverage across the middle. Jefferson hauled in a
perfect pass, eluded a halfhearted grab by the safety, and pranced
into the end zohis third TD of the season. At 64 yards it
was his longest touchdown grab ever, and tied for the
second-longest reception of his career (he had a 76-yarder against
the Vikings in 1997).
</P>
<P>
   ``They were playing a lot of one-on-one today,'' he shrugged.
``We just took advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Touchdown No. 2 came on a first-and-10 at the Cardinals 35.
Bledsoe had just connected on a 19-yard pass along the left
sideline to Vincent Brisby. The Cardinals made a replay challenge,
apparently thinking Brisby had not gotten his feet inbounds.
</P>
<P>
   One play later, Bledsoe was lofting a perfect pass to a
streaking Jefferson for a nice-'n-easy TD. ``Drew led me
perfectly,'' lauded the 30-year-old nine-year veteran. ``It was a
day of big plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson was so blase about his performance he was almost able
to sneak out of the locker room without speaking up for himself.
``It was just a break-out day for us,'' he decided.
</P>
<P>
   Was it also a break-out day for him?
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't say that,'' he replied. ``It was all about the team.
For me, it was `Been there; done that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It was a little more than that to his coach. ``He's just a
fantastic worker,'' said Carroll. ``He had those stitches (having
taken a helmet to the knee against Miami) last week, and he
couldn't practice. So this week he must have decided he was going
to make it all up. He was out there as much as possible _ offense,
defense, everything. I was kidding him about never wanting to leave
the field. I just love the way he approaches the game. To see him
break out like this was kind of a reward.''
</P>
<P>
   After a demanding seven-week stretch in which six games were
decided by 3 points or fewer and the seventh was an aggravating
taffy pull with an expansion team, this affair gave the team a rare
opportunity to stand around the sideline and giggle for the final
five or six minutes. Had to be fun, huh, Shawn?
</P>
<P>
   ``It really doesn't matter to me,'' he insisted. ``I really
don't care how we win, as long as we win. I don't care if we win by
half a point. On Monday morning, people don't ask how you won; they
just want to know whether or not you won. It's not supposed to be
easy. The guys on the other side of the ball get paid, too. Those
guys are not going to lay down because we're the New England
Patriots.''
</P>
<P>
   All right, already, we get the point. All you did was run
around, get open, and wait for Bledsoe to find you. It doesn't
matter if you win by half a point or 40 points. And catching a tuna
is an existential experience. That's the Shawn Jefferson story, and
he's sticking to it.
</P>
<P>
   Fine, but he had a lot to do with making the trip from New
England worthwhile for an amazing number of Patriot fans. He may
have been there and done that, but someone should tell him it never
gets old. It's OK with Carroll if he'd like to do it again when the
season resumes against the Jets two weeks from Monday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
