<HEADER>
A4861 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-TV-COSSELL-AZR &LR;      11-01 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-COSSELL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MONDAY NIGHT FOOTBALL' COSELL'S CLAIM TO FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the past week, America has been buzzing about Jim Gray's
interview with Pete Rose, in which the NBC reporter repeatedly
hammered Rose with questions about whether the banned former player
gambled on baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Rose had just been named to the All-Century team; Gray quizzed _
or ambushed, depending upon whom you ask _ him right after the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking just about debates among baseball geeks.
Gray's tactics have been fodder for editorial pages, radio call-in
shows and the like _ we're talking Actual Big Story here.
</P>
<P>
   When was the last time America was so riveted by a sportscaster?
I can't say for sure, but I'd be willing to bet it involved Howard
Cosell.
</P>
<P>
   There was no middle ground with Cosell. You either loved the guy
or hated him. Or, possibly, both _ a 1978 ``TV Guide'' poll named
Cosell both the most liked and most disliked sportscaster in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   So how would Cosell have handled the Rose interview? Perhaps no
one is more qualified to answer than Ross Greenburg, senior vice
president for HBO Sports and the executive producer of ``Howard
Cosell: Telling It Like It Is,'' a one-hour biography of the Mouth
that Roared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he would have asked the first question about the Dowrt (which supplied evidence that Rose bet on baseball), and
whether or not he was finally willing to admit that he bet on
baseball,'' Greenburg said last week. ``But I think Howard probably
would have followed up with a series of questions about whether the
ceremony would create an atmosphere where (baseball commissioner)
Bud Selig would be forced to accept Pete Rose into the Hall of
Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Cosell being Cosell, he wouldn't have stopped there, Greenburg
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he would have walked across the field and ambushed Bud
Selig and asked him in follow-up whether Bud Selig would now think
twice about this continued banishment of Pete Rose, or whether he
would induct him into the Hall of Fame on the spot, at the
stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   It's delicious fun to imagine Cosell, his inimitable whine
droning above the din of the crowd, boring in on baseball's
commissioner. But thanks to ``Tell'' ``It Like It Is,'' we don't
have to. This great documentary of Cosell's life includes so much
riveting real-life footage that we don't need to dream up anything
to bolster it.
</P>
<P>
   Just hearing the voice again is a treat. It's a voice Billy
Crystal describes like this: ``Think of a very smart man scolding
you with a bad sinus condition who had a great vocabulary.''
</P>
<P>
   Woody Allen, who hired Cosell for a role in his movie
``Bananas,'' says, ``If Howard said, `Pass the salt,' or, `I'm
going to get the newspaper,' it sounded like an exciting event.''
</P>
<P>
   Cosell was born in Winston-Salem, N.C. _ something he denied for
years _ but his family moved to Brooklyn when he was 9 months old.
He became a successful union lawyer, but longed to break into the
world of sportscasting. He finally did, but not until his late 30s.
</P>
<P>
   Sports was a close-knit world in which athletes and the
reporters who covered them shared an intimacy _ an intimacy Cosell
didn't enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using this tape recorder as a battering ram, he slugged his
way into the group,'' Robert Lipsyte, a ``New York Times''
reporter, says in the piece.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Semitism delayed Cosell's television debut, according to
the film. Perhaps his personal experience with bigotry is what
fueled his attraction to Cassius Clay, soon to be Muhammad Ali.
(Cosell was the first broadcaster to call Ali by his Muslim name.)
</P>
<P>
   Cosell's support of Ali came at a price _ in what seems almost
unbelievable today, Cosell was deounced, sometimes in print, with
the crudest racial slurs. Yet his refusal to back down also gained
him a measure of respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in the right place in the right time, which I know is a
cliche which he would never use,'' Greenburg said. ``But he was . .
. in an era of revolutionary struggle, and race relations were a
major part of our culture in that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Cosell's greatest fame came from ``Monday Night
Football.'' His work with Frank Gifford and Don Meredith has never
been equaled, not on the current version of the show or on any
other sports broadcast. Forget the game _ just listening to the
banter between the two ex-jocks and the big-mouthed former lawyer
was worth staying up late for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, you tuned in to ``Monday Night Football'' and you felt
like every Monday night was a Super Bowl,'' Greenburg said. ``When
was the last time you had that feeling? All anyone does on the East
Coast (now) is wonder what time they can go to bed.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it wasn't always smooth sailing in the booth. ``Tell
It Like It Is'' includes amazing footage of a 1970 game in
Philadelphia in which Cosell increasingly slurs his speech; by
halftime, he was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Spence, who worked the game for ABC Sports, says he called
the production truck to ask what the problem was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to our producer,'' Spence says, ``and said, `Howard
OK?' And he said, `Jim, Howard's had too much to drink.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Cosell claimed to have an ear infection.
</P>
<P>
   Late in his life, Cosell wrote ``I Never Played the Game,'' a
bitter book that ABC's Al Michaels calls ``cruelty in the guise of
candor.'' The interviews with Gifford, whom Cosell slammed in the
book along with Meredith (who declined to be interviewed for the
film), are gripping.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very tough interview for Frank to actually sit down
and do, because of his mixed emotions,'' Greenburg said. ``That was
as candid as you'll ever see Frank.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has ever really filled Cosell's place in sports
broadcasting, Gray's Rose-colored flap notwithstanding. Greenburg
doubts anyone ever will.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't duplicate Howard,'' he said. ``Unless a human being
can actually become another Howard Cosell, you're in apples and
oranges territory.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Cosell's daughters puts it best:
</P>
<P>
   ``The silence,'' she says at the end of ``Tell It Like It Is,''
``is deafening.'' &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8974, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 0052EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
