<SLUG> BC-LA-EGYPTAIR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTIMS' KIN FLOCK TO LAX FOR INFORMATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY HARRISON SHEPPARD 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- As federal investigators on Sunday questioned
employees who worked on EgyptAir Flight 990 before it left Los
Angeles, grief-stricken family members converged on Los Angeles
International Airport desperately seeking information about loved
ones who boarded the plane hours before it crashed off the
Massachusetts coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very, very difficult, anxious time for the family
members now,'' said Bonnita Wirth, an American Red Cross grief
counselor who met with three families at LAX.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-three passengers and 11 crew members were believed to
have been on the Boeing 767-300ER when it left LAX for a layover in
New York before continuing to Cairo. At least one crew member was a
regular worshipper at a Los Angeles mosque.
</P>
<P>
   But with few bodies recovered and no confirmed passenger list,
families were clinging to the faintest hope that their loved ones
survived, Wirth said.
</P>
<P>
   Red Cross and airport officials were unable to provide the 15
people from three families who came to LAX with much information.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest thing for the families right now is waiting for
confirmed information and that process can take a very long time,''
Wirth said. ``So it's very difficult for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one person, an EgyptAir contract employee, was known to
have exited the plane at New York's John F. Kennedy International
Airport. He was reportedly cooperative when questioned by
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   No cause was immediately determined for the crash. While there
was no early evidence of foul play, FBI agents and Federal Aviation
Adminstration officials questioned ``any employee who had anything
to do with that aircraft,'' as part of standard procedure, said LAX
spokeswoman Nancy Castles. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The local Islamic community mobilized to provide support and
prayers for families who lost loved ones, said Hussam Ayloush,
executive director of the Anaheim-based Council on American-Islamic
Relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep holding out hope that there will be survivors, but
meanwhile those families will need all the help they can get,''
Ayloush said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Islamic Center of Southern California, more than 200
people chanted ``Allahu Akbar'' _ ``Allah is great'' _ in prayers
for two EgyptAir pilots who attend services at the mosque during
their frequent stays in Los Angeles. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; One of the pilots was Hatem Rushdy, said mosque member Aboubakr
El-Tawansy. He said he had known Rushdy for about five years, since
the pilot helped his daughter on a flight from Los Angeles to
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He upgraded her seats because she wasn't breathing well in a
smoking area and was very generous with her,'' El-Tawansy said.
``Since she heard the news she's been crying and crying.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosque members also prayed for another EgyptAir pilot they
believed was on the flight. Members spell his name Mohammed Gamal
El-Battooti, but that doesn't precisely match any names on the crew
list released by EgyptAir.
</P>
<P>
   El-Battooti was known for dropping by the mosque and also for
his attempts to ban alcohol on EgyptAir in keeping with the
teachings of his faith, said Ahmed ``Jimmy'' Ahmed, a worker at the
mosque.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very friendly and kept in touch with the community,''
Ahmed said. ``He helped most of the people here with flights.''
</P>
<P>
   A family assistance center was set up in Providence, R.I., to
provide information and counseling to family members, and EgyptAir
was arranging to fly people there, Castles said.
</P>
<P>
   EgyptAir has set up an information line for family members
seeking information on people who may have been passengers on
Flight 990. Call (800) 243-1094.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
