<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOORE-REACTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOORE'S FELLOW DRIVERS LEFT SADDENED, SPEECHLESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL HELMS  
 Inland Valley Daily Bulletin  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA _ The CART drivers had come to the California Speedway
to crown a champion, not to praise a fallen competitor.
</P>
<P>
   They did both Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   When Greg Moore was killed after a horrifying crash on the 10th
lap of the Marlboro 500, CART lost one of its most popular drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Fernandez won the race, and Juan Montoya captured the
points championship, but neither driver was in the mood to
celebrate their achievements. They had trouble even talking
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   It was a somber scene in the garage area at the California
Speedway as fellow drivers, crew members and fans grieved the loss
of the 24-year-old Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just ...,'' Fernandez said as he struggled to speak
through tears. ``It's just so hard because Greg was such a friend
of ours. We've been racing awhile. We have shared so many great
moments inside and outside of the race track.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore was described by friends as an energetic and enthusiastic
person who enjoyed life. Moore had five wins in his CART career,
including a season-opening victory in Miami. He was first among
CART drivers last year in oval events, winning the U.S. 500 at
Michigan and finishing second at the California Speedway. He was
fifth in points last year and 10th overall in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, he became the youngest race winner in CART history at
22 years, one month and 10 days when he held off Michael Andretti
to win at the Milwaukee Mile. He was considered one of the
up-and-coming stars in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greg was one of the new young tigers of championship car
racing, certain and unequivocally a champion of tomorrow,'' CART
president Andrew Craig said. ``He was talented, competitive,
courageous and fit, everything that is good. He really loved life
and loved having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The drivers were not told of Moore's death until after the race,
although it was announced to the California Speedway crowd while
the race was still going on after flags had been lowered to half
staff.
</P>
<P>
   A bouquet of flowers sat outside the Player's-Forsythe truck
that hauled Moore's car to the track. Devastated crew members met
in a hospitality tent behind the garage area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, I lost one of the best friends I ever had,'' driver
Dario Franchitti said. ``In the last couple of years, ever since
I've known him, we shared a lot of good times together. He was the
guy I competed the hardest with on the track, and he was the guy
that I had the most fun with away from the track. The guy was going
to be a champion, many, many times over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in shock,'' driver Michael Andretti said. ``I knew it was
a really bad accident, but I had no idea it was this bad. Greg was
a great race driver with tremendous talent, but beyond that he was
a great role model and friend to many people.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore was to be paired with Gil de Ferran next year on a two-car
team for owner Roger Penske.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
