directed at children and parents has been mushrooming. And that has
meant plenty of work for wranglers. By Patricia Winters Lauro.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT19) and graphic have been sent to NYT
photo/graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-RESEARCH (San Francisco) _ Scientists at a variety of
elite laboratories around the country are sharing a growing sense
that they are on the brink of a new era in digital electronics. It
will usher in a world of circuits no more than a few atoms wide,
with a potential impact on computing, in terms of speed and memory,
that may be too profound to fathom. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-TALK (Undated) _ Imagine that the gleaming new Conde Nast
building in Times Square is a giant cocktail shaker, and rumors and
speculation are the ingredients. Also: If Howard Stern could
fulfill his fantasies, would he still be _ well, Howard Stern? Many
fans and radio pundits were asking this last week after the
announcement of the end of his 21-year marriage to his wife,
Alison.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News of an online support group for
ChapStick addicts, Internet problems encountered by Encyclopedia
Britannica, and more.
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-LAUNCH _ The E-commerce report column. Many off-line
retailers who haven't yet launched e-commerce sites were hoping to
do so by Monday, in time to work out some kinks and start marketing
for the holiday rush. Many of them haven't made it, as they've
underestimated the time and effort involved in launching a good
e-commerce site. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ Brent Lee Farley could be said to take a
quirky view of life, and he has earned patents for sled pants, a
hand-shaped hair dryer and an inflatable shower curtain. But right
now he's most enthusiastic about a patent he won recently for a
system of fighting wildfires. By Sabra Chartrand.
</P>
<P>
   LOWELINTAS-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ Interpublic Group of Cos. in
New York is combining two of its four global agency networks:
Ammirati Puris Lintas and the Lowe &AMP; Partners Worldwide unit of
Lowe Group. The merged Lowe Lintas &AMP; Partners Worldwide will have
offices in 80 countries and billings of more than $11 billion,
ranking it fourth among all agency networks. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   MOTOROLA-CHIP (Undated) _ Motorola will announce a chip that the
company says can work with all the various transmission formats
used for wireless communications. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-RDP (Washington) _ Even before the judge issues his
widely anticipated findings of fact in the Microsoft antitrust
trial, the company is trying to manage public expectations in
various ways. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-SIGNATURES (Washington) _ It started as congressional
legislation that would unify the nation's laws recognizing the
legal validity of digital signatures. But to the outrage of the
Clinton administration, the bill has been seized upon by the
financial services lobby and stretched into legislation that would
nullify all state and federal consumer-notification requirements _
as with insurance policy cancellations _ for contracts that have
been signed digitally. By Jeri Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   SINCLAIR-TV-FCC (Washington) _ Sinclair Broadcasting's petition
to have the FCC reconsider the digital television technical format
continues to gain supporters. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   CITIBANK-ISRAEL (Jerusalem) _ Citibank opens a full-service
branch in Israel, which will serve corporate customers, the first
major international bank to open a full-service branch in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   LATIMES-PUBLISHER-MEDIA (Undated) _ Profiling the publisher of
the Los Angeles Times, who found herself having to apologize to the
newsroom last week, after disclosure of a profit-sharing
arrangement between the paper and the owners of a new sports
complex. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   REPORTER-SOURCES-MEDIA (Undated) _ Judge overrules subpoena
demanding that reporter turn over her notes of interview with white
supremecist who, in an interview, confessed to killing a black man.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GRUNWALD-BLINDNESS (Undated) _ Henry Grunwald confronts his
blindness in a new book. By Dinitia Smith.
</P>
<P>
   HERMITAGE-MUSEUM (London) _ Russia's Hermitage Museum plans a
permanent exhibition space at Somerset House, in London. By Carol
Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   DESTROY-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Richard Bernstein reviews
``Destroy the World To Save It,'' by Robert J. Lifton.
</P>
<P>
   TV-PUERTORICO-REVIEW (Undated) _ In a first, new Nickelodeon
series features Puerto Rican girl and family.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (New York) _ Bob Herbert attacks Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's latest plan for the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Washington) _ William Safire writes about the
dangers of the new banking reorganization bill.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-FREEMAN-COLUMN (Philadelphia) _ Sports column on the
Giants-Eagles game. By Mike Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   MARATHON-SLOWS (Undated) _ The universal symbol of running has
always been the winged foot, an embodiment of the pursuit of speed.
But that emblem has begun to give way to a new symbol _ the penguin
_ that reflects a growing movement of extremely slow runners who
are changing the character of American road racing. Embracing a
kind of slow chic, this new breed of runners emphasizes fun over
achievement, rejecting the traditional asceticism of road racing
for a more relaxed, uncompetitive ethos. They have cheerfully
adopted the penguin for its girth and its waddling gait, and they
amble their way through marathons, stopping not only for a drink
but to dance or cheer or simply take in the flowers. Many members
of this new wave in running will be on display Sunday during the
30th New York City Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   RAC-BREEDERSCUP (Undated) _ Breeders Cup advance focusing on
Challukee. By Joe Durso.
</P>
<P>
   SKATE-JUMPS (Undated) _ Can five revolutions be far behind? Not
with Timothy Goebel, the first man ever to land a trio of quadruple
jumps in official competition, on the hunt. By Robin Finn.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-COLLEGE-RANKING (Undated) _ The New York Times college
football computer ranking.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
