<HEADER>
A4902 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     11-01 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WOULD triumph trump tragedy in the end Sunday? No, I think not.
</P>
<P>
   Even Tiger Woods, the once and future phenom, couldn't fully
overshadow the horrors of the week. But give this gifted young man
credit. Woods dug down and lived up to his marquee billing. He gave
his all, which is to say he gave a lot, to deflect attention from
the veil of tears that has gripped the PGA Tour since Payne
Stewart's plane plunged to earth Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a very draining week,'' Woods said. ``Man, it's
been tough. I'm thankful it's over. But going out there and playing
was definitely good for me emotionally.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger conquered all, Love included. He won again, for the sixth
time in his last nine starts, with a sprint to a $900,000 payday.
Woods' star power, which seems to increase hourly, was already
verging on being larger than life. At Champions Golf Club _ the
latest fast track to feel the golfing wrath of this Tiger, Tiger
burning bright _ it dared to challenge death as well.
</P>
<P>
   Only one guy _ Woods _ could have saved such an out-of-sorts
tournament from mere afterthought status, never mind the gaudy $5
million purse, after Stewart perished.
</P>
<P>
   Only one guy _ Woods _ was sufficiently positioned to give the
final leader board more than cursory significance.
</P>
<P>
   Only one guy _ Woods _ could have turned the season-ending event
into anything more than a teary-eyed memorial to Stewart, one of
golf's most popular, accomplished and, to be sure, stylish players.
</P>
<P>
   It would be, and will forever be, Stewart's week posthumously,
signified by the plus-fours most of the lads (Tiger not included)
donned Sunday. But it was Woods' tournament every step of the way,
just as it has been his own private tour since May.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, given his seven PGA Tour titles in six months, a
feat most recently accomplished _ over an entire year _ by Johnny
Miller a quarter century ago, we can safely speak of Woods in the
same breath as we speak of former greats.
</P>
<P>
   Including the greatest, Jack Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   Two months shy of his 24th birthday, Tiger is the youngest
player to notch seven victories in a year since Horton Smith won
eight at 21 _ in 1929. His pace in the majors isn't quite the equal
of the baby Nicklaus, but he has prevailed more frequently overall
than Jack had at the same point in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Yikes, if his putts ever begin dropping on a really consistent
basis
</P>
<P>
   Woods came to Houston ranked No. 1 in greens hit in regulation
but only 84th in putts required per round. He ``burned'' a bunch
more cups Sunday, resulting in a modest final-day 69 that still
left the pack four strokes to the rear. Davis Love III placed
second, but not for a moment did he make us remotely suspect he was
a threat despite his closing 67.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a good reason,'' Love noted, ``why Tiger's winning
every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah. Because Tiger is amazingly, astonishingly, incredibly
good.
</P>
<P>
   And getting better. After taking five of his first 15
tournaments as a professional, following a third consecutive U.S.
Amateur championship, he concluded he didn't have solid enough
mechanics to truly make his mark on the game. The subsequent
reconstruction process took a temporary toll _ he went 3-for-43
thereafter _ but it was at the Byron Nelson in the spring when
everything suddenly clicked for him.
</P>
<P>
   He phoned his swing doc, Butch Harmon, and almost screamed into
the phone, ``I've got it!'' Then he went out and shot a 61. He
wouldn't win Dallas, but the inevitable was suddenly upon us. Tiger
has been terrorizing his PGA competition, such as it is, ever
since. Factor in a victory in Germany, and he has taken seven
titles in 10 tournaments entered, including three in a row.
</P>
<P>
   His lead in 1999's cash dash is now nearly $2 million over David
Duval. Rivalry? What rivalry? There is no rivalry anymore.
</P>
<P>
   It has turned into Tiger vs. history. He's lapping the field, as
we suspected he might do. Somehow, Woods is managing to live up to
the most unrealistic of expectations we established for him.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, with every triumph, those go up, up, up. And how high
is Woods' sky?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' he said, smiling. ``We'll see. I always felt I
would start to win in bunches because of all the work I've done,
and I'm going to keep paying my dues.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do I want to get to? It's like the Army commercial, I
guess _ to be the best I can be. Over the course of the next 20
years, we'll see what happens. I don't know what that is, but I can
tell you one thing: I will continue to work very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a threat as much as a promise. And it bodes rather
ill for the competitive balance of the PGA Tour entering the new
millennium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
