<HEADER>
A4903 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-COLTS-COWBOYS-HNS     11-01 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLTS-COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
INDIANAPOLIS _ Erik Williams forgot that in some cases, two points
is better than seven. Deion Sanders forgot to cover his man. And
the Dallas Cowboys forgot it's OK to keep scoring when ahead.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first two were unusual occurrences, but the third has become
all too familiar for the Cowboys, who lost to the Indianapolis
Colts 34-24 Sunday before a crowd of 56,860 at the RCA Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no excuse for what happened today,'' Dallas running
back Emmitt Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   With the loss, the Cowboys (4-3) fell into third place in the
NFC East behind Washington (5-2) and the New York Giants (5-3).
</P>
<P>
   Losers of their last eight non-division road games, the Cowboys
have squandered leads in all three of their defeats this season.
After assuming a 17-3 edge in Sunday's second quarter, they didn't
score again until late in the third _ after the Colts (5-2) had put
up 18 unanswered points to take a 21-17 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's a problem putting four quarters together
or not,'' Smith said. ``Last week, we played well (against the
Redskins). I don't think we had a problem putting four quarters
together last week. The thing we have to learn to do as a team is
be more consistent. We can't play the first half like lights out,
then start off the second half slow and sluggish and let the other
team creep back into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly when the other team boasts blossoming superstars
Peyton Manning, Edgerrin James and Marvin Harrison. Manning
completed 22 of 34 passes for 312 yards and one touchdown. Harrison
caught six balls for 85 yards and a touchdown, and James carried 26
times for 113 yards and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their offense is one of the most talented I've seen in
years,'' Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   And he should know. It's the first one this year that hasn't
shied away from his side of the field, and the gamble paid off. In
a rarely seen Cowboys lowlight, Harrison put 20 yards between
himself and Sanders, caught a pass and flew 40 yards into the end
zone. The touchdown gave the Colts a 28-24 lead with 14:55 to play
in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking right in the backfield, and the guy ran right
past me,'' Sanders said. ``I'm not blaming it on the safety, not
blaming it on nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only one of several unsettling moments for the Cowboys.
The worst came in the third period when Chad Bratzke came around
the right side and sacked Troy Aikman at the Dallas 12. The ball
came loose and bounced toward the Cowboys' end zone. Williams got a
hand on the ball, but instead of falling on it and handing the
Colts two points for a safety, he batted it away from the end zone.
Bratzke came up with it at the Dallas one.
</P>
<P>
   From there, it was an easy plunge for James, and the Colts had
their first lead of the game, 21-17, with 8:01 to go in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the most unique play I have ever had,'' Bratzke said.
``I got the sack and stripped the ball. I felt a lot of people
around me, so I just tried to knock the ball toward our end zone.''
</P>
<P>
   There was also one series Aikman missed after suffering one of
his four sacks. A helmet-to-helmet collision with Jeff Burris left
him dizzy and blurred his vision. Backup Jason Garrett directed one
drive of minus-one yard while Aikman was administered smelling
salts. Aikman was able to return for the final two possessions of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was remembering the plays and what we were doing,'' Aikman
said, ``so I felt I could go back in.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a game that featured a bit of everything. Sanders
returned the Colts' first punt 76 yards to the Indianapolis two. He
was chased down and caught by Colts punter Hunter Smith, who
Sanders said ``had the eye of the tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders was taken off the hook this time, however, because
Emmitt Smith ran for the final two yards on Dallas' first offensive
play, giving the Cowboys a 7-0 lead with 2:02 elapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter came a blocked punt, with newly acquired
Dallas special-teamer Lemanski Hall getting to Hunter Smith's next
attempt. Darren Hambrick recovered to give the Cowboys possession
at the Indy 24. Seven plays later, Richie Cunningham booted a
24-yard field goal for a 10-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   So when the Colts had surrendered 17 points by halftime, their
defense didn't feel like it was getting pounded. The Cowboys had
only one sustained drive, a 13-play, 60-yard possession that
culminated in a four-yard touchdown run by Chris Warren with 10:26
left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like we spotted them 10 points on the punt return and
the blocked punt,'' Manning said. ``We felt like we could still
score points, and we knew we had to start converting some third
downs. We finally started doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colts scored on five of their six second-half possessions,
failing only when they were trying to run out the clock and turned
the ball over on downs. They scored touchdowns on their first three
possessions of the half, then added field goals of 33 and 27 yards
by Mike Vanderjagt, who already had 43- and 30-yarders in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts converted five of 13 third-down plays, while the
Cowboys were successful on only two of nine. And the Colts managed
414 yards of total offense while the Cowboys eked out just 232.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman's longest pass was a 22-yarder to tight end David
LaFleur. Manning completed passes of 54, 40 and 38 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not playing like a good team this far into the season,''
said Dallas defensive tackle Chad Hennings. ``We haven't been able
to put four quarters together in the three phases, pure and
simple.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
