<HEADER>
A4905 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-TOUR-APPLEBY-HNS &LR;      11-01 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TOUR-APPLEBY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DEAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Twenty-three of the 29 golfers at the Tour Championship on Sunday
wore knickers in tribute to Payne Stewart, a rival and friend who
died tragically Monday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stuart Appleby went a step further. Appleby wore Stewart's
clothing for the final round.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one thing that I wore on my body today that was
mine, and you're not looking at it,'' said Appleby, who looked like
Stewart on the Cypress Creek Course at Champions Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart was the most recognizable golfer on the PGA Tour because
of his trademark knickers and Ben Hogan-style tam-o'-shanter cap,
which was his tribute to golfers of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Tour players originally were undecided on how to show their
respect for Stewart, who was on board an ill-fated Learjet on
Monday to Dallas and then was to come to Houston to participate in
the Tour Championship. Only the top 30 money-winners were eligible
for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of dressing similiar to Stewart was shared by Tom
Lehman, who ordered the knickers for any of the golfers who were
interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea just popped into my head,'' said Appleby, who resides
in Orlando, Fla., where Stewart lived. ``Why not do it? He'd be
laughing at us thinking he was the only one wearing stuff, and now
he has twenty-some-odd guys wearing it now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd think it would be quite funny.''
</P>
<P>
   After Thursday's 27 holes were concluded, Appleby flew home to
Orlando to help console Stewart's wife, Tracey, and attend
Stewart's memorial service Friday before play at the Tour
Championship resumed Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby proposed the idea of wearing knickers for Sunday's final
round to several golfers, and the response was positive and
approved by Tracey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked Ian Baker-Finch; he said, `Great idea,''' Appleby
said. ``And I asked Tracey what do you think, and she said `Great.'
So I just went upstairs and raided his closet.''
</P>
<P>
   And Stewart's clothes were an almost perfect fit for Appleby,
except the cap was tight.
</P>
<P>
   The shoes were a size 12, and both have a waist of 33 inches.
The outfit Appleby chose to wear had a Scottish look and had blue
socks, shirt and cap with red-plaid pants.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby had plenty from which to choose. The hard part was
deciding on colors and combination, but Baker-Finch served as his
fashion coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an unbelievable selection,'' Appleby said. ``If you had
them all lined up together it was enough to supply this field for a
whole week.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Appleby's way of honoring Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't be him, I can only look like him,'' said Appleby, who
finished tied for 26th in the 29-man field. Sunday. Appleby shot a
final-round 74 for a 285 total, 16 strokes back of winner Tiger
Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all going to miss him,'' Appleby said of Stewart. ``The
public's going to miss Payne Stewart. His difference from the
normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to miss his passion for the game. His fire. And on
the personal side, his family is going to miss him. The memories he
made are going to be talked about for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   This summer Stewart, the sixth-ranked golfer in the world, won
the U.S. Open at Pinehurst and in September was a member of the
winning U.S. Ryder Cup team. Entering the Tour Championship he was
third on the money-earning list and enjoying his finest year as a
professional.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby said he did not wear the clothing Stewart wore the
Sunday of winning the U.S. Open out of respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt we better not do the U.S. Open color,'' Appleby said.
``We'd leave that with him. That was his swan song. We tried to
come up with a scheme. It's confusing actually because there's too
many to pick from.''
</P>
<P>
   Appleby had a special link to Stewart on Sunday by wearing
Stewart's clothes and also has a link with Tracey. Appleby knows
about grieving. In the summer of 1998, Appleby's wife, Renay, was
killed in a bizarre automobile accident in London.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby can fit in Stewart's clothes but he said he could never
emulate Stewart's golf swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt really weird,'' Appleby said. ``It's like walking in
his shoes for one day. I felt like him for one day even though my
swing wasn't as fluid as his and I didn't putt as well.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a long week for the players, who paid their last
respects to Stewart and tried to concentrate on a tournament.
Woods' first-place money was $900,000 of the total purse of $5
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all the guys are happy at least to finish the week on
that note,'' Appleby said. ``I'm glad I did it and I'm glad Tracey
said it was OK.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
