<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4907 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-TOUR-LEHMAN-HNS &LR;      11-01 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TOUR-LEHMAN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Tom Lehman thought it was an idea that had no downside. He found
out different when it came to executing his brainstorm.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lehman was the force behind the push to have all the players
wear knickers Sunday at the Tour Championship as a tribute to the
late Payne Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   He was the one who contacted Stewart's clothing company and had
a box of knickers, argyle socks and tam-o'-shanters shipped to
Houston on Friday. Saturday night, most players were trying them on
in the locker room, and it became clear a lot of them were
agreeable to wearing them as a tribute to Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was against it at the beginning of the week,'' Davis Love
III said. ``I didn't think we should put pressure on guys to do
something they didn't want to do. If half the guys did it and half
didn't, they would feel bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I told Tom Lehman when we got out there (Sunday) that this
just feels right. The fans are going to enjoy it. And we'll always
remember this tournament. You can pick out this event on highlights
from now on.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, 24 of the 29 players did some sort of
sartorial tribute to Stewart, who wore his outfit throughout
virtually his entire career. The ones who didn't were winner Tiger
Woods, David Duval, John Huston, Carlos Franco and Brent Geiberger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sort of ruined my day,'' Lehman said. ``I felt bad because
some of the guys felt bad for not wearing them. I didn't want some
guys to feel like they were being forced to do something that they
weren't comfortable with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it with the best of intentions. It was a symbolic move
from the heart. But it didn't work out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman was being too hard on himself. The gesture was beautiful,
and it was something fans got a kick out of. And if Stewart had
been there to give his say, he would have been in favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just kind of our way of saying we're not going to
forget you, Payne,'' Lehman said. ``But I understand that different
guys have different ways of doing it. And if it's something that
you're not comfortable doing, we understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Maggert echoed that sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has their own beliefs and their own way to mourn,''
Maggert said. ``If you feel awkward about something like that, then
you shouldn't do it. You have to feel right about it. And it's no
disrespect not to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those players who chose not to don the knickers, Duval and
Woods explained their cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a comfort thing in my case,'' Duval said. ``As it
turned out, I wouldn't have been able to wear them anyway because
there were none in there that were my size.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if there had been a pair my size, I still would have
chosen not to wear them.''
</P>
<P>
   In Woods' case, he said his character trait of internalizing
things was the deciding factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have an internal resolve, then that's the way you
handle it,'' Woods said. ``I don't need to show it outwardly, the
pain I feel inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``And for how much I hold Payne in honor. I don't need to do
that. Other players may feel differently, but that's the way I
feel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
