r s BC-FBC-USC-LADN     11-01 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACKETT WILY ABOUT FOX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With a 3-5 record, there's not much worth saying
about USC, so a possible quarterback controversy adds a little
diversion from the Trojans' tailspin.
</P>
<P>
   If there really is a controversy.
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Paul Hackett warned Sunday not to believe what he says
about who will start at quarterback this week. But all indications
continued to point to fifth-year senior John Fox starting for the
first time in two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Hackett said he will make a decision Tuesday between
Fox and current starter Mike Van Raaphorst.
</P>
<P>
   Unofficially, Hackett admitted Sunday that he ``sort of''
already decided which quarterback he would select.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not really sure yet,'' Hackett added.
</P>
<P>
   Based on his comments Sunday, though, it sure sounds like Fox is
the starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, we've lost four in a row and we're looking for
a spark. We need a shot in the arm of adrenaline,'' Hackett said.
``We need it from somebody. Something needs to happen to this team.
We don't have the spark right now.''
</P>
<P>
   That's something Hackett might believe he could get by starting
Fox on Saturday against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, he is lying. Remember this quote last year,
after Hackett said Van Raaphorst would start against Washington and
really started Carson Palmer?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I lie sometimes. I thought I'd let you guys know that,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett is remaining a little cautious this week, in part
because he doesn't want to tip off Arizona State. He thinks it
might have made a difference last year against Washington.
</P>
<P>
   This situation is hardly as dramatic, but Hackett wants to keep
an edge if he can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to stay on the fence here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he was being gracious when evaluating Fox's 12-of-25
effort for 226 yards and one touchdown in the 17-7 loss to Cal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rustiness shows up but the excitement and running around
shows up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There's another change possible at quarterback, although it's
not likely to happen this season. Hackett said he will study the
idea of using the shotgun formation in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   He previously opposed any thought of using the shotgun. But the
question persists after the Trojans allowed nine sacks against Cal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not opposed to the concept,'' Hackett said. ``But it's
probably a little ambitious right now. To do it in midseason, with
an iffy quarterback situation and centers who haven't practiced it,
it seems a little ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not convinced after the (Cal) game, the shotgun would have
made a lot of difference. I mean, on first-and-10, we wouldn't be
in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: USC's game against Arizona State on Saturday at the
Coliseum will kickoff at 3:30 p.m. and be televised on Fox Sports
West.... Wide receiver R. Jay Soward (strained hamstring) did not
practice Sunday and remains questionable. Offensive lineman Brent
McCaffrey (ankle) is also questionable.... The perplexing stat for
Hackett was that the Trojans had 18 drives against Cal and not one
started in the Golden Bears' territory.... USC had 13 penalties
against Cal, and four were declined. Four of the penalties were for
blocking in the back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
