<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOPPY START DOOMS DUCKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ For several years, no team has stirred the emotions of
the Mighty Ducks more than the Phoenix Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, however, a mysterious lack of intensity and Mikhail
Shtalenkov turned the Pond into a house of horrors for the Ducks
and the 13,896 that suffered through the 3-0 Halloween-night loss.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after beating Washington, the Ducks flatlined their way
through the first period, giving up a shorthanded goal and digging
themselves a hole that former Ducks goalie Shtalenkov kept them in
the rest of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we talk about taking the next step, this isn't what we
wanted,'' Teemu Selanne said. ``Last game we were so happy, now
this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks did pick up the pace in the second and third periods
and outshot the Coyotes 33-24. But the Ducks never slipped one past
their former backup goalie.
</P>
<P>
   Shtalenkov, who has stopped all 54 shots in two games against
the Ducks, turned away great scoring chances by Paul Kariya,
Selanne, Tony Hrkac and Jim McKenzie in the period. He also had
some help. Defenseman Keith Carney dove to knock away Matt Cullen's
shot at an empty net that would have tied the game three minutes
into the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to help my defensemen, they try to help me,'' deadpanned
Shtalenkov, who is 5-1 with three shutouts against his former team.
</P>
<P>
   Shtalenkov stopped Kariya from point-blank range early in the
third and then watched the Ducks hit the post on back-to-back shots
in the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some nights things just go your way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya said the Ducks didn't deserve any better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had chances, but when you aren't doing the little things
right, you aren't going to be rewarded,'' he said. ``When you are
working hard you get the breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks' power play, ranked No. 1 last season, came into the
game ranked 23rd and certainly did nothing to improve. Anaheim was
0 for 3 with the man advantage and gave up its second shorthanded
goal of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Hrkac couldn't handle Oleg Tverdovsky's pass at the Phoenix blue
line and Trevor Letowski scored on a breakaway at 13:15, slipping a
backhander through Guy Hebert's pads.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks (6-6-1-1) are treading water. Anaheim's 14 points in
October equals its best total in the opening month, but that hardly
leaves Kariya feeling satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been hovering around .500, and that is not acceptable,''
he said of a Ducks team which has yet to win more than two
consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   In the second period, a lost faceoff led to the goal that all
but sealed the Ducks' fate. Jeremy Roenick beat Cullen cleanly, and
Deron Quint's shot from the left point was deflected through
Hebert's legs at 13:08.
</P>
<P>
   Former Ducks center Travis Green scored an empty-netter with
2:14 to go in the third.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
