<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MNF' OFFERS NATIONAL SETTING FOR SEAHAWKS TO SHOW THEY'RE REAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. _ Only in the NFL _ a sport built on, by and for
television _ can a team's relative worth be measured accurately by
its value to network TV.
</P>
<P>
   All sports have marquee teams that draw the biggest TV interest,
but no sport has a stage like Monday Night Football, ABC's 30-year
institution that by its success altered the game as well as how TV
covered sports.
</P>
<P>
   MNF is so big a deal in jockland that to be excluded is an
embarrassment. Since the event has left the Seahawks off its invite
list since 1992, their appearance Monday night against the Packers
here is mindful of the time the Clampetts loaded up the truck and
moved to Beverly. Hills, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Seahawks fans are well versed in the dreary liturgy that the
club has not been to the playoffs since 1988 and hasn't had a
winning season since 1990. All the larger world of pro football
knows is that for most of the last decade, the Seahawks, absent
prime time, haven't registered.
</P>
<P>
   Flatliners. A backwater. A one-headed calf.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday night is the debutante ball for the Seahawks. The
runway is the game's most hallowed ground, against the most storied
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monday Night Football at Lambeau Field against the Green Bay
Packers,'' said Seahawks coach Mike Holmgren, ``is very special.''
</P>
<P>
   To put it in comparative context:
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the Yankees of the NFL,'' said longtime Packers center
Frank Winters. ``You think about the championships both teams have
won. You think of Mantle with the Yankees and Starr with the
Packers. The Packers are also a team owned and loved by its
community. It makes the place extra special.''
</P>
<P>
   To Holmgren's credit, he hasn't issued a football coach's usual
moronic pay-no-attention command regarding the atmospherics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably the best pure football stadium in the country,''
he said. ``I've tried to tell my players about what a special place
it is. I really want them to soak it up a little.''
</P>
<P>
   The travelogue is worthwhile; the Seahawks haven't played here
since 1981. Besides, for Holmgren to suggest otherwise would be
stupid, calling into question just why it was such a big deal to
hire him away from here in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks haven't played in a game with such trappings in a
long while. For Holmgren, the game is bigger on a level beyond his
return to where he was hailed, and a little bit reviled.
</P>
<P>
   It's a rare opportunity to justify, in his first season on the
new job, why he's worth more money than anyone in the NFL not
wearing a plastic hat.
</P>
<P>
   For Holmgren to walk away from what was a great job in this town
took a lot of gumption, something his critics interpret as a
runaway ego. As with colleagues who occupy multiple roles, such as
Miami's Jimmy Johnson and Denver's Mike Shananan, the pressure is
enormous to back up the boldness with results. Quickly.
</P>
<P>
   To overcome the Packers' home-field advantage and talent
superiority, especially with quarterback Brett Favre _ as well as
the Seahawks' injury absence of center Kevin Glover _ Holmgren and
his assistants have to use the extra time for a Monday game to
outsmart their Packers successors.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night has not been kind lately to Holmgren. In his final
season as Packers coach last year, he lost all three MNF games:
34-27 to Minnesota, 27-20 to Pittsburgh, and 24-22 to Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Packers coach Ray Rhodes acknowledged that the time puts the
onus on both staffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long week, and the more you see, the more you add,'' he
said. ``It puts an emphasis on game planning. Mike knows everything
this offense is going to do. And vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's up to us (coaches) to make a false key here, or a
false key there, to make things happen. We practice against (the
Seahawks' West Coast offense) every day, so it comes down to game
planning.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation for Holmgren was similar to what he encountered as
Green Bay coach in 1995 when he first met his previous team, the
San Francisco 49ers, where he had been offensive coordinator. His
knowledge of Niners offensive tendencies helped create an upset
victory in an NFC semifinal game in Candlestick Park.
</P>
<P>
   Should the Seahawks pull off an upset Monday night in the
showcase game, the implications go beyond the bump in the W column.
They will draw instant national legitimacy for the rest of a season
where rampant parity has left no opponents on the remaining
schedule that can be considered formidable (the non-division foes
are Cincinnati, Tampa Bay and the New York Jets).
</P>
<P>
   A victory is also a handy recruiting tool, since the Monday game
is the only one most NFL players can kick back and enjoy,
particularly those free agents who like to do some early scouting.
</P>
<P>
   A loss, however, means the entire Holmgren acquisition was a
bust, the Seahawks are doomed and Rhodes will be declared a genius
superior to Lombardi and Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   See how intense this Monday night business is?
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135 or
artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 0214EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4910 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-FBC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     11-01 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSKIES FORGE NEW, WINNING IDENTITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Who are the Washington Huskies?
</P>
<P>
   They're a bunch of accident-prone thrillers who won't take
``no'' for an answer.
</P>
<P>
   They're exciting. They make mistakes. They make one-handed
pickoffs out of thin air. They throw egregious interceptions. They
come back.
</P>
<P>
   Their best player is the guy with the ball in his hands all the
time. Another of their best players is a defensive back who can
make interceptions exactly when the Huskies need them most.
</P>
<P>
   They kick field goals from 47 and 49 yards when Huskies kickers
haven't scored from those spots consistently in years. They look
completely juvenile and mistake-prone one play. Then they spend
yardage-eating drives proving themselves otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Against Stanford Saturday in Husky Stadium, a sophomore named
Terry Tharps kept zig-zagging kickoff returns to the Washington 1
and still the Huskies found a way to go 99 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine. Down, 23-12, in the third quarter. You're on your own
1. Your quarterback has a sore butt that at halftime had teammates
wondering if Marques Tuiasosopo could even get out of his chair,
and poof, next thing you know, you're hauling 99 yards downfield
for the score.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, who are these Huskies?
</P>
<P>
   If you had asked anyone that question about eight weeks ago,
it's almost a guarantee that you would have gotten some shrugs of
the shoulders and a few furrowed brows, as if to say: Who really
knows?
</P>
<P>
   It figured to be an experiment requiring dedication and patience
with a premium placed on the future: When the new recruits arrived,
when better athletes showed up, refusing UCLA or Florida State or
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   After all, there was the new coach _ villified across the nation
because he is lucky enough to be making huge money.
</P>
<P>
   There was the new staff which had to kick into dangerous
overdrive to catch up on recruiting and scheme devising.
</P>
<P>
   There was a gutsy new starting quarterback completely different
than the classic drop-back passing quarterback last year.
</P>
<P>
   And, last but not least, there was a collection of players who
had spent their entire careers at the University of Washington
wallowing in the post-sanctions era. There was a sluggishness and
stagnation that seemed to slow the players down to three-quarters
time.
</P>
<P>
   And as the team wallowed, everyone from Snohomish to Vancouver
was wondering, ``How is this team going to turn around?''
</P>
<P>
   For awhile there, as the Huskies lost a close opener to BYU and
failed to defend against Air Force's well-oiled option, Rick
Neuheisal attempted to pass off the 1999 Huskies as a ``work in
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   But by the fourth week, that label seemed decidedly
conservative, especially in the bouyant moments after the Huskies
handily defeated Oregon. The Dawgs had kicked off conference play
with a eye-popping bang.
</P>
<P>
   And now _ with the comeback victory over Stanford, a 4-1 Pac-10
record and all eyes trained on Pasadena _ the 1999 Huskies have so
far exceeded expectations. It should be considered a gift to the
college football-adoring public that this November, the Huskies are
going to play three games that matter.
</P>
<P>
   How did this happen?
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we put ourselves in a position to win against
BYU, it showed we had some character,'' senior Joe Jarzykna said.
</P>
<P>
   It must be remembered that of all the players Neuheisal and his
staff had to convince, seniors like Jarzynka would serve as the
toughest sells.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as Jarzynka sees his playing time diminished and even
as he gets benched for fumbles made after ill-advised punt returns,
Jarzynka professes loyalty to the new regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the coaching staff has done a great job. It's hard to
come into a new program and deal with a lot of guys you don't know
and be able to gain their confidence. It's a two-way street. You
can't demand respect and not earn it from your players. You can't
expect anything without giving something out. I think we've done a
pretty good job on both sides of earning respect and dealing with
each other,'' Jarzynka said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most important things that has happened in making the
Huskies so eager and able to hang in with the new staff and new
schemes, even when they have fallen behind in games, is that every
player is getting a fair chance to earn a spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we had a little bit of talent, but we also had guys
who've been waiting to play. Some guys were really anxious to play.
People who really wanted to win,'' Jarzynka said.
</P>
<P>
   By letting everyone compete, there is a program-wide aura of
togetherness and competitiveness that now drives these Dawgs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't Rick Neuheisal's team. This is the Washington
Huskies. I'm just part of it,'' said Neuheisal, sounding like he
might just as well play free safety as call the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to become the Washington Huskies. Don James came to
fall camp. Jim Lambright came to our banquet. For all the turmoil,
we're still all Huskies. I'm just the guy who decides to go for it
on fourth down.''
</P>
<P>
   To say that Neuheisal and the Huskies are experiencing a form of
``beginner's luck'' would probably earn a person a trip to the Dawg
Pound.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever it is these Dawgs are up to, the winds of change
have whipped up the scent of roses for the start of this important,
anticipated November.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
