<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S SOLE PURPOSE: BEAT USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Pac-10 title vanished weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   A winning season disappeared Saturday night in the Pasadena
haze.
</P>
<P>
   So did a bowl bid.
</P>
<P>
   November's here, and the UCLA Bruins have one goal left in this
disastrous season: beat USC. They must wait three torturous weeks
to get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ineligible for a bowl, but that's not the important
thing,'' UCLA coach Bob Toledo said after the 33-7 loss to Arizona.
``The important thing is to finish strong. I don't want any
finger-pointing.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't get any. Not even close. The Bruins (3-6, 1-5) have
been more unified in defeat than they were in glory. They won 10
games last year, they challenged for a national title and won the
Pac-10, but they could not avoid an offense-defense rift. This
year, as the losses mount, internal conflicts remain dormant.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's a result of UCLA's inexperience. The young players
are not as outspoken _ and not as desperate to win _ as last year's
vocal senior class. Then again, since both units are struggling, no
one has ammunition with which to sling criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll be able to stick together,'' offensive tackle
Brian Polak said. ``Maybe this bye week will settle it, clear our
heads so we can concentrate on Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   The bye, although welcome, is weeks late. The Bruins needed it
after the Oct. 16 loss to Cal, when a winning season was possible.
At this point, a bye provides the chance to heal their bodies and
clean their psyches, but it's not going to change the season.
</P>
<P>
   All that remains is the postscript, and that comes Nov. 20 in
the Coliseum against the only team in the conference with
disappointment to match UCLA's: The Bruins and Trojans were a
combined 2-8 in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Myself and the seniors have two opportunities to leave their
mark on UCLA football,'' fullback Durell Price said. ``Yeah, 5-6 is
not a good record, but it's better than 3-8.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Bruins' season had come to _ the difference
between three wins and five, the difference between spoiling
Washington's Pac-10 title and winning it themselves, the difference
between hope and belief. UCLA has plenty of the former and little
of the latter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see what kind of team we are,'' receiver Freddie
Mitchell said. ``There's a lot of obstacles, and this is one we've
got to handle.''
</P>
<P>
   There isn't much Toledo can do. He won't _ and shouldn't _
change quarterbacks. He's playing all available freshmen and
sophomores. He can't heal the injured or turn followers into
leaders. He can't change the offense or revamp the defense; it's
too late in the season for major revisions.
</P>
<P>
   All he can do is spend two weeks rebuilding confidence and hope
the Bruins are ready for Washington.
</P>
<P>
   If they spend too much time thinking about USC, they'll be
crushed by Washington and won't have anything left for the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've still got two games, and SC will come,'' linebacker Tony
White said. ``We need to focus on Washington. They can embarrass us
if we don't regroup.''
</P>
<P>
   Note: The Washington game Nov. 13 is expected to start at 12:30
p.m. An official announcement is expected today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
