<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-BAKER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAKER LIKING HOW HE LOOKS, PLAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ You cannot blame Vin Baker if some days he empathizes
with Oprah and Liz and Luther Vandross _ folks with chronic weight
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, the Sonics' 6-foot-11 forward, knows his way around a
kitchen. But now, at least, he has a nutritionist to guide him.
</P>
<P>
   Baker had built a reputation as one of the more dominant power
forwards in the game _ until spectators began gawking at his
waistline more than his wicked outside shot.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there is the question.
</P>
<P>
   The weekly question born out of Baker's battle with the bulge
and poor performances last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much do you weigh?'' Baker is often asked after long,
sweat-drenching workouts with weights and on the StairMaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't bother me at all. I know how hard I'm working,''
Baker said. ``I didn't turn down (the media) when I was heavy and I
haven't turned down (the media) now. I don't worry about who says
what. The final product, me being on the floor, will be the
tell-all. I can say every day how much I weigh or I'm getting
better. When you see me on the court and you see me playing better
... that's what people want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of a new NBA season, Baker is ready to introduce a
meaner, leaner version of himself.
</P>
<P>
   He says his weight is down from more than 270 pounds last season
to 262. His teammates and coaches see reasons for optimism. Aside
from having regained his confidence, he is decisively quicker on
the court.
</P>
<P>
   For Baker, that makes all the difference in the world.
</P>
<P>
   His effectiveness is predicated on being more mobile than most
power forwards and centers. Baker was an all-star when he exploded
past big men, or faced them and drilled a midrange jump shot.
</P>
<P>
   When he was overweight, he lacked versatility and became an
average player.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's much better than he was last year and he's the strength
of this team,'' said Sonics coach Paul Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's able to get up and down the floor. He's blocking shots.
He's getting rebounds. He doesn't have to hurry his shot as much.
He's just in better condition and playing with more confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing fat on Baker now is his wallet. The expectations
that go with helping the Sonics get back to the playoffs are heavy,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Baker signed a seven-year, $87 million contract this summer. The
Sonics made the commitment to Baker even after his worst NBA
season. A recent list in USA Today had Baker ranked 24th,
statistically, among power forwards last season.
</P>
<P>
   He averaged 13.8 points and 6.2 rebounds in 34 games.
</P>
<P>
   The team is betting that Baker returns to the form he was in
when it traded Shawn Kemp for him in 1997. Baker averaged 19.2
points and 8 rebounds his first season in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Baker's only way of giving the Sonics' some degree of protection
was agreeing to a weight clause. The team can randomly weigh Baker
each month. He will lose money if he doesn't meet a required
weight.
</P>
<P>
   Because muscle is heavier than fat, Baker can carry a few extra
pounds as long as his body fat is reasonably low.
</P>
<P>
   Though Baker's conditioning is not 100 percent, he doubts his
weight will ever be an issue again. He said he developed a new work
ethic with the help of Sonics strength coach Dwight Daub.
</P>
<P>
   Daub worked with Baker throughout the summer. He is at the
Sonics' practice facility to receive Baker well before most players
arrive. A typical day has Baker lifting weights before practices
and games, working on the StairMaster afterward, and running
sometime in between.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done everything we've asked,'' Daub said. ``You see
there's a real commitment there. You can tell that he's encouraged
by how his body has reacted. He's in very good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker averaged 31 minutes _ more than anyone on the team _
during the preseason for the purpose of conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been hard to do,'' Baker said of the extensive
workouts. ``Once you start seeing results, and you hear people say
you're looking better, it's not hard getting up. I know the goal I
want to reach. And I know the people are depending on me in
Seattle. So getting up and going before practice about 45 minutes
on the treadmill is not hard at all. I can see the difference in my
body and in my play.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally, there isn't much emphasis put on preseason statistics.
The case was different for Baker, who searched for positive signs.
Particularly encouraging for the Sonics was how Baker ended the
preseason schedule.
</P>
<P>
   In the finale, Baker collected 21 points and eight rebounds
against Vancouver. He also sank a buzzer-beating, game-winning
jumper.
</P>
<P>
   At least one teammate had been reassured the night before when
Baker lit up Sacramento (with Chris Webber and Vlade Divac
defending him) for 31 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you mean, `Is he back?''' Payton snapped at a group of
reporters after the game. ``Shoot, he was an all-star for four
years, then he has one bad 50-game season. I don't see that he ever
lost it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should you be surprised he had 31 points? I'm not
surprised. He should do that every night. Shoot, you guys are the
ones who wrote him off after one bad season.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. Baker took the blame for his debacle.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it is clear he's taken his comeback personally, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel like I was a key part of missing the playoffs,''
Baker said. ``And I want to see that I hold up my end of the deal
this year so we can get back into playoff position.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012 or at
</P>
<P>
   ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
