<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY KEEPS ITS COOL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ Looking more winded and desperate than a Dallas team
that supposedly spent most of its energy getting here, the Galaxy
beat the Burn 2-1 on Sunday in the type of game it usually gave
away in the past.
</P>
<P>
   While Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid was figuring his shootout lineup
with less than a minute to play, defender Ezra Hendrickson scored
from an impossible angle. On an attempted cross, he got a gift
deflection off Burn defender Bryan Haynes that rolled inside the
near post with 40 seconds left _ leaving Los Angeles one win away
from the MLS championship game.
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of afternoon for the Galaxy, which saw its 1-0
lead erased in the 75th minute by Dallas striker Ariel Graziani _
ending Galaxy goalkeeper Kevin Hartman's scoreless streak at 313
minutes in front of 17,372 at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But for a change, the Galaxy won a game when it was ripe for an
upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good teams find a way to win when they're not playing as well
as they're capable of playing,'' midfielder Danny Pena said. ``Us
not playing well had a lot to do with Dallas. They didn't allow us
to do what we normally do.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it doesn't matter, this game is about results in the
end.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory gives the Galaxy a 1-0 lead in the best-of-three
Western Conference final series with the Burn. Game 2 is Sunday at
the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   During the week, Schmid figured the Galaxy would be able to wear
Dallas down in the second half because the Burn had just finished a
penalty-filled three-game series with Chicago while the Galaxy had
a week off.
</P>
<P>
   That's not how it worked out as Dallas had more chances at the
end with the Galaxy back-pedaling.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got possession of the ball we turned it over when
normally we don't,'' Schmid said. ``And our decision making wasn't
as sharp as normal.''
</P>
<P>
   So what happened? ``You know ... it just wasn't one of our best
game's of the season, that's for sure,'' Schmid said. ``Anytime you
get into a game like this sometimes nerves play a role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they (Dallas) looked a little fresher in the second
half, and for some reason we stuttered _ but we got the win anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just can't allow ourselves to have another game like this.
We need to play better in Dallas and I assure you we will.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendrickson, who joked that his teammates nicknamed him ``The
Solution'' long ago, was certainly opportunistic.
</P>
<P>
   All he was trying to do was set up someone in front of the goal
when his cross defected off Haynes, rolling past the outstretched
fingers of Dallas goalkeeper Matt Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a minute to go I just wanted to make something happen,''
Hendrickson said. ``You don't expect to get rewarded on a cross
like that, but luck play's a big part in this game. Hopefully, we
can take some of this momentum to Dallas with us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
