<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL EYES ON HOLMGREN IN RETURN TO LAMBEAU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. _ After a seven-year banishment rooted in poor
performances and even poorer ownership decisions, the Seahawks
return to Monday Night Football this evening.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the 10-year playoff drought, the longest in the NFL.
Never mind that the Seahawks haven't had a winning season since
1990. Try and dash the memories of the Behrings' bumbling ownership
and that ill-fated attempt to move the franchise to Southern
California in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The league apparently has.
</P>
<P>
   All it took was Mike Holmgren jumping from the Packers to the
Seahawks, and the fact that his new team just happened to be
scheduled to play his old team at fabled Lambeau Field.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITAL) Voila. (END ITAL) The Seahawks suddenly were deemed
ready for prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to feel wanted again,'' said defensive end Michael
Sinclair, the sarcasm laid on thick as he offered a playful grin.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you suppose it was that got us back on the Big Game?''
added Sinclair, who joins defensive tackle Cortez Kennedy as the
only players still on the roster from the Seahawks' last MNF
appearance in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   It's Holmgren vs. his former team.
</P>
<P>
   It's Holmgren vs. the fans in this city, where he returned
winning to a hamlet that modestly calls itself Title Town.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Holmgren vs. Brett Favre, the wild-child
quarterback he nurtured into a three-time league MVP.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget Holmgren vs. Ray Rhodes, his former defensive
coordinator who succeeded him as Packers head coach after Holmgren
jumped to the Seahawks in January.
</P>
<P>
   But it's still just a football game between 4-2 teams, each
needing a victory to maintain a share of its division lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great matchup and people are going to try to make more
of it than it really is,'' Favre offered in one of those too-late
statements. ``It's us against Seattle. It's not Mike Holmgren
against Brett Favre. But people are going to make it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both need to win this game for obvious reasons, not for
personal satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's what the Seahawks need to do to pull off an upset against
the Packers, who are favored by five points and have won 33 of
their past 34 regular-season games at Lambeau:
</P>
<P>
   -- Be aggressive _ This is one of those games where the Seahawks
can't afford to let it come to them. They must force the issue from
the opening kickoff. Score early. Stop the Packers early. Act like
they belong, rather than being invited guests to Holmgren's
homecoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing we have to do is slow down the running game,''
linebacker Chad Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Huh? Isn't that just putting the ball, and the game, into
Favre's hands? Despite playing with a sore thumb on his passing
hand, he has led the Packers to three victories in the final two
minutes of games this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's second-and-5, you don't know what they're going to
do,'' Brown said. ``If it's second-and-8, they become more
predictable. That allows us to dictate more to them, which allows
you to be more aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Be creative _ The conservative, keep-it-close-until-the-end
approach that Holmgren used in victories over the Bears and the
loss to the Chargers won't cut it this week. Neither will trying to
get into a shootout.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks must do things that will surprise the Packers and
knock them back on their heels. It won't be easy, not with Holmgren
knowing the Packers as well as he does and the Packers knowing
Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know each other extremely well,'' Rhodes said. ``I think
the bottom line is going to be the adjustments that they see versus
our defense and vice versa. It's going to be little things like
that that will make the difference in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Be precise _ The Seahawks continue to thrive on turnovers.
The defense has scored twice while setting up two of the offense's
nine touchdowns and a pair of field goals.
</P>
<P>
   Favre will throw into coverage, a daring trait that Holmgren
worked so hard to curtail but which has resurfaced this season.
Last week, the Seahawks got their hands on 15 of Doug Flutie's
passes. Favre will provide them with opportunities for
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, Jon Kitna has thrown only two interceptions in 148
attempts _ the primary reason his QB rating of 92.4 tops the AFC.
But both set up touchdowns by the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers will make Kitna pay if he is not sharp. They have
intercepted a league-high 15 passes, despite starting rookie
cornerback Mike McKenzie (two interceptions) and using rookies
Antuan Edwards (three interceptions) and Fred Vinson (one
interception) in their nickel package.
</P>
<P>
   -- Don't be intimidated _ Even Holmgren acknowledges that his
old team has the league's best quarterback in Favre, the league's
best receiver in Antonio Freeman and one of the league's most
versatile backs in Dorsey Levens.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren also points out what a special place Lambeau is. The
Seahawks have not played there since Nov. 1, 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren even admits to being a little anxious about this game
for more than the obvious personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the schedule and you're kind of saying, `Well, you
have a young developing team and you want to go against the big
boys,''' he said. ``That can get you a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to weather the storm early,'' Kitna said.
``I think they might come out and try to shellshock us. We have to
deal with that and then settle in.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Clare Farnsworth can be reached at 206-448-8016
</P>
<P>
   or clarefarnsworth &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
