<SLUG> BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENNIS, STAY BY THE PHONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Tuesday, the Rodman watch begins again.
</P>
<P>
   As if last night wasn't scary enough when trick-or-treaters were
showing up at your door with yellow hair and a No.73 jersey lookin'
for a handout.
</P>
<P>
   The posture that Phil Jackson will take for now and probably
through the 30 games when Lakers huddle around the .500 mark is
that adding Dennis Rodman won't be an option, but talk to me in
February.
</P>
<P>
   As public opinion mounts outside the Staples Center after
another loss to a Pacific Division foe with an out-of-control
offense, Jax may have no choice.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of slitting his wrists at the thought of Rodman's
return, Jerry West tried every other option _ Chris Weber, Tom
Gugliotta, Lorenzen Wright, Charles Oakley _ he came up with
letting loose J.R. Reid, keeping Robert Horry, adding A.C. Green
and John Salley, and is even considering Bison Dele.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to that, how does Rodman look? Pretty good to Jerry
Buss, who might not want to pay Scottie Pippen money but won't make
the discount forward deal again.
</P>
<P>
   _How secure does Jackson feel with his five-year, $30 million
job? He's having a 6,000-square-foot house built for him and the
missis in Santa Monica.
</P>
<P>
   Not far from Montana Avenue, we're guessing, just to remind him
of his roots....
</P>
<P>
   _Thespians Woody Harrelson, Damon Wayans and David Duchovny have
reportedly committed to playing in a 10-team ``Entertainment
League'' sponsored by the NBA. Supposedly, the games would be
played at an undisclosed gym in L.A. and be closed to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Something the under-the-cap Clippers might consider in their
next talent search....
</P>
<P>
   _For anyone in the Dodgers management group who hasn't figured
it out, Bob Daly is the new sheriff in town. Or, from his Warner
Bros. days, he's the lethal weapon....
</P>
<P>
   _Fox's backing off from the day-to-day operation of the Dodgers
was one of the smartest things Rupert's boys could do. As was
keeping a majority ownership. Imagine Daly's decision-making duties
with Fox's finances backing it up....
</P>
<P>
   _The Angels have probably lost any chance of bringing in Davey
Lopes, who reportedy goes in for a follow-up interview today with
the Brewers....
</P>
<P>
   _Why hasn't Mike Scioscia's name come up anywhere yet?...
</P>
<P>
   _Remember when Joe Torre used to be with the Angels? Right, as a
broadcaster....
</P>
<P>
   _Although Max Patkin, the clown prince of baseball, passed on at
age 79 over the weekend, the real fun at the ballpark actually died
years ago....
</P>
<P>
   _There's a movement in the Latino community to boycott using
MasterCard because its sponsored Major League Baseball All-Century
team left off Roberto Clemente....
</P>
<P>
   _Add Jerry Rice to the list of sports superstars who should pack
it in in '99....
</P>
<P>
   _The San Jose Clash of the Major League Soccer is changing its
name next year to the Earthquakes, which is what the city's NASL
team went by in the 1980s. Team general manager Lynne Meterparel
explaining why the disasterous name isn't inappropriate: ``It's
part of life here. It creates a community that is prepared, that
works together to conquer the odds. That's exactly what you want to
do with a team on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   So, ya see, earthquakes are a (begin ital)good(end ital) thing. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
