<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-CRASH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE CRASH HAPPENED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG PADILLA  
 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA _ Without warning, and seemingly without reason, Greg
Moore lost his life Sunday after his car slid out of control while
exiting Turn2 on Lap 10 of the Marlboro 500 at California Speedway
and broke apart on impact with an infield retaining wall.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's light-blue car slid and began to spin through the
infield grass before crossing an asphalt access road. The left-side
tires dug into another section of turf and the momentum forced the
car into the air.
</P>
<P>
   The Player's Forsythe Racing Mercedes-powered car flipped upside
down while airborne just before it struck the retaining wall. The
car appeared to almost complete a half-turn before the right side
made hard contact with the top of the wall at the base of the
attached catch fence.
</P>
<P>
   Before the crash, the 24-year-old Canadian's fastest recorded
speed was 216.298 mph on Lap3. Taking into account a reduction of
speed after executing Turn2, as well a limited loss of speed from
sliding through the infield grass, Moore still was traveling at
well over 100 mph at the moment of impact.
</P>
<P>
   Moore was almost directly upside-down when he crashed. The car
exploded into pieces as it hit the top of the wall. The driver's
cockpit that contained Moore rolled four times before coming to
rest upside-down.
</P>
<P>
   The accident was eerily similar to one that happened to Richie
Hearn just six laps before Moore's fatal wreck. In fact, marks
across the track and through the grass appeared to be parallel,
almost leading to the identical spot of impact on the infield wall.
</P>
<P>
   Hearn made a hard impact with the wall, but unlike Moore, he
appeared to be less vulnerable to injury because his car remained
right-side up.
</P>
<P>
   Even before learning of Moore's fate, Hearn commented that it
didn't take much to cause his accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a good run off Turn 2 on (Mauricio) Gugelmin and pinched
in too low,'' Hearn said. ``I caught some bad air and that was it.
There were several cars in front of me battling for position,
making it that much tougher back there.''
</P>
<P>
   It might have been more than a coincidence that both accidents
happened coming out of Turn2. Juan Montoya, who wound up clinching
the points title by finishing fourth, said he was approaching Turn2
with caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``This morning, I had a big scare there (in warmups),'' Montoya
said. ``Right at the end (of the turn) the car just tried to point
in a different direction. I suppose that's what happened to Greg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good because for the race, I was very careful with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The live television broadcast on ESPN did not catch the moment
Moore spun out of control, but switched from a shot of Max Papis'
car to Moore's car as it was rolling over through the grass.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN did not show a replay of the accident, but before the race
ended a video clip was available for download on at least one
Internet Web site.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of Moore's wreck, ESPN commentator Parker
Johnstone speculated on the reason for the crash, and his
assessment was similar to Hearn's.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get behind a line of cars and the car is perfectly
balanced ... These cars might look pretty sleek, but the tires
produce huge amounts of turbulence,'' he said. ``That's all it
takes to take away your downforce.''
</P>
<P>
   According to CART's 1999 media guide, ``Downforce may create
loads of up to three times the weight of the race car permitting
the vehicle to corner at greater speeds while drivers experience
loads of over five Gs (a lateral load equivalent to more than five
times the pull of the Earth's gravity) in cornering as a result of
the efficiency of ground effects.''
</P>
<P>
   Another contributing factor to the fatal wreck might have been a
broken forefinger and lacerations that Moore suffered on his right
hand the day before the race. Moore was riding a scooter, like most
drivers do when maneuvering through the track's paddock, when he
was hit by a car.
</P>
<P>
   Moore missed Saturday's regular qualifying session, but
convinced CART doctors he was OK by running two laps at 219 mph
during a special qualifying session. Moore was fitted with a brace
on his hand and started last in Sunday's 27-car field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I examined him after the warmup and he was extremely excited
and confident,'' said Dr. Steve Olvey, CART's director of medical
affairs. ``We feel strongly that the hand was not related to the
accident.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
