</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-OBERJUERGE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACING PAYS THE PRICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA _ It was a weird but overpowering tidal wave of grief.
It began with heads bowed in the Players Forsythe Racing garage,
and ended with a stadium in mourning.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knew it was a horrific accident. Greg Moore's careening
car seemed almost to vaporize when it slammed into the infield
wall. Debris sprayed. Tires bounded wildly. What was left of
Moore's chassis tumbled four times over the grass.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers gasped involuntarily. You didn't need to be a race
expert, or a doctor, to recognize young Greg Moore was in serious
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, however, he was ``receiving treatment,'' and a news
blackout descended over the track.
</P>
<P>
   A jog to the track hospital yielded little. The helicopter
carrying Moore's body lifted off at 1:41 p.m.; reporters were given
no new information.
</P>
<P>
   A walk back to Moore's garage told much more.
</P>
<P>
   Crew members sat in their firesuits without speaking. Most
stared into space. All seemed deeply shaken.
</P>
<P>
   At 1:56, a Forsythe official called together Moore's crew
members, and they filed into the sky-blue truck-transporter of
Moore's No.99 Mercedes Reynard. The doors slid shut behind them.
</P>
<P>
   At 1:58 p.m., the mechanics and engineers exited the trailer.
Several were weeping. It was clear Moore was beyond their help.
</P>
<P>
   Within the hour, as the race went on, flags near the
start-finish line were lowered to half staff. A few minutes later,
word of Moore's death, of massive head and internal injuries, was
announced to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers, Moore's best friends at California Speedway, were
the last to know. Most were informed after they crossed the finish
line, 240 laps after Moore, only 24, hit the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Most drivers seemed anguished, and the post-race atmosphere
turned deeply funereal.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Fernandez, winner of the race, had trouble speaking,
stopping several times to choke out words of sympathy and
condolence.
</P>
<P>
   Runners-up Max Papis and Christian Fittipaldi fought back tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not here to kill oursevles,'' Papis said. ``We are not
here for this reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Fittipaldi: ``We are out to put on a good show for the
fans, but we're not out there to give our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The death of Greg Moore seemed to hit drivers hard because he
was so young. And because he was so good.
</P>
<P>
   Moore was not a marginal talent who made mistakes every lap. He
was a rising star marked for greatness. He wasn't supposed to go
out this way.
</P>
<P>
   The reality though, is that motor racing is a lethal sport.
People die. Spectators, crewmen, drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The CART circuit has been lucky, in terms of drivers and
accidents; Moore's fatality was only the fourth in-race fatality in
CART history.
</P>
<P>
   But when cars qualify at an average speed of 235 miles per hour,
when they cling to the track by a gravitational thread, and when a
mistake or an equipment failure happens in the blink of an eye _
eternity is always only a few seconds away.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe some modern drivers haven't accepted that. Perhaps a man
needs to be in deep denial to be able to strap himself into a
rocket and expect to have a long, pain-free career.
</P>
<P>
   At 200 mph, a driver has placed himself in harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does have the appearance of being a tragic racing
accident,'' said Andrew Craig, CART president and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racing accident.'' That's motorspeak for ``stuff happens.''
</P>
<P>
   As somber fans filed out of California Speedway, and grieving
drivers and teams packed up, about all they could be sure of was
this:
</P>
<P>
   They will grieve for someone else some other day. That is a
price the sport of motor racing has agreed to pay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
