r s BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     11-01 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYER NEEDS INNER PEACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Joe Inman packed a new weapon in his bag Sunday
for the final round of the Pacific Bell Senior Classic. It wasn't a
bubble driver, a lob wedge or a long putter. It was perspective,
and boy, did it come in handy on the penultimate hole of the
three-day tournament at Wilshire Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Inman pulled his second shot at the par-4 17th, and it went
screaming into the creek left of the green. As he stood over his
next shot, a tricky 75-foot chip, you could almost see his
three-shot lead evaporating like water in the 85-degree heat.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the wine-sipping patrons chilling out in the shade of
the sponsor's tent nearby, Inman was the coolest customer of all.
The stirring memorials in the wake of golfer Payne Stewart's death
last week made this very important shot seem pretty insignificant.
As he stood over his ball, Inman told himself, ``Look what happened
to Payne. Chip it and do the best you can. It's not the end of the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a peace I've never had before,'' said Inman, who chipped
to within three feet of the pin and stole a bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, playing partner Gary Player, couldn't get as good a line
on the game, despite fine counsel from his son and caddy Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   Player, who turns 64 today, started the final round three shots
off the lead. With nine holes to play, the usually affable South
African was very much alive in his drive to become the oldest
winner in Senior PGA Tour history.
</P>
<P>
   He missed birdie putts at 10 and 12 by inches and bogeyed 11, 16
and 18 to finish in a tie for 11th. Not that it mattered to the
many people for whom Player is second to none.
</P>
<P>
   On the 10th hole, a man in the gallery approached the golfer's
wife, Vivienne. With a nod to a shy woman hovering nearby, the man
told her, ``My wife absolutely adores your husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Player was arguably the biggest draw in a tournament that
proceeded without oldies-but-goodies Jack Nicklaus, Arnold Palmer
and Tom Watson.
</P>
<P>
   Understand: Player wasn't a poor man's stand-in for the absent
stars. One of only four men to have won golf's Grand Slam, Player
stands out in any constellation. He is one of golf's most precious
jewels.
</P>
<P>
   As treasures go, he's perfectly preserved; his 5-foot-7 frame is
as taut as a teenager's, his step as spry as ever.
</P>
<P>
   But as the hooked shots and missed putts multiplied, Player's
posture slumped. At the 18th tee, after bunkering a 5-iron, he
grimaced all the way down the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   He implored Wayne to tell him what he had done wrong on the
shot. Indeed, he told his son he'd give him $100,000 if he could
straighten his swing with a few magic words.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took all my strength to be patient with him,'' Wayne said,
sighing, to his mother as they made their way to the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Player was nowhere to be seen. He had bolted for the sanctuary
of the locker room, leaving behind not only his family but a few
fans who wanted his autograph, at least one man who wanted a
picture taken with him and a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   The group dwindled until only Vivienne, Wayne, a man with a
disposal camera and the reporter remained. They caught up with
Player at the entrance of the clubhouse where he was pacing back
and forth, swigging a beer and muttering under his breath while he
waited for a courtesy car that was late.
</P>
<P>
   His wife and son had the good sense to stand back and give
Player his space. The man with the camera stepped in his path and
Player stopped pacing long enough to have his picture taken. But
that was the extent of his goodwill.
</P>
<P>
   When the reporter approached and introduced herself, one of the
game's greatest ambassadors cut her off. ``Let me suffer in
silence,'' he snarled. ``I feel terrible. Don't you see I'm
suffering?''
</P>
<P>
   That a man on the verge of 64 could score 7-under par over 54
holes on a 6,610-yard layout seemed to inspire awe in everybody but
the man in agony.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Super Senior being in the hunt on Sunday. Isn't that the
most remarkable thing you've ever heard?'' Inman said, shaking his
head.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it would have been a great story if Player hadn't
spoiled it. It says here the best birthday present Player could
give himself is an inner peace that's not predicated on his
performance. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 0235EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
