<HEADLINE>
LAKERS RECHARGED AS OPENER NEARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Six exhibition games in eight days left the Lakers
weary, and by game six last Thursday, a bit deflated as well. They
lost their last three games, all to Western Conference rivals, and
looked anything but ready for the real season that opens Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   A few days of practice couldn't fix all that ails them, but the
Lakers offered coach Phil Jackson some hope Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was the first legitimate practice that we've had since
we started the six games in eight days, where we've come and
practiced up to the intensity level that an NBA team demands,''
Jackson said. ``I was heartened today by the energy the players
came with.''
</P>
<P>
   They'll need it. They open at Utah, against a Jazz team that has
dominated the Lakers the past few years, including a 92-76 pasting
last Thursday to close out exhibition play.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Lakers make their Staples Center debut against
the lowly Vancouver Grizzlies, but the weekend brings a tough
matchup with the Portland Trail Blazers, heavily favored to win the
West.
</P>
<P>
   The lousy exhibition season, which netted a 3-5 record, combined
with the pending season opener refocused the Lakers in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so,'' Jackson said. ``I think the fact they're getting
their legs underneath them (helps) too.... Physically, they're
starting to find the strength to be there in a conditioned way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had couple of good runs (Saturday), but we just didn't
carry the intensity all the way through. Granted, it's 90-degree
days and a different type of atmosphere to play in and coach in
than I'm used to or maybe they are. It still hasn't come to that
level where we feel the intensity this team must play at to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Decisions, decisions: As of Sunday, the Lakers roster stood at
15, and Jackson was mum on how they'll get down to the mandated 12
by today's 3 p.m. deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant's broken right hand will put him on the injured
list, but Jackson still had not decided if Travis Knight, nearly
recovered from a sprained ankle, will start the season on reserve
as well.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the Lakers probably will cut at least one player
today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
