<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JACKSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN JACKSON MAKE THE DIFFERENCE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This year's Lakers savior does not measure
7-foot-1. He is not a teenage phenom. He was not drafted nor traded
for, though it could be said he was a considerable free agent.
</P>
<P>
   It is an annual refrain, the Lakers talk of claiming their first
NBA title since 1988, but this year the reason for their optimism
is not an exciting new player but a very graying coach.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson was hired not to simply improve the Lakers, but to
take them to basketball's Promised Land. A franchise hungry for
another championship now turns to the man who directed the Bulls to
six NBA titles in the '90s and pleads he can duplicate it here.
</P>
<P>
   History says it will not only be difficult but unlikely. In the
52-year history of the NBA, only one man _ Alex Hannum _ has ever
won titles with two different organizations. Lenny Wilkens and Pat
Riley are two current NBA coaches who have won titles but still
search to find another with a different team.
</P>
<P>
   Now Jackson comes to the Lakers, armed with the respect of six
rings and a five-year contract at $6 million per. There was no more
advancing an assistant or hiring a professorial outsider. This time
owner Jerry Buss shelled out the big bucks for for the son of two
Pentecostal ministers and asked him to make the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Only, just how much difference can a top coach really have on an
NBA team? What is it actually worth?
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty wins,'' Lakers forward Rick Fox said. ``But it's where
those are coming, the playoffs or regular season? I think this team
on talent alone can win 55 games. But get into the playoffs, as
we've proven the last few years, and we self-destruct.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Lakers guard Ron Harper, who won two titles with Jackson
in Chicago, said he knows what a high-profile coach can mean to a
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worth a pot of gold if we can apply what he's trying to
express to us,'' Harper said. ``You can have the best coach in the
world and have a (lousy) team. So it's his job to make us a very
good basketball team. I mean, he's won six NBA rings, but what he
does here will set him apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Add a coach who dominated the past decade with a team
universally perceived as a talented underachiever, and the
expectations are off the charts. It seems the perfect NBA marriage,
but Clippers vice president Elgin Baylor argues for caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like you're putting a coach there and putting a
Michael Jordan on that team,'' Baylor said. ``Even though Phil is a
great coach, that's a difference. Nothing is guaranteed.''
</P>
<P>
   With Jackson for each of his six titles was Jordan, generally
recognized as not the greatest player of his time and all-time. Red
Auerbach won nine NBA titles with the Celtics, all with Bill
Russell at center, and could never separate his success from his
star. As Harper and others point out, this is Jackson's opportunity
to validate himself as a coach.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are all too eager for it to happen. Indeed, with
Jackson the only real significant change to the Lakers, he is at
the heart of those ready to trumpet their return to greatness.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson plainly came here because felt he could win a title, but
he has asked for patience as the team adjusts to his triangle
offense and he to his new personnel. Veteran players, too,
recognize even giving Jackson a team with the talent of Shaquille
O'Neal and Kobe Bryant brings no instant invitation to the finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``A coach is not going to mean any automatic victories,'' Lakers
forward A.C. Green said. ``All he can do is take you to the water.
He can teach you and train you and prepare you, and hopefully that
does mean something, but that's not going to be the end result.
It's important you have players who buy into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't presume too much about what's going to happen. We
have a talented team on paper and a new coach with great history.
That should not tickle everyone's fancy to the point they get in
line for a parade. Not now. Hold on a moment.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 13 seasons before Jackson won his first title, eight
different coaches _ Jack Ramsay, Dick Motta, Wilkens, Paul
Westhead, Bill Fitch, Riley, K.C. Jones and Chuck Daly _ won NBA
titles and ultimately moved to other teams without capturing
another title. Riley, Fitch and Jones did make it to the finals
with other teams.
</P>
<P>
   It plainly isn't always just about coaching. Baylor said you
have to compare the talent those coaches won with to what they
inherited with the other teams.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Ford became the Celtics coach the final two years of Larry
Bird's declining career. Three years after Bird retired, Ford was
fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timing is everything,'' said Ford, now the Clippers coach.
``Where you are with the athletes you're dealing with, where are
they in the prime of their careers. A lot of things go into making
a winning situation. It doesn't just happen by waving a magic
wand.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford, who played 10 years, said there is no denying a team
recognizes when it has a coach of significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Bill Fitch came to Boston, I thought he was going to make
a difference,'' Ford said. ``We ended up winning a title and had
large success.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Sharman, the Lakers special consultant and coach of the
1972 title team, said a coach who has won before should
automatically get the attention of a young team like the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past we've had coaches ... where they didn't have that
much of a reputation, and sometimes the players can take advantage
of that,'' Sharman said. ``If they don't win they can say, `Well,
the system is not right for me or the players.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But with Phil _ besides that he's an outstanding teacher _
with his reputation and six championships, the players are not
going to be able to say it's the coach's fault, it's the coach's
system that doesn't work. Because we know it does. Now we just feel
we have the best coach available.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said the impact of a coach typically doesn't rest upon
the coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it depends more on the team than the coach,'' Jackson
said. ``You have a few systems that are really dominant in this
game now. Most typically run similar stuff out on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a unique system of offense we want to work with, so I
think it's more or less what we're doing rather than who's doing
it. History has obviously not been necessarily a precursor of
coaches moving from one place to another to win a championship, but
that doesn't mean that you can't take a system and keep moving and
find a way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson points out Wilt Chamberlain ran similar systems under
different teams and coaches for his two titles. Those systems were
similar to his triangle, and Chamberlain a player similar to
O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have new people in this system eventually,'' Jackson
said. ``Right now I came to bring a change to the system. Not to
bring this team, perhaps as personnel, to a championship. If you
get my distinction.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has a long contract, and added to his success, instant
respect. During an exhibition game against the Jazz last week at
the Pond, when O'Neal was replaced in the fourth quarter, Jackson
waited in front of the scorer's table.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stand here,'' Jackson said, pointing to an area directly in
front of him.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal stood exactly there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to look at this guy and say, `Hey, he's won
championships. He's had a great deal of success.' He's going to
have an easier time as far as convincing the players this will
work, whatever system he's going to implement,'' Baylor said. ``If
you've been successful at it, it's much easier to get players'
attention. And that's the key thing.''
</P>
<P>
   It always begins, however, with talent. And plenty of other
teams have talent. Portland is the popular pick to capture this
coming season's NBA title, yet no one suggests Mike Dunleavy is a
superior coach than Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   In the Los Angeles area, though, Jackson is in the spotlight. He
is the difference-maker, the savior, despite all that history and
the difficult odds of actually pulling it off, particularly in his
first season with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really feel if we can get everyone healthy and they can
learn this new triangle system quick enough, they have a good
chance at a championship year,'' Sharman said. ``But to be
realistic, it might take all the team half the season to learn this
system. It might be a little difficult to predict a championship
the first year. But it's certainly not out of the question.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
