<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALPHABET SOUP IS BRAIN FOOD
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ I'm not a member of Mensa, due in part to my
adherence to the Groucho Marx rule of organization membership, but
Dave Pressman sent me a copy of the current local Mensa newsletter.
<P>
   It's called the Intelligencer, possibly to remind members that
they are, like, more intelligencer than the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Atop the monthly Calendar of Events is a glossary of codes used
with the various event listings. Such as: BYOB means bring your own
beverage.
</P>
<P>
   Some others: LCR (light carpet rules _ no red wine or other
staining substances), PFE (perfume-free event), WBC (well-behaved
children), FE (fictional event).
</P>
<P>
   I'm guessing if it's an FE, all the other rules are off; it's
KBFD (Katy bar the fictional door).
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's city election, by the way, is an NFE (non-fictional
event), BYOB (bring ye olde brain), NDDVP (no dead or duplicate
voters, please).
</P>
<P>
   And today's column from this WBC (well-behaved columnist) is
coded NUT (no unifying theme), FE (frictional event), WOAHCSB
(written on a Halloween-candy sugar buzz).
</P>
<P>
   A BAD SIGN, as if 49er fans need another: In the NFL Shop on
Pier 39, William Stern came across a rack of Steve Young and Jerry
Rice 49er jerseys on sale, half-off.  &UR; Go, 24.5ers!  &LR; (That was for
our Mensa friends.)
</P>
<P>
   The sale is glumly appropriate, because Rice has half his old
speed and Young's thinking processes may be marked down 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   So preoccupied is everyone with Young's playing (or non-playing)
status that nobody's even talking about the fact that he's engaged
again.
</P>
<P>
   SOMETHING FISHY: Remember good old Spenger's Seafood Grotto in
Berkeley, born in the 1800s and died of old-aged fish a year ago?
It was supposed to re-open in August after a massive $2 million
renovation. Didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   Latest word: It will open the first week of December, boasting
$6 mil in renovations. For that kind of dough I hope they're
raising the Titanic and using it as a salad bar.
</P>
<P>
   CRIME BEAT: In the border zone between the P.D.'s Park District
and its Northern District, some thugs were busily mugging the
muggable _ the weak, the elderly, women alone. There were at least
five attacks over a month, including a German woman tourist who was
choked unconscious and robbed.
</P>
<P>
   When she was revived, the woman hit the streets with the cops as
they traced clues and made the bust, the three bad guys confessing
to the series of attacks. Good to see the tourists helping the cops
clean up the city.
</P>
<P>
   CRIME BEAT II: At the Pan Pacific Hotel near Union Square, man
sneaks into underground garage, drives up and out in a shiny new
Jaguar convertible that isn't his.
</P>
<P>
   Eagle-eyed doorman Marlin Pelejo sizes up the situation, yells
to front-drive attendant Angel Lozano, ``Get in your car and follow
that Jag!''
</P>
<P>
   Around corner from hotel, Jag man stops at red light, primps
hair and puts down convertible top. Then he pulls into a station at
4th and Folsom to gas up with a stolen credit card. Lozano calls
cops on his cell phone, and, bless those little technomiracles,
four cop cars arrive, nab stylish scofflaw.
</P>
<P>
   When you've got Marlin and Angel, who needs Nash Bridges?
</P>
<P>
   ENOUGH IS ENOUGH: I get a report from within this very Chronicle
Building that some of the men's rooms have toilet paper printed
with advertising: ``Get the poop on building an online community.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly a case of ``Is nothing sacred?'' But I was
hoping we'd at least get through the current millennium without
this sort of thing.
</P>
<P>
   TRULY SCARY: The traffic around the greater Metreon area
Saturday afternoon was blood curdling. Lines of cars wound around
entire huge blocks, waiting for parking. It was blocks and blocks
of gridlox, no bagels.
</P>
<P>
   And creeping along with the rest of the log-jammed vehicles:
Muni buses. So those who took Muni to do their civic transit-first
duty suffered along with the sinners.
</P>
<P>
   People eager to have fun, breathe the San Francisco air and
spend money were doing none of the above. They were sucking
tailpipe while nursing rat-in-cage rage.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's time to take another look at closing Market Street
for the bottom two miles. At least the buses would move, thus
encouraging people to ride 'em. Sebastian Johnck points out that a
sticky Market Street clogs the feng shui of the entire city. Lose
the cars, he says, and we'll see:
</P>
<P>
   ``Walkers waving at happy bike messengers delivering vital
documents safely. The city coming together at the Market Street
Promenade. Beer gardens, European models strutting in elevator
shoes, happy palm trees waving at the European models. That's good
feng shui.''
</P>
<P>
   THE MOURNING for Payne Stewart isn't over in this neck of the
state. Lou Bristol points out that the two major golf events next
year are the Crosby/AT&AMP;T and the U.S. Open, both at Pebble Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The most-honored golfer at these events is always the previous
year's champion. And in both tournaments, that's Payne Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD SERIES? I sneezed and missed it. All I know is that the
MVP was Pete Rose, and Jim Gray was banned from baseball for life
for betting that TV viewers wanted a rubber-hose interrogation of
Rose.
</P>
<P>
   No salutes here to the Yankees. I will never give my affection
to a Steinbrenner team.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Braves' fans, now they can retire to the privacy of
their own trailers and put that rhythmic up-and-down hand motion to
more productive use.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 0332EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
