<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISH-ANCIENT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANCIENT FISH RAISE MOUNTAIN OF QUESTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
An ugly fish with snapping teeth, found dead in an Indonesian
marketplace two summers ago, is posing a new puzzle for scientists
tracing the faint record of continental mountain-building over
millions of years across the vast Indian Ocean.
<P>
   The fish is called a coelacanth (see-la-canth) known to
biologists as a ``living fossil'' because its remains date back for
at least 350 million years in the fossil record. And scientists
thought it had been extinct for at least 80 million years, until a
living specimen was caught in a fisherman's net off the Indian
Ocean coast of southern Africa some 60 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, scientists had assumed that the coelacanth's only
habitat was in the deep waters of volcanic caves around the tiny
Comoro islands, which lie between Africa and Madagascar.
</P>
<P>
   The coelacanths there have been rarely caught, and they have
long been listed as an endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   But two summers ago, marine biologists were astounded when Arnaz
Mehta, the wife of a young Berkeley post-doctoral researcher named
Mark Erdmann, stumbled on what appeared to be a coelacanth in a
fish market on the Indonesian island of Manado Tua off the north
coast of Sulawesi.
</P>
<P>
   That fish had been swimming in deep water off the island's
volcanic shore, more than 6,000 miles from the Comoro islands.
Scientists could not understand how it could have shown up in
Indonesia. They even puzzled over its true identity.
</P>
<P>
   Erdmann's research project involves studying the ecology of
shrimp species in an effort to protect Indonesia's endangered coral
reefs, and he is no coelacanth specialist. But his friend,
ichthyologist John McCosker of the California Academy of Sciences
in San Francisco, flew to Sulawesi to compare the strange fish with
the coelacanths he had encountered many times on expeditions to the
Comoro islands. They seemed identical.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Similar Fish, Different DNA
</P>
<P>
   Then a team of French biologists sampled the Manado coelacanth
and studied its gene sequences to compare them with the Comoro
fish. They found distinct differences in portions of the DNA in the
two samples.
</P>
<P>
   The French biologists declared that the two fish represented two
distinct species of coelacanth. Using a technique that assumes the
rates in time  &LR; at which the different DNA samples diverged from
each other, they reported that the two populations probably
separated about 1.3 million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Comoro creatures bear the scientific name Latimeria
chalumnae, and the French biologists, who had only a single sample,
named the Manado species Latimeria menadoensis.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Caldwell, a Berkeley biology professor and Erdmann's senior
colleague, then flew to Indonesia and brought back another
coelacanth sample frozen in liquid nitrogen.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell enlisted the help of a University of Texas group headed
by David Hillis that specializes in using DNA analysis as a kind of
``molecular clock'' to estimate when apparently identical fish
species might have diverged long ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas scientists estimated the coelacanths from opposite
sides of the world must have diverged into two separate species at
least 5 to 6 million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   One of the unique features of coelacanths is the lobe-shaped
structure of their paired fins, a characteristic that seems to link
them on the evolutionary time scale to four-footed salamanders,
while other aspects of their bodies seem to relate them to even
more ancient sharks.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Fish and Geology
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the two coelacanth species may well have diverged
as long  &LR; far back as 16 million years ago _ a time when the bed of
the huge Indian Ocean was in a state of upheaval, riven by volcanic
activity by the rise and fall of mid-ocean ridges and by the
crashing of the Indian subcontinent against what are now the
Himalayan mountain ranges.
</P>
<P>
   It was also a time when many forms of life around the world
became permanently separated, with each group evolving
independently over the millennia into distinctly different species
_ some adopting totally different body shapes and others
indistinguishable except for their DNA sequences.
</P>
<P>
   Erdmann and his wife are still in Sulawesi, and this week they
will be joined by German scientist Hans Fricke and his two-person
submarine, Jago. Fricke has filmed coelacanths off the Comoros, and
he and Erdmann will explore the steep underwater cliff sides of the
islands off Sulawesi to hunt for still more cave-dwelling
Indonesian coelacanths.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a case where the fishes and their ancestors can teach
the geologists a lot about the way continents were formed and
volcanoes erupted a long, long time ago,'' said McCosker, of the
Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   A report on the new coelacanth species appears in the current
issue of the Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
