<HEADER>
A4948 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CRASH-CAIRO-BOS &LR;      11-01 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-CAIRO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POIGNANT STORIES MIX WITH GRIEF IN CAIRO
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO _ Horror and chaos engulfed the makeshift information
center at Cairo International Airport Sunday as scores of family
members scanned a computer list of the 217 people aboard EgyptAir
Flight 990.
</P>
<P>
   From those who had confirmed loved ones were on board the downed
plane, there were tears and cries of anguish. A man with gray hair
was wailing, ``My son. My son. His baby is 6 months old.''
</P>
<P>
   A middle-aged woman in a black veil grabbed the list from the
EgyptAir officials, screaming, ``I want to know. I have to know.''
</P>
<P>
   She saw the list, and collapsed. A team of doctors and nurses
attended to her, first with smelling salts, then with what appeared
to be a tranquilizer. In one corner of the room, a family was
weeping and joining in quiet prayers as they read from the Koran.
</P>
<P>
   Hishem Mansour saw on the tattered computer list the name of his
cousin, Wala Hanafi, 21, but demanded further, ``Is she dead or is
she lost?''
</P>
<P>
   Some were too terrified even to check the list, not wanting to
see what they feared.
</P>
<P>
   Tariq Samek stood in the hallway just outside the room in
Terminal One after seeing that the name of his brother, Khalid
Samek, was on the flight manifest. Crying, he waved off questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is there to say?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Every story from every family seemed to produce tears.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most poignant was the story of Mustafa El Shura, a
well-known professor at Ain Shams University, who had come to pick
up his daughter, Jihen. She was an American citizen who was eight
months pregnant and flying home to give birth to the child in
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Mahmud Rashad, the chief manager of the airport who spoke with
El Shura, said, ``It was very sad. He was asking so many questions.
And there are just no answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Zein Ahmed, a cook at a diner in Albany, N.Y., had waited for
hours at the Cairo airport to find the news that his cousin, Imad
Suliman, 31, was on board the flight. The victim, whom he described
as ``like a brother to me,'' was a communications engineer in the
Egyptian military who, he said, had been training at a US military
base in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed, who was in Egypt for a three-week vacation, said his
cousin, Suliman, was very excited about making his first trip to
America. He left behind his wife, their 1-month-old infant son, and
a 16-month-old son.
</P>
<P>
   His eyes were red from crying, and his rapid-fire questions
focused on the location of the crash in the deep waters off
Nantucket where the plane went down.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the first time in this location. John Kennedy, TWA
800, Swissair, and now EgyptAir . . . Why is this happening in this
location?'' Ahmed asked. ``There has to be some answer. There are
too many questions in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Egypt's leading newspapers in Monday 's editions also keyed in
on the location where the plane disappeared in their coverage. The
front page of Al Ahram had a headline that read: ``The Worst
Catastrophe in the History of Civil Aviation: The plane fell in the
same place as the TWA and Swissair crashes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Al Waf'd newspaper carried a story headlined, ``The Curse of
the Kennedy Family is Chasing Egyptian planes.''
</P>
<P>
   EgyptAir chairman Mohammed Fahim Rayan spoke to a crush of
reporters outside the terminal, saying, ``We are trying to make
sure that we give the families all of the information we have and
to be sure they are given all of the assistance we can provide
them.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was seething anger against the airline among some of
the passengers. The 67-year-old national carrier has never had to
handle a downing of this magnitude and seemed ill prepared for
procedures to assist the grieving, questioning families.
</P>
<P>
   Suhir Hatut, 50, wearing a black dress, had just learned that
her sister, Wafa'a, 56, and brother-in-law, Adel, 56, were aboard
the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Through tears, she directed her anger at the airline's chairman,
saying, ``I will take a gun and walk into Rayan's office and shoot
him.''
</P>
<P>
   But others, like Ahmed, were more understanding of the confusion
at the airport and less questioning of the airline's competence.
``I wish it was more sophisticated, more developed. But we are a
developing country. I do not have major complaints,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One issue that seemed to be consuming the families was how they
would retrieve the bodies for proper burial. In the Muslim faith,
it is important for the dead to be buried immediately, typically
before sundown the day after death.
</P>
<P>
   Hesham el Shaer, who had just confirmed that his cousin Hussein
Ismael, 33, was on board the flight, said to an EgyptAir official,
``How can we bring him home? . . . My relatives' parents are
killing themselves over this.''
</P>
<P>
   In this religious and traditional culture, most of the victims'
families seemed to turn to faith amid tragedy. Samiha Isaeli had
come to the airport to pick up her sister and brother-in-law at the
airport. They were moving home after 15 years in America, she said.
She arrived thrilled with the idea of bringing them back into the
family fold, only to collapse in tears upon hearing the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``God is all that survives in this,'' she said. ``Only God can
help you understand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 0924EST &QL; 
