A4955 &Cx1f; var-z
u v BC-R-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      11-01 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Sunday, Oct. 31, moved Saturday and are repeated
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in the `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   ETHNIC-POLITICS-REVIEW (New York) _ Ethnic politics has reached
a level of complexity that is confounding politicians across the
nation. Candidates are being forced to take positions on
complicated issues, pitting the perceived interests of one ethnic
group against the sentiment of the population at large, or dividing
members of these purportedly solid constituencies by generation,
ideology and economic class. These pressures come at time when
ethnic groups that once existed at the margins of politics have
become powerful forces. The Senate race in New York may provide an
intricate roadmap for where ethnic politics in U.S. is heading. By
Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   OBESITY-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at the upsurge in obesity and
the prospects of drugs and other treatments for dealing with it. A
hormone called leptin that was supposed to be the magic bullet for
obesity, making people effortlessly lose fat while retaining
muscle, looks like a bust. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   PRESCHOOL-REVIEW (Undated) _ What is the appropriate age for
children to start school? Americans instinctively say 5 or 6. In
some European countries, toddlers of 2 and 3 attend government-run
classes. And with a host of new research showing lasting impact of
education in the earliest years of life, along with the continued
push of women into the workforce _ both among upper-class
professionals and former welfare recipients _ a movement for
universal preschool in the U.S. is gaining momentum. By Jodi
Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   SUBSTANTIVE-POLITICS-REVIEW (Undated) _ For all the grousing
about 30-second sound bites and shallow politicians, this already
has been one of the most substantive presidential campaigns in
years _ if not decades. Candidate after candidate has issued quite
detailed position papers on a host of issues, far more and far
earlier than the last few campaigns. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   SIDEWALK-TV-REVIEW (New York) _ Early-morning television is
taking to the sidewalks here as never before _ sidewalks that have
become, in effect, sound stages where cameras can capture the
exuberance of nose-to-the-glass fans waving, shouting and reveling
in their 15 seconds of fame. By James Barron.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-FEAR-ADS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Be afraid. Be very afraid.
This is the message at the heart of public health campaigns
encouraging young people to abandon unhealthy behavior like
smoking, binge drinking or unsafe sex. From billboards to public
service ads to ``Scared Straight,'' appeals to fear endure despite
mixed reviews from public health and communications experts and
doubts about whether such entreaties can effect long-term behavior
change. By Jeff Stryker.
</P>
<P>
   DOW-ECON-REVIEW (New York) _ The Dow Jones industrial average
has long been viewed as the most prominent measure of the financial
health of Corporate America. Maybe now it should be seen as a
barometer of how fast the U.S. economy is changing. By Floyd
Norris.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Moved in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIAN-ECON-REVIEW (Ramallah, West Bank) _ A new route for
goods and people between the West Bank and Gaza offers the prospect
of unifying them into one integrated economy, a prerequisite for
building a viable Palestinian state. But new opening has already
exposed the stark cultural and economic contrasts between the two
regions. Now, the poorer, more religious and less educated Gazans
will compete for jobs with the more settled and secular urbanites
of the West Bank. This could mean unwelcome sacrifices for the West
Bank, and could trigger resentment and envy among the Gazans. By
William Orme.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL-ASIA-MUSLIMS-REVIEW (Osh, Kyrgyzstan) _ The appearance
of Islamic insurgents in this remote Central Asian country has not
only shocked regional leaders and their Russian and Chinese
neighbors. It has also awakened the world to a troubling new
phenomenon: the existence of a floating army of religious fighters
who are roaming this part of the world in search of regimes to
overthrow. By Steven Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-U.S.-REVIEW (Washington) _ A delicate diplomatic question
of the moment in the Clinton administration: Who will lead the U.S.
delegation to the formal handover of the Panama Canal in December.
Volunteers are not exactly flooding the White House with calls. By
David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-CORRUPTION-REVIEW (Undated) _ Each year, Transparency
International, a non-profit group based in Berlin that specializes
in tracking global thievery, releases a list of the world's most
corrupt countries. But while Transparency's work has been lauded
for helping to make corruption a centerpiece of economic
development debates, some economists say the group's hit-list
unfairly tars countries that may be no more corrupt than those
ranked much lower. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-REVIEW (Rome) _ It looks like the lunch menu, but it's
really your child's report card. A first-hand account of poor
public service in Italy, with the focus on schools. By Alessandra
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Weekends, Tim Hilchey (e-mail, hilchey(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 346-9867
