<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: There's more than isolationism to GOP's meanness
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   White House national security adviser Samuel Berger has deplored
congressional foreign-policy votes and meanness in foreign-affairs
funding this year as a new isolationism, but that seems too fine a
word for what looks, in sum, more like simple vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of Congress have honest policy differences with the
administration over specifics. Others would have Washington scale
down its international involvements out of worry we are
overextended, a legitimate if doubtful point. But more are using
foreign policy as a way to impeach President Clinton piecemeal out
of pique they couldn't convict him outright.
</P>
<P>
   Rank partisanship was notoriously at play in the Senate defeat
of the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, forfeiting U.S. arms control
leadership that goes back to the Eisenhower presidency. GOP leaders
agreed to hearings, and just perfunctory ones even then, only after
they had locked up enough votes to reject the pact, in effect
holding the trial after sentence has been pronounced.
</P>
<P>
   The leadership continues ceding its bitter Foreign Affairs
Committee chairman, Jesse Helms, arbitrary power over
ambassadorships. Helms earlier killed the nominations of William
Weld (a Republican, mind you) to Mexico and Robert Pastor to Panama
out of political grudges. Now he's barring Carol Moseley-Braun from
appointment to New Zealand. Moseley-Braun, when she was in the
Senate, frustrated Helms's effort to grant the Daughters of the
Confederacy an official federal patent to use the Confederate flag.
</P>
<P>
   Cumulatively, the greatest damage to U.S. world leadership and
interests is in Congress's parsimony. GOP majorities have:
</P>
<P>
   _ Failed to provide funds to hold up our part of the
U.S.-brokered Wye River Accords that restarted Middle East
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Withheld funding essential to American participation in Kosovo
peacekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   _ Impoverished our program to shield the nuclear facilities,
personnel and weapons of the former Soviet Union from exploitation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Withheld funds from efforts to restrain North Korea's nuclear
arms development.
</P>
<P>
   _ Again indulged an anti-abortion amendment that would hamper
U.S. participation in family-planning projects overseas, holding up
payment of our United Nations dues by assuring a presidential veto.
Deadbeat America is close to losing its U.N. vote, even though U.N.
peacekeeping from East Timor to Sierra Leone serves our manifest
interest in international stability.
</P>
<P>
   Is any matter too small to escape abuse? The U.S.-Canadian
Pacific Salmon Agreement ends years of friction, but GOP leaders
have put the accord in jeopardy with anti-environment riders that
risk another presidential veto.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign operations budget approved by Congress this year
runs at only half of 1985's rate. By increasing our reliance on
military means alone to assert U.S. interests, Congress isn't so
much slipping into neo-isolationism as it is scrapping a working,
companionate internationalism for an unbecoming bully
internationalism.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
