<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 10:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4985 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-SIDEWALK-TV-REVIEW-     11-01 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SIDEWALK-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORNINGS, THEY LIKE TO WATCH
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(bl) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ East Side, West Side, all around the town,
early-morning television is taking to the sidewalks of New York as
never before _ sidewalks that have become, in effect, sound stages
where cameras can capture the exuberance of nose-to-the-glass fans
waving, shouting and reveling in their 15 seconds of fame.
</P>
<P>
   Picture-window studios have become a New York phenomenon.
Network executives say stations in other cities cannot afford to
spend millions on studios the way the networks can, and besides,
New York is the people-watching capital of the world, and the
networks know it. Every aunt or grandmother who tunes in, hoping
for a glimpse of a relative in the background behind Matt and Katie
or Charlie and Diane or, starting Monday, Bryant and Jane, adds to
a show's ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This breaks every rule in TV 101,'' said Robert Thompson, a
professor of film and television at Syracuse University. ``You're
not supposed to take the attention off the business at hand, but
when the business at hand needs a little push, the audience
provides a vast and sometimes amusing unpaid cast.''
</P>
<P>
   And so ABC and CBS are trying to catch up to the ``Today'' show
on NBC, which moved to a first-floor studio in Rockefeller Center
in 1994. Ever since, ``Today'' has been showing off its
standing-room-only sidewalk space _ and bragging about displacing
``Good Morning America'' for the lead in the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Imitation is the surest form of television; ABC moved ``Good
Morning America'' into a glass-walled studio in Times Square in
September. ``Today'' remains No. 1, but since ``Good Morning
America'' began showing crowds on the lower level of its two-story
studio and inviting a lucky few upstairs for consumer-affairs
segments, its ratings have risen somewhat.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Nov. 1, CBS moves its newly renamed ``Early Show'' to
Fifth Avenue and 59th Street, with world-famous hotels in the
background. CBS is betting that its new studio will help make the
network competitive in the morning for the first time since
``Captain Kangaroo'' went off the air a generation ago.
</P>
<P>
   But not all the hotels are looking forward to the arrival of
Bryant Gumbel and Jane Clayton and their fans. The
Sherry-Netherland Hotel went to court to block CBS' plans,
complaining that the show would lead to overcrowded sidewalks and
noise that could wake late sleepers at the hotel. ``People will be
waving and shouting and creating that fake Beatlemania-like
sensation,'' the hotel said in court papers. A CBS spokesman would
say only that the matter remains unresolved, but that the two sides
have been talking.
</P>
<P>
   The networks have spent heavily to show their viewers New York
up close. NBC spent $15 million; CBS is said to have spent $30
million. MTV also broadcasts from studios with floor-to-ceiling
windows. Its home, across Broadway from the new ``Good Morning
America'' quarters, draws neck-craning fans hoping for a glimpse of
their favorite veejay or, better, their favorite rock star. (The
neck-craning is a must. Unlike the ``Today'' and ``Early Show''
studios, MTV's base of operations is on the second floor.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously the success of the `Today' show woke other
television people up,'' said Steve Friedman, who was the executive
producer of ``Today'' when it moved and now has the same job at its
new CBS competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Something else that woke up the networks' decision-makers was
New York's surging popularity as a tourist destination. ``New York
is hot again,'' Thompson said. ```Seinfeld' did this, `Friends' did
this, and they contributed to the idea that New York is the place
to be. There was a sense a few years ago that you wanted to ignore
New York, the symbol of all kinds of collapse, the inner city, the
economy. That's all changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Out-of-towners find themselves peering in the morning shows'
windows because there is not much to do at 7 a.m. The Statue of
Liberty and the observatory at the Empire State Building do not
open until 9:30.
</P>
<P>
   For the folks back home, the streetscape provides an element
that producers consider increasingly important _ ``visual relief.''
Playing peekaboo with passersby gives viewers something more than
just another glitzy set filled with people sitting around talking.
</P>
<P>
   If two's company, Friedman's show will make an early-morning
crowd. But he said the decision to put the hosts in front of glass
was not about imitation. ``The fact is that people expect more out
of television than a studio that's supposed to look like somebody's
living room or dining room and isn't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His counterpart at ``Good Morning America,'' Shelly Ross, said
the new studio provides a pool of people who can go on the show and
or talk with consumer experts about why they buy what they buy or
eat what they eat. ``In the past,'' she said, ``Good Morning
America'' relied on ``handpicked friends of friends of friends''
for such interviews.
</P>
<P>
   But showing crowds on live television is not without risks.
``When you see people holding up one finger, you wonder are they
saying, `You're No. 1,''' Thompson said, ``or are they saying
something else?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 1029EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0090 </DOCNO>
