<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4440 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-SUBSTANTIVE-POLITIC     11-01 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SUBSTANTIVE-POLITICS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATES, TAKING A STAND, MIX POLICY AND PERSONA 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(bl) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, N.H. _ It was once a sure-fire attack strategy in
presidential debates: Candidates turn to their rivals and scold
them for espousing policies that are fanciful, shallow and even
risky. ``Where's the beef?'' asked Walter Mondale, memorably
needling Gary Hart during the Democratic primary campaign in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   No one's asking now. The 2000 campaign has been marked by an
extraordinary (if not mind-numbing) degree of substance. Candidates
have issued more meaty 10- and 12-point plans, earlier in the
season, than ever before in presidential politics. The question is,
will it pay off? Or are the voters more attuned to that elusive and
much-trumpeted concept, character?
</P>
<P>
   The dueling over policy pronouncements by Vice President Al Gore
and Bill Bradley was on display last week at the first televised
debate here at Dartmouth College. They eagerly plunged into a
discussion of the intricacies of more funding for special
education, health insurance for children and protections for
homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   The leading Republican candidate, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, has
issued stacks of position papers (his recent education plan was 12
single-spaced pages) to fend off critiques that he is, in the
parlance of his state of Texas, more hat than horse. But he doesn't
talk about them as much, preferring to project a Reaganesque
geniality and optimism.
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, the candidates' handling of issues reveals their
own approaches and personalities. Gore and Bradley built their
Senate careers on mastery of daunting matters like the environment
and tax system overhauls. ``He's equal part dreamer and policy
wonk,'' Eric Hauser, a Bradley spokesman, said of his boss.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, partly because he prides himself on not sweating the
details, speaks more about grand themes that have served him well
as governor. He is, no doubt, mindful of polls showing that while
most people are not paying much attention to the presidential
contest, those who do seem more interested in the candidates'
personal qualities.
</P>
<P>
   Still, by being substantive, candidates can achieve other goals.
``There's an implicit presidential aura to presenting six-point
programs,'' said Anthony Dolan, a former speechwriter for Ronald
Reagan. ``There's a subliminal message you send to voters: `I have
the will to govern.''' Some candidates use detailed policies to
prove their bona fides with a narrow group of partisans and
interest groups whose support is crucial in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   There is another practical explanation for so much substance so
early: Because the primary schedule next year is the most
compressed in history, the entire process is accelerated.
Candidates who wait until January to issue proposals may be
dismissed as too slow _ or imitating their rivals.
</P>
<P>
   And in the past, candidates did not have to be so specific
because the parties often set the agenda. During the Cold War, the
prescriptions for dealing with the Soviet Union were starkly
different in both parties. Now that there are fewer differences _
and no overriding, burning issues _ candidates face greater
pressure to define themselves through their distinct plans.
</P>
<P>
   The danger for politicians is they can get tripped up in the
minutiae. Gore, relying on his vast experience in the White House
and in Congress, has emphasized his command of the issues. But
early this year he put out such a blizzard of issue papers that the
Bradley camp ridiculed him for being bogged down in small-bore
matters. He has tried to remedy that recently by mixing the policy
with the personal.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates complain that if they dwell on issues, the media
ignores them and focuses on personality and the horse race anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has also learned the down side of serving up too much
detail. Refuting accusations that his proposals lacked heft, he
boasted that he was going further than most politicians in setting
a price tag _ $65 billion a year _ for his plan to make health care
available to virtually all uninsured Americans. But in doing so, he
gave Gore an opening that the vice president happily seized upon
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be a big idea.'' Gore said, ``but it's not a good
idea.'' Should Bradley makes it to the Democratic nomination, that
line may well turn up in the Republicans' attack commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers, as well as Bradley's, have urged their
candidates not to be prodded into appearing like policy mavens.
``Yes, a tax plan is important and, yes, an education proposal is
important,'' said Karen Hughes, Bush's communications director.
``But the specific percentage of a proposed tax cut is probably
less important to the average voter than, `Do I agree with this
candidate's overall philosophy?'''
</P>
<P>
   Gore hopes he can undermine Bradley in the same way President
Gerald R. Ford poked holes in a plan issued by Reagan during the
campaign for the 1976 Republican nomination that called for
stripping $90 billion from the federal budget. The proposal created
a firestorm, with the Ford campaign warning that it would cause
massive cuts in federal programs. The Ford camp issued detailed
breakdowns of how the plan would damage New Hampshire, which holds
the first primary. Reagan was so unnerved by the criticism that he
backed away from it, saying he ``didn't pay attention'' when aides
listed the $90 billion in cuts _ and that he meant his proposal to
be taken only figuratively.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Besides worrying how their opponents will respond, candidates
have to be mindful that voters do not always take detailed policy
proposals at face value. When Bob Dole, the Republican nominee in
1996, issued the economic and political foundation of his campaign
_ a 15 percent income tax cut and a halving of the capital gains
tax _ polls showed that voters did not view it too seriously.
That's because the Dole campaign publicly tinkered with several
alternatives. It did not help that President Clinton's campaign
distributed quotations to reporters in which Dole had belittled the
supply-side economics that was central to his proposal.
</P>
<P>
   A heavy emphasis on substance was first notable during the 1992
Democratic presidential run by then-Gov. Bill Clinton, former Sen.
Paul Tsongas and Sen. Bob Kerrey. All sought to demonstrate their
seriousness of purpose. Substance, indeed, was a way for Clinton to
deflect questions about his personal conduct and assure voters that
he knew how to fix the economy. One of his strategists, George
Stephanopoulos, went as far as to say that ``specificity is the
character issue of '92.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, of course, never escaped questions about his integrity.
In the current campaign, politicians who want to succeed him are
again trying to use substance to prove their own character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because Clinton was perceived to be a smooth operator, there's
an extra motivation for candidates this year to show that that's
not them,'' said Dan Schnur, communications director for Sen. John
McCain, who is seeking the Republican nomination. ``The way you do
that is by flashing the policy credential. Bob Dole stood up and
said, `I have character.' That's not good enough. Policy is the
prism through which voters judge character.''
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis on substance may seem like a public service. But
the bad news is that the more candidates propose, the more they
overpromise. Clinton had ambitious plans for his national service
program that were scaled back after his election. Chances are, most
of the heady dreams of Campaign 2000 will never be more than
dreams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 1031EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
