<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4995 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-PALESTINIAN-ECON-RE     11-01 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-PALESTINIAN-ECON-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LINK THAT DRIVES PALESTINIANS APART 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMALLAH, West Bank _ In jeans and T-shirts, each carrying a
small gym bag, a group of young Gaza men drew taunts and stares as
they wandered the streets here Friday evening in a fruitless search
for work. ``They told us we were ruining Ramallah,'' said Adham
A'jour, 22, taken aback by the hostility. ``People in the West Bank
should be more understanding of our situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Shadi Achmed, his companion, concurred: ``I felt that they hated
us the way that they were looking at us. If they come to Gaza, we
will treat them the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   The two 22-year-olds were among the first of several hundred
Gazans to travel a two-lane road to the rocky uplands of the West
Bank last week, an hour's drive but still an eventful journey.
Cousins embraced for the first time since Israel closed its borders
to most Gazans six years ago. Young day-trippers eyed their first
mountains. And Palestinian peace negotiators hailed the belated
fulfillment of a promise extracted from Israel by President Clinton
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   This new ``safe passage'' route for goods as well as people
holds out the promise of unifying the West Bank and Gaza into one
integrated economy, a prerequisite for building a viable
Palestinian state. But in a place like Ramallah, the bustling
administrative center of the Palestinian-governed West Bank, the
sudden appearance of Gazan visitors aroused undisguised
trepidation.
</P>
<P>
   Although people here welcome the theoretical prospect of
Palestinian unity, the new opening has already exposed the stark
cultural and economic contrasts between the two regions. Now the
poorer, more religious and less educated Gazans will compete for
jobs with the more settled and secular urbanites of the West Bank.
This could mean unwelcome sacrifices for the West Bank, and could
trigger resentment and envy among the Gazans.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment in Gaza hovers above 17 percent, double the rate in
the West Bank. And the median age in the Strip is just 14, compared
to 17 in the West Bank. In southern Gaza, the poorest and most
densely populated Palestinian region, per capita spending is $2.50
a day, far below the still-modest $6.00 average around Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
   ``In taxis and shops throughout the West Bank, people have been
whispering about the changes these newcomers might cause in the job
market,'' noted Daoud Kuttab, a political columnist in Ramallah.
``They are afraid that the Gazans will accept lower wages than are
being paid now, and that many employers will be tempted to exploit
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Prominent economists say West Bankers are right to be worried.
Hisham Awatani of the Palestinian Center for Research and Studies
in Nablus contends West Bank wages will inevitably drop if Gaza
job-seekers can freely relocate. And with access to porous West
Bank borders, Gazan immigrants will also compete for high-paying
construction jobs in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all saw what happened to Germany after unification,''
Awatani said. ``There is often an economic price to be paid for
political goals.'' That price won't be paid by economists or
government planners, however.
</P>
<P>
   Equally problematic, an economic merger of a million Gazans and
nearly 2 million West Bankers requires bridging a cultural chasm.
The West Bank is worldly, secular, educated and entrepreneurial,
while the closed, ingrown economy of Gaza mirrors the insular,
religious, walled-in refugee society that fostered it. Despite
family ties and a shared Palestinian nationalism, these are two
quite different places.
</P>
<P>
   Even their legal systems remain separate and distinct. In the
West Bank, old Jordanian laws still prevail, with Ottoman and
Napoleonic underpinnings. Gaza is governed by a hybrid Egyptian and
British legal code, though a parallel Islamic court network there
is fast extending its role.
</P>
<P>
   Compounded by geographic separation, this central Palestinian
fault line is at least as profound as the much-analyzed rift
between secular and religious Israelis, with great potential for
political tension as Gaza and the West Bank become intertwined.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest gulf, though, is economic. And it has steadily
widened over the past six years, as Israeli border closures and
transit restrictions caused Gaza commerce to contract by 40 percent
or more.
</P>
<P>
   If the regional economies merge, as safe passage theoretically
permits, Gaza's per capita income of roughly $1,200 and the West
Bank average of $1,700 would gravitate toward a common mean,
economists say. Gaza's living standard should rise more than the
West Bank's would fall, but the short-term impact on West Bankers
could still be acute.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   This transitional pain is worth the long-term gain, many
Palestinians argue. The unemployed youth of Gaza are not only the
most serious economic problem confronting the Palestinian
Authority; they are its greatest political challenge, since they
provide rank-and-file support for the Authority's militant Islamist
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The average Gaza family has six children; population growth is
an explosive 4.3 percent. Gaza desperately needs an economic safety
valve that Israel is unwilling to provide: the only day laborers
permitted into Israel are on a carefully screened list of married
men over 30. And Israel is now unexpectedly suggesting that its
restrictions on Palestinian goods and labor could be tightened
further.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Labor governments of Yitzhak Rabin and Shimon Peres,
the vision of a peaceful, mutually advantageous relationship with
an autonomous or independent Palestinian neighbor always presumed
some kind of free trade area, with open movement of goods, labor
and capital. In 1994, Israel and the Palestinian Authority agreed
on a five-year customs union, lifting most hindrances to internal
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   This free-market approach to peacemaking was one of the few
legacies of the Rabin era to be embraced by Benjamin Netanyahu's
right-wing administration. But now Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who
has long wanted legal and physical barriers between Israelis and
Palestinians, is urging consideration of ``economic separation''
too.
</P>
<P>
   This new notion of separation appears to go well beyond tariff
walls. The Barak government said last week that it was exploring
the legalization of 100,000 or more undocumented workers from East
Asia and Central Europe. Peace negotiators had long assumed that a
final settlement would be an opportunity to replace this illegal
foreign work force with Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Some Palestinians dismiss such talk as a bargaining ploy,
intended to remind Yasser Arafat of his would-be state's dependence
on Israeli investment and commerce. Israel is the lopsided
beneficiary of trade with the Palestinians, selling $1.5 billion
yearly but importing just $250 million, so it has no commercial
motive for protectionism.
</P>
<P>
   But even barring complete Israeli-Palestinian separation, there
are almost infinite gradations of integration. And any new Israeli
barriers will force the West Bank and Gaza even closer together.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, unification should be good for Palestinian
business. Palestinian planners have long complained that Israel's
separation of Gaza from the West Bank made their market too small
to entice serious investors or breed competitive exporters.
Integration should give a quick boost to some local companies:
Cold-pressed Palestinian olive oil could outsell Israeli varieties
in Gaza, while Gaza citrus may replace Jaffa oranges in Hebron
market stalls. But family firms in both Gaza and the West Bank will
also face pressure from more efficient rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as Messrs. Barak and Arafat enter final status talks, they
must devise formulas for the further knitting together of Gaza with
Ramallah and Nablus and Hebron. The initial Palestinian experience
with safe passage will help determine how fast and far unification
will proceed _ and how eagerly it will be embraced by the
Palestinian majority on the West Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
