<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5001 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-WORLD-CORRUPTION-RE     11-01 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-WORLD-CORRUPTION-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S ONE TOP 10 LIST NOBODY WANTS TO MAKE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(bl) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like music CDs, box office receipts and the world's richest
people, corruption has its own top 10 list.
</P>
<P>
   For the last five years Transparency International, a nonprofit
group based in Berlin that specializes in tracking global thievery,
has released the annual Corruption Perceptions Index, ranking the
world's most corrupt countries.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the group declared Cameroon, Nigeria, Indonesia,
Azerbaijan, Uzbekistan, Honduras, Tanzania, Yugoslavia, Paraguay
and Kenya as the world's most graft-ridden countries, populated by
public officials who are much quicker to take bribes than their
counterparts in countries like Denmark, New Zealand and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   But while Transparency's work has been lauded by economists and
other analysts for helping to make corruption a centerpiece of
debates about economic development and public policy, critics say
the group's hit list unfairly tars countries that may be no more
corrupt than those ranked much lower on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, say critics, the media is so quick to latch on to top 10
lists that agencies like Transparency International have an obvious
incentive to present their information that way to score public
relations coups. All the attention generated by the Corruption
Perceptions Index, and criticism that it tended to highlight poor
countries without noting the role that industrialized countries
play in fomenting corruption abroad, led Transparency to introduce
yet another ranking last week _ the Bribe Payers Index.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the worries people have had is that the ranking is very
misleading,'' Rafael di Tella, an economics professor at Harvard
Business School and one of Transparency's outside advisors, said of
the Corruption Perceptions Index. ``Transparency International has
become a slave to the success of the index and it doesn't want to
address the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, as di Tella and others see it, is that the data
used to analyze corruption _ surveys, for example, of business
executives' perceptions _ are so fuzzy that huge margins of error
exist when assigning a numerical yardstick to graft.
</P>
<P>
   Johann Graf Lambsdorff, a German statistician responsible for
orchestrating Transparency's numbers into a coherent whole, says
critics of the list unfairly imply that his methodology is faulty
when, in fact, the only issue is how the results of Transparency's
surveys are presented. Even so, Lambsdorff says he is comfortable
with his group's list.
</P>
<P>
   ``A ranking is easier to convey information to a large public,
like a football ranking,'' said Lambsdorff, a professor at
Goettingen University. ``We can clearly say that Denmark is cleaner
than Germany and Germany is cleaner than Botswana. But in between
there may be some problems _ saying that Kenya is cleaner than
Tanzania, for example.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is precisely the problem, say critics , pointing to
Bolivia's presidential election in 1997 as an example of the list's
far-reaching influence. The former dictator Hugo Banzer won the
presidency that year on an anti-corruption platform bolstered by
the release of Transparency's rankings shortly before the election
_ rankings showing that corruption in Bolivia was worse than in
many of its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Lambsdorff says Transparency cannot avoid having such an impact
because elections are occurring in many countries when their
rankings are released.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep on stressing that these are perceptions, not hard
facts,'' said Frank Vogl, Transparency International's
vice-chairman and co-founder. ``You always have this problem of how
to present the data.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the list has stirred dissent within the group's own
membership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Transparency's index was good when there were no other numbers
available but we need to go further now,'' said Luis Moreno Ocampo,
a prominent anti-corruption crusader in Argentina who is a member
of Transparency's advisory council. ``The issue is not which
country is worse than another, the issue is how to solve the
problem. We need to track where the money is going and who is
stealing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreno has been working with the World Bank to come up with new
methods of measuring and presenting data on corruption. Daniel
Kaufmann, a senior manager with the World Bank, says grouping
countries in broad categories _ rather than ranking them _ is the
fairest way to shine a spotlight on corruption. ``The idea that
Transparency International had is brilliant and now we all want to
be more rigorous and circumspect when we analyze corruption,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 1038EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
