 Monday, Nov. 1, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Mark Helm at
202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTION (Mexico City) _ The Berlin Wall crumbled, the
Soviet Union collapsed and Mexico, too, is changing at the edge of
a new century. That is the comparison made by a Mexican official to
characterize the sweeping changes in the 70-year-old Institutional
Revolutionary Party, the longest ruling party in the world, as it
heads to an unprecedented primary election on Sunday. By SUSANA
HAYWARD.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-MEDIA (Bogota, Colombia) _ Concerned that saturation
coverage of guerrilla attacks, murders and economic woes will scare
off advertisers and readers, major Colombian newspapers, magazines
and television stations are seeking out sunnier stories. By JOHN
OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ELDER-RODEO (San Francisco) _ At 71 years old, Bill Cresta is
one of your older addicts around and an unrepentant one at that.
His vice _ if you can call it that _ is riding in rodeos, a passion
that many of his peers can only enjoy as spectators. Last weekend,
Cresta and 65-year-old partner Jack Montgomery, Cresta participated
in the rodeo's first senior team roping competition. At a combined
age of 136, the pair was the oldest of the five teams in the
competition. By RYAN KIM.
</P>
<P>
   OLDEST-LUTHERAN (Albany, N.Y.) _ In 1649, a mere 132 years after
Martin Luther nailed his Ninety-five Theses to the chapel door in
Wittenberg, followers of his faith founded the First Lutheran
Church of Albany, the oldest Lutheran congregation in the United
States. The church is celebrating its 350th anniversary this year.
By THAI JONES.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NY-COURT-OF-APPEALS (Albany, N.Y.) _ New York state's highest
court has long relished its national prominence as a trailblazing
tribunal that expanded the rights and liberties of individuals. But
in the last few years, some analysts and observers say, the Court
of Appeals has grown timid and conservative and seems now to shy
away from controversial cases and decisions, particularly in
criminal matters. By JOHN CAHER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-WHAT-IF-REVIEW (Undated) _ The World's foremost military
historians imagine what might have been in ``What If?'' (Putnam,
$75), which is edited Robert Cowley. By LEE CEARNAL.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-ALLENDE-PROFILE (Undated) _ American novelist Isabel
Allende's new book, ``Daughter of Fortune'' (HarperCollins, $26),
is a historical novel that moves from Chile to Gold Rush-era
California. By FRITZ LANHAM.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-HAUNTED (Undated) _ If Jan De Bont's ``The
Haunting'' is ``Scooby Doo'' in the
big-scary-mansion-as-amusement-park movie sweepstakes, then ``The
House on Haunted Hill'' is the sub-sub-sub- genre's ``Scrappy
Doo.'' But the two films with their youngish casts couldn't be more
different. One had Anglo-Latina bombshell Catherine Zeta-Jones, the
other has Bridgette Wilson. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL/BUSINESS NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TAX-PLANNING (Undated) _ One of the best ways to reduce any
income taxes you'll owe in the spring is to start figuring your tax
liability now, tax experts say. With nine weeks left in the
calendar year, taxpayers still have time to shift deductions, make
adjustments to retirement accounts and take other legitimate steps
that will lessen the tax burden come next year. By JO-ANN JOHNSTON.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-NO-WINE (Houston) _ Whether it's the herbal bitterness of
an artichoke, the grassiness of asparagus or the high acidity in
chocolate, sometimes a dish simply doesn't match up with a wine. By
MICHAEL LONSFORD.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The stories of most people can
be told on the lines on a page, but the story of Jim Nielsen, 89,
is best told from the lines on his face. Each of those creases and
wrinkles are like the back roads on a detailed map of the
wilderness, leading off to secret canyons, ridges and adventures,
telling of a journey like no other. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Malta, N.Y.) _ A creek runs through it, this sad
tale of state conservation bureaucrats who are unwilling to
overcome inertia because the aggrieved citizen simply doesn't have
political clout. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ Proponents of a new Texas
Constitution are right. Most Texans are tired of trying to decipher
a dozen or more constitutional amendments every other November and
have found something else to do on Election Days in odd-numbered
years. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
