<HEADER>
A5008 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN02-COX     11-01 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Figuring out what retired farmers do
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio. _ It's harvest time. Starting at sun-up,
tractors pulling
</P>
<P>
   wagon-loads of corn go rumbling past my front door headed for
the elevator a block away. Sometimes, if there's a line waiting to
be weighed and unloaded, they'll turn the corner beside my bedroom
and go around the back way to join the lineup in the bank parking
lot, across the street from the co-op.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of folks got their feathers in a ruffle when the new bank
moved to town and bought up land next to the railroad right-of-way,
including the gravel path where the farmers wait their turn on the
scales. Some of us were particularly unhappy when the 60-foot
spruce the village always decorated with aluminum pie tins and
Christmas lights was chopped down.
</P>
<P>
   But it turned out okay. The bank told the farmers to keep on
doing what they were doing and even put up a sign asking folks on
bank business not to block the farmers' wagons during harvest. And
some committee or other planted a new Christmas tree in the log
yard next to the Sunoco station. It's pretty tall now and looks
real festive decorated for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Farm communities are hard-working places, I have discovered.
Farmers are out before dawn, well before most of us in town have
even rolled over for an extra 40 winks. And after supper, when the
village is settling down to homework and reruns of MASH, the fields
around us are dotted with what look like giant fireflies but are
really the powerful headlamps on the tractors lighting the way so
the farmers can work another acre or two before calling it a day.
</P>
<P>
   This morning I had coffee with a few of my retired buddies at
the cafe - two or three farmers, a couple of railroad men, a
chemist, and a partially-retired heating and air-conditioning
contractor who often hangs out at one of his company's job sites
just to be sure his son is doing it right. They're a pretty laid
back bunch, particularly now that they)re not punching a time
clock. A few even have time for hobbies.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the guys fish all summer long and up until there's ice
on the docks. A couple even have boats. Three or four hunt. In
fact, just last week Charlie broke his leg when his stand fell out
of the tree.
</P>
<P>
   But not a single one of the retired farmers I know hunts or
fishes. I got to wondering why. Cal says it's because all of his
life, ever since he was old enough to feed chickens or water the
livestock before climbing on the school bus, time has mattered. It
was never something he had the luxury of wasting by sitting around
with a fishing pole in one hand and a lukewarm brew in the other.
</P>
<P>
   In winter when the lake freezes over, the diehards like Elmer
and Charlie go
</P>
<P>
   ice fishing, but not the farmers. While the railroad man and the
chemist are
</P>
<P>
   out putting up a shanty and boring holes in the ice in hopes of
catching something other than pneumonia, Amos is out in the barn
helping his son repair
</P>
<P>
   a bent axle or a broken plow.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers are just not geared for wasting time. Amos says he and
his wife had been married 16 years before they ever felt they had
time for a vacation. Cal says it wasn't the time but Amos was just
too cheap to spring for a weekend at Niagara Falls.
</P>
<P>
   Amos complains because his wife won't bake him pies anymore. She
says he doesn't work hard enough to burn the fat. Cal says his
wife's `honey-do' list is so lengthy he can't figure out how
anything ever got done around the house when he was still in the
fields.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, while Elmer and Charlie are grumbling about how
tough it is to clean up their boats and find a cheap place to store
them, Amos and Cal are shaking their heads over corn prices - $1.60
a bushel, down by half.
</P>
<P>
   Old habits die hard.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, Ohio 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
