<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5011 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN01-COX     11-01 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What seemed like cakewalk is about to get messy for Bush, Gore
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ A funny thing is happening on the way to
anointment.
</P>
<P>
   George Bush, the drive-through ATM candidate, is driving off
Republican candidates who could help get him nominated and/or
elected.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, the automatic Democrat _ some would say automated _ has
another Demo model sharing his showroom, and party regulars are
looking it over.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not prepared to answer this, but: Is it possible that
invincibility could be the downfall of both?
</P>
<P>
   Surely not. Surely Bush and Gore will face each other in the
general election. They have amassed too much cash and name backing
not to.
</P>
<P>
   But they may get the scare of their lives in so doing. And at
some point they will curse Dame Invincibility for making things _
difficult?
</P>
<P>
   The case of Gore and Democratic challenger Bill Bradley is the
perfect example of what can be wrong with having too much momentum.
</P>
<P>
   We can't know what Gore was thinking when prospective Democratic
challengers dropped away: Richard Gephardt, Jesse Jackson, Bob
Kerrey. Maybe Gore felt elation and relief. On the other hand, when
the very-solid Bradley stepped to the line, Gore instantly might
have gotten wistful for a crowded field, for a nettlesome Paul
Tsongas, a Tom Harkin, a John Kerry. Come one, come anybody.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, the more Democrats in the race, the more diluted
would be the ABG, or anybody-but-Gore, vote (more accurately, it's
the anybody-without-a-hint-of-Clinton's-aftershave vote.)
</P>
<P>
   As it is, Bradley is a mighty threat to Gore. Make no mistake.
And the New Hampshire primary looms like none other. Though he
trails nationwide, the ex-New Jersey senator leads Gore in New
Hampshire, according to a Quinnipiac College poll. Should Bradley
win Feb. 1 in New Hampshire or make it close, Gore's invincibility
will be out the door.
</P>
<P>
   As for Bush, the monstrous mountain of cash he's amassed is the
equivalent of having canceled half a dozen primaries, so rapidly
has it winnowed the Republican field. But that's not all good for
the Dub.
</P>
<P>
   As William Safire points out, having Elizabeth Dole on the
primary ballot was a way of splitting support of those GOP
moderates who see Bush as a question mark and who now might turn to
John McCain. Similarly, having Dan Quayle and Lamar Alexander
jettisoned from the ballot means more face time for Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Having lots of names on primary ballots would have helped Bush
in dividing and conquering his GOP doubters. Now McCain is standing
as Bush's chief threat on an electability scale, while Forbes hangs
around to spend with dispatch and cast doubts about the front
runner.
</P>
<P>
   But the real curse of Invincibility, as pertains to the end
result of this whole exercise, may be in the Reform Party, where
contenders like Pat Buchanan, Donald Trump or maybe Ross Perot
again stand to siphon votes away from Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The assertion that a Reform candidate would hurt Gore and Bush
equally is hogwash. The Reform Party remains a refuge for the AWM,
the angry white male vote. A pivotal portion of that vote went to
Perot in 1992. Gore (or Bradley) would not expect to have any of it
in 1999. But Bush is _ was _ counting on every one.
</P>
<P>
   That Trump and Buchanan (and maybe Perot) appear ready to debate
and draw lots of attention to themselves means one of the two will
acquire stature and visibility among angry white males.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush hadn't appeared so invincible, Buchanan would have hung
around to pester him in the GOP primaries, not bolt to bleed
crucial ABG, AWM votes from Bush in the general election _ or to
make Trump look like Lancelot by contrast.
</P>
<P>
   What's a candidate to do? Even when invincible, sometimes you
just can't win.
</P>
<P>
   John Young writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
