<P>
   The breakdown:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOK EXCERPTS! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three excerpts from the book ``Dreaming the Dawn'' (University
of Nebraska Press) by the late E.K. Caldwell have been sent this
week as part of New America News Service. Caldwell, a respected
Native-American poet, musician, writer and interviewer, chatted
with a number of Native-American artists and activists who have
challenged and helped reshape prevailing expectations about Native
cultures and identities during the late 20th century. A cover shot
of the book can be sent to you electronically. Please contact Aidan
McNulty, senior editor, by phone, (212) 499-3338; fax, (212)
499-3382; or e-mail, mcnulaj(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   PART 1 -- SHERMAN ALEXIE: MORE THAN JUST A WRITER
</P>
<P>
   PART 2 -- LITEFOOT: VOICE OF A GENERATION
</P>
<P>
   PART 3 -- BUFFY SAINTE-MARIE: UP WHERE SHE BELONGS
</P>
<P>
   EL REY OF PUBLIC BROADCASTING. After a successful run as host of
National Public Radio's ``Talk of the Nation,'' Ray Suarez has
landed a dream job at the ``NewsHour with Jim Lehrer'' on PBS. This
move cements Suarez's position as one of the top journalists _ not
to mention Latino journalists _ working on national news programs
in the United States. In addition to his nose for news, keen
intellect and topnotch interviewing skills, Suarez will bring a
multicultural perspective that can surely benefit television news.
Katharine Diaz profiles Suarez in this excerpt from Hispanic
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   FROM HAITI TO AMERICA IN SERVITUDE. People who do not live in
South Florida probably have not heard of Charlyne _ the name the
Miami Herald gave to a 16-year-old girl in Pembroke Pines. She is a
restavec _ the Creole term for the turn-of-the-century institution
of involuntary child servitude in Haiti. More than a decade ago,
monied Haitian immigrants nationwide secretly imported the restavec
system to the United States. South Florida has the highest number
of restavecs in America. Restavecs get less attention in the United
States and elsewhere than do black slaves in the African nation of
Sudan, writes columnist Bill Maxwell. The Florida Department of
Children and Families is just now waking up to its responsibility
to protect these youngsters. ``The problem, of course, is that a
restavec, like the black slave of old, is an invaluable piece of
property, and, in most cases, those involved will remain silent,''
Maxwell writes.
</P>
<P>
   BURYING THE FACTS ON YOUTH VIOLENCE. Ever since the Columbine
High School shooting in April, Congress has been under increasing
pressure to do something about gun control and youth violence. The
Senate and the House passed separate versions of a new
juvenile-crime bill in the spring, and Republican leaders of both
houses are nearing agreement on a compromise. A national coalition
of children and youth organizations is worried about provisions in
both bills that would do away with dozens of court consent decrees
that have forced state prison systems to segregate juveniles from
adult prisoners. Also, both bills would allow federal prosecutors
to try youths as young as 13 as adults, increase mandatory
sentences and do away with confidentiality provisions in juvenile
courts. Columnist Juan Gonzalez reports.
</P>
<P>
   WE ONLY WANT WHAT WAS OURS TO BEGIN WITH. A kettle will be
returned to the Ho-Chunk people when all the legal documents are in
order, writes columnist Karen Lincoln Michel. It's a cast-iron
vessel that when covered with deerskin serves as a ceremonial drum
kettle used in Native-American Church religious rites. ``Quite
generous of the Wisconsin State Historical Society to give back the
sacred item to the rightful owner after holding it for more than 40
years,'' she writes. How would other churches react to their
religious paraphernalia being collected, catalogued and put on
display with a hodgepodge of items from other cultures? This week,
Michel reports on the kettle and other items that are being
returned to their rightful owners thanks to Native American Grave
Protection and Repatriation Act.
</P>
<P>
   FOR MORE INFORMATION ABOUT NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE -- AND TO
RECEIVE THE SERVICE FOR 30 DAYS FOR FREE -- please contact sales
representative Ana Pena by phone, (212) 499-3333, or fax, (212)
499-3382.
</P>
<P>
   Many thanks!
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Times Syndicate.
