<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5024 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-01 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S HARD TO GET VOTERS FOCUSED ON STATE CHARTER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Proponents of a new Texas Constitution are
right. Most Texans are tired of trying to decipher a dozen or more
constitutional amendments every other November and have found
something else to do on Election Days in odd-numbered years.
</P>
<P>
   Going to their kid's soccer game, watching the leaves fall or
even cleaning out the garage are deemed more worthwhile pursuits
than deciding, among other things, how universities can invest
money, how many constables a county can have or what kind of
insurance a school district can buy.
</P>
<P>
   Local races and issues may boost turnout in Houston and San
Antonio, but Election Day elsewhere will slip, sight unseen, past
millions of nonvoting people of voting age.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide turnout is expected to be less than 10 percent of
registered voters, true to recent form for an election in which
constitutional amendments are the only statewide issues.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking hope wherever they can find it, some advocates for a new
constitution suggest that Texans, by boycotting the polls, are
silently expressing support for a new charter. Texans, they hope,
have finally had it with an antiquated, 123-year-old document that
already has been amended 377 times to try to keep pace with
changing times.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, though, people are simply saying that they don't
want to be bothered with voting for amendments that they don't want
to take the time to understand. Many Texans don't even know that
there is a constitutional amendments election, since this year's
crop of 17 proposals has generated only minimal controversy and
minimal publicity.
</P>
<P>
   If a groundswell of public support for a new constitution is
forming, it wasn't detectable in Austin earlier this year, when two
of the Legislature's most influential members _ state Sen. Bill
Ratliff, R-Mount Pleasant, and state Rep. Rob Junell, D-San Angelo
_ offered their colleagues the opportunity to vote on a new state
charter.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Ratliff's and Junell's clout and persuasive talents as
chairmen of the Legislature's budget-writing committees, their
proposal, which would have modernized the constitution and made
some significant changes in state government, went nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   And hardly anyone outside Austin noticed _ or cared.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers simply approved one of their periodic ``cleanup''
amendments to remove obsolete language from the constitution _
Proposition 3 on the statewide ballot _ and 16 other, more
substantive changes.
</P>
<P>
   Except for an occasional high-profile issue, such as a proposed
pay raise for legislators _ which isn't on the ballot this year _
constitutional revision is just too arcane and too boring to grab
the attention of most people, even if the issues involved can
ultimately affect their pocketbooks or the quality of public
services.
</P>
<P>
   The public disinterest plays into the hands of numerous elected
officials, public institutions and special interest groups that
have special favors and protections built into the present
constitution and actively resist efforts to rewrite it.
</P>
<P>
   Also working against Ratliff's and Junell's effort this year was
Gov. George W. Bush's coolness toward it. Legislators who may have
been interested in rewriting the constitution knew that they
couldn't do so without disrupting the legislative harmony that Bush
insisted upon in anticipation of his presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   The governor can be key to any revision attempt. Gov. Dolph
Briscoe's opposition was instrumental in defeating the last major
attempt at a constitutional overhaul in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Although Texas probably should have a new constitution, such a
change is not essential, and a serious constitutional rewrite won't
happen anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   If it ever does, it will require the support of many factions,
led by a popular governor, to sell a new charter to the Legislature
and the voters.
</P>
<P>
   And a lot of stars will have to line up just right too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
