<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5035 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-BOOK-WHAT-IF-REVIEW-H     11-01 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-WHAT-IF-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORIANS PONDER SOME FASCINATING WHAT-IFS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (``What if? The World's Foremost Military Historians Imagine What
Might Have Been''; edited by Robert Cowley; Putnam, $27.95.) 
 
By LEE CEARNAL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   History is replete with days when fate changed horses. Consider
where the world would be today if:
</P>
<P>
   _ Disease hadn't wracked the Assyrian forces as they besieged
Jerusalem in 701 B.C., allowing the last remaining group of Jews _
and their religion _ to survive.
</P>
<P>
   _ The winds had favored the Spanish Aug. 7-8, 1588, in the
English Channel, Philip II's armada had smashed the British fleet
and his army had invaded and subjugated England.
</P>
<P>
   _ A dense fog hadn't enabled George Washington and his trapped
army to escape from Brooklyn Heights in 1787.
</P>
<P>
   Those and other provocative ``counterfactuals'' are the topic of
the intriguing ``What If?,'' a compilation of essays by 34
distinguished historians written for Military History Quarterly and
edited by Robert Cowley.
</P>
<P>
   Among the contributors are some of the most prominent historians
of the day: John Keegan, Thomas Fleming, David McCullough, Stephen
Ambrose and Cowley.
</P>
<P>
   Each essay testifies to the fact that history hangs by a thread.
Similar alternative scenarios are employed by military schools to
teach how the principles of war (mass, movement, surprise, etc.) _
no matter how well-followed _ can be made irrelevant by weather,
disease, happenstance and whim.
</P>
<P>
   In positing the consequences of history taking a different turn
at each point, the essays all assume the trends at the time would
have continued in a more or less straight line. That is, that no
Jews would have survived the siege of Jerusalem to keep the flame
alive, that Spain would have continued to be the pre-eminent world
power, and that no one would have replaced a captured George
Washington and the colonies would not have been able to field
another army.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, this assumption is questionable indeed.
Nevertheless, these essays are valuable in that they illuminate the
importance of what did happen and thus help define the points at
which the world turned.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other what-ifs:
</P>
<P>
   _ If the loose confederation of Greek city-states had not
defeated a much stronger Persian fleet at Salamis in 480 B.C. Much
of the culture of the West would have been stillborn.
</P>
<P>
   _ If Robert E. Lee's ``lost order'' had not been found by a
Union soldier, enabling the North to win a narrow victory at
Antietam. Had Lee won, the South might have been formally
recognized by England and France, and gone on to win the war.
</P>
<P>
   _ If Hitler had invaded the Middle East instead of the Soviet
Union. He would have secured a limitless supply of oil (and
deprived the Allies of it) and saved his army from a debilitating
defeat in the snows of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Others include the death of Alexander at the battle of the
Granicus River in 334 B.C. (as very nearly happened), a victory by
Napoleon at Waterloo (which could very easily have happened), an
Allied defeat at Normandy on June 6, 1944, and a Japanese victory
at Midway.
</P>
<P>
   Today, considering how things actually turned out, the natural
instinct when reading of such close calls is, ``Whew, dodged a
bullet there.''
</P>
<P>
   But then again, if things had been different and Philip's armada
had prevailed, George Washington had been forced to surrender or
Lee had won at Gettysburg, the posited counterfactuals would have
been the opposite, and a reader's reaction might well have been ...
exactly the same.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
