<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ALLENDE-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLENDE'S EXPERIENCE AND LATEST NOVEL PROVE POSSIBILITIES OF LIFE
IN CALIFORNIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By FRITZ LANHAM 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   America has always been the land of new beginnings, a place
where immigrants cast off the miseries and failures of the past and
reinvent themselves.
</P>
<P>
   California, more than any other part of the country, seems to
whisper persuasively that promise of starting over. Ask the
thousands of young men who hotfooted it there when gold was
discovered at Sutter's Mill in 1848. Ask Chilean-born novelist
Isabel Allende, who moved to Northern California in 1986 and has
lived there ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration, transformation and the price of passion all figure
in Allende's new novel, ``Daughter of Fortune'' (HarperCollins,
$26), most of which is set in Gold Rush-era California.
</P>
<P>
   Allende is one of those rare writers who has a true following.
Her fans don't settle for reading one of her books; they read them
all.
</P>
<P>
   It's telling that everything she's published _ from her debut
novel, ``The House of the Spirits'' (1985), through more recent
nonfiction titles such as ``Aphrodite: A Memoir of the Senses''
(1998) _ remains in print.
</P>
<P>
   Allende's been traveling to promote ``Daughter of Fortune''
since December and won't be finished until February. The book is
No. 1 in Germany and the Netherlands and was on the best-seller
list in Spain for nine months. It's big in Australia and,
naturally, in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Her first novel since 1993's ``Infinite Plan, Daughter of
Fortune'' took seven years to research. What piqued Allende's
interest initially was learning that San Francisco, today such an
urbane, sophisticated city, was founded during the Gold Rush by
``scoundrels and bandits and madams.'' Allende lives in San Rafael,
in Marin County north of San Francisco. She does her writing in
nearby Sausalito, in a small Victorian house that has at various
times been a brothel, a church and a chocolate-chip cookie factory.
</P>
<P>
   Without knowing exactly what she was going to do with the
material, she plunged into histories, memoirs, diaries and letters
of the Gold Rush period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became a place of diversity and adventure, the land where
you would really start a new life,'' Allende says. ``I think that
was the greatest attraction, more than the gold. ... It was a no
man's land, with gold and no rules _ you could make up the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming from Chile, where class divisions continue to be fairly
rigid, she liked the anarchic spirit of the Gold Rush. That grubby
miner might be an aristocrat down on his luck; bandits sometimes
dressed like lords.
</P>
<P>
   The novel begins in the Chilean port city of Valparaiso, where
an infant is left, apparently abandoned, on the doorstop of a
middle-class English trader, Jeremy Sommers, and his sister Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Eliza, as the girl is named, grows into a spirited if sheltered
teen-ager who falls in love at first sight with Joaquin Andieta, a
proud but poor young clerk for Jeremy Sommers' trading company.
</P>
<P>
   The lovers give vent to their passion with the predictable
result: Eliza gets pregnant. Before learning the news, Joaquin
embezzles money from his employer and takes off for California _
gold has been discovered there. Eliza, facing disgrace at home, has
no choice but to pursue her beloved, and with the help of a young
Chinese doctor, she stows away in the bowels of a ship heading for
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   She loses her baby on the voyage, but she and Tao Chi'en arrive
in Northern California in time to join the thousands of others from
all over the world in the race for riches.
</P>
<P>
   Since virtually the only women in California at the time were
prostitutes, Eliza must disguise herself as a man as she and Tao
search for the missing Joaquin, who seems to have transformed
himself into a much-feared Mexican bandit known as Joaquin Murieta.
</P>
<P>
   As this summary suggests, ``Daughter of Fortune'' is part love
story but mostly adventure story, and the straightforward narrative
is packed with historical events. Allende isn't shy about unloading
the fruits of her research.
</P>
<P>
   Although the main characters are fictional, the things they see
and experience have a basis in fact. There really was, for example,
an elusive bandit named Joaquin Murieta. Allende has Tao embark on
a campaign to save young Chinese prostitutes held in killingly
brutal conditions. The conditions really were as bad as described,
Allende says.
</P>
<P>
   Having a young woman pass as a boy is no hoary literary device.
There were many cases when women donned a male identity to survive
in an overwhelmingly masculine world, she says.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Allende tells of a Chilean businesswoman who hits
upon the idea of packing a ship with ice and carrying fresh fruits
and vegetables all the way from South America to San Francisco.
That too is based on fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't possibly invent something like that,'' she says,
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gold Rush was a time of extremes,'' she continues.
``Extreme violence and greed and conquest, but also freedom,
adventure, idealism. Many utopians went to California because they
had the idea that the societies they could not found in Europe they
could found in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many Chileans and Peruvians joined the Gold Rush, few
stayed, largely because Anglos adopted laws that made it virtually
impossible for non-Anglos to get secure title to their claims,
Allende says.
</P>
<P>
   Love _ first love in particular _ is the engine that sets the
plot in motion. Rose ends up exiled to Chile because she has an
affair with an opera singer in England. Eliza's torrid relationship
severs her from her adoptive family and sets her on the roller
coaster of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the cataclysm of my first love,'' Allende says.
``It lasted two years, and it was just awful _ it was like being a
lunatic for two years.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't last, but her relationship with current husband
William Gordon is going strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the first night in William's house, when I came
just to visit, and I had a feeling I could invent a new version of
myself, just for this man. I think the United States offers that to
immigrants. That's the attraction.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
