<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-GENETICS-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAITING UP: WHAT IF YOU COULD HAVE THE TRAITS OF YOUR CHOICE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES A. FUSSELL  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   First there was the couple who advertised they would pay $50,000
for an egg from a tall, athletic, college student with high scores
on the Scholastic Aptitude Test.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the fashion photographer on the Internet who
offered to auction models' eggs to buyers willing to pay up to
$150,000 in hopes of having a beautiful child. (OK, so some
observers now say that was just a ruse to attract visitors to his
pornography site. He did make the offer.)
</P>
<P>
   And that got us to wondering. What if you could pre-select the
specific traits your heart desired?
</P>
<P>
   Want the brains of Stephen Hawking? You got 'em. The body of
Arnold Schwarzenegger? It's yours! The athletic ability of Michael
Jordan? The musical ability of Beethoven or the Beatles?
</P>
<P>
   Just ask.
</P>
<P>
   Forget for a moment the monumental ethical problems of such a
world gone mad and dream a little. What might you pick if you pluck
any genetic trait from any person on earth?
</P>
<P>
   We asked a handful of folks. Here's what they said:
</P>
<P>
   - Paige Pryor, a high school student at Blue Valley Northwest
High School, wanted only two things: ``I think if (Sports
Illustrated cover girl) Heidi Klum had Rosie O'Donnell's
personality, that would be the all-around perfect person,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   - Julian Craig, a graduate student at the University of Kansas,
was a little more particular. He wanted the face of model Tyson
Beckford, the body of Hercules, the brains of W.E.B. DuBois, the
sense of humor of Robin Williams, the athletic ability of Sandy
Koufax, the musical ability of R&AMP;B artist R. Kelly and the
compassion of Toni Morrison.
</P>
<P>
   Dianne Donnici, a hairstylist from Kansas City, gave reasons for
all her selections. She'd be thrilled to have the face of ``Days of
Our Lives'' actress Kristian Alfonso (``she's got a different look
to her that's really, really pretty''), the legs of Tina Turner
(``they're long and slim and they've got good tone''), the hair of
Heather Graham as she wore it in ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who
Shagged Me'' (``her hair was really long and beautiful and shiny. I
mean, it was just awesome. Power hair! We were all ready to go get
extensions after that movie''), the arms of Jennifer Aniston
(``they're still tiny. They look real feminine, but you can tell
she's been working out''), the musical ability of Madonna (``I love
how her voice sounds, and her style''), the athletic ability of a
Laker Girl, the sense of humor of Adam Sandler and the brains of a
surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   Proving that people are unique, her friend, Erin Reese, a
student at Rockhurst College, made completely different choices.
She went with the face of Meg Ryan (``her face is very animated,
very cute.''), the legs of Naomi Campbell, the hair of Portia de
Rossi (who plays Nelle on ``Ally McBeal''), the arms of Angela
Bassett, the musical ability of Courtney Love, the athletic ability
of volleyballer Gabrielle Reece, the sense of humor of MTV's Tom
Green (``he has a real weird sense of humor; I don't think a lot of
people understand it'') and the brains of a rocket scientist.
</P>
<P>
   And finally there was Richard Carter, a salesman from
Warrensburg, who would give anything to look like Harrison Ford in
his Indiana Jones period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately,'' he said, ``I look like Don Knotts in his
Barney Fife period.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's other wants?
</P>
<P>
   He'd like the feet of the late ballet star Rudolf Nureyev (``he
was strong and graceful, and I'm so awkward''), the brain of Albert
Einstein or Albert Schweitzer (``they thought on a completely
different plane than the rest of us''), the writing ability of
William Shakespeare, the musical ability of Eric Clapton, the voice
of Nat King Cole (``perfect'') and the athletic ability of, well,
best to let him explain it:
</P>
<P>
   ``I want,'' he said, taking at least five minutes to write it
out on a napkin, ``a combination of Maurice Green's legs, Jim
Brown's heart, Wayne Gretzky's talent, Michael Jordan's desire,
Bill Russell's character, Wilt Chamberlain's dominance and Babe
Didrickson Zaharius' versatility. Everybody else could go home
then. I'd win it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Whoa there, Richard. Back to reality. We're still figuring out
whether we can buy genetic beauty.
</P>
<P>
   What if instead of getting the supermodel's beauty, you end up
looking like her short, bald great-grandpa? And what if instead of
the running back's athletic ability we get the klutziness of his
nerdy bookworm uncle?
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who believes we can engineer our genetic destiny might do
well to heed the wisdom of George Bernard Shaw. As the story goes,
a woman once came up to Shaw and remarked that since he was smart
and she was beautiful, they should have children.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's retort:
</P>
<P>
   ``What if they get my looks and your brains?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 1127EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0134 </DOCNO>
