<HEADER>
A5042 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u d BC-FOOD-NO-WINE-HNS &LR;      11-01 1580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NO-WINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO-WINE SITUATIONS: SOME FOODS CAN INCUR THE WRATH OF GRAPES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL LONSFORD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Red wine with meat, right? White wine with fish ... .
</P>
<P>
   That's the ``rule'' most commonly associated with wine and food,
although in these days of innovative chefs and creative
wine-and-food pairings, almost anything goes.
</P>
<P>
   Almost anything.
</P>
<P>
   Red wine with fish? You bet, especially if it's grilled salmon
and a smoky, silky pinot noir (or red burgundy). White wine with
beef? Why not? A big, full-bodied white burgundy (or chardonnay)
and a grilled piece of fine beef _ or pork _ and you're there.
</P>
<P>
   Foie gras and sauternes? Fabulous. Stilton and vintage port?
Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, today almost anything goes.
</P>
<P>
   Except artichokes.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe asparagus.
</P>
<P>
   And many times, chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Those are just a few of the foods that good cooks and chefs have
trouble pairing with wines. Whether it's the herbal bitterness of
an artichoke, the grassiness of asparagus or the high acidity in
chocolate, sometimes a dish simply doesn't match up with a wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Artichokes? I'd stay away from them,'' says Mercer A. Mohr,
executive chef at the Omni Hotel's La Reserve in Houston.
``Brussels sprouts, too. Any vegetable that has a bitter aftertaste
is difficult to match with wine.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Ruppe, owner/chef of his eponymous restaurant near
downtown, agrees. ``Artichokes are tough. Some foods just blow wine
out of the water.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Cox, owner/chef of Mark's, also says artichokes are a
difficult match, as is asparagus.
</P>
<P>
   But Tim Keating, executive chef at the Four Seasons' DeVille in
downtown Houston, takes the opposite tack. ``I'd like to blow away
that myth about artichokes. A sauvignon blanc or a white `meritage'
(white Bordeaux blend) can go with artichokes _ the flavors don't
fight that much.''
</P>
<P>
   So if you can drink a wine with artichokes, what would it be?
``The tougher the food, the simpler the wine,'' says Robert Del
Grande, owner/chef of Cafe Annie. ``I'd drink a rose with
artichokes.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some people to whom food is both a passion and a
vocation will tell you there are no taboos associated with matching
wine with food _ even artichokes. Monica Pope, owner/chef at
Boulevard Bistrot, says that even though vinaigrettes and sauces
can cause wine-food headaches, ``I go by the theory that there is
no food that won't go with some wine, even if it's something very
different.''
</P>
<P>
   She says that even with a ``literal marriage of opposites, there
is something indisputable about why those two are together _
something connects them.'' Running a restaurant, she says, ``We
deal with connecting flavors to devise a successful special
(combination), and the wine is really an extension of our work.
Bridging the artichoke to the wine can be done by choosing certain
other flavors in the sauce or other elements in the dish.''
</P>
<P>
   Asparagus is another food commonly considered no friend to a
glass of wine.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Asparagus is rough, but again, an acidic, grassy-style
sauvignon blanc (such as a Sancerre or a New Zealand sauvignon
blanc) can be a winner,'' Keating says.
</P>
<P>
   You can pair a wine with asparagus, says the Houstonian's
executive chef, Jim Mills _ just not a red wine. ``With a Vouvray
(an off-dry chenin blanc) or a big sauvignon blanc, it'll work.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Mitchell, executive chef at the Rainbow Lodge, also likes
a sauvignon blanc with asparagus. ``It can go pretty well
together.''
</P>
<P>
   A particular nemesis for Mitchell has less to do with flavor
than temperature: soups. ``Sometimes it's hard to pair a hot liquid
with a liquid that's cold or even room temperature.''
</P>
<P>
   Other vegetables can also raise a red flag when matched with
wine. For example, Mills says, the woodiness of shiitake mushrooms
conflicts with the tannins in red wine. ``There's this funky
chemical reaction,'' he says. And he's also leery of eggplant.
``It's one of my pet peeves. It can have a very big flavor, and
that messes with wine. Of course, the more you cook it, you don't
notice it so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Most chefs agree that vegetables are much harder than meats to
match with wines. Most cooked meats have their wine marriages:
cabernet sauvignon, or red Bordeaux, with beef; a red Rhone or a
zinfandel with lamb; lighter reds such as pinot noir with game
birds.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes you can have too much of a good thing. A trend
these days is cooking beef jammed with cracked black peppercorns.
In that case, beware, says Del Grande _ that's a serious spice hit.
But you can match it with wine, although a cabernet may not be the
way to go. ``With some foods, you need less serious wines _ like an
Australian shiraz or a grenache, because they're flexible. Cabernet
is like the prow of a ship _ it just stays on course.'' And beef
and cracked pepper isn't even on the map.
</P>
<P>
   Another particular meat that can raise culinary eyebrows is ham.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too salty,'' says Mitchell. ``Wine seems to give ham a
metallic taste.''
</P>
<P>
   But, says Del Grande, ``I love ham; we always have some kinds of
ham here at the restaurant. I would drink a wine like a nice,
fruity grenache with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's not the food or wine but the styles that
conflict, especially with the most popular wine, chardonnay. Says
Ruppe, ``A big fat, buttery chardonnay with a lightly poached sole
and light cream sauce doesn't work, because the food needs a wine
with more acidity.''
</P>
<P>
   Mohr agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chardonnay is a great before-dinner drink, but taking
chardonnay to the dinner table doesn't always result in a good food
match. If the dominant impression of the chardonnay is crisp and
citrusy, then it can match well with several foods. But if the
chardonnay is buttery and creamy, food pairings are much more
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Spices are often what really make foods both interesting and
flavorful. But those same spices are also what can spell doom for a
glass of wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very spicy foods need a quencher, like beer or water _ not
wine,'' says Del Grande, no stranger himself to the spice rack.
</P>
<P>
   Cox agrees about spices. ``A little can go a long way _ the food
can mask the wine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hot spices, like chilies, don't match with most wines,'' says
Keating, ``especially tannic red wines like cabernet or Bordeaux.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell reacts gingerly when trying to match wines with ...
ginger. ``It usually stands alone, as a flavor. It doesn't even go
with gewurztraminer (a spicy white wine of Alsatian origin) because
of the spicy heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Another spice that generally doesn't curry favor with wine is
... curry. But there are exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Curries are OK if they're matched with something sweet,'' says
La Reserve's Mohr, mentioning Vouvray, the often off-dry French
chenin blanc. ``But watch out _ curries can cover up the wine if
they are too hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Chenin blanc is Mitchell's choice for curries, too, as is
gewurztraminer. Ruppe opts for riesling or sauvignon blanc.
</P>
<P>
   Keating named one food that seems so obvious, yet mention is
rarely made of it in connection with wine: eggs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard-cooked eggs fight with wine because of their sulfur
content. But if the dish has egg yolks mixed in, then maybe a
chardonnay or white burgundy.''
</P>
<P>
   Dessert souffles are based on eggs, of course, and can be quite
sweet. Cox says he usually avoids serving wines with very sweet
desserts. ``We tend to go with cordials, liqueurs or cognac rather
than sweet dessert wines.''
</P>
<P>
   Caviar is a dish that is popularly associated with champagne.
Yet many wine-and-food buffs say the saltiness of the fish roe can
make champagne taste metallic. Options: ice-cold vodka or ice-cold
beer.
</P>
<P>
   While Keating advises against pairing shellfish and cheese, he
also says that cheese and champagne don't work together. ``And I
have generally stayed away from chocolate and champagne, but the
more I travel, the more I could make a case for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate appears to light the furnace with chefs when it comes
to matching it with wine. ``Champagne works better with fruit than
it does with chocolate,'' says Cox.
</P>
<P>
   Ruppe minces no words. ``One of the worst combinations is
chocolate with a sauternes or a late-harvest riesling (very sweet
dessert wines) _ it'll jar the teeth right out of your mouth. Port
is better with chocolate, but a dry red wine is dangerous unless
you have the right red wine and the right chocolate.''
</P>
<P>
   While Pope says that ``people love chocolate with cabernet,''
Del Grande says he prefers chocolate with ... coffee. ``It's a
great combination!''
</P>
<P>
   If you can afford truffles, you can afford to try any kind of
wine with them. But watch out, say those who work with them _ and
wine _ on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the truffles are real perfumey, wine doesn't work that
well,'' says Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truffles are a hard match with wine,'' says Cox. ``You have to
be very careful not to overpower the truffle flavor, because the
truffle is a flavor in itself. You don't want the two to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Another strong flavor is blue cheese, and it elicits strong
reactions from chefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue cheese is tough,'' says Del Grande. ``Be careful: The
harsh flavor can stay on your palate for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Keating votes the same ticket. ``Steer clear of dishes at the
start of a meal that have an intense blue cheese, because then your
palate's history. Wine? What wine?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
