<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 12:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5081 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-STYLING-MACHINE-HOLLY     11-01 1613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLING-MACHINE-HOLLYWOOD-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCK AND ROLE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from The Daily News
Record, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    TWO COLOR SLIDES -- of JENNIFER LOPEZ and THE BACKSTREET BOYS --
are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of this article. The art
can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please specify that you want
the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``e'' entertainment news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By VICKI VASILOPOULOS 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   In the world of music videos, stylists used to be anonymous
entities _ when they existed at all. As music videos become an
integral part of an artist's marketing message, the music-video
stylist has assumed an ascendant position, helping to craft the
public image that will sell those records and inspire fans all over
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might see a fashion look from the video shoot incorporated
for the CD,'' says Mike Fish, fashion marketing director of Spin
magazine. He points to the white fashion theme in the Backstreet
Boys video ``I Want It That Way'' that was then carried over into
the ``Millennium'' record.
</P>
<P>
   Music videos are ``an artistic marketing endeavor,'' Fish says.
So much so, he adds, that ``you will hear a denim company say that
an artist is helping sell a particular pair of overalls'' when it's
seen by fans in the artist's video.
</P>
<P>
   Emil Wilbekin, editor of Vibe magazine, says stylists ``know
what's hot on the street and what's hot in Paris and Milan, and
they're able to translate the images for the artists _ whether it's
sexy or fun or thuggish.''
</P>
<P>
   Hip-hop is a primary forum for the work of stylists. Wilbekin
says that ``esthetics are so important to hip-hop that artists have
put a lot of money into marketing their image. It's a cultural
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Blevins, fashion editor of Rolling Stone, concurs. ``Music
artists have realized that they have to look so good in these music
videos, and they've got to wear the latest Dolce &AMP; Gabbana. The
audience is looking up to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fish points to Gavin Rossdale of Bush and his penchant for
wearing contemporary designers like Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young men would look to him for style direction,'' he says.
And pop sensation Ricky Martin has become ``the poster child for
Giorgio Armani. He makes the clothes come alive,'' Fish adds.
</P>
<P>
   The current interest in music videos is such that MTV actually
has a behind-the-scenes show called ``Making the Video,'' which has
featured Jennifer Lopez, Red Hot Chili Peppers and Puff Daddy, with
future shows scheduled on Sugar Ray, Garbage and Whitney Houston.
</P>
<P>
   In the video-styling realm, street fashion coexists with
designer couture and custom designs. Vintage pieces are the icing
on the cake.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Lieberman, 31, who has worked in videos for
singer/actress Jennifer Lopez, Mary J. Blige, Everlast, Wyclef Jean
and Pras, says the starting point for any video stylist is the
director's treatment. But that only goes so far, adds Lieberman:
``The bigger the artist, the less the director can say about their
image. Jennifer (Lopez) has a clear idea of what her image is, but
by the same token they (artists) would never be able to do it
without us. A stylist acts as the artist's eyes and ears and
differentiates what Jennifer's going to wear from what Foxy Brown
would wear.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman describes Lopez's look as ``high-fashion, sexy couture
infused with a little bit of street.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Lopez favors such sexy, top-drawer designers as Versace,
Gucci and Dolce &AMP; Gabbana.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work very closely with Donatella. We also work with Prada.
Everybody wants to dress her,'' Lieberman adds.
</P>
<P>
   While Lieberman shops designer lines for clothes, she also works
on custom looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work a lot with Puffy and the majority of his stuff is
custom,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend these days is adaptability,'' says Lieberman, using
Everlast as an example. Musically, she says, ``he's hip-hop, he's
funk, he's blues, he's rock, so we'll take the fly Gucci leather
jacket with some Enyce or Polo black jeans.''
</P>
<P>
   Style-wise Everlast ``is pretty much straight-up street _ a
little bit of white trash and a little bit of hip-hop. We used a
lot of Triple Five Soul, Ecko Unlimited, Structure. It's raw, it's
spiritual, it's deep and it's street,'' Lieberman says.
</P>
<P>
   She emphasizes that ``the most important thing with my artists
is we don't like to look like we're trying too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The average budget on Lieberman's jobs has been between $10,000
and $20,000 but have been as high as $35,000 to $40,000 for the
``Puffy level.''
</P>
<P>
   Budgets have risen, she says, because ``everybody in R&AMP;B wants
to be in fur and leather and jewels, and that costs money.''
</P>
<P>
   June Ambrose, 28, is another top stylist in the music video
field who works with Puff Daddy. She's also part of the triumvirate
known as the Mode Squad (pronounced like the old TV series) that
includes Roger McKenzie, 29, and Andrew Caesar, 27. Their resume of
music videos reads like a roster of the top hip-hop and R&AMP;B acts:
R. Kelly, Missy Elliot, Mariah Carey, Will Smith, Busta Rhymes and
Janet Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting for an interview, Ambrose is the picture of high-fashion
chic. She wears a Gucci jeans-jacket and boots with her skirt and
finishes off her look with a pink pashmina scarf and Fendi baguette
bag. She started styling about nine years ago, ``when artists only
wanted to wear black, brown and gray,'' she says. ``I put Jay-Z
into his first Armani suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Flash-forward to 1999 for the Hype Williams-directed video
``Something Wet'' with Busta Rhymes and Janet Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The object was for Busta to look like a terminator,'' Ambrose
says. ``We used silver mylar that looks like chrome. I was inspired
by Thierry Mugler and science-fiction magazines. The dancers were
supposed to look like raindrops or amoebas.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose says that ``because we spend so much money on it, the
music video has incorporated many film elements.'' She cited
Japanese animation as an important influence. ``Music videos should
take you out of reality,'' she maintains. ``I always tell my
clients, `It's not about you; you're playing a part. When you go
home you can be yourself.'''
</P>
<P>
   While the Mode Squad often uses designs from Ralph Lauren,
Prada, Versace, Armani, Gucci and Gaultier, it is increasingly
doing more custom looks for its clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to deliver something to my clients that's not been seen
before _ we're sketching and creating it from the core. We can
easily pull Versace and Gucci, but just being a high-fashion
stylist is boring. With Hype Williams, we work on the evolution of
hip-hop fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose and the Mode Squad, because of their high-profile work
and success rate, have been instrumental in turning stying into a
real profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dealing with music videos that have an $80,000 clothing
budget. It's a lot of pressure for the stylist because you
basically have to deliver a marketing tool to the record company,''
Ambrose says. ``Styling has become a newfound phenomenon. We're not
just personal shoppers; it's artist development.''
</P>
<P>
   Stylist John Baptiste, 28, is the fashion editor for XXL
magazine and has his own company called Baptised Inc. He used to
work for record labels Sony, Motown and RCA doing radio promotion,
and has styled videos for Wu-Tang Clan and SWV.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a black Sean John jeans-jacket, denim RLX snowboarding
pants and an Avirex watch, he radiates a street vibe _ which
translates into his styling choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I use clothing, I avoid the big labels,'' he says,
because, ultimately, he's more concerned with communicating the
concept of the video. His budgets have ranged from $400 to $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   For the Wu-Tang video, the look was inspired by the film ``The
Matrix,'' which Baptiste saw four times. He had just four days to
create the padded leather costumes with set-in muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan native Wendy Schecter, 35, has been a stylist for 15
years. ``I had been picking out people's clothes since I was 8 and
I found out at 19 that I could get paid for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her first video was Debbie Gibson's ``Only in My Dreams,'' after
which she spent two years doing low-budget hip-hop videos. Her last
video was for Luscious Jackson, which was directed by filmmaker
Tamara Davis (``Gun Crazy''). She has also styled videos for Sting
and Santana and was responsible for Courtney Love's dramatic
high-fashion makeover when she showed up at the Academy Awards in a
white Versace gown.
</P>
<P>
   Schecter approaches each artist and each situation differently.
For Santana, Schecter says, ``Carlos had these beautiful jackets
from the '40s and we put together looks around them.
</P>
<P>
   She maintains that ``people that wind up becoming celebs _
there's something about them, there's a spark. I like to find that
spark and develop it into something magnificent and personal or the
thing they didn't know they wanted yet. It's me helping them flesh
out their fantasy; it's the objective eye helping them realize
their vision.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Vicki Vasilopoulos is a reporter for Fairchild
Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
