<HEADLINE>
ALI MACGRAW'S URBANE ARTIFACTS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    FOUR COLOR SLIDES are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``e'' entertainment news files.)  
 &HT;    
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Ali MacGraw is stepping into a new role: accessories designer.
And while that may seem like a stretch for someone who achieved
movie-star status for roles in such classic films as ``Love Story''
and ``Goodbye Columbus,'' the actress actually spent the first six
years after college working in the fashion industry _ first, as
Diana Vreeland's assistant at Harper's Bazaar, and later as a
stylist to the fashion photographer Melvin Sokolsky.
</P>
<P>
   Her collection of luxurious handbags and pashmina shawls shows
that she hasn't forgotten what she learned then. The pieces feature
traditional Indian designs in strong colors, from rich fuchsias and
bonfire reds to vibrant aquas and warm greens, and many of the
looks are inspired by her passion for exotic travel.
</P>
<P>
   MacGraw got involved in this venture in much the same way she
got her start in acting--by chance. Back in the '60s, an agent
spotted her photo in a Chanel bath oil advertisement and urged her
to test for film parts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, she landed the starmaking role in the film ``Goodbye
Columbus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I became an overnight success. It was thrilling, yet
terrifying at the same time. I come from a very practical
background, and the glamour that success brought was unfamiliar to
me,'' she says. But she was a quick study, and swiftly became
Hollywood's girl-of-the-moment, marrying Robert Evans, head of
production at Paramount, and later, Steve McQueen.
</P>
<P>
   MacGraw, who's now living in Santa Fe, New Mexico, decided to
start her business after a conversation with Veena Advani, a master
embroiderer who has worked for such designers as Isaac Mizrahi and
Oscar de la Renta.
</P>
<P>
   The two became business partners, and named the company Ali
MacGraw Milagro _ milagro means miracle in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   MacGraw is quick to point out that her collection isn't intended
to be trendy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a slave to fashion,'' she says. ``I'm just doing what
I love. Indian textiles and designs are very hot right now, but I
will continue doing them even when the fashion world has moved to
another area of the world. I'm fascinated with the culture of India
and its sensibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The handbags vary in shape from soft silk shoulder-strap pouches
with tassel accents to more structured, sophisticated clutches.
</P>
<P>
   The collection is available at Jeffrey, New York; Neiman Marcus;
Browns in London, and Savannah, Santa Monica. Prices range from
$350 to $1,100 for the beaded bags and $600 to $1,200 for the
pashminas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an adventure for me,'' MacGraw says. ``And the most
important part is to enjoy the whole process of it, not just the
outcome. Even if this collection isn't a success, I know 21
girlfriends will have the best presents.''
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
