KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Tuesday,
Nov. 2. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News Desk
at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   ACCRED: A hearing in federal district court determines whether
the state's move to unaccredit the KC School District stands. If
the district fails in its quest to block the state's action, the
district will file an appeal in Jackson County Circuit Court and
possibly other legal action. U.S. District Judge Dean Whipple could
decide he has no standing in the case because the state is no
longer a party to the desegregation case, or he could restore the
state as a defendant in the case on the grounds that a decision to
withdraw accreditation could lead to a more segregated school
district. That could force the state to compromise with the
district. Photo. Phil O'Connor and Kevin Hoffmann.
</P>
<P>
   TRAGEDY: It's been a hellacious couple of weeks for the Jackson
County Medical Examiner's office, when the bodies of seven kids _
victims of murder or abuse//neglect _ came in for examination:
Pamela Butler, killed by a stranger; an accidental drowning
attributed to neglect; two Bass boys starved to death; Jacob Dube
shot by his stepfather; and two toddlers beaten to death.
Typically, Jackson County records only 3 or 4 abuse//neglect deaths
a year, but in this one period, they dealt with five. The other
two, of course, were homicides. Trying for mugs of all victims.
Donald Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ZOO. In what was once a treeless valley outside Salina, Kan.,
self-made millionaire Charlie Walker has used a chunk of his
fortune to create the Rolling Hills Refuge Wildlife Conservation
Center, a 45-acre zoo that opened to the public last week. The
animals (rhinos, lions, white tigers, orangutans, giraffes) are
impressive, and the landscaping (more than 3,000 trees planted) has
created a prairie oasis. They expect to attract at least 150,000
visitors annually. We'll also take a look at Walker, a truck stop
operator, and what made him want to build the place. Tom Perrin.
42. Pix. Graphic
</P>
