<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S RULING PARTY CHANGES WITH THE TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The Berlin Wall crumbled, the Soviet Union
collapsed and Mexico, too, is changing at the edge of a new
century.
</P>
<P>
   That is the comparison made by a Mexican official to
characterize the unprecedented changes in the 70-year-old
Institutional Revolutionary Party, the longest ruling party in the
world, as it heads to an unprecedented primary election on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is many Mexicans are not convinced there is a new
and improved PRI, and they suspect a fixed election.
</P>
<P>
   The test will be in the turnout on Nov. 7, when voters choose
the PRI's presidential nominee from among four candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are times of change and renovation,'' said longtime
party insider Fernando Gutiirrez Barrios, in charge of overseeing
the PRI's internal revamping.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the end of a millennium in which humanity believes
everything must change. The Berlin wall fell and the Soviet Union,
too,'' Gutiirrez said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the party was founded in 1929, the outgoing president
selected his successor after consulting with party leaders. The
practice is called dedazo, which is Spanish slang for the big
presidential finger signalling a heir.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI successor, in turn, has always beat opposition
candidates. An efficient, well-financed, mammoth PRI machinery that
reaches into all echelons of society has ensured that victory,
often through fraud and influence-peddling.
</P>
<P>
   But in times of free trade and globalization, when world opinion
counts in financial markets, the PRI this year saw the need for
change, a radical shift Mexicans have been loudly clamoring for
this past decade.
</P>
<P>
   On the initiative of President Ernesto Zedillo, the party
announced this year an open, U.S.-style primary to elect the PRI
presidential nominee to run in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Of Mexico's three main parties, the PRI is the only one having
such an election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since 1916, Mexico has moved in evolutionary fashion, rather
than a revolutionary fashion,'' said George Grayson, a professor of
government and a Mexican analyst at William and Mary College.
``While this may not be Jeffersonian democracy in its purest form,
the PRI primary represents a huge advance over the dedazo.''
</P>
<P>
   Four party veterans are running for their party's nod, but the
race has evolved into a two-man contest and many Mexicans believe
one is the choice of Zedillo, the ``official candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   The man is Francisco Labastida, 57, a congenial, subdued
economist who until earlier this year was secretary of the
interior, a powerful post that usually precedes the PRI's
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida is the man to beat next Sunday, and the only one with
that chance is Roberto Madrazo, the brash, 47-year-old former
governor of Tabasco state who has caused a stir within the party
because he has taken the business of the primary quite seriously,
official candidate or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Madrazo has taken off like a Roman candle,'' said Grayson, who
recently concluded a study of the primary for the Center for
Strategic and International Studies in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   However, Madrazo has had to fight the image, dissiminated by
Labastida's campaign, of being a close associate of ex-President
Carlos Salinas de Gortari, who left the country in economic
shambles in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Further, he has been linked to wealthy businessman Carlos Hank
Gonzalez, who embodies the old PRI guard resistant to
democratization and market reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Grayson said even though Madrazo is running about
10 points behind Labastida in most recent polls, he could stage an
upset if there is a large turnout.
</P>
<P>
   The number of believers aren't high. In a recent Louis Harris
poll, only 36 percent of Mexicans said they thought the primary
would be clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I vote? I don't like any of the four candidates and
besides, it is all fixed so Labastida will win. He is the
president's man,'' said one housewife buying groceries at a
shopping center.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, who didn't want to be identified, nevertheless
admitted she was leaning toward Labastida because he seemed the
most honest.
</P>
<P>
   The other two candidates, former PRI leader Humberto Roque
Villanueva and former Puebla Gov. Manuel Bartlett, are seen as dark
horses. But they, too, have thrown their full effort into the
fight.
</P>
<P>
   After the newspaper Reforma reported last week that the governor
of Chiapas, Roberto Albores, urged state and local party lawmakers
to promote the vote for Labastida, Madrazo and Roque cried foul.
</P>
<P>
   And they demanded to the PRI that Labastida be disqualified from
the race.
</P>
<P>
   Not much chance of that.
</P>
<P>
   Gutierrez said Albores was ``|sanctioned''| privately, but the
perception remains among the three candidates and much of the
public that Labastida is the president's man.
</P>
<P>
   He said about a dozen other party officials have been
``|sanctioned''| for openly promoting Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Zedillo reiterated that he had no favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not before, not during, nor in what remains of this process
have I had, will I have, a preferred candidate,'' Zedillo told
national party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI is expecting at least 6.5 million to vote in the
primary. Fewer than that would be a great disappointment, Gutierrez
said.
</P>
<P>
   The question many are asking now is what will happen when
Labastida wins? Will Madrazo surrender or protest?
</P>
<P>
   Most political analysts here believe Madrazo will remain within
the comforting PRI fold and work out a cushy deal for himself. Life
outside the party has not been advantageous for many of its
deserters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 1300EST &QL; 
