<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !! 1/2 ``Beefcake'' Thom Fitzgerald's documentary-and-drama
about the world of ``male physique'' magazines and films in the
1950s is odd in tone, both sweet and sour. This subterranean world
is viewed mostly through the lens of Bob Mizer, a sweet-seeming
photographer who captured the images of buff young men, naked or
near-naked, for an audience that would have to wait years for any
more openly homosexual culture to grow up. But Mizer's arrest and
trial for running a prostitution ring is also covered, adding
darker tints to the pastel nostalgia. (Unrated) (Jim Sullivan) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(FR) !!!! ``Being John Malkovich'' A refreshingly original comedy
that riffs on celebrity and consumer culture and the proverbial 15
minutes of fame. John Cusack plays an impoverished puppeteer who
discovers a portal into the head of John Malkovich and starts
selling admission for 15-minute intervals. Malkovich goes along
with it all, a good sport who enhances his own cool quotient under
the direction of Spike Jonze, whose fun with the film's skewed
metaphysics posits the universe as God's own pinball machine. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``The Grandfather'' Slow-moving but solidly made Spanish period
piece, carried by Fernando Fernan-Gomez's magnificent old
impoverished aristocrat who still roars like a lion, especially
when he discovers that one of his beloved granddaughters wasn't
fathered by his late son. (PG) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``Julien Donkey-Boy'' To Harmony Korine falls the
distinction of making America's first Dogma 95 film, in line with
the edgy back-to-basics esthetic of Denmark's New Wave. It focuses
on a family for whom dysfunction would be a step up. Sometimes the
dynamics are fascinating; sometimes their emotional nakedness makes
you squirm, especially those involving Ewen Bremner's schizophrenic
Julien. Some improvised sections fall flat, others impale you on
their raw urgency. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``Music of the Heart'' The title sounds corny, but Wes Craven's
dramatization of the true story of Roberta Guaspari _ who beat both
the odds and arts-funding cuts to teach East Harlem public school
pupils how to play the violin _ is one of the few films that can
wholeheartedly be called uplifting. Meryl Streep is grittily
convincing as the determined teacher, as well she must be to occupy
the screen alongside Guaspari's real-life students. (PG) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!!! ``Princess Mononoke'' The crowning achievement of Japan's
leading animator, Hayao Miyazaki, this is a magical epic with a
reverence for nature rarely seen in Western films, animated or
otherwise. There's plenty of action in this myth of the retreat of
the forest gods before encroaching humans in medieval Japan, some
of it violent and brutal. But the grand and mystical presence of
nature as a healing force is what stays with you. The story
involves a fierce young princess who runs with the wolves, a young
warrior on a quest, and a formidable woman with a ``civilizing''
but humane agenda. (PG-13)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
