<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5105 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-BURNS-BOS &LR;      11-01 1760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BURNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEN BURNS'S `FAMILY DRAMA' ON WOMEN'S HISTORY  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ As with his films, there is an easy, flowing
lyricism to the way Ken Burns speaks _ except when he wants to
underscore a point. Then his words collide in a sudden stampede.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Burns is talking fast because he has a bone to
pick with that fickle amnesiac we call posterity. He believes the
subjects of his new PBS documentary, ``Not for Ourselves Alone: The
Story of Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Susan B. Anthony,'' are largely
unknown today, their pioneering efforts on behalf of women's rights
largely forgotten. Burns finds this inconceivable.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two women led the largest social transformation in
American history _ and nobody knows about it!'' he exclaims. ``If
it were two men, there would be marble monuments in Washington with
cherry blossoms around them.''
</P>
<P>
   But surely, his interlocutor ventures, the general public is
familiar with the achievements of Anthony, at least? Burns fires
back: ``She's a failed dollar coin: That is what people know.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns is a man on a mission. Yes, he is aware of the irony
embedded in the fact that he and coproducer Paul Barnes are men
whose mission is to reclaim from semi-obscurity two women who shook
the very ground of 19th-century America by creating the women's
rights movement, leading it for a half-century, and paving the way
for women's suffrage.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Burns insists on the universality of this story _ which he
calls ``history running on all cylinders, as important and dramatic
as the Battle of Gettysburg'' _ and contends that it transcends the
gender of the teller. ``We all share this past in common,'' he
says. ``This is a family drama. It does not feel separate to me in
that way. . . . I am sure that I will get something wrong, and the
mistakes we made we will take full credit for, whatever they are,
but I don't think they are gender-related.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses, takes a breath, finishes: ``You know, this is just a
good story.''
</P>
<P>
   That it is. Today, in what Burns calls our ``post-feminist media
culture,'' it's become fashionable to take for granted the gains
won by the women's rights movement. But ``Not For Ourselves Alone''
is an eye-opening reminder of the way things were, a memory map
leading us back to the world Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Susan B.
Anthony struggled to change.
</P>
<P>
   `Cult of true womanhood'
</P>
<P>
   When they first met, in 1851, women did not have the right to
vote or to own property in America. They could not testify in
court. They were usually denied custody of their children if they
divorced. The notion of equal pay for equal work did not exist.
Until a few years earlier, women had been prohibited from attending
college, and even if they become one of the very few to graduate
from college, they were expected to fulfill only submissively
domestic roles, as dictated by the ``cult of true womanhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanton and Anthony began to change all that. They forged a deep
friendship and partnership that survived innumerable obstacles and
setbacks _ not to mention their radical differences in background,
demeanor, and lifestyle. Stanton was born in Jonestown, N.Y., to a
wealthy family; she possessed a native ebullience and an outgoing
personality, and bore seven children during a lengthy marriage.
Anthony was the child of financially struggling Quakers in Adams,
Mass.; she was driven by an unwavering intensity of purpose that
made scant room for a personal life, and never married.
</P>
<P>
   But together, they were political dynamite. Stanton was a writer
and theorist of great power and eloquence _ ``She writes as well as
Emerson,'' maintains Burns _ while Anthony was a tireless lobbyist
and campaigner who traveled incessantly from town to town on behalf
of women's suffrage. They came to believe that the right to vote
was the cornerstone from which all other women's rights would flow,
so they talked, wrote, agitated, and strategized ceaselessly toward
that goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need them both; we all need them both, not just women.
They're great characters in American history,'' says Burns. ``You
can't have Jefferson without Hamilton. They are both aspects of the
same Washingtonian genius. These two women come and provide us with
what we all needed to get this work done.''
</P>
<P>
   However, neither would live to see the fruits of their lifelong
labors. Stanton died in 1902, at 86, Anthony four years later, also
at 86. It was not until 1919 that Congress passed a constitutional
amendment _ lifted verbatim from the one drafted in the 1870s by
Stanton and Anthony _ that granted women the right to vote. The
next year, in 1920, the 19th Amendment was ratified, and that year,
more than 8 million women went to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The seed for ``Not For Ourselves Alone'' was planted in 1988,
when Burns was working on the television documentary that would win
him national fame, ``The Civil War,'' with Barnes as his editor.
``Paul was reading this great book, a biography of Stanton, and
every day at lunch he is telling me: `This is a great story,' ''
recalls Burns. Initially, they planned to make a film about just
Stanton, but then concluded that the friendship between her and
Anthony was so rich and important that the film should focus on
both of them.
</P>
<P>
   A national viewing event
</P>
<P>
   As with previous Burns documentaries like ``The Civil War''
(1990) and ``Baseball'' (1994), ``Not For Ourselves Alone'' has the
potential to become a national viewing event that refocuses our
attention on an essential part of our history. Already, it has been
embraced by women's groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been urging their memberships to do viewing
parties,'' Burns says proudly. ``What has been happening in the
last couple of months is that we have been hearing that this is
happening all across the country: Women are getting their
daughters, their mothers, their husbands, their sons, and they are
going to watch it on the 7th and 8th with everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's recapitulating a lot of that enthusiasm when `The Civil
War' came out, which was a surprise, when conventions would stop
their evening programs so everybody could go back to their hotel to
watch `The Civil War.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In the nine years since he created a genteel sensation with
``The Civil War,'' Burns has produced one epic documentary after
another to tell more parts of the story of America. They include
the 18-hour masterpiece ``Baseball'' (Burns promises that ``When
the Sox win the World Series, I will do the last episode'' of
``Baseball''); ``Thomas Jefferson'' and ``Lewis and Clark: The
Journey of the Corps of Discovery,'' both in 1997; and last year's
``Frank Lloyd Wright.''
</P>
<P>
   The documentary style Burns first employed on 1982's ``Brooklyn
Bridge'' _ involving the copious use of archival photographs, a
gallery of expert talking heads, and a narrative approach to
history _ today is imitated not just on his home territory of PBS
but also on The History Channel and the A&AMP;E channel. Many young
documentarians _ including Burns's brother, Ric _ have gotten their
start at Florentine Films, Burns's production company based in
Walpole, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   At 46, Burns has created an intellectual empire so vast that
historian Stephen Ambrose has said: ``More Americans get their
history from Ken Burns than any other source.'' An unusual
achievement for a filmmaker who as a young man dreamed of being the
next John Ford or Alfred Hitchcock, and who to this day insists
that ``I don't have any credentials in history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am still a filmmaker, not a historian,'' says Burns. ``I
choose history the way Cezanne chose oil as opposed to watercolors.
It's just a place to practice my art and craft.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the acclaim for Burns have come some brickbats,
principally from critics who have mocked his style _ with its
mandolin music and sonorous narration _ as self-indulgent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am what I am,'' replies Burns. ``I have developed my own way
of asking questions of history, and in my own way I am solving the
problems that those questions raise. . . . I am sure there's an
element of truth to it, . . . but I can't be somebody that I am
not. . . . There are lots of rhythms in life and in nature; there
are fast rhythms and there are slow rhythms, and whatever cadence I
have found is my own.''
</P>
<P>
   Loss and melancholy
</P>
<P>
   When it is suggested there is an undertow of melancholy in his
films, Burns does not dispute it. He points to a deeply personal
reason that only recently became apparent to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's part of my psychology,'' he says. ``I think that
all of it, as Stanton points out, is about loss. My mother died
when I was 11 years old. I recently realized that, to some extent,
I was keeping her alive.''
</P>
<P>
   The lingering effect of his mother's death revealed itself in a
conversation with a friend. According to Burns, the friend said to
him: `` `What do you think you do for a living?' I said, `What do
you mean?' And he said, `Well, you wake the dead. Who do you think
you are really trying to get back? You make Thomas Jefferson,
Abraham Lincoln, and Jackie Robinson real for us _ but who do you
think you really want to get back?' And I started to cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suddenly realized that at the heart of this may be a
melancholy, but if you see the films, they are also about joy and
the human spirit. There is not a film that I have made that has not
had an aspect of a higher purpose to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The narrators and commentators of ``Not For Ourselves Alone''
are women, and Burns and Barnes relied on an all-female advisory
board. Burns says he was not averse to showcasing a male historian
as one of the film's talking heads, but he found that men
specializing in women's history are scarce.
</P>
<P>
   Given that Burns believes ``history is not really about the
past,'' but rather about ``the present-day consideration of what
went before us,'' he is clearly hoping many young women will be
inspired by ``Not For Ourselves Alone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, basically we live in the culture of `Victoria's
Secret,' '' he says. ``Women are being pushed and strangled and
cajoled into a kind of acquiescence to some of the demands now. We
don't have an Equal Rights Amendment! I am the father of two
daughters, and they still make certain choices because they are
women, and I want them to see this film and go, `Wow, I don't have
to make that decision not to do something.' That's very important.
Very important.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
