<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TRUTHS ARE STILL SURFACING ABOUT STUART CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps never before in his career has former Boston police
commissioner Francis ``Mickey'' Roache come under such heavy media
criticism as he is now enduring over charges that he recently
``revised'' the history of the Carol DiMaiti Stuart murder case.
</P>
<P>
   But a rediscovered tape recording, made during one of his
appearances before a youth group in January 1992, proves that
Roache is not changing his tune now, just to help himself win a
third term on the City Council. The tape shows that eight years ago
he said, for all to hear, that Willie Bennett was never a prime
suspect in the Stuart murder _ just as he is saying now.
</P>
<P>
   Roache recently generated considerable attention when, on the
10th anniversary of the case, he told the Globe's Peter Canellos
that, in the days after the murder, law enforcement officials knew
that Bennett was probaby not the man who shot the Stuarts while
they sat in their car on a street in the Mission Hill neighborhood
of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, an African-American known to have a criminal record,
was never in danger of being indicted, Roache said in an interview
published Oct. 20. In fact, he said, the investigation ``was going
the other way'' _ even as officials let Bennett's name be floated
publicly as the probable or possible shooter, and as then-District
Attorney Newman Flanagan ordered Bennett's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately after the Globe's article appeared, Roache
came under a barrage of criticism from the media and others.
Questions were raised as to why he came forward with this view of
Bennett only two weeks before the City Council election.
</P>
<P>
   A campaign aide, Brian Wallace, said Roache gave the interview
only because he promised to give it on the 10th anniversary after
refusing a request for an interview on the fifth anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   To appreciate the importance of Roache's comments, recall the
events of fall 1989. A shocked city heard and read media reports of
a wounded Charles Stuart telling police that a black man shot and
killed his wife, and wounded him, as they were driving home from a
childbirth class at a nearby hospital. The case dominated the news,
as police searched the city's black neighborhoods for the killer.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett was arrested by Flanagan's office on warrants unrelated
to the Stuart case. He stopped being a suspect only after Charles
Stuart's brother came forward to present evidence that Stuart
actually murdered his wife and wounded himself. Stuart then
apparently committed suicide, plunging to his death from a bridge
over the Mystic River.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than be self-serving, Roache's recent remarks merely
reflect what he said to a 1992 event called ``Rap With The Top
Cop'' forum attended by some 400 youths, most of them
African-American.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Donahue, who keeps hundreds of events he recorded during
his days as a sound engineer for the mayor's Office of Business and
Cultural Development, found the 1992 tape, which contains the
comments plus a few others regarding the murder.
</P>
<P>
   Youths attending the forum at the UMass-Boston gymnasium asked
Roache _ who was police commissioner during the Stuart case _ about
it. He responded: ``If you remember, I didn't make any comments
about that arrest in 1989, because the DA was running the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my heart, I felt that Willie Bennett was not in jeopardy of
being indicted or being arrested for the murder. The warrants
served on Bennett were for unrelated crimes,'' Roache continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our homicide unit was ordered (by Flanagan, he said later) to
go out to Mission Hill and several other locations to serve a
warrant. I knew that day there would be a perception that Willie
Bennett would be viewed as the possible person involved. We did not
want to serve those warrants. We knew Willie Bennett was not
involved. But you will never know that, won't believe that, until
20 years from now, when somebody has the guts and courage to write
the real story.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Friday, Roache said Flanagan had the
authority under general statutes to take over the Boston Police
Department's homicide unit. William Celester, a deputy
superintendent at the time, and an African-American, confirmed that
the DA's office took control of the unit and sent the detectives to
issue warrants.
</P>
<P>
   Roache also told the youth forum that, during the height of the
case, he followed up on reports that police were breaking down the
doors of blacks' homes, particularly in Mission Hill, in search of
Bennett. Roache said he told the city's corporation counsel to call
Doris Bunte, then head of the Boston Housing Authority, to ``check
the damage'' in the Mission Hill public housing development.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what the response was? You've all been led to believe
hundreds of doors broken down, windows. Anybody want to guess how
many doors broken, how many windows broken? None. Zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Roache told the forum eight years ago, he was afraid that
riots would break out during the case, because of the way the black
community was targeted. ``I ran out of the office and spent the
entire day and entire evening in Mission Hill,'' he said, ``knowing
that this city was in trouble.'' He credited African-American
community leaders such as Don Muhammad for helping to prevent the
city from exploding.
</P>
<P>
   Roache acknowledged Friday that ``we, as police, were extremely
aggressive in the Mission Hill area that night, particularly in the
initial investigation, because we were trying to obtain information
to find the assailant.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``The African-American community suffered and felt a
lot of pain because they were being painted as the group that may
be involved in that horrible, horrible crime. I had no control over
that. I hope that will never happen again in a million years.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis ``Mickey'' Roache has been consistently honest with a
case that began 10 years ago in brutal dishonesty.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
