<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5118 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-FIREBIRD-BOS &LR;      11-01 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FIREBIRD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNING AN ANGUISHED CHILDHOOD INTO A LIFE OF POETRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
FIREBIRD 
A Memoir 
By Mark Doty 
HarperCollins, 200 pp., $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps no passage better captures the humor and heartbreak of
Mark Doty's vivid, exquisite memoir, ``Firebird,'' than his
recollection of an incident when he was 10. When his friends decide
to put on a play, Doty's contribution is his rendition of Judy
Garland's classic ``Get Happy.'' With a red chiffon scarf and black
cane, he doesn't just sing the song, he seems to channel Garland,
``amphetamine bright and glittering on the inside, too,'' belting
out every word ``as if I were born knowing it.'' He is joyous and
daring, full in places where he had long felt emptiness.
</P>
<P>
   His big finish is interrupted by his mother's knock on his
bedroom door. He tries to explain the scarf, the jaunty sway of his
hips, how he will perform this number for their neighbors. No, she
says, you will not sing this song for anyone. His mother ``says
with a hiss, with shame and with exasperation, Son, you're a boy.
''
</P>
<P>
   In that moment, he knew something had irreparably broken between
mother and son. For her, ``his dissolute future spreads out in
front of her like an oil slick: shameful, worthless, sick. For
Doty, it is a ``watershed between childhood and something else. I
have been ushered into the world where adults live; I have been
warned, have been instructed to conceal my longing.''
</P>
<P>
   Longing pulses through the bittersweet heart of this moving
memoir by Doty, an award-winning poet. This is his second memoir,
the first having been the achingly beautiful ``Heaven's Coast,''
which concerned his life with, and the AIDS-related death of, his
longtime partner, Wally Roberts. As with that book, it is not so
much Doty's experiences that elevate ``Firebird.'' It is the
extraordinary lilt of his words, each chosen with great care, which
make even ordinary moments _ such as the hidden meanings a young
boy coming to terms with his sexuality could find in Petula Clark's
1965 hit ``Downtown'' _ become fresh and indelible.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in the 1950s and 1960s, Doty had a childhood that often
seemed a blur of addresses. His father's work for the Army Corps of
Engineers often meant the family was rustled from one state to the
next _ Tennessee, Arizona, Florida, California. Such rootlessness
would be difficult for the happiest of families, but it was
especially tough for the Doty household, which was far from
blissful. Even as a child, Doty was aware of the distances between
himself and his parents.
</P>
<P>
   Though his mother was ``often quite tender to me, there is
something about her which precludes ease,'' he writes. ``That's the
signal characteristic of our relation: intimacy without ease.'' As
for his father _ ``aftershave, boxer shorts, milk of magnesia in
blue bottles'' _ they ``simply lack connection. He's a force on the
horizon, but a distant one.''
</P>
<P>
   Young Mark is closer to his sister, Sally, a bawdy type who
represents freedom and possibilities. She listens to rock 'n' roll
and, much to the chagrin of her parents, cuts her long blonde hair
into a boyish DA. Then one day Doty is told, ``Your sister has to
get married.'' He's too young to understand that she's pregnant,
but this he knows: Sally is getting out. Writes Doty: ``Maybe my
sister's trapped in something she doesn't want, certainly in
something she isn't old enough to manage, but she's found a way to
take the next step.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually so does Doty, but it isn't easy. He's bookish,
unathletic, and increasingly estranged from his classmates. Worse
still is his mother's alcoholism, which would eventually kill her.
Yet he is saved time and again by the alchemy of art _ dance,
music, the rhythm of words. This memoir borrows its title from Igor
Stravinsky's ``Firebird'' Suite, Doty's favorite symphonic piece.
Doty casts himself as the same kind of mythic bird, always rising
from the dust and ashes to grasp onto something wondrous and
exciting.
</P>
<P>
   Some memoirists attempt to reinhabit their childhood minds, with
wildly varying results. (Frank McCourt's ``Angela's Ashes'' is one
of the standout successes.) Doty does not. He is always the
narrator walking through his own life, the man gazing upon the
child. This method allows Doty to observe himself, sometimes with
devastating scrutiny. It imbues this book with greater honesty, and
makes his observations _ such as remembering himself as a ``heavy
little sissy in glasses'' all the more poignant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Firebird'' is not merely a coming-out story, though Doty's
burgeoning homosexuality is certainly part of the equation. It
really concerns the creative birth of a poet _ one whose collection
``My Alexandria'' won the 1993 National Book Critics Circle Award _
and a man polished by hardship, including an ill-fated 9-year
marriage. By book's end, it seems that Doty finds the bad memories
as precious as the good ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live the stories we tell; the stories we don't tell live
us,'' Doty writes. ``To tell a story is to take power over it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
