<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5120 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHORS-PHILIP'S-WAR-     11-01 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHORS-PHILIP'S-WAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNEARTHING KING PHILIP'S WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUDBURY, Mass. _ Eric Schultz is walking past gravestones, on a
search deep into New England's past, to the time when the early
harmony between the British settlers and Native Americans ended,
disastrously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just about here,'' says Schultz, gesturing toward a patch of
ground in the middle of the Wadsworth Cemetery. ``That's where they
were buried, stacked in a square, and covered with stones to
protect them from wolves.''
</P>
<P>
   Schultz points to a spot where three Colonial officers and 26
militiamen were killed by Nipmuc Indians and their allies during a
fierce, three-day firefight in April 1676.
</P>
<P>
   The Sudbury Fight and myriad other clashes of what became known
as King Philip's War are chronicled _ and clearly mapped _ in a new
book by Schultz and fellow amateur historian Michael Tougias.
</P>
<P>
   While the warfare was a landmark event of the era, it has
received scant attention in American histories, rating at best a
sentence or two. But that is changing. Schultz and Tougias's book,
``King Philip's War: The History and Legacy of America's Forgotten
Conflict,'' is one of three dealing with the war to appear in a
two-year period. It joins Jill Lepore's ``The Name of War,''which
won the prestigious Bancroft Prize for 1998, and ``King Philip's
War,'' a scholarly account by James D. Drake to be published by the
University of Massachusetts Press in January.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the Schultz-Tougias book that brings the many battle
sites across southern New England to light, as best they can be
determined from the evidence left from an age of wilderness, and
it's a useful guide to the curious.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians' leader was Metacom, or King Philip, as he was known
by the colonists. In the kind of ironic twist often found in
history, he was the son of Massasoit, who had helped the Pilgrims
during their early years at Plymouth.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, relations between the native Algonquin people
and the ever-increasing numbers of colonists soured. Angered by the
unchecked spread of settlements, Philip began attacking them in
June 1675.
</P>
<P>
   In the 14 months that followed, 25 towns _ more than half the
Colonial settlements of New England _ were destroyed and at least
10 percent of the Colonial population killed. But the Indian losses
were even greater, mainly from disease and starvation. Many of the
survivors were sold into slavery. And the settlers emerged
paramount.
</P>
<P>
   The Sudbury battle was the high-water mark for the Indians, says
Schultz: ``It was their finest victory, and very cleverly
planned.'' They lured the militia up the slope of Green Hill behind
the field that is now the cemetery _ in the direction of two
fortified garrisons _ but then set the hillside brush afire to
drive the militiamen down into the ambush.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
An unusual scholar
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, Schultz seems in some ways the opposite of a
historical scholar. He's a high-tech CEO at Sensitech, a firm that
creates programs to monitor perishable goods as they're
transported. But history is his passion, and was his major at Brown
University before he attended Harvard Business School.
</P>
<P>
   He started researching the war eight years ago, when he took a
year off from work following the birth of his first child.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz grew up near one of the major sites of King Philip's War
_ Anawan Rock, in Rehoboth, Mass., where the Wampanoag leader
Anawan was captured in August 1676, effectively ending the war in
southern New England _ just four months after the Indian victory at
Sudbury and two weeks after Philip himself was killed at Bristol,
R.I.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I took the school bus right past Anawan Rock,''
Schultz says.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the frustration he experienced while reading a 1906
recounting of the war that that inspired him to research it _ and,
in particular, its historic sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the kind of person who likes to see, touch, walk the
places I read about,'' Schultz says, ``like walking the field at
Gettysburg.'' But, he says, ``I couldn't find the places where
events happened from what was in the book. So I went off myself and
started compiling and mapping the sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, he says, he'd start with a local historian. ``In
every town, I'd find someone who knew the local site. And if the
historical marker was in the wrong place, they'd know where it
should be.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Schultz's year off was over, he had three-quarters
of a book written. ``I figured I'd pick away on it,'' he says,
``maybe finish it up the next time I had a career change.''
</P>
<P>
   But two years ago, Schultz read an item about the publication of
a novel by Tougias and dropped him a note. Tougias, like Schultz,
has a ``day job'' _ at Liberty Mutual _ but has written a series of
books describing nature walks in New England. After writing a
historical novel about the war, ``Until I Have No Country,'' he had
thought about doing a guidebook to the sites.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Covering the same ground
</P>
<P>
   ``Our paths had probably crossed in the woods,'' Tougias says.
``But with our notebooks in our hands, we wouldn't have even
noticed each other.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tougias replied to Schultz's note, and the two met and
agreed to collaborate on a book that would tell the history of the
war through its sites, with accounts of what happened at each and
detailed maps of the major ones.
</P>
<P>
   Finding them was not all that easy, Schultz says.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler's Surprise, an Indian victory on the scale of the
Sudbury Fight, occurred in what is now New Braintree in August
1675. But exactly where is uncertain. The stone marker off Route 32
reads ``Somewhere within 1/2 mile . . . ,'' and historians, Schultz
says, ``have been debating the possibilities for years. There's
good evidence for each one, but no clear winner.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there are sites like that of Beer's Ambush in
Northfield in September 1675, which has been clearly marked. ``You
can walk right along the route the militia took that led them into
the ambush site,'' Schultz says.
</P>
<P>
   Precise identification and mapping of the sites is not just
useful for readers who may want to visit them, but also important
in understanding the tactics and the opposing sides. The Colonial
militia, at least in the early months of the war, marched into
battle _ and often into ambush _ like British regulars, while the
Indians used the terrain both to set up ambushes and, as at
Sudbury, to score a victory.
</P>
<P>
   While his and Tougias's book is not intended ``to prove a
thesis,'' Schultz says, he remains struck by ``how two cultures
almost overnight became so violently and so brutally at war with
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   And after all the years of being virtually forgotten, he says,
``it is begging to be reinterpreted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 1357EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
