<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5132 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-KNUSSEN-BOS &LR;      11-01 1528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-KNUSSEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONDUCTOR KNUSSEN BRINGS COPLAND, SENDAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the proudest traditions of the Boston Symphony Orchestra
is the composer-conducted concert. Ravel, Prokofiev, and Stravinsky
conducted their own works in historic Symphony Hall events, and in
more recent years so have Sir Michael Tippett, Sir Peter Maxwell
Davies, Witold Lutoslawski, and Oliver Knussen.
</P>
<P>
   Knussen returns this week for an unusual alternative version of
one of the most popular works of the repertory, Copland's
``Appalachian Spring,'' and the local premiere of one of his own
most successful works: ``Where the Wild Things Are,'' a one-act
opera he wrote in collaboration with Maurice Sendak, the famous
writer and illustrator of children's books. In a way, the piece
will be coming home, because its history began at Tanglewood in
1975.
</P>
<P>
   Knussen, one of the musical world's great talkers, came on the
phone from his home in London early last week to talk about the
opera and its story. ``It was the heady summer that the French
composer Olivier Messiaen was at Tanglewood, so that's why I was
hanging around. One night I was at a concert in the Shed, and a man
came up to me and asked if I were interested in writing an opera. I
said, `Well, sort of,' and I had actually been thinking about it.
He suggested we meet for lunch the next day because he had some
things he wanted to show me. I thought he was a potential
librettist _ his name was Mitchell Miller, known as Mike, the son
of Mitch Miller, a children's-book illustrator who had been
encouraged by Maurice Sendak.''
</P>
<P>
   Knussen, who turned 23 that summer, had been regarded as the
greatest hope for the future of English music since the premiere of
his First Symphony, when he was 15. ``As we sat in the cafeteria,
Mike took a bag and emptied the complete works of Maurice Sendak
onto the table. He told me that Sendak wanted to make an opera out
of his book `Higglety-Pigglety-Pop' _ I thought it was a wonderful
gesture for Mike to bring the work of someone else to my attention.
He suggested that I call Sendak. I knew who Sendak was, because I
had been hanging out at the Book Store up in Lenox. I'm a
generation too old to have grown up on the Sendak books, but I had
seen these extraordinary creations in the store, and knew his
position in the illustrating world. I thought that calling him up
would be a little like a composer calling up Leonard Bernstein and
saying, `Hey, I'm here.' But one day the phone rang, and it was
Sendak.''
</P>
<P>
   The first part of the conversation, Knussen reports, was a test.
``What's the best children's opera ever written?'' Sendak asked.
``I came back with the smart-aleck answer, which turned out to be
the right one _ the second act of `Boris Godunov,' with
Mussorgsky's fantastic characterization of the tsar's children and
their games. We started out sketching a libretto for `Higglety,'
but at that time I didn't write any music.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, Sendak was approached by the Theatre de la Monnaie in
Brussels, which was interested in turning ``Where the Wild Things
Are'' into an opera. ``We had talked about this book,'' Knussen
says, ``but we had decided it was too much of a visual thing. But
when this inquiry came, Maurice said, `Why don't we have a go, and
see if we can do something?' So we blocked it out, and over the
next two years I wrote it. What made it difficult to do is that the
story is mostly pictures, with very few words, so Maurice had to
build up the text, and I had to spell out the pictures in
orchestral terms. The score lasts just under 40 minutes, but it is
248 densely packed pages that represented a colossal effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many of Knussen's works, ``Where the Wild Things Are'' had
a difficult birth. The composer had not yet finished the opera at
the time of the first performance in 1980, so the premiere had
``holes'' in it. And, Knussen says, ``the event was what we
politely call `not a success.' The Brussels school kids were the
noisiest on the planet, and not a note of the music could be heard
over the incredible din. The dry-ice machine ran amok, so nothing
on the stage could be seen through the smoke. The opera was
performed in Flemish and in French, but you couldn't make out a
single word, so later performances were preceded by a professional
storyteller reading the book, originally a six-minute exercise
which got longer and longer every night, until it turned into `War
and Peace.' ''
</P>
<P>
   News traveled fast that the opera was ``not a success,'' so a
planned concert performance in London was canceled. The resourceful
composer, like many of his predecessors, got busy and ``extracted a
concert suite with some scissors and glue. I called it `Songs and a
Sea Interlude,' which I did with the BBC Symphony in 1981 _ this
was the first time I actually heard the music. As a result the
concert performance was reinstated, and then the Glyndebourne
Festival came onto the scene.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, after Knussen had rewritten about half the score,
``Where the Wild Things Are'' ran for more than 20 performances at
Glyndebourne, on tour, and in London's National Theater. It was
recorded and translated to video, and, Knussen says, ``the history
of the piece began.'' The original production, with sets and
costumes by Sendak, was widely seen (in America it was done in New
York, Chicago, Minneapolis-St. Paul, and Los Angeles). It has also
been performed in Germany in productions not designed by Sendak.
``I didn't see those German productions, but the photographs of one
of them looked as if it had been designed by Magritte, and everyone
was dressed in tight leather. By now, I have also done the opera
many times in concert, and it works extremely well that way because
the orchestra plays so active a role in it. I composed everything
with Maurice's drawings right in front of me, and the music
wouldn't exist without them.''
</P>
<P>
   Knussen and Sendak went on to create another opera out of
``Higglety-Pigglety-Pop,'' which was designed to go on a double
bill with ``Where the Wild Things Are,'' but its creation was
attended by even more difficulties. So far, it hasn't built up a
comparable performance history. But that may change; Knussen has
recorded both operas for Deutsche Grammophon with the London
Sinfonietta, and the performances await release. Sendak has heard a
rough cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``He semed to be very moved by it,'' Knussen says. ``It's no
secret both operas had a difficult start. It took me forever to
write them, and they were performed in various stages of
completion. But now, in their modest way, they seem to be coming
into their own, particularly `Where the Wild Things Are,' and
that's probably tremendously satisfying for him. I think Maurice is
a tremendously musical person, and I learned a tremendous amount
from him _ how you can cast a net of references very wide, provided
you've got your feet on the ground, and know who you are.''
</P>
<P>
   In his capacity as conductor, Knussen has become the most
significant advocate of Copland's music since Leonard Bernstein.
``I'm afraid Copland has become one of the great underrated
composers, and the more underrated he gets, the more important I
think he is. The elegance and discipline of his music stands the
test of time more and more, and it's still growing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Appalachian Spring'' was originally composed for a chamber
ensemble to accompany Martha Graham's choreography. Later Copland
expanded the scoring for full orchestra, but omitted some episodes
of the original ballet; in 1954, he orchestrated some of the
omitted passages for the Philadelphia Orchestra. Knussen is going
to conduct that version. ``The lesser-known passages are mostly the
music for Merce Cunningham's original role in the ballet, and it is
quite outside the style of the rest of the piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Knussen has long been a sought-after conductor; his Deutsche
Grammophon recordings of neglected 20th-century works are among the
most distinguished being produced  &UR; today &LR; . About half the 20 discs
he has made have been released; among those in the can are an
Elliott Carter disc (the clarinet concerto and the Symphonic
Triptych), a Mussorgsky/Stokowski record (``I pride myself on my
good taste,'' Knussen says), the two Schoenberg one-act operas, a
Peter Lieberson record, and a Busoni CD. ``Next year I'm going to
do Henze's Eighth Symphony and some music by Julian Anderson, a
spectacularly gifted young British composer who is worth fighting
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Knussen says he has been ``dormant'' as a composer for the last
couple of years, though he did replace an entire scene of
``Higglety-Pigglety-Pop'' before recording it. He is working on
pieces for Peter Serkin and the London Sinfonietta, and on a Fourth
Symphony for the New York Philharmonic. ``In various forms, that
has been in my notebooks for about eight years. I wanted to get it
out before 2000, but I'm not going to make it until next year. It's
another one-movement symphony, my fourth, and, I feel sure, my
last. Then I will be moving into other areas _ only I don't know
yet what they are!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
