<HEADLINE>
HOWARD COSELL'S LEGACY IN   THE TELEVISION WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With his zeppelin-like cigars, an even larger ego, and a
limitless supply of bombast, Howard Cosell harrumphed his way to
the top of the sportscasting world in the 1970s and early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But it turns out he had his eye on a more prestigious prize. In
an HBO documentary Monday night, Peter Jennings reveals (with a
barely suppressed smile) that Cosell ``told me for years that he
should have been the anchorman for the ABC Evening News.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, that ambition would have been laughable. But it
would be harder to laugh at today. For the strange and perhaps
unsettling reality is that while much has been written about
Cosell's impact on sports broadcasting, it is the news-oriented
hemisphere of the television world that bears Cosell's mark most
distinctly.
</P>
<P>
   Look around the tube. The cult of the outsized personality begun
by Cosell _ the notion that the interviewer is the star, whose
opinions and charisma outshine the guest _ has come to define
television. From Sam Donaldson to John McLaughlin to Chris
Matthews, from Geraldo Rivera to Larry King to Bill O'Reilly, it's
in vogue to strain for a Cosell-like aura of unpredictability and
contrarianism _ and for a voice no one can ignore or forget.
</P>
<P>
   There is another, broader development that can be indirectly
traced to Cosell: the transformation of prime time from the
exclusive bailiwick of entertainment to a place where news packaged
as entertainment increasingly holds sway.
</P>
<P>
   It all began with Cosell's influence on what makes a successful
television personality. Like Cosell, who died in 1995 at age 77,
today's media stars know the attention-getting value of
controversy, and consequently seem as willing to be hated as loved.
During his heyday, one survey rated Cosell both the most liked and
the most disliked sportscaster in America. However, one suspects
that the poll he valued most (and that Rivera et. al. would covet
most) was the one revealing that his name recognition stood at a
staggering 96 percent.
</P>
<P>
   His spirit of brash self-promotion coupled with genuine
journalistic enterprise is also reflected in ambitious young TV
reporters like ABC's John Stossel, who recently launched a regular
``20/20'' segment whose title Cosell would have liked: ``Give Me a
Break!''
</P>
<P>
   The key word in that title is ``Me.'' The projection of self was
the essence of Cosellism _ ``I think Howard saw himself as much of
an entertainer, as much of a celebrity, as the people he was
covering,'' one of his former bosses remarks in the documentary _
and it is the essence of the new media persona.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Barbara Walters is a major figure in this shift as
well. Her influence on the personality-driven journalism favored by
the current TV generation has been profound. But it was Cosell who
fused egocentricity with a tough-talking candor that have become
the twin hallmarks of contemporary media heavyweights.
</P>
<P>
   Cosell's trademark boast was that he alone was ``telling it like
it is,'' and it was often true. When Frank Gifford once protested
that he was being too tough on a football team, Cosell retorted:
``If we see it, Giff, we've got to say it.'' That could be the
credo of the best of the news-oriented talkshow stars, such as
Matthews, host of CNBC's ``Hardball,'' who refuses to let his
guests off the hook as tries to blast through the prevailing
Beltway cant.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this description of Cosell by a former colleague: ``He
was frankly sort of bored with the mundane essence of sports. He
loved the larger issues of conflicts, politics and human drama.''
Now substitute the word ``policy'' for ``sports.'' Couldn't that
quote fit any number of contemporary talk-show hosts?
</P>
<P>
   By contrast to the freewheeling news-talk arena, national sports
broadcasts are still dominated by ex-jocks who subscribe to a
speak-no-evil ethos, or announcers who seldom venture a criticism
of the athletes they plainly worship. The hellfire that rained down
last week on NBC's Jim Gray after he badgered Pete Rose on gambling
issues derived partly from Gray's ham-fisted approach, but part of
it may have been the public's shock at seeing a sportscaster
actually confront an athlete. Gray apologized to viewers the next
night; it is difficult to picture the defiant Cosell doing the
same.
</P>
<P>
   It's become increasingly common for TV reporters, anchors and
talk-show hosts to play themselves in movies, blurring the line
between journalism and showbiz. Cosell was ahead of that curve,
too. Back in the early '70s, when Woody Allen was still making
funny movies rather than stilted exercises in pseudo-profundity,
Cosell made a hilarious cameo appearance in Allen's ``Bananas.'' He
paved the way for Larry King, who has cropped up in more movies
lately than Kevin Costner.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he was announcing, interviewing, or reporting, Cosell
never had any problem throwing off the constraints of objectivity,
and he saw the value of wrapping himself in a good cause. To his
eternal credit, he championed the cause of Muhammad Ali. For much
of 1998, Geraldo Rivera threw himself with Cosellian fervor into a
more dubious cause: the defense of President Clinton against
efforts to impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond all this is the transformation of prime time from pure
entertainment to news-as-entertainment, a shift that Cosell helped
make possible.
</P>
<P>
   Before ``Monday Night Football'' debuted in 1970, prime time
belonged almost entirely to sitcoms, dramas, and variety shows.
There was only one newsmagazine on the air, CBS's then-young ``60
Minutes.'' Network entertainment divisions ruled the nighttime
roost; the news and sports divisions had to settle for time slots
in the early evenings and and on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   However, with Cosell as its star for the next 13 years, ``Monday
Night Football'' earned blockbuster ratings and became a national
phenomenon. It also established a beachhead for nonfiction TV
programs from which there was no turning back. It proved networks
didn't need to rely on sitcoms and dramas alone to succeed in prime
time, as long as nonfiction programs were dressed up with snazzy
production values.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the technological bells and whistles of the football
telecasts upped the ante, and set the standard, for the news
divisions. It was no accident that the architect of ``Monday Night
Fooball,'' ABC Sports president
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 1358EST &QL; 
