<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5134 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-TUROW-BOS &LR;      11-01 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TUROW-BOS </SLUG>
  
 TUROW THRILLER PUTS SLEAZY OPERATOR IN LAW'S EMPLOY
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   PERSONAL INJURIES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Scott Turow &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. 403 pp. $27. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When people invoke the thuggish proposal in Shakespeare's
``Henry VI'' to kill all the lawyers, chances are they mean to put
personal-injury attorneys at the top of the hit list. These are the
guys, according to stereotype, who see a cash cow in every tragedy
_ who would make a relative wear a neck brace for a stubbed toe if
it would raise the ante. But they're also the ones who fight for
the little people against the Darth Vaders of the insurance
business (albeit for a third of the cut). So leave it to Scott
Turow to recognize an enticingly murky moral situation within the
not-so-hallowed halls of our legal system. In ``Personal
Injuries,'' he has made his anti-hero a likable PI lawyer with an
inner code as mutable as a chameleon at twilight. The villains, if
they'll stay still long enough to be ID'd, are the supposed icons
of integrity wearing black robes _ judges on the take, in other
words, and hardly above killing the lawyers who try to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Since ``Presumed Innocent'' made him America's erudite Grisham
more than a decade ago, Turow has centered each of his elaborate
legal thrillers upon some classic moral conundrum: the collision
between private love and public honor; avarice and sacrifice;
personal honesty and professional scorn. His skill has been in
imagining characters of emotional complexity whose human failings
have enormous consequence _ jealousy writ large as homicide;
betrayal offering the first loose thread of a widening scandal. In
``Personal Injuries,'' he has envisioned this mare's nest of
intrigue with legal sophistication and narrative tension. But
Turow's creative gifts are too often eclipsed by his analytic ones
in this novel; it's simply a matter of death by detail. For all its
intelligence and painstaking legal accuracy, ``Personal Injuries''
can be as wearying as studying torts on a Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Though not all the time, thanks to two indelibly realized
characters _ a lawyer and an undercover FBI agent _ who steal the
show from the pallid gang of thieves. The first is Robbie Feavor,
the snake-oil protagonist who in the opening pages of the novel is
busted by the IRS for concealing money. Robbie is privy to bigger
things, which is why the US attorney is present at the raid. With
his lawyer and lifelong friend, Mort Dinnerstein, Robbie has been
paying off some of the top judges in Turow's fictional Kindle
County. The highest on high, and the most untouchable, is one
Brendan Tuohey _ former police officer, legendary pol, and
presiding judge of the Common Law Claims Division, where all
personal-injury cases are heard. He also happens to be
Dinnerstein's beloved uncle, and the Irish patriarch who played
paterfamilias to Robbie's own fatherless youth.
</P>
<P>
   Which ought to make this a drama of great emotion, since its
crux _ the sins of the father, and all _ rests on Robbie's turning
confidential informant for the state. Agreeing to wear a wire while
he makes the money drops, Robbie finds himself the star player in a
veritable roadshow of lawyers, guns, and money _ a judicial sting
orchestrated to such fine pitch that the state even brings in fake
lawyers to try fictional cases before the judges under suspicion.
Their best plant, for our purposes, is the other wonderful
character of the novel: an FBI agent posing as Robbie's paralegal,
Evon Miller, who also happens to be a Quantico firearms instructor
and former Olympic hockey player.
</P>
<P>
   The legal labyrinths revealed by Operation Petros are deftly
navigated by Turow, though they hardly make for mesmerizing
narrative. More problematic is an unevenness in character
dimension; in some ways, ``Personal Injuries'' is simply too
complicated to be very deep. This particularly applies to the bad
guys, who mostly come across as scantily imagined blackguards,
whatever their individual moral failings. Tuohey himself remains
utterly unknowable, at best an amoral apparition, while his
lower-court judges _ ranging from a Southern black man with a chip
on his shoulder to a soft-centered alcoholic woman _ all lend
themselves to one-sentence personality profiles. This lightness of
attention robs the novel of a certain emotional staying power: We
know the rascals are criminal and even dangerous, but they don't
seem very real, and therefore not very threatening _ more like bad
outtakes from ``Law &AMP; Order.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead Turow has concentrated his empathic sights on the likes
of an oily rogue with a well-concealed and tender heart, as well as
the conflicted young female agent who agrees to spot him for the
feds. Robbie's charismatic optimism barely conceals his troubles at
home, where the wife he adores lies dying from the last awful
stages of Lou Gehrig's disease. Evon, who's spent her career and
most of her life shielding herself from getting too involved with
anyone, finds herself caught in the tailspin mutability of
undercover work, caring for Robbie even as she disdains him. Both
characters, especially Evon, are intricate enough to draw us
through their story, even when it resorts to a kind of
write-by-numbers formula of the white hats in pursuit of the black.
</P>
<P>
   Because really, how long can you rework this genre, even
intelligently, before you simply start sounding like yourself all
over again? And Turow sounds tired here, at least when he's
relinquished the personal turmoil of his best characters for the
demands of dramatizing the judicial sting. He's also set up a
credibility problem by telling his story from the first-person
point of view of Robbie's lawyer, George Mason. This means that
Mason must explain his own impossible omniscience, which extends to
Evon's inner thoughts and private dialogue, by saying he learned
all this later from lengthy conversations with everyone involved.
Turow could have solved his dilemma by cross-cutting between (say)
Mason's and Evon's voices, or even Mason's and a third-person
narration; as it is, the story continually grates when it gets into
territory surmised or imagined by Mason.
</P>
<P>
   But these are literary failings, none of which ever kept a
certain kind of writer off the best-seller list. Turow has made his
mark over the years by corralling the depravity of the human
condition within the ironic parameters _ scuffed mahogany and
burned-out idealists _ of the judicial system itself. The plot of
this novel is based on a similar judicial sting that took place in
Chicago in the 1980s, which Turow, as a practicing lawyer, helped
to try.
</P>
<P>
   So he may have his own lesson to learn in ``Personal Injuries,''
which is that the facts of law are no more compelling, or
demanding, than the laws of fiction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
