</P>
<P>
   BOOK-TUROW (Undated) _ In ``Personal Injuries,'' Scott Turow he
has made his anti-hero a likable PI lawyer with an inner code as
mutable as a chameleon at twilight. But Turow's creative gifts are
too often eclipsed by his analytic ones; it's simply a matter of
death by detail. By Gail Caldwell. 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-FIREBIRD (Undated) _ Perhaps no passage better captures the
humor and heartbreak of Mark Doty's vivid, exquisite memoir,
``Firebird,'' than his recollection of an incident when he was 10.
By Renee Graham.
</P>
<P>
   AUTHORS-PHILIP'S-WAR (Undated) _ In a new book, two history
buffs locate key New England battle sites from King Philip's War,
often desribed as America's forgotten conflict. By Michael Kenney.
1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-TIPS (Undated) _ What's hot on the just-published list.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-RAGE (Undated) _ It comes as no surprise that the group
Rage Against the Machine is still raging on a new album, ``The
Battle of Los Angeles.'' By Steve Morse. 970 words.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-MURRAY (New York) _ The question puzzling many jazz fans
in recent years is, whatever happened to saxophonist David Murray?
As far as Murray is concerned, he never left the scene. By Fred
Kaplan. 1,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-KNUSSEN (Undated) _ Conductor Oliver Knussen returns to
the Boston Symphony Orchestra for an unusual alternative version of
one of the most popular works of the repertory, Copland's
``Appalachian Spring. By Richard Dyer. 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
