<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5138 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-TB-ART-BOS &LR;      11-01 1506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-TB-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUBERCULOSIS STRATEGY BORN OF TWO DOCTORS' DEVOTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a spring day in 1995, a relief worker for Partners in Health
flew from Peru to Boston. He was coughing terribly. Doctors later
diagnosed him with tuberculosis and began their treatment with
antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   Seven weeks later he was dead.
</P>
<P>
   Lab results revealed that his strain of the disease couldn't be
cured by four common anti-TB drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston health care community worried that the worker's
illness would trigger an outbreak, but fortunately it never
occurred. But the tragedy also propelled Partners in Health, begun
by Drs. Paul Farmer and Jim Yong Kim, back to Peru to find the
source of the multidrug-resistant TB _ and then figure out how to
treat it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, four years later, their effort not only has saved the lives
of about 100 people in Lima who had the disease, but they hope it
saves tens of thousands more around the world.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, the World Health Organization and others at
the center of global TB control had been saying that if you were
poor in the Third World and you contracted multidrug-resistant TB,
there was nothing to be done. Most would die. Drugs were too
expensive and treatment too difficult.
</P>
<P>
   But in Lima, Partners in Health proved otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Following a meeting with global TB experts last week in New
York, including WHO officials, Partners in Health's Peru
prescription _ an intensified regimen in which additional drugs are
given to people over a longer period of time _ will be adopted in
pilot projects in drug-resistant TB ``hot spots'' such as Russia,
Latvia, and Kazakhstan. Comprehensive programs there and elsewhere
in the world, however, won't start until caregivers secure hundreds
of millions of dollars in additional funding.
</P>
<P>
   That hunt for money is now under way by Partners in Health
co-founders Farmer and Kim, who are taking their pitches to
foundations established by the barons of the 20th century:
Rockefeller, Soros, Gates, Kellogg, and Ford.
</P>
<P>
   The new strategy, which is to give patients up to seven drugs
daily for up to two years, appears to be 85 percent effective, and
costs between $300 and $4,000. That's far less than what treatment
costs for TB in the United States and other developed nations.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer and Kim's efforts represent a huge leap from the group's
beginnings in 1987, when Partners had no paid staff and a one-room
office in Cambridge, Mass.. Now, they have a $3 million budget, 300
paid workers (most of them in Haiti and Peru), and they are the
co-directors of the program in infectious disease and social change
at Harvard Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, the group expanded its delivery of health
care from the countryside of Haiti, to the slums of Peru, to the
mountains of Chiapas, to the streets of Roxbury, Mass., and to the
prisons of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   They traveled to all those places guided by a single principle:
every person should have equal access to health care. That
philosophy springs from Roman Catholic liberation theology, which
says it's imperative to give preferential options for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it O-for-the-P,'' Farmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer and Kim, both 40, met as Harvard medical students,
arriving in Cambridge on roads that wouldn't normally intersect.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer was born in North Adams, Mass., and his schoolteacher
father and mother took him and five siblings through a years-long
adventure in the South, settling once in a bus-turned-house in
Florida that had been used as a roving clinic to immunize people
against tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   Kim, born in Seoul, immigrated at the age of 4 with his family
to Dallas. His father was a dentist and his mother a neo-Confuscian
philosopher. They settled the family on the banks of the
Mississippi River, in Muscatine, Iowa, a place that Mark Twain
loved for its crimson sunsets.
</P>
<P>
   At Harvard, they interned and completed their residencies
together at Brigham and Women's Hospital, earned medical degrees
and doctorates in anthropology, and teamed to form Partners in
Health.
</P>
<P>
   Partners, almost from the start, has been directed by five
people in all: Farmer; Kim; writer Ophelia Dahl, daughter of writer
Roald Dahl; philanthropist Thomas J. White, a Boston builder; and
Todd McCormack, a businessman. It now includes a new generation of
Harvard-trained medical scholars, all about 30 years old: Mercedes
Becerra, Jennifer Furin, Carole Mitnick, and Sonya Shin.
</P>
<P>
   The group's first focus was Haiti, the poorest nation in the
Western Hemisphere. There, they established a community health
center in the village of Canges. Farmer liked to call work in Haiti
``an area of moral clarity,'' because, he said, service to the
destitute and sick was ``morally, speaking, a no-brainer.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the community-based projects in Chiapas, Mexico; Lima,
Peru; and Boston. The latter is a $500,000 annual project called
Soldiers of Health, a partnership with a local group that helps
residents navigate and gain access to the health care system, even
if Brigham and Women's Hospital is just a subway stop away.
</P>
<P>
   Tuberculosis, often tagged ``ebola with wings,'' because of its
lethality and because of its ease of spreading through air, has
become more entrenched and more difficult to treat in the past
decade, as inefficient control programs have helped create new
strains of drug-resistant TB. TB now kills more than 2 million
people a year, more than AIDS/HIV, or malaria, or any other
infectious disease. No vaccine exists. No new drugs have been
developed in a generation.
</P>
<P>
   It passes from person to person with a sneeze or a cough, the
tiny bacteria inhaled or ingested. A person sick with TB will
infect, on average, about 10 others a year. And once the TB bug
settles in someone's lungs and starts destroying them, it can move
to the brain, liver, kidney, and spine, setting off a fight between
the bug and a person's immune system.
</P>
<P>
   Multidrug-resistant TB is much more complicated and expensive to
cure. But Farmer and Kim explained how they attacked the problem in
Peru to a group of TB control experts at a meeting in Cambridge
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people came very skeptical about what these guys had
to say,'' said Dr. Howard Hiatt, former dean of Harvard's School of
Public Health and now professor of medicine at Harvard Medical
School. ``They were blown away by what they heard. Imagine going
into an impoverished community in Peru and attacking a problem that
the experts said was insoluble and coming out with nearly 90
percent cure rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hiatt believes that Farmer and Kim, in particular, ``are really
the ones responsible for this worldwide decision to address the
problem of MDR-TB (multi-drug resistant TB). It's not only for
humanitarian reasons, though that's what motivates Farmer and Kim,
but for practical reasons. As long as it exists, it's a threat to
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The two longtime friends, Farmer and Kim, aren't shy about
articulating their fervent beliefs about the need for equal access
to health care for the poor. Sometimes that rankles others,
sometimes that wins them over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farmer challenged me,'' said Dr. Arata Kochi, director of
WHO's global tuberculosis program, referring to the meeting called
by Hiatt. ``Farmer said, `What are you going to do about MDR-TB?' I
told him we don't have the data yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Kochi said there was a clash in perspectives: ``They see a
patient from a very individualistic perspective. We look at it from
a public health perspective, where we have to make priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was no ill feeling from the meeting, he said,
adding, ``We need these kinds of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmer and Kim say that they see matters from both humanitarian
and practical perspectives, even if their top priority is the care
of the patient.
</P>
<P>
   The jump into fighting drug-resistant TB worldwide comes with
substantial risks. One is financial. The group has been long
supported by White, the Boston builder, who is in the process of
giving out his last millions. Now it must find new sources of
funding. Hence, the appeals to the foundations of the barons. If
they don't secure funding in the next few months, they may be
forced to scale back their operations.
</P>
<P>
   Another risk is taking on too much. But they both have no doubt
their focus will remain the same _ O-for-the-P, as they like to
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we talked about moving beyond Haiti and Peru, we decided
that we should do it, but only if we had a chance to impact on
international policy,'' Kim said. ``What we hope is that MDR-TB may
be the way of pushing forward this option for the poor movement. To
us, those with drug-resistant TB are among the most outcast, the
most marginalized people in the world. We will always remain
grounded in the experiences of the poor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 1400EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5139 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-GERMS-ART-BOS &LR;      11-01 1731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GERMS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS LAUNCH COUNTERATTACK ON RESISTANT BUGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo and graphic are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since midsummer, a nasty intestinal bug called shigella has
sickened hundreds of adults and children in western Massachusetts
with its customary misery of abdominal cramps, nausea, and bloody
diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
   Shigella bacteria, which can spread through lax handwashing and
are sometimes found in food, rarely kill, and common antibiotics
like ampicillin and sulfa drugs usually knock them out. But when
doctors prescribed these antibiotics for the current outbreak, they
were disturbed to learn that the drugs didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started getting calls from pediatricians saying the kids
weren't getting better,'' recalled Dr. Donna Fischer, a children's
infections specialist at Bay State Medical Center in Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   Lab tests revealed that this particular strain of shigella was,
like an increasing number of bacteria today, resistant to the
first-line antibiotics that once killed them. Now, doctors in the
Springfield, Mass., area had to switch to more powerful
antibiotics, like augmentin and ciprofloxacin. It made treating the
outbreak ``a little more difficult and expensive,'' said Fischer.
</P>
<P>
   This is just one skirmish in the great global battle pitting
medications once dubbed ``miracle drugs'' against wily bacteria,
which have often learned to outmaneuver them. Decades of too-casual
use and inappropriate prescribing of antibiotics for colds or other
viral illnesses have enabled many disease-causing bacteria to
develop resistance to many of the drugs, and in some cases, to
nearly all of them.
</P>
<P>
   When antibiotics are overused, they create conditions under
which a few mutant bacteria that evade the drug can reproduce and
flourish. These resistant strains replace the normal bugs, and they
also can pass their traits to other microbes.
</P>
<P>
   This potentially disastrous trend has been worsening year by
year, but until recently, hadn't prompted much action. ``We have
failed to see the true dimensions of the problem,'' said Dr. Stuart
B. Levy, a Tufts University School of Medicine infectious disease
specialist who has been sounding the alarm for many years.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jesse Goodman, a Food and Drug Administration official who
co-directs a federal interagency task force on antibiotic
resistance, said the problem is so serious that in intensive care
units of big hospitals ``we may have only one, or in some cases, no
effective licensed products to treat certain infections.'' And he
continued, ``in the community (outside hospitals), where tried and
true and inexpensive therapies may have worked for many, many
years, we may now have to use more expensive agents'' or ones that
have drawbacks, like side effects such as rashes, vomiting, and
muscular pains.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a counterattack is under way. Medical organizations here
and abroad are launching campaigns to promote more responsible use
of antibiotics. Pharmaceutical companies _ which 10 or 15 years ago
viewed antibiotics as a dwindling market because many infectious
diseases seemed to have been conquered _ have begun developing new
drugs that they hope will hold the fort against the superbugs, at
least for awhile.
</P>
<P>
   One such drug, Synercid, was rushed through approval by the FDA
this year for use against life-threatening infections by a bug
called enterococcus faecium. Even before approval, the FDA allowed
Syndercid to be used on an emergency basis for hospitalized
patients with enterococcus infections that were invulnerable to
vancomycin, a last-ditch antibiotic.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Cambridge, Cubist Pharmaceuticals, Inc. is
developing a novel drug called daptomycin that's shown it can kill
vancomycin-resistant enterococcus in animals.
</P>
<P>
   Another new drug, still in the pipeline, is called Zyvox. If it
is approved, it will be the first antibiotic with a new way of
killing bacteria in the United States in 35 years; it's previously
been used in Europe and targets a part of the bug's life cycle that
hasn't been attacked before.
</P>
<P>
   And Tufts' Levy has jumped into the antibiotic fray himself,
forming a company along with Harvard's Nobel prize-winning
biologist Walter Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   Their first project is to revive the potency of tetracycline, a
venerable antibiotic that has lost much of its power. ``Our goal is
to bring about a renaissance of tetracycline,'' which was
discovered in 1947 and was for decades a safe, reliable workhorse
antibiotic. The refurbished drug is in animal testing now.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston company, called Paratek, has won the confidence of
Glaxo, the pharmaceutical giant, which is putting up $95 million to
collaborate with Paratek in its effort to bring a rejuvenated
tetracycline to market, as well as other antibiotics yet to be
developed.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, ``The Antibiotic Paradox,'' Levy relates one of the
earliest examples of the lifesaving power of penicillin. In the
early 1940s, a tragic fire in Boston's Cocoanut Grove nightclub
killed more than 400 people, but more would have died, Levy writes,
had the federal government not released some supplies of penicillin
to treat the survivors of the fire, who were at great risk of
lethal infections from severe burns. Penicillin was still a
top-secret drug, reserved for military use only. But during the war
and afterwards, penicillin took the spotlight as the first of the
``wonder drugs'' _ and for years it was available without
prescription, encouraging overuse of the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Antibiotics halt infections by attacking some key structure or
event in the bacteria's life cycle, preventing it from reproducing.
But over time, bacteria exposed to rising levels of antibiotics
often adapt, evolving through mutations a strategy for foiling the
antiobiotic's assault.
</P>
<P>
   Levy discovered in the 1980s the clever evolutionary trick by
which some bacteria became resistant to tetracycline. The
antibiotic normally works by entering the bacterium through its
cell wall and jamming a genetic mechanism necessary for the cell to
reproduce.
</P>
<P>
   Through years of exposure to tetracycline, though, some of the
strains developed tiny pumps in their cell walls. So now, when the
antibiotic entered the cell, it was immediately pumped out again,
like sailors bailing out of a boat.
</P>
<P>
   Paratek's scheme for thwarting the resistant bugs is to
bioengineer tetracycline with a molecule that blocks the pumps so
they can't remove the tetracycline. And, the scientists found,
these modified tetracycline versions also neutralize a separate
resistance mechanism deeper in the cell.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the more that antibiotics are used, the more they
seed their own destruction _ the ``paradox'' of Levy's book. By
some estimates, half the antibiotic prescriptions in the United
States each year are unnecessary; they're given for viral
infections against which they're ineffective, for example. In other
cases, patients stop taking antibiotics as soon as they feel
better, a dangerous practice because partially resistant bugs can
survive and add to the pool of resistant organisms.
</P>
<P>
   Giving antibiotics to farm animals in their feed is another
source of resistance, and one that the FDA, after years of urging
by activists like Levy, is scrutinizing. The agency has pubished a
proposed regulatory framework for reducing the drugs' use in
agriculture, said the FDA's Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, most troubling, are signs that resistant bugs once found
only in hospitals, brewed in intensive care units by the
unavoidably high use of antibiotics there, are making their way
into the outside world. In August, the federal Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention reported that four children had died since
1997 in Minnesota and North Dakota from common infections that had
become drug-resistant.
</P>
<P>
   The children, who had previously been healthy, contracted
infections from staphylococcus aureus _ a leading cause of hospital
infections _ that couldn't be killed by methicillin, the drug
normally used to treat them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those patients could have been treated with vancomycin, but it
was assumed you didn't get antibiotic resistant organisms outside
the hospital,'' said David K. Stone, managing director of Liberty
Tree Advisors of Acton, which follows the pharmaceutical industry.
``They were initially treated with antibiotics that weren't
effective, and by the time it was recognized'' it was too late to
save the young patients, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A particularly sharp worry is that vancomycin itself may become
ineffective against staph aureus infections, leaving no drug to
combat this common bug. The staph bacteria live harmlessly on the
skin of most people, but a break in the skin or another injury can
enable them to invade the heart, bone, and bloodstream with lethal
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the most widespread resistance problem involves
streptococcus pneumoniae, the germs that cause bacterial pneumonia,
ear infections, and meningitis. When pneumococcus invades the
bloodstream, it can be quickly lethal.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, there were 60,000 cases of invasive pneumococcal
infections, ``and one-quarter were not susceptible to penicillin,''
said Dr. J. Todd Weber, senior medical officer at the CDC, adding
that one in seven of the cases involved pneumococci that were
resistant to three different classes of drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Synercid, the new drug against vancomycin-resistant enterococci,
seems potent but hasn't yet been proven to reduce deaths from the
resistant bugs. In any case, Levy says, Synercid, while filling an
important need, ``is only a partial answer.'' For already, in
clinical trials, bugs resistant to Synercid have already appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman, the FDA official, says that the need will continue
``for many different drugs and strategies'' to fight the resistance
problem. Some measures are as simple as more conscientious
handwashing, to reduce the spread of germs, to high-tech vaccines
that may prevent many infectious diseases that now are treated with
antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   At present, he said, antibiotics old and new ``have saved many
lives, but given the nature of how microbes evolve, we can't rely
on any one drug or class of drugs to solve the problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
