<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINE SHUTTLE RULES NOT THE TICKET FOR COUPLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL AND PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stephen Smith knows air travel is full of unpredictability, but
this much he thought he knew: Pay in advance for a flight, and the
airline is guaranteeing you a seat or compensation if it can't put
you on board.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith's expectation turned out to be wrong when dealing with
the US Airways Shuttle, one of two shuttle services that fly from
Boston to New York and Washington, D.C. He found that with this
service, the concept of ``first-come, first-served'' is the only
one that really counts. A prepaid ``reservation'' doesn't mean
anything in the traditional sense.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's other shuttle carrier, Delta Air Lines, which charges
roughly the same prices as the US Airways Shuttle, says it promises
a seat to all ticketed passengers, even those arriving within a few
minutes of departure. Delta officials say anyone denied a seat gets
a free ticket and room on the next flight.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's recent mix-up with US Airways caused him and his wife,
Marcia, six hours of hassles one recent night, and nearly forced
them to make on-the-spot arrangements for an overnight stay in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this one, I was out of my mind,'' said Smith, 61, a
financial officer who lived in Needham, Mass. for 30 years before
moving recently to Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
   At first, nothing seemed out of the ordinary on the evening of
Oct. 10, when the Smiths went to Logan Airport for an 8:15 p.m.
shuttle flight, the last of the night, to Washington's Dulles
Airport, near their new home.
</P>
<P>
   The couple had a written confirmation of their reservation for
the flight and, having paid at least 14 days in advance, each got a
$134 round-trip fare, about one-third of the full fare.
</P>
<P>
   Like other consumers, they appreciate the convenience of shuttle
services that operate every day with flights generally every hour
or every other hour and with reduced rates for weekend, off-peak,
and advance-purchase customers.
</P>
<P>
   When the Smiths arrived at the gate well before departure time,
their relaxed evening turned frantic: The gate agent told them no
seats were left. The agent said all seating was first-come,
first-served, the first notice the couple had that their tickets
guaranteed no seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I protested this cavalier approach, I was informed that I
could book the first flight out the next day,'' Stephen Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Even as agents offered the next-day flight and no sleepover
accommodations, they also reminded the couple to be there bright
and early because the US Airways Shuttle never guarantees a seat.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he later learned from fellow travelers that two US
Airways shuttle flights earlier that evening had been canceled,
causing those passengers to bump many customers, like him and his
wife, booked for the 8:15 p.m. flight.
</P>
<P>
   After much arguing with gate agents, he and his wife got on the
shuttle scheduled for 8:15, which did not leave until after
midnight. They ended up at their home around 2 a.m. the next day.
Smith said he and other travelers never got a satisfactory reason
why the plane was delayed for so long.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the nonreservation issue gets worse. US Airways had
imposed a $75 penalty when Marcia Smith, earlier in the month, had
to cancel a shuttle ticket because of a change in plans. He said
she ``ended up paying $75 to cancel a flight that she didn't have
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the penalty, which he originally thought was
reasonable, now seemed outrageous. He likened it to a restaurant
owner charging a penalty for a reservation no-show, even though the
owner never saved a table for that person anyway.
</P>
<P>
   David Castelveter, a spokesman for US Airways based in
Arlington, Va., acknowledged that a prepaid ticket is no guarantee
of a seat, only the ability to secure a lower fare. He said
ticketed passengers _ whether they paid months in advance or that
day _ compete equally for seats once the gate opens an hour ahead
of departure time.
</P>
<P>
   Castelveter confirmed that a $75 penalty is charged to
passengers with advance-purchase tickets who make changes to the
itinerary or cancel. The only exception is that US Airways does
allow passengers to fly ``stand-by'' on the same day for a
different flight and will waive the fee.
</P>
<P>
   William Crumbley, managing director of the Delta Shuttle, said
``we hold that promise sacred'' that any ticket holder or walk-up
passenger is guaranteed a seat on the next shuttle, even if they
have to pull out an extra plane for only a few passengers. He said
Delta fulfills that promise 95 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   An infuriated Smith said US Airways ought to write out its
shuttle rules for customers like himself, so they can know when a
flight's rules differ from the standard practice. No such brochures
exist, and even our phone calls to US Airways ticket agents
produced different answers to the same questions.
</P>
<P>
   And, said Castelveter, such a shuttle-rules brochure is unlikely
given the complexity of the task. ``We'd issue a book,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bypass long-distance fees
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So many readers were interested in prepaid calling cards as a
way to avoid those onerous fees and charges showing up on
long-distance bills that we thought we'd provide updates on a
couple of other options.
</P>
<P>
   Calling over the Internet is one of our favorites. A computer
isn't necessary; you just have to dial some extra numbers. With
most companies, you dial an access number (local or toll-free),
punch in a pin number, and then dial the number you are calling.
The call is carried over the Internet and then routed on to the
local phone system wherever you are calling. You prepay for calls
with a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   We've tried and liked Net2Phone Direct from IDT Corp. of
Hackensack, N.J. (877-627-4663), which charges 4.9 cents a minute
any time when a local access number is used and 7.9 cents a minute
using a toll-free number. Best of all, there are no extra fees or
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has its version called Connect'N Save (800-345-0995). It
charges 7.5 cents a minute any time using a local access number and
15 cents a minute with a toll-free 800 number. George Kelly of
Scituate has been using Connect'N Save since February and loves it.
``Sure it's a few extra numbers to dial, but I'm the kind of guy
who will drive around the corner to get a lower price,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocate Edgar Dworsky told us about Bigzoo.com, a Web
site offering a prepaid calling card without the card. Bigzoo
charges 3.9 cents a minute for all calls inside the United States
except Alaska and Hawaii, and uses regular land lines instead of
the Internet. Neither we nor Dworsky has tried Bigzoo, but the Web
site is intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Odd &AMP; Ends
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Airline credit rules. A reader discovered, to her dismay, that
a credit voucher for an unused airline ticket was good for only one
year. Her voucher had expired and was now, she learned, useless.
``Can an airline establish such a rule?'' she asked. The answer is
yes. A federal transportation official said airlines are allowed to
establish any time restrictions on unused tickets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(If you have a consumer tip, e-mail mohl(at)globe.com or
wen(at)globe.com, or write Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
