<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF ANYONE KNOWS DIETS, IT'S DEE DEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our all-purpose advice columnist's correspondence is clogged
with messages from anguished readers desperate for diet advice.
</P>
<P>
   Dee Dee knows the source of their panic. Last week, a special
issue of the Journal of the American Medical Association reported
that more Americans are fatter than ever. It urged a national
antiobesity campaign to encourage us to quit pigging out and get
moving, for our health's sake.
</P>
<P>
   Dee Dee, who has been on every diet known to woman _ and to man
too _ feels obliged, if not completely qualified, to respond to her
readers' cries for help.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dear Dee Dee:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I have been following ``Oprah's Cake and Cookies Diet,''
featured in a recent issue of the weekly tabloid Star, but I seem
to be gaining, not losing. Am I doing something wrong?
</P>
<P>
   _ Vexed, Gulfweed, R.I.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed you are. You have fallen for yet another fad diet. Why
not do as Dee Dee does? Eat one doughnut three times a day, drink
nothing but Diet Coke, and go to bed when you feel hungry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dee Dee:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fat-melters. Sugar-busters. High this. Low that. None of these
new diets works for me. After I study all the details about what
I'm supposed to eat and when I'm supposed to eat it, I'm so
confused and frustrated I order in an extra-large pizza with
everything on it (except anchovies) and forget about dieting.
</P>
<P>
   _ Discombobulated, Ducksmere, N.H. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dee Dee agrees that most diet plans are distressingly
complicated. You will probably be amazed to learn that science has
made a connection between how much you eat and how fat you are. So
try eating half what you normally do. Actually, in your case, you
may want to halve that amount yet again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dee Dee:
</P>
<P>
   I have been following the diet outlined in the popular book
``NeanderThin: A Caveman's Guide to Nutrition.'' Recently I learned
Neanderthals have been extinct since the late Pleistocene era,
which I believe was some time ago. Is this what I can expect if I
stay on the diet?
</P>
<P>
   _ Wrought-up, Passepartout, Maine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The caveman diet won't render you extinct, but the daily
exercise regimen, described as the ``equivalent of tracking down
and killing a woolly mammoth,'' could prove wearing over the long
haul. Dee Dee suggests you try an equally insane but less-strenuous
plan, perhaps the new ``blood-type'' diet, or that old standby,
eating naked in front of a mirror.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dee Dee:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Each time I fall off yet another crazy diet, I am tempted to try
a program of sensible eating and exercise. But I never do, because
I cherish the hope that some easy way to lose weight is just around
the corner. Am I fooling myself?
</P>
<P>
   _ Bemused, Full Circle, Conn. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yes and no. Some researchers believe there may be a diet ``magic
bullet'' in our future. But will you _ and will Dee Dee _ live long
enough to see it? Perhaps, if we eat moderately and exercise
faithfully. But is it worth the terrible sacrifice?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dee Dee:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I lost 50 pounds and wrote a book about it, ``The Joy of
Hunger.'' The basic concept involves learning to love feeling
hungry all the time. Unfortunately, I hate feeling hungry and I
have gained back the 50 pounds and then some. My book tour starts
next week. Should I come clean and cancel my appearances?
</P>
<P>
   _ Chagrined, Lobscouse, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why start being honest now? Remember, you're a diet book author.
Dee Dee advises you to wear black and brazen it out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 1402EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5146 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-EDUCATION-RACE-BOS &LR;      11-01 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-RACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOPPLING THE TABOO ON THE ACHIEVEMENT GAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Edmund Gordon recalls appearing at a conference of fellow
educators six years ago and bringing up a fact he took to be
self-evident: Blacks don't do as well as their white peers on a
host of academic measures, even blacks with affluent and
well-educated parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nearly chased out of the room,'' recalls Gordon, a
retired professor at Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   It was hardly the first time anyone had seen the data revealing
a gap between black and white achievement. But to talk about it
publicly was a different matter.
</P>
<P>
   Today, not only are educators everywhere talking and writing
about it, but also minorities themselves are leading the
discussion. To acknowledge the so-called ``achievement gap'' no
longer guarantees being branded a racist.
</P>
<P>
   So why is the taboo lifting?
</P>
<P>
   Partly, it is the frenzy of new high-stakes tests, which are
becoming a graduation requirement in most states. The results,
broken out by race and income, are made public, published in
newspapers, and used by Realtors to determine the value of
neighborhoods. Massachusetts Governor Paul Cellucci is among those
promising to use them to rank schools in a sort of public hall of
shame. When the gap is in cold hard type for the world to see, it
is hard to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the courts' rejection of affirmative action has made
talking about why certain minorities don't achieve at the highest
levels a more pressing issue; top colleges want to see more
minorities doing well early on, so that they don't need racial
preferences when they apply to college.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest difference is the minority voice.
</P>
<P>
   Before the College Board issued a report this month urging a new
focus on raising minority achievement, black parents in 14
comfortable suburbs across the country had created a network to
identify the reasons behind the gap, and come up with promising
strategies to close it.
</P>
<P>
   Their effort is being widely watched because it gets at the most
perplexing question: Why are blacks in integrated, well-off towns
like these _ Shaker Heights, Ohio; Evanston, Ill.; Amherst _ still
so far behind whites in the same schools, when their parents make
the same amount of money, and have the same education? In fact, as
the College Board noted, black children whose parents attended
college score only about as well on nationwide reading and math
tests as white children whose parents didn't finish high school.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Jeff Howard, director of the Lexington-based Efficacy
Institute, publicly urged his fellow minority parents to support
the controversial state MCAS test, calling it their best
opportunity to focus on closing the achievement gap. The quality of
their children's lives, he implored, depends on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We members of the minority community have not wanted to talk
about these issues,'' acknowledges Gordon, who heads a College
Board task force on the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this discussion now is a recognition that if we don't
emphasize these issues, we're really going to be lost. In the 21st
century, the folks who can't reason, can't think critically, are
really going to be left out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to understand the historical discomfort when you
consider the tenor of discussions about race and achievement over
the past three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Abigail Thernstrom, who with her husband, Stephan, documented
the achievement gap in their 1997 book ``America in Black and
White,'' traces the uneasiness to the 1965 report written by Daniel
Patrick Moynihan that identified a vicious cycle of poverty and
fatherlessness in the black family. Moynihan, retiring next year
from the US Senate, was a policy adviser to President Johnson back
then.
</P>
<P>
   As Moynihan himself later recalled to a columnist, ``All hell
broke loose.'' The Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. worried that
opponents of the Civil Rights Act would wield the report as proof
of some sort of innate laziness among blacks. Moynihan himself was
chased out of the administration, denounced for his ``racist
attack.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It took the whole question of black culture off the table for
years,'' says Thernstrom, whose next book, also with her husband,
is about the reasons for the achievement gap. ``You couldn't talk
about the fact that these kids are coming into kindergarten so far
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   The gap came to be more evident in the late 1980s, notes L.
Scott Miller, a College Board researcher, with the flood of new
East Asian immigrants, who tended to score in the highest levels of
achievement. This pushed up the averages, and made it more obvious
that blacks and Hispanics were disproportionately represented in
the lowest levels. In the 1990s, the non-Asian minority achievement
gap actually began to widen.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was the fear that talking about this would somehow
imply that blacks were simply genetically less intelligent _ a view
echoed in ``The Bell Curve,'' the 1994 book by Richard Hernstein
and Charles Murray. While widely discredited, the book highlighted
a basic paradox: By shying away from talking about the achievement
gap, there was no hope of understanding why it existed, leaving the
public free to conclude that Murray and Hernstein were right.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps driven by outrage about the book, many minority
researchers began investigating why blacks and Hispanics don't do
as well as whites. At the same time, says Adelaide Sanford, a
member of the New York State Board of Regents, ``We began to see
the test scores that showed a pattern of low-performing schools. If
we could talk about low-performing schools, rather than
low-performing children, that began to remove some of the
discomfort.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers like those involved in the College Board task force
say they have more to learn. But they have begun to identify some
plausible reasons for the gap: Black and Hispanic students who do
well in school talk about being discouraged by their peers who
accuse them of becoming ``too white''; teachers admit to having
lower expectations for blacks, discouraging them from taking more
challenging courses; certain traditions, like college education or
having books in the home, don't run as deeply among more
newly-affluent black and Hispanic families as they do among whites.
</P>
<P>
   Even in today's more candid atmosphere, raising such
possibilities can still feel risky. Suggesting, say, that blacks or
Hispanics don't have enough books in the house or don't read to
their infants enough risks patronizing, moralizing, blaming. Eugene
Cota-Robles, who cochairs the task force with Gordon, acknowledges
that he has heard some complaints of this in focus groups already.
</P>
<P>
   But discomfort, he says, is no longer a viable option; staying
silent only risks condemning minority children to the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Howard _ whose Efficacy Institute helps try to bridge the gap in
school systems in several cities, including Boston _ says there is
still not nearly enough discussion about the gap among minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go to Winnetka or Newton, you don't have any black
parents in those communities talking about this,'' Howard says.
``The solution is for leadership to make a connection between
proficiency and citizenship for the 21st century. We have to make
clear what the mission is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
