<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA REVISITS LEGACY OF ITS WAR, DOWN TO THE NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ Having shed apartheid five years ago, roughly on
the eve of the centenary of the Boer War, South Africa is now
poised to rewrite a narrative that for most of the century was
dominated by the Afrikaner point of view.
</P>
<P>
   Historical revisions can be important, especially for societies
trying to redefine themselves after decades of exclusion and
oppression. But as the country commemorates the firing of the first
shots of the war 100 years ago this month, a war that laid the
basis for the territorial unity of modern South Africa, the flurry
of today's newfound inclusiveness is making yesterday's tragedies
hard to recognize.
</P>
<P>
   No one seems to know anymore what to call the battle between
British soldiers and Dutch descendants for control of the gold- and
mineral-rich lands at the southern tip of the African continent.
</P>
<P>
   Historians have always called it the Boer War, or the Anglo-Boer
War. But ``Boer'' has fallen into disrepute. The British recently
suggested that it is derogatory (even if Afrikaners still use it to
describe themselves).
</P>
<P>
   Afrikaners have always called the battle The War _ a name that
reflects the Boer view that it was always about them, their
suffering, their oppression, their need for freedom. They were
shaped by it, much as the American South was shaped by the Civil
War. Others now say that ``Boer'' and ``Anglo-Boer'' fail to
acknowledge the role blacks played in the fighting. Hence, new
names have been suggested, such as Anglo-Boer South African War or,
simpler, the South African War.
</P>
<P>
   These latter terms invite new problems, and South African
newspapers are filled these days with fresh disagreements. The
Afrikaner poet and journalist Antjie Krog argued in the weekly Mail
and the Guardian recently that it is time to recognize that blacks
fought and suffered in the conflict, but that under apartheid, the
war became exclusively Afrikaner lore: ``Because the Anglo-Boer
South African War lacked an inclusive narrative, it became an
exclusive myth. The centenary is about finding that comprehensive
story.''
</P>
<P>
   John Matshikiza, a black columnist for the same publication,
took exception. Blacks might have been exploited, forced into
menial servitude for one side or the other, but the war was never
about their emancipation, he said. ``The Boer War, or the
Anglo-Boer War, or the South African War, as it is referred to by
those anxious not to offend minority sensibilities on either side,
was decidedly not a war in which the majority of the population had
a stake. It was a white man's war,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Thabo Mbeki, once a freedom fighter struggling against
Afrikaner domination, now president of ``the rainbow nation,'' ever
a towering intellect, had trouble picking his way through the
battle field of modern inclusiveness. Laying a wreath at a war
memorial last week, he said the Boers ``had courage to take on
Goliath in defense of their freedom. Black allies who stood side by
side with the Boers were ready to lay down their lives for their
freedom and land.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he was identifying, in a common past, the basis for a
common future between foes of a later South African conflict. But
to keep the John Matshikizas of his country happy _ not to mention
one of South Africa's most important trading partners, Mbeki added
of the blacks: ``Others said they could align themselves with the
British to reclaim their freedom and land.''
</P>
<P>
   The British had the final word on the battlefield a century ago,
and seem ready to have it again today. Laying a wreath at a war
memorial last week and offering an apology on behalf of his nation
for the suffering endured by Afrikaner women and children in
British concentration camps during the war _ an apology less
explicit and more implied _ Britain's Prince Edward, the duke of
Kent, said, ``Today we can agree that the war was not just a white
man's war as has been claimed.''
</P>
<P>
   Or at least not just a white man's debate anymore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
