 Monday, Nov. 1, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Mark
Helm at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all
sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   VIEQUES-BOMBING (Washington) _ Puerto Rico Gov. Pedro Rossello,
sticking to his hard-line opposition to using the island of Vieques
for a target range, threatens to break off talks with the Pentagon
unless the Navy agrees to end target practice there permanently.
Rossello also vows to go to court to fight any decision by the Navy
or the White House to resume bombing. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Politics is often more a clash of
egos than ideas. With Patrick Buchanan around, the competition is
stiff, but New Hampshire Sen. Bob Smith wins the prize for
opportunist of the year. He rejected the Republican Party after his
presidential candidacy went nowhere but suddenly reversed himself
when the independent groups didn't want him either and a GOP
chairmanship became available in the Senate. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
</TEXT>
