A5119 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-ELDER-RODEO-HNS &LR;      11-01 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDER-RODEO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENIOR CITIZEN RODEO COMPETITOR SEES NO END TO THE TRAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RYAN KIM  
 c.1999   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ At 71 years old, Bill Cresta is one of your
older addicts around and an unrepentant one at that.
</P>
<P>
   His vice _ if you can call it that _ is riding in rodeos, a
passion that many of his peers can only enjoy as spectators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like sky diving,'' Cresta, of Santa Rosa, Calif.,said.
``It's just an adrenaline high.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Cresta got into the arena and indulged his
addiction at the 1999 Grand National Rodeo Horse and Stock Show at
the Cow Palace. Riding alongside 65-year-old partner Jack
Montgomery, Cresta participated in the rodeo's first senior team
roping competition.
</P>
<P>
   At a combined age of 136, the pair was the oldest of the five
teams in the competition.
</P>
<P>
   For Cresta, who grew up roping in the shadow of the Cow Palace,
rodeo is as much a part of him as the air he breathes.
</P>
<P>
   Both he and Montgomery said they can't imagine giving it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost worse than an addiction or I wouldn't be at it
this many years,'' said Montgomery, who lives in Napa.
</P>
<P>
   The team roping was just one of many events, which was
designated Senior Day. The program also included bareback bronc
riding, barrel races and steer wrestling. None of the participants
in those sports was a senior citizen.
</P>
<P>
   The senior team roping was added for the first time to spice up
the program and play to Saturday's older crowd, Grand National
public relations director Al Guthertz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's to get everyone involved so it's not just the young dudes
out there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cresta, for his part, thinks nothing of mounting a horse and
chasing down calves, saying he has too much fun to get caught up
with his age.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like any athlete, if he stays with a sport, never quits
and stays healthy,'' he said. ``It's no tougher than when you were
young.''
</P>
<P>
   Team roping is an intricate sport requiring the cooperation of
two skilled ropers. The first roper or ``header'' snares the calf's
horns or head, then leads the animal toward his partner. As the
animal kicks and wrestles with the rope, the second roper lassoes
the animal's legs. It doesn't always go off perfectly _ but when it
does, it's pure magic, ropers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you just see those heels fly up, it's just one of the
greatest feelings in the world,'' Dusty O'Farrall, 62, of Santa
Rosa, said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Farrall started roping when he was 6 and only begrudgingly
admits that he might have lost a step or two over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to say I'm as fast as I once was, but every once in a
while these kids will show me I'm not,'' he said with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   During the competition, Montgomery burst out of the shoot and
snared the calf's horns but Cresta missed the legs, much to his
chagrin. O'Farrall and his partner Lee Persico didn't fare any
better. For many of the seniors who showed up Saturday, it was
still a treat to see their peers out there roping cattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just in their prime,'' John Osmers, 81, of Santa
Clara, said. ``It's very encouraging to see they still have the
stamina to go out there.''
</P>
<P>
   After a lifetime of riding and roping, the ropers said they'd
sooner die than hang up their boots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll keep doing this until they have to pry me off the
saddle,'' O'Farrall said. ``If you're a real cowboy, you never
quit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
