u v AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      11-01 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Nov. 2:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EGYPTAIR CRASH &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 2 pages of stories, photos and graphics
on the EgyptAir crash.
</P>
<P>
   AIRCRASH (Undated) _ Ledeall on the EgyptAir crash; What we know
about the investigation. By Robert D. McFadden.
</P>
<P>
   With photos and graphics.
</P>
<P>
   AIRCRASH-VICTIMS (Undated) _ More on those who died.
</P>
<P>
   AIRCRASH-INQUIRY (Undated) _ More on what investigators are
focusing on. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   AIRCRASH-SCENE (Dateline to kum, R.I.) _ As the crash is pieced
together in Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   AIRCRASH-STUDENTS (Baltimore) _ Mourning exchange students at
their school. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, we are considering stories on the search effort and
a feature on the initial recovery of wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Oslo, Norway) _ Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian
leader, and Ehud Barak, Israel's prime minister, in a surprise,
hold a meeting one day ahead of their meeting with President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-DEFENSE (Jerusalem) _ Israel successfully tests the Arrow
anti-missile missile, part of a $2 billion defense system being
developed with the United States. By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-STORM (New Delhi) _ Developments in the wake of the
devastating cyclone that struck India's east coast. By Barry
Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-MUSHARRAF (Islamabad) _ Pakistan's new military leader,
Gen. Pervez Musharraf, holds his first news conference, outlining
his regime's goals and announcing plans to hold a referendum to
seek affirmation of last month's coup. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.S. (New York) _ More on the U.S. meeting with Iraq
oppositions figures. By Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   UKRAINE-ELECT (Kiev) _ Folo on Sunday's presidential election,
and the runnoff in two weeks between between Leonid Kuchma, the
current president, and Petro Symonenko, the Communist Party leader.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ A roundup: The Supreme Court agrees to
take a police search case from Florida. The case raises the
question of whether an anonymous tip to a police department about a
man with a concealed gun gives officers the right to conduct a
search. Other cases. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INTERNET (Washington) _ President Clinton will field
questions from the public over the Internet for an hour and a half
next Monday with an advanced technology that will allow 50,000
people to see and hear him. By Irvin Molotsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SHEPARD-TRIAL (Denver) _ The judge in the Matthew Shepard trial
will decide on Monday whether to allow a defense of ``gay panic,''
in which defense lawyers say that the defendants were repulsed and
had to fight back when a gay man, Matthew Shepard, approached them.
By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   PORTLAND-INTERNET (Portlan, Ore.) _ A federal appeals court
hears arguments on this city's bid to force AT&AMP;T to open its cable
lines to competition among companies offering high-speed Internet
access, bringing out a high-priced, all-star cast of lawyers for
the diverse interests represented. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-NH (Dateline to kum) _ George W. Bush arrives in New
Hampshire Tuesday after watching as his Republican opponents have
slowly chipped away at his once-overwhelming lead. A look at how
much trouble he may be in and what his strategy will be. By Richard
L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-NH-POLL (Undated) _ Analyzing the poll data. By Janet
Elder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM-SUIT (New York) _ A federal judge on Monday ordered New
York City to restore millions of dollars in funding to the Brooklyn
Museum of Art in a dispute over the controversial ``Sensation''
exhibit. The order also bars Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and city
officials from ``taking steps to inflict any punishment,
retaliation, discrimination or sanction'' against the museum. By
David Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTLAND-TECH (Glasgow) _ Scotland is trying to break its
economic dependence on manufacturing and imported technology by
promoting collaboration between university researchers and
corporate partners. Tbe new push hopes to harness Scotland's output
of well-qualified college graduates in a high-technology revolution
of its own, one that may already under way in the corridor of
technology companies between Glasgow and Edinburgh known as Silicon
Glen. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 2 p.m., stocks were mixed. The Dow Jones
industrial average was down 41 points, the S&AMP;P 500 was also down 4
points, but the Nasdaq composite index was up 3 points. The 30-year
bond was priced to yield 6.17 percent. Many European markets were
closed, however, London was up 0.59 percent and Frankfurt up 0.14
percent. In Asia, the Nikkei closed up 0.31 percent and the Hang
Seng ended up 0.49 percent. The dollar was at 104.27 yen and 1.0503
euros. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-SALES (Detroit) _ General Motors and other automakers
report October sales. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   CHASE-CHARGE (New York) _ Chase Manhattan says its
fourth-quarter trading revenue would be reduced by $60 million
because trading profit figures in previous periods had to be
corrected, and an employee involved in the matter was dismissed. By
Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   DAEWOO-FOUNDER (Seoul, South Korea) _ The chairman of Daewoo
Group has offered to step down after 32 years at the helm of the
conglomerate he founded with a $10,000 loan. By Samuel Len.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-EURO (London) _ British business is deeply divided on
joining the single currency, a new opinion poll shows. By Alan
Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENATARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Gail Collins' ``Public Interest'' and Anthony Lewis' ``Abroad at
Home.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET _ A rundown of culture, lifestyle, sports, and
special section stories will move by 3:00 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   AM-PAGE1-NYT-CONSIDER _ A list of stories being considered by
New York Times editors for Page 1 will move at 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AM-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ Stories scheduled for Page 1 will be
listed by 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
