<SLUG> BC-OLDEST-LUTHERAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATION'S OLDEST LUTHERN CONGREGATION CELEBRATES 350TH ANNIVERSARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By THAI JONES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In 1649, a mere 132 years after Martin Luther
nailed his Ninety-five Theses to the chapel door in Wittenberg,
followers of his faith founded the First Lutheran Church of Albany,
the oldest Lutheran congregation in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The church is celebrating its 350th anniversary this year,
culminating in a festival service on Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Over the centuries, services at the First Lutheran have been
delivered in Dutch, High German (as of 1760) and English (since
1808). The name of the town in which the church stands has changed
from Fort Orange, to Beverwyck in 1652, and finally to Albany in
1664. The land beneath it has been part of The Dutch West India
Company, the British Empire and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In 350 years there have been 42 U.S. presidents, two World Wars,
29 popes in Rome, 13 kings and four queens of England. The Yankees
have won 25 World Series, McDonald's has served billions and
billions of burgers, and Halley's Comet has appeared four times. It
is older than any living human, but not beyond the grasp of a
collective human memory.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Mosmen, who is 100 years old and has been a church member
for 49 years, said, ``it's wonderful that the congregation has
stayed together.''
</P>
<P>
   The congregation has outlasted five church buildings over the
centuries. The original church was built just within the stockade
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Florence Christoph, who serves as church archivist along with
her husband, Peter, can claim descent from the brother of an
original member of the 17th-century congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Bredt was a prominent businessman, church elder and fur
trader. Florence moved to Albany in 1965 and has been a member of
the church for 19 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised when I found out,'' she said, referring to the
discovery of her relationship to the well-known Bredt. ``There are
people around, tombstones around, and it makes me feel a part of
the region.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the archives is the church register with long lists of
deaths, births, and marriages. It is a straight-ruled record of
life and love and death for two centuries of Albany residents.
These are the things that the congregation at First Lutheran will
be celebrating Sunday, when their year-long anniversary
commemoration culminates with a celebrity-filled gala on
Reformation Day.
</P>
<P>
   They will celebrate 350 years of history, of dusty books, framed
deeds and charred remnants of former sanctuaries. They will
celebrate the 70 original families and the current 475 members,
including Mosmen, who remembers when almost nobody had a car and
she had to walk to church each Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It is a celebration of the life of a community as well as the
congregation, and it is a tribute to the hardiness of its
inhabitants living and dead that Albany has clung to the cold and
often dreary banks of the Hudson River for so long.
</P>
<P>
   As the first Lutheran himself said, ``Here we stand; we can do
no other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
