<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL CLOUT WINS OUT IN NEW YORK STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALTA, N.Y. _ As pallid morning sunlight flickered through the
naked tree limbs overhead, Mark Newton moved into the creek,
sinking into swiftly running water nearly to his knees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you coming?` he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The boots I'd worn came up only to the tops of my ankles. In
Autumn, that water was sure to be cold. On the other hand, what the
hell? I went lurching in after him.
</P>
<P>
   We splashed through the icy water for several hundred yards
along the meandering creekbed, following its gentle curves right
and left through the trees as fallen leaves swirled in the wake we
left. Then, maybe a hundred yards from the lake, the creek's sandy
bottom rose up finally to form a dyke.
</P>
<P>
   That was where the stream died while its water spilled in all
directions. All directions, that is, except the one God had
intended. That was into Round Lake _ to nourish the still water and
serve as crucial breeding grounds for fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's it,` Mark Newton said. ``That's where it ends now. And
I can't get the state to do a thing about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Newton owns a pleasant old farmhouse atop a hill on the
north side of Round Lake in this northern Albany suburb. He also
owns 45 or so other acres behind the hill that slope down to the
lakeshore. A few years ago, he bought the place from Don Corp, now
his next-door neighbor, who was raised on that farm and lived there
until he was 70.
</P>
<P>
   Don Corp calls the stream Maltaville Crick. He's not sure if
that's the official name. But he has known that narrow waterway for
seven decades and more. He's as horrified as his new young
neighbor, Mark Newton, at what has happened to it.
</P>
<P>
   That, apparently, is this: A mile or two upstream, a builder
began to erect nice houses on a hill overlooking the stream. Sand
from that construction site washed down into the water. Over time,
the sand crawled down the creek until it formed that dyke.
</P>
<P>
   And the water? It just keeps flowing.
</P>
<P>
   Now, much of the land Mark Newton bought from Don Corp is under
water. Come next spring, when the snow melts, it's likely that most
of Mark Newton's place _ the sprawling farm he bought from Don Corp
and uses to raise a few cashmere goats to supplement what he earns
from his job in Albany _ will become part of Round Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Newton doesn't own that stream. Its proprietor is the State
of New York. Somebody with a backhoe and a dump truck could make
Maltaville Crick flow freely again. But if Mark Newton brings in
somebody to do that, he risks arrest. And the State of New York
exhibits no eagerness to fix this.
</P>
<P>
   I spoke to the regional director of the State Department of
Environmental Conservation (DEC). He described this as an
``enforcement issue'' and was reluctant to say more.
</P>
<P>
   I suggested that he warn department headquarters that I would be
calling and tell them what he seemed so wary of explaining to me.
When I called, they'd heard from the regional director and said
that this would be looked into.
</P>
<P>
   That was weeks ago. I've heard from nobody from DEC and neither
has Mark Newton. He now has a well that spews sand into his sinks,
and his land is vanishing, and nobody will even talk to him about
it.
</P>
<P>
   I called somebody else I know in that department. Why won't the
DEC brass fix this, I asked?
</P>
<P>
   Simple, I was told. This Mark Newton? This guy whose property is
becoming lake bottom before his very eyes?
</P>
<P>
   He's nobody important enough for the State of New York to fret
about.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
