<SLUG> BC-SUSAN-SARANDON-IN-ANYWHERE-BUT-HERE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANYWHERE BUT DOWN: SUSAN SARANDON DOESN'T LET ICON STATUS GET IN
HER WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Susan Sarandon with Natalie Portman in a
scene from ``Anywhere But Here.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    If the fans at a recent midnight showing of ``The Rocky Horror
Picture Show'' in New York had turned around to see who was sitting
behind them, they might have forgotten all about Dr. Frank N.
Furter and friends.
 &HT;    Blending into the audience were Susan Sarandon, star of the 1975
cult classic, and Natalie Portman, star of 1999's biggest
box-office smash, ``Star Wars: The Phantom Menace.'' With them,
just as a bonus, were a star of the current hit ``American Beauty''
and one of today's leading young male actors.
 &HT;    Sarandon, who had come so Portman could see the film for the
first time in the right setting, was disappointed in what she saw.
 &HT;    ``I took Nat, Thora Birch, my daughter and Lukas Haas,'' the
actress says. ``I hadn't seen it since I took Molly Ringwald when
she was 11.
 &HT;    ``The audience has diminished,'' she reports. ``It was everyone
just shouting obscenities for two hours, and you couldn't
understand what they were saying. There used to be a bit of
organization.
 &HT;    ``I sound like an old lady,'' she admits with a laugh, ``but
there was total anarchy. Everybody was trying to put new lines
in.''
 &HT;    Portman wasn't even born when Sarandon appeared in ``Rocky
Horror,'' and Ringwald is now 31. Even Sarandon's longtime beau,
Tim Robbins, was only 17 when ``Rocky Horror'' hit the scene.
 &HT;    Clearly, Sarandon has been around a long time. Many a young
actor looks up to her, wants to work with her, cites her as a hero.
 &HT;    ``It's great,'' Sarandon says during a conversation at New
York's Rihga Royal Hotel. As usual, she looks great _ far younger
than her 53 years _ and doesn't hesitate to speak her mind about
any topic.
 &HT;    ``I didn't have very many heroes,'' she says. ``I'm glad if I'm
helping somebody think the possibilities are bigger. I'm not quite
sure if it's me as much as some of the roles I've played. I don't
get it, but I don't mind it.
 &HT;    ``It's wonderful if you can encourage people to tell stories
they feel passionate about.''
 &HT;    When Sarandon looks back, she sees an awful lot _ children, a
divorce, an Oscar, political activism and, of course, her
long-running union with Robbins. Not to mention films beginning
with ``Joe'' (1970) and including hits as diverse as ``Rocky
Horror,'' ``Pretty Baby'' (1978), ``Atlantic City'' (1980), ``The
Witches of Eastwick'' (1987), ``Bull Durham'' (1988), ``Thelma and
Louise'' (1991), her Oscar-winning role in ``Dead Man Walking''
(1995) and ``Stepmom'' (1998).
 &HT;    Unlike many performers, Sarandon admits that she often watches
her old films.
 &HT;    ``It's not scary,'' she says. ``In some ways it's bittersweet. I
see people who are gone. I have no regrets, so I don't mind
watching anything at all. And I look at my work and I think, `Wow,
I packed a lot in these years.'
 &HT;    ``In that sense, it is really good.''
 &HT;    Her current film, ``Anywhere But Here,'' opens Nov. 12. Based on
the novel by Mona Simpson and directed by Wayne Wang, the film
explores the volatile relationship between 14-year-old Ann August
(Portman) and her loving-but-eccentric mother, Adele (Sarandon).
 &HT;    Adele can't keep a job or a man, but relocates from a lazy
Wisconsin town to Beverly Hills, determined to start anew and chase
her dreams afresh.
 &HT;    ``When you start edging toward this icon thing that everybody
puts you in, you don't want to lose your sense of humor,'' Sarandon
says. ``I was really looking forward to wearing eyeliner and doing
something fun.
 &HT;    ``I also thought that the story was about something that people
could relate to,'' she adds, ``that there was an element of truth
there, not just for mothers and daughters, but for anyone trying to
raise a child and everybody who's had a mother.
 &HT;    ``Letting go, learning to love somebody and letting them be who
they are is something that's tough not just as a mother, but as a
person,'' the actress says. ``It gave me a chance to practice all
the things not to do with my teen-age daughter.''
 &HT;    Add Sarandon to the list of people impressed with Portman, who
has already been hailed as a rising young star and, who knows,
perhaps the next Susan Sarandon.
 &HT;    ``She's always been incredibly bright,'' Sarandon says. ``She
comes from a very interesting background. She's a person with a
natural grace that doesn't seem like today _ that's very much just
who she is.''
 &HT;    In years to come Portman may have a screen career as prolific as
Sarandon's, but she'll be hard-pressed to match the older actress'
phenomenal roster of extracurricular activities.
 &HT;    Sarandon has been arrested several times while taking part in
protests on behalf of various political causes. She even incurred
the wrath of Oscar when, during an Academy Awards telecast, she
unexpectedly interrupted the show-biz preening for a brief,
impassioned plea on behalf of the struggling people of Haiti.
 &HT;    She didn't apologize for it, either. As a celebrity with access
to the world media, Sarandon considers it her responsibility to
speak out for those who might not otherwise have a voice.
 &HT;    ``The turning point came for me years ago, for the ERA,'' she
recalls, ``when I was on the steps of a library in front of this
bank of microphones.
 &HT;    ``I didn't want to go up,'' the actress admits. ``Bella Abzug
had just spoken, and she was amazing. Marlo Thomas just kept
pushing me, saying `You have to. That's the only way this will get
on the news. It doesn't matter what you say. Just get up there.'
 &HT;    ``And she was absolutely right,'' Sarandon says. ``When I have
to, I just speak from the heart. But I'm not someone who's
comfortable with rhetoric _ I'm not comfortable in the public eye.
 &HT;    ``I end up having to do it, but it's hard.''
 &HT;    Another unconventional aspect of Sarandon's life is her
relationship with Robbins, 12 years her junior. The two met in 1988
on the set of ``Bull Durham'' (1989), and have been together ever
since. They have two children together, but have never married.
 &HT;    ``I like the idea of remembering to tell someone you love them
and not taking them for granted,'' Sarandon says. ``In my mind,
this works.
 &HT;    ``Were it to mean something to my children, I'd do it,'' she
says. ``It's not that big a deal. We've been together so long now,
we take each other for granted anyway.
 &HT;    ``No, that's not true,'' she adds with a laugh.
 &HT;    ``So this is my feeble attempt at trying to keep my identity and
be separate,'' Sarandon concludes. ``As my daughter said when she
was little, `Marriage, what an embarrassing word.' I thought, `What
does that mean, exactly?'
 &HT;    ``But mostly it is just a way of saying that, every day, I
choose to be with this person.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
