<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRIS-ODONNELL-IN-THE-BACHELOR-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BACHELOR' AND MARRIED MAN: CHRIS O'DONNELL ON LIFE, LOVE, RINGS
AND THINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Chris O'Donnell in a scene from ``The
Bachelor.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    He's not a bachelor _ he just plays one in the movies.
 &HT;    Chris O'Donnell's bachelor days ended three years ago in a small
apartment in Washington, where he finally got up the nerve to
propose marriage.
 &HT;    ``Well, I picked up my future wife Caroline from school, where
she was teaching,'' he recalls. ``We walked into her apartment and
she said, `Let's go for a run.' I said, `Nah, let's go sit on the
couch.'''
 &HT;    O'Donnell nervously fumbled through a catalog on the coffee
table _ coincidentally, a jewelry catalog with one particular
engagement ring circled. It was sort of ugly, he told her.
 &HT;    ``She said, `Are you nuts? That's a gorgeous ring,''' he
recalls. ``I said, `Well, I like this one better,' and I pulled out
her ring.''
 &HT;    O'Donnell smiles at the memory. Tired and jet-lagged, he
nonetheless looks muscular and sleek in khaki pants and a beige
silk shirt, only the dark circles under his eyes revealing that he
only recently arrived from New Zealand, where he's filming
``Vertical Limit,'' to do interviews for his new film, ``The
Bachelor.''
 &HT;    ``We haven't been home for months,'' he says, shaking his head
wearily, ``so during my 24 hours in Los Angeles before going back
to New Zealand, I have to go check on the contractors. They've been
finishing our bathroom for six months.''
 &HT;    Opening Nov. 5, ``The Bachelor'' casts O'Donnell as a young heir
who finds himself forced to get married within 24 hours or lose a
$100 million inheritance. A botched proposal to his girlfriend
(Renee Zellweger) leads to a frantic search for a wife, culminating
in a personal ad which has him fleeing from a throng of eager
would-be brides.
 &HT;    ``People have asked me if this movie is about sexual politics,''
says O'Donnell, who also served as executive producer on the film.
``What does it say about women who will do anything to get married,
including chasing me down the street in one scene in wedding
dresses?
 &HT;    ``I don't think we're making any statement,'' he says. ``It's
just a fun, wacky comedy about love.''
 &HT;    It was O'Donnell's wife who suggested Zellweger _ best known for
``Jerry Maguire'' (1996) _ to play O'Donnell's true love. ``Jerry
Maguire'' is her favorite movie, the actor says. But just as much
fun was lining up the parade of famous faces who have cameo
appearances as would-be brides.
 &HT;    Among them are actress/model Brooke Shields and singer Mariah
Carey, playing respectively a chain-smoking snob and an Italian
opera singer.
 &HT;    ``It's funny,'' O'Donnell says, ``because part of my education
as an executive producer meant that agents were calling me
suggesting these women. I've never been on the other end, where I
could say, `Well, send me a tape of her work.'''
 &HT;    The various famous faces add a lot to the film, he says, even if
their appearances are brief.
 &HT;    ``I thought it would be nice to have some familiar faces to cast
as the girlfriends,'' he says. ``And it was great because, even
though these women were big stars, there were no problems.
 &HT;    ``Look at Brooke, who used to do an anti-smoking campaign _ in
the film, she had to smoke,'' he says. ``This poor girl would go
and puke between scenes, but she was a trouper. She was just
no-attitude.''
 &HT;    O'Donnell himself has always been noted for his laid-back
attitude, ever since his first movie audition. As a Chicago
teen-ager, he answered an open casting call for the role of Jessica
Lange's son in ``Men Don't Leave'' (1990).
 &HT;    ``At the audition, I told them there was one problem: I didn't
know who Jessica Lange was,'' O'Donnell recalls. ``I also told them
that the movie could not interfere with my practice for the
high-school crew team.
 &HT;    ``The casting director's mouth flew open,'' he says, laughing.
``You could hear her thinking, `Who is this kid?'''
 &HT;    As it turns out, that kid would grow into the handsome,
clean-cut star of some of the 1990s' most popular films, including
``Scent of a Woman'' (1992), ``School Ties'' (1992) and ``Circle of
Friends'' (1995). But he got his first taste of real superstardom
when he was cast as Robin, first in ``Batman Forever'' (1995) and
again in ``Batman and Robin'' (1997).
 &HT;    ``It still amazes me to know I'm known globally,'' he says. ``I
was in the airport in Indonesia, and I was recognized. I thought I
was on the other side of the world, and it's like `Ro-binnn!
Ro-binnn!'''
 &HT;    He was en route to New Zealand, where he's currently filming
``Vertical Limit,'' a mountain-climbing movie due out in summer
2000.
 &HT;    To prepare for the strenuous role, O'Donnell and his very
pregnant wife left their home in Chicago and landed in New Zealand
on the Fourth of July. The actor immediately began a rigorous,
eight-week training program with professional climbers.
 &HT;    ``It is very dangerous work,'' he says. ``You're climbing up
400-foot, sheer mountain walls. We climb up frozen waterfalls. Your
hands are holding onto ice picks and your feet are dug into the
side of a mountain.
 &HT;    ``Storms blow up out of nowhere,'' he adds. ``Two days ago I was
hunkered down on the mountain with rain pouring on me. I was just
holding on.
 &HT;    ``It's very easy to fall,'' O'Donnell says, ``and, even though I
have a safety rope, it still stops your heart when you tumble 10 or
15 feet. You're just waiting for the rope to break your fall. It's
very hairy.''
 &HT;    Especially if you've got a wife who's due to give birth at any
moment.
 &HT;    ``I was so worried that I'd be on the side of the mountain and
my cell phone would ring,'' O'Donnell says with a grimace. ``I
could imagine her saying, `It's time! Get down here!'
 &HT;    ``My nightmare was that I couldn't get to her.''
 &HT;    Finally, the birth was induced in August. After a five-hour trek
to the nearest hospital that had a good neonatal unit, O'Donnell
was indeed present for the birth of his first child, Lily.
 &HT;    ``It was a miracle,'' he says, groping for words. ``It was just
so overwhelming. I still can't believe it.''
 &HT;    Not that he has to rely on his memory of the event, of course.
 &HT;    ``It was so funny,'' the actor admits, laughing. ``The doctor
thought I was nuts _ he even said, `I've never seen so many cameras
in my life.' I had the video camera going, I had the digital
camera.
 &HT;    ``The minute after she was born,'' he adds, ``I downloaded her
picture for my folks back home and E-mailed them the first photo of
their granddaughter.''
 &HT;    Those bachelor days seem a long time ago now, O'Donnell adds.
 &HT;    ``I honestly thought the biggest change in my life was getting
married, but that wasn't the half of it,'' he says. ``Having a kid
really changes all your priorities. This little girl is the focus
of my life.
 &HT;    ``I was so sad to leave her yesterday.''
 &HT;    But don't cry, Lily _ jet-lagged or not, O'Donnell is on his way
home.
 &HT;    ``I'm on the first flight to New Zealand after this is over,''
he says with a tired-but-happy smile. ``In about 24 hours, I'll be
on diaper duty.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Bachelor,'' consult the
