<HEADER>
A5179 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-THE-WEST-WING-STARBEA     11-01 1364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-WEST-WING-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING DRAMA IN THE OVAL OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Martin Sheen with Richard Schiff and
John Spencer in a scene from ``The West Wing.'') 
 By DAVID KRONKE  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 Not available in Canada until Nov. 15, 1999. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talk about science fiction.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the United States in NBC's new hit series ``The
West Wing'' is a principled man who invariably opts for the right
decision over the politically prudent one. He doesn't care about
politics, only about helping his fellow Americans, and has
surrounded himself with a staff of sharp, canny professionals more
attuned to getting the job done than to brown-nosing the boss.
</P>
<P>
   What planet does this show take place on, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Sorkin, the 38-year-old playwright/screenwriter who
created ``The West Wing'' and, before it, the acclaimed ``Sports
Night,'' is no stranger to the world of politics, having previously
scripted the films ``A Few Good Men'' (1992) and ``The American
President'' (1996).
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain amount of wish-fulfillment here,'' he
admits. ``Maybe it'll be exciting to look at the White House the
way we wish it was a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Bringing life to Sorkin's stirring, epigrammatic dialogue _
``When people talk in things that I write,'' he admits, ``they tend
to be hyper-communicative, which is to say they can't shut up'' _
is a sterling cast drawn mainly from feature films.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Sheen plays President Josiah Bartlet, with Rob Lowe as
his sardonic, womanizing deputy communications director. Richard
Schiff as the communications director, Allison Janney as Bartlet's
press secretary and John Spencer as his chief of staff have a wide
range of film credits, as do Tim Matheson as the vice president,
Stockard Channing as the first lady and Timothy Busfield as a
scrappy reporter covering the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a tough time slot opposite ABC's ``The Drew Carey
Show,'' ``The West Wing'' made a splashy October debut and drew
respectable ratings from day one _ not bad for a show whose
production was delayed for a year because of network qualms over
the recent White House sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that the events of the last two years in
the Clinton White House have been dismaying, to say the least,''
Sorkin admits. ``You're setting yourself up for the snicker factor
anytime you mention the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Sheen says, he was fascinated by the show from the
moment he read Sorkin's script for the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read it,'' the actor recalls, ``and said, `I'm not nuts
about doing a TV series. I've never done one. I have no interest in
doing one.
</P>
<P>
   ```But I will do this as long as you write every script that I'm
involved in.'''
</P>
<P>
   And, indeed, so far the workaholic Sorkin, who had a major hand
in every ``Sports Night'' episode last season, has written every
script. Part of his motivation, no doubt, is the intriguing
character of Bartlet _ originally scheduled to appear only once
every three or four episodes, but soon upgraded to regular status.
</P>
<P>
   ``He backed into the presidency,'' Sheen says, ``and, not having
a mandate and not having a fully coordinated agenda, he was freed
to form an administration that would be responsible for all the
people in the best possible sense.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been such a president not so long ago, Schiff adds _
that of Harry Truman, from 1945 to 1952.
</P>
<P>
   ``My favorite presidency in American history is Truman's,
because he was a reluctant servant,'' Schiff says. ``He found
himself in the office after Roosevelt died and he really understood
how to respect what the office was about. He understood the gravity
and profundity of the decisions that were made there, by the office
_ the man was secondary. I've always respected that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheen hastens to add that the show isn't about any real
administration, past, present or future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be clear about that,'' he says. ``Otherwise we're
not going to be free to have a public debate on the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to confront issues on a personal level, and if
you're not interested in going on this battleground with us, don't
join the army,'' Sheen declares, his voice rising. ``Get out now.
Because we're gonna fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Which sounds militant, but Sorkin _ a self-professed liberal _
insists that the show isn't about the personal politics of himself,
Sheen or anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your enjoyment of the show really isn't going to depend upon
whether you agree with that episode or character politically,'' the
writer/producer says. ``Issues are going to be on the show, but
really only as fodder for drama _ the show is going to be all over
the map. This president is extremely unpredictable, politically.
</P>
<P>
   ``The West Wing' isn't meant to be `good for you,''' he adds.
``We're not telling anyone to eat their vegetables. It's going to
be for the sake of drama, not for the sake of winning your vote
somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Lowe is struck by the show's realism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like a real world,'' he says. ``I come home and watch
`Crossfire' and go, `I'll have to talk to them about that the next
day.' You really get lulled into the fact that you're actually
working there.''
</P>
<P>
   In pursuit of that realism, Janney has befriended Dede Myers,
who was the real-life White House press secretary in the early
years of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me that the hierarchy at the White House is totally
personality-driven, not according to your job role,'' Janney says.
``Who gets to be in on meetings doesn't depend on your job _ your
title doesn't entitle you to be somewhere _ but if you get along
with someone, then you get invited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Wow _ it's just like high school!'''
</P>
<P>
   The only real hazard the show faces, many observers feel, is the
pressure on Sorkin to continue pumping out 45 minutes of new,
top-quality material every week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the writing, there's nothing going on,'' Schiff says.
``When writing for television, you're supposed to resolve the
conflict in the 39th minute, and a lot of times easy choices are
made because of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that happens on this show,'' he says, ``it'll be a tragedy.
Because the potential is for us to reach a level of work which
would be so rare.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheen is confident that ``The West Wing'' won't succumb to the
siren calls of standard television writing or the dictates of
network programmers and publicity flacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there will be any assassination attempts,
impeachment attempts or any kind of hanky-panky in the Oval
Office,'' Sheen adds. ``I would be an outspoken critic of such a
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is one aspect of network politics which will
unavoidably affect the world of President Bartlet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get picked up for a fourth year, I will have been
re-elected,'' Sheen says. ``If we get cancelled in the fifth or
sixth year, I've been impeached.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (David Kronke is a Los Angeles-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The West Wing,'' consult the
NBC Website at www.nbc.com. And don't forget to visit The New York
Times Syndicate Website at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
