w a BC-PLAYWRIGHT-NEIL-SIMON     11-01 1433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLAYWRIGHT-NEIL-SIMON-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT-SO-SIMPLE SIMON: THE COMPLICATED TRUTHS ABOUT AMERICA'S MOST
POPULAR PLAYWRIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of playwright Neil Simon.) 
 By MICHAEL J. BANDLER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    There's a theater in the heart of New York's theater district
that's named after playwright Neil Simon, but it hasn't hosted one
of his own plays in years.
 &HT;    That might change next year. His latest play, ``The Dinner
Party,'' is being launched in Los Angeles in December 1999, and
could be a Broadway transfer in 2000.
 &HT;    If it isn't, though, Simon won't be too upset.
 &HT;    ``In the time I have left as a writer _ it could be a few years,
it could be more years than I imagine _ all I want to do is write
new and original plays, and not worry about where it goes from
there,'' he says during an interview at his New York office.
 &HT;    He's still one of the busiest men in show business, of course,
with a memoir recently published and another new play in the works
_ plus his recent marriage to his fourth wife, actress Elaine
Joyce.
 &HT;    One topic not on the mind of this elder statesman of the
American theater _ so old-fashioned that he writes all his books,
plays and screenplays first on a pad and then on a typewriter, but
never on a computer _ is age, even though he's now 72.
 &HT;    ``Seventy's all right if you accept it,'' he says breezily. ``I
have to _ I don't have a choice.''
 &HT;    His first volume of memoirs, ``Rewrites'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
1996), took him from childhood to the death of his first wife, Joan
Baim. ``The Play Goes On'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, 1999) brings the
story up to the present.
 &HT;    It wasn't easy for this famously self-effacing, private man to
write a memoir. He did so, he says, because he wanted to let people
know some things about himself and because he wanted to cut through
the anecdotes to find some truths about himself that even he didn't
know when he began.
 &HT;    ``It's like sitting down and writing a confession to the police,
or to the chief of your religion,'' he says. ``But it's not a
confession of the good and bad things I did _ I'm not trying to
empty my baggage and lay it at the feet of the people who read this
book.''
 &HT;    He freely admits to having left out a lot of material which he
considered too private to discuss. What's left, he says, is in
large part the story of a writer, a look at the creative process
itself.
 &HT;    ``Most people can't relate to that,'' he says. ``People at my
tennis club, for example, have no concept. They say, `You sit
alone?'
 &HT;    ``There's hardly a job in the world like that,'' the playwright
says. ``Almost everything includes other people. This one doesn't
include them until I'm finished writing _ yet I've never had
trouble with coming up to the office, because I never felt alone
here.''
 &HT;    In the process of writing the memoir, he says, he came to terms
with his own identity in a way he hadn't before.
 &HT;    ``For a long time, I didn't even see myself as Neil Simon,'' he
says. ``I had no idea who Neil Simon was. I knew who I was, but I
wasn't necessarily the Neil Simon people wrote wonderful and
not-so-wonderful things about, that public figure. I don't usually
see that _ I see myself walking along the street, almost invisible.
 &HT;    ``So it took some doing to come to terms, to make those two
people one, which I have now,'' he says. ``I accept being that
other person. We've made friends.''
 &HT;    Simon's book offers insights into the creation of his plays, and
shows unmistakable pride in discussing his two daughters, Nancy and
Ellen, accomplished writers in their rights. And he somewhat
gingerly explores the same traumatic events which for years have
fueled his plays _ the death from cancer of his first wife, and the
three failed marriages that followed.
 &HT;    ``There's nothing in the book that I'm ashamed of or afraid to
tell,'' Simon says. ``The places where I don't want to go, I don't.
I'm not going to tell what goes on in the rooms where the door
should never be opened.
 &HT;    ``But if I do it,'' he says, ``it can open others up to doing
it. When you're in pain, if you go back and search through it all,
where it came from, maybe you'll find the beginning of that pain
and help relieve some of it.''
 &HT;    Some have marveled at Simon's propensity for turning his private
turmoil into the stuff of comedies, but he doesn't find it so
surprising.
 &HT;    ``All my plays are based on stress, which is basically
conflict,'' he says. ``That's what I look for in every play stress and conflict that characters have to go through, and the
journey that the audience takes with them.
 &HT;    ``The great thing about the writing is that it has supported me
emotionally all through the bad times and the good times,'' he
adds. ``It never abandons me. It never walks out.''
 &HT;    Audiences and critics alike have often assumed that Simon's
style, with its easygoing humor and deft one-liners, must come
easily. Actually, the playwright says, that isn't usually the case.
 &HT;    ``No, it hasn't been facile,'' he says. ``I really work hard.
Some days the pages flow, and other days you just look at them.
When you stop to think that I've just finished the seventh draft of
`The Dinner Party,' which has taken nine months, you realize that
pages don't fly all the time.
 &HT;    ``They may fly out of the typewriter, but they can fly right
into the wastebasket!''
 &HT;    Simon's other theatrical project of the season is the
one-act-play collection ``Hotel Suite,'' which will open in
Philadelphia next spring. Its four one-acters are drawn from his
three hotel-based anthologies, ``Plaza Suite'' (1968), ``California
Suite'' (1976) and ``London Suite'' (1995).
 &HT;    ``It's a crystallization of the best of them,'' he says, ``and
tied together much better, because there's no way I could have
written `Hotel Suite' this way without going through the other
three plays.''
 &HT;    Recently Simon has also been enjoying his fifth marriage _ after
his first wife's death, he was married to actresses Marsha Mason
and, twice, Diane Lander. He and Joyce first met back in the 1970s,
but became reacquainted earlier this year, after Simon's second
divorce from Lander.
 &HT;    ``I'm not taking a chance,'' the playwright says. ``This is the
last marriage _ I'm so sure about her.''
 &HT;    Settled down again, an hour or so away from his daughters and
their families, Simon says that what he most wants out of life now
is peace of mind _ which isn't to say that retirement lies anywhere
in his foreseeable future. The act of putting words on paper, of
creating characters and giving them life, is still intensely
rewarding to him, he says.
 &HT;    ``It's not merely words, but the means of expression, going to
someplace that's richer and more meaningful,'' he says. ``And yet I
always need the humor, because I find that in my life all the time
_ when things are bleakest I'll find some humorous way to look at
them, not to avoid the pain, but just to see the absurdity of life.
 &HT;    ``I'm at that age when you start saying, `OK, it's not going to
go on forever,''' the playwright says. ``But I'm not ready to
settle down and stop writing. I have enough writers and therapists
who've said, `Never stop writing _ it's going to keep you alive and
keep a lot of other people happy.'''
 c.1999 Michael J. Bandler  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Michael J. Bandler is a Silver Spring, Md.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Play Goes On,'' consult
the Simon and Schuster Website at www.simonandschuster.com. And
don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
