<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5331 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV07-NY     11-01 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE OUTER LIMITS OF THE ENVELOPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Nov. 7)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics. Double parentheses
should be set as brackets.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Allergies, I am told, don't flare up the first time you come
in contact with the offending agent,'' writes Tom Wolfe, author of
the novels ``Bonfire of the Vanities'' and ``A Man in Full.'' ``The
allergens build up gradually over time until one day you can't take
it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a writer's way of beginning a letter. None of this
right-to-the-point e-mail stuff, or apologies for belatedness, or
arch ``anent: whatever.'' On the contrary, a letter that begins
with an apt metaphor or an original turn of phrase causes the
recipient to sit back and prepare to enjoy the vanishing art of
correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   ``That happened to me when it came to the expression  &UR; pushing
the envelope &LR; ,'' Wolfe continued, enclosing a clipping from The New
York Times with the headline `` &UR; Pushing the Bleeping Envelope &LR; .''
The article quoted Doug Herzog, president of the Fox Entertainment
Group, about the sex talk and profanity in one of his television
series: ``Without question, it  &UR; pushes the envelope &LR; .'' The
reporter, Bernard Weinraub, then observed, ``Mr. Herzog is hardly
alone in  &UR; pushing the envelope &LR; .'' This was fairly heavy pushing.
</P>
<P>
   `` &UR; Pushing an envelope &LR;  isn't very hard,'' notes the novelist.
``It's one of the easiest things in the world and one of the most
pointless. The actual expression, which comes from flight test, is
` &UR; pushing the outside of the envelope &LR; .'''
</P>
<P>
   There is a world of metaphoric difference between shoving a
piece of stationery around and pushing the outside of a container
from the inside. ``Each type of aircraft has a certain envelope
within which it can operate safely,'' writes Wolfe. ``It can dive
safely only up to such-and-such a slope or turn safely only beyond
such-and-such a radius. Trying to stretch those limits is  &UR; pushing
the outside of the envelope &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   In mathematics, the outer boundary of a family of curves has
been known since the mid-19th century as the  &UR; envelope &LR; .
Aeronautical engineers later applied the word to the limits of
aircraft operation, from  &UR; gust envelopes &LR;  to  &UR; maneuver envelopes &LR; 
to  &UR; flight envelopes &LR; . When a test pilot presses against those
outer limits, he  &UR; pushes the outside of the envelope &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe helped introduce the metaphor and certainly popularized
the phrase in ``The Right Stuff,'' his 1979 book about astronauts.
``Perhaps that's why the allergens finally got to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Clymer's Kennedy
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy clan's reverence for evocative language has long
ennobled political speech. My New York Times colleague Adam Clymer,
in the new ``Edward M. Kennedy: A Biography'' (Morrow, $27.50),
shows how the youngest of the Kennedy brothers has used the
family's affinity for the sea in political metaphor: In his 1978
speech challenging Jimmy Carter on health insurance, Kennedy said,
``Sometimes a party must sail against the wind.'' Two years later,
his challenge to Carter's renomination defeated, he boasted, ``We
have kept the rudder true.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator compiled a privately printed book, ``Words Jack
Loved,'' Clymer recounts, which shows the origins of some familiar
themes and lines in President Kennedy's speeches.
</P>
<P>
   This collection included a rhyme attributed to soldiers in the
Irish brigade in the Civil War's Battle of Fredericksburg: ``War
battered dogs are we/Gnawing a naked bone/Fighters in every war and
clime/For every cause but our own.'' And this biblical passage from
Luke 12:48: ``For unto whomsoever much is given, of him much shall
be required; and to whom men have committed much, of him they will
ask the more.''
</P>
<P>
   Poetic allusions pervade Kennedy prose to this day. In his
eulogy to JFK Jr., Edward Kennedy sorrowed that the young man did
not ``live to comb gray hair,'' from William Butler Yeats' 1919
poem ``In Memory of Major Robert Gregory'': ``What made us dream
that he could comb gray hair?''
</P>
<P>
   I'd add that though Ted Kennedy has few rivals in the delivery
of a prepared address, his extemporaneous oratory sometimes falls
short. In last month's Senate debate on the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty, he rose to urge continued funds for the Nuclear Stockpile
Stewardship Program, which aims to keep our weapons in usable
condition without testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A key element of our adherence to the treaty ... is the
Stockpile  &UR; Stewardess &LR;  Program,'' Kennedy said. Aides winced at the
slip of the lip, but he did it again in his ringing voice. As Al
Kamen of The Washington Post cruelly noted, he concluded that
``with the Stockpile  &UR; Stewardess &LR;  Program, we will still be able to
maintain a powerful nuclear deterrent.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a fine orator can goof. (The preferred term is  &UR; flight
attendant &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   Editor Gore
</P>
<P>
   To show that Al Gore personally participated in the writing of a
TV spot blasting the Senate rejection of the nuclear test ban, his
campaign made available the script with his handwritten editing.
Let's see how he did:
</P>
<P>
   A line in the draft read, ``I want to ensure ((the drafter meant
 &UR; assure &LR; )) our nation and the entire world that this vote does not
speak for the majority of the American people.'' Gore changed that
to ``I believe in my heart that this vote does not speak for the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Another line went, ``Campaigns should be about the important
issues, and there's none more important than stopping the spread of
nuclear weapons.'' Gore's fix: ``I believe campaigns should be
about the future, and there is no more important challenge than
stopping the spread of nuclear weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Note (1) the insertion of the self with  &UR; I believe &LR; ; (2) the
substitution of  &UR; the future &LR;  for the dull  &UR; the important issues &LR; ;
(3) the replacement of the ungrammatical  &UR; there's none more
important &LR;  with  &UR; there is no more important challenge &LR; , a correct
use of the singular that avoids repeating  &UR; important &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The weak draft: ``I will ask the American people for a clear
mandate. And if elected president, my first act will be to resubmit
the test ban treaty.'' The vice president's handwritten redraft
rolls along with greater strength: ``I ask for your support and
your mandate if elected President to send this treaty back to the
Senate with your demand that they ratify it.''  &UR; Demand &LR;  beats
 &UR; resubmit &LR;  any day, and by making it  &UR; your &LR;  demand, rather than his
own, he avoided arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   A careful TV-spot writer would not use the plural  &UR; they &LR;  with
the singular  &UR; Senate &LR; , but that's nitpicking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
