<HEADER>
A5341 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     11-01 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEING PAST OUR OWN PAIN TO HELP OTHERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bea Salazar was down on her luck, suffering emotionally and
physically from the pain of a broken marriage and a workplace
injury that rendered her unable to work and provide for her five
children.
</P>
<P>
   Her suffering had almost consumed her. Then one day, she
happened upon a little boy looking for lunch in the trash bin
outside her apartment.
</P>
<P>
   She took him home, fed him a peanut butter and jelly sandwich,
and sent him on his way. Fifteen minutes later, six 5-year-olds
were at her door. They were hungry, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it true you're giving peanut butter sandwiches away?'' one
little boy asked.
</P>
<P>
   Salazar told them she wasn't, but she fed them anyway. When the
next batch showed up, she fed them, too. And the next.
</P>
<P>
   Peanut butter and jelly and a sense of purpose. For the first
time in a long while, Bea Salazar could lay down her burden and
embrace the tremendous joy life offers us in helping others.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she is known as the founder of ``Bea's Kids,'' a
nonprofit organization in the Dallas suburb of Carrollton.
</P>
<P>
   I liked this story for two reasons: First, peanut butter and
jelly is my favorite sandwich. More important, it was uplifting to
see how Salazar realized that she wasn't the only one with burdens
and pain.
</P>
<P>
   Her story is just one of 30 sketches in Jackie Waldman's ``The
Courage to Give,'' a collection of stories describing how people
healed themselves by reaching out to others.
</P>
<P>
   The title implies giving, but more often than not the stories _
for me at least _ were about putting the needs of others before our
own.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to stay in a place of pain, to ask, ``Why me?'' and
``How?'' and ``When?'' I know, because more than once I've asked
God ``Why?''; Why is there is so much injustice in the world? Why
does it seem evil always triumphs?
</P>
<P>
   Those questions, in particular, were lingering when ``The
Courage to Give'' showed up on my desk last week. I had been trying
to help a friend through a rough spot and not even my faith in an
all-powerful, all-knowing God seemed to be enough.
</P>
<P>
   In my mind, I recounted every biblical story I'd ever read:
Daniel in the lion's den, the three Hebrew boys in the fiery
furnace, David when he faced Goliath, and even Paul when he was
thrown into a Roman prison.
</P>
<P>
   But, like Salazar, I couldn't see past the pain I'd witnessed in
my friend. I was angry.
</P>
<P>
   I had to read no further than the foreword of ``The Courage to
Give,'' however, to reclaim my peace: ``A heart filled with anger
has no room for love.''
</P>
<P>
   Where does the courage to give in the face of adversity come
from? How do you love someone, for instance, who has wronged you or
someone you love?
</P>
<P>
   By letting go of the pain and seeking the greater good.
</P>
<P>
   I knew this just as surely as Daniel was rescued from the lion's
den, as the Hebrew boys escaped the fiery furnace and as David slew
Goliath.
</P>
<P>
   Reading ``The Courage to Give,'' I was reminded that their focus
was never on their adversity; it was on all-powerful, all-knowing
God.
</P>
<P>
   Job said that though you slay me, yet will I trust in God.
</P>
<P>
   Once or twice a month, a book comes to me that I either toss
into the office giveaway box or put in my bookcase to read at a
later date.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, though, I get a book like ``The Courage to Give'' and
I have to read it right away. I've done that, but I'm going to put
it in the giveaway box anyway. Maybe it will inspire someone else
as it did me.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Send E-mail to gbs(at)startext.net. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 1627EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
