<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5343 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-COUNTRY-MUSIC-JINKINS     11-01 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNTRY-MUSIC-JINKINS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON, RIMES RECAPTURE THE MAGIC OF CLASSIC COUNTRY MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By SHIRLEY JINKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like opening volleys of cannon fire, Alan Jackson and LeAnn
Rimes released two of the year's most significant country albums
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Far from being rivals, ``Under the Influence'' and ``LeAnn
Rimes'' represent a singular statement, a stylistic line drawn in
the sand.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson actually fired the first shot last month, with his small
act of defiance during the Country Music Association awards show in
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   You remember: George Jones had been told to cut his song to fit
into a tight time frame. Jones said forget it and didn't perform.
Jackson came on to do his new single from this album, ``Pop a
Top,'' and slipped in a verse of Jones' scheduled song,
``Choices.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought it wasn't right, and that George Jones deserved
more respect than that,'' Jackson said of his actions, on an
appearance the next night on ``Prime Time Country,'' itself a
canceled show.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Waylon Jennings has joked around at Billy Bob's
about lighting a fire, literally, under certain music programmers.
And fans have written this newspaper in support of an
editorial-page piece written by veteran Arlington radio man Bill
Mack.
</P>
<P>
   For country music lovers, this is obviously Day 13 of the siege
of the Alamo.
</P>
<P>
   Against that background, ``Under the Influence'' is Jackson's
best shot yet, lobbed over country's battered walls.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's choices here are warm and familiar, but not overdone.
His reflections on each song, printed in the margins of the lyric
sheet, reveal his own past, as well as country music's more honest
era.
</P>
<P>
   Savor ``Farewell Party,'' ``Once You've Had the Best,'' and
``Revenooer Man.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't attempt to sound like the originals, instead bringing
his own clean baritone and uncluttered arrangements to the
material. (However, he sounds uncannily like a young Merle on ``My
Own Kind of Hat.'')
</P>
<P>
   It really breaks the mood to include ``Margaritaville,'' but
hey, Jackson got Jimmy Buffett to duet with him, so can you really
blame him?
</P>
<P>
   The album's best cut, another Haggard song, ``The Way I Am,''
might be Jackson's own mission statement, and everyone else's, too.
</P>
<P>
   LeAnn Rimes' return to the traditional country fold with her new
self-titled album on Curb is perhaps an even more crucial move than
Jackson's.
</P>
<P>
   She's been in real danger of becoming yesterday's entertainment
news, and this could be her ticket back to credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Recent campy forays and misfires in song selection (an album cut
of Prince's ``Purple Rain'' comes to mind) have undercut Rimes'
``Blue'' success and alienated many of her traditional fans.
There's nothing sadder than a good girl gone bad, you know.
</P>
<P>
   But here's ``LeAnn Rimes'' to salvage LeAnn Rimes, and it's good
enough to work. (Too bad they couldn't have come up with a more
imaginative title, though.)
</P>
<P>
   All but one of the 12 offerings are old songs, including
``Crazy,'' ``Born to Lose,'' ``Cryin' Time'' and especially,
``She's Got You,'' which may actually improve on Patsy.
</P>
<P>
   Nah, that's blasphemy. Pretend you didn't read that.
</P>
<P>
   Now 17, Rimes obviously has some emotional maturity to go along
with that perfect voice. Take ``Faded Love'': She goes for low and
smoky at first, then piercingly poignant on the higher notes.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, ``LeAnn Rimes'' has an old-time, countrypolitan feel
with lush strings, snare drums and quartet background vocals. It
harks back to the Patsy Cline era in more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   Best upbeat song? ``Lovesick Blues,'' so filled with flirty
turns, yodels, trills and triks, it comes off more Tin Pan Alley
than honky-tonk.
</P>
<P>
   Though a departure from the earlier material of the '50s and
'60s, LeAnn's upbeat ``Me &AMP; Bobbie McGee'' is another good turn,
though she hopelessly mangles some of the lyrics in an effort to be
stylish. ``Bobbie McGee'' comes off sounding like ``Babb-ey
Mag-hee-aah.''
</P>
<P>
   The one new song, ``Big Deal,'' owes more to Brenda Lee than
Patsy Cline stylistically.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Rimes fans may miss the purity and innocence of Rimes'
earlier work. But they all grow up sometime, huh? ___
</P>
<P>
   Alan Jackson, ``Under the Influence,'' Arista Nashville. Five
stars
</P>
<P>
   LeAnn Rimes, ``LeAnn Rimes,'' Curb Records. Four stars. ___
</P>
<P>
   (Shirley Jinkins covers the country music scene for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
