<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5344 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-MADIGAN-COLUMN-TEX     11-01 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MADIGAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MAN TRUSTING THERE'S MORE GOOD THAN BAD
</HEADLINE>
 ATTN: Colo. 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a recent morning, I bought a newspaper at the neighborhood
bagel shop and had found a booth to read, when a front-page
headline caught my eye: ``Tragedy Again Hits Columbine.''
</P>
<P>
   For a long while, I could manage only the first few paragraphs
of the story about Carla Hochhalter's suicide, which had occurred
in a Denver suburb the day before. I wept that day in the bagel
shop, mourned for a woman and her family that I never really knew,
and remain saddened even now, several days later.
</P>
<P>
   She had walked into a Colorado pawnshop, asked to see a handgun,
loaded it and then shot herself, the newspaper story said. Just the
month before, the day after the shootings at Wedgwood Baptist
Church, I had traveled to the Denver suburb of Littleton and spoken
with her husband, Ted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lose our faith, not only in God, but in the goodness of
human nature, we lose everything,'' Ted Hochhalter told me on the
telephone that September night.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed a remarkable statement under the circumstances. In
April, his teen-age daughter had been paralyzed in the infamous
rampage at Columbine High School. Now, with his wife's suicide, Ted
Hochhalter's remarkable faith is being tested again. The intensity
of my own grief on that Saturday morning surprised me. In the bagel
shop, I wondered how much suffering a human could possibly endure.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of assignment I dread, calling to request an
interview with a bereaved person, to intrude on their pain. And my
unease that night in September only intensified after hearing the
profound weariness and sadness in Ted Hochhalter's voice.
</P>
<P>
   On April 19, Anne Marie Hochhalter, Ted's daughter, was eating
lunch outside Columbine High when two young gunmen approached. Anne
Marie was critically wounded and left partially paralyzed. Her
younger brother, Nathan, was trapped inside the school that day and
still carries emotional wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Hochhalter's wife, Carla, battled severe depression, her husband
told me that night. He was struggling desperately to keep his
family afloat. Quite obviously, another call from another reporter
was the last thing that Ted Hochhalter needed.
</P>
<P>
   But only the night before my call, another gunman entered a
public space, this time Wedgwood Baptist Church in Fort Worth,
pitching another community into the darkest days of shock and
grief. I had been sent by the Star-Telegram to Littleton to
interview the survivors of Columbine in the hope that our residents
might learn something from brethren in the recently stricken Denver
suburb. That night on the telephone, after a moment's hesitation,
Ted Hochhalter agreed to talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart goes out to the people in Fort Worth, and will
continue to,'' he said in that unforgettably weary voice that
night, ``because it's like the doctor said about Anne Marie's
injury: `It's not a short race. It's a marathon.' Now they have to
go back in and pick up the pieces, and it's not an easy thing to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet from somewhere within his devastation, Hochhalter managed to
offer hope. Fort Worth would rise to the occasion, he said,
``because it's happened here for us.'' He spoke of the meals
prepared for his family, help with the laundry, the hundreds of
cards and letters from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something you can never forget is that there are many more
good people in the world than there are bad, like the one
individual who did this in Fort Worth,'' Hochhalter told me. ``If
we lose our faith, not only in God, but in the goodness of human
nature, we lose everything. Things will get better. The community
in Fort Worth will rise to the occasion and be there for those
people. I believe that from the bottom of my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   To me, his words were an extraordinary act of courage and
generosity, a source of light for Fort Worth, a place badly in need
of it. Ted Hochhalter and I had talked on the telephone for only 30
minutes, but in 20 years of journalism, few people had touched me
so deeply.
</P>
<P>
   Then came that headline and the surprising intensity of my own
grief. Further on in the grim account of Carla Hochhalter's suicide
were the hopeful comments of her husband, spoken to me in our
previous interview. Ted Hochhalter's hope now seemed tragically
ironic.
</P>
<P>
   The question that the newspaper story raised was only implied,
but unavoidable: After yet another wrenching tragedy, could he
possibly feel the same way, cling to even the faintest hope? Who
could blame him if he couldn't?
</P>
<P>
   But somehow I believe he will. Maybe not now _ but someday, I
believe, his hope will return. One can only imagine the burdens
that await him: the grief of the loss of his wife, the struggles of
caring for his scarred daughter and son. But there is a certain
indestructibility to hearts like that of Ted Hochhalter's, a person
who found it within himself to offer comfort to Fort Worth amid his
own profound weariness and pain.
</P>
<P>
   My own hope is that we can now reciprocate _ perhaps not in a
tangible way, but with our thoughts and prayers for Ted and his
family. Maybe, in this sad moment, it is a chance to demonstrate
what Ted Hochhalter has publicly believed: In this world, despite
so much evidence to the contrary, there are many more good people
than bad. ___
</P>
<P>
   Cards and letters to Ted Hochhalter and his family may be
addressed to:
</P>
<P>
   Christ Lutheran Church
</P>
<P>
   8997 S. Broadway
</P>
<P>
   Highlands Ranch, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   80126 ___
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Madigan is a senior writer in the Fort Worth Star-Telegram
features department. You can reach him at
tmadigan(at)star-telegram.commor (817) 390-7544. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com).
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
