<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRAL-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIFTING THE HEARTS OF SPORTS STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By PAUL HARRAL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the many things that offend me on television these days is
an advertisement that clearly makes fun of something very serious.
</P>
<P>
   You will have noticed in recent years that football players from
opposing teams occasionally gather in a small group after the game
to offer a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Some find such an obvious display of religion offensive, either
because they are not religious or because they believe that prayers
are more properly offered in private.
</P>
<P>
   There is Scripture to support the latter view in Matthew 6,
where Jesus warns about those who ``love to pray standing in the
synagogues and in the corners of the streets, that they may be seen
of men.''
</P>
<P>
   So some think the football-field prayer circles are too much for
show.
</P>
<P>
   Others see them as a witness.
</P>
<P>
   There is support for this in Matthew 5, where Jesus reminds his
followers that they are ``the light of the world'' and commands
them to ``let your light so shine before men, that they may see
your good works, and glorify your Father which is in heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   I suppose the difference is in the heart. Prayer offered so that
the person doing the praying may be seen as being religious is
questionable. Sincere prayer is not.
</P>
<P>
   Until someone proves differently to me, I will choose to believe
that those football players who point to heaven after a score, or
who kneel in the end zone or who gather with opposing players in
small groups are doing it because their hearts are sincere.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I find this particular advertisement offensive. It's
a really good ad _ showing a football player trash-talking by
questioning his opponent's investment strategy.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the game, several players are shown kneeling on
the field, discussing investments. It's funny right up to that
point, but that's where it crosses my personal out-of-bounds line.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings me to golfer Payne Stewart. Stewart's Learjet
crashed last Monday, killing all aboard.
</P>
<P>
   There will be many ways to remember Stewart, but the image that
will remain in my mind is of his fist-pumping, leaping celebration
on the 18th green at Pinehurst in North Carolina when he dropped a
seemingly impossible putt to win the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   But do you remember what he did next?
</P>
<P>
   On national TV, he credited his win to God.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that happens often after athletic conquests,
setting off no shortage of skeptics questioning the true religious
commitment by the victorious sports star,'' writer Larry Guest said
in The Orlando Sentinel on Oct. 18, before Stewart's death. ``Payne
has had more skeptics than most during his 20-year PGA Tour career.
Perhaps it's the playful costume and the jaunty personality that
was interpreted as a lack of depth.''
</P>
<P>
   No need to question his sincerity any more, Guest said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Pinehurst, Stewart said his recent religious growth came by
osmosis through his children's experience at The First Academy, the
private Christian school on the FBC (First Baptist Church of
Orlando) campus,'' Guest said. ``He wore a simple, woven bracelet,
a gift from son Aaron, with the letters `WWJD' _ the Christian
guideline for daily living, `What Would Jesus Do?' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Guest notes that Stewart did not stop there. Without
fanfare, he and his wife, Tracey, gave a half-million dollars to
the First Foundation, the fund-raising arm of the First Baptist
Church of Orlando. Stewart also invited other parents to a barbecue
to urge them to contribute. The group pledged another $700,000.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a William J. Stewart House for the use of families
of cancer patients, a tribute to Stewart's father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payne funded it by donating the $108,000 first-place check
right after he won the 1987 Bay Hill Classic,'' Guest said.
</P>
<P>
   I liked watching Payne Stewart play golf. I liked his clothes. I
liked his style. And I like the quote from Stewart in Guest's
column when he was asked about his gift to the church:
</P>
<P>
   ``Tracey and I and our kids have more than we deserve. That's
just the way it is. So it's not that hard to give something back.
We decided we wanted to give where it would make an impact, mostly
in the lives of children.''
</P>
<P>
   If you were skeptical after the U.S. Open or when other athletes
choose to proclaim a witness in public, consider this:
</P>
<P>
   We tread dangerous ground when we make assumptions about people
and about their motives. And we tread dangerous ground when we find
humor in people's most deeply held beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Who are we to question?
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it God's job to (as the ``Battle Hymn of the Republic''
puts it) sift out hearts before the judgment seat?
</P>
<P>
   (Paul K. Harral is vice president and editorial director for the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram. You can reach him at
harral(at)star-telegram.com; (817) 390-7836; or P.O. Box 1870, Fort
Worth, TX 76101. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
