   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Oslo, Norway) _ Back in the birthplace of the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process, President Clinton on Monday
presided over a kind of multinational homage to the original dream
of a permanent peace. Israeli and Palestinian leaders, with
sideline cheers from the Norwegians, recommitted themselves to
forging a framework agreement by February. And in a series of
two-way meetings, with each other and separately with Clinton, they
began designing an approach to carry forward at a quickened pace.
By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHAN-REBELS (Khwaja Bahaouddin, Afghanistan) _ Special Report:
The Lion of the Panjshir is not a big man, especially so for
someone thought to be Afghanistan's greatest guerrilla fighter.
With his beret cocked to the side and his brow in a pensive
wrinkle, he has the look of a beat generation poet, more at home in
a basement coffee house than in high-altitude combat. But among
this nation's storied commanders, only the Lion _ Ahmed Shah
Massoud _ is left to fight on against the Taliban militia, the
others all killed or chased into exile or bought off with cash. By
Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-NH (Lebanon, N.H.) _ Gov. George W. Bush's advisers,
acknowledging they were caught off guard by Sen. John McCain's
recent rise in the polls in New Hampshire, said they were now
bracing for a hard-fought contest in this state that holds the
first presidential primary. McCain's campaign here could complicate
Bush's strategy for wrapping up the nomination quickly and, if
McCain wins here, could threaten the entire Bush juggernaut. By
Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic and sidebar: BUSH-NH-POLL (Undated) _ Analyzing the
poll data. By Janet Elder.
