<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO BUCKING VETERAN DEAR HUNTER JIM NIELSEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The stories of most people can be told on the
lines on a page, but the story of Jim Nielsen, 89, is best told
from the lines on his face.
</P>
<P>
   Each of those creases and wrinkles are like the back roads on a
detailed map of the wilderness, leading off to secret canyons,
ridges and adventures, telling of a journey like no other.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen, always an avid outdoorsman, is believed to be the only
hunter in North America to have filled his buck tag for 70 straight
years. In addition, he has done it in a state, California, where
deer hunting is so difficult that 85 percent of hunters fail to get
their deer and many never see buck for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing you need is a love of nature,'' Nielsen said.
``It is so beautiful at sun-up. I sit out there and listen to the
wild birds, the coyotes every morning. That can't be replaced by
anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you must study the country,'' he continued. ``Out there
in the dry canyon country of the Coast Range, I know where the
water holes are. I'll get 100 yards from the water holes and watch
the wind, you know, keep the wind in your face and they can't smell
you. I've learned between 11 a.m. and 2 p.m. is a very good time. A
buck nibbles on something, wants to get a drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people go too fast. They don't stop, look and listen.
They don't see the places where they feed, water and the routes
they take to those places. I've tromped around plenty to find those
places. 'Course, I enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen has lived in the Watsonville, Calif., area for his
entire life. He is an avid hiker, camper, fishermen, bird hunter
and deer hunter, with his home decorated with several of his
trophies, including a 333-pound blue marlin, a one-in-a-million
buck with a strange non-typical rack that looks something like a
cactus, and a trophy deer mount with horns nearly two feet high,
with nine points and a 35-inch spread.
</P>
<P>
   He also won a Distinguished Service Award from Ducks Unlimited
for habitat conservation work in Elkhorn Slough area near Monterey
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Marilyn, almost always joins him on his hunts.
</P>
<P>
   ``At age 65, he took me on hikes that I was sure were going to
kill me off _ I figured he wanted another wife,'' she joked. ``But
this is a hunting family. We go into tough country, rocky and
steep, and we look forward to it. We always spend our anniversary,
Aug. 16, at deer camp in the Coast Range.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim has a son from a previous marriage, Ray of Sacramento, 57,
who got his first buck as a 12-year-old, and a daughter, Jane Sharp
of Pleasanton. Jane has two sons, David, 20, and Steven, 16, who
both just passed hunter safety courses, and as a reward, Jim gave
them both hunting rifles.
</P>
<P>
   At 89, Nielsen still works his job, distributing grain seed to
farmers. He's owned a grain business since 1940, selling the seed,
then buying the harvest to sell to brokers for distribution across
the country. ``I've done it since the day I finished high school,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen credits his long, healthy life to the great love and
bonds in his family and his passions for his career and outdoor
adventure. ``'Course, I never smoked or drinked.''
</P>
<P>
   His first successful hunt was in 1930, deep in Chular Canyon in
the Coast Range of Monterey County.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a greenhorn, about 20, and the fellow who was with me,
Dan Ready, my friend, was also a greenhorn,'' Nielsen said. ``We
didn't know too much about it. It was a hot day and I was pretty
tired, and I sat down at a brush patch for about an hour to rest,
and then I spotted this forked horn. I tracked him up a mountain
side, around a brush patch, and that's where I surprised him.''
</P>
<P>
   In the time since, he's been schooled by the University of
Nature. Most of the lessons have come in the dry, brushy canyon
country of the Coast Range in Monterey and San Benito counties, and
the high rocky ridges of the Sierra Nevada, where he has driven his
Jeep, hiked and bushwhacked in wilderness to learn the skills of
woodsmanship. Most hikers never see much wildlife, he noted, and
many fishermen don't catch many fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most hunters get up early in the morning, tromp around for a
couple hours, don't see anything, and then go back to camp,''
Nielsen said. ``I go out in the morning and also hunt around as
much as I can, but I don't quit. I've seen most of my deer right in
the middle of the day, when most of the guys are back at their
camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also have two rules. I always use binoculars, wouldn't go
unless I had a pair. And I have to have a scope on my rifle for a
clean, accurate shot.''
</P>
<P>
   His most difficult hunt, Nielsen explained, was back in 1961,
just after he had been released from a hospital with multiple
injuries from a vehicle accident. He had been driving a harvester
on a twisty road near San Jose when a speeding car sailed around a
bend and rammed the harvester over a cliff _ ``I had a wrecked
ankle, broken pelvis, busted shoulder and a crooked neck, those
were the main things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The week after I got out of the hospital, my boy Ray took me
out hunting,'' Nielsen said. ``One arm was still in a sling, and he
helped me put my boots on, put shells in my rifle. I wasn't strong
enough to hold a rifle. The last weekend of the season, we went
down Chular Canyon with the Jeep, the same area where I got my
first buck in 1930, and positioned ourselves at this one spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to lay the rifle on the Jeep and got down on my knees,
cause I only had one arm _ and I got my buck with one shot.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiled at the memory, lines around his eyes bunching into
little crinkles. The story on his face was like a book. It told of
70 years of hunts, adventures and passions fulfilled. No more words
were necessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
