<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Impact of Climate Change &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The effect of climate change on ecosystems is well known. In a
region experiencing a drought, to take an obvious example, less
flora is available for the fauna, which can cause populations of
certain animals to decline.
</P>
<P>
   But climate change can also have a more indirect effect on an
ecosystem, by altering the behavior of predators within it. The
latest illustration of this is from a long-term study of wolves in
Isle Royale National Park, an island sanctuary in Lake Superior.
</P>
<P>
   The study, by a team of researchers led by two Norwegian
biologists, shows that during harsh winters with more snow, wolves
hunt in larger packs. This makes them more efficient hunters and is
bad news for their favorite prey, moose. But what is bad for the
moose is good for the vegetation: fewer moose means that more
balsam fir saplings, the animal's main winter forage, survive.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers studied data collected over 40 years in the
park. Their analysis, reported in the journal Nature, shows that
average pack size ranged from 4.5 wolves during the mildest winters
to 12 during the snowiest, as grown pups that would normally leave
to seek mates stayed with the family instead. Larger packs killed
up to three times more moose than smaller ones.
</P>
<P>
   The data showed there were fewer moose in the year after a snowy
winter. And by studying tree rings, the researchers found that in
those same years, growth of balsam fir saplings increased.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Legacy of an Intruder &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ecosystems can also be affected by the introduction of an
aggressive, non-native species. Often the result is significant, as
anyone who has spent hours chopping kudzu vine from fences and
telephone poles can attest.
</P>
<P>
   But a new study by Canadian scientists suggests that even a
seemingly innocuous alien invader can have a negative impact.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers studied crested wheatgrass, which has steadily
supplanted native grasses in much of the northern Great Plains,
often at the enthusiastic insistence of ranchers and government
agencies. The grass was first imported from Siberia during the
drought years of the Dust Bowl, and is still valued for its
hardiness, long growing season and because it makes good hay.
</P>
<P>
   But the scientists, writing in the journal Ecology, show that
all that crested wheatgrass appears to have reduced the quality of
the soil. Analyzing samples from Grasslands National Park in
Saskatchewan, the researchers found that soil under the wheat grass
had significantly fewer nutrients and less organic material than
soil under native varieties.
</P>
<P>
   The wheatgrass' root system is probably to blame. Wheatgrass
develops only shallow root, devoting most of its energy to its
above-ground shoots. Native grasses do not grow as tall, but their
roots are more extensive, allowing for greater enrichment of the
soil.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Star Measuring &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NASA has chosen a U.S. Naval Observatory satellite to check out
the neighborhood _ the galactic neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The craft, called the Full-Sky Astrometric Mapping Explorer,
will carry a telescope to determine position, distance and other
information about stars brighter than 15th magnitude. Stars of that
magnitude are very faint (the North Star, by contrast, is of second
magnitude), so the spacecraft will have its hands full, measuring
about 40 million objects.
</P>
<P>
   Among the stars that the satellite will study are a class called
the Cepheids, which are used to measure the distance of galaxies
and other objects that are extremely far away. The telescope should
also be able to detect the presence of large planets in orbit
around other stars, by accurately measuring a star's wobble, which
is caused by the gravitational pull of a planet or other object.
</P>
<P>
   The satellite, which is expected to be launched in 2004, will
make use of the solar wind, the waves of electromagnetic radiation
emanating from the Sun, as a kind of solar sail to help keep the
telescope in the proper orientation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
