<SLUG> BC-NY-COURT-OF-APPEALS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S HIGHEST COURT TAKES TO TURN TO THE RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CAHER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ New York's highest court has long relished its
national prominence as a trailblazing tribunal that expanded the
rights and liberties of individuals.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last few years, some analysts and observers say, the
State Court of Appeals has grown timid and conservative and seems
now to shy away from controversial cases and decisions,
particularly in criminal matters.
</P>
<P>
   Some tie the perceived shift to Gov. George Pataki's 1995-96
criticisms of the court, when he characterized its rulings as out
of touch and far too liberal. Others say Pataki's two conservative
appointments to the seven-judge tribunal have swung the court from
a generally liberal 4-3 majority to a generally conservative 4-3
court.
</P>
<P>
   What many court watchers, prosecutors, defense attorneys and
even former judges say is certain is that the court has become far
more reserved and, at the moment, seems to have abandoned its
traditionally progressive stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is now one of the most conservative courts in the United
States,'' said Marvin E. Schechter, president of the state chapter
of the National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers. ``It is
not a court in transition from liberalism to conservatism, it has
made that transition. It is a conservative court, led by a
conservative chief judge.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Stewart E. Sterk, a law professor at the
Benjamin N. Cardozo School of Law at Yeshiva University and former
clerk to Chief Judge Charles D. Breitel, said the court has
retained its historical commitment to individual rights,
particularly in right-to-counsel cases, even if it hasn't gone out
of its way to expand those protections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be hard put to say there is clear evidence of a
conservative tilt,'' Sterk said.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Judge Judith S. Kaye declined to partake in the debate.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that anyone is even arguing over whether Kaye is a
liberal or conservative is in itself noteworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye, a Democrat from Manhattan appointed in 1993 by Gov. Mario
Cuomo, has long been part of the court's moderate to liberal wing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, she criticized the majority for breaking ``with its
proud tradition'' and diluting the right-to-counsel protection.
And, after Kaye became chief judge in 1993, the panel's ``liberal''
rulings _ those in favor of the individual, often times a criminal
defendant, over the government or police _ more than doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Now the court's decisions on individual liberties are right back
where they were before Kaye took over _ about 80 percent for the
government and about 20 percent for the individual, according to
Albany Law School Professor Vincent M. Bonventre.
</P>
<P>
   Bonventre, who tracks and analyzes every decision the court
renders, said that in the late 1980s and early 1990s, Kaye
frequently dissented when the panel cut back on, or declined to
expand on, the rights of the accused.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last few years, you don't see anything written by Judge
Kaye on the rights of the accused or civil rights and liberties
areas complaining about the court cutting back on rights and
liberties, or even in the majority arguing in favor of protecting
rights and liberties,'' Bonventre said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Kaye is consistently voting with the two
``conservative'' judges appointed by Pataki: Richard C. Wesley and
Albert M. Rosenblatt, both Republicans. Wesley, a former
assemblyman, voted for the death penalty. Rosenblatt, as a trial
judge, imposed the death penalty in a case where Kaye wrote the
opinion overturning the sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no (crimimnal) case last term in which Judge Kaye and
the two Pataki judges were on the opposite side,'' said Paul
Schechtman, an attorney in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Schechtman served as the governor's criminal justice director at
the time the Kaye court was under siege by the administration.
``That to me speaks volumes about how non ideological and middle of
the road the court has become. ''
</P>
<P>
   A survey by the New York Law Journal showed that in criminal
cases prosecutors prevailed in 54 of 79 cases _ 68 percent _
between September 1998 and July 1999, and won 80 percent the year
before. In prior terms, prosecutors typically won less than 60
percent of their appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, the Law Journal survey also showed that over the
last three years the court has dramatically cut back on the
percentage of criminal cases it agrees to hear _ about 1.9 percent,
compared to an average of roughly 4 percent over the prior 15
years.In other words, criminal defendants are getting their appeals
before the high court less frequently and losing more often.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see the kind of decisions that sent prosecutors into
spasms years ago,'' Schechtman said. ``It is not like they cut back
on what they created, they are just not expanding. To my mind, it
is a good, responsible court, but I think anyone who thinks it
hasn't moved back toward the center just misreads the last
decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonventre said his analysis suggests that the court is ducking
tough issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as though you read these opinions and you say it is
impossible or illogical to reach these decisions,'' Bonventre said.
``But it is just that when there is a controversial case or a
difficult case, the court typically chooses the easy,
non-politically difficult road. What it means is that the
individual cannot expect nearly as much protection from government
over-reaching as it could have expected in the past.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 1658EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
