<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5447 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d BC-REPLICAS-LADN &LR;      11-01 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPLICAS-LADN </SLUG>
  
Restaurant Replicas: Re-create the Cheesecake Factory's bruschetta 
(Eds: includes two more Restaurant Replicas) 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
 
By Natalie Haughton, Food Editor 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mail continues to bring new requests for copycat versions of
Cheesecake Factory creations. This time it's the bruschetta
requested by reader L.S. Nelson of North Hollywood, who notes that
it is delicious and has a wonderful taste. A recent sampling
verified that it is indeed terrific.
</P>
<P>
   Even better, our version designed for home cooks goes together
in a jiffy with chopped fresh tomatoes, red onion, garlic, basil
and olive oil. Be sure to use fresh basil _ it's not the same
without it. And use top-quality extra virgin olive oil. Serve as an
appetizer or offer as a quick meal with a big green salad with or
without meat.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for something different for an entree salad,
consider the cold Chicken Diablo Salad, a replica version of one
from the take-out counter of Gelson's market. The flavor is
intriguing _ hot and spicy with a slight sweet and sour twist. It's
not too time-consuming to prepare if you use cooked chicken breasts
or a whole chicken from the market. Remove the skin and dice the
meat. Red pepper strips, rehydrated sun-dried tomatoes (Gelson's
uses yellow, which we couldn't locate, so red ones were
substituted), red onions and ripe olives add color while a little
chopped green chile, cilantro, rice vinegar, soy sauce, garlic and
oil add interesting flavor. The mixture is best chilled an hour
prior to serving if you have the time.
</P>
<P>
   Serve piled on assorted greens for a beautiful-looking variation
on the chicken salad theme. Keep this salad in mind next time
you're entertaining at a midday shower or weekend lunch. Both its
appearance and flavor make it a showstopper.
</P>
<P>
   Another novel entree salad _ that could be served in a smaller
portion as a dinner salad, especially during the holiday season _
completes today's replica collection. It's a fabulous-tasting
combination sampled at the Bongo Room, a restaurant in Chicago. The
restaurant is small and busy at breakfast and lunch and brunch on
the weekends. And with the wonderful array of tempting-sounding
salads and sandwiches, it's no wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast dishes sound innovative with offerings like Raspberry
Cheesecake Hotcakes and Pineapple Upside Down Brioche French Toast.
Go early if you want to avoid waiting for a table.
</P>
<P>
   The salad, referred to as the Ambassador on the menu, combines
fresh spinach leaves, fennel pieces, red onion slices, toasted
pecans, dried sour cherries and manchego cheese. The ingredients
are dressed with an Orange-Balsamic Vinaigrette, which in our
version has lots of fresh orange juice along with a little orange
peel.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not familiar with fennel, give it a try in this dish.
It has a pale green feathery top and large bulblike base. The
distinctive flavor is similar to licorice or anise seed but less
pungent. Look for fresh green leaves and crisp, large compact
greenish-white bulbs with no sign of splitting, drying or browning.
Keep refrigerated until using.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare, rinse well and trim top and bottom, removing any
bruised outer pieces. Although all parts of the fennel plant are
edible _ and can be eaten raw, steamed, baked, stir-fried or
sauteed _ we used the bulb (cut out and discard the hard center
core) cut into thin slices. Blanch in boiling water in the
microwave oven for a few minutes, just until crisp-tender.
</P>
<P>
   If you can find it, use manchego cheese (a rich, golden semifirm
cheese with a mellow flavor) as the restaurant does. In a pinch,
substitute a very mild crumbled feta or goat cheese so you don't
overpower the other ingredients. Manchego is famous in Spain and
was so named because originally it was made only from the milk of
Manchego sheep that grazed the famous plains of La Mancha.
</P>
<P>
   These three facsimiles are all winners. Tasters gave them top
marks. Clip and save to use throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BRUSCHETTA &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 cups finely diced tomatoes (about 5 to 6 plum tomatoes _ squeeze
out seeds and most of juice before dicing) &QL; 
1/3 cup finely diced red onion &QL; 
3 tablespoons finely chopped fresh basil &QL; 
1 small clove garlic, crushed through a press or minced &QL; 
Extra virgin olive oil &QL; 
Seasoned salt and pepper to taste &QL; 
6 (3/4- to 1-inch thick) diagonally cut slices sourdough or French
bread (from a baguette or flute)
</P>
<P>
   In a medium stainless steel or glass bowl, combine tomatoes, red
onion, basil, garlic and 1 to 1 1/2 tablespoons extra virgin olive
oil. Toss gently to mix. Stir in seasoned salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Brush both sides of bread slices with olive oil and place on a
foil-lined baking sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Toast under preheated broiler about 8 inches from heat source
about 2 minutes per side until light golden.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon tomato mixture onto toast slices and arrange slices
attractively on a serving plate or platter. Or spoon tomato mixture
into a small bowl or souffle dish and place in center of serving
plate surrounded by toast slices. Makes 3 to 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CHICKEN DIABLO SALAD &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 1/2 to 3 cups diced cooked chicken breast &QL; 
1/4 to 1/2 red onion, chopped &QL; 
1/2 cup chopped soft sun-dried tomatoes (rehydrate tomatoes in
boiling water 10 minutes and drain well) &QL; 
1/2 red bell pepper, cut into strips &QL; 
2 teaspoons soy sauce &QL; 
2 1/2 teaspoons sugar &QL; 
1 teaspoon water &QL; 
1 to 2 tablespoons finely chopped Anaheim OR California chile &QL; 
3/4 cup drained whole medium ripe olives &QL; 
1/4 cup chopped fresh cilantro &QL; 
1/4 cup vegetable OR olive oil &QL; 
1/4 cup rice vinegar &QL; 
1 clove garlic, pressed &QL; 
Seasoned salt and garlic pepper to taste &QL; 
Hot sauce to taste
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, combine all ingredients, mixing well.
</P>
<P>
   Refrigerate 1 hour before serving on assorted greens. Makes 4 to
4 1/2 cups, about 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
AMBASSADOR SALAD &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Orange-Balsamic Vinaigrette &QL; 
8 cups spinach, cleaned and torn into pieces &QL; 
1 fennel bulb, cut in thin slices, blanched in boiling water in
microwave oven until crisp-tender and drained &QL; 
1/2 red onion, thinly sliced and slices cut into strips &QL; 
1 cup toasted pecans &QL; 
2/3 cup dried sour cherries &QL; 
3/4 cup crumbled manchego cheese
</P>
<P>
   Prepare Orange-Balsamic Vinaigrette; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine spinach, fennel, red onion, 1/2 of
pecans and 1/2 of cherries. Add vinaigrette and toss well.
</P>
<P>
   Serve on salad or dinner plates and sprinkle with remaining
pecans and cherries. Top with cheese, dividing evenly. Makes 3 to 4
entree-size servings; 6 salad-course size servings.
</P>
<P>
   ORANGE-BALSAMIC VINAIGRETTE: In a small bowl, whisk together 1/3
cup oil, 2 to 3 tablespoons Balsamic vinegar, 6 tablespoons fresh
orange juice, 1 teaspoon grated orange peel and seasoned salt and
garlic pepper to taste. Makes about 3/4 cup. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
