<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Nov. 2, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Pittsburgh reached 70 degrees Monday, it marked the fourth
consecutive day that readings surpassed 70 degrees. The strong high
pressure system that has held steady along the Northeast Seaboard
will weaken and drift east Tuesday, setting the stage for a
dramatic change in the weather across the much of the Northeast and
Ohio Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Low pressure moving north along a slow-moving front will
circulate copious Atlantic moisture into the Appalachians and
eastern Great Lakes. As the moist air intercepts the front, a large
swath of heavy showers, accompanied by local flooding, will fall
across the region. Isolated thunderstorms will also occur. Farther
east, sunshine will fade behind a thickening veil of clouds over
New England with heavy rain arriving overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Brisk winds from the northwest gusting past 40 mph will direct
much colder air into Great Lakes and Middle West on Tuesday. Midday
readings will hold in the 30s over much of the region. As the
chilly air passes over the still tepid waters of the Great Lakes,
ascending currents of moistened air will lead to snow showers in
parts of Michigan and northern Indiana. Some accumulation is
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the West will be dry and tranquil as a large ridge of
high pressure at 20,000 feet diverts inclement weather from the
Pacific into western Canada. California will remain seasonably warm
with readings well into the 80s across southern sections, though
onshore breezes will keep the air cooler along the Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Indian Summer
</P>
<P>
   During late October and early November, a second summer often
comes. Indian summer is the name given to a mid-autumn period of
abnormally warm weather accompanied by sunny, hazy days and cool
nights. While there is no official definition, tradition suggests
that a killing frost must precede the warm spell for it to be
considered true Indian summer. The origin of the term most likely
relates to the way American Indians used these last mild days to
increase their winter stores. The recent spell of Indian summer
across the East will come to an abrupt end as a strong cold front
sweeps south from Canada.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
