<HEADLINE>
HOLIDAY TAX TIPS COULD MAKES FOR A JOYOUS APRIL 15 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JO-ANN JOHNSTON  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ One of the best ways to reduce any income taxes
you'll owe in the spring is to start figuring your tax liability
now, tax experts say.
</P>
<P>
   With nine weeks left in the calendar year, taxpayers still have
time to shift deductions, make adjustments to retirement accounts
and take other legitimate steps that will lessen the tax burden
come next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing to do is get a good estimate of what kinds of
income you'll have this year and what your deductions are,'' said
Jeffrey M. Levine, an Albany financial consultant. ``Get a good
overview so you can do some planning.''
</P>
<P>
   This shouldn't be too tough for most people this year, since
there have been no major changes in the tax code, said Gerard
Mazurkiewicz, who runs the upstate New York tax preparation
business for accounting firm KPMG.
</P>
<P>
   Start by checking your pay stubs, and seeing if you have any
self-employment income.
</P>
<P>
   Cross check these against your likely deductions and withholding
payments and any quarterly payments already made to the IRS and
your state.
</P>
<P>
   Then, see if anything on this checklist could help your tax
standing.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you're a homeowner, make an extra mortgage payment in
December in time to be posted for 1999, Levine said. This will
increase your mortgage interest deduction. People who have just
bought their first home are especially apt to overlook this
deduction, Levine said. Home buyers also need to remember they get
a deduction for mortgage points, he added.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you suffered any damage to property from Hurricane Floyd,
document the value of any losses not reimbursed by insurance. The
IRS allow deductions, within certain limits, for such casualty
losses. IRS allows people to ammend their 1998 tax returns to
reflect those losses, and get any refunds more quickly,
Mazurkiewicz said.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you have any self-employment income, make your January
state quarterly tax payment in December to boost your deductions,
Levine said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Similarly, self-employed people might purchase now any new
computer, fax, electronic or other business equipment they've been
needing and planning to buy, said Mazurkiewicz. The IRS will allow
the purchases to be deducted all in one year, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   _ Plan charitable giving now. Clean out closets and basements
and donate any unused clothing, Levine said. If you are considering
a major cash contribution to a charity and own stock, consider
instead donating stock worth the same amount, said Mazurkiewicz.
The charity can sell the stock for cash, tax-free, and the giver
can avoid incurring capital gains tax that would be triggered by
selling the stock while still in his or her name.
</P>
<P>
   _ Look to ``bunch'' other kinds of deductions in either 1999 or
2000. These would include your taxpayer's uninsured costs, such as
medical and dental work, miscellaneous deductions for
non-reimbursed employee business expenses or payments for tax and
investment advice. The IRS ties the deductions taxpayers can take
on such items to a percentage of income.
</P>
<P>
   With medical expenses, taxpayers can only deduct the amount that
is more than 7.5 percent of the adjusted gross income. For
miscellaneous expenses, taxpayers can deduct only the expenses
exceeding 2 percent of the adjusted gross income. The upshot is
that it's hard to have enough expenses in any one year to earn the
deductions, Levine noted, but sometimes people are successful at
grouping the bills into one year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
