<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXTBOOK-BATTLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXTBOOK BATTLE BREWING IN TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By R.A. DYER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ An 11th-hour request by a State Board of
Education member to revise the content of first-grade textbooks has
outraged publishers, who said the changes would unfairly cost them
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But board member Geraldine Miller, who asked for the changes in
September, said publishers have only themselves to blame _ and
possibly bad advice from the Texas Education Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just stepping in and fixing this,'' said Miller,
R-Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy is expected to peak this week when the board
votes on $90.6 million in reading and language arts textbooks for
kindergarten through third grade. The board begins meeting
Wednesday, with the general session scheduled for Friday in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is what percentage of words should be ``decodable,'' or
simple enough that students can read by sounding out letters or
combinations of letters. The state board said ``most'' words should
be ``decodable;'' almost a year ago, the education agency told
publishers that ``most'' meant 51 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said she has the votes to require publishers to include
more decodable words. The 15-member board will decide which
textbooks comply with the state's curriculum guidelines, meaning
many publishers may have prepared books that will not be used.
</P>
<P>
   Books that do not conform may still be selected by local
districts, but publishers say that rarely happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking the position that the publishers have produced
awful good materials and that it's not right _ and maybe illegal _
to require that they change them,'' said Joe Bill Watkins, an
attorney representing the Association of American Publishers. ``It
will cost several million dollars. But it's the principle that's
really wrong. If this happens, then every November, some member of
the board can put together a majority and rewrite'' the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Words that beginning readers can decode, or sound out using
phonics, include straightforward spellings such as ``cat,'' ``see''
and ``it.'' Many simple words do not follow phonics rules, however,
and children learn to read them on sight. Examples would be
``one,'' ``two,'' ``there'' and ``their.''
</P>
<P>
   As supporters of phonics, many board members want a high
percentage of decodable words in early reading textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Miller has called for an average of 80 percent. She said the
education agency should have told the board that a question had
arisen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have every right do to this because the process was
flawed,'' Miller said. ``In hindsight, we should have defined what
`most' meant. But we never dreamed that they would define it as 51
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Joey Lozano, an agency spokesman, said the TEA frequently
responds to requests to clarify legislation and board rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody identified this as an issue, or expressed a concern,
until that September meeting,'' he said. ``It was then that Mrs.
Miller raised the issue.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said he is not sure there was an error, ``it's just that
nobody ... brought this to our attention.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate cuts to the heart of the sometimes contentious
discussion over how best to teach reading: either through phonics
instruction or whole-language instruction.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the phonics method of sounding out words, whole
language emphasizes reading through the use of context, encourages
children to draw inferences from clues within the text and even
permits children to invent their own spellings.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins, of the Association of American Publishers, said the
board has changed the guidelines too late.
</P>
<P>
   To help untangle the mix-up, education agency staff members have
asked publishers to come up with plans to include more decodable
words.
</P>
<P>
   Lozano said the board could adopt textbooks on a provisional
basis, then provide a permanent endorsement later if publishers
fulfill those plans.
</P>
<P>
   Local school districts may choose conforming or nonconforming
textbooks and can receive state funding for either. Still, failing
to make the board's conforming list can doom a textbook because
districts generally prefer those aligned with the state's
high-stakes testing process, publishers say.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, State Education Commissioner Jim Nelson issued
recommendations about which books conform to the state's
curriculum. Basing his decision on the 51 percent standard for
decodable words, Nelson recommended first-grade reading textbooks
from about a dozen publishers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commissioner gave publishers a letter saying that you
voluntarily might want to come up with a plan in case the board
decided to change'' the standard, Watkins said. ``Well, the
publishers have to protect their investment, so they say the plan
is voluntary, but it's more like there is a gun to their head.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) .MDBO/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 1714EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
