<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5464 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NFK-FEATURE02-COX     11-01 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    l
 &HT;    S T R E T C H YOUR IMAGINATION
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I like to pretend that my imagination is a rubber band.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that's right. A rubber band. It sits dusty and curled in
the back of my mind when I'm not daydreaming.
</P>
<P>
   But when my mind begins to wander, oh how that rubber band
changes. I imagine myself stretching and twisting it into all kinds
of new and wonderful shapes.
</P>
<P>
   You may find my metaphor (remember that word from English
class?) a stretch, but I think it captures what makes writing
strong.
</P>
<P>
   Even though imagination is key, it is not enough. You must
hammer a good idea into shape through hard work.
</P>
<P>
   How, you may ask, would I know?
</P>
<P>
   Because I write stories for the newspaper every day and have
written two children's novels.
</P>
<P>
   Each of my books began as a crazy idea that made me laugh out
loud. Unfortunately, a good laugh was not enough. I learned the
hard way it's tough to turn a funny scene into a readable story.
</P>
<P>
   That requires something else _ craft.
</P>
<P>
   Look at it this way. Learning to write well is like figuring out
how to hit a baseball or bake bread. There are certain things you
can do that ensure the bread rises and your bat connects with the
ball. It's the same with writing.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some tricks I've learned for hitting a home run with
stories:
</P>
<P>
   TIPS FOR FANTASTIC WRITING
</P>
<P>
   -- Pepper your stories with crazy characters doing interesting
things. Nobody wants to read a story with a great character who
sits around twiddling his thumbs in a corner.
</P>
<P>
   -- Don't tell your readers the characters are interesting, show
them. Use meaningful details to describe the colorful things that
make your characters unique. For example, don't write ``Paula loves
the color green.'' Write instead, ``Each day, Paula wore army green
pants, a lime green shirt and even painted her nails a pale shade
of Chartreuse.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Grab your reader from the first sentence. Begin your stories
in the middle of the action and then work backward to explain
what's going on. (The ancient Greeks always did this!)
</P>
<P>
   -- Never start a story with ``Let me tell you a story,'' or
``Once upon a time.'' It's a lazy way to begin.
</P>
<P>
   -- Think about your stories as scenes. Connect the scenes in a
story line driven by conflict and action.
</P>
<P>
   -- Keep your writing crisp. Use strong, specific verbs, such as
grumble, wallop or wheeze. Avoid strings of adjectives. Keep your
writing and story line taut (that means tight) _ just like this
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   -- And lastly, never fear rewriting a story. Writing is
rewriting. Your best ideas will come in the third or fourth drafts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
