<SLUG> BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEWS FLASH: News shorts for kids
 &HT;    By Julie Bryant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   New peace
</P>
<P>
   talks to begin
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians and Israelis are trying to make peace after years
of fighting. Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak, along with President Clinton, will meet in
Norway this week to discuss a final treaty. They will negotiate
over some of the most difficult issues in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations created Israel from the territory of
Palestine in 1948 after World War II. The goal was to give the
Jewish people, many of whom were survivors of the Holocaust in
Europe, a homeland. However, many Arabs felt the Palestinians were
treated unfairly and they decided to fight. Violence has raged off
and on, as Arabs and Jews struggle with who will occupy what land.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders will try to settle the final borders of Palestinian
territory, how the city of Jerusalem should be divided and the
future of millions of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   BACKSTREET BOYS
</P>
<P>
   Man arrested in scam
</P>
<P>
   Buyer beware _ especially when it comes to Backstreet Boys
tickets. A New Jersey man was arrested last week for trying to sell
nonexistent tickets to the sold-out Nov. 24 Backstreet Boys show in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   He offered the tickets on eBay's Internet auction site during
the summer. At least two dozen people from across the country,
including Georgia, said they sent $200 to $1,000 in response to the
posting. However, they got no tickets in return.
</P>
<P>
   The man could face several years in prison if convicted of
forgery, theft and other charges.
</P>
<P>
   BLOW OUT
</P>
<P>
   Gum-slinger takes 2nd
</P>
<P>
   Champion bubble-blower Jimmy Bender isn't sore about being a
mere half-inch of gum away from victory at the Bubble Yum World
Series Blowout. The Parkview High School student competed last week
for a chance to win up to $35,000 in savings bonds and a spot in
``The Guinness Book of World Records'' at the national
bubble-blowing competition in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy faced off with his bubble-blowing challengers Tuesday. He
puffed a 7.5-inch bubble that set the pace for the competition. But
a kid from New Jersey later blew away the competition with an
8-inch bubble, which took first prize.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Jimmy said the experience was an interesting one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like in any major sporting event, it comes down to mere inches
between who wins and who takes second place,'' Jimmy said.
</P>
<P>
   News services contyributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
