<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5467 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-DIET-FADS-COX     11-01 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIET-FADS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Diet game: The skinny on quick fixes
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking for a quick fix? These diets are among the most popular,
but all have drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   LOW-CARBOHYDRATE, HIGH-PROTEIN DIET
</P>
<P>
   A diet with many variations, and known by many names _ Atkins
Plan, The Zone, Sugar Busters _ the premise is the same: By
drastically cutting down on carbohydrates, the body will burn up
stored fat because it's not getting the usual daily shot of energy
boosters (insulin) from the carbs and sugars found in breads,
potatoes, fruits and juices. People can, however, gorge themselves
on protein and fats. So those items normally banned on low-fat
diets _ bacon, steaks, cheese hamburgers, eggs, and peanut butter
sandwiches without the bread _ are on the menu. Low-carb diets have
been around for three decades but are now enjoying a resurgence of
popularity; four of the most popular low-carb diet books top the
paperback New York Times best-seller list this week.
</P>
<P>
   -- Risks: Although people can drop significant weight on these
diets, nutritionists and doctors warn that the diet can be
dangerous to your kidneys and heart, and it most likely won't be a
long-lasting solution. ``They will lose weight because protein does
not retain fluid as much as carbs do,'' says Franca Alphin,
dietician and administrative director of Duke University Diet and
Fitness Center. ``Therefore, when they go make the switch, it will
be an immediate weight loss, and they are eating fewer calories
also. But people tend to crave carbohydrates, and when they
eventually go back to adding carbs, they will regain weight.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Other concerns: The high-saturated fat content of the diet
can raise cholesterol levels and put people at risk for heart
disease; high-protein consumption over several weeks will stress
the kidneys. Eliminating fruits and vegetables cuts down on
cancer-fighting and fiber needed for proper digestion. Nausea, hair
loss, and muscle strain are also possible side effects, dieticians
say.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD COMBINING
</P>
<P>
   These diets not only dictate what foods to eat, but when they
should be eaten and whether certain foods can be eaten with other
foods at the same meal. Two best-selling books pushing this regimen
are from TV personalities Marilu Henner and Suzanne Somers. The
premise is that weight loss and maintenance can be controlled by
when the hormone insulin is released into the body after a meal.
This is also done by cutting down on carbohydrates and eating more
fats, proteins and nonstarchy vegetables. In a sequel to her
best-selling ``Get Skinny on Fabulous Foods,'' Somers suggestions
for ``metabolism reprogramming'' include: Eating fruit alone on an
empty stomach, do not eat proteins and fats with carbs and
eliminate all ``funky'' foods, such as alcohol and caffeine.
</P>
<P>
   -- Risks: Although Somers's second book is co-authored by a
physician, some dieticians still frown on the idea of combining
certain foods to lose weight because it's not based on any
scientific research. ``This one really gets me going,'' says Duke's
Alphin. ``Of course, if you eat simply one type of food and not in
combination, it is more easily digested.'' Page Love, an Atlanta
dietician with Nutrition Solutions, says this type of diet flies in
the face of what she would recommend for a dieting client. ``About
50 to 60 percent of diet should come from grains, vegetables and
fruits,'' Love said. ``People are setting themselves up for craving
if they don't have what they are used to eating together, such as
cereal and milk, a sandwich with actual bread. It's the only way of
getting in a healthy supply of food and meeting complex
carbohydrate needs.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Other concerns: Being low in fiber, the diets could cause
constipation.
</P>
<P>
   QUICK WEIGHT LOSS
</P>
<P>
   Pick up any women's magazine and you're sure to find a blurb
screaming: Eat X and Lose Y in Z Days. Whether it be grapefruits,
or cabbage soup or `gazpacho fat-burning miracle soup,''' these
diets allow a person to eat as much as they want of one item for
one week (some allow additional ``mini-meals.'') People can drop 5
to 10 pounds on such diets because the body drops significant water
and muscle mass. If not followed for more than one week, such diets
can provide the jump-start some people need to get motivated for a
longer-term healthy weight-loss plan.
</P>
<P>
   -- Risks: But too many see results on these quick-loss diets and
stay on them too long, dieticians say, leading to nutrient loss,
nausea, fatigue, and dizziness.
</P>
<P>
   -- Another danger: Revolving-door crash dieting can lower the
body's metabolism, meaning it takes more exercise to burn off fat.
``Every time you go on one of these, the ability to lose weight
decreases over time with each diet cycle,'' says Love of Nutrition
Solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``With quick muscle loss, you are dramatically decreasing
metabolism.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
