<HEADER>
A5472 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-COX-SOY02     11-01 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-SOY02 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DIETARY SOY SEEN REDUCING COLON CANCER RISK
 &HT;    Moving in Washington (w) and Lifestyle (l) categories.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Small amounts of soy protein, consumed daily for a
year by persons who had been diagnosed with colon cancer or
precancerous colon polyps, appeared to cause changes that reduced
the likelihood of recurrent tumors or polyps, researchers said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The experiment, which involved only 29 persons, was described as
a preliminary indication that soybean products may help in
preventing or treating colon cancer. A larger and longer trial
would be required to produce more definitive evidence a benefit,
said Maurice Bennink, the Michigan State University researcher who
directed the study.
</P>
<P>
   But the findings were greeted warmly at a scientific symposium
here on the role of soy in preventing and treating chronic disease
that was underwritten by the soybean industry.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier studies have produced still unconfirmed indications that
soybean products may be effective in preventing breast cancer,
prostate cancer, coronary heart disease and osteporosis.
</P>
<P>
   As the four-day symposium was getting underway, the American
Institute for Cancer Research warned against loading up on soy or
soy concentrates. The private, nonprofit organization noted that,
although evidence that soy might be valuable in warding off
prostate cancer appears to be encouraging, those findings also are
preliminary.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence of benefits in preventing breast cancer is even
more mixed, the institute said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's simply not possible as yet to draw any conclusions about
soy consumption and cancer prevention,'' but further research is
certainly warranted,'' said soyfoods expert Mark Messina, a former
researcher with the Diet and Cancer Branch of the National Cancer
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Bennink's study was described as the first human study
suggesting a benefit in preventing or treating colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, there was a change in the characteristics of the
colin lining which is consistent with a reduction in colon cancer
risk,'' Bennink said. ``It appeared that these people would be less
likely to develop cancer or polyps a second time,''
</P>
<P>
   Every day during the study, the10 women and 19 men consumed a
two-ounce supplement of soy isolate, the kind sold in health food
stores, Bennink said, and were asked not to change their diets in
other ways.
</P>
<P>
   In another study, scientists from Harvard University Medical
School transplanted human prostate cancer into the prostate glands
of mice and tested the effects of dietary soybean extracts.
</P>
<P>
   Jin-Rong Zhou said tumor growth was reduced from 50 to 60
percent in mice fed the soy extracts and metastasis to lungs and
other organs was from 40 to 50 percent less common than in animals
that were not fed the extracts.
</P>
<P>
   Zhou said the soybean substances appeared to block development
of blood vessels needed by the tumors and ``starve them to death.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
