<HEADER>
A5473 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-HEALTHY-DAY-COX     11-01 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHY-DAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TO YOUR HEALTH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News ServiceWhat if you're not trying to lose weight
<TEXT>
but just want to be healthy? What makes up a good, healthy day? An
adult woman needs about 2,000 calories per day; an adult man about
2,800 daily calories. Eat a variety of foods from the bottom up
from the Food Guide Pyramid: Six to 10 servings of bread, rice,
pasta or cereal; at least five servings of a combination of fruits
and vegetables; two to four servings of fruit; two to three
servings of milk and cheese group and two servings of meats,
poultry, eggs and other proteins. Consume fats, oils and sweets
sparingly.
<P>
   -- Rise and drink water: Begin the day with a glass of water.
And keep drinking water throughout the day. Most adults need 8 to
12 cups of water daily, but that can come from other beverages
(except caffeinated drinks, since caffeine actually depletes your
body of water) and some foods, such as lettuce, carrots, apples and
yogurt. Water is vital in carrying nutrients throughout your body
and in carrying waste products away. It helps soften stools,
cushion joints and protect body organs and tissues.
</P>
<P>
   -- Eat breakfast: No matter what your age, it's still the most
important meal of the day. After eight to 12 hours without a meal
or snack, your body needs replenishing of glucose, or blood sugar.
Your brain particularly needs a morning shot of glucose because it
has no stored reserves. Studies show breakfast eaters have more
strength and endurance and better concentration and problem-solving
ability.
</P>
<P>
   A bowl of whole-grain cereal with low-fat milk, a slice of toast
with jam, and a glass of citrus juice can provide 100 percent of
daily vitamin C needs, 33 percent of calcium, thiamin and
riboflavin and a good supply of fiber and iron.
</P>
<P>
   Skipping breakfast or any other meal won't necessarily help
dieters shed pounds. Eating revs up your metabolism. If you don't
eat, your metabolism slows down to conserve energy.
</P>
<P>
   -- Take time, make tracks: Park a distance from the subway
station or your workplace to get in a short walk. If you work a
desk job, get up and walk around every hour. Take the stairs up and
down, or at least alternate between the stairs and elevator.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in the late afternoon, break away for 15 minutes to
stroll a few blocks and get your body and brain stirred up. During
your day, fit in a total of at least 30 minutes of physical
activity. You don't have to go to a health club. Physical activity
includes walking briskly, cleaning house, gardening, raking leaves,
or washing the car.
</P>
<P>
   -- Snack well: Eat healthy snacks between meals, especially
between lunch and dinner.
</P>
<P>
   -- Rest: Get at least 8 hours of sleep. Avoid caffeine and
alcohol too close to bedtime. Alcoholic drinks may make you sleepy,
but studies show they actually contribute to a less restful night.
Also, try not to exercise late at night, as that may make it more
difficult to fall asleep.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, American
Dietetic Association, U.S. Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   For more information: To read more about the food pyramid and
the U.S. government's dietary recommendations for Americans: Web
site: www.pueblo.gsa.gov/cictext/food/food-pyramid/main.htm
</P>
<P>
   Or write: USDA, Center for Nutrition Policy and Promotion, 1120
20th St. NW. Suite 200 North Lobby, Washington, D.C. 20036
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
