<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5487 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HEALTH-CONSUMER-COX     11-01 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-CONSUMER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Airlines give breaks flying to a sick family member, but not
much
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If your out-of-town relative is gravely ill or seriously
injured, don't look to the friendly skies for too much compassion
when it comes to the cost of your ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Although some travelers are fortunate enough to stumble into a
sympathetic ticket booker, most airlines are taking a harder stance
on illness and bereavement policies.
</P>
<P>
   The industry does offer discounts for emergency flights _
typically, half of what a walk-up ticket would cost. And they often
allow the traveler to have an open-ended return date _ useful when
you don't fully know what the situation is at the other end of your
journey.
</P>
<P>
   But beware: Requirements to get these fares are getting stiffer.
For example, Delta's policy only allows bereavement discounts for
situations involving imminent death or life-threatening situations.
Stuff that doesn't qualify include terminally ill patients
traveling to a medical facility; people visiting terminally ill
relatives and emergencies that aren't life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   If you do qualify for a bereavement discount, be prepared to
have a physician's statement on letterhead stating that imminent
death is probable. Some airlines also require the address and phone
number of the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   And expect to wince from the price tag. For example, a
bereavement round-trip fare to Los Angeles on Delta Air Lines would
total more than $1,000, based on a Friday inquiry. That contrasts
with a 14-day advance fare of $350.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airlines are not that sympathetic with travelers in
difficult situations,'' said Mark Alan Reinke, of Carlson-Wagonlit
Travel in Atlanta. ``And although 50 percent off sounds like a lot,
when you get right down to it, it's no bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   Even airline representatives advise that travelers seek other
solutions than bereavement fares. Jackie Pate, Delta's spokeswoman,
recommended that you always compare the bereavement cost with that
of the airline's lowest priced ticket. AirTran Airlines doesn't
even offer bereavement tickets because its fares already are
discounted, said spokeswoman Cara Maruskin.
</P>
<P>
   So what else can a traveler do, especially when time is of the
essence? Start with a travel agent, so you get a more comprehensive
view of the industry's prices. In the case of the Los Angeles fare,
for example, while Delta's bereavement fare hovered at $1,000,
Frontier Airlines offered on the same day a walk-up fare of $410,
with a change in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   And travel agents will also know about quirky changes in the
market. America West Airlines was also offering a $202 round-trip
special to LA on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   There are also other ways to beat back the costs if you have a
little bit of flexibility. For example, ask your travel agent if it
would be cheaper to book two flights _ on even two different
airlines _ to get to your destination. For example, it might be
cheaper to fly to Chicago on one airline, and then fly from Chicago
to Minneapolis on another.
</P>
<P>
   It is also worth checking the Internet if you've got a little
time. Log on to airline websites, which often run cut-rate
specials. Delta (www.delta-air.com) posts its cut-rate flights on
Wednesday for the following weekend. And check out other websites,
like www.priceline.com, that feature so-called ``distressed
inventory'' _ flights that aren't booked to capacity. If you don't
mind out of the way stop-overs, twin-engine airplanes and an
itinerary that's not revealed until you buy the ticket, it might be
the perfect ride.
</P>
<P>
   Also, if you'll need to fly often to see your ailing relative,
buy several tickets in advance with penalty clauses. Often, this is
a cheaper alternative than waiting until the last minute, with the
traveler paying only a $50 to $75 penalty for changing dates.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers can also use a trick known in the business world. If
you already hold a ticket for a flight days or weeks in advance of
the trip, you can usually redeem it at the airport to fly standby
on earlier flights.
</P>
<P>
   Those with thousands of frequent flyer miles can sometimes
finagle a free ticket quickly. That's because instead of being
merely ``self-loading cargo'' (as travelers are fondly referred to
by the industry), you move into the realm of being a valued
customer.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if you call the airline and find the customer service
representative isn't willing to work with you, thank them, ask for
a supervisor or call back to get someone else. Experts say the
market is wildly subjective and wink-wink deals are still common,
if you hit the right sympathetic soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't any magic answers to getting a reasonable fare,''
said Carole Barrett, owner of the Art of Travel. ``And the airlines
haven't done anything to make it easier for consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
