<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5490 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MORTGAGES-COX     11-01 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORTGAGES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Change in interest rates reflected in fewer number of mortgages
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One little percentage point can turn feast to famine
in the mortgage lending business.
</P>
<P>
   Since the average home-loan interest rates for metro Atlanta
jumped in June from the 6-percent range into the 7-percent range,
mortgage lenders have watched a big hunk of their business
disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Now, total mortgage applications _ new-home loans and
refinancings _ are down. They dropped 59 percent in the third week
of October, compared with the same period a year ago, according to
the Mortgage Bankers Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The refinance segment of our business has dropped from
probably 50 percent the first half of the year to 10 percent now,''
said Brooks Campbell, vice president of MetroFirst Mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   The mortgage loan industry is coming down from a ``tremendous
spurt of activity,'' said Fannie Mae economist Robert D. Barr.
</P>
<P>
   Loan originations are expected to drop 16 percent in 1999,
ending the year at $1.32 trillion, compared with a record-breaking
$1.45 trillion in 1998. He forecasts loan originations will fall
under $1 trillion for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   An end-of-summer slowdown in relocations also fed the drop-off
in the loan business, said Bob Slocum, senior vice president at
Premier Lending.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of all this, lenders have two ways to maintain
profits. They can cut prices or trim operating costs.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, there are spotty reports of layoffs, said Julia
Hiler-Barrette, executive vice president of Sunshine Mortgage and
current president of the Mortgage Bankers Association of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen and experienced a slowdown, with refinancings
having gone away and the (new-home-loan origination) market
slowing. It is true that people have been laid off ... ,'' she
said. ``It is also true that we have shifted staffing around to
busier areas like recording deeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the Bureau of Labor Statistics expects the number of
jobs in the industry to decrease from 375,000 to 300,000.
</P>
<P>
   When loan volume is down, mortgage loan employees make less
money in commissions.
</P>
<P>
   The loan originator then has to try harder, Slocum said. ``You
have to be aggressive to keep the business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spend more time bonding with customers, giving them special
attention, because it is very hard to win loans on the best rate
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Slocum, most loan originators can adjust pricing no
more than 1/2 percent in closing costs and 1/8 percent in the loan
rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take the difference between making a 6 1/2 percent loan and a
7 3/4 loan, last year and now,'' he said. ``Now, you have to price
more aggressively, but, at the same time, you are less likely to
make as much money per loan.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Harte writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 1752EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
