<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers' 'soft' approach not working, but all news not bad
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The signs of a team in search of a presence could be
found on Petr Buzek's lower lip Monday. It was split, precisely
where it was met by a Kelly Buchberger elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost lost a tooth,'' the Thrashers' rookie defenseman
said, smiling nonetheless. ``It was a physical practice. That's
good. I like it. We need it. We need to toughen up a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten games into the season, a bell appeared to have sounded
before the Thrashers' practice Monday at the Duluth IceForum. The
words from coach Curt Fraser came louder, the stick slamming came
more frequently, than in some time. Another home loss will do that
to a coach, particularly when it appeared that every goal was
caused by a defensive lapse.
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Damian Rhodes might not have been in Vezina form in
Sunday's 6-4 loss to Ottawa, but the Senators found the slot area
in front of him as comfortable as a park bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought defense would be a strength of ours,'' Fraser said.
``I think it's still going to be. But maybe we tried to do too much
early, and we got our lunch fed to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering their second month, the Thrashers are 2-6-2 with a
regulation tie. It's not a great record, but it's not terrible,
considering that they're still under warranty and that the schedule
has ranked among the league's toughest. The losses have come to New
Jersey, Detroit, New York Rangers, Colorado, Toronto and Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   What has been disturbing to the coaching staff and general
manager Don Waddell are repeated mistakes in the defensive zone and
at times, such as Sunday, a lack of physical presence in front.
Fraser used the word ``soft'' after the Ottawa game
</P>
<P>
   Waddell has made several minor changes to the team already,
including Monday's acquisition of rugged winger Eric Bertrand from
New Jersey. But in terms of serious roster analysis, he is sticking
to his plan to break the season into 20-game segments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, I'm happy with the direction we're going in,''
Waddell said. ``We could have had another one or two wins, but,
hopefully, by the way we've lost some of the games, we'll use it as
a learning experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is, how big is the learning curve for the several
veterans on the roster? When Waddell put this team together,
largely through the expansion draft, he thought that he was getting
a team that would be fairly solid in its own zone. It hasn't always
been the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the veteran players have to be better, no doubt about
that,'' he said. ``The young players have been the bright spots;
the older players need to pick it up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers have given up 38 goals in 10 games for a
league-worst 3.80 average. Particularly disturbing to Fraser was
the timing of Sunday's goals by Ottawa: The Senators scored 1:12
into the first period, once with 1:11 left in the period, twice in
the first 4:39 of the second and again 18 seconds into the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk a lot of about your first shift, your last shift, the
first shift after a goal,'' Fraser said. ``We may have to expand
that to the first five minutes, the last five minutes and the last
five after a goal.''
</P>
<P>
   As to his series of lectures Monday, the coach said, ``We're
working on our shortcoming. Hopefully, we can shore things up, but
it's going to take time. . . . You can't teach offense. You have a
50-goal scorer and a 20-goal a scorer and a 10-goal scorer. But
everybody can play good defense. It just takes hard work, and you
have to be willing to be physical. But we've gotten away from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
