<SLUG> BC-SCI-MEDICAL-GUIDELINES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS LAPSES ON MEDICAL GUIDELINES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich.)   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By MARCIA SHERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is hard to imagine the wizards of ``E.R.'' stopping to
consult the latest practice guidelines before rushing to deliver a
baby or cracking open a dying patient's chest. But for real-life
practitioners, staying up to date with medical science increasingly
means staying abreast of such guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines are meant to improve medical care by codifying
what panels of experts deem to be best practices in a given field;
there are hundreds of them, the American Medical Association says.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that many doctors are unaware of any number of
guidelines, and those who read them often fail or refuse to adopt
their recommendations, according to a study published last month in
The Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which reviewed 120 physician surveys spanning the
last 30 years, reached these conclusions:
</P>
<P>
   _ At any given time, at least 10 percent of doctors are unaware
of a particular guideline that pertains to their practice.
</P>
<P>
   _ At least 10 percent more, while probably aware of the
guideline, are not familiar enough with its specifics to be able to
follow it correctly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Yet another significant group knows the guideline but refuses
to follow it for a variety of reasons. For example, the study said,
doctors sometimes decline to order recommended tests that they
believe will expose patients to unjustifiable risks. A persistent
minority of doctors resent what they often call a ``cookbook''
approach to patient care.
</P>
<P>
   _ Guidelines for preventive medicine are often disregarded
because doctors do not think their advice will be taken seriously.
Physicians place little faith in studies that show a small but
important minority benefiting from such advice.
</P>
<P>
   _ And patients may resent clinical guidelines because the
treatments recommended may be expensive or uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too often, the creators of medical guidelines have a `Field of
Dreams' mentality,'' the study's author, Dr. Michael Cabana, a
pediatrician at the University of Michigan, said in an interview.
``They think, `If you develop it, they _ the average practitioner _
will come.' It just doesn't work that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than just publishing guidelines and hoping doctors will
notice them, a more aggressive approach may be warranted, he said.
Direct mailing of guidelines has been successful in some
situations.
</P>
<P>
   Cabana recommends an even more unorthodox tactic. It may be
possible for better-informed patients to bring their doctors up to
date with changes. ``I often learn about a new therapy from a
patient who read about it before I got there,'' he said. Now the
Federal Agency for Health Care Policy and Research is compiling
clinical guidelines online at a Web site (www.guideline.gov) where
more than 3,500 will be available in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be worried if my own physician blindly followed
clinical guidelines,'' Cabana said. ``But I would also be worried
if my physician never followed guidelines or, worse, was unaware of
them. The critical use of a recommendation is the key.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
