</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FLORIDA-PANTHERS-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS RESCUE SQUAD COMES TO AID OF FLORIDA PANTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By MARK DERR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. _ With its Roman nose, gray-tinted coat and
lethal jaws, the Florida panther was once a figure of mythological
power that roamed throughout the southeastern United States. But in
the last century, hunting and development isolated the panther in
the vast undeveloped swamps and forests of South Florida, and by
1967, when the cats were listed as endangered, there were barely 30
of them left.
</P>
<P>
   Although they continued to reproduce, evidence mounted that the
big, solitary cats _ males weigh 130 to 140 pounds; females, 80 to
90 pounds _ had become dangerously inbred. With kinked tails and
cowlicks, recessive traits manifested in no other subspecies, the
panthers were vulnerable to disease and parasitism and prone to
heart abnormalities. Most of the males were cryptorchid, meaning
one or both testicles had failed to descend, and had an
extraordinarily high percentage of malformed sperm, which pointed
toward growing fertility problems.
</P>
<P>
   But now the Florida panther (Puma concolor coryi), a subspecies
of the cougar, is on the verge of a remarkable comeback. In a bold
effort to restore genetic diversity to the panther, wildlife
biologists four years ago imported a handful of females from a
closely related subspecies, the Texas cougar. Uprooted from the
arid hills of West Texas, three of the imports have died, but the
remaining five adapted to swamp life and have each given birth to
at least one litter of kittens.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the original imports have produced 17 kittens. Several
of those kittens have now produced as many as seven
second-generation hybrids, bringing the total population to 50 to
70 adults and kittens. In at least one instance, a first-generation
male hybrid mated with an unrelated Texas female and a
first-generation hybrid female, according to Darrell Land, panther
section leader for the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The hybrid kittens do not have cowlicks or kinked tails, and
they appear more robust than their pure cousins. Biologists have
yet to conduct biomedical tests to see whether other negative
effects of inbreeding have vanished, but the prognosis is
promising.
</P>
<P>
   But in the arcane politics of the Florida panther, success also
breeds debate. Dr. David Maehr, assistant professor of forestry at
the University of Kentucky and former project leader of the
recovery effort, frets that the crossbreeding has gone so far that
it ``is spiraling out of control.'' The Florida panther's unique
physical and behavioral characteristics could be lost, he says, if
its genetic makeup becomes dominated by the slightly larger,
browner and flatter-nosed Texas cougars. He urges immediate removal
of all Texas cougars and their offspring by first generation
hybrids.
</P>
<P>
   Other biologists dismiss such concerns. Dr. Stephen O'Brien,
chief of the National Cancer Institute's genomic diversity
laboratory, said the various subspecies of puma _ also called
mountain lions, panthers, catamounts and cougars _ were
indistinguishable genetically and so there was no cause for alarm.
O'Brien, who is preparing to conduct DNA analysis of the hybrids,
said of the Texas cougars: ``Removing the cats is a concession to
purists. I don't think it's necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   It was O'Brien who paved the way for the revitalization program.
In the late 1980s, he showed in genetic studies that historically
the puma was a single, unbroken population, ranging from northern
Canada to Tierra del Fuego and mating regularly across subspecies.
He also documented that a handful of Florida panthers in Everglades
National Park were the descendants of hybrids released by a private
collector, with the consent of the park superintendent, between
1956 and 1966. Those cats, O'Brien said, were derived from crosses
the collector had made between Florida panthers and pumas from
Costa Rica in the 1940s and 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   The descendants of those hybrids, which had mingled freely with
Florida panthers, showed no signs of the ``inbreeding depression''
threatening their ``pure'' cousins in nearby Big Cypress Swamp.
Their health, O'Brien said, provided crucial evidence that genetic
supplementation through crossbreeding could work and that the
differences between the Florida panther and other pumas were
largely the ``consequences of inbreeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on genetic and demographic studies, the IUCN (World
Conservation Union) Conservation Breeding Specialty Group, led by
Dr. Ulysses Seal, bluntly warned in 1989 and again in 1992 that
without human intervention, the Florida panther would probably be
extinct before 2055. Finally responding to the alarm, the Florida
Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission drew up a plan for
genetic enhancement using Texas cougars, because their historic
range had abutted that of the Florida panther.
</P>
<P>
   The plan called for introducing eight cougars from West Texas
and leaving them in place until each had produced two breeding
offspring _ enough to increase genetic variability within the
Florida panther population by 20 percent _ and then removing them.
Females were selected because of the belief that they would
acclimate without conflict, whereas males will fight to the death
over territory.
</P>
<P>
   Geneticists calculated that the influx of new genetic material
from those crossbreedings would equal what had occurred naturally
in the past and would correct problems resulting from inbreeding
without obscuring whatever evolutionary adaptations the Florida
panther had made to its wet, hot and humid home. Laying aside their
often rancorous debate over how best to preserve the Florida
panther, state and federal wildlife officials, environmentalists
and independent scientists endorsed the proposal, and in 1995 the
eight cats were brought from Texas and released.
</P>
<P>
   Participants at a workshop held last June in Gainesville, Fla.,
to review the recovery project agreed that the most pressing issue
now was allowing the Florida panther population to expand in size,
to as many as 500 individuals, and in geographic distribution.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the past two years, several males have moved north of the Big
Cypress Swamp across the Caloosahatchee River, west of Lake
Okeechobee, but they have no mates and efforts to find a place to
establish another reproducing population have so far fallen prey to
human concerns about living close to a large predator.
</P>
<P>
   Without those demographic changes, the South Florida cats remain
at risk from epidemics and natural catastrophes. They will also
require infusions of new genes every two decades or so, something
Land of the wildlife commission hopes can be accomplished with new
reproductive technology to avoid repeatedly relocating pumas.
</P>
<P>
   According to Seal, even with those caveats, the Florida panther
program ``shows you can outbreed to help isolated populations of
other animals, like tigers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
