<HEADER>
A5507 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-MENINGITIS-965(2T     11-01 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MENINGITIS-965(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRONT LINE IN MENINGITIS CAMPAIGN: FRESHMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Calif., Mich., Mass.)  (The Science Times) 
(lb) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN, M.D.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the infectious diseases that afflict Americans,
meningitis ranks nowhere near the top. But meningococci, the
bacteria that are a cause of both meningitis and other serious
health problems, bring chaos disproportionate to the low case
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The infection can progress with devastating rapidity even under
the best of medical care; what starts as a mild flulike infection
can kill an otherwise healthy person in hours. A single case of
meningococcal meningitis can prompt emergency public health drills
to identify the scores of people with whom the victim came in
contact before falling ill, so that each can be given immediate
antibiotic therapy. The accompanying media attention intensifies
the air of panic.
</P>
<P>
   That is why a federal health advisory panel has urged the
520,000 college freshmen who live in dormitories to consider
rolling up their sleeves to get the meningococcal vaccine ahead of
the peak season, November through January _ even though it is not
expected to prevent much more than a couple of dozen cases.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, which advises the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention on immunization practices, called on universities and
health professionals last month to tell college freshmen and their
parents about the availability of a well-established vaccine that
is safe and effective against most subtypes of the bacteria that
affect college-age Americans.
</P>
<P>
   (The vaccine is not recommended for the general population,
because of the low incidence of infection, and it is not effective
against the subtype of bacteria that causes most cases among
infants and occasional cases in other age groups.)
</P>
<P>
   Each year in the United States, there are about 3,000 cases of
meningococcal infection, including 300 deaths. Of the total, about
125 to 175 cases occur among college students, including 15 to 20
deaths. By contrast, pneumonia and influenza killed 86,449
Americans in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But while the overall meningococcal rates are low, they have
been rising among young adults _ from one to more than two per
100,000 people aged 15 to 24, since 1991. Although the centers
started keeping statistics on college students only last year,
outbreaks seem to have been rising in this group as well.
</P>
<P>
   And recent studies have found that freshmen living in
dormitories have six times as much risk of developing meningococcal
infections as students overall.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists do not know why. The centers recently conducted an
extensive survey, said Dr. Nancy Rosenstein, an expert there in the
epidemiology of meningococcal infections, but could not come up
with an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not smoking, drinking, attending bars or anything else
we asked about,'' Rosenstein said. ``It may have something to do
with the difference in the behavior of freshmen living in
dormitories compared to other groups of students, and despite our
study we were not able to identify what that was.''
</P>
<P>
   Freshmen live in close quarters, and Rosenstein noted that in
homes where someone has a meningococcal infection, the risk of
someone else's being stricken is 500 times that of the general
population.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, meningococcal infection was a serious problem for the
military until 1970, when the rate was 25 per 100,000, with most
cases occurring in the recruits' initial training camps. Since
1971, thanks to routine immunizations, the rate has plummeted _ to
0.51 per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts speculate that the lower rates among upperclassmen
may relate to the buildup of immune defenses against the bacteria,
particularly the diversity of subtypes that students bring with
them from homes in different geographic areas.
</P>
<P>
   Many people have meningococci in their throats yet do not become
ill. The bacteria are spread through the air in respiratory
droplets. They also can be spread by direct contact _ by kissing,
for example, or by sharing cigarettes or drinking glasses. From
seven to 10 days after exposure, a person can come down with a
flulike illness that starts with mild, nonspecific symptoms like
fever, sore throat, headache, rash, nausea, vomiting and malaise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a hard disease to diagnose in its early stages,'' said
Dr. James Turner, who heads the student health center at the
University of Virginia and is chairman of the American College
Health Association's task force on diseases that can be prevented
by vaccines.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids can walk into your office with a mild headache and
a low-grade fever, and look like they have the flu, just like the
other 50 to 60 people you saw that day,'' Turner said. ``Then they
can go home and slip into a coma and shock within hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Of those who develop meningococcal infections, 13 percent die,
according to the centers _ a rate rivaled by few other types of
infections in the United States. And about 15 percent of survivors
develop permanent brain damage, which may include hearing loss and
learning disability.
</P>
<P>
   For an idea of how savage this infection can be, consider
Melanie Benn. On the day before Christmas in 1995, Ms. Benn, then
an 18-year-old student at Humboldt State University in Arcata,
Calif., woke up at her home in San Diego feeling as if she were
coming down with the flu. She felt worse as the day went on. By the
time she arrived in the emergency room on Christmas Eve, she was in
shock.
</P>
<P>
   Meningococci destroyed her kidneys and caused gangrene as the
bacteria spread to her arms and legs. Doctors had to amputate all
four limbs. She required kidney dialysis treatments for a year.
Then her father donated a kidney in successful transplant surgery.
Her medical costs have exceeded $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Benn, who graduated from San Diego State University in May,
plans to use her training in psychology to counsel others about
disabilities.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The federal panel's recommendation for meningococcal vaccine
grows out of one that the American College Health Association made
in 1997. Since then, more than 70 colleges and universities have
included information about meningococcal vaccine and other
immunizations in the packets they send to students announcing their
acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday, more than 2,000 students turned up at a
vaccination clinic at the University of Virginia that Turner said
was modeled after clinics at the University of Pennsylvania and
Princeton. The clinic was part of a strategy, developed long before
the federal panel's recommendation, that has resulted in the
immunization of at least a third of the university's 12,440
undergraduates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got embroiled in this,'' Turner said, ``because we had five
nonfatal cases in 1995-96; each case occurred at an interval of
about three or four months. With each succeeding case the level of
panic and hysteria grew and grew. We had parents and students
concerned. We had family physicians calling in prescriptions for
antibiotics over the phone and giving vaccine over holiday
breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   The university's strategy was to appeal not just to students _
who tend to think they are invulnerable _ but to their parents.
After advertising the clinic during student orientation in the
summer, Turner reinforced its importance in a letter early last
month to every parent. And since the vaccine costs $65 or so per
shot, the university timed the clinic to be three days after
parents' weekend, in hopes that parents would pick up the tab.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, this was an extraordinarily successful campaign,''
Turner said. ``We created such a demand that they ran out of time
and vaccine, so we are going to repeat it on Wednesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia is hardly alone. At Michigan State University on Oct.
9, a student entered a hospital with meningococcal infection. This
was the university's fourth case since late 1996, and two of the
others had been fatal. On Oct. 11, Michigan State officials
recommended vaccinations, and, through last Friday, 16,000 of the
university's 55,000 students and faculty members had received a
free meningococcal shot.
</P>
<P>
   But other colleges are not rushing into a vaccination program.
The University of Massachusetts, for example, has not recommended
the vaccine, is working out the logistics of changing its policy,
and has not been flooded with calls about it, a spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine is about 85 percent effective against four subtypes
of meningococci, accounting for about two-thirds of the cases among
18-to-23-year-olds. Because such protection lasts more than three
years, a booster is not needed while a student is still in college.
</P>
<P>
   If used widely among college students, the vaccine is expected
to prevent from 14 to 26 cases and up to three deaths from
meningococci each year. The vaccine's side effects are minimal.
Some recipients may develop a mild fever and have pain and redness
at the site of injection for one to two days after the shot.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenstein of the CDC says the question parents most often ask
her is whether the vaccine can cause meningococcal infections. The
answer, she says, is no. ``It is impossible, because the vaccine is
made from only the outside of the bacteria,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Information about meningococcal vaccinations is posted on the
Web site of the American College of Health Associations
(www.acha.org). CDC plans to put the full version of the
recommendation, when it is completed in about two months, on its
Web site (www.cdc.gov).
</P>
<P>
   What about groups other than college freshmen? Rosenstein says
the centers are considering new studies of the incidence of
meningococcal infections among summer campers, preparatory school
students, prisoners and other groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
