<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITH-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S MAKE SURE MEXICAN TRUCKS ARE SAFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JACK SMITH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eleven years ago, on a pleasant October day, I was cruising
eastward on Interstate 30 near Greenville in Northeast Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly there was trouble ahead. A pickup and a larger truck
had collided. I braked like crazy, going from 70 mph to a dead stop
as fast as my little Toyota Corolla would permit.
</P>
<P>
   I barely avoided hitting the rear of an 18-wheeler that also had
braked hard for the accident. But in the next split second, another
18-wheeler _ which I never saw coming _ creamed me from behind.
</P>
<P>
   My 150-pound frame was rocked by a stunningly powerful jolt from
the truck and its cargo of South Texas produce, which together
totaled about 80,000 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old truck driver emerged from his vehicle literally
shaking, fearful he had killed me. My car was history, the rear
squeezed like an accordion. The trucker, unable to stop in time,
had popped me at 50 mph. I was get-down-on-my-knees grateful to
come out of that accident with an aching neck and back as my only
ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since that crash, I've been extra-paranoid about big trucks
and their capability of rearranging my innards. I therefore have
read with alarm in recent weeks about the potential for waves of
reportedly unsafe Mexican trucks to begin hauling commercial cargo
throughout the Unites beginning Jan. 1, under provisions of
the North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has indicated that he will indefinitely delay
this vehicular onslaught from south of the border because of grave
doubts as to whether the trucks are safe. Let's hope he sticks by
that.
</P>
<P>
   Trucks from Mexico are now permitted only in very limited areas
along the U.S.-Mexico border. These trucks should be prevented from
entering other parts of the United States until there is a strong
assurance that they are safe, and only after Congress has
appropriated more money to greatly increase the already thin ranks
of truck safety inspectors along the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely have a concern over the safety of the trucks,''
said Bill Munk, a captain in the traffic law enforcement division
of the Texas Department of Public Safety.
</P>
<P>
   There already are safety concerns about the growing numbers of
U.S. trucks on the road. There should be a magnified safety concern
for Mexican trucks, many of which are older and in poorer condition
than the average U.S. truck.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has less rigorous safety standards for both trucks and
drivers than the United States does, according to testimony at a
recent National Transportation Safety Board hearing in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   A report by the U.S. inspector general's office states that
fewer than 1 percent of the 3.9 million Mexican trucks that cross
the border each year are inspected for safety. Among Mexican trucks
inspected in 1997 at Texas border checkpoints, nearly half were so
unsafe that they were ordered off the road or back to Mexico, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Truck safety issues should particularly concern Fort
Worth-Dallas residents and other Texans who frequently drive on
Interstate 35. This road is increasingly congested by all kinds of
vehicles, including escalating numbers of trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 3 million additional Mexican trucks might enter the United
States every year under NAFTA. And the most favored route for these
trucks would be up I-35 from Laredo into and-or through Fort
Worth-Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Truck traffic on the entire 1,500 miles of I-35 _ from Laredo to
Duluth, Minn. _ is expected to grow by a staggering 85 percent by
2025, according to a new study done by a Kansas City, Mo., firm.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate 35W _ the portion that goes through Fort Worth _ will
require 16 lanes to handle the expected growth in urban and truck
traffic in Fort Worth over the next 25 years, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   There's already been a huge increase in commercial truck
traffic. From 1990 to 1997, for example, the number of large trucks
traveling on I-35W at its juncture with Interstate 20 in south Fort
Worth spiraled from 4,700 to 8,837 trucks daily _ a huge 88 percent
increase in just seven years, Texas Department of Transportation
figures show.
</P>
<P>
   There's serious talk now about creating a series of ``truck
byways'' on I-35 _ separate lanes for trucks through busy areas.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, officials in Houston are discussing dividing freeways
into separate truck and car lanes.
</P>
<P>
   There is legislation pending in Congress that could produce
substantial increases in funding for truck safety, including money
to hire more inspectors on the U.S.-Mexico border. That's greatly
needed.
</P>
<P>
   I have great admiration for the skills and stamina of
professional truck drivers in both the United States and Mexico.
And I'm not an opponent of NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
   But memories of the jolting blow I suffered 11 years ago from
that 18-wheeler in Northeast Texas are still fresh in my mind.
</P>
<P>
   Let's keep those Mexican trucks down south until we're sure they
won't pose a major safety threat. I don't want to become road kill
in the name of free trade.
</P>
<P>
   (Jack Z. Smith is an editorial writer and columnist for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. He can be reached at
jzsmith(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7724. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
