<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   EGYPTAIR _ QUONSET POINT, R.I. _ The Coast Guard kept up a grim
search for survivors in the choppy waters off Nantucket Island
early today as hope dwindled of finding anyone alive from EgyptAir
Flight 990. Navy divers and a salvage ship are expected to arrive
off the Massachusetts coast by tonight to help in the search for
debris. While relatives mourned the 217 passengers and crew
members, investigators began the painstaking task of figuring out
what caused the jetliner to plummet into the sea from 33,000 feet
early Sunday.(Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitutioin).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   EGYPTAIR-EGYPT _ CAIRO _ As grief-stricken friends and relatives
of passengers aboard EgyptAir flight 990 prepare to leave here for
New York today, they recount through tears their last words with
loved ones. Developing. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). 25
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS-MILCRASHES _ The F-18 jet fighter crash that killed two
members of the Navy's Blue Angels demonstration team last week is
among more than 100 aviation incidents linked to military air shows
since 1972. Never-before released computer records show a
disproportionate number of those incidents _ 46 _ were major
accidents, killing at least 97 people and causing more than a
quarter of a billion dollars in damages. Among the dead were at
least six civilians, one described by Navy records as an adolescent
ejected from a parked aircraft at an airshow in Maryland in 1980.
Seeking comment on whether the crashes raise questions about using
demonstration teams for recruitment purposes. (Carollo, Dayton
Daily News). 20.
</P>
<P>
   PANDAS _ ATLANTA _ Panda countdown for their arrival in Atlanta
later this week begins. What's happening to the pandas: the
itinerary, a look at the new panda house. (Hendrick, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS. 32.
</P>
<P>
   WALMART-WWF _ ATLANTA _ Wal-Mart stores have pulled action
figures of WWF wrestling star Al Snow, whose prop of a woman's head
has caused controversy. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-MISHAP _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush suffered
some minor injuries while diving to avoid a truck while jogging.
Bush's press secretary says he was treated at the scene for minor
bruises to his leg and hip and that he returned home. She says he
is traveling to New Hampshire this afternoon. A Texas Department of
Public Safety agent who was with him is hospitalized. (Herman,
Austin American-Statesman) 8.
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ Campaign 2000 has witnessed an unexpected event:
the re-emergence of a formerly taboo term: liberalism. (Baxter,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SOY _ WASHINGTON _ Soybean growers and processors, already
basking in FDA approval of their claim that soybean products reduce
cholesterol, heard more good news Monday _ that dietary soy protein
appears to reduce the likelihood of recurrent tumors in persons who
have colon cancer or precancerous colon polyps. A study by Michigan
State University scientists suggesting the protective effect was
described at an industry-financed symposium on the role of soy in
preventing chronic disease. (Nesmith, Cox News Service)
</P>
