<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5512 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     11-01 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERVIEWS: A SOURCE OF INFORMATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The problem with TV sports reporter Jim Gray's controversial
interview with Pete Rose, a reader informed me the other day, was
that Gray was glorifying himself rather than attempting to elicit
information from Rose.
</P>
<P>
   The reader couldn't be more correct. If Gray was looking for
information, there were lots of questions he could have asked
baseball's all-time hit leader. The one question that was
guaranteed NOT to elicit information from Rose was the one that
Gray asked. And asked. And asked.
</P>
<P>
   Rose would have happily talked all night long about his many
accomplishments as a ballplayer, but he had no intention of
discussing the gambling allegations that led to his 1989 suspension
from major-league baseball. He had no intention of confessing that
he gambled on baseball games _ the most serious charge against him
_ and he certainly had no intention of apologizing for a
transgression that he insists he didn't commit.
</P>
<P>
   That line of questioning was going nowhere _ and Gray surely
knew that from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the reader who responded to my Friday column about
the interview by pointing out the self-promotional nature of Gray's
questions was one of many baseball fans who weren't taken in by
Gray's tough-interviewer shtick. Let's hope that they weren't taken
in by Rose's disingenuous stonewalling, either.
</P>
<P>
   But all this misses an important point. Those of us who have
always believed that the purpose of an interview is to elicit
information are clearly barking up the wrong tree _ at least where
TV interviews are concerned.
</P>
<P>
   As annoying as Gray's approach to the Rose interview may have
been to some viewers, it was hardly an aberration.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of a television interview nowadays is confrontation. If
a tidbit of information should happen to emerge amid the verbal
jousting, well, that's an unexpected bonus.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time, I seem to recall, when bona fide journalists
such as Edward R. Murrow and Walter Cronkite would conduct
interviews as if they were actually interested in the person they
were interviewing. They wouldn't hesitate to ask tough questions,
if such questions were warranted, but they would ask them in a way
that communicated a certain level of respect for the interviewee _
and for the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an example. After Frank Sinatra died, CBS reran an
hourlong special from the 1960s in which Cronkite interviewed ol'
Blue Eyes about his life and his music. Cronkite was respectful
without being even slightly obsequious, and Frank was unusually
forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to ask Sinatra the inevitable question about
allegations of
</P>
<P>
   mob connections, Cronkite asked it in such a subtle and
dignified way that it didn't offend his subject _ and yet left no
doubt in the viewer's mind that Cronkite was putting Sinatra on the
spot.
</P>
<P>
   Can you imagine one of today's TV hotshots confronting Sinatra _
or trying to _ on the mob issue? Sinatra would probably reply with
a string of unprintables and storm off the set. Matt Lauer or
whoever would achieve the electrifying confrontation he was hoping
for, and he'd snare some shrieking headlines in the tabloids _ but
to what benefit for the viewer?
</P>
<P>
   Would we know any more about Sinatra than we did before the
sparks started flying?
</P>
<P>
   The way Cronkite handled the situation, we actually gained some
insight into Sinatra's thoughts and feelings about a highly
sensitive subject.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the new interviewing style is just another product of the
much-discussed decline of civility in our society. Or maybe it has
nothing to do with anything except the frenzy to rack up TV ratings
_ and big ratings most often follow fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it's unfortunate that a once civilized and
illuminating format, the TV interview, has degenerated into nothing
more than a daily showcase for self-aggrandizing media stars to
indulge their mammoth egos at the expense of the
information-starved public.
</P>
<P>
   And if you think it's bad now, it's about to get worse. Bryant
Gumbel has a new morning show on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
