<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5514 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-GUMBEL-TEX     11-01 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GUMBEL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN BRYANT GUMBEL RISE AND SHINE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good Morning America has taken on an embattled atmosphere; this
must be what it's like to be reading a TelePrompTer with a gun to
your head. Co-hosts Diane Sawyer and Charlie Gibson no longer look
like they want to be where they are, and would make a run for it if
there were someplace they could run to.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be NBC's Today, where hosts Katie Couric and Matt
Lauer are sitting awfully pretty, putting up huge ratings with a
show that's as transparently superficial as the new and
bubbleheaded Later Today that it spawned.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder it has taken the return of the exceptionally cranky,
annoyingly whiny, pompous, arrogant, humorless Bryant Gumbel to
make us care about morning television again.
</P>
<P>
   Since signing up as the host for the revamped CBS morning show,
which began Monday, Gumbel has become the equivalent of the doomed
lab frog _ a much-dissected specimen for critics and
industry-watchers who consider Gumbel's interviewing skills without
peer but compare his warmth to that of a Minnesota winter.
</P>
<P>
   I've always been a Gumbel fan, blaming in part his low scores
for humility, humanity, tact and grinning banter on a society that,
by and large, still reads overconfidence in African-American men as
how-dare-he arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   That said, there is a coldness about Gumbel in person, a feeling
that you're beneath him, a feeling that whatever question you ask
is a dumb one and whatever answer you give is the wrong one. Sad to
say, all that ult seeps through on air.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, time has moved on without him, and not in his favor.
Morning television may have begun as an extension of hard-news
programs, designed to get early risers caught up with the world _ I
mean, Walter Cronkite was the first host of the CBS show in 1954.
That the current CBS morning program ended its run Monday with Mark
McEwen, a weatherman by trade, says something, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Over time, the a.m. programs morphed into a news-you-can-use
mixture of information and entertainment, hosted by charming,
breezy, awfully good-looking personalities intent not on informing
us as much as comforting us.
</P>
<P>
   Now, ABC's GMA and CBS' Early Show, have even duplicated Today's
``window to the world'' idea, where a glass window looking onto the
studio allows gawkers to wave signs screaming ``We Luv U.'' Morning
television has become nothing more than a New York City attraction,
something to put on the list of tourist things to do, like visiting
the Bronx Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to why Gumbel, who vowed never to return to
morning television after 15 years of dragging himself out of bed
for Today, would subject himself to such slumming. Gumbel never
seemed all that comfortable at Today, particularly when he had to
venture outside to actually talk to people. (Though Couric seemed
sincerely interested or at least accepting of this part of her job,
you could tell Gumbel couldn't care less.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gumbel says he's returning to ``a wonderful opportunity''
and is royally pumped by the idea of starting an operation from
scratch. But the real reason is that after CBS canned his
prime-time newsmagazine, Public Eye, the network was paying him in
the ballpark of $7 million annually and getting nothing for it.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether Gumbel's failure with Public Eye will be
indicative of how he'll be received on the Early Show. Maybe, even
though my theory on the newsmagazine's failure has more to do with
TV's cyclical nature than Gumbel's lack of talent or appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Public Eye aired at a time when viewers were conditioned to
expect salacious, alarmist stories offered up by the PrimeTime
Lives and Dateline NBCs _ not the gumshoe investigative pieces
Bryant delivered. (The show, by the way, received a pair of Peabody
Awards even as it gasped for ratings air.)
</P>
<P>
   But back to the Gumbel likability factor: No one I've sparred
with over Gumbel has ever said the guy is terrible at what he does,
that he's not one of the best at cornering a politician or even
deflating an actor trying to pitch his or her film as serious art.
But rarely has a news figure elicited so much passion, for and
against, as Gumbel. I have to say this doesn't bode well for the
chances of his show catching Good Morning America in the ratings,
let alone Today, which recently completed a staggering 200 weeks at
No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel has made the point, accurately, that he was successful on
Today with Jane Pauley, Deborah Norville and Couric, so how could
he be the bad guy? (Early on, Couric, in particular, received good
press reviews, even though her journalistic approach was more like
that of a giggling, cuddly panda bear.) Or was it that these
co-hosts, no matter their weaknesses, help soften Gumbel's glare?
</P>
<P>
   Can Gumbel's Early Show co-host, Jane Clayson, a former ABC news
correspondent and complete unknown, balance Gumbel's perceived
weaknesses? Well, we'll see.
</P>
<P>
   But now more than ever, morning television involves being chummy
and accommodating, or occasionally stern and sympathetic. Gumbel
can be all those things, but only if he tries really, really hard.
And I have to wonder whether he sees wake-up television as a whole
as even more cosmetic and superficial than when he left.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sawyer said recently that it troubles her that so much
emphasis was being put on ABC's new digs, as if it doesn't matter
which hosts are on the other side of those windows.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Zucker, the executive producer of Today, has been so
adamant about the window trend not being a big deal that he's MADE
it a big deal. Zucker can't deny that Today owes much of its
ratings lead to the gimmick, which is why GMA is now in a 2-story,
glass-encased studio, with an anchor desk overlooking Broadway and
a ground-level area for passersby.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Early Show, it will broadcast from a new $30 million
studio across the street from New York's Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   But for all its techno-wonder, the best thing about CBS' see-me
window version is that, unlike on Today, the glass can instantly
turn opaque, shutting out the animated movement over the hosts'
shoulders that has now become a ratings necessity.
</P>
<P>
   A Gumbel request, you think?
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at kperkins(at)star-telegram.com
or (817) 390-7862. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
