<SLUG> BC-CD-RELEASES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME TO POP OPEN A SIX-PACK OF HOLIDAY-GIFT CDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By TODD CAMP, DAVE FERMAN 
And MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Music and Christmas go together like eggnog and Christmas,
office parties and Christmas, and credit-card debt and Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   The record industry has long recognized it, thus timing new
releases and best-of CDs for the last two months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   This year's lineup of ``Super Tuesdays'' starts this week and
continues through Nov. 23, with releases by Dr. Dre, Savage Garden,
Mariah Carey, Will Smith, Korn, Beck, The Artist Formerly Known As
Popular and others.
</P>
<P>
   And in the spirit of giving, we're doing reviews of the biggest
of the big, starting with six CDs that hit the shelves Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   Mariah Carey, ``Rainbow,'' Columbia Records: Among female pop
vocalists, Carey's popularity is unmatched. This time out, though,
she's actually not so bad. More genuinely streetwise than her last
CD, ``Butterfly,'' ``Heartbreaker'' scores some points for the
vocal restraint that Carey lacked in the past, and a few of the
songs _ ``X-Girlfriend'' and ``Did I Do That?'' _ are fairly good.
Three stars (out of five).
</P>
<P>
   Counting Crows, ``This Desert Life,'' DGC: Is there anyone who
has done so well but sounds so miserable as the Crows' lead singer,
Adam Duritz? As usual, he sings about feeling stuck and bored. And
as usual, the band follows through with basic pop/rock.
``Hanginaround'' is the first song here, and it's a) about nothing
more than hanging around your old hometown and being bored, and b)
emblematic of the CD as a whole. Two and a half stars.
</P>
<P>
   Foo Fighters, ``There Is Nothing Left to Lose,'' RCA: This, the
third disc from the ex-Nirvana drummer-turned-guitarist-frontman
Dave Grohl and his ever-changing band, is one of those records that
sounds really good the first few times you hear it. Then you just
don't wanna hear it anymore. Two and a half stars.
</P>
<P>
   Rosie O'Donnell, ``A Rosie Christmas,'' Columbia Records: Rosie
and Celine. Rosie and Billy Joel. Rosie and Elton. Rosie and Cher.
Rosie and 'N Sync. This CD has 'em all. For an all-purpose pure-pop
seasonal effort, this is actually fairly good, especially when
O'Donnell stays in the background and lets the featured artist do
all the work. Three and a half stars.
</P>
<P>
   Pet Shop Boys, ``Nightlife,'' Sire Records: While plugging PSB's
recent appearance at the Bronco Bowl, lead singer Neil Tennant
described their latest disc as a salute to the night, ``when
people's fears are greater and people's desires are greater.''
Count on plenty of the kind of ethereal electronica you've come to
expect from PSB. It's not as dance-driven as earlier efforts, but,
hey, everyone's gotta grow up sometime. Three and a half stars.
</P>
<P>
   Rage Against the Machine, ``The Battle of Los Angeles,'' Epic:
In 1999, RATM is a rock-music rarity _ a band unafraid to protest
this or question that. On its third disc, nothing, thankfully, has
changed: The quartet continues to successfully mine the same
territory it did with its first two records. More lyrics about
political unrest and injustice, more songs that combine the
abrasiveness of rock with the infectiousness of hip-hop. Four
stars.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
