<HEADLINE>
SO MUCH FOR PRINCIPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Political scrimmage involves clashing egos more
than competing ideas, even though our elected officials habitually
cloak their motives in lofty principles.
</P>
<P>
   The instinct to look altruistic in public while being privately
selfish is so pervasive that voters who don't pay attention can
easily get confused about why national figures do what they do.
</P>
<P>
   The competition is stiff for the title of opportunist of the
year (or maybe the decade), particularly with Patrick Buchanan
around. But we have a clear winner these days, a senator who is
protecting his rear no matter how the maneuver looks. And it looks
terrible.
</P>
<P>
   He is Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., who had the audacity to run for
the Republican presidential nomination earlier this year despite a
conspicuous lack of legislative achievements or national
recognition. He was re-elected to the Senate with a mere
3-percentage-point margin five years ago, and Democrats consider
him among their most vulnerable targets in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   When he could stir up no noticeable GOP interest in a White
House future, he turned on his party in a fury and formally became
an independent in July. He trashed the Republicans as an
unprincipled lot, sharply contrasting his colleagues' views to his
own purely idealistic stands.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday he returned to the Republican fold as though his
summer departure had all had been momentary madness, a mere
bagatelle in the game of life. He had said only a few months ago he
was resigning as a ``decision of conscience,'' but now we are not
to take his conscience seriously.
</P>
<P>
   His new career as an independent wasn't working out. Third party
groups were just as unimpressed by his presidential credentials as
the Republicans. He was having second thoughts. And he had suddenly
been offered the dazzling chance to become chairman of a major
Senate committee _ if he just belonged to the majority party.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders, nervous about the 2000 elections, were shamefully
eager to welcome him back. They need every Republican they can get.
</P>
<P>
   No hurt feelings. Numbers are more important than personal
pride. Republican Party Chairman Jim Nicholson, who Smith had
complained was ``petty, vindictive and insulting,'' stood
cheerfully at Smith's side during his homecoming ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   When Sen. John Chafee, chairman of the Senate Environment and
Public Works Committee, unexpectedly died last week, Smith's
seniority put him in line for the post. So much for principle. A
chairmanship dangled, and with it real political power. Temptation
reared its unprincipled head.
</P>
<P>
   Smith undoubtedly wishes we would ignore his parting shot at the
GOP now that he's had a political epiphany. But it is a classic
example of the truth of the old saw that it is never wise to say
``never.'' Things change.
</P>
<P>
   Upon his leaving, Smith gave the Republican Party no quarter. He
accused it of being more concerned with winning elections than
promoting conservative ideals. He professed not to understand why
the GOP is willing to ``walk away from the issues that got us
here'' just to stay in power.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a party,'' he said in a Senate floor speech.
``Maybe it is a party in the sense of wearing hats and blowing
whistles but it is not a political party that means anything. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The party, to put it bluntly, is hypocritical,'' he thundered.
He called the ``fancy words'' in the platform issued at the GOP
presidential convention every four years ``a charade'' and added,
``I am not going to take part in it any more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not come here (to the Senate) to compromise my values to
promote the interests of a political party,'' he said. Repeatedly,
he cited as a chief gripe the party's refusal to punish folks who
won't crusade to overthrow the Supreme Court's ruling that a
limited right to abortion is constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   He also whined about attacks on his judgment for leaving the
GOP, saying, ``That is what is wrong with politics. It is the ugly.
It is the bad. It is the worst. I am going to stay an independent,
whatever happens in the future. I am the same ingredients. I have
merely redesigned the label.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, so much for the new label. No shelf life. The GOP hasn't
changed since July. There must be some other factor working here.
</P>
<P>
   If Smith were to become chairman of the environmental panel, he
would likely use the post as a pro-business spokesman to try to
undo several decades of progress in conservation. In that role, he
would also attract the kind of big business bucks he could not
raise in his defunct presidential campaign. His re-election coffers
would swell.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunity, it's wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached by e-mail at means(at)hearstdc.
com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 1815EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
