<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MORNING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A REBAPTISM BY CRASH, GUMBEL IS TRUE TO SELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just in case Bryant Gumbel had forgotten how hectic the world of
morning television can be, he was served up a reminder Monday as he
launched CBS's ``The Early Show,'' on the heels of a major news
story: the crash of EgyptAir Flight 990.
</P>
<P>
   Between coverage of that tragedy and a timely interview of
President Clinton in the Oval Office, taped on Sunday, Gumbel got
off to a solid start. But there were also a number of missteps, as
Gumbel and cohost Jane Clayson began the long uphill climb toward
the peaks occupied by NBC's ``Today'' and ABC's ``Good Morning
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Audio glitches marred parts of the ``Early Show'' debut, seen
locally on WBZ-Ch. 4. The downside of broadcasting outdoors _ de
rigueur on morning programs these days _ became apparent when
ambulance sirens virtually drowned out the show's closing moments.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of noxious noise, was it really necessary to inflict
Donald Trump on innocent viewers at such an early hour, even if
Trump does own the building where the ``Early Show'' studio is
located? As for Gumbel's interview of Clinton, obviously a booking
coup, it was smoothly professional until the end, when he adopted
an overly chummy tone in pointing out that he belongs to a country
club near the president's future address in New York.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Gumbel generally seemed to regain his stride without
too much difficulty. He did not try to reinvent the morning-TV
wheel, but he offered a few reminders of the unpredictable
qualities that have made him stand out from the pack. A case in
point: Immediately after Mark McEwen's puffy interview of Mel
Gibson, Gumbel bluntly opined to McEwen that Gibson has said
``outrageous things over the years and no one seems to call him on
it. Didn't he say something about the homeless one time?''
</P>
<P>
   The run-up to ``The Early Show'' had been spiced with
controversy. Late last week, the pop diva Mariah Carey bowed out of
a scheduled appearance on ``The Early Show'' and was immediately
booked by the ``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Gumbel has made news by taking a thinly veiled shot
at Couric, his old ``Today'' show partner. In an interview with The
New York Times, he sought to rebut claims that he's hard to work
with by noting that ``somebody who shall remain nameless'' had gone
through five assistants in five years while he has had the same
assistant for two decades. (Coincidentally, when ``The Early Show''
broke for commercials at 7:59 a.m. Monday, Channel 4 broadcast an
ad for a supermarket tabloid that promised to tell ``Why Bryant
Hates Katie.'')
</P>
<P>
   The newcomer Clayson, in her first stint as anchor of a national
show, played it low-key and let her famous partner set the
program's tone. ``You having any fun yet?'' Gumbel teased Clayson
in one of their appearances before a crowd gathered outside the
studio. It was hard to tell. Whereas the female anchors are the
main stars of ``Today'' and ``GMA'' _ Katie Couric and Diane
Sawyer, respectively _ that will clearly not be the case on ``The
Early Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically enough, the person who seemed most comfortable on the
air was McEwen, former host of the now-defunct ``CBS This
Morning,'' which ``The Early Show'' replaced. McEwen showed energy
and good humor in performing his new duties of delivering weather
reports, doing celebrity interviews, and bantering with the crowd
(which included Clayson's parents). Kevin James, star of CBS's
``King of Queens,'' provided one of the high points by leading a
hilarious tour of the ``Early Show'' neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   But the 51-year-old Gumbel _ with his eyeglasses on again, off
again _ was the focus of attention. If you liked him on ``Today,''
where he coanchored from 1982 to 1997, you'll like him on CBS. If
not, you won't. He hasn't changed his style. He has a no-nonsense
way of charging up the atmosphere; his verbal tempo is as rapid as
ever, and he conducts interviews with the same juxtaposition of
long, ornate questions and short, sudden word bursts.
</P>
<P>
   It's his strongest suit, as he showed while quizzing Clinton
about the airline crash, his wife Hillary's Senate campaign, his
``one-line'' description of his own legacy, and the ``line of
demarcation'' that George W. Bush has drawn regarding questions
about past cocaine use.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Gumbel followed one light moment by asking
Clinton a tough question about whether the president will be a
``liability'' to his wife's campaign. But it was jarring when
Gumbel noted that he belongs to a country club near Chappaqua, the
New York community where the Clintons have bought a home, and that
it is the ``closest golf course'' to that home. Clinton replied:
``I'd be happy to be your guest any time.'' Afterwards, Clayson
gushed to Gumbel: ``Even the president could use a little help from
you.'' Said Gumbel, alluding to golf: ``If I give him two a side,
it could be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, despite his initial reluctance about returning to the
morning beat, Gumbel seemed glad to be back on the air Monday. For
the most part, he seemed to be genuinely enjoying himself. Over the
long term, that just might be bad news for ``Today'' and ``GMA.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
