<HEADER>
A5546 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-555&AMP;ADD-NYT     11-01 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-555&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT TO DECIDE WHETHER TO ALLOW ANONYMOUS GUN TIPS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Fla., Ga., Pa., Nev.)  (nk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court agreed Monday to decide whether
the police may stop and frisk someone solely on the basis of an
anonymous, uncorroborated tip that the person is carrying a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, an anonymous tip that describes seemingly innocent
behavior _ standing on a particular corner, for example _ and that
has not been verified by further police work gives the police an
insufficient basis on which to detain someone, even briefly, the
court has ruled. The question in this case is whether the specific
allegation of the presence of a concealed weapon is inherently so
alarming as to tip the constitutional balance in favor of a brief
``investigatory detention.''
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Supreme Court said no, declaring last year in a 4-2
opinion that it would ``decline the state's invitation to create a
firearm or weapons exception to the limitations on searches and
seizures'' contained in the state and federal constitutions. The
state court barred prosecutors from introducing as evidence the
unlicensed gun a police officer discovered in the pants pocket of a
teen-ager who was wearing a plaid shirt and standing with two other
youths in front of a pawn shop _ details the anonymous caller had
provided.
</P>
<P>
   Florida appealed the decision, arguing that guns are so
dangerous that the police should not have to wait until a suspect
actually brandishes one before moving in. The Fourth Amendment,
which bans unreasonable searches, ``is not to be read in a
vacuum,'' the state said, adding that under these circumstances, a
brief stop and frisk was ``reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   The state courts are divided over the issue, with a majority,
including those in New York and New Jersey, having ruled that a tip
about a gun justifies an investigatory detention. Last month, the
Supreme Court turned down, without comment, a similar case from
Pennsylvania, in which that state's supreme court suppressed the
narcotics evidence that Philadelphia police found when they
conducted a stop and frisk of a man whom an anonymous caller had
identified as carrying a gun. It was not clear in that case,
Pennsylvania vs. Allen, No. 98-1910, whether a gun was ever found _
a gap in the record that may have led the justices to select the
Florida case instead. The case is Florida vs. J.L., No. 98-1993,
with the defendant being identified only by his initials because of
his age.
</P>
<P>
   The new Supreme Court term is developing as an important one for
the law of police searches. On Tuesday, the justices will hear
arguments in Illinois vs. Wardlow, No. 98-1036, posing the question
of whether a person's unprovoked flight at the sight of an
approaching police officer is such inherently suspicious behavior
as to justify a stop and frisk. And last month, the court agreed to
decide whether a law enforcement agent's action in looking for
drugs by manipulating bus passengers' carry-on luggage with his
hands is a ``search'' that is illegal in the absence of a reason to
be suspicious of a particular passenger. That case is Bond vs.
United States, No. 98-9349.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   These were among the other developments at the court on Monday:
</P>
<P>
   Juvenile Execution
</P>
<P>
   Accepting the Clinton administration's advice, the court turned
down an appeal by a Nevada man sentenced to death for a double
murder he committed in 1993 at the age of 16. He argued that the
Senate's ratification in 1992 of the International Covenant on
Civil and Political Rights, which prohibits capital punishment for
crimes committed before the age of 18, pre-empted Nevada's law and
meant that his execution would violate international law.
</P>
<P>
   When the appeal, filed on behalf of Michael Domingues, reached
the court last spring, the justices sought an opinion from the
administration. In a brief filed last month, the administration
said the juvenile death penalty provision was not binding because
the Senate, at the request of President George Bush, had explicitly
refused to consent to that provision, instead adding the following
language to the treaty: ``That the United States reserves the
right, subject to its constitutional constraints, to impose capital
punishment on any person duly convicted under existing or future
laws permitting the imposition of capital punishment including such
punishment for crimes committed by persons below 18 years of age.''
</P>
<P>
   The defendant's lawyers also argued that, apart from the treaty,
the execution of juveniles has become so disfavored around the
world as to violate basic norms of international law. In addition
to the United States, only Iran, Nigeria, Pakistan, and Saudi
Arabia permit capital punishment for crimes committed by people as
young as 16. The Supreme Court ruled in 1989 that such executions
did not violate the Eighth Amendment's prohibition against cruel
and unusual punishment. The case Monday was Domingues vs. Nevada,
No. 98-8327.
</P>
<P>
   Extradition
</P>
<P>
   The court cleared the way for the United States to extradite a
man wanted in Spain on charges of participating in terrorism on
behalf of Basque separatism in the late 1980s. Ramon Aldasoro
Maguna-Celaya, a Spanish citizen, argued that the evidence against
him had been obtained in Spain by the torture of his alleged
accomplices in the crimes of murder, robbery, and an attack on the
barracks of the Spanish civil guard.
</P>
<P>
   He initially won a petition for a writ of habeas corpus from the
federal District Court in Miami. But the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, in Atlanta, overturned that ruling on the ground that the
evidence of torture was too equivocal to cast doubt on the
evidence. The case was Maguna-Celaya vs. Haro, No. 99-5526.
</P>
<P>
   Beachfront Begging
</P>
<P>
   The court turned down a First Amendment challenge to a
regulation in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., that prohibits ``soliciting,
begging or panhandling'' along a five-mile strip of Atlantic Ocean
beachfront as well as on a promenade and on the sidewalk in front
of the commercial establishments across Highway A1A from the beach.
</P>
<P>
   The case, Smith vs. Fort Lauderdale, No. 99-377, was brought by
the state's American Civil Liberties Union chapter as a class
action on behalf of homeless people who beg for money or food along
the beach. The challenge failed both in federal District Court in
Miami and in the 11th Circuit, which agreed with the city that
begging ``adversely impacts tourism.'' The appeals court agreed
with the plaintiffs that begging was a form of speech, and that the
beach area was a public forum in which speech is protected by the
First Amendment. But it said the begging ban was ``narrowly
tailored to serve the city's interest in providing a safe, pleasant
environment and eliminating nuisance activity on the beach,'' and
was therefore constitutionally permissible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 1830EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
