<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5547 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-WALMART-WWF-COX     11-01 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALMART-WWF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wal-Mart gives action figure the take-down
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Chastened by an Atlanta-area college instructor and
one of its own store managers, Wal-Mart has pulled an action figure
from its shelves: a WWF wrestler who carries around a woman's head.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart spokesman John Bisio said Monday that complaints from
Sabrena Parton, an assistant professor of communications at
Kennesaw State University, and from the manager of a Wal-Mart store
spurred the company to pull Summer Slam '99: Road Rage Al Snow. The
toy _ modeled after Al Snow, a World Wrestling Federation
competitor who carries a female mannequin's head on a stake _ comes
with a woman's head with the words ``Help Me'' scrawled across her
forehead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our management has decided it is at least a questionable
item,'' Bisio said from the company's Bentonville, Ark.,
headquarters. ``So we are removing it from the shelf, probably
permanently.''
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Kinnick _ who with Kennesaw State colleague Parton
co-authored an essay in the Atlanta Journal-Constitution newspaper
protesting the toy _ was jubilant at news of Wal-Mart's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrific to see corporations do the right thing _ and
that a couple of Cobb County moms can make a difference,'' said
Kinnick, 36. ``My sons are 6 and 11: What kind of message would
this toy send them about brutalization of women?''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the toy's manufacturer, Jakks/ Pacific in Malibu,
Calif., and its licenser, the WWF, said they were unfamiliar with
the toy and were not aware of any complaints about it. A spokesman
for Toys R Us, which also sells the toy in stores and on its Web
site, did not return a phone call.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old Parton, while shopping with her infant daughter,
was shocked to see the toy in a store near her home several weeks
ago. When she pointed it out to the manager, he agreed that the toy
was offensive and filed a joint complaint with Wal-Mart
headquarters. Parton then learned from her students that Snow
actually does carry a woman's head on a stake in televised
wrestling matches, and when he shouts, ``What do you want?'' the
crowd bellows the sexual innuendo, ``Head!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see if this was an adult novelty item, people could
make a choice about whether to buy it,'' Parton said. ``But the
label says it's recommended for children ages 4 and older. That's
terribly wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after her visit, Parton said, the toy was still on
Wal-Mart and Toys R Us shelves, and she and Kinnick decided to
publish their essay in the Sunday edition of the
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
