<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5549 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-STRITCH-SAIL-NYT &LR;      11-01 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRITCH-SAIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING FAME WITTILY, WITH COWARD AS GUIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Spelling in quotes cq.) 
(ms) 
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One evening in March 1961, Noel Coward had dinner with Elaine
Stritch, who was to star in his forthcoming Broadway musical,
``Sail Away.'' Coward, the author, composer, lyricist and director
of the show, wrote in his diary that Ms. Stritch was ``wildly
enthusiastic and very funny'' and would be wonderful in the role of
the cruise director on a British ship. He had also heard that she
was a woman with problems, and added: ``However, I think I shall be
able to manage her. If I can, all will be fine and dandy, if not ze
scenes will be terribile. I must engage an expert understudy.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, after that passage was read back to Ms. Stritch, she
laughed and said, ``Not only didn't he get an expert understudy,
but I ended up playing both parts.'' When the musical was trying
out in Philadelphia, Coward suddenly merged her character with that
played by the opera singer Jean Fenn. Ms. Stritch became the
romantic leading lady as well as the comic centerpiece of the show.
</P>
<P>
   For her this was a breakthrough. ``That was relatively
revolutionary then,'' she said. ``It used to be that the soprano
got the guy and the funny girl went off with the 11 o'clock number,
laughing hysterically, never to be heard from again.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Stritch drew rapturous reviews on Broadway and
later in London, the musical was not a success. Since then _ in
contrast to other Coward shows _ it has rarely been performed.
Wednesday night, 38 years after the musical's premiere, it is being
staged in a concert version at Weill Recital Hall, with Ms. Stritch
in her original role. Featured in the cast are Marian Seldes,
Gordon Connell, Jane Connell and Alison Fraser.
</P>
<P>
   The production, which is to run through Nov. 13, is in honor of
Coward's centenary. Ms. Stritch said that she was reviving it ``for
Noel,'' and because the show was for her ``one of the most
unbelievable learning experiences.'' It was also a pivotal moment
in her career. Following ``Sail Away,'' she went on to star in
shows by Edward Albee and Stephen Sondheim.
</P>
<P>
   The original idea for a revival of ``Sail Away'' this year began
with Andre Bishop, the artistic director of Lincoln Center Theater.
A great admirer of Coward, he had thought about staging it for one
night at the Vivian Beaumont Theater. Bishop had been there on the
closing night of the Broadway production and thought that Ms.
Stritch gave ``the single greatest musical comedy performance I
have ever seen in my life _ and I never forgot it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stritch remembered her first meeting with Coward. After
appearing on Broadway in ``Bus Stop'' and singing ``Zip'' in the
1952 revival of ``Pal Joey,'' she was starring in the musical
``Goldilocks'' by Walter and Jean Kerr, with a score by Leroy
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   The leading man, Barry Sullivan, had been replaced by Don
Ameche, and the show was in trouble in Philadelphia. After a
performance one night Ms. Stritch was in her dressing room, ``in
tears, drinking a Dewars and soda.'' There was a knock on the door.
``Stritchie,'' said the visitor, inventing a nickname that he would
use all his life. ``It's Noel Coward.'' He took one look at the
distraught actress, excused himself and returned with the Kerrs and
the producer Robert Whitehead.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stritch recalled, ``He took them into my dressing room and
said, `I'm veddy veddy sorry to tell you that you have no book, no
score, and you have an absolutely brilliant young performer who is
in tears, drinking in her dressing room.'' She said that she
remembered the event as if it were a scene in a play: ``It was the
opposite of being sent to your room for something you didn't do. I
had a champion. And the next thing I know: `Sail Away.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1930s after sailing on a cruise ship, Coward had
conceived the show as a vehicle for Ethel Merman or Rosalind
Russell. The original title was ``Later Than Spring,'' and a song
by that name was in the musical when the author finally wrote it
more than two decades later.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stritch said that when Coward asked her to come to his suite
during the Philadelphia tryout, she fully expected to be fired.
Instead he said he was expanding her role: ``You're going to play
two parts, the part that you're playing now rather well, and you're
going to play Miss Fenn's part.'' She recounted what Alice Pearce,
who was also in the cast, said about Miss Fenn: ``First they cut
her hair, then they cut her part and then they fired her.''
</P>
<P>
   The actress spent the next day, Sunday, learning her new
dialogue and songs (including ``Later Than Spring'' and ``Something
Very Strange''), and, filled with adrenaline, charged onto the
stage for the Monday opening. ``The romantic qualities that I have
in me came alive,'' she said. After the opening, exhausted, she
lost her voice and missed the next performance, but then returned
to the show. When ``Sail Away'' opened in New York, Howard Taubman
of The New York Times said she gave ``what must be the performance
of her career.''
</P>
<P>
   The musical itself had a modest run and then moved to London.
Once again the reviews were favorable for her, less so for Coward _
but the run was somewhat longer. The actress soldiered on and grew
closer to the author. ``Noel was crazy about me because I delivered
for him,'' she said. They became good friends: ``You went out with
Noel and you felt so feminine,'' she said. ``It took me days to
plan a wardrobe. How you wanted him to be proud of you.''
</P>
<P>
   In his company, she also felt obliged to be funny, to match him
wit for wit: ``It was like we had a script going,'' she said. ``He
brought it out of me. It was a challenge, and I meet challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   But her most interesting visit with Coward was when he was not
funny at all. One evening he asked her to have supper with him in
his suite at the Savoy in London. ``It was his birthday,'' she
said, ``and I didn't know it. So I got all emotional about that. We
had a few drinks. Noel tipped a few, but he was so elegant that you
never thought of him as someone who had a problem with alcohol. He
was so meticulous and so beautifully groomed. In my estimation, he
was an alcoholic. It takes one to know one, which is rather
frivolous. But I never met an alcoholic I wasn't crazy about.'' Ms.
Stritch, who is diabetic, stopped drinking some years ago.
</P>
<P>
   After dinner Coward played the piano, then started to cry. ``He
said he had fallen in love and it was an impossible situation,''
Ms. Stritch said. ``As he talked about it, I referred in my mind to
that lyric, `a talent to amuse.' When people who have that quality
get to that line, it's almost hard to go on with the song. It
usually means the other side of the coin is not so good, and I
think that really applied to Noel.''
</P>
<P>
   Then they started talking about death. ``A real fun evening,''
she said. As she recalled, Coward told her there was only one thing
that frightened him about dying: ``I don't think I'm going to be
remembered.'' She thought quickly and said that anyone who had
written ``Brief Encounter'' (the movie based on his play ``Still
Life'') was going to be remembered.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the passage of time, she said she had no hesitation
about returning to her role in ``Sail Away'': ``I don't feel the
least bit about age. The script is about an older woman with a
younger man. Today it would have to be a love affair between a
woman of, let's say 70, and a man of 50.'' Speaking of age reminded
her of her favorite birthday greeting. When an actress friend of
hers turned 60, Ms. Stritch, who was nine years older, sent her a
telegram: ``Welcome to my decade. I can only stay a minute.''
</P>
</TEXT>
