<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5554 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-REAL-NETWORKS-BOS &LR;      11-01 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-NETWORKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL NETWORKS SAYS IT WILL MAKE SOFTWARE MORE SECURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Real Networks Inc., maker of a popular software program for
playing music on personal computers, has vowed to make changes in
its product after a Boston-area programmer found that the company's
software transmits information about users' music listening habits
over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Computer programmer and consultant Richard Smith of Brookline,
Mass. found that a Real Networks product called Real Jukebox
collected the information without warning users. As a result, Smith
said, the software could violate the privacy of millions of
Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times published a story about Smith's discovery
Monday morning. By afternoon, Real Networks said it would publish a
software ``patch'' that would prevent Real Jukebox from collecting
the information. This patch will be available for download over the
Internet at http://www.real.com/rjcentral/privacyupdate.html.
</P>
<P>
   ``We respect and value the privacy of our users, and we deeply
apologize for doing anything that suggests otherwise,'' said Rob
Glaser, chairman and chief executive of RealNetworks.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of people have downloaded free copies of Real Jukebox
over the Internet. The software allows a user to play music CDs on
a desktop computer and copy the CD onto the computer's hard drive,
using the popular MP3 music format. These MP3 files can then be
loaded into portable music players such as Diamond Multimedia's Rio
or Creative Labs' Nomad, which can replay high-fidelity digital
music without using a CD or tape.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Real Jukebox can be connected over the Internet to
CDDB, a database containing listings of millions of CDs. By linking
to CDDB, the computer can generate a listing of every music cut on
the disk. This enables users to make accurate playlists of their
favorite music.
</P>
<P>
   But unbeknownst to users, when they connected Real Jukebox to
CDDB, the software also sent electronic messages to Real Networks.
Among other things, the messages revealed what CD the user was
listening to, what music recordings were stored on the user's hard
drive, and whether the user had a portable MP3 player such as the
Rio connected to the PC.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, it included a unique serial number, called a GUID,
attached to each copy of Real Jukebox when a user registers the
software. When they register, users are asked for their names and
e-mail addresses, so Real Networks would be in a position to
recognize individual listeners by their GUID numbers.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, whenever anyone used Real Jukebox while connected
to the Internet, it would be possible for Real Networks to know
that user's taste in music. ``They've got your registration
information, so they've got the option of monitoring all the CDs
you listen to,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, an industry gadfly, has previously revealed privacy flaws
in Microsoft Corp.'s popular Office software suite. He also took
part in the investigation that tracked down the creator of the
Melissa computer virus that attacked thousands of computers earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Real Networks says it was collecting the data to build a general
or ``aggregate'' picture of the listening habits of Real Jukebox
users. ``They were using the GUIDs to aggregate data, not to
identify and monitor individual users' listening habits,'' said
Thomas Frank, Real Networks' chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Aggregate data, in which individual identities are not revealed,
is routinely collected by Internet companies. They use the data to
send targeted advertisements to users, based on their tastes and
interests. But Smith warns sometimes Internet companies take the
concept too far by using targeting methods that reveal the identity
of individual listeners.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Rotenberg, executive director of the Electronic Privacy
Information Center in Washington, said the Real Jukebox incident
illustrates the need for federal laws to protect the privacy of
Internet users. ``I think we obviously need some rules that are
going to protect the collection of personal information,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
