<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5556 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COURT-POLICE-HNS &LR;      11-01 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-POLICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT TO DECIDE WHAT POWER POLICE HAVE WHEN SOMEONE RUNS AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's a scene played out all the time across
America.
</P>
<P>
   A patrol car cruises a high-crime neighborhood. The police
officer inside scans the streets for signs of trouble. Suddenly, a
young man sees the cop and bolts down an alley. The officer jumps
out of his car and chases him.
</P>
<P>
   But the Supreme Court could use an Illinois case to make this
common scenario a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the high court will hear arguments on the case,
which raises the question of whether police chasing people because
they run is unconstitutional or if the mere fact that the people _
who otherwise are doing nothing illegal _ flee is enough reason for
officers to suspect that they have committed a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement groups argue that it's common sense to believe
that people do not run from police unless they have something to
hide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police can't be expected to shrug their shoulders and look the
other way at obvious and highly suspicious behavior,'' said Robert
T. Scully, executive director of the National Association of Police
Organizations, which represents 4,000 law enforcement groups with
more than 220,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   Scully said that forbidding police to chase people who run would
make their job ``extremely difficult'' and result in a ``more
dangerous society.''
</P>
<P>
   But civil rights watchdog organizations contend that pursuing
someone just because that person runs violates the Fourth
Amendment's protection against unreasonable search and seizure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, in many neighborhoods, innocent young men may
have good reason to be afraid of the police and feel that they
should get off the street before a cop starts questioning them,''
said Susan Herman, a law professor at Brooklyn Law School and a
member of the American Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   She said running should not be considered a crime just because
it happens in a high-crime neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``So in a nice, white suburb, it's all right to go for a jog or
to walk away from police, but in a mostly black, poor city
neighborhood it's not?'' Herman asked rhetorically.
</P>
<P>
   The Illinois case began on Sept. 9, 1995. Sam Wardlow was
standing in front of a building in an area of Chicago known for its
heavy drug activity when he spotted uniformed officer Timothy Nolan
driving an unmarked police car.
</P>
<P>
   Although he wasn't doing anything unusual or suspicious, Wardlow
began running down the nearest alley. Nolan, seeing Wardlow
fleeing, jumped out of his car and began chasing him.
</P>
<P>
   When he caught Wardlow, Nolan found a white envelope in his
pocket. Inside was a Colt .38 revolver loaded with five bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Wardlow, a convicted felon, was not supposed to possess any
weapon; so police charged him with a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Wardlow was convicted of unlawful possession of a weapon by a
felon and sentenced to two years in prison. But his conviction was
overturned in 1998 by the Illinois Supreme Court, which ruled that
the ``sudden and unprovoked flight of a suspect upon seeing police
... is insufficient to create a reasonable suspicion of involvement
in criminal activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the prosecution emphasized that Wardlow's flight
occurred in a neighborhood known for heavy drug trafficking, the
court ruled that innocent activity doesn't become sinister simply
because it takes place in a high-crime area.
</P>
<P>
   The court said police need an ``independently suspicious
circumstance'' that, considered in conjunction with the flight,
creates a reasonable inference of a guilty conscience.
</P>
<P>
   The Illinois court's decision was based on a 1968 U.S. Supreme
Court ruling _ Terry vs. Ohio _ in which the high court said police
cannot stop and begin questioning citizens unless the officers have
``reasonable suspicion'' that criminal activity is afoot.
</P>
<P>
   But according to legal experts, the Supreme Court has never
spelled out exactly what constitutes suspicious behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because each case is different, the court has been reluctant
to lay out what specific actions are suspicious and which aren't,''
said Louis Michael Seidman, a law professor at Georgetown
University here.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, lower courts have been divided over whether the
mere act of fleeing constitutes ``reasonable suspicion.''
</P>
<P>
   Seidman said the Supreme Court now has the opportunity to end
that dispute. ``The way every cop on the street does his or her job
could change with this decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
