<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5565 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HIMMEL-PHOTOGRAPHY-NY     11-01 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIMMEL-PHOTOGRAPHY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: FOR A THERAPIST, THE RETURN OF A FREEWHEELING
PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MARGARETT LOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like his wife, the fashion photographer Lillian
Bassman, Paul Himmel isn't much interested in the past.
</P>
<P>
   After he gave up photography in 1969, when he was 55, and became
a psychotherapist, he and Ms. Bassman decided they no longer needed
separate studios in their Upper East Side carriage house. They
rented out the downstairs studio and in the process jettisoned
practically all the fashion work he had done since the mid-1940s
for magazines like Harper's Bazaar and Vogue. Also thrown away were
almost all the negatives of the portraits he had taken for Theater
Arts magazine, Himmel recalled in a recent interview at his home.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Ms. Bassman's negatives ended up in the garbage as well.
And after she, too, stopped accepting fashion assignments in the
early 1970s, the couple went off the photography world's radar.
While Ms. Bassman confined her camera work to personal projects,
Himmel built up his psychotherapy practice.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1991, their photographic past caught up with them.
Martin Harrison, a photography historian and curator from England,
was staying at the Himmel home when he noticed a garbage bag in a
darkroom that had been damaged after a rainstorm. The bag held some
of Ms. Bassman's negatives, most dating from the 1940s and 50s,
that had been salvaged during a house cleaning, put away and
forgotten. Her subsequent, darkly romantic ``reinterpretations'' of
those early images led to exhibitions in the United States and
Europe. Suddenly Ms. Bassman, then in her 70s, was again a hot
fashion photographer.
</P>
<P>
   In quick order, Himmel the photographer was also rediscovered. A
small selection of his noncommercial work was exhibited at the
Howard Greenberg Gallery in SoHo in 1996. And a retrospective of
his published and personal work opened last month at the James
Danziger Gallery (851 Madison Ave., at 70th St.).
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying the show is a book, ``Paul Himmel: Photographs''
(Assouline), that was designed by Ms. Bassman, who began her career
as the assistant to Alexey Brodovitch, the brilliant and
influential art director at Harper's Bazaar in the 1930s, '40s and
'50s. In the introduction, Harrison quotes a Brodovitch reference
to Himmel: ``Of all my proteges, he was the one who best understood
what I meant about movement.''
</P>
<P>
   In her 1992 book, ``The New York School: Photographs 1936-63,''
Jane Livingston highlighted the work of 16 photographers, many of
whom _ among them Diane Arbus, Richard Avedon, Robert Frank and
Lisette Model _ were influenced by Brodovitch through the rigorous
photography courses he offered. The work of these photographers
flouted the rules of photography and showed a romanticism that had
nothing to do with the heroics of the self but rather with a grainy
film-noir reality that was sometimes brutally frank and yet often
surprisingly lyrical.
</P>
<P>
   Himmel was not among the 16 photographers, but his consistently
freewheeling and experimental work stamps him as a member of this
school. As a young man he aspired to be a dancer, and his work
seemed to have a striking affinity for the kind of choreographed,
evanescent movement that Brodovitch aimed for in a 1945 book of his
own photographs titled ``Ballet.''
</P>
<P>
   What he learned from Brodovitch, Himmel said, was ``that it's OK
not to do what the camera tells you to do. To that extent he was a
tremendous influence.''
</P>
<P>
   Himmel's interest in photography began in his early teens
because a close friend was an avid photographer. Self-taught, he
photographed friends and the streets of New York. But photography
for him was a hobby, and he earned a master's degree in adolescent
psychology and taught biology. He kept up his amateur photography
and followed the work of Farm Security Administration photographers
like Dorothea Lange.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the mid-'40s, Himmel decided to spend his summer
vacation as a photographer's assistant at the Vogue studios. From
the moment of his first sitting he was hooked. Helping John
Rawlings as he photographed Marlene Dietrich, Himmel recalled,
``really threw me.'' Dietrich was ``extravagantly pleasant _ very
campy,'' he remembers.
</P>
<P>
   At summer's end Himmel gave up teaching and, like many aspiring
young photographers, took Brodovitch's ``Graphic Journalism''
course. ``He liked what I did journalistically,'' said Himmel. ``So
he gave me an assignment for Harper's Bazaar.''
</P>
<P>
   Himmel quickly became a fashion photographer who didn't simply
pose models as static, rarefied creatures on city streets, but made
them part of the streetscape. His mastery of movement in street
photography gave these fashion pictures a special immediacy and
vibrancy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1947 he did a test series of models mixed into the crowds at
the Grand Central Terminal concourse. Photographed from above, the
models _ who were directed to stand still _ were transformed into
islands of tranquillity among the swirling, milling, dizzying,
abstracted crowds. These are the only fashion negatives Himmel has
saved, and photographs made from them are in the Danziger show and
accompanying book.
</P>
<P>
   Himmel's work appeared in the country's major illustrated
magazines. Three of his pictures were included in the monumental
1955 ``Family of Man'' exhibition organized by Edward Steichen at
the Museum of Modern Art. Among them was his lyrical portrait of a
pregnant Ms. Bassman, her dreamy profile contrasted with a
profusion of bold silhouettes of potted plants.
</P>
<P>
   But after a few years of doing fashion photography, Himmel grew
increasingly bored with it. ``I was always interested in the
extremes of it, the limits of where it could go,'' he explained.
``I was never interested in straight fashion photography, and of
course later on what they wanted was the straight stuff.'' By 1950
fashion editors were also losing interest in his photojournalistic
style, preferring more conventional poses.
</P>
<P>
   All along, Himmel had pursued his own projects: photographing
boxers in a gym, people at a horse show, circus performers and
ballet dancers (published as ``Ballet in Action'' in 1954). In his
circus series is an extraordinary example of Himmel's ability to
fool the camera into showing a rope twirler seemingly enveloped in
a big undulating bubble.
</P>
<P>
   Himmel also experimented with attenuated silhouettes of nudes.
In his final photographic series, he made strikingly abstract color
prints from black-and-white negatives, using color photographic
paper and solarizing the images with colored light.
</P>
<P>
   But the more Himmel experimented, the less commercial work came
his way. Finally he simply switched careers.
</P>
<P>
   Does he have any regrets? ``What kills me now,'' he said, ``is I
didn't save the theater personalities' pictures. I wish I had. The
only picture I have left of that is Bert Lahr.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he have any plans to pick up the camera again?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were to go back to photography,'' he replied, ``I would
have to go back with an idea. I haven't thought about that
seriously. To the degree that I have, I haven't come up with
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Himmel remains a psychotherapist. In his spare time he has been
producing meticulous three-dimensional needlepoint wall art. He has
also been creating assemblages _ small, still, delicately
surrealistic worlds out of found objects. One includes his
photographs of attenuated nudes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
