<SLUG> BC-USFS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Competition, interest rates cutting into USFS
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Increased competition may have investors in U.S.
Franchise Systems sleeping a bit uncomfortably in the near future,
President Mike Leven warned Monday. At the same time, the company
reported that third quarter earnings increased substantially.
</P>
<P>
   Leven said that while franchise sales, unit growth and brand
awareness have been strong over the last few months ``we are not
impervious to the increasingly downward trends in the lodging
industry''
</P>
<P>
   He said the company has been hit by increased competition in the
mid- to low-priced market and will be affected by higher interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   The company also might have to take a write-down on a $15
million loan to one of its hotel ownership groups and lose the
interest income. Should that happen, it would mean a 9 cents a
share hit to 2000 earnings, Leven said.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the company expected to earn between 70 cents and 75
cents a share in 2000. Now, he said, the company will not ``even be
close to that that number.''
</P>
<P>
   The warnings came as Atlanta-based USFS reported third quarter
net income of $3 million, or 15 cents a share, compared to
$109,000, or 1 cent per share, for the same period a year earlier.
Net income from continuing operations was 16 cents a share, up from
1 cent a share for the same period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   That was in line with Wall Street expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue for the quarter rose 108 percent to $7 million, compared
to $3.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased with our earnings,'' said Leven. ``Basically, I
think what happened is that we failed to look at some things that
were going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The company said openings of its successful Microtel Inn &AMP;
Suites brand fell in the third quarter. The company had expected to
open 20 new Microtel properties, but opened only 12. Leven said
overhead also increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of that created an environment in which we have to say we
can't make the earnings next year on the base business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company is ranked among the top hotel franchise companies
with its Microtel Inn &AMP; Suites, Hawthorn Suites and Best Inns &AMP;
Suites Brands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a small company doing the best we can with what we
have,'' he said. ``I think the industry is going to be softer.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Woodworth, a vice president with PKF Consulting in Atlanta,
said he expects the lodging market to be flat ``with little or no
growth in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The company ``indicated caution,'' said John Rohs, an analyst
with Schroder Securities in New York. And that spooked some
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what scared most investors,'' he said. ``It makes it
sound like this is not the kind of problem that is going to get
solved in one quarter and it is going to take a little time to work
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Rohs said the company's properties are in a highly competitive
segment of the lodging industry _ the mid- and lower-priced market.
As a result, USFS's outlook is ``murky'' in the short term, but
``the long-term outlook is positive,'' Rohs said. ``The have a
particularly good product with Microtel and a good management
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheila M. Poole writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
