<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Washington) _ (Exclusive) The question of China's
entry into the World Trade Organization may not be dead for this
year, officials say. The U.S. trade representative, Charlene
Barshefsky, announced Monday that she expected formal negotiations
with China to resume this month on its entry into the World Trade
Organization, and some officials said she may travel to China
before a trade meeting in Seattle at the end of the month if there
is enough progress that President Clinton could announce a deal in
Seattle. But in public, Ms. Barshefsky _ once burned when the
president turned down her advice to take the April deal _ is being
quite cautious. ``We have got to see,'' she said Monday, when asked
about the possibility of a deal. ``There is quite a bit of work to
go.'' By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM-SUIT (New York) _ A federal judge ruled Monday that Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani violated the First Amendment when he cut city
funding and began eviction proceedings against the Brooklyn Museum
of Art for mounting an exhibition of contemporary art he deemed
offensive and sacrilegious. The judge ordered the mayor to resume
the city's monthly payments to the museum and end his campaign to
evict the museum and remove its Board of Trustees. By David
Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   AIRCRASH-RDP (Undated) _ Ledeall: Investigators locate the
EgyptAir jet's black box, but have yet to retrieve it; new details
about the plane's descent suggest it was intact when it fell from
33,000 feet to 19,000 feet; the Coast Guard and Navy effort is
officially labeled a recovery effort; teams are working against
time in trying to retrieve the plane, as bad weather is expected
Tuesday. By Robert D. McFadden.
</P>
<P>
   With photos and graphics.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-ADS (Undated) _ Convinced that this yuletide season will
be make-or-break, e-commerce companies are engaged in a very
expensive war to bring their names to consumers through TV
advertising. There is little evidence that such exposure in a
crowded market will prove to be a cost efficient way to attract new
customers. In fact, Amazon.com recently said it would triple
holiday ad spending, a move that gave stock analysts pause and sent
its stock price plunging. The upstarts may be buying air time at
the expense of other important components, such as customer
service, inventory, and simple Web design. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   PARK-RESORTS (Pagosa Springs, Colo.) _ Amid millions of acres of
national forest, private deluxe resorts are blooming, from Colorado
to Maryland to Alaska, sparking fierce battles over land
preservation and the rights of the taxpayers. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-U.S. (Washington) _ (Exclusive) The Clinton
administration is thrashing out policy on how to keep Serbs from
freezing this winter in the context of a European-run pilot program
to send millions of dollars worth of oil to Serbia. By Philip
Shenon.
</P>
