<SLUG> BC-INDIA-STORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DELHI GOVERNMENT CRITICIZED FOR SLOW RESPONSE TO CYCLONE
DEVASTATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ The eastern state of Orissa remained largely
cut off from the rest of India on Monday, four days after the most
ferocious cyclone in recent memory tore through coastal areas with
160 mph winds.
</P>
<P>
   Army rescue teams have been unable to reach the regions most
devastated by Friday's storm. Flood waters are still moving in
torrents across many roads. Where the ground is higher and the
pavement dry, tens of thousands of refugees have set up camp,
sleeping on the blacktop.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1 million people remain homeless, untold numbers are
dead, and so many are hungry that sporadic food riots have broken
out.
</P>
<P>
   Orissa's capital, Bhubaneshwar, has the look of a place that was
destroyed by the stomping of a malign giant, with 90 percent of its
trees uprooted, billboards torn to pieces, and most electric and
telephone lines snapped and frayed.
</P>
<P>
   Only 94 bodies have been recovered, state officials in
Bhubaneshwar said Monday, but the death toll is expected to go far
higher, perhaps into the thousands. Most of the affected areas are
backward villages difficult to get to even under the best of
circumstances. It may be a week or more before they are reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tens of thousands of people are marooned, and we have lost
contact with hundreds and hundreds of villages,'' S.T. Misra,
Orissa's deputy secretary in charge of relief operations, said in
an interview from one of the state capital's few working phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to establish communications with the various district
headquarters by tomorrow, but those villages that are just a
collection of mud huts, I would suppose they have been washed
away,'' Misra said. ``The death toll may go into the thousands, but
that is just a guess. The simple truth is that no one can yet begin
to calculate the extent of the damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Orissa, with a population of 35 million, is one of India's
poorest states. The districts that appear to be the worst hit are
Kendrapara, Jagatsinghpur, Puri, Cuttack and Jajpur, Misra said.
</P>
<P>
   The army has begun the arduous task of clearing roadways of
felled trees. Air force helicopters have begun air-dropping dried
food and fresh water. Naval ships carrying medicines, potable water
and emergency generators have positioned themselves near the port
of Paradip, but will not be able to enter until the channel is
cleared.
</P>
<P>
   An appeal for help has been put out by the International
Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies, asking donors
for more than $3.3 million for emergency relief. The organization
sent an assessment team into the area Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The devastation is extensive, even more than we could have
imagined,'' said Geoffrey Dennis, the head of the regional
delegation for South Asia.
</P>
<P>
   For days, entire families have squatted under thin sheets of
plastic without food or drinking water. Some of the hungry have
attacked trucks carrying emergency supplies. Buses have been
stopped and ransacked as people searched for food. A helicopter
that had carried Defense Minister George Fernandes for a first-hand
look at the damage was beset at one point by a protesting mob.
</P>
<P>
   Monday brought some good news, however: a respite from the rain.
The storm has moved further inland, and its winds have decreased to
40 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Indian officials have called the storm ``a national calamity''
and sanctioned an immediate infusion of $70 million in aid. But
Monday morning many Indian newspapers faulted the New Delhi
government for its continuing lack of preparedness in a country
challenged by nature with such a continuing succession of
disasters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, it is only too well known, those who are
entrusted with this task _ especially if they work for government
departments _ do not respond with a sense of urgency and are
insensitive to the travails of those who badly need their help,''
read an editorial in The Hindu, a usually temperate daily.
</P>
<P>
   The Times of India said: ``From all accounts, there are
contingency plans; a disaster management scheme has been devised
for the very purpose of dealing with cyclones. However, there is
the same desperation, the same abject surrender each time nature
vents her fury.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's cyclone was the second to hit Orissa within a two
weeks. It churned off the coast for several days, gathering
strength from the sea before racing to shore. While some
meteorologists had urged people to evacuate low areas, others
played down the seriousness of the danger.
</P>
</TEXT>
