<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5576 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ANGELS-MILCRASHES-COX     11-01 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGELS-MILCRASHES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Military air shows: Public's right to see or tragedy-in-waiting?
 &HT;    By Russell Carollo
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The F-18 jet fighter crash that killed two
members of the Navy's Blue Angels demonstration team in Georgia
last week is among more than 100 aviation incidents linked to
military air shows since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Never-before-released computer records show that 42 of those
incidents were major accidents that killed at least 100 people.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dead were at least six civilians, one described by
Navy records as an adolescent ejected from a parked aircraft at an
airshow in Pennsylvania in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The military argues that air shows allow the public to see what
it is paying for and serve as a recruiting tool. Critics say the
price may be too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time, we're not considering stopping our participation
in air shows,'' Pentagon spokesman Lt. Col. Steve Campbell said on
Monday. ``Our flying teams are the best of the best. Accidents are
extremely rare.
</P>
<P>
   Air shows, Campbell said, are one way the military communicates
directly with the public, showing people how their tax dollars are
spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They serve to inspire participation and encourage young men
and women to serve in the defense establishment.''
</P>
<P>
   The computer records came from the safety centers for the Army,
Air Force and Navy, which also investigates Marine Corps accidents.
The Dayton Daily News newspaper obtained the records through the
federal Freedom of Information Act during an 18-month examination
of military aviation safety.
</P>
<P>
   The crash involving the Blue Angels occurred as the team
prepared for a show at Moody Air Force Base in Valdosta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Killed in the crash were Lt. Cmdr. Kieron O'Connor of
Burtonsville, Md., who joined the Blue Angels in September 1998,
and Lt. Kevin Colling of Castle Rock, Colo., who joined the team in
September 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy canceled a show at Moody Air Force Base scheduled for
last weekend and another show in Jacksonville, Fla., scheduled for
this coming weekend. A show is still scheduled at Naval Air Station
Pensacola, Fla., scheduled for the weekend of Nov. 12-13.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Naval Safety Center's computer database, the
accident in Georgia was among 36 aviation incidents involving the
Blue Angels since 1980, and it was the first fatal accident
involving the team since 1985, when the team was involved in a
mid-air collision at Niagara Falls, N.Y., killing a 32-year-old
lieutenant commander.
</P>
<P>
   Those 36 incidents occurred between April 1980 and March 1998,
the date the Daily News records were updated, and accounted for two
deaths, eight injuries and $51.5 million in damages _ not counting
the latest accident.
</P>
<P>
   In all, eight people were killed in 16 major accidents involving
the Blue Angels since 1972, Col. Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   On July 4, 1996, a Blue Angels F-18A Hornet headed for Traverse
City, Mich., sustained more than $75,000 in damage near
Wright-Patterson Air Force Base in Dayton when a refueling
receptacle cover was sucked into an engine.
</P>
<P>
   In all three services, there were at least 105 aviation
incidents, ranging in severity from minor emergencies to fatal
crashes, linked to air shows, rehearsals or demonstration teams.
Those accidents cost at least $284 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News records end in early 1998 and vary somewhat among
the services, which keep separate databases. Army and Air Force
records date back to 1972, but Navy records begin eight years
later, in 1980. In addition, Army records are incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   The Army had the highest number of dead, 68. Forty-six of those
were killed in a single accident on Sept. 11, 1982, in Mannheim,
West Germany. Six others were killed and 16 injured in a single
crash at Fort Campbell, Ken., on June 18, 1996, when two UH-60
Blackhawk helicopters collided during a demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen others were killed in incidents the Army described as
``demonstrations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Navy accounted for the largest number of incidents with 60,
including 13 major accidents in which 17 people were killed. Three
others were identified as missing.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force accounted for the largest dollar loss, $134.5
million. Much of that came from a single crash, on Sept. 14, 1997,
when an F-117 Stealth Fighter crashed into an apartment complex in
Maryland. The pilot ejected, but the plane was destroyed. The cost
was estimated at $51.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Campbell said the Air Force Thunderbirds accounted for 10
deaths since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Following that accident, Sen. John W. Warner, R-Va., chairman of
the Senate Armed Services Committee, said he was concerned about
the cost of risking front line aircraft in air demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those 117s are about $100 million a copy if you look at total
program costs,'' he said during a hearing. ``That's a lot of
money.''
</P>
<P>
   The most serious Air Force accident on its safety center
database came on March 13, 1987, when a KC-135 tanker crashed at
Fairchild Air Force Base, Wash., killing seven people. The plane
was practicing a routine for a newly formed air demonstration team
called the Thunderhawks.
</P>
<P>
   The Thunderhawks, planned to be the former Strategic Air
Command's official air demonstration team, never flew in an air
show and were disbanded following the fatal crash.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if continuing the air shows was worth the death toll, Col.
Campbell said, ``We don't think anything is worth loss of life.
Every accident is preventable. Accidents occur whether you fly
training missions or demonstration missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that doesn't mean when accidents happen we're going to
stop what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell Carollo writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAYTON NEWSPAPERS INC., DAYTON, OHIO
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-11-01-99 1814EST
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
