<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5579 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-CENTURY-CHOICE-NYT     11-01 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CENTURY-CHOICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: WHEN TV CHANGED AMERICAN POLITICS
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Wis., Ala.)  (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(With TV-CENTURY) 
(nk) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a sidewalk in the shopping district of a small Wisconsin
town, Hubert H. Humphrey stops passers-by and hands out business
cards. ``Good to meet you,'' he says over and over. ``I hope you'll
be at the election booth tomorrow, April 5. Let me give you one of
my cards.'' Those cards might as well say ``Willy Loman for
President.'' With his baggy overcoat and his hat at an angle that
should look jaunty but only manages to seem sad, Humphrey looks
desperately old-fashioned compared with the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever John F. Kennedy, his opponent in this 1960 presidential
primary, steps out of his car, young women rush at him to get
autographs. The camera follows Kennedy as he wades into an
energetic and grasping crowd in the kind of scene that has become
commonplace for rock stars.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after that primary, the Kennedy-Nixon debates allowed
voters to see how Kennedy and the camera adored each other, and
television permanently transformed American politics. But the
visual evidence of that immense cultural change is all here,
captured months earlier in Robert Drew's ``Primary.''
</P>
<P>
   A restored version of that groundbreaking cinema verite work
begins ``A Century of Reality,'' a monthlong series on Turner
Classic Movies. The documentaries range from chestnuts to oddities,
but by far the most revealing are Tuesday night's political
documentaries by Drew. Three years after ``Primary,'' with Kennedy
in the White House, ``Crisis'' eavesdropped as Robert F. Kennedy,
the attorney general, forced a defiant Gov. George C. Wallace to
allow black students to enroll at the University of Alabama.
Sophisticated and influential in themselves, these films are also
fascinating documents that chart how the camera has affected
politics and government in the last four decades.
</P>
<P>
   Though ``Primary'' will be shown in a restored version, its
sound is shaky and its black-and-white photography seems quaint.
But these dated elements seem at odds with the film's modern feel,
which flows from its camera-savvy subjects and sleek editing style.
At a rally full of men and women who look as if they have stepped
out of a 1950s Sears catalog, all the Kennedys seem impossibly
glamorous and young. Jacqueline Kennedy shyly speaks a single line
of Polish and the flattered crowd goes crazy. Meanwhile, Drew's
camera closes in as she nervously twiddles the fingers of her
white-gloved hands behind her back.
</P>
<P>
   Then Robert Kennedy steps on stage to charm voters with wry
humor about his enormous extended family. And the candidate himself
_ warm, commanding, ever so slightly aloof _ exudes Hollywood-style
magnetism. The idea of politics as performance, so taken for
granted now, started in rooms like this.
</P>
<P>
   So did much of what we know as cinema verite. The photographers
on ``Primary'' included three of the most dynamic documentary
filmmakers of the last decades: Richard Leacock, Albert Maysles and
D.A. Pennebaker. There is a direct line, in fact, from ``Primary''
and ``Crisis'' to ``The War Room,'' Pennebaker and Chris Hegedus'
engrossing and demystifying look behind the scenes at the 1992
Clinton campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crisis,'' filmed in June 1963, captures Robert Kennedy having
breakfast at home with his children and meeting with his brother at
the White House. He knew that Wallace intended to stand on the
university steps, blocking the two black students when they arrived
to register. The Kennedys discuss if and when to call out the
National Guard. If troops were put on alert in advance, the
Kennedys would look like the heavies; but if they waited it would
take another day to mobilize the soldiers and the students would
have to walk away in temporary defeat.
</P>
<P>
   And even with troops standing by, there would be strategic
problems. Robert Kennedy is heard on the phone talking to a
National Guard officer, planning how to move Wallace physically.
``I'm not very much in favor of picking the governor up,'' Kennedy
says. It would be better ``if you had enough people just to push
him aside.'' He doesn't need to add that hauling off a governor
would not have created a picture that generated support for the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the acute sense of image-making that Drew and his
subjects share, there are moments in ``Crisis'' that are jolting in
this age of instant communication and 24-hour television news.
Robert Kennedy stayed in Washington while a deputy attorney
general, Nicholas deB. Katzenbach, accompanied the students up the
university steps and confronted Wallace. Although dozens of
television cameras were filming the scene, the man in charge got
his minute-by-minute information by phone. ``Is he getting to talk
to the governor?'' Kennedy asks anxiously into the speakerphone on
his desk. Today, every television viewer in the country could
witness such a confrontation while it was unfolding on CNN, MSNBC
and Fox News. As that political era fades into history, that change
is the one that makes ``Crisis'' seem most like a message from the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's offerings in ``A Century of Reality,'' a
monthlong series of historical documentaries on the Turner Classic
Movies channel:
</P>
<P>
   ``Primary'' (Robert Drew, 1960), Kennedy and Humphrey campaigns
for the Democratic presidential nomination, at 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crisis: Behind a Presidential Commitment'' (Robert Drew,
1963), confrontation over desegregation of the University of
Alabama, at 9 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faces of November'' (Robert Drew, 1963), on Kennedy's funeral,
at 10 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four Days in November'' (Mel Stuart, 1964), response to
Kennedy's assassination, at 10:15 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   ``Point of Order'' (Emile de Antonio, 1964), on the McCarthy
hearings, at 10:30 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   ``The War at Home'' (Glenn Silber, 1979), on opposition to the
Vietnam War, focusing on protests at the University of Wisconsin,
at 12:30 p.m. ET.
</P>
</TEXT>
