<HEADER>
A5580 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-VIEQUES-BOMBING-HNS &LR;      11-01 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIEQUES-BOMBING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUERTO RICO AND PENTAGON FAIL TO FIND COMPROMISE ON TARGET RANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senior officials from Puerto Rico and the Pentagon
ended emergency talks Monday without finding a compromise solution
to the six-month stalemate over whether the Navy can use a target
range on the island of Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   The setback means that President Clinton now faces a politically
delicate decision over whether to order resumption of live fire
combat training on the target range, despite the objections of
Puerto Rico's political leaders, First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton,
Vice President Al Gore, former Sen. Bill Bradley and Hispanic
lawmakers in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy says it needs a presidential go-ahead by mid-November
if a Navy-Marine Corps battle group led by the aircraft carrier USS
Dwight D. Eisenhower is to train on Vieques before sailing for the
Persian Gulf on Feb. 18.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing range has been closed since April 19 when a Marine
pilot mistakenly bombed a rangvation post, killing a Puerto
Rican security guard working for the Navy and injuring four other
civilians working on the range.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Puerto Rico Gov. Pedro Rossello, a Democrat with
close ties to Gore and Mrs. Clinton, adamantly ruled out further
discussions with the Pentagon unless the Navy first agrees to
permanently end 58 years of bombing on an island that is home to
more than 9,300 civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello, reiterating a hard-line at the outset of two days of
meetings in the nation's capital including one with Mrs. Clinton,
said his administration would immediately seek a federal court
injunction to stop any resumption of Navy bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remain very hopeful that the president will come down with a
decision that will prevent future bombing,'' Rossello told
reporters. ``But again, the courts are available for an injunction
basically preventing further bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   The last-ditch effort to find a compromise took place during a
90- minute meeting at the Pentagon between the governor's chief of
staff, Angel Morey, and two Pentagon officials _ Rudy deLeon,
undersecretary of defense for personnel, and Robert Tyrer, chief of
staff for Defense Secretary William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon official, speaking on condition of anonymity, later
said that no decisions were made and that no follow-up meetings
were planned.
</P>
<P>
   Morey said that neither the Pentagon nor Puerto Rico offered
concessions to reach a compromise. Morey said he emphasized that
Puerto Rico's demand that the Navy withdraw from Vieques was a
matter of principle rather than a matter of negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico's position remains: ``Not one more bomb _ not now,
not Dec. 1, not at the end of the year, not in the new
millennium,'' Morey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They explained their needs and I explained our position,'' he
continued. ``If they can find a way to reconcile their needs with
our position, then we are moving forward in this process.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Morey and Rossello said no further talks with the Pentagon
or the Navy will be scheduled because the Navy has not accepted
Puerto Rico's demands for a permanent end to bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Armed Services Committee Chairman John Warner, R-Va., in
a bid to pressure the White House, says that he plans to convene an
emergency session of the Senate Armed Services Committee if the
White House decides to deploy the Eisenhower battle group without
live fire training on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Warner introduced a sense of the Senate resolution last Friday
demanding that Clinton not deploy the Eisenhower battle group until
he reviews the combat readiness of the armada and notifies Congress
that the forces are ``free of serious deficiencies in major warfare
areas.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton awaits recommendations from his defense secretary on the
Navy's future use of Vieques. Morey said he has asked the White
House for a face-to-face meeting with the president before a final
decision is made.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 19, Cohen received recommendations from a four-member
panel appointed at the request of the president to look for a
compromise. The Pentagon review panel recommended reducing live
fire combat training on Vieques from 180 days a year to 130 days a
year, during a five-year phase out of Navy operations on the
33,000-acre island.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello said Monday that Gore has told him that he supports
Puerto Rico's demands for cessation of bombardment and Navy
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came to the conclusion that the Navy should leave Vieques
and look for other sites for their training,'' said Rossello,
Gore's fund raising chief in Puerto Rico. Rossello said he would
welcome a public statement by Gore, as Bradley has made.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
