<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-WORLD-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN EAST TIMOR, BUILDING A NATION FROM THE BASICS UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, East Timor _ Even before the recent violence that
destroyed most of East Timor's buildings, the creation of a newly
independent society and economy here presented a harsh case study
in development from the ground up.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a spokesman for the World Bank compares the task to landing
on a desert island and trying to build a nation from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from roads, ports, airfields and power plants, East Timor
has almost none of the basic elements of a functioning nation: no
budget or banking system, no judiciary or law enforcement, no civil
service or government institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Its educational, health care, trade and agriculture systems are
a shambles. Most of its people are subsistence farmers; most are
illiterate.
</P>
<P>
   A 40-member assessment team led by the World Bank received an
immediate initiation into the problems ahead when it arrived here
last week and began its work from a tent city without electricity
or running water. The food is military rations.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are extremely unusual conditions for us,'' said the
director of the mission, Klaus Rohland, who runs the bank's
operations in the Pacific Islands.
</P>
<P>
   He said his team's task _ in advance of an international donors'
conference next month _ is urgent and delicate.
</P>
<P>
   With a limited window of time before international attention
moves elsewhere, he said, funds must be raised soon. But if the
team's efforts are not carefully concentrated, they could do as
much harm as good, skewing East Timor's economy and creating social
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``East Timor can expect huge international interest maybe for
the next three to four years,'' he said. ``After that it's yet
another Pacific island. So whatever money comes in now, if it is
not spent properly it's wasted.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without these potential problems, Rohland said, the
elements of a functioning society are a complex Rubik's Cube of
interrelated institutions: ``No education system without
infrastructure, no civil service without development of the private
sector: They are all linked.''
</P>
<P>
   Foremost among the pitfalls, he said, was the inevitable
economic distortion of the huge international assistance program
that was being established, creating a voracious service economy
that would eventually shrink.
</P>
<P>
   Since Indonesia annexed the former Portuguese colony as its 27th
province in 1976, East Timor has been administered by Indonesia,
with Indonesians running everything from schools to power plants.
</P>
<P>
   With its formal grant of independence last week, East Timor
faces the challenge of managing its own affairs for the first time
since it became a colony more than 400 years ago. It is utterly
unprepared.
</P>
<P>
   Under a U.N. administration that will run East Timor during a
transition period of two or three years, the small land of 800,000
people will be home to thousands of foreign officials, aid workers
and peacekeeping troops.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will this inflate the economy, Rohland said, but also
will create a temporary demand for jobs designed to support the
foreign workers, stimulating urban migration.
</P>
<P>
   This would shift the focus from East Timor's long-term economic
foundation, agriculture, and could leave the capital with a
potentially dangerous population of unemployed young men.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can already see all these young men running around in the
city center,'' Rohland said. ``The priority is to get them back to
the villages where the real work needs to be done. It's a dangerous
mixture: a huge number of unemployed young people, a total
destruction of the social fabric.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign of destruction by military-backed militias in
September, after East Timor's vote for independence on Aug. 30,
pushed the territory back to ground zero.
</P>
<P>
   But it was already the poorest of Indonesia's provinces, said
Sarah Cliffe, an economist for the World Bank who is a member of
the assessment team.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's investment budget here was almost double per capita
that of other provinces, she said, but the ``development outcome''
was at the bottom _ the fewest schools, clinics and other basic
services per person of any province.
</P>
<P>
   That discrepancy could support a widespread analysis that much
of Indonesia's spending here went to support its huge military
presence, which at one point reached 24,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, East Timor's very poverty is the most hopeful
factor that will contribute to the territory's eventual recovery,
Rohland said. Ninety percent of its economy has been based on
agriculture, particularly the plantations that produce coffee, the
territory's leading export.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that makes me feel more optimistic,'' he
said. ``This is not a developed economy that has been bombed back
to the Stone Age. It was already a poor country.''
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman for the World Bank team here, Graham Barrett, said
the bank would set up a trust fund for donors to which it would
contribute up to $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   The money will come in grants, not loans, to the fledgling
nation, he said. ``This is a country that has no need of an instant
debt load.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
