<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5583 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-CRIME-REVIEW-NYT     11-01 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CRIME-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF CAMERAS AND CONSEQUENCES AT A WOMEN'S PRISON
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the course of a somewhat strained exchange with the chief
medical officer at the Valley State Prison for Women in central
California, Ted Koppel announces that for the moment he is acting
as an advocate for the prisoners who have been complaining to him
about their medical care.
</P>
<P>
   That should startle few viewers of ``Crime and Punishment,'' a
weeklong series about the largest women's prison in the United
States, which began on Friday on ``Nightline.'' The sympathetic
hearing Koppel gives the prisoners' allegations is fairly typical
of television's approach to a perennial subject and is in marked
contrast to the skepticism with which he treats the responses of
Dr. Anthony Di Domenico.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Di Domenico is asking for it. In countering charges
that the prison's medical staff is doing unnecessary cervical
examinations, he suggests that many inmates ``deal in a great deal
of fiction'' and that some ``like to be examined _ it's the only
male contact they get.'' Even after Koppel cautions him, ``That's
an extraordinary thing to say,'' the doctor repeats that ``maybe
there's some gratification on their part from the exam.''
</P>
<P>
   A day after the interview, Di Domenico's boss, Dr. Susan
Steinberg, flew down from Sacramento to meet with Koppel, and
before you could say pre-emptive protection, Di Domenico, who had
lately been described by Steinberg as ``a very dedicated,
compassionate physician,'' was reassigned to a job in which he
would have no contact with patients. She assured Koppel that ``this
doctor will never have patient care again in the Department of
Correction.''
</P>
<P>
   What do we have here? Hard-hitting journalism or an example of
bureaucratic timidity confronted with the power of television?
Although Di Domenico may have made few friends with his benighted
comments about the women in his care, and he assuredly committed
the television crime of insensitivity, Koppel provided no evidence
to support the inmates' stories of medical misdemeanors, notably
unnecessary cervical examinations. (``It doesn't matter what you go
in there for,'' one woman says, ``he wants to give you a PAP
smear.'') Steinberg reports that in her year and a half in her job,
she has never received a complaint from Valley State about
physicians' doing inappropriate pelvic examinations.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it beyond belief that prisoners (and their lawyers) might
lie about this or other complaints to which Koppel gives much
attention and his own implied backing. When it comes to prisoner
behavior, Koppel, the inmates' advocate, plays psychologist: ``It's
easy for frustration to turn to anger and for anger to evolve into
psychosis in a place like this.'' An inmate in a maximum-security
section puts the situation in straighter language: ``There's an
awful lot of disrespectful people housed back here.''
</P>
<P>
   In a homily that sets the tone for his report, Koppel says:
``The women here have been sentenced to forfeit their freedom, not
their dignity or their self-respect or their health.'' Nobody is
likely to quarrel with that. But he does little to explore what
``dignity'' and ``self-respect'' mean in prison. He calls strip
searches, vividly described here, ``the final indignity,'' but the
program notes how difficult it is for warders to control prisoners'
access to drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Koppel promises one admitted addict _ who confesses, ``I love
drugs, and life doesn't really matter to me without it'' _ help in
getting a job, and she pledges in a teary scene that she will
reform. It's effective television, but Koppel, a journalist after
all, not a social worker, does not exert himself in evaluating the
credibility of inmates' accounts of their records or their
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledges that some of the women have committed ``quite
horrific crimes'' and quotes a correction officer on the duty to
keep criminals ``on this side of the wall'' for society's
protection, but the chronic message of the series is that most of
the women are victims of abuse by families, boyfriends, society and
the prison system. We are supposed to take their word for it. The
approach succumbs to the fashion for stories of sexual abuse and to
television's craving for human interest, even at the expense of
straight reporting, a disappointment coming from the usually
businesslike Koppel.
</P>
<P>
   As for Di Domenico, should his crudely expressed opinions and
benighted insinuations be enough, without solid evidence of
malfeasance, to blacken his career and disqualify him from a job
that for all Koppel and ``Nightline'' viewers know, he was doing in
a professional manner? His removal was a quick and easy way for his
superiors to get rid of a nationally televised embarrassment, and
so, perhaps unintentionally, a famous journalist's reputation and
reach became weapons to punish this doctor for his words, not any
documented deeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``NIGHTLINE: Crime and Punishment: Women in Prison''
</P>
<P>
   ABC, Tuesday night through Friday night at 11:30 ET
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 7 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Ted Koppel, anchor and managing editor; Tom Bettag, executive
producer; Mark Nelson, senior producer; Jay LaMonica, producer;
Gillian Parker, producer. A production of ABC News.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
