<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES REFUSE TO REINSTATE SEXUAL HARASSMENT SUIT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday refused without comment
to reinstate a sexual harassment lawsuit brought by an employee of
the Texas comptroller's office who had claimed unwanted touching
and lewd comments from a co-worker.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Jean Shepherd, who has held a variety of posts in the
comptroller's office, had claimed that colleague Jodie Moore in
1993 often touched ``various parts'' of her and would make comments
about her body.
</P>
<P>
   Shepherd alleged that she complained to her bosses, Fern
Francis-Jackson and Grundy Wiley, about the harassment but nothing
was done.
</P>
<P>
   Shepherd suffered a nervous breakdown in the winter of 1994,
which she said resulted from the harassment, and was admitted to a
psychiatric ward for a week. She was then placed on a medical leave
of absence, not returning to work until June 20, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   During her hospitalization, Wiley was fired and Francis-Jackson
was demoted because of their failure to handle Shepherd's
complaint's adequately. Moore, on his own initiative, transferred
to another department.
</P>
<P>
   Shepherd sued the comptroller's office in Texas state court Jan.
17, 1997, alleging that the agency should be held liable for the
harassment she endured. The agency then asserted its right to have
the case heard by the U.S. District Court for Southern Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The district court without comment dismissed the case.
</P>
<P>
   On appeal, the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans
ruled March 16 that Shepherd had failed to prove that the agency
tolerated the harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find, based on a consideration of all the circumstances,
that Moore's conduct did not render Shepherd's work environment
objectively hostile or abusive,'' the 5th Circuit ruled. ``We find
each comment made by Moore to be the equivalent of a mere utterance
of an epithet that engenders offensive feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   In her unsuccessful appeal to the Supreme Court, Shepherd argued
that the 5th Circuit was too strict in deciding how egregious
office behavior must be before it reached the level of illegal
sexual harassment under Title VII of the federal 1964 Civil Rights
Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Repeated efforts to look down petitioner's dress or blouse,
and regular unwanted stroking of petitioner's arm, the court
reasoned, could not support a Title VII claim _ no matter how often
they occurred _ because they were not as severe as actually
grabbing a woman's breast,'' wrote Shepherd's lawyer, Eric
Schnapper of Seattle, in a legal brief to the high court. ``Since,
on the 5th Circuit's views, none of these abuses were serious
enough to support a hostile-environment claim, Title VII would
allow an employer to knowingly tolerate or even encourage the
obnoxious conduct that occurred in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston attorney Peter Costea, who represented Shepherd in the
lower courts, assisted Schnapper on the brief.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Attorney General John Cornyn, representing the state
comptroller's office, successfully urged the justices to reject the
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply put, the severity of Moore's conduct was not
sufficiently egregious to constitute a hostile work environment
claim,'' Cornyn wrote in a brief to the justices. ``The 5th Circuit
correctly labeled the comments made by Moore as `boorish and
offensive.' Necessarily, the 5th Circuit held, based on a
consideration of all the circumstances, that Moore's conduct did
not render Shepherd's work environment objectively hostile or
abusive.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
