<SLUG> BC-TV-EARLY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAKING UP TO GUMBEL, SERVED IN A NEW BLEND
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   During Monday's premiere of ``The Early Show,'' CBS's entry into
the morning-show wars, Bryant Gumbel's smartest move was his first.
He announced that he and his co-anchor, the virtually unknown Jane
Clayson, had had their ``enthusiasm tempered enormously by a major
tragedy,'' the Egyptian airliner crash on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably that news prevented the CBS stars from jumping up
and down with excitement. But it doesn't explain the pokey pace and
cloned feel, suggesting that ``The Early Show'' is in an amoebalike
state of development. So far it has a noisy location, a cipher of a
co-anchor and Bryant Gumbel.
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel (secret weapon or disaster in the making?) is the most
intriguing and curious part of this project. Warmth, fuzziness and
chipper personalities are now at a premium in the morning, and he
would have been an unlikely choice if not for his fabulously
successful run on ``Today.'' But will he lead ``The Early Show'' in
a less cloying direction than the competition or will he become
less acerbic to survive? Monday sent mixed signals. Surely Gumbel's
stature helped get him an interview with President Clinton, taped
on Sunday. Yet the interview was soft and unsurprising. Asked about
polls that suggested he would be a liability campaigning for Al
Gore and Hillary Rodham Clinton, the president said voters wanted
to make up their own minds.
</P>
<P>
   The show's dampened enthusiasm didn't prevent endless plugs.
Kevin James, the star of the CBS working-class sitcom ``The King of
Queens,'' gave a supposedly comic but genuinely unfunny tour of the
upscale Fifth Avenue neighborhood surrounding the ``Early Show''
studio. And the relentlessly self-promoting Donald Trump, who owns
the building, greeted the hosts and got in a plug for an insurance
company. That's what a serious presidential candidate does, right?
</P>
<P>
   It is now required, of course, for morning shows to feature a
set with a window onto the sidewalk and forays by the anchors into
the crowd. The noise of trucks and sirens Monday sometimes made it
difficult to hear the anchors and Mark McEwen, the weather and
entertainment reporter, when they were outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Ms. Clayson did a stiff, rote interview with the
author of a book about marital infidelity near the end of the show,
she had every reason to look grim. Anyone flipping to NBC would
have caught Mariah Carey's live performance in Rockefeller Plaza on
``Today.'' Originally booked for ``The Early Show,'' Ms. Carey
bolted to the competition last week, citing fears that CBS could
not get the permit for an outdoor performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today'' has a seamlessness and rhythm that helps explains its
popularity. ABC's ``Good Morning America'' has improved in ratings
and appeal by bringing in Charles Gibson and Diane Sawyer,
demonstrating the drawing power of familiar, likable personalities.
This week ``The Early Show'' will bring on Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, Gore and Bill Bradley on consecutive days, and it has at
least a half-dozen regular segments still to be unveiled. But
nothing iconoclastic is planned. Call it what you like, this truly
is The Bryant Gumbel Show, his to succeed in or fail.
</P>
<P>
   THE EARLY SHOW
</P>
<P>
   CBS, weekday mornings at 7 ET
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 2 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Al Berman, executive producer; Steve Friedman, senior executive
producer; Jose Diaz-Balart, Hattie Kauffman, Dr. Emily Senay and
Herb Weisbaum, correspondents; Martha Stewart, Bob Vila, Dr.
Bernadine Healy, Eleanor Mondale and Kristin Jeannette-Meyers,
contributors; Jim Ackerman, Andrew Cohen, Laura Dubowski, James
Segelstein and Alex Wallace, senior producers; Don Poole, Anjie
Taylor and Stephanie Zarpas, broadcast producers; Don Roy King,
director. A production of CBS News. Bryant Gumbel and Jane Clayson,
anchors.
</P>
</TEXT>
