<P>
   &UR; EGYPTAIR CRASH &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 2 pages of stories, photos and graphics
on the EgyptAir crash.
</P>
<P>
   AIRCRASH-RDP (Undated) _ Ledeall: Investigators locate the
EgyptAir jet's black box, but have yet to retrieve it; new details
about the plane's descent suggest it was intact when it fell from
33,000 feet to 19,000 feet; the Coast Guard and Navy effort is
officially labeled a recovery effort; teams are working against
time in trying to retrieve the plane, as bad weather is expected
Tuesday. By Robert D. McFadden.
</P>
<P>
   With photos and graphics.
</P>
<P>
   AIRCRASH-VICTIMS (Undated) _ More on those who died. By Francis
X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   AIRCRASH-INQUIRY (Newport, R.I.) _ Developments: The Egyptair
Boeing 767 that crashed Sunday was equipped with an unusually
sophisticated ``black box,'' one that recorded three times as many
categories of data as the standard required in the United States,
Boeing said today. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   AIRCRASH-TWA800 (Undated) _ Thee TWA Flight 800 investigation
hangs over the Egyptair inquiry, both informing this investigation
and affecting how it being done and presented, for both better and
worse. By Andrew Revkin. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   AIRCRASH-RECOVER (Undated) _ The accounts of the merchant marine
cadets who came upon the wreckage. By Andrew C. Revkin. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   These stories, budgeted earlier, are now scratched:
</P>
<P>
   AIRCRASH-SCENE and AIRCRASH-STUDENTS, their spot elements folded
into AIRCRASH-VICTIMS.
</P>
