<HEADER>
A5600 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-GENEALOGY-BOOM-2TAKES     11-01 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENEALOGY-BOOM-2TAKES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DOT-COM FAMILY TREE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until recently, most of Pamela Titzer-Garrison's family history
was locked away in her father's rapidly fading memory.
</P>
<P>
   Then her uncle _ her father's last surviving sibling _ died, and
the Saginaw, Texas, mother knew it was up to her to chronicle her
family's past. Not just for her father, but for her children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called Indiana and found a distant relative that had some
written records, so that kind of gave me a start,'' Titzer-Garrison
says. ``I came here because the library kept showing up on the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Titzer-Garrison is doing research at the Family History Center,
located in the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints in
southwest Fort Worth. It is one of two local branches of the Family
History Center run by the Mormon church, which maintains one of the
world's most extensive genealogical research databases.
</P>
<P>
   Titzer-Garrison is researching information about her
great-great-grandfather, Johann Titzer, who immigrated to the
United States from Germany between 1844 and 1850 and settled in
southern Indiana. The center's Peggy Besselievre guides her through
an Internet search of German maps.
</P>
<P>
   Titzer-Garrison knows that Johann Titzer and his two brothers
were Catholic. She knows they were farmers and that he had seven
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited,'' she says. ``I was up till 1 a.m. the other
night. I found a town in Germany with the name Titzer. I couldn't
sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Besselievre, who runs the center with her husband, Philip, says
this is typical of those tracing their genealogy. Pieces of
information usually provide the impetus for more research.
</P>
<P>
   There are now an estimated 100 million Americans like
Titzer-Garrison who are tracing their family history, digging for
their roots, says Kathleen Hinckley, author of ``Locating Lost
Family Members &AMP; Friends.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you know that your great-great-grandfather was in the
Civil War or the gold rush, you not only have a greater
appreciation of American history, (but) that becomes the driving
force to do more research,'' Hinckley says.
</P>
<P>
   Slaves' descendants face obstacles
</P>
<P>
   Americans' interest in family history first peaked after the
critically acclaimed TV miniseries ``Roots'' aired in 1977. Now,
the Internet is helping create an even bigger boom as people of all
ages trace their roots. Some are are even forming teams to research
their family history, and many are seeking help from genealogists
and family-history detectives like Hinckley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody I know anticipated this level of
interest,'' says John Wylie, a professional genealogist and
co-founder of GENTECH, a nonprofit national education organization
that promotes the responsible use of computers in family history
research.
</P>
<P>
   Wylie says that once people are hooked by the Internet, they
continue their search by using libraries and the National Archives,
and by joining one of approximately 3,000 genealogical
associations.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Internet provides a window to the past,
genealogists stress that using the information superhighway is just
one step in a laborious process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beginning genealogists make hasty decisions and go off
climbing the wrong tree,'' Hinckley says. ``The Internet opens the
door into the wide world of genealogy, but there are more original
records scattered in courthouses and libraries.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two types of genealogy Web sites: free sites that are
generally paid for by advertising, and fee-based sites that require
users to buy a product or a subscription.
</P>
<P>
   Fee-based sites are the largest, Wylie says, but only a few _
among them www.ancestry.com _ are up and running.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison. there are approximately 51,000 free sites. That
does not include another 100,000 sites that people have established
for their own families.
</P>
<P>
   Even using all the sources available, experts say that tracing
your heritage can be tricky, especially for African-Americans who
are descendants of slaves.
</P>
<P>
   Because census reports only recorded the names of free people,
slaves were excluded. Birth dates and locations may be inaccurate
because many slaves didn't know where or exactly when they were
born. And family members were often sold.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth Star-Telegram asked Hinckley to find out as much
about this reporter's family as possible for $300. She and Wylie
are professional genealogists who will do the detective work for a
fee.
</P>
<P>
   After nine hours of research, Hinckley was able to construct a
family pedigree that spanned four generations and more than 100
years. But there wasn't much information beyond names, birth dates
and marriages. Census tracts showed whether ancestors could read,
owned or rented a home, and what they did for a living.
</P>
<P>
   Hinckley says the material was fairly easy to collect because my
family lived in one place for the most part. But to trace my
family's history back to the time of slavery would have been more
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Joy Jones, an author and storyteller living in Washington, D.C.,
says African-American family history often is more anecdotal than
it is documented.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' mother, for instance, has done a formal genealogy of her
side of the family, while her father did it through storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The telling of stories is not just an African-American thing,
but a primal thing in humans, from cavemen gathered around the fire
to yuppies communicating through e-mails,'' Jones says.
</P>
<P>
   She suggests that families save their stories in other ways,
too, such as listing all the addresses where they've lived and the
types of cars they've owned, and saving tapes from their answering
machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will have the voices of people you loved,'' Jones says.
MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   Mormon church keeps extensive files
</P>
<P>
   The Mormon church, however, may be the best source for tracing
family history. Located in Salt Lake City, the church has been
involved in genealogy since its founding nearly 170 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The church's goal is to help its members find names of deceased
persons to baptize by proxy, an ordinance that Mormons believe
gives the dead the opportunity to embrace the faith in the
afterlife.
</P>
<P>
   The Mormon church is considered the world's largest collector of
genealogical data, with 2 billion rolls of microfilm, 700,000
microfiches and 280,000 books in its Salt Lake City library.
</P>
<P>
   About 800,000 people worldwide visit the library every year to
research their family tree, says Elaine Hasleton, the library's
public affairs supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have census records, federal and state records from 1790 to
1920,'' she says. ``We have probate records, land records, cemetery
listings, and family history books that we obtain through
individual donations.''
</P>
<P>
   The library also catalogs purchase records, immigration records,
county histories and several large databases, among them ancestor
files and an international genealogical index.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, those two files hold about 340 million names from
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the Mormon church also launched its own Web site,
www.familysearch.com. It contains links to 400 million names dating
to 1500, many with family pedigree charts, and gets 8 million hits
a day.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a century, the Mormon church has dispatched
members throughout the world, first to hand-copy and then to
photograph and microfilm parish and civil records.
</P>
<P>
   The church has approximately 3,400 Family History Centers
throughout the United States and in 72 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Titzer-Garrison traveled 20 miles from her home in Saginaw to
the Fort Worth branch to do her research. Although her trip didn't
produce a lot of new information, she gained some insight about
German culture from the center's volunteers. She believes that her
great-great-grandfather was probably a member of the German army
because all young men were required to serve.
</P>
<P>
   She is determined to continue her quest for information and to
pass it on to the next generation of her family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hooked,'' she says.
___
How to climb your family tree
</P>
<P>
   Researching family history can be a time-consuming project.
There are no shortcuts, and those who really want to find their
roots must be ready to invest time and maybe some money. Here's a
look at the resources available as you begin the search.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet:
</P>
<P>
   A few of the better Web sites:
</P>
<P>
   GENTECH, genealogy support organization, www.gentech.org.
</P>
<P>
   Mormon genealogy site, www.familysearch.org.
</P>
<P>
   The Statue of Liberty-Ellis Island Foundation,
www.ellisisland.org.
</P>
<P>
   Rootsweb, www.rootsweb. com.
</P>
<P>
   Links to more than 55,000 Web sites, www.cyndislist.com.
</P>
<P>
   Other tips:
</P>
<P>
   Visit the library; it will have such things as obituaries and
local history.
</P>
<P>
   Attend a class. Local genealogy societies sometimes offer
workshops on surfing the Net for family history.
</P>
<P>
   Read a book; there are many on how to research your family tree,
including Kathleen Hinckley's ``Locating Lost Family Members &AMP;
Friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk to relatives, especially grandparents. They are a great
source of family history.
</P>
<P>
   Check for name changes; somewhere along the line a relative may
have changed the spelling of his or her last name or shortened it.
It may also have been recorded incorrectly in official records or
on headstones.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
