<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-ADS-ART-1130(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE COMPANIES USING TV ADS TO SPUR HOLIDAY SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Send.com is buying its 15 minutes of fame right now.
</P>
<P>
   The year-old Internet gift site has raised only $10 million in
venture capital funding so far, but it has committed to spend $20
million for television advertising on such top-rated shows as Ally
McBeal, Frasier and Monday Night Football in the next eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Its budget would be substantial for even a big retailer like
Amazon.com, which is said to have spent $17 million on television
for all of 1998. But for tiny send.com, which has negligible
revenue and no profits, it is stunningly audacious.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has borrowed against investors' pledges of more
capital to pay for his ad spending spree, Send.com chief executive
Michael Lannon sees little choice. ``Not every company is going to
survive this Christmas,'' he said. ``We are treating the next eight
weeks like an election campaign. Both we and our investors believe
that customers are going to vote on who the leading gift site is,
and only one candidate wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that this holiday season will be make-or-break,
e-retailers are burning through resources as they race one another
to bring their names to consumers through TV advertising.
</P>
<P>
   There is little evidence that such exposure in a crowded market
will prove to be a cost-efficient way to attract new customers. In
fact, Amazon.com recently said it would triple holiday ad spending,
a move that gave stock analysts pause and sent its stock price
plunging. Moreover, in some cases, the start-ups are buying air
time at the expense of other important components, such as customer
service, inventory and simple Web design.
</P>
<P>
   But many companies say they feel compelled to spend everything
they have (and more) and hope the financial markets will refill
their coffers after the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   In all of 1998, Internet companies _ including portals and
online brokerage firms, as well as e-retailers _ accounted for $323
million in TV ad spending, according to Competitive Media
Reporting, an advertising monitoring service. In the first half of
this year, they spent about $400 million on TV, and media buyers
estimate that spending in the second half will far surpass that and
push the sum for the year well past the $1 billion mark.
</P>
<P>
   Though retailers and other gift sites are leading the charge,
almost every site is desperate to register with consumers in the
end-of-year buying crush. Total Internet sales of products and
services like travel are expected to be $6 billion in November and
December, according to Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of e-tailers have sold their souls to the TV networks,
gambling that they can drive massive customers through the site
through mass advertising,'' said David Cowan, a partner in Bessemer
Venture Capital, a Silicon Valley firm that has helped finance such
Web start-ups as Etoys and Mothernature.com. ``This season will be
a proving ground for the TV networks to flex their muscles as the
true portals of e-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   As more Internet companies feel the need to match their
competitors' presence on television, the higher the cost of being a
noticeable player in the TV market will be. ``The price of entry
for an annual plan might be $40 to $50 million a year _ $8 to $10
million a quarter,'' said David Smith, the principal in Mediasmith
Inc., a San Francisco agency that plans and buys ad time for
Interactive firms. ``That is a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   To put that in perspective, an established retailer typically
spends 3 percent to 4 percent of its revenue on advertising,
according to Burt Flickinger III, managing partner of Reach
Marketing, a consulting group in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Gap Inc., one of the United States' largest retailers, with $9
billion in expected 1999 revenue, allotted $157 million for
television advertising last year, reports Competitive Media. And
Gap is ubiquitous on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Nordstrom Inc., the department-store chain with more than $5
billion in revenue last year, has just announced its biggest
national TV and print campaign ever. The $17 million effort will
promote _ what else? _ Nordstromshoes.com, its newest Internet
retailing site.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the feeding frenzy has been a boon to the Old Media
concerns that e-companies tend to mock as dinosaurs. Newspapers,
magazines and radio stations have all seen a generous flood of
media dollars. But TV outlets, with their relatively high rates,
have been swimming in Internet funds.
</P>
<P>
   At the major networks, fees for 30-second ads on top programs
like E.R. and Monday Night Football cost a substantial premium over
last year. For 30-second spots on the Super Bowl, average prices
rocketed from $1.6 million on Fox TV last January to $2 million for
ABC's broadcast in January 2000, partly on the strength of Internet
demand.
</P>
<P>
   CBS Inc. has been trading on the desperation of Internet
companies by offering television time in exchange for stock in
those ventures. ``We've been swapping equity for branding,'' said
company spokesman Gil Schwartz, who said the network now has stakes
in 13 companies. Four of the companies, including CBS marketwatch
and cbsmedscape.com, are public, and CBS' stake in those firms is
worth more than half a billion dollars, Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
   The obsession with television is a new and unproven strategy
among Internet companies. Even a year ago, most Internet companies
concentrated their ad dollars online. ``Last Christmas, merchants
were allocating 70 to 80 percent of their marketing budgets online
largely at portals,'' said Ken Cassar, a digital commerce analyst
at Jupiter Communications, a new media consulting firm. ``Today,
that is flipped, with the majority being spent on traditional media
and most in television.''
</P>
<P>
   Several factors have led to the transformation of marketing
across the industry. There is a general belief that online
advertising through banners and portals like Yahoo! and America
Online is ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   This past year, Internet companies have enlisted executives from
marketing giants like Pepsi and Procter &AMP; Gamble, which have a
history of using television to increase customer awareness of their
branded products. But most important, television in particular is
perceived as a king maker based on a few Cinderella stories last
year.
</P>
<P>
   In its first year in business, Etoys, a Web-based toy seller,
did $2 million in sales. Then the credit-card consortium Visa
decided that a good way to support e-commerce in general during the
Christmas season was to air an ad for the retailer showing children
snuggled in bed as parents clicked away to get their presents.
Etoys' revenue jumped to $23 million in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Last year there was relatively little ``dot com'' advertising.
Now the ads flow together one after another through the commercial
breaks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
