<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-OSLO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO GIVE PEACE TALKS A NUDGE DURING SUMMIT  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSLO, Norway _ President Clinton pledged ``there is nothing I
would not do'' to secure peace in the Middle East as the Israelis
and Palestinians embark on the final but most difficult phase of
their seven-year negotiations Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton joined Middle East leaders for a two-day summit that
also commemorates the memory of Yitzak Rabin. The slain Israeli
prime minister signed the 1993 Oslo Accord, a product of secret
negotiations that provided the current blueprint for peace.
</P>
<P>
   The president met privately with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak and Palestinian Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat, and Barak
and Arafat later met. All three will meet Tuesday as Clinton
attempts to nudge the peace process toward its final leg.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides will launch talks Nov. 7 to begin resolving the
most contentious remaining issues such as the status of Jerusalem,
Palestinian statehood, refugees, Jewish settlements and prisoners.
They want a framework for an agreement set by February and a final
treaty crafted by September.
</P>
<P>
   Barak suggested the possibility of a three-way summit similar to
the 1979 Camp David negotiations. He also reportedly sketched for
Clinton a ``red-linend issues on which Israel will not
negotiate, although details were not available.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said it was premature to speculate on a second Camp
David summit. Two decades ago, the United States hosted intense
talks that led to the peace treaty between Israel and Egypt. The
Camp David Accord was one of President Jimmy Carter's biggest
achievements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't rule anything out,'' Clinton said of a Camp David
sequel. ``As you know, going all the way back to '93, there is
nothing I would not do if I thought it would genuinely help to
build a lasting peace in the Middle East. There is nothing I would
not do, and I'm prepared to reaffirm that to Prime Minister Barak
and to Chairman Arafat.''
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli official suggested a U.S.-led summit may be held if
the initial two-way talks next week go well. ``We are entering a
100-day period, which is fateful,'' the official told reporters.
``Now the talks will start with the teams, but if they are positive
and successful there might be a chance for a trilateral summit
meeting in January or February.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat declared himself ready to ``seize the opportunity'' for
peace but also complained of Israel's continued expansion of Jewish
settlements and affirmed his continued position that ``Holy
Jerusalem'' will be the capitol of an independent Palestine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that I can seize this opportunity with your assistance
and the assistance of the others so that we can revive the peace
process and put it back on track,'' Arafat said as he met with
Norway's Prime Minister Kjell Bondevik.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat welcomed a Camp David-style session. ``As far as the
process is concerned, we would agree at any way that would be
suggested by those involved in the peace process _ the
international community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, speaking during a separate session with Bondevik, said
there were limits to what the United States could accomplish. ``The
hard decisions have to be made by the parties,'' Clinton said.
``The States can help with financial support, with military
support, with moral backup.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was important to keep negotiations on the timetable.
``So I will do what I can to get this thing going,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official said the focus now is on
structure, process and organization rather than on substance.
</P>
<P>
   King Harald of Norway hosted a commemorative dinner in memory of
Rabin. It also marked the anniversary of the 1993 Oslo Accord, the
agreement by which Israel allowed Palestinian control over the Gaza
Strip and portions of the West Bank. There have been a series of
interim agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Rabin, who won the 1994 Nobel Peace Prize with Arafat and
Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, was assassinated in 1995 by
a Jewish extremist opposed to the Oslo pact. King Harald called
Rabin a ``soldier of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is November again,'' recalled Leah Rabin, referring to the
month of her husband's death. ``It is his spirit and legacy which
has brought the parties of the peace process back here to Oslo
where it all began.'' Rabin was shot leaving a peace rally for the
Oslo Accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm now turning to you Chairman Arafat and to you Prime
Minister Barak,'' Leah Rabin said. ``It is your commitment to now
find the right formula to finish what my husband started and had to
pay the highest price for, his life. It is now up to you. Is it too
much to ask for?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
