<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5612 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-CENTURY-NYT     11-01 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CENTURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SMALL-SCREEN BURST OF VERITE FROM THE BEST OF THE CENTURY
</HEADLINE>
  (With TV-CENTURY-CHOICE) 
(nk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charlie Tabesh, vice president of Turner Classic Movies, a cable
television channel devoted to classic movies, knew that despite
being a confessed ``film fanatic,'' he had a significant gap in
film knowledge, one that corresponded to a gap in his channel's
programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had seen `Hoop Dreams' and `The Thin Blue Line,' and they
really had an enormous impact on me,'' Tabesh said. ``And I thought
there had to be other films that had had enormous impact on people
over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   Resolving to learn more, Tabesh began collecting books about
documentaries, then decided to provide an outlet for the classics
of the form. The result is a festival that TCM is calling ``A
Century of Reality,'' an assemblage of the top examples of
documentary film in the 20th century. These include early efforts
like ``Nanook of the North,'' Robert Flaherty's portrait of an
Eskimo hunter, and ``South,'' Frank Hurley's exploration of the
polar expedition of Sir Ernest Shackleton, on through examples of
the Soviet avant-garde films of the late 1920s to a collection of
World War II films and contemporary classics like ``Harlan County,
U.S.A.'' and ``Hoop Dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival begins Tuesday night with three films by Robert
Drew about the political career of John F. Kennedy. ``Primary,''
widely labeled as the first use of cinema verite as we have come to
know it, is a behind-the-scenes look at Kennedy's underdog campaign
against Sen. Hubert H. Humphrey in Wisconsin's Democratic
presidential primary in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   It is followed by ``Crisis,'' a minute-by-minute account of the
confrontation between the Kennedy administration and Gov. George C.
Wallace over the admission of the first black students to the
University of Alabama in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   The Drew trilogy concludes with a short film made the weekend
after the Kennedy assassination, ``Faces of November,'' which has
never been presented on television. All three films have freshly
restored prints. A fourth film, ``Four Days in November,'' by Mel
Stuart, follows.
</P>
<P>
   The festival, which runs on Tuesdays throughout this month, may
be the most comprehensive exploration of the best documentaries of
the 20th century ever presented on television. But TCM did not do
it because its vast libraries contained these films. In fact, the
channel owned almost none of them until Tabesh set out to acquire
the rights to them.
</P>
<P>
   Tabesh found himself fascinated by the history of the
documentary but realized he knew little about it. ``I've never been
to film school,'' he said. ``I'm just a buff.''
</P>
<P>
   He consulted some film experts, including the director of the
Independent Film Association, Betsy McLane, and bought a batch of
books, including ``Documentary Film Classics'' and ``Documentary: A
History of the Nonfiction Film.''
</P>
<P>
   The research turned up lists that had many of the same titles.
``There were films I knew we just had to have,'' Tabesh said. ``We
had to include the Leni Reifenstahl films from before the war. We
needed those early classics like the Shackleton film. And I wanted
to have the Soviet movies because they were so experimental.''
</P>
<P>
   His research turned up some gems that are not widely known
outside documentary circles, including one made by John Huston in
World War II, ``The Battle of San Pietro,'' which presented combat
so realistically that the Army decided not to release it, and a
film about the Spanish Civil War called ``The Spanish Earth,''
narrated by Ernest Hemingway.
</P>
<P>
   Assembling the collection was time-consuming, Tabesh said, but
not expensive. The time was spent locating the films, because,
Tabesh pointed out, there is no central studio library that houses
many of them. Many are owned by governments, including the German
government, which Tabesh said still has a claim on the Reifenstahl
Nazi films. Educational institutions own some, and so do museums;
the Museum of Modern Art has the rights to the Hemingway Spanish
Civil War film, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Some had to be purchased from the British-based film library,
Janus Films, Tabesh said. But with interest in them not especially
intense, and with few television outlets willing to present them,
none of the films were dauntingly priced. ``For the most part, this
was very inexpensive,'' Tabesh said. He declined to put an overall
price on the festival.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tabesh said, he became convinced early on that the key to
the festival was the acquisition of the three Kennedy films made by
Drew _ and the filmmaker had them.
</P>
<P>
   Now 75 and living in Brooklyn, Drew is still an active
filmmaker. He has two in the early stages of production, one about
pain and what can be done about it, the other about his exploits in
World War II, when he was shot down behind enemy lines in Italy and
survived many close calls.
</P>
<P>
   Drew was relatively unknown in the late 1950s when he first
encountered John Kennedy. He had been looking for someone with the
qualifications for a film idea he had long been contemplating.
</P>
<P>
   Having read ``The Education of Henry Adams,'' Drew said, he was
struck by the author's contention that he was the last man who
would truly know everything, but that someone would be born at
about the time of his death who would come to think he could ``see
it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew said he saw Kennedy give a speech in Detroit early in his
campaign, and ``at once I knew I had found that man. Kennedy really
did believe he could see it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Convinced he was in the presence of an extraordinary figure,
Drew approached Kennedy and asked if he could be allowed what was
then unprecedented access to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 1929EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5613 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-CENTURY-2NDTAKE-NY     11-01 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CENTURY-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: his campaign. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cinema verite in 1960 did not mean a hand-held camera or a
camera tucked away in someone's brown-bag lunch. In those days it
meant a team of two or three people, one lugging a bulky camera,
another toting bulky sound equipment and possibly a third to carry
extra film and equipment. All of that had to be hauled from place
to place as the subject of the film moved through the day. Nothing
about the effort was unobtrusive. The secret, Drew said, was
winning the subject's trust and doing nothing to violate it.
</P>
<P>
   Drew said Kennedy embraced the idea quickly. But he had to
persuade Humphrey. ``I don't think Humphrey understood what I was
doing, but I don't think it mattered. He was so tied up in his own
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Allowed to travel with both men, Drew knew quickly he was
capturing moments that no filmmaker ever had before. ``We were
getting reality,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he believed he had made something groundbreaking, though
the network news departments at the time did not agree. ``Primary''
was turned down. ``Elmer Lower of NBC told me I had some pretty
good footage,'' Drew said. ``The networks just didn't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   The film was eventually shown on stations owned by Time
magazine. But Kennedy loved the film, and that connection led to
``Crisis,'' which was the fulfillment of Kennedy's promise to Drew
to allow him inside the day-to-day events of a White House crisis.
</P>
<P>
   On that film, made for ABC News, the challenge was to persuade
Gov. Wallace. Once inside the Wallace camp, Drew said, the access
was complete. And Wallace even found he liked the film. Drew said
it had been his experience that the subjects of his films always
believe they look great and the opposing side looks foolish.
</P>
<P>
   The final Kennedy film came about because Lower, at that point
president of ABC News, asked Drew after the assassination to go to
Washington and ``make one of your films.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew was unsure what that meant in the context of the Kennedy
funeral. So he decided, he said, ``to film the events backward.''
Instead of showing the funeral, he turned his camera on the faces
of the people watching the events. ABC never ran the film.
</P>
<P>
   Drew said that whenever he has screened the three films
together, as he has on occasion at schools, the effect is always
the same. ``Nobody applauds. They just walk out looking kind of
shaken.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Drew said he was delighted that TCM has chosen to
give some recognition to great documentaries. ``I think it's a
well-thought-out list,'' he said. ``And I'm happy my films are in
there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 1929EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5614 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SHEPARD-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      11-01 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHEPARD-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DISALLOWS GAY-PANIC DEFENSE IN SHEPARD MURDER TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ A district court judge in Laramie, Wyo., ruled Monday
that lawyers for a man accused of murdering a gay college student
last year may not use a gay-panic defense in the trial to justify
the actions of their client.
</P>
<P>
   While the ruling carries no weight beyond Wyoming, some legal
experts and gay rights advocates said it amounts to a political
victory for gays and lesbians at a time when a growing number of
defense lawyers are using the strategy of casting the defendant as
victim _ with some success _ to obtain lighter sentences.
</P>
<P>
   But others expressed anger at the ruling, saying that it
reflects the growing influence of gay and lesbian groups that have
always demanded compassion and equal justice and now appear as
vengeful rather than sympathetic, denying the accused his only
possible defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do we want, justice or revenge?'' said William K. Dobbs,
a lawyer and gay rights activist in New York. ``Gay political
capital has become so substantial that it can now be used to
railroad others and compromise the ability of a defendant to get a
fair trial.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge in the case, Barton R. Voigt, told the lawyers that
their efforts to demonstrate a panic defense was little more than
an attempt to show that their client, Aaron J. McKinney, suffered
temporary insanity or diminished capacity when he admittedly killed
the student, Matthew Shepard, by beating him with a pistol during a
fit of ``homosexual rage.'' Neither defense is recognized by
Wyoming law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if relevant,'' the judge said of gay panic as a defense,
`'the evidence will mislead and confuse the jury.''
</P>
<P>
   Stripped of their plan, defense lawyers rested their case Monday
after calling the last of just seven witnesses. Closing arguments
are scheduled for Tuesday, after which the jury will begin
deliberations. Following any guilty verdict, arguments will begin
on the penalty phase, in which Voigt said he might allow testimony
on McKinney's past as a victim of homosexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
   In a gay-panic defense, a phrase that does not exist in statute
law, a defendant tries to win sympathy from the jury by
characterizing the victim as a homosexual predator and by
demonstrating that the defendant found his homosexual advances were
so repugnant and offensive, he resorted to violence. In a sense, it
suggests self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy has gained widespread use in recent years although
only rarely has it persuaded juries to find defendants guilty of
lesser crimes. Perhaps in response to more tolerant attitudes, in
general, toward gays and lesbians or to intense lobbying efforts
against such legal ploys by gay and lesbian activists, juries more
often have ignored the defendant's psychology as a reason to excuse
a violent act.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a desperate defense, to begin with,'' said Nanci
Clarence, a criminal defense lawyer in San Francisco who has worked
many cases involving gays as victims and witnesses. ``You are
asking jurors to buy the notion that internalistic homophobia can
be used to justify killing. That's a lot to bite off.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinney, who is 22, has confessed to killing Shepard, and
prosecutors who have charged him with first-degree murder say they
will seek the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   But in opening arguments last week, his lawyer, Jason Tangeman,
told the jury that McKinney's `'five-minute emotional rage''
against Shepard followed homosexual advances that reminded McKinney
of homosexual abuse he had suffered as a child. Therefore, Tangeman
argued, his client deserves no more than a conviction for
manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say attempts by lawyers to mount such a defense
have grown in recent years out of need, as society has become more
tolerant of alternative lifestyles. Beatrice Dohrn, legal director
of the Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund, a gay advocacy
group in New York, said historically lawyers could win lighter
sentences, even acquittals, for defendants accused of violent
crimes against gays simply by playing to a jury's homophobic bias.
</P>
<P>
   But as Americans have grown more accepting of gays and lesbians
and more states are recognizing a victim's sexual orientation as a
basis for prosecution as a hate crime _ 38 states now have such
designations although the federal government does not _ defense
lawyers are finding they can no longer expect juries to respond
based purely on prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Ms. Dohrn said, lawyers began designing a strategy
that paints the defendant as victim, selling juries the idea that
the defendant was either acting out of self-defense against
homosexual advances or as a consequence of suspended rational
thinking because a homosexual advance unloosed painful memories of
the defendant's own experience with sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
   With the number of cases increasing, a colloquial phrase,
gay-panic defense, gained currency within the gay and lesbian
community even as most juries demonstrated an unwillingness to
consider the defendant as a victim. But occasionally, the tactic
has worked.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 7, 1998, the same day Shepard was found outside of
Laramie tied to a fence and unconscious, a jury in Honolulu found a
man guilty of third-degree assault, a misdemeanor, for beating to
death a gay man who had made sexual advances toward him. The
defendant, Stephen Bright, had been charged with the second-degree
murder of Kenneth Brewer, but successfully argued in court that he
was acting in self-defense, fearing that he would be assaulted for
resisting Brewer's advances.
</P>
<P>
   Bright, who testified that he was not gay, was sentenced to one
year in prison and fined $2,000, prompting gay and lesbian
advocates in Hawaii to complain that the jury gave in to
homophobia.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, juries in more than a dozen cases around
the country have rejected gay panic as a defense. Perhaps the most
celebrated case involved Jonathan Schmitz, a guest on the Jenny
Jones talk show who shot and killed a gay man, Scott Amedure, who
admitted during a television taping that he had a crush on him.
</P>
<P>
   After one Michigan jury's second-degree murder conviction was
overturned on appeal, a second jury convicted Schmitz on the same
charge. He had argued that his response was justified for the
humiliation he suffered. The judge did not agree and sentenced him
to 25 to 50 years in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
