A5615 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-ROCK'N'ROLL-TEX     11-01 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK'N'ROLL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BREED OF BANDS DOESN'T NEED AN ATTITUDE TO ROCK FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unless you're a HUGE Creed fan, or one of their moms, would you
recognize any one them walking down the street?
</P>
<P>
   Didn't think so.
</P>
<P>
   Creed, a Florida quartet that sounds like Pearl Jam's younger
brothers, is on the road supporting ``Human Clay,'' the band's
second CD and the most popular in the country. Four million people
bought Creed's first CD, ``My Own Prison,'' and thousands are
showing up for their tour, which stops at Dallas' Starplex on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   All this for a band that's basically four nondescript-looking _
and, many would argue, nondescript-sounding _ young musicians who
play no-frills, grunge-influenced rock 'n' roll and sing about
basic hopes and frustrations.
</P>
<P>
   And they are not alone. Witness the success of other regular-guy
bands such as matchbox 20 (8 million CDs sold), Our Lady Peace
(which opens for Creed at Starplex), Canada's Barenaked Ladies,
Collective Soul and New Orleans' Cowboy Mouth, which recently
headlined a show in downtown Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Although these bands don't all sound alike, they are bound
together by their often straight-ahead rock 'n' roll and their lack
of image: They don't dress up like drug-addled space aliens, they
don't flash jewelry and furs, they don't sing about committing
suicide or hating the whole world. They don't go in and out of
rehab or get arrested for having a pound of cocaine on their tour
bus. They release CDs, they tour, they get large numbers of people
to sing along and have a good time, and then they do it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to be based on image,'' says Creed bassist
Brian Marshall, calling from backstage before a show this week in
Colorado Springs. ``We don't get a lot of attention from ``Rolling
Stone'' and MTV, and that's fine with us. The songs are meaningful
and uplifting at points and can work on a vast audience.''
</P>
<P>
   And that could be a working definition of all of the above
bands. Their music is usually about everyday concerns and joys, and
the music rocks without being as hard and angry as Rage Against the
Machine, Korn or Limp Bizkit. Its familiarity is its greatest
asset.
</P>
<P>
   Several musicians and record-company executives say there are a
lot of rock fans who live average, everyday lives and want to hear
music that speaks to their experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hootie and the Blowfish outsold Nirvana _ they BOTH tied into
the nation's consciousness,'' says Fred LeBlanc, vocalist and
tireless drummer with Cowboy Mouth, whose sturdy pop and energetic
shows have earned the band a large following throughout the
Southeast. ``People listen to music to find things that relate to
them, and that's what a lot of these bands do. We speak the
language. Everybody knows about love and trying to keep a job and
maybe doing a job you don't like.''
</P>
<P>
   LeBlanc compares the current crop of regular-guy bands to
everyone from Chuck Berry to the Clash to New Wave acts such as the
Replacements. In each case, the performer was writing about
everyday enjoyment and frustration, be it Berry's anthems to cars
and dating in the 'the Clash's portrayal of unemployment in
the late '70s.
</P>
<P>
   He knows firsthand how unexciting this can be to the media:
Years ago a record company executive told him mainstream press
would never write about the band because ``I didn't have a drug
addiction, I wasn't worshipping Satan and I wasn't trying to commit
suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The label _ my record label _ told me that people weren't
interested in people playing music and celebrating life,'' says
LeBlanc. ``I'm not gonna put a needle in my arm to get copy in
``Rolling Stone'' _ sorry. I'm not even gonna say I do _ and
believe me, a lot of those stories about musicians' drug problems
are planted.''
</P>
<P>
   But as it turns out, that's not what a lot of music fans want to
hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The audience for these bands is baby boomers on down to
18-year-olds,'' says Steve Brown, the rock buyer for Tower Records
in Dallas. ``It's just safe, good-time rock 'n' roll _ it's not as
hard as Rage Against the Machine and it's not Britney Spears. Young
people 18 to 24 like it, and it's also palatable to older rock
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are tired of songs about being unhappy _ they just want
rock music, and these guys give it to 'em without all the
peripheral stuff, like who in the band was arrested. People are
tired of Axl Rose and guys like that.''
</P>
<P>
   And young fans also want a band they can see regularly and watch
develop. Major bands that only put out a CD and tour every three or
four years seem remote, and it's hard to build a fan/band
relationship with acts that come and go on the strength of one big
hit single.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the pop stuff, they have one hit and do really well
but they don't deliver beyond that,'' says Eric Lawrence, Our Lady
Peace's manager. ``Fans want to believe in a band and the band's
career. They want to buy into a band and go see them. These bands
have all been around a while and continue to put out good
records.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman covers the pop music scene for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can reach him at dfer(at)star-telegram.com or
(817) 390-7839. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
