<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5618 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-PANDAS-COX     11-01 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANDAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The bear necessities: Compound gives pair all the comforts of
home and more
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Pandastic!
</P>
<P>
   Lun-Lun and Yang-Yang will arrive in Atlanta Friday morning
after a long-long flight from China. They'll have jet lag from the
time change and 19 hours in the air. Just as human travelers would,
they'll be confused. Nervous. Easily annoyed.
</P>
<P>
   Then they'll have to settle into a brand-new, unfamiliar home at
the zoo.
</P>
<P>
   So the least you can do, when you get to see them starting Nov.
20, is to pronounce their names correctly. Nothing less than the
future of giant pandas could be at stake!
</P>
<P>
   Pandas are emotionally sensitive, especially when they're young,
says Zoo Atlanta Director Terry Maple, who's also a psychology
professor at Georgia Tech. And unless the cubbies acclimate, they
may never mate and procreate.
</P>
<P>
   So remember this:
</P>
<P>
   Lun-Lun rhymes roughly with ``loon-loon.'' And Yang-Yang is
pronounced ``yong-yong,'' like ``song-song.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want people to say Yang-Yang like `bang-bang,' ''
says Zoo marketing director Gail Eaton. ``The pandas will be
confused anyway, and they're used to hearing their names in a
Chinese accent.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the folks at Zoo Atlanta have thought of everything, or so
they hope. The bears' living area is lush and spacious, complete
with gray boulders, new grass and bamboo _ their main food _
sprouting up just outside their steel-fenced compound.
</P>
<P>
   The $7 million facility, the most expensive and advanced panda
habitat anywhere, gives the young bears plenty of room, and, if
they so desire, complete privacy, even from each other.
</P>
<P>
   It has indoor and outdoor facilities, the former of which has
thick-glassed, 25-foot-long windows for gawkers to peer inside. The
pandas can easily retreat to two skylight-lit, climate controlled
``dayrooms'' if the weather turns bad. And if one gets in a mood to
be alone, it'll be free at all times to roam alone to a private
cage, separated from an adjacent one by a small door. Indoor rooms
are decorated with wallpaper made of enlarged photographs of bamboo
jungles.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a private space for making hay, called a ``cubbing
den,'' and another, smaller ``birthing den,'' should they do what
Maple hopes will come naturally.
</P>
<P>
   The outdoor area is equipped with log-made climbing towers,
carefully modeled to resemble similar play areas in their old home
at a panda research facility in Chengdu, China. Trees in the zoo
habitat aren't big enough for climbing, but they have been fitted
with electric-wire collars to keep the cubs from trying _ and
falling. And small swimming pools are located both in outdoor and
indoor areas, because pandas love to splash around.
</P>
<P>
   If the pandas want to sneak away from prying eyes, they can at
any time.
</P>
<P>
   Or so they'll think. Yang-Yang and Lun-Lun will be able to avoid
the gaze of people they can see, but specially trained keepers will
sit in a control room 24 hours a day, at least for the first six
months. With 16 globe-shaped camera installations, the keepers will
be able to see or videotape each bear, 24-7.
</P>
<P>
   That's important, Maple says, because Zoo Atlanta's $22 million
panda program is aimed at helping scientists better understand the
animals, which almost never mate in captivity. The goal is to solve
the mating puzzle so that pandas, a critically endangered species,
will one day produce healthy offspring routinely.
</P>
<P>
   At Washington's National Zoo, one of only two other American
zoos with giant pandas, there have been several stillbirths. At
least one baby survived but was rolled on by its mother and
suffocated.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Zoo recently had a successful birth, the result of
artificial insemination.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the money for Zoo Atlanta's project has been raised both
from big corporations and from personal contributions. The money
will keep flowing in, Maple says, ``because people just seem to
love pandas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're beautiful animals, different from any other. We'll be
inundated with visitors.''
</P>
<P>
   But the goal of the panda project is to get the bears to make
love, not money.
</P>
<P>
   If the cubs learn to like each other enough to play together,
Maple says, then it's probable they'll connect, emotionally and
physically, in more important ways.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, they're too young to be interested in sex, and
wouldn't know what to do if they did. He's hoping that by the time
they're 5, they'll jive, and Lun-Lun will give birth.
</P>
<P>
   Maple and his crew of professionals will give the bears all the
help they need. If one wants to be alone and the other doesn't, a
keeper will separate them. And fighting won't be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's likely they will breed, but we really just don't know,''
Maple says. ``The way I believe it happens is through rough and
tumble play. That helps them develop the proper behaviors
associated with mating. It takes maturity and time. But our plan is
to have a baby panda in three years or so.''
</P>
<P>
   After a flight from Chengdu on a domestic carrier, the pandas
are scheduled to leave Beijing at 5:10 p.m. Thursday, Atlanta time,
via United Parcel Service. They'll make a stop in Anchorage,
Alaska, then continue on to Atlanta, where they are expected to
land at Hartsfield International Airport about 9:30 Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Two veterinarians and a panda keeper will check on the bears
almost continually en route.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of reporters from around the country will be at the UPS
hangar near Hartsfield Airport to greet the bears, along with
perhaps 100 other people. But no one except Maple and a few
associates will be allowed near the specially designed cages.
Security will be heavy to prevent overzealous media types from
running out for a scoop.
</P>
<P>
   The cages will be spirited to Zoo Atlanta in a brown UPS van
almost immediately, and within an hour the pandas will be
introduced to their habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Given their temperament, it's likely Yang-Yang and Lun-Lun will
find places in their habitat to be alone, at least until they sleep
off their jet lag, Maple says. Zoo officials can only guess how
long it'll take them to become bright-eyed and frisky. The Nov. 20
target date for public viewing might have to be changed if the
pandas don't respond well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what they'll do,'' Maple says. ``We'll have a
schedule that gives them some quiet time. We're just going to do
the best we can.''
</P>
<P>
   The bears will be placed in quarantine, seen and touched by only
a few people for a while, Maple says.
</P>
<P>
   So remember, try to pronounce Lun-Lun and Yang-Yang correctly.
And Lun-Lun's the female, so don't say ``Come here, boy.''
</P>
<P>
   The way zoo folks see it, you can't be too careful.
</P>
<P>
   Maple's hoping the pandas won't be as anxious as the zoo folks.
Because he concedes that the bamboo eaters have the whole harried
zoo staff pretty, well, bamboozled. Maybe even a bit . . .
pandanoid.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
