u p BC-BAXTER-COLUMN-COX     11-01 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: `Liberal' is mentionable, and that's revolutionary
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two South Carolina Republicans were eating barbecue at
a rally for Sen. John McCain a few weeks ago when one voiced the
opinion that Bill Bradley, should he win the Democratic nomination,
would be a formidable opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a basketball player, people like him . . . and he's a
liberal,'' he explained. His friend nodded in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In that passing assessment there may be the evidence of a
significant political shift.
</P>
<P>
   Whether these Republicans worries about Bradley will seem
justified a few months down the road is not the point here. It's
the underlying assumption that to be liberal _ though the word was
pronounced with as much disgust as ever by this conservative voter
_ would give Bradley an advantage in a national election next year.
</P>
<P>
   The political winds of the past decade or so have not reversed
themselves in a year or so. Bradley doesn't bill himself as a stern
liberal, the way Gov. George W. Bush calls himself a compassionate
conservative. It shows how much the very meaning of the words
liberal and conservative have shifted rightward, that McCain _
hawkish, small-government and pro-life _ is characterized by some
as the liberal side of the GOP field.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the sense of what the South Carolinians were
talking about is detectable in the way the candidates are
presenting themselves this year and how they stack up in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The ``l'' word isn't being tossed at opponents with the same
swagger, and the ``c'' word doesn't have the same cachet. If
there's such a thing as a modish political position this year, it's
probably a Ventura-esque disdain for all the old labels.
</P>
<P>
   The change in tone could be heard in last week's Democratic and
Republican debates in New Hampshire _ the way the candidates
answered, but even more so in what the voters asked. They were the
questions of an electorate little inclined toward any ideological
labels, and at least interested in the power of government activism
to solve their problems.
</P>
<P>
   In the Democratic debate, Gore raised doubts about the viability
of Bradley's big spending proposals, but did not attempt to brand
him as a elitist liberal, the words Gov. Roy Barnes used in
Georgia. On the stump in New Hampshire, energetically condemning
offshore drilling and outlining a national crusade for education,
Gore in fact has seemed far more the inheritor of Hubert Humphrey's
mantle than the dour Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   In the Republican debate the following night, Steve Forbes, Gary
Bauer and Alan Keyes continued to espouse one or another form of
unbending conservatism, but they were the pack behind the absent
Bush and McCain, conservatives with a more flexible approach. Pat
Buchanan, the fiercest conservative flag-bearer of four years ago,
was absent from the stage altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The climate for liberalism seems more promising in part because
so many establishment conservatives have put their money on Bush
and have little reason to raise their voices at the moment. But
something has changed since the days when candidates in the
farthest districts of Massachusetts and New York were inventing
ingenious ways to call themselves conservatives. Liberal, whatever
it means, is no longer synonymous with doormat.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
