u f BC-AVADO-COX     11-01 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AVADO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Group plans offer for Avado Brands
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A management group led by Chief Executive Tom E.
DuPree Jr. plans to make an offer to buy Madison, Ga.-based Avado
Brands.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement coincided with the release of the restaurant
chain's third quarter results, which fell short of analysts'
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   DuPree said submission of an offer is ``imminent.'' He declined
to say how much the group, which includes about a dozen top Avado
executives and senior leaders of its four restaurant brands, would
pay for the company.
</P>
<P>
   The company's board of directors is expected to form a special
committee, comprised of the three independent directors, to
evaluate the management proposal and other alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, we have done enough evaluation to believe our
proposal will have merit,'' DuPree
</P>
<P>
   ``The big question mark is that if they do make a bid for it, is
it one that will be financed and what's the price.'' said Barry
Stouffer, an analyst with J.C. Bradford in Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   He said the price was not likely to be much higher ``than where
the stock was in August _ the $7 to $7.50 (a share) range.''
</P>
<P>
   The company was once the largest Applebee's franchisee in the
nation. Formerly known as Apple South, Avado operates Don Pablo's
Mexican Kitchen, Canyon Cafe Southwestern Grill, Hops
Restaurant-Bar-Brewery and McCormick &AMP; Schmick's.
</P>
<P>
   The divestiture of 279 Applebee's restaurants was completed
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, the company announced it had hired BancBoston
Robertson Stephens to explore new strategies to ``maximize
shareholder value.''
</P>
<P>
   The company also reported its third quarter results. Net income
was $2.4 million, or 10 cents a share, compared to $24.4 million,
or 58 cents a share, for the like period in 1998. The 1998 results
included a $19.6 million, or 44 cents a share, after-tax gain
related to asset disposals.
</P>
<P>
   First Call had an 18 cents a share estimate.
</P>
<P>
   DuPree said the company was affected by higher-than-expected
costs associated with a Don Pablo's marketing campaign. The
company's sales were negatively impacted by severe weather in Texas
and along the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues for the quarter ended Oct. 3 were $157.3 million, down
from $204.4 million for the same period a year earlier. The company
said lower sales reflected the completion of the divestiture of the
Applebee's division. Net sales for the four core brands were $157.3
million, up from $135.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Shelia M. Poole writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
