<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5634 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-AMERICAS-CUP-1150     11-01 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-AMERICAS-CUP-1150(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACING YACHTS SAILING ON EDGE OF TECHNOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y., R.I.)  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Years of planning, design and fixation on the tiniest details
have finally come to this: Catching a light breeze in its sails, a
mighty yacht heaves its sleek form through the chilly New Zealand
waters with sailors straining to understand every nuance of its
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Forged by computers, with scale models in wind tunnels and in
towing tests, and by imagination, some of the most unusual vessels
built to ply the seas are setting out to make all the effort
worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   The quest for the America's Cup is under way in Auckland, New
Zealand, and teams from around the world are beginning a long
competition to see if one of them has the boat and the crew capable
of taking the world's most prestigious sailing trophy from the New
Zealand team that captured it in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of using the wooden boats with billowy cotton sails of
yesterday, or even the fiberglass hulls and sheets of woven
synthetic fibers common today, the cup challengers and defenders
steer craft that their builders say shove sailing technology right
to its edge, pushing their materials to the breaking point.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the pinnacle of boat building,'' said Ted Brown,
construction manager for AmericaOne, one of five American groups
vying for the cup. ``This is as high-tech as you can get and
probably the biggest challenge of anyone's boat-building career.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other leading contenders, AmericaOne, representing the St.
Francis Yacht Club of San Francisco, has constructed two boats with
slightly different capabilities to vie against each other and
against competitors in the initial series of elimination races.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, 11 teams from seven nations will begin a second
series of round-robin races to determine which will challenge Team
New Zealand. The Prada Challenge team from Italy and boats from
AmericaOne and another American syndicate, Young America, led the
pack after the first round, which ended last Thursday. The eventual
winner will face the New Zealanders, who are known for sailing
innovations and who will be fielding two new boats under their
Black Magic banner. That best-of-nine match is to begin Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   The boats are very similar in design and construction because
all must adhere to the rigid International America's Cup class rule
that has governed this type of yacht since the 1992 competition.
The design is based upon a mathematical formula that balances
waterline length, sail area and displacement such that adding
significantly to one dimension requires adjusting the others. Yet,
even within these strictures, designers and builders say there is
room for improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the rule book and find opportunities to do
better,'' said Duncan MacLane, design and technology manager for
Young America, the syndicate representing the New York Yacht Club
in its bid to regain the cup.
</P>
<P>
   The trophy, first won by the schooner America in 1851 in a race
against British yachts, resided in a case at the club until 1983,
when Australia II, with its innovative winged keel, ended the
longest title defense in sports history and took the cup to
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   A team from the San Diego Yacht Club recaptured the cup in 1987
and defended it three times before the Royal New Zealand Yacht
Squadron took it in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Young America hopes that its two new yachts, the product of
years of research and testing, will return the cup to New York next
year after a 17-year absence.
</P>
<P>
   Putting boats into the water is the end of a design and building
process that takes many teams two or three years, progressing from
initial designs, one-third scale models tested in water tanks and
wind tunnels, to computer programs designed to predict performance
under expected conditions in the Hauraki Gulf off Auckland.
</P>
<P>
   Experts estimate that some teams spent up to $10 million for
research and design, plus $3 million to $5 million for each
custom-made boat.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, an America's Cup yacht is 75 to 78 feet long and
weighs 45,000 to 48,000 pounds. The yachts are very much alike but
in races that take two or three hours that are decided by one
boat's crossing the finish line a minute or two ahead of another,
anything that affects speed and performance by even 1 percent is
crucial.
</P>
<P>
   The designs call for precision measured in thousandths of an
inch, and the use of materials and methods normally seen in the
aerospace industry.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most critical parts of the yacht is the hull, and the
building material of choice has become carbon fiber composites,
displacing wood, aluminum and even fiberglass because of their
strength and light weight. Used extensively in aircraft, composites
are made of fibers bonded by a resin or polymer glue that are
applied in layers to build up a structure and hardened by heat for
strength.
</P>
<P>
   Like expert cooks, builders use similar recipes for constructing
hulls of composites, but vary their techniques to squeeze
improvements from the process that they hope will result in a
better boat coming out of the oven.
</P>
<P>
   AmericaOne's two boats were built by Westerly Marine of Costa
Mesa, Calif., and Brown, the construction manager, said that about
17,000 hours of labor went into each craft. ``Even though we use a
lot of state-of-the-art machinery, actual construction requires a
lot of time-consuming, hands-on labor,'' he said. ``It takes some
finesse to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Goetz of Goetz Custom Sailboats in Bristol, R.I., who built
the two yachts for Young America, says oven curing makes the
material stronger while allowing use of less resin, which means
less weight. ``The idea is to make the boat as light as possible
but strong enough to stay in one piece.''
</P>
<P>
   A boat starts out as a designer's computer files, some of which
are used to guide laser or mechanical cutters that carve out wooden
molds that define the shape of the hull. These plywood forms, cut
in precise shapes and sizes, are lined up in an exact sequence at
intervals, like ribs, to define the boat's shape. Then this
skeleton is covered with thin, wooden strips, and then plywood and
a layer of either carbon fiber or fiberglass to produce a shell
over which the actual hull is built.
</P>
<P>
   The hull built over the mold is to consist of a core of
honeycomb material, made of aluminum or a tough synthetic product,
sandwiched between two layers of carbon fiber skin. Each layer of
skin is made by putting down successive sheets of resin-impregnated
carbon fiber, which comes in 12-inch-wide rolls, and heating the
material for hours at 220 degrees Fahrenheit to cure it into a
hardened material.
</P>
<P>
   To heat a hull that is almost 80 feet long, builders encase the
mold in an insulated structure built inside the warehouse-like
buildings they use for normal boat construction. This giant oven, a
building within a building, not only is heated to cure composite
materials, they say, but also helps hide the design from potential
spies from rival groups.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Different builders vary the sequence for heat-curing the
composite sandwich hull, with some curing the inner layer first,
and then applying the honeycomb and second layer to the first
before the next warming cycle to activate and harden the resin.
Goetz puts the first composite layer and the honeycomb together for
the initial heat treatment, he said, but first puts the entire
structure in a giant nylon bag and pumps the air out. This
compresses the materials and squeezes out air pockets for a
smoother seal.
</P>
<P>
   After the final cure, the hull is removed from the mold and
checked for unevenness and flaws, Brown said. If needed, the
surface is sanded and imperfections filled with resin compound
before the boat's shape is checked against the designer's original
specifications.
</P>
<P>
   The owners and designers are not the only ones to inspect the
hull. To check compliance with America's Cup hull rules, race
officials visit each completed shell and drill a half-dozen core
holes in it to see if it meets regulations for maximum thickness
and materials. ``The holes are easy to repair, but seeing your boat
drilled is a very unsettling experience,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   After the boat is painted (with as little paint as possible, to
save weight), the hull is turned over and internal supports added
before the deck, also made of composites but built and cured
separately, is attached. Then the boat's mast, boom, rigging and
other hardware are added to complete the vessel before it is partly
disassembled for shipping.
</P>
<P>
   Cup challengers need to get their hulls built as precisely as
possible to take advantage of their research. Young America team
members enlisted Brown &AMP; Sharpe, a manufacturing company in North
Kingston, R.I., which specializes in precision measurement, to help
with making their boats and aligning appendages and other parts
when attached.
</P>
<P>
   The company used a new laser scanner capable of measuring
complex curved surfaces to check the Young America hulls with an
accuracy of one millimeter over 70 feet, a level not previously
possible, said MacLane, Young America's design and technology
manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could evaluate the mold before we put the carbon fiber
on,'' MacLane said, ``and the more accurate the mold, hopefully,
the more accurate the boat.''
</P>
<P>
   There are early signs that the New York group may have achieved
some of its precision goals. When the first boat arrived in
Auckland, it was immediately noticed that it had a shiny, black
hull much like Team New Zealand's yachts. However, the hull of the
American boat is not painted and the blackness is the natural color
of its carbon fiber components covered with a clear seal.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Baird, the Young America team captain, told onlookers that
the hull was unpainted because it was made exceptionally smooth and
did not need paint to cover up fillers normally used to repair
imperfections.
</P>
<P>
   Another noticeable feature on the new boat was a wing mast,
similar to the kind seen on the New Zealand boats in the last
competition. This mast, and the other poles and pulleys on the
boat, was made by Hall Spars of Bristol, R.I., of carbon fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a decade ago, masts for large sailing boats were
usually made of aluminum and were little more than tall, hollow
poles. Now, racing boat masts are taking on the shape of airfoils,
with contours similar to those of thin airplane wings placed
vertically in the deck to direct airflow during certain maneuvers
to improve performance.
</P>
<P>
   A third major area of research is sail design, with teams
changing the shapes, sizes and materials used for sails to make
them more versatile, durable and lighter. Young America and America
One are working with teams from North Sails Inc., an international
sailmaker, on new types of sails for their boats.
</P>
<P>
   North Sails has developed a process it calls 3DL that produces a
laminated, one-piece sail that can be molded in three dimensions
into any shape to give it the characteristics desired by a
designer. Mainsails traditionally are made by assembling numerous
panels of cloth to form curved shapes, a design that puts undue
pressure on seams that causes them to stretch and distort the
shape.
</P>
<P>
   With 3DL technology, technicians in the manufacturer's plant in
Minden, Nev., use a designer computer graphics file to create an
electronic mold that instructs a large, flat surface machine the
size of a sail to bend itself into the desired shape. A single
sheet of Mylar plastic goes over the mold and a device on an
overhead gantry moves over the surface putting down a specified
pattern of structural fiber threads made of tough material like
Kevlar. Once the reinforcing yarn is in place, a second sheet of
plastic film goes on top to sandwich it in and the whole mold is
encased in a vacuum bag to compress the laminate. A moving heat
source then passes over the sail to cure it and set its shape.
</P>
<P>
   The finished, one-piece sail can weigh up to a third less than a
conventional sail, and it holds its shape better under a wide range
of wind and sea conditions, users say.
</P>
<P>
   A set of sails made of composite materials costs $30,000 to
$50,000 and each boat requires more than a dozen sets for the
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the designing, planning and building for the America's
Cup challenge is over, but as the boats battle one another in the
coming months, each team will have opportunities to adjust and
refine its designs and tactics, reacting to competitors'
innovations and skill.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of smart guys trying to win the cup and nobody
has a monopoly on good ideas,'' said MacLane of Young America. ``We
just hope we are smarter and made the right choices.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
