<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5645 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBO-PAYTON-COX     11-01 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-PAYTON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `One of the greatest': Walter Payton 1954-1999
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walter Payton's soft-spoken nature won him the nickname
``Sweetness.'' The powerful running style that earned him a place
in the Pro Football Hall of Fame proved that moniker to be a
contradiction.
</P>
<P>
   Payton, the NFL's all-time leading rusher, died Monday of liver
disease that was untreatable because of cancer. He was 45.
</P>
<P>
   Payton, who rushed for 16,726 yards during his 13-year career
with the Chicago Bears, disclosed in February that he was suffering
from primary sclerosing cholangitis, a rare disease that scars and
blocks the bile ducts of the liver. During treatment for that
disease, doctors discovered that Payton had advanced bile-duct
cancer. The malignancy prevented Payton from receiving a new liver,
according to his physician, Dr. Greg Gores, of the Mayo Clinic in
Rochester, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   Payton died at his home in Barrington, Ill., a suburb of
Chicago, about noon Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter was an inspiration in everything he did,'' said NFL
commissioner Paul Tagliabue, who called Payton, ``one of the
greatest players in the history of the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The tremendous grace and dignity he displayed in his final
months reminded us again why 'Sweetness' was the perfect nickname
for Walter Payton,'' Tagliabue said.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about Payton's health were prompted last week when his
son, Jarrett, a freshman running back at the University of Miami,
left the team and returned to Chicago. On Sunday, radio stations in
New York and Philadelphia reported erroneously that Payton had
died. A family friend told the Associated Press on Sunday that
Payton's condition had not changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last 12 months have been extremely tough on me and my
family,'' Jarrett Payton said Monday at a news conference in
Chicago. ``But through these difficult times, we've learned a lot
about love and life. From the days in February when my dad told the
world about his liver disease, the outpouring of love and support
from around the world astounded even him.''
</P>
<P>
   As a runner, the 5-foot-10, 220-pound Payton could run over or
around would-be tacklers. Payton was an exceptional receiver _ he
holds the Bears record with 492 career catches _ and a punishing
blocker. He also was known for a powerful stiff-arm and his
extraordinary ability to leap over pileups near the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were guys who ran with the ball better, faster,'' said
New Orleans Saints coach Mike Ditka, who coached Payton for six
seasons in Chicago. ``But I don't think anyone ever ran with more
determination than Walter. . . . The will is a powerful thing, and
Walter had a great will and heart. When you look at Walter, his
impact on the game was on the field and off of it. He was the
epitomy of class. He handled himself with such humility and
dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   Drafted fourth overall in the 1975 draft, Payton played on only
two winning teams in his first nine seasons with the Bears. In
1977, in only his third year in the league, Payton won his first of
two MVP awards by rushing for 1,852 yards and 14 touchdowns, both
career highs. He ran for 275 yards against Minnesota that season,
which still stands as the NFL's single-game rushing record.
</P>
<P>
   Ditka arrived before a strike-shortened season in 1982, and the
Bears made the playoffs four seasons in a row, 1984-87. Payton and
the ``Monsters of the Midway'' defense led Chicago to a 46-10
victory over the New England Patriots in Super Bowl XX in 1986.
Payton gained 61 yards in that game but did not score.
</P>
<P>
   Having surpassed Jim Brown's NFL rushing record by more than
4,000 yards, Payton retired after the 1987 season, and the Bears
immediately retired his No. 34 jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to set the record so high that the next person who
tries for it, it's going to bust his heart,'' Payton once said.
</P>
<P>
   Payton was inducted into the Hall of Fame in 1993, his first
year of eligibility, and he asked Jarrett to be the first son to
present his father for induction in the Hall. Payton still holds
nine NFL and 28 Bears records. Payton played in nine Pro Bowls and
missed only one game, during his rookie season after a coach
wouldn't let him play because of a sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Payton, born in Columbia, Miss., attended Division I-AA Jackson
State and led the NCAA in scoring in 1973 with 160 points. A
two-time All-American in college, Payton finished fourth in 1974 in
voting for the Heisman Trophy, which was awarded to Ohio State's
Archie Griffin for the second year in a row. Payton left college as
the NCAA's all-time leading scorer with 464 career points.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the first running back that I ever saw that I
respected,'' former Bears linebacker Mike Singletary said. ``He
gave me a new respect for running backs. The way he prepared made
me believe that he could have been a great defensive player. But
his attitude for life was what made you want to be around him. He
was definitely a bright spot wherever darkness appeared.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
