<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-SMITH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITH REJOINS GOP, SEEKS ENVIRONMENT PANEL LEADERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate is poised to alter the course of its
environmental committee for the first time in decades by selecting
a pro-business leader as its next chairman _ either James M. Inhofe
of Oklahoma or Bob Smith of New Hampshire, who Monday rejoined the
Republican Party and made a bid for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Not in 30 years has a pro-business senator chaired the powerful
Senate Environment and Public Works Committee, and its most recent
head, the late Senator John H. Chafee of Rhode Island, was dubbed
by environmentalists as one of the ``greenest'' leaders on Capitol
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Smith made an open plea for the post, which would have
been rightfully his had he not left the Republican Party in August.
Renouncing his switch to be an independent, Smith declared he was
switching back to the GOP and implied becoming chairman was his top
priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``To assume the chairmanship would give me the opportunity to
help accomplish what my goal has been all along _ to make
conservative policy the national policy,'' Smith said. ``It would
be irresponsible of me to delay this announcement as it could
potentially jeopardize the chairmanship.''
</P>
<P>
   After Smith, Inhofe is the second-most senior Republican on the
committee. In the opinion of the Sierra Club, the decision between
the two is a ``competition between bad and worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Smith considers himself an environmentalist, both he
and Inhofe have low ratings from the League of Conservation Voters,
which ranks public officials according to how they vote on
environmental issues. While Chafee rated a 70 _ meaning he voted on
the side of environmental groups 70 percent of the time _ Smith's
lifetime average is 36. In the previous session of Congress, his
rating was 13.
</P>
<P>
   Inhofe's numbers are lower still, with a lifetime average of 7.
In the previous session, he rated zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either one is bad news for the environment,'' said Allen
Mattison, spokesman for the Sierra Club. ``Smith is slightly not as
bad as Inhofe, which is about as faint praise as I can give. But
comparing yourself to Inhofe and saying, `I'm an environmentalist,'
is pathetic.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hickey, a spokeswoman for Smith, responded: ``Sierra Club
thinks environmental protection lies in the federal government. We
think its best left in the hands of localities.''
</P>
<P>
   To business leaders, the selection of either senator would be
welcome after years of battling the restrictions of the
Environmental Protection Agency with little congressional help.
Both Smith and Inhofe have worked on their behalf in the past,
advocating fewer federal restrictions on costly environmental
measures.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, for example, Inhofe unsuccessfully opposed an
EPA initiative to lower the percentage of sulfur in gasoline. And
he successfully defeated a measure that would have required
chemical facilities to divulge the dangerous contents inside the
plants, citing national security.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has more of a mixed record that includes some measures
environmentalists support, such as helping pass the 1996 battery
recycling law and pushing Congress to restore money to the federal
Land and Water Conservation Fund in 1997. But his pet project, a
redesign of the superfund program, has come under harsh attack from
conservationists. Although Smith says his bill would speed the
cleaning up of hazardous waste by exempting some small businesses
and redefining liability, environmental groups worry Smith would
weaken hazardous waste laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would weaken the aspect of the law that makes polluters pay
for the mess they created,'' Mattison said. ``We're afraid that if
Smith is in the chairman's seat, this will move ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is Smith's intent. In a statement released
Monday, he spelled out his enthusiasm for running the committee and
for rejoining the party he left in a fit of pique earlier this
year. At the time, Smith said he was leaving the GOP out of
principle as he launched his grass-roots presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   That campaign ground to a halt last week, and Smith dropped his
bid without having ever gotten more than 1 percent in the polls.
Then, after Chafee's death, Smith hinted at a party re-switch. He
made it formal Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have received thousands of calls, letters and e-mails from
wonderful people who agree with me that we, as conservative
Americans, need to unite and advance a strong, forceful agenda,''
Smith said. But, he said, ``they pleaded with me to come back and
fight within the party. People that I respect and trust told me _
in no uncertain terms _ that I had become a lightning rod for
divisiveness, not the rallying and unifying factor that I had hoped
to be in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Smith said, he technically never left the GOP. The
reason: The town councilors who approve party switches had not yet
held a meeting since Smith filled out his party card three months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, during all these weeks of controversy, I've actually been
a Republican after all!'' Smith said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
