<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MIDEAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRUE PATH TOWARD MIDEAST PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Oslo, where Israel's Prime Minister Ehud Barak, Yasser
Arafat, and President Clinton have gathered to honor the
assassinated Israeli peacemaker Yitzhak Rabin, all the public talk
has been of process and timetables. ``I would feel that real
progress had been made if they made agreements about the modalities
under which they will proceed,'' Clinton said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But issues of substance can no longer be postponed. Barak's
commitment to a compressed calendar _ a framework for agreement by
February and a final-status accord by the end of next year _
compels the parties to clarify their positions now.
</P>
<P>
   The contours of Israel's stance were described Monday in the
Israeli newspaper Ha'aretz. The central point of an account leaked
to the paper by the Barak government is that the framework
agreement in February will authorize the Palestinians to establish
an independent state before the signing of a final agreement.
</P>
<P>
   There is a certain irony in the rationale for this sequence,
given the history of Israeli opposition to a sovereign state for
Palestinians. The Barak government recognizes that a Palestinian
state must come into being before a final agreement is reached,
because at present neither the PLO nor the Palestinian Authority
can sign what Ha'aretz calls ``an international agreement that
settles the conflict between two sovereign states.''
</P>
<P>
   If that agreement is to prohibit the Palestinian state from
forming alliances with other parties hostile to Israel, as Barak
will insist, then the guarantee must be given by the new state, not
by a precursor organization. In this manner form becomes content;
the diplomatic calendar dictates the substance of a peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators are also talking about expanding Jerusalem to
include Palestinian neighborhoods, making possible an undivided
city that may nevertheless serve as capital for two separate
states. Rabin's goal, a negotiated peace agreement, is no longer
the mirage of visionaries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
