u a BC-CRASH-PEOPLE-BOS &LR;      11-01 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-PEOPLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIENDS, FAMILIES RECALL PERSONALITIES OF FLIGHT 990 DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One passenger was once kidnapped by Kurdish rebels.
Another couple were missionaries going to visit refugees in the
Sudan. A woman from Chicago was traveling as a birthday present to
herself. She had just turned 80.
</P>
<P>
   And a retired surgeon, who loved ``working cattle'' on his
family's Colorado ranch more than anything else, pushed himself to
go on a two-week Egypt tour because ``he kind of thought his time
was limited,'' his son said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On EgyptAir Flight 990, they were among the 217 people on board,
all now presumed dead.
</P>
<P>
   In a sweeping sense, the passenger list, released Monday by the
airline, wasn't that different from the profiles of other New
York-to-Cairo flights. Nearly a third were Egyptian and nearly
two-thirds were American or Canadian tourists, all steeling
themselves for an 11-hour flight over the Atlantic, anticipating
going home, a trip of a lifetime or simply an adventure among
friends.
</P>
<P>
   But the airline's manifest tells no stories about the people in
the almost-full flight. That was left to friends and relatives
Monday. They told fascinating stories, everyday stories that
revealed character. They told stories you might hear if you sat
next to the person on the airplane, full of facts, dreams, fears
and hope of what awaited them in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   It's what binds the 217 now, the people they left behind, their
friends and families telling stories about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing about my dad was that he liked people. He had a
lot of patience,'' said Kevin McCulloch, 36, whose father, Tom, 72,
was on the flight. Tom McCulloch, a retired surgeon from Durango,
Colo., was traveling with a friend, John Voelker, 70. They had both
signed up for an Elderhostel two-week trip that was to be full of
lectures on ancient Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad would get out on the ranch whenever he could. Even when
he was practicing, he would take off Wednesday afternoons and by 1
p.m. he was out working cattle,'' Kevin McCulloch said. ``My mom
died 10 years ago this month, and my dad had never done any
traveling before that. He kind of thought his time was limited and
he needed to get out and see some of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   From Toronto, Salah Adam, his wife Saline and their two
children, Joshua, 4, and Rebecca, 22 months, were on their way to
Sudan for a wedding, to see family and friends and then to visit
refugee camps. It was only natural for them. They were
missionaries.
</P>
<P>
   Eugenia Rhodes traveled from Chicago. She had turned 80 on July
11, and Egypt was the latest in her long life of travel, which
included visits to China, Russia, Indonesia, Hong Kong and all over
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had some challenges with arthritis, but she had no problem
figuring out how to get around. She had an independent spirit and
was outspoken and opinionated _ just about everything,'' said the
Rev. Leonetta Bugleisi of Beverly Unitarian Church in Chicago. ``I
think Egypt was one of the last wonderful places that she hadn't
gotten to. She had a little anxiety about planning, though. And she
had made some tongue-in-cheek jokes to her friends that she might
not come back from this trip alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Worries about flying, of course, aren't unusual. Harry Kolander,
79, of San Ramon, Calif., worried about his wife, Imilda, 66,
traveling alone. His diabetes made it difficult for him to travel,
and he encouraged her to continue to see the world without him. In
1991, she had visited Turkey and was one of five people held
hostage by Kurdish rebels for three days, escaping with the tour
director by scrambling over a mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Imilda Kolander boarded a flight in Los Angeles and met in New
York with a group organized by Grand Circle Travel in Boston. On
the way to the Los Angeles airport, Harry Kolander told the Contra
Costa Times, his wife talked about something bad happening on the
flight. He said she told him, ``If that will happen, I do hope it's
fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Also boarding an American Airlines flight in Los Angeles were
four Orange County women who played cards together every Thursday
night for years, the youngest was 57, the oldest 82. Their names
were Judy Bowman, Beverly Grant, Sheila Jaffee and Tobey Seidman.
</P>
<P>
   The four, who joined the EgyptAir flight in New York, had spent
a year of Thursday nights planning an agenda as they played cards,
talking about motoring down the Nile on a cruise ship to Luxor and
Aswan, perhaps riding a camel to the Pyramids outside Cairo and
then heading north to the Sea of Galilee in Israel to walk where
Jesus walked.
</P>
<P>
   In West Point, Miss., Edmund Miller Sr., and his wife Hannah,
both in their 70s, were excited about the same trip _ they, too,
had booked the same tour.
</P>
<P>
   Edmund Miller was a retired Navy captain, and he had settled in
the northeastern Mississippi town of 12,000 people because it was
where he grew up. His grandfather was pastor of the First Baptist
Church at the turn of the century, said the current pastor, the
Rev. Gary Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were Christians,'' the minister said. ``They were very
much looking forward to the trip to Israel. They loved this church.
And they were both loved here. Hannah Miller was a very giving
person, concerned particularly for the elderly. She made sure two
people in particular were watched over. I've talked to one of them
and it's very hard, very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Hisham Elzanaty will tell you it's hard for all those left
behind now.
</P>
<P>
   He lost his mother and father, Abdu and Fawqia Elzanaty of the
Heliopolis section of Cairo on the flight. All four of the couple's
children now live in the United States, so the parents visit for
two or three months every year. But at the end of each year's trip,
Hisham Elzanaty said, his parents are always eager about getting
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always try to get them to stay longer,'' said Hisham
Elzanaty, 40, the second oldest child. ``They always like to get
back to their nest in Cairo. But when they are here, they make so
many friends. My father, he's friends to all my friends. He's
worked all his life. He's a contractor for an oil company, and he's
out of the house at 9 in the morning and not home until 9 at night.
That's pretty good for someone 74. He had a big presence in life.''
</P>
<P>
   No more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll miss my parents. I'll miss their presence,'' Hisham
Elzanaty said. ``You miss the thing that you lean on, and now it's
sort of like I'm on my own. I have a wife, three children, and
another one due in three weeks, but you always look for your
parents no matter how old you get. You still may think you're a
little kid sometimes, and you want them to lean on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
