<HEADLINE>
TEXAS JUDGE REFUSES TO STOP FORMER PLAYMATE'S BANKRUPTCY CLAIM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Optional ending included) 
 
By RON NISSIMOV 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ For the second time in a week, a Texas judge refused
to stop former Playboy Playmate Anna Nicole Smith from pursuing her
bankruptcy claim in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Although Harris County Probate Judge Mike Wood on Monday
declined to grant an injunction preventing Smith from continuing
her bankruptcy trial that started last week, lawyers said the judge
again expressed ``strong concern'' that the bankruptcy court may
interfere with his jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers said Wood's ruling presumably means that Smith's
bankruptcy trial, which resumes Wednesday, will be completed
Friday, as scheduled. The bankruptcy court's jurisdiction to
enforce any orders could be challenged after it makes a final
ruling, lawyers said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Samuel L. Bufford in Los Angeles has
raised concerns about jurisdiction by issuing an order in May that
Smith is entitled to half of the wealth amassed by her deceased
billionaire husband, J. Howard Marshall II. Her lawyers have said
the fortune is worth more than $1.6 billion, and Smith should get
$820 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bufford did not make the ruling based on the merits of the case,
but to sanction Marshall's younger, son, E. Pierce Marshall, 60, of
Dallas, for allegedly destroying evidence and not showing up for
depositions. E. Pierce Marshall, who took over his father's oil
business, claims he was willed the entire fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 31, who was married to J. Howard Marshall II for 14
months before he died in 1995 at age 90, claims he promised her
half of his wealth if she married him. She maintains E. Pierce
Marshall defrauded her out of her inheritance.
</P>
<P>
   E. Pierce Marshall's attorney Don Fogel said Monday that
Bufford's rulings may not only affect his client, but also other
parties who claim they are owed a piece of the estate.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall's elder of two sons, J. Howard Marshall III, 63, of Los
Angeles has sued his brother in Houston's Harris County for
fraudulently denying him half of the estate he says he is owed. E.
Pierce Marshall says the father disinherited the elder son over a
1980 business dispute. Bufford did not allow the elder son to
intervene in the bankruptcy matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Harris County) court is very concerned that the
bankruptcy court, if it enters the judgment (Smith) seeks, would be
interfering with the court's jurisdiction and the rights of other
claimants,'' Fogel said.
</P>
<P>
   Other entities making claims to the fortune are Yale University,
where the deceased Marshall earned a law degree, and Haverford
University in Pennsylvania, where he earned an undergraduate
degree.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fogel said Wood told attorneys Monday that if Smith's bankruptcy
was in a Houston federal court, the presiding judge would have
likely postponed the proceedings pending the outcome of the probate
case. Fogel said all federal bankruptcy judges have to follow the
same jurisdiction laws, and he did not know why Bufford is not
postponing the matter in his court.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's attorneys have claimed that they are not interfering
with Wood's jurisdiction because they are only making claims
against E. Pierce Marshall in bankruptcy court, not against the
estate.
</P>
<P>
   But since E. Pierce Marshall's wealth primarily comes from the
family business willed to him, Fogel said it would be impossible
for Bufford issue a monetary judgment against his client without
dividing the estate.
</P>
<P>
   E. Pierce Marshall's attorneys have denied their client did
anything to warrant such severe sanctions in bankruptcy court. They
said the evidence that was allegedly destroyed were business
documents that their client routinely discarded and which were
easily available through other sources.
</P>
<P>
   They have also said that a lawyer handling the estate's taxes
has possession of some of the documents and has been unwilling to
give them up. They said E. Pierce Marshall has no authority to tell
the lawyer to give up the documents. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
