<HEADLINE>
EXCURSION TO MONTEVIDEO  
 GRAND CANYON FROM ABOVE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 7) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Questions may be italicized)  
 By PAUL FREIREICH (af)  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Excursion to Montevideo &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. During a short visit to Buenos Aires this fall we will have a
free day and wondered if it would be possible to take a day tour of
Montevideo with an English-speaking guide. _ Anthony A. Leach,
Eastham, Mass.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The best way to get across the Rio de la Plata from Buenos
Aires to Montevideo, Uruguay, is by ferry or plane.
</P>
<P>
   The ferry takes two and a half hours and costs $107 round trip
and $53 one way on both lines that operate on the route:
Ferry-lineas, telephone (54-11) 4314 0228, fax (54-11) 4314 1190,
and Buquebus, telephone (54-11) 4316 6500, no fax.
</P>
<P>
   The word ``hydrofoil'' may call up an image of speed. And, in
fact, the hydrofoil takes a mere 45 minutes across the Rio de la
Plata to Colonia, Uruguay, a town that's worth a visit if you have
the time. But coursing through Uruguay's hilly terrain by bus adds
three hours of travel time.
</P>
<P>
   The hydrofoil run by Ferry-lineas is about $66 round trip and
$31 one way, and the bus to Montevideo is $16 round trip, $8 one
way.
</P>
<P>
   Five hydrofoils and five ferries depart on weekdays from Buenos
Aires during the summer. The first ferry leaves at 8 a.m. and the
first hydrofoil at 8:20 a.m. Returning from Montevideo the last
ferry leaves at 6:40 p.m. and the last hydrofoil at 8:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   With limited time, you may want to consider flying one or both
ways. The flight is only 40 minutes, and for much of the day planes
leave almost every hour between Aeroparque Jorge Newbery in Buenos
Aires and Aeropuerto Internacional Carrasco, about a half-hour
outside of Montevideo.
</P>
<P>
   The three main airlines that fly the route are Lapa, Aerolineas
Argentinas and Pluna. A round-trip ticket costs $150 and one way is
$68.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you are interested in shopping, a half day is all it
takes to see the city's highlights. English-speaking tours usually
cover the Ciudad Vieja, the Colonial Town Hall, the Cathedral,
Centenario Park, the Cerro (from which one can see the city) and
the highway along the Rio de la Plata.
</P>
<P>
   Among the companies in Monte-video you might try for half-day
tours are Jetmar, (598-2) 902 0793, Viajes Bueme, (598-2) 902 1050,
and M.T. International, (598-2) 902 2672. A private tour costs $46
a person but if you join a group of 5 to 15, the price drops to
about $15. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you prefer, these companies offer sightseeing in the morning,
a visit to a shopping center in the afternoon and then transfer to
the airport or a hotel. In addition to the charge of $46 a person
for sightseeing, tack on $24 for the shopping stop and $12 an hour
for waiting time while you roam the aisles. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grand Canyon From Above &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are hoping to visit the Grand Canyon next year.
Can you tell me about tours by helicopter or small plane? _
Salvatore R. Conte, Morristown, N.J. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. While the battle over aircraft noise over the Grand Canyon
continues, so do the flights. To comply with a 1987 law, the
Federal Aviation Administration and the National Park Service are
working to ``substantially restore natural quiet in the Grand
Canyon National Park.'' Proposals presented by the agencies call
for increasing the ``quiet zone'' and for limiting air-tour flights
over the park to 88,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest obvious difference between airplane and helicopter
tours is cost, with helicopter trips being $80 to $90 more. But
there are other differences, too: A helicopter flies lower (at
least 500 feet above the ground versus 1,000 feet for a plane) and,
says Ron Williams, president of AirStar Helicopters, it flies more
slowly _ 69 to 104 miles an hour (converted from knots) versus a
plane's 104 to 115 miles an hour. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aerial tours from Grand Canyon National Park Airport are offered
on helicopters that carry 4 to 6 passengers and on planes that
carry 9 to 19. There are basically two routes, which are given a
variety of enticing names by tour operators:
</P>
<P>
   _ The central corridor: A tour of 25 to 30 minutes by a
helicopter that heads basically north along the canyon's Dragon, or
central, Corridor to the North Rim, does a 180-degree turn and then
heads south.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big circle (called East Rim, for shorthand, below): A tour
of 40 to 55 minutes by helicopter (45 to 50 minutes by plane) that
travels over the Colorado River, the Painted Desert and the eastern
canyon and then across the North Rim before turning south at the
central corridor.
</P>
<P>
   For one of the clearer maps of the both routes, you may want to
look at the Kenai Helicopters Web site, www.flykenai.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The companies with flights from Grand Canyon National Park
Airport _ rates including taxes and fees _ are these:
</P>
<P>
   AirStar Helicopters, (800) 962-3869, fax (520) 638-2607;
www.airstar.com. Most flights are by helicopter. Central corridor
by copter: $94. East Rim by copter $161; by Cessna 207, which
carries nine passengers, $71, $51 for those under 15.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Canyon Airlines, (800) 528-2413 or (520) 638-2407; on the
Internet at www.grandcanyonairlines.com. A single type of flight is
offered: over the East Rim aboard a 19-passenger modified Twin
Otter. Cost: $75, $45 age 2 to 12.
</P>
<P>
   Kenai Helicopters, (800) 541-4537; www.flykenai.com. Central
corridor: $99, $89 ages 12 and under. East Rim: $155, $145 ages 12
and under.
</P>
<P>
   Papillon Grand Canyon Helicopters, (800) 528-2418 or (520)
638-2419, fax (520) 638-3235; www.papillon.com. Central corridor:
$99, $80 ages 2 to 11. East Rim: $159, $128 ages 2 to 11.
</P>
<P>
   For those setting out from Las Vegas, two carriers operate
flights over the West Rim of the canyon that also offer views of
Lake Mead and the Hoover Dam.
</P>
<P>
   Papillon, mentioned above, (888) 635-7272, fax (702) 736-0099,
has a 90-minute helicopter flight at a cost of $257.
</P>
<P>
   Scenic Airlines, (800) 634-6801, fax (702) 638-3275,
www.scenic.com, has a long and short flight aboard a Twin Otter;
both have the same itinerary. The 80-minute version is $162, $132
for ages 2 to 11; the 60-minute version is $110, $90 for ages 2 to
11. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
