<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 7) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vast Arizona Caves Will Open to the Public &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, two spelunkers, Randy Tufts and Gary Tenen, set out in
search of undiscovered caves in southern Arizona. After wriggling
through a crawl space that was about 10 inches high and 2 feet
across, the men discovered what today is known as Kartchner
Caverns, a seven-acre cave system in the Whetstone Mountains, 40
miles southeast of Tucson. The caverns include two galleries the
size of football fields, each with 100-foot ceilings and 26 smaller
chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years and $28 million after the caverns were first
discovered, the public is about to get its first look at them.
Kartchner Caverns State Park _ named after the family that owned
the land and helped preserve it _ is scheduled to open Friday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The caves took more than 330 million years to evolve. Rock
formations include thousands of stalactites; a 21-foot-2-inch-long
soda straw _ the longest mineral formation of its kind in the
United States; and one of the world's most extensive formations of
brushite moonmilk (microscopic calcite crystals).
</P>
<P>
   Fossils were discovered in the caverns as well. Paleontologists
found the skeletal remains of an 80,000-year-old Shasta ground
sloth, the head of a 34,000-year-old horse and an 11,000-year-old
bear. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures inside the cave average around 68 degrees, with 99
percent humidity year round. Tours of the Rotunda and the Throne
Room in the upper chambers, which last about an hour and are nearly
a mile in length, leave approximately every 20 minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 550-acre state park has hiking trails, picnic areas and a
Discovery Center that provides educational information about the
caverns including interactive exhibits, among them the
``Underground Journey,'' a computer-simulated tour of the cave
system.
</P>
<P>
   Kartchner Caverns State Park will be open from 8 a.m. to 6 p.m.
Reservations are highly recommended. Admission is $10 a car. Cave
tours are $14; $6 for children 7 to 13. Information: (520) 586-2283
or www.pr.state.az.us.
</P>
<P>
   Alisha Berger &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Depot Is Saved, A Museum Born &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Science City, a 55,000-square-foot science museum, will open on
Nov. 20 inside the recently restored and expanded Union Station in
Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   A visit there is likely to engage both history and science
buffs. Built in 1914, Union Station, the second-largest railroad
station in the country (Grand Central Terminal in New York is the
largest), is a superb example of Beaux-Arts architecture. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the last five years, a combination of private
contributions and public funds has been used to restore the train
depot to its original glory. The total cost of the renovation was
$250 million.
</P>
<P>
   During the renovation process, city planners were looking for
new uses for the building and turned to the Kansas City Museum for
ideas. Science City took form, and a new addition to the west of
the station's north waiting room was built to house the museum. The
depot will also house numerous restaurants, shops and theaters,
making it an appealing evening destination as well.
</P>
<P>
   Science City will feature more than 50 hands-on learning
environments, including the space center and the media lab. Each
was designed to be as realistic as possible, and visitors are
encouraged to get involved by using the museum's computers,
simulators and other props. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Science City, 30 West Pershing, Kansas City, Mo. 64108, (816)
460-2222, will be open 9:30 a.m. to 5 p.m. daily. Admission is
$12.50, $11 for seniors and $9 for children 4 to 12; children under
3 are free. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
