<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5661 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$A     11-01 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV07-1090(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGLE TRAVELERS ARE BEING HEARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Nov. 7)  
(lb) 
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tour companies say they are hearing clients voice an increasing
distaste for the single supplement, the additional fee for those
occupying a room alone.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Cali, senior vice president for marketing at Grand Circle
Travel in Boston, for example, said the clients he met on two
recent trips complained to him a lot about this extra charge, which
some catalogs list at 25 percent of the quoted price of a trip. A
friend who travels often says she believes supplements add 30
percent to her land costs.
</P>
<P>
   Cali said that among his company's clients who are 65 and over,
nearly 50 percent of the women and 14 percent of the men were
traveling by themselves, and that ``they want us to be more
single-friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Many companies catering to travelers 45 to 65 years old are
trying to accommodate those wanting single rooms; demographics
demonstrate how the chorus is likely to rise. Martha Farnsworth
Riche, a former director of the Census Bureau, says this age group
is increasing so rapidly that it is in effect a ``new country,''
populated by people still working, in good health and in their
prime spending years. They frequently travel alone or, if with
friends, seek the privacy of a single room.
</P>
<P>
   In a U.S. population totaling 270 million, Ms. Riche said in a
discussion at the Journalism and Women Symposium in September, 57
million _ 21 percent _ were in the 45-to-65 group in 1998, with the
baby boomers pouring in at the young end. She said Census Bureau
statistics indicated that this bloc would number 62 million by next
year, and 73 million by 2005, an increase of almost 18 percent in a
decade when the overall U.S. population will be growing 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Riche, who heads her own demographics organization in
Bethesda, Md., emphasizes that these people will be active because
``healthy life expectancy is growing just as fast as the older
population.''
</P>
<P>
   Working With Hotels
</P>
<P>
   Big tour operators I talked to said they were closely examining
the changes that are coming with the surge in those enjoying what
Ms. Riche called their ``20 new years.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last three years, Saga International in Boston, which
sells tours directly to people over 50, has been highlighting
``single rooms at no additional cost'' on brochures for some trips.
Kerry Chrisley, a spokeswoman, said 10 percent to 25 percent of her
company's clients got single rooms. ``We try to foster
relationships with our hotels,'' she said, so that when extra
single rooms are needed, the hotel is willing to be accommodating.
</P>
<P>
   Single rates without surcharges are more often found on trips
using only one hotel or residence. A Saga trip to Costa Rica is
typical. A one-week stay at the San Jose Palacio is offered nine
times early next year at a price of $1,099 to $1,299 a person,
including air fare from Miami, whether two are in a room or one.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Circle, which also markets directly to over-50 travelers,
has some single rooms with no extra charges in its listings, for
example, 13-night visits to the Nautilus Hotel on the Costa del
Sol, and offerings in Majorca. Cali said that five to 10 rooms out
of 25 on a regular departure might be singles. A 1997 survey of
clients indicated that 36 percent were not married, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Price range is also a factor in the surcharge, and less
expensive trips are more likely to have no extra fee. Smithsonian
Study Tours appends a note giving the extra cost for a single room
to virtually every listing. (On the Oxford study tour, all rooms
are singles.) But the brochure for Smithsonian Odyssey Tours, a
less expensive line operated by Saga, says: ``A limited number of
single rooms are available on each tour at the best rate possible
or at no additional charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Lucash of Middletown, N.J., said she looked for places
that cater to solo travelers, not in hopes of meeting Mr. Wonderful
but because she did not want to spend her vacation surrounded by
couples.
</P>
<P>
   And, she said, places that charge a single supplement seem to
discourage solo travelers. At a resort in Playa del Carmen, Mexico,
she said, ``When I went in to dinner, the maitre d' graciously
pulled out the chair at a table for two, and that was where I was
supposed to spend my vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lucash said her trip was saved when she met three women from
Toronto and they hung out together. Organizations like Club Med
that seek to match up single travelers, even if they do not succeed
in finding a roommate, usually have a dining-room plan that does
not leave singles stranded.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the Numbers
</P>
<P>
   Paolo Mantegazza, president of Globus and Cosmos Tourama in
Littleton, Colo., which takes 2.5 million clients a year on its
tours, said that his company saw changing patterns reflected in its
recent demographic survey. ``The boomers turning 50 and entering
this market are more travel wise, more open to experiences,'' he
said. ``Their sheer numbers alone force us to review what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The earlier senior market,'' he added, ``was more balanced in
the number of couples and single travelers. The new senior market
is much more driven by single women: divorced, widows and `travel
widows.' The boomers are used to going out on their own if the
partner does not want to participate.''
</P>
<P>
   Retirees, he said, have a lot of time and want to be active on
their vacations. Now, people still working want to vacation longer
in one place and examine it in more depth _ for example, to
experience ``the real Asia'' by taking tai chi classes or learning
to cook dim-sum.
</P>
<P>
   The design of tours, formerly focused on the
five-cities-in-10-days model, he said, is also affected by the
popularity of cruises and all-inclusive resorts, which do not
require daily repacking and moving.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Anthony, president of Saga, concurred on the increasing
demand for in-depth and educational travel, which meshes easily
with the use of one hotel as a base for exploration. ``We find that
single people can meet with others or explore on their own,'' he
said. ``If one person in a couple wants to stay behind, this is
manageable.''
</P>
<P>
   Being based in one place makes it easier for the operator to
offer a lower surcharge or none, because it will deal with only one
hotel and the longer stay increases an operator's leverage.
``Single travelers have paid a lot, a penalty,'' Anthony said. ``We
try to make a name for ourselves in avoiding this. For two years,
we have had a London Christmas for singles that sells well, and we
look to continue expanding that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Globus, Mantegazza said, has been seeking to make the prices
more attractive to single travelers. The company's numbers allow it
to negotiate vigorously for better rates, but there is still
another anomaly: ``Europe has been in a boom,'' he said, and
``hoteliers are not always responsive. If things slow up, we will
be able to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Lucash noted, there is a second problem: eating alone.
The options are opening up here, too, because of more older
travelers and an increasing number of women traveling on expense
accounts. And more and more, travelers complete their business but
stay over Saturday night to avoid higher fares, yet dislike being
compelled to have a room-service dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Business travel magazines have recently spotlighted restaurants
that provide big tables where solo diners are grouped together, and
arrangements for eating at the bar or in the bar area. I recently
found that the Holiday Inn at the Salt Lake City airport was able
to provide an acceptable Saturday afternoon supper at the bar for a
stomach from another time zone.
</P>
<P>
   Marya Charles Alexander in South Pasadena, Calif., has been
harvesting such tidbits in her newsletter ``Solo Dining Savvy,''
published six times a year. (She also publishes a yearly list of
100 best choices.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Alexander urges single diners who have a bad experience to
write the restaurant, or her, rather than make a scene on the spot.
She says she gets news from restaurateurs about what they offer to
attract solo diners. She finds that single diners increasingly
consider themselves worthy of good treatment and are assertive
about their needs.
</P>
<P>
   The newsletter costs $29 a year; the ``100 Top'' $9.95. Solo
Dining Savvy, P.O. Box 1025, South Pasadena, CA 91031; (800)
299-1079.
</P>
<P>
   The single supplement is not immutable. For those willing to
share if they can find a suitable single, many tour companies, in
addition to newsletters and membership groups like Jens Jurgen's
Travel Companion Exchange in Amityville, N.Y., (516) 454-0880,
offer ways for people to connect with others. Some tour companies
offer singles-only trips, especially at slow periods. Tours to some
areas _ India, for example _ use hotels built with only single
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   But expectations create difficulties. Americans who book a
single room abroad are sometimes surprised by what they find,
probably because they were looking for a 300-square-foot U.S.-style
hotel room, with two beds or a double bed. What they more often
find is a rather cell-like room with a single bed, a desk-dresser
and a shallow cupboard.
</P>
<P>
   Operators try to warn Americans that Europeans build single
rooms on the less desirable sides of hotels, the trade-off for
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   I got a typical European single for a health conference in
Zurich, Switzerland, years ago. What really stunned me was the
vista: a huge clock tower just outside the one window. It stayed
lighted all night. But by the end of the week, it seemed like a
friend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
