<SLUG> BC-SHUSTER-CASE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUSTER CASE CLOSES AS TWO AIDES PLEAD GUILTY TO MISDEMEANORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Citing a recent Supreme Court ruling that raised the
bar in proving political corruption cases, federal prosecutors
Monday dropped a sweeping indictment against a former high-ranking
Congressional aide and a lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Ann Eppard, former chief of staff for US Representative
Bud Shuster, the powerful House transportation committee chairman
from Pennsylvania, and lobbyist Vernon Clark were allowed to plead
guilty to misdemeanor charges.
</P>
<P>
   Eppard admitted receiving several payments totalling $15,000, an
interest-free $30,000 loan, and meals, lodging, travel and
entertainment totalling $12,000 from lobbyist Clark while working
for Shuster. She must pay a $5,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, who was representing two Boston businessmen whose
property was threatened by the Big Dig, pleaded guilty to making
the payments to Eppard and to a separate charge of filing a false
income-tax return. He was fined $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   US District Judge Joseph L. Tauro declined the government's
request to place Eppard and Clark on probation for a year, saying
it wouldn't benefit society.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's hearing appeared to mark the end of a five-year federal
investigation of Shuster, who has been a key player in helping
Massachusetts obtain funding for the Big Dig, and had allegedly
been the ultimate target of the probe that snared Eppard and Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant US Attorney Ben T. Clements told the court that a plea
agreement between the government and Eppard and Clark stemmed from
a recent Supreme Court ruling ``that narrowly construed the
gratuities law'' that had been used to indict the pair last year.
</P>
<P>
   The high court ruled unanimously last April that jurors couldn't
convict Sun-Diamond Growers of California of giving $5,900 in
illegal gratuities to former Secretary of Agriculture Mike Espy
because there was no evidence that the gifts were linked to any
official act.
</P>
<P>
   The court concluded that it isn't enough for prosecutors to show
that gift-givers wanted to curry favor with officials in a position
to help them. Rather, the court said, prosecutors have to tie the
gift-giving to an official act performed or about to be performed.
</P>
<P>
   In a press release issued Monday, US Attorney Donald K. Stern
said Clark's clients were seeking government action on the Big Dig
when Clark made the payments to Eppard.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there is no evidence of a quid pro quo, these payments
are nonetheless illegal,'' Stern said. ``The machinery of
government is corrupted by under-the-table payments designed to
smooth the way for lobbyists.''
</P>
<P>
   But attorney Richard Egbert, who represents Eppard, lashed back
at Stern, saying that if he had evidence that the machinery of
government was corrupted, ``Then he should have continued the
prosecution of these indictments instead of dismissing them. If he
had such evidence and dismissed these cases, he should consider
whether or not he should be in the position he holds.''
</P>
<P>
   Egbert described Clark as a longtime friend of Eppard and
described the three $5,000 payments he gave her through an unnamed
relative as consulting fees. The $30,000 loan she received from
Clark was a bridge loan that she used to buy a condo and later
repaid, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have no evidence that it was an effort to influence and
no evidence that it did influence her,'' Egbert said. He noted that
as part of the agreement, Eppard wasn't charged with willfully
committing a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Egbert said the government brought a broad and sweeping
indictment against Eppard involving corruption, mail fraud, wire
fraud and embezzlement ``based on an erroneous understanding of the
law.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington attorney Barry Simon and Boston attorney Terry Segal,
who represented Clark, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Stephen Delinsky, who represents Shuster, said Shuster
has ``enormous respect and admiration'' for Eppard and Clark and
that the outcome of the case validates his longheld belief in their
integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Delinsky said the Supreme Court ruling in the Sun-Diamond case
``refocuses prosecutors' investigations onto the traditional
notions of what corruption means: selling your office in exchange
for money, bribery. When people think of corruption that's what
they think of. They don't think of gratuities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
