<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSEUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RESINSTATES SUBSIDIES FOR BROOKLYN MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Saying Mayor Rudolph Giuliani had run roughshod over
the First Amendment, a federal judge ruled Monday that the mayor
had no right to cut off city subsidies to the Brooklyn Museum of
Art for displaying art that he considered ``disgusting'' and
``anti-Catholic.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 40-page decision, US District Judge Nina Gershon charged
that the mayor had violated the museum's free speech rights by
forcing a choice between city funding and closing the controversial
exhibit. She ordered him to restore the subsidy, barred him from
denying or delaying future payments, and warned against any attempt
by the city to evict the museum or to interfere with the museum's
directors.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the museum's board, Robert S. Rubin, hailed the
decision as ``a victory for the citizens of New York and for
freedom of expression across the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani denounced not only the ruling but also Gershon, calling
her ``totally out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   City Hall's chief lawyer said he would file an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The case erupted a month ago, when the museum opened
``Sensation,'' an exhibition of works by young British artists that
included such provocative exhibits as a dead shark floating in a
tank of formaldehyde, a sliced-up pig, and _ most offensive to the
mayor _ a painting of the Virgin Mary decorated with elephant dung.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani threatened to withhold city funding, amounting to over
$500,000 a month or one-third of the museum's operational budget,
if the exhibit was not canceled or the painting of Mary was not
removed.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's board refused to back down, and sued the city and
the mayor, accusing them of violating its First Amendment rights.
</P>
<P>
   The city's lawyers had argued, in a court hearing last month,
that the First Amendment does not require the government to
subsidize art.
</P>
<P>
   Gershon agreed that the government has no obligation to provide
benefits, but called that only half the argument. Subsidies, once
provided, may not be denied ``if the reason for the denial would
require a choice between exercising First Amendment rights and
obtaining the benefit,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is,'' she elaborated, quoting from one of many US Supreme
Court rulings, ``it may not `discriminate . . . in its subsidies in
such a way as to aim at the suppression of dangerous ideas.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And that, the judge said, is just what Giuliani did: ``The facts
establish an ongoing effort . . . to coerce the Museum into
relinquishing its First Amendment rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge also rejected the city's argument that taxpayers
should not have to pay for expression they dislike. She noted that
federal taxes subsidize the mailing of magazines many find
objectionable, and that state taxes pay the salaries of professors
who give controversial lectures.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's lawyers had argued that he cut off subsidies not
because of the ``Sensation'' show's contents but rather because the
museum, in its handling of the show, violated its lease with the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Gershon rejected this argument as a ``pretext'' and a ``sham,''
finding ``no language in the lease . . . that gives the Mayor or
the City the right to veto works chosen for exhibition.''
</P>
<P>
   She also noted that the city's lawyers, at one point in the
hearing, ``admitted the obvious'' _ that Giuliani's action was
``directly related . . . to the content of the exhibit.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge added, ``There can be no greater showing of a First
Amendment violation.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's ruling does not end the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do city lawyers plan an appeal, but the museum plans to
seek judicial approval to make Monday's temporary injunction
permanent.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hess, City Hall's lawyer, said he would try, in opposing
a permanent injunction, to introduce a new argument, based on an
article in Monday's New York Times that detailed how the museum
raised funds to put on ``Sensation'' from donors who had a
commercial interest in the exhibit's artworks.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter Monday morning to Gershon, Hess alleged that such
``unethical conduct'' by the museum amounts to a violation of the
requirement of its lease that it limit the use of the museum
building to a `public purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Hess asked Gershon to reopen the case in light of the Times's
``extraordinary revelations.'' She turned down this request before
handing down her decision.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams Monday afternoon both rejected Hess's accusation and
derided it as legally irrelevant. Such questions do not, he said,
go to the ``core reality of this case _ that the mayor has punished
the museum for the content of its art.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
