<HEADLINE>
IN ITS FIRST LIVE TEST, ISRAEL'S ARROW II INTERCEPTS INCOMING
ROCKET  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Passing its first major antiballistic missile test,
the new Arrow II missile successfully intercepted and destroyed a
dummy incoming rocket over the Mediterranean on Monday, the Israeli
air force reported.
</P>
<P>
   The exercise was a critical rite of passage for the joint
Israeli-American Arrow II program, the only antiballistic-missile
defense system under active development with the capacity to
demolish warheads high in the stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The first two $170 million batteries of the Arrow II are being
installed here. Military officials here say they expect the system
to become operational early next year. The U.S. Congress recently
appropriated $42 million for the third battery, raising the total
direct American contribution to $83 million in the current fiscal
year. About two-thirds of the cost of the program is being covered
by Israel's defense budget, although American military aid is
underwriting much of the expense.
</P>
<P>
   The destroyed missile, an earlier generation Arrow programmed to
mimic the trajectory of an enemy scud, was launched from an Israeli
warship and shot down by an Arrow II at 11:42 a.m. local time, the
air force said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Israeli military did not provide details, the Arrow
II is widely believed to have been launched from an air force base
20 miles south of Tel Aviv. The Arrow II was designed to knock out
missiles up to 30 miles away at altitudes of up to 25 miles.
</P>
<P>
   The exercise was intended to test not just the missile itself,
but also the Israeli-designed Green Pine radar and Citron Tree
``fire management.'' The radar and targeting systems had previously
been tested only by their Israeli manufacturers, Elta Electronics
and Tadiran Systems. ``The Green Pine fire-control radar obtained
the target, and the Citron Tree calculated the intercept, upon
which the Arrow hit and destroyed the target,'' the Defense
Ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1998, an Arrow II was reported to have hit a
``virtual'' target in its first airborne test. This first live
exercise with an incoming warhead was originally scheduled for a
year ago, but was postponed because of undisclosed technical
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   After further analysis of the test Monday, the Israeli military
is generally expected to proceed almost immediately with deploying
the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing everything to create an initial operational
capability within the coming months,'' Ilan Biran, a manager of the
Arrow program before stepping down last month as the Defense
Ministry's director-general, told Israel Radio last weekend. ``I
want to assume that by 2000 we will have this basic capability and
that we will build our forces to full capacity in the coming years,
with up to three full batteries that will be able to shoot down
ballistic missiles in the air.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 2001EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5666 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS02-COX     11-01 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons: Everything better after win
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was fun again Monday to be a Falcons player.
</P>
<P>
   Players were celebrating Sunday's 27-20 victory against
Carolina, and right tackle Ephraim Salaam was able to pick up his
mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``People look at you differently,'' Salaam said. ''You might get
a smile now when you're putting gas in your car, or a hello when
you go to the mailbox. It's like the world is much friendlier when
you win.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's it like at the mailbox when the Falcons lose?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't go,'' Salaam said. ``I just let my mail accumulate.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong safety Marty Carter said he has been picking up his mail
all along. But it was less painful Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just feel better,'' Carter said. ``It's like anything in
life. You get a win the day before, you know, and you feel better
getting up. My neck is not as stiff; my limp isn't as bad with the
win.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Falcons get no rest, with a home game on Sunday against
Jacksonville (6-1), one of the best teams in the league.
</P>
<P>
   With a bye the next week, however, players might be tempted to
look forward to better things. If the Falcons could steal an upset
victory over the Jaguars, they would return from the bye with road
games at Tampa Bay (3-4) and Carolina (2-5) before a home game
against New Orleans (1-6).
</P>
<P>
   Could the Falcons be looking at 6-6? Looking ahead, however,
might have been one of the Falcons' many problems this season.
Players did not look ahead in 1998, when the Falcons went 14-2
season and played in the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're looking ahead, then we've got more problems than we
thought,'' center Robbie Tobeck said. ``Last year, we were great at
just focusing on the game we were about to play. Like New England.
We went up there (Nov. 8) and beat the heck out of them (41-10) and
didn't even think about San Francisco the next week. Then, we beat
San Francisco (31-19).
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, before the season even started, everybody was
talking about the whole season, about the Super Bowl being in
Atlanta and making the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons won Sunday, Carter said, in part because they did a
very good job of not looking ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Free safety) Eugene (Robinson) said it best,'' Carter said.
`He said on every series, `Just think about this series and nothing
else.' We . . . were just thinking about making plays on that
series.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday's game, right guard Gene Williams is doubtful, with a
high right-ankle sprain.
</P>
<P>
   But the victory over Carolina will make getting ready for
Jacksonville easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always fun when you win; that's why we play,'' kicker
Morten Andersen said. ``Everything is easier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, when you win, there aren't that many mistakes,''
defensive end Lester Archambeau said. ``When you go into film, you
look for good things you did instead of not wanting to see the
mistakes you made and getting chewed out for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can handle it a lot easier when you win,'' Reeves said.
``It makes it a little bit easier to look at film and makes it a
little bit easier to go to sleep. But if we look any further than
the next opponent, it's a huge mistake. There is no way we can get
to .500 if we don't get No. 3 first.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
