<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ACCIDENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SUFFERS MINOR INJURIES AFTER AVOIDING OVERTURNED TRUCK  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush escaped with only minor
injuries to his leg and hip Monday as he dived to avoid debris
flying from a waste disposal truck that overturned next to the Town
Lake hike and bike trail.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the governor's security detail _ Department of
Public Safety Staff Sgt. Roscoe Hughey _ was knocked off his
bicycle and sustained injuries that required treatment at
Brackenridge Hospital. Hughey, 39, was released after treatment for
a cut on his side.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a freak accident. It was a close call for the governor,
and a close call for our guy,'' said DPS spokesman Tom Vinger. ``He
(Hughey) got knocked around pretty good, quite a bit of trauma.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinger and Austin Police Department spokesman Tracy Karol said
Bush was running west on the trail about 12:06 p.m. CDT when an
eastbound tractor truck pulling a dumpster-topped trailer
overturned on Cesar Chavez Boulevard. Debris from the trailer _
brush, concrete, wood and wire _ flew across the jogging trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It overturned and sprayed debris,'' Vinger said. ``It was from
a demolition, from a construction site.''
</P>
<P>
   In the area where the accident occurred, the riverside
dirt-and-gravel jogging trail runs next to the road like a
sidewalk. Garbage from the wreck fanned out from the street to the
river.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at the end of a three-mile run when I heard the noise,
looked back, saw it start to tip and my instincts were to dive,''
Bush told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, front-runner for the Republican presidential nomination,
said he scraped his right leg and hip when he dived behind a bridge
support. He said he was not struck by the debris from the truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a significant strawberry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was pleased to learn that Hughey was not seriously
injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very lucky and so is the DPS agent. I was very concerned
about him,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Edwards, the governor's press secretary, said Bush saw the
trooper buried in the debris and picked up the officer's cellular
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor used the officer's phone ... to call DPS at the
(governor's) mansion, and then they called 911,'' Edwards said.
``The governor stayed with Roscoe (Hughey) until he was put in the
ambulance.''
</P>
<P>
   An eyewitness, construction worker Joe Cardinas, told KTBC-TV in
Austin that emergency medical personnel tried to treat Bush at the
scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were trying to tend to him, but he was more concerned
about the (trooper),'' Cardinas said. ``Of course, the guy was
buried under the debris.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush returned to the mansion after the accident, changed clothes
and left on a trip to New Hampshire for his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Bush) knew his (Hughey's) injuries were not life
threatening,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   Hughey has been with DPS for six years and on the governor's
security detail since last December, Vinger said.
</P>
<P>
   Vinger said there was no reason to believe the truck's driver
was trying to hit Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Vinger nor Karol said the cause of the accident had been
determined, and neither had any information on the truck driver.
</P>
<P>
   Bush runs for exercise at least five days a week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Former Texas Gov. Ann Richards in 1993 broke her ankle when she
slipped on loose gravel while walking on the Town Lake hike and
bike trail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vinger said the truck is owned by Longhorn Disposal Co. The
phones at Longhorn's Austin office were not answered late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
