<HEADER>
A5686 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-EGYPTAIR-EGYPT-1102-C     11-01 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPTAIR-EGYPT-1102-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EGYPTIAN FAMILIES OF CRASH VICTIMS MAKE SAD VOYAGE TO U.S.
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    EDs: With coverage of EgyptAir crash.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ With the crash of EgyptAir Flight 990, Egyptian
sisters Rania and Suha El-Shagie(CQ) went, in one week, from the
joy of marriage to the grief of widowhood.
</P>
<P>
   Early Tuesday, they flew to the United States with others in
mourning, seeking to identify their loved-ones' remains.
</P>
<P>
   The journey came after a day of logistical preparations,
emotional outbursts and, finally, subdued waiting in the same
airport where victims' families had hoped to greet Flight 990 a
day-and-a-half before.
</P>
<P>
   But, the airplane had crashed into the Atlantic Ocean near
Massachusetts Sunday, apparently killing all 217 aboard. The dead
included two flight attendants betrothed to the two sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything seemed so perfect. He was everything to me,'' said
a red-eyed Suha El-Shagie as she and her sister waited in the
dining hall of Cairo International Airport where relatives were
awaiting their flight to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Suha, 26, and Rania, 23, just a week ago had completed the bulk
of the paperwork for their marriage and the two flight attendants,
Mohammed Galal and Hassan Farouk, respectively, left the next day
on the ill-fated Boeing 767.
</P>
<P>
   Flying was the centerpiece of their relationships, as all four
had met as flight attendants. Although last week, they completed
the paperwork in the long process of formal Muslim weddings, they
had not completed all the Islamic and social steps needed to start
their lives together in marriage.
</P>
<P>
   The women had a feeling they would never get the chance. Both
received ominous calls from the men before their last flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, 'I don't know why I'm so worried this time. I feel
like I need to talk to you before I get on the plane,''' Rania
recounted from her long-distance conversation from Farouk.
</P>
<P>
   The two women sat listlessly early Tuesday, crying often and
awaiting a journey they were about to begin with family members of
the 62 Egyptian passengers on the flight.
</P>
<P>
   While waiting to depart, some began to strike up conversations
and form friendships with people they had only met through the
tragedy. One man questioned the wisdom of taking the trip, all
expenses paid, by EgyptAir.
</P>
<P>
   They were headed to New York and then Rhode Island, to await the
recovery and identification of the victims' remains.
</P>
<P>
   Officials on Monday, all-but-ruled out the prospect for
survivors of the crash when they switched the operation to a
recovery effort. They had found seats, life vests, one body and a
major chunk of wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   There were reportedly 106 Americans on the flight and most were
apparently tourists or visitors to Egypt. U.S. Consul General Roger
Pierce said that he had no reports of Americans, except for those
holding dual Egyptian-American citizenship, residing in Egypt who
were killed in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   So, the focus Monday was on getting paperwork completed for the
Egyptian family members to go to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference room in the high-rise, downtown U.S. Embassy _
the largest U.S. Embassy in the world _ some of the 5,000 embassy
staff issued on-the-spot visas that normally take two days to
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an emotional thing and we've been working very long
hours,'' Piece said.
</P>
<P>
   EgyptAir pledged to compensate the victims' families and pay all
expenses for their flight and undetermined stay at a hotel near
where the wreckage is being unloaded. The airline is only taking
one family member for each victim.
</P>
<P>
   Mustafa Ibrahim Saleh Sa'ad, 42, prepared to go identify his
brother, Talat(cq), a Lt. Colonel in the Egyptian army. There was a
group of about 30 army officers on the flight after attending a
training course in communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was happy and everything was OK,'' Sa'ad, an agricultural
expert for the Egyptian government, said of a phone call he
received from his brother before the ill-fated flight.
</P>
<P>
   He said Talat leaves behind three children, from nursery school
to 19 years old, and his wife, Salwa Shami.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is totally collapsed. My father is in worse shape,'' Sa'ad
said, with obvious anxiety about his first trip to the United
States. ``I already feel like I have lost something very essential
that was a part of me. Now, I don't know if I am going to find a
corpse or not, or if I will find half a corpse. I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the family decided not to hold a funeral until Talat's
body is recovered. They will bury him in their rural town of Shebin
El-Koum in the Nile Delta. Before his trip, Sa'ad said, Talat had
joked that if anything happened to him he wished to be ``buried in
the countryside with my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
