<HEADLINE>
BUSH AVOIDS SERIOUS INJURY AS GARBAGE TRAILER FLIPS OVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By THOMAS TERRY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush received a few scrapes and
bruises on Monday when he dodged a garbage truck trailer that
flipped over and scattered debris onto a trail where he was
jogging.
</P>
<P>
   A state trooper riding behind Bush on a bicycle during the
midday jog along Austin's Town Lake was not so lucky. Agent Roscoe
Hughey was hospitalized after being hit with some of the truck's
contents, officials said. He was released after treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard a large boom and saw a garbage truck lose control;
its trailer flipped and sent construction debris flying everywhere.
Next thing we saw was a hand reaching up out of the debris,''
Ernest Bedford, a city inspector who was working nearby, said of
the trooper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great,'' Bush told The Associated Press by telephone
from New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at the end of a 3-mile run when I heard the noise,
looked back, saw it start to tip and my instincts were to dive,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he scraped his right leg and hip when he dived behind a
bridge support. ``I've got a significant strawberry,'' Bush said,
adding that he was pleased that Hughey was not seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Cardenas, a city inspector who witnessed the accident, said
Bush was ``startled'' after the accident but got up quickly as 15
to 20 state troopers converged on the scene within 30 seconds and
surrounded him.
</P>
<P>
   The truck driver was taken from the scene and questioned by
Austin police. A police spokeswoman said the accident was under
investigation. She declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That old boy was going too fast,'' Cardenas said. ``Way too
fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Vinger, a spokesman for the Department of Public Safety,
said the incident shows how ``things come when they're least
expected.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It just highlights that danger comes in many shapes and forms
in protecting the governor,'' Vinger said. ``It was just a freak
accident.''
</P>
<P>
   The accident did not alter Bush's campaign schedule, which
includes a major education address in New Hampshire today,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's third education speech, focusing on school
security, comes as rival Sen. John McCain, R-Arizona, has begun
nipping at his heels in first-test New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   According to a New Research 2000 poll, Bush is leading McCain
39-27. That reflects a drop of 23 points in Bush's lead since
August.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
