<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5696 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CRASH-EGYPTAIR-BOS &LR;      11-01 1479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-EGYPTAIR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCHERS BEGIN RETRIEVAL OF REMAINS, WRECKAGE FROM FLIGHT 990 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS AND THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ As hope of finding survivors evaporated, search
crews collected human remains and a large piece of a doomed
EgyptAir jetliner from its ocean grave Monday, and detected pinging
sounds believed to be from one of the plane's two so-called black
boxes.
</P>
<P>
   High-technology Navy salvage ships steamed for the wreck site
off the coast of Massachusetts in advance of a gathering autumn
storm that was expected to transform Monday's ideal, summer-like
search conditions. And National Transportation Safety Board
chairman James E. Hall warned Monday it would be ``36 to 48 hours''
before the Navy vessels could be positioned for recovery
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators, who were assembling a team up to 1,000 members
strong, made plans for a temporary morgue at Quonset Point. They
also made it clear: finding the cause of the crash early Sunday
morning could take months, if not years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may be looking at a long investigation,'' said Hall, who
flew over the crash site Monday. ``We have a very difficult job of
recovery ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   The first family members arrived in Rhode Island Monday. NTSB
managing director Peter Goelz said an assistance center, staffed by
the NTSB, EgyptAir and the Red Cross, has been set up for them at a
Newport Hotel. The families will receive twice-daily briefings
there.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Lincoln Almond pledged full assistance from the state. ``I
know that all Rhode Island will open its hearts to the victims from
wherever they come,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 family members from the United States and the
Middle East are expected to arrive here during the next two days, a
painful journey to be near those who died and learn all they can
about how it happened.
</P>
<P>
   EgyptAir Flight 990, en route to Cairo from New York's John F.
Kennedy Airport, plunged from the sky, dropping almost 14,000 feet
in just 36 seconds. The 10-year-old jetliner, with at least 217
people on board, had been airborne about 30 minutes and was
cruising south of Nantucket at 33,000 feet when it disappeared from
radar screens.
</P>
<P>
   A clear cause for what sent the Boeing 767-300ER plane into a
fatal dive remained elusive.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, President Clinton and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
warned against early, unfounded speculation that the crash was due
to a terrorist act.
</P>
<P>
   In Oslo, where he was attending Middle East peace talks, Clinton
said he was not aware of terrorist threats that could be linked to
the crash. ``If there have been any such threats, I do not know
about them,'' he said. ``Nothing has been ruled in, nothing has
been ruled out. And I hope no one will draw any conclusions one way
or another until we finish the work.''
</P>
<P>
   And Mubarak, speaking on CNN, said ``Sabotage? I don't think
that, or a terrorist act? I don't think that. But I cannot
foretell. We are waiting until the investigation comes to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Mawn, special agent in charge of the Boston office of the
FBI, said ``there is no indication of criminal activity'' thus far.
Nevertheless, agents assisted in the investigation and in
cataloguing each piece of wreckage as evidence. Mawn urged
Nantucket beachcombers to turn in anything from the plane that
washes ashore.
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard officials somberly announced that an extensive
search of the area 60 miles south of the island had turned up no
signs of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average life expectancy in water temperatures of 58
degress is about five to six hours,'' Coast Guard Rear Admiral
Richard M. Larrabee said. ``We have far exceeded that.''
</P>
<P>
   Larrabee said recovery crews found ``a significant piece of the
aircraft,'' but he would not describe it. The metal piece was
hauled from the water by a crane on a Coast Guard vessel early
Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   He said ``at least one'' signal, presumably from the flight data
recorder or its cockpit voice recorder, was detected Monday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have a pinger signal, at least one that we are working
with right now,'' Larrabee told reporters. ``Our efforts today will
be to try and, as best we can, identify the location of that target
so that when the Navy vessels arrive here we'll have a location for
them to start.''
</P>
<P>
   The 767's ``black boxes'' _ its original flight data recorder
which monitors 55 different aspects of the plane's flight and
performance, and a cockpit voice recorder _ have underwater
locating beacons that can work in depths up to 20,000 feet and
persist for 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   The cockpit recorder can also capture noises in the airplane,
including a straining engine or the sounds of an explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was an explosion on board in the range of the cockpit
area microphone, it would pick it up,'' said a federal investigator
who spoke under the condition of anonymity. ``We would hear the
rise and fall of the blast signature.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the airplane's transponder, a device which sends
information to air-traffic control radar, was working for the first
30 seconds of the plane's nosedive from 33,000 feet, investigators
hope the two recording devices were functional as well.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the plane's systems, the transponder is powered by
electricity generated from the plane's twin engines. Aviation
specialists said it is likely that those on board were well aware
of the plane's rapid descent.
</P>
<P>
   In two recent disasters, TWA Flight 800 and Pan Am Flight 103,
both the black boxes and the transponders stopped when the plane
lost power and therefore could not provide clues about the cause of
the crashes.
</P>
<P>
   John Hansman, a professor of aeronautics at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, said a working transponder indicates that
much of the cabin was intact.
</P>
<P>
   The transponder is located in the nose of the airplane and the
antennas are a third of the way down the fuselage, ``so there was
structural integrity through the front half of the airplane,''
Hansman said.
</P>
<P>
   At least one radar tape shows the plane breaking apart after the
transponder stopped working.
</P>
<P>
   The only fatal crash of a Boeing 767 due to mechanical problems
occurred in Thailand in 1991. A Lauda Air jet crashed there after a
thrust reverser, designed to slow the plane upon landing by
redirecting the engines' exhaust, accidentally deployed as it was
climbing to 24,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA ordered airlines to install locking mechanisms on all US
Boeing 767s. A high-ranking EgyptAir official said the airline did
so on the ill-fated jet in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reviewed the paperwork and found that the modification was
done. We checked that very carefully,'' said Mustafa El Gammal,
general manager of EgyptAir for quality assurance control. He spoke
before boarding a flight in Cairo bound for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know anything yet. We need data. Data is the key to
any understanding,'' he said. ``The (flight data recorder) must be
found, otherwise nobody knows anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides dozens of US tourists, the Pentagon said the EgyptAir
plane carried about 30 Egyptian military officers, many of them
army pilots. They had been flying AH-64 ``Apache'' attack
helicopters during training exercises in the United States. Three
of the officers were brigadier generals.
</P>
<P>
   EgyptAir said the passengers included 106 Americans, including
54 bound for a two-week trip to Egypt and the Nile, 62 Egyptians,
22 Canadians, three Syrians, two Sudanese and one Chilean. The full
passenger list was released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   With more precise radar data from the Federal Aviation
Administration, the Coast Guard narrowed its search to a
40-square-mile patch of ocean 250 feet deep. There, they found
``small portions of the aircraft, primarily seats and cushions, the
remains of people's clothing and paperwork,'' Larrabee said.
</P>
<P>
   Larrabee said he had no information that any of the recovered
items showed burn marks or anything else that would indicate a fire
or explosion. He said while one body has been recovered, ``we have
begun to see evidence of further human remains.''
</P>
<P>
   Collection of those remains, Hall noted, ``has been extremely
limited and we may be looking at a more extended period than in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as officials awaited a National Oceanographic and
Atmospheric Administration vessel with side-scan sonar to begin
mapping the ocean floor in an effort to pinpoint the areas of
debris, Coast Guard boats continued to search the water's surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those of us who do this business for a living, this is
certainly another one of those tragedies that is very difficult for
all of us to deal with,'' Larrabee said. ``Our thoughts and prayers
are with those victims and all of the families as they deal with
this very traumatic event.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 2027EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
