<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0397 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5698 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-AIRCRASH-RECOVER-NYT &LR;      11-01 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRCRASH-RECOVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCHANT MARINE TRAINEES ARE FIRST TO FIND CRASH SITE AND ITS GRIM
DEBRIS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Mass.)   By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At 2:30 a.m. on Sunday, a terse alert crackled from the radio of
the Kings Pointer as the training ship steamed across the Atlantic
south of Cape Cod: a Boeing 767, Egyptair Flight 990, had
apparently gone down south of Nantucket. Ships in the area were
urgently needed to help search for it.
</P>
<P>
   That alert radically transformed what had been the ship's
routine annual fall ``liberty run,'' in which cadets from the
Merchant Marine Academy in Kings Point, N.Y., venture out to sea
for a training mission before heading to Boston for several days of
shore leave.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours after that alert, 17 cadets who were the equivalent
of college upperclassmen found themselves, along with 9 instructors
and crew, circling at dawn through a spreading pool of jet fuel and
grabbing with gloved hands at hundreds of fragments of wreckage,
luggage and human remains that came bobbing to the surface around
them.
</P>
<P>
   By chance, their vessel was the first _ by more than an hour _
at the crash site, and it quickly became clear that what the cadets
and crew hoped would be a rescue mission was something far grimmer.
When the alert first came in, four people were on duty: three
cadets, all under 21, and a recent graduate, Bryan Grube, 24, who
had volunteered to serve as an officer on the training run while on
vacation from his position on an oil tanker on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Grube reflected on the events of the next few hours,
which he said were still tumbling in his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the academy, we receive training in ship's medicine, CPR,
trauma, but I've never seen anything like it,'' he said. ``I'm 24
years old. I'm just out of school a few months now. I've lived a
pretty quiet life. I never thought I'd see something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Grube and other crew members and cadets described in interviews
Monday how the ship stumbled on the crash site 10 miles from the
spot identified by the Coast Guard as the last known location of
the plane.
</P>
<P>
   After the radio alert, they headed east at the 12-mile-an-hour
top speed of the ship, until, at 5:55 a.m., the growing cluster of
cadets and crew members on the bridge noticed a spot ahead where
the sea surface, which was otherwise lightly ruffled, appeared dark
and flat.
</P>
<P>
   They were still about an hour from the theorized crash site,
said the ship's commander, Capt. Robert Allee of the Maritime
Service. When he stepped outside of the bridge cabin, the breeze
hit him, and immediately so did ``the overpowering odor of fuel,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   At first, only a few floating plastic shopping bags floated in
the black surface of the water, said Benjamin Lyons, 20, a
fourth-year cadet from Glyndon, Md. But as the rest of the cadets
were roused by orders from the bridge and the ship came to a stop,
objects large and small slowly rose to the surface in a surreal
upside-down rain of wreckage, belongings and remains, several
members of the crew said.
</P>
<P>
   Allee notified the Coast Guard, but it would be more than an
hour until the first helicopters and rescue ship, the cutter
Monomoy, arrived. In the meantime, they were alone at the crash
site.
</P>
<P>
   He ordered his ship's white 16-foot inflatable rescue boat
lowered into the water to begin collecting material before the wind
carried it away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a training ship _ these are college-age youngsters on
board _ but they all did their duty and performed very
professionally,'' the captain said. ``It started to sink in to them
as the day wore on that they were in the midst of a real tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to accounts provided by the Coast Guard and aviation
officials on Sunday, the cadets and crew said Monday that they
retrieved only partial remains, not a body.
</P>
<P>
   Grube said many objects could be seen floating suspended beneath
the surface, adding that at one point the ship's depth sounder,
which had been steadily reading depths of around 180 feet, suddenly
jumped to 5 feet. ``You have to wonder if that was a piece of the
aircraft that was down there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons did his stint in the little boat, filling plastic bags and
buckets with pieces of beige foam, with airline tickets, passports,
toys and many, many shoes _ large and small. Nothing appeared
burned, the cadets said.
</P>
<P>
   But every object spoke of the immensity of the tragedy when an
airliner goes down, he said. ``You would see little teddy bears,
plane tickets, wallets, all these remnants of what was,'' Lyons
said.
</P>
<P>
   He and the others continued to work through the morning, but a
breeze began to disperse the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Eight hours after the cadets first encountered the crash site,
at 2 p.m. on Sunday afternoon, the Coast Guard released the Kings
Pointer from the search for victims and wreckage, transferring its
lode of recovered material to other ships.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons said he was proud to think that the cadets probably saved
many hours of flying time by rescue craft searching for the crash
site. But he was still shaken, and would be for days to come, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Grube said: ``You expect a nice quiet trip up to Boston, but you
never know. One of the rules out here is to keep a sharp lookout at
all times. It's actually required by law. You just never know what
you'll ever see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
