<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Henderson health a key for Hawks
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Forward Alan Henderson has one goal in mind as the
Atlanta Hawks prepare for the new season, starting tonight against
the Washington Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal for this season is simple,'' Henderson said. ``I want
to play in all 82 games.''
</P>
<P>
   Good health is a prerequisite for Henderson, who has missed a
number of games with injury during his four-year career. Henderson
played 79 games as a rookie in 1996-97, but played only 30 games
the following season and 69 games in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson played 38 games in the lockout-shortened 1999 season
but missed the final week of the regular season and the playoffs
after he was struck in the eye by Cleveland's Cedric Henderson (no
relation). Alan Henderson has battled weak ankles, now made
stronger by exercise; assorted muscle pulls; and a prolonged bout
with pancreatitis.
</P>
<P>
   Emotionally, Henderson says, he has emerged stronger for his
battles. Financially, he is established, as he starts the second of
seven seasons in a $40 million deal. Physically, Henderson says, he
has never been better.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks bigger, maybe 6-9,'' center Dikembe Mutombo said. ``I
think he's grown to about 6-9.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe 6-10, Deek. I've been 6-9.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, Al, you were never 6-9.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no argument that Henderson has played bigger than
6-foot-9, especially in 1997-98 when he averaged 14.3 points,
averaged 6.4 rebounds, shot 48.5 percent and was named the most
improved player in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the first time he had been honored. At Indiana, he was
Big 10 player of the year. For his work as a high school player in
Indianapolis,he recently was named one of the 50 best players in
Indiana history.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Henderson would like to participate in more than a modicum
of NBA team success. Of 13 roster players, only he and Mutombo have
played more than two seasons in Atlanta. Better than others, they
know the onus of consistent playoff failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the mission, to get to the Finals,'' he said. ``But
saying that, it bothers me that people point to the players last
year and talk about what a disaster it was. Sure, it was bad
getting swept by the Knicks (in round 2), but we were out of
players. I was out. (LaPhonso Ellis) was out. Mookie (Blaylock) and
Steve (Smith) were worn out. It's not like the team quit.''
</P>
<P>
   On more than one occasion, Henderson has stated his belief that
trading Blaylock and Smith was an over-reaction. But that doesn't
mean he can't accept his new teammates _ all seven of them _ or
that he has lost faith in his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got a chance to be pretty good, real good, in
fact,'' he said. ``There's a lot of talent in this locker room. All
we got to do is get on the ball, kick it out to the one, two or
three man (guards and small forward) and get it pushing. We'll come
behind them and fill the lane. (Last year,) we had to work hard
just to get a shot. But if we get a few easy baskets, that can make
a big difference. You get 15, 20 fast-break points in a game, come
the fourth quarter you'll be a lot fresher.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Lenny Wilkens has so many options, Henderson said, that
the Hawks constantly can present a different look. ``Just look at
how many guys we can have playing (the) three (position). Four
different guys. That's incredible. We've got a lineup to fit every
situation. A lot of talent. It's gonna be good.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, to complete the picture, Henderson says, he needs only good
health.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
