<HEADER>
A5704 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-ARREST-NYT &LR;      11-01 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ARREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN BUSINESSMAN UNDER INVESTIGATION IS DETAINED IN HUNGARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ One of Russia's most prominent businessmen has been
detained in Hungary at the request of Russian law enforcement
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials said Monday that Anatoly Bykov, an aluminum
factory chief from Siberia, had been apprehended recently by
Hungary's border police. The Russian authorities have opened a
criminal investigation of Bykov's finances and are seeking his
extradition.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has a dismal track record in arresting and convicting
corrupt officials and businessmen. But stung by accusations that
Russians have moved billions of dollars through foreign bank
accounts to avoid taxes and, perhaps, launder money, the Kremlin is
making an effort to demonstrate that it is serious about fighting
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   And it has no loyalty to Bykov. As chairman of an aluminum
factory in the Siberian city of Krasnoyarsk, Bykov has often been
in the public eye.
</P>
<P>
   He emerged as a political rival to Aleksandr I. Lebed, the
former general who is now the governor of the vast Krasnoyarsk
region. More recently, the Russian press has reported instances
that suggest that Bykov has laundered money and has organized
contract killings _ allegations that Bykov has strenuously denied.
</P>
<P>
   Bykov has been living abroad, apparently in an effort to avoid
prosecution at home. He has given television interviews from
undisclosed locations proclaiming his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Bykov sought to run for parliament on the ticket
headed by Vladimir V. Zhirinovsky, the ultranationalist politician.
Members of parliament enjoy immunity from prosecution, and Bykov's
recent interest in politics was widely seen as a bid to protect
himself from the police.
</P>
<P>
   Bykov denied that he had purchased a place on Zhirinovsky's
slate and insisted that he had developed a new-found love of
politics. In a television interview last month, he asserted that he
had been planning to enter politics before he was accused of
financial irregularities and murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can only improve the situation by our concrete actions,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Central Election Commission put an end to Bykov's
candidacy. It barred him from running on the grounds that he had
failed to disclose all of his property holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on his supporters in Krasnoyarsk, Bykov was trying to
contest that ruling from his foreign hideaway. But things went from
bad to worse when he was detained at the request of Interpol and
the Russian interior ministry. The Russian news agency Itar-Tass
reported Bykov was detained by Hungarian border guards on Monday at
the Hungarian-Yugoslav border.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 2035EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
