<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5707 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BRITAIN-EURO-NYT &LR;      11-01 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-EURO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS SUPPORT DECLINES IN BRITAIN FOR ADOPTION OF THE EURO  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In a remarkable decline in support for adopting the
European single currency, British businesses are evenly split on
whether to abandon the pound sterling, a survey showed Monday _ a
sharp contrast to strongly favorable sentiment about the euro a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The findings of the survey, conducted by the Mori polling group
and commissioned by The Financial Times, coincided with other signs
of boardroom disaffection not just with the single currency but
with what respondents called the failure of Prime Minister Tony
Blair's Labor government to promote the advantages of joining the
euro bloc.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, the euro _ and Britain's broader attitude toward
the rest of the European Union _ has come to form the central
political division in this country, the last major European economy
to resist joining the 11-nation euro zone.
</P>
<P>
   But the survey results also suggested that the euro's decline
against major currencies including the dollar, the yen and the
pound since its creation in January has mirrored the drop in
British corporate support. That augurs badly for Blair, who had
viewed the nation's executives and managers as a pool of support
for adoption of the euro.
</P>
<P>
   The survey among 1,000 businesses of varying sizes found that 52
percent of those surveyed were in favor of abandoning the pound in
favor of the euro soon after the next national election which will
take place, at the latest, in 2002. That figure contrasted with 63
percent in a similar survey a year ago, which had been widely
regarded as a sign of a broad business support.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major setback for the government,'' said Nick
Herbert, the head of Business for Sterling, saying the results
``give the lie to the pro-euro lobby's claim that business favors
the euro.''
</P>
<P>
   The release of the survey results was timed to coincide with the
annual conference in Birmingham this week of the Confederation of
British Industry, the main employers' group, which castigated
Blair's government for its caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``British business would like to see the government leading the
debate on the pros of the euro,'' the group's president, Clive
Thompson, said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The employers' group maintains that British participation in the
euro zone of nations has ``the potential to deliver significant
benefits to the U.K. economy enabling British companies to
participate fully in a more complete and competitive single
market.''
</P>
<P>
   The government's circumspect approach partly reflects political
concern _ that a majority of British voters, encouraged by some
mass-circulation newspapers, do not want to lose the pound. The
authorities have said they will decide about euro membership only
after a referendum following the next election and only if the
currency meets a series of economic criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said the government's attitude had ``delayed serious
debate longer than necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Brown, the chancellor of the Exchequer, rejected that
argument in a radio interview Monday, saying the government had
consistently advocated ``a strategy of prepare-and-then-decide''
and would insist that the European currency met British economic
criteria as a condition of entry. ``I believe we should be
applauded for our consistency,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the survey suggested that British business generally looked
askance at such assurances. While 80 percent of those responding
said the government was right to insist on economic criteria, 76
percent thought political considerations would dictate the final
decision.
</P>
<P>
   At present, the British economy seems well out of sync with
Continental Europe, but in a way that the government praises as a
sign of Britain's flexibility and vibrancy. Unemployment around 5
percent, for example, is roughly half the Continental European
average.
</P>
<P>
   But reflecting British concerns about inflationary pressure,
benchmark interest rates of 5.5 percent are more than twice the
euro zone's 2.5 percent. At the same time, Britain has taken issue
with Continental European proposals to standardize some taxes
across the European Union in a way the British fear would damage
London's status as the leading European financial center.
</P>
<P>
   Also worrisome to the government is the way the opposition
Conservative Party has been able to mine a seam of British popular
mistrust of the euro, making it a centerpiece of political debate.
</P>
<P>
   William Hague, the Conservative leader, who is stridently
opposed to the government's euro policies, extended his assault on
European economic practices Monday by assailing efforts to
harmonize taxes throughout the 15-nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the Confederation of British Industry conference, he
compared highly taxed Continental European economies to ``great
stumbling mammals'' destined for extinction, while the ``lean,
low-tax nation state'' would survive and prosper. He extended the
Darwinian metaphor, labeling the Labor Party a ``woolly mammoth''
of big government and over-regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The comparison backfired somewhat when Matthew Taylor, a
spokesman for the pro-European Liberal Democrats, reminded Hague
that ``the woolly mammoth died out because it became isolated and
frozen out in the cold _ which is exactly where William Hague's
Britain would be left in Europe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
