<HEADER>
A5708 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-BLASS-FASHION-NYT &LR;      11-01 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLASS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL SALE OF BLASS LEAD TO A NEW IMAGE?  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Bill Blass wardrobe for Madonna? Suits for Sting?
</P>
<P>
   Those were a couple of the marquee names bandied about as
potential Blass customers by Charles A. Koppelman, a partner in CAK
Universal Credit, which last week worked out a deal to finance the
purchase of Bill Blass Ltd. through bonds.
</P>
<P>
   In the transaction, which an executive who worked on the deal
said is expected to bring Blass, 77, more than $50 million, the new
owners will be Haresh T. Tharani, the chairman of the Resource
Club, a Blass licensee, and Michael Groveman, who's been with the
Blass company 10 years and is chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why shouldn't Sting be someone who wears Bill Blass?''
Koppelman said last Friday. It may be wishful thinking, but given
Koppelman's ties to the entertainment industry (he is the former
chairman of EMI-Capitol Records) and the fact that the Blass label
has lost ground to companies that court celebrities, it may not be
such an impossible dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bill Blass is going to be more valuable in 10 years
than it is now,'' Koppelman said, adding that while Blass' name may
hold more meaning with an older generation, he has a strong brand
identity that can be exploited. ``It's Coca-Cola. It's Bill
Blass.''
</P>
<P>
   Koppelman suggested there may be room for mass-marketing the
Blass style. ``For example, we could make a great case for going
back into the archives and bringing forward some of Bill Blass'
early couture designs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such decisions will be up to the company's new owners. Groveman
said: ``There are a lot of places to grow this brand. It's been
undermarketed for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing that will matter to stores and Blass fans is who will
design the label.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Blass jokingly said that he'll ``soon be found on
Fiji.'' Aside from the fact that Blass probably wouldn't care for
the food or the climate there (are there antiques on Fiji?), he may
find that key retailers, like Saks and Neiman Marcus, will be eager
to see that he has some hand in the design. Groveman said that
Blass does about $1 million in retail sales each season with Saks
in New York. Another possibility is that the owners will look for a
high-profile designer to give the brand heat.
</P>
<P>
   Though none of the principals will speculate about the future of
the collection line, where suits retail for about $4,000, it seems
unlikely it will be stopped, given the company's niche in that
market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 2038EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
