A5709 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     11-01 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOR. PAGE B10  
  
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
 STAR QUALITY 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oracle's  &UR; Larry Ellison &LR;  is at war with officials in San Jose, &LR; 
because airport rules make it illegal to fly his $38.7 million
private jet there late at night, when nearby homeowners might fancy
sleeping. ``San Jose has no right to tell me when I can land my
airplane,'' he says. ``It's like saying people who weigh more than
200 pounds can't go into a store after 6 p.m.''
</P>
<P>
   On the opposite coast,  &UR; Bob Saks &LR; , 58, whose family founded Saks
Fifth Avenue and who requires that his Manhattan dry-cleaner
de-pill, de-lint, iron flat and fold in tissue his cashmere socks,
told a New York Times reporter, ``I was born, my dear, to be a
connoisseur. Everything must be perfect. It doesn't matter if it's
steak or socks.''
</P>
<P>
   Also pursuing perfection is  &UR; Suzanne Somers &LR; , who told Time
magazine _ in a quote mined by &UR; Firat Yener &LR;  _ about her Somersizing
diet: ``The reason I used to be bloated was a gastric war between
the protein and carbohydrates. Now I never have gas, I can proudly
say. It's a great thing not to have gas.''
</P>
<P>
   And finally,  &UR; Monica Lewinsky  &LR; attended the Friday opening of an
exhibition of photos by  &UR; Timothy Greenfield Sanders &LR;  at the
 &UR; Mary Boone &LR;  gallery in Manhattan.  &UR; Baird Jones  &LR; overheard her
telling Time editor  &UR; Walter Isaacson  &LR; about ``a fantastically
interesting book being written on what happened to me in the last
year, including the book tour. I feel so gagged because I'm not
writing another book, and I'm not having a direct input on the new
one.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CREATIVE IMPULSE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Mark Bittner &LR;  and his cherished and nourished wild parrots of
Telegraph Hill are the subject of a documentary in the works by
producer  &UR; Judy Irving &LR;  of the nonprofit Independent Documentary
Group.
</P>
<P>
   IDG has a Schwab One account, and its September statement
informed Irving that it had been credited with an apparently
erroneous $98,661. Irving wrote to &UR; Charles Schwab &LR;  proposing that
it be left there, ``as a thank you for our honesty and integrity''
and earmarked as a contribution to the wild parrots movie. No
response yet. The money disappeared from the account before she
received an answer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Berkeley video artist  &UR; Stephen Beck &LR;  was in New York last
week, where his ``Cycles'' is part of the Whitney Museum show ``The
American Century.'' That's the good news. The bad news was that his
Visa card was pickpocketed, and $9,000 was charged in a day ``at
vendors ranging from the Gap to Sally's Sunshine Spa.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck's philosophical question: Is he entitled to frequent-flier
miles for charges placed on a stolen card?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The familiar ``Morning Edition'' voice of NPR's  &UR; Carl &LR; 
 &UR; Kassel &LR;  is heard on the answering-machine message of  &UR; Andrew &LR; 
 &UR; Sullivan &LR; , chairman of the commuter group Rescue Muni. Sullivan won
the greeting as a prize on the NPR quiz show ``Wait Wait Don't Tell
Me.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Physician  &UR; Rudolf Noble  &LR; of San Francisco has sent word of the
publication of his paper, ``Uptake of calcium and magnesium by
human scalp hair from waters of different geographic locations,''
in the journal the Science of the Total Environment. Noble has been
able to prove that when washing one's hair while traveling, ``with
some waters hair turns out limp and loose while with others it
turns out stiff and full.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Fortune-teller  &UR; John Boe &LR;  is predicting the rise of feng shui
experts called in for consultations on arranging computer desktops.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Roger Friedman &LR;  of Foxnews.com reports that the  &UR; Nicole
Brown &LR; 
 &UR; Simpson  &LR; family charity for abused women and children, &LR;  took in
$113,000 last year but donated only $6,500.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Queen Noor &LR; , 47-year-old widow of  &UR; King Hussein  &LR; of Jordan,
is moving back to the United States, reports the New York Post.
Noor has a house near Washington, and she is looking for a place in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Barbra Streisand &LR; 's gardenia commode was in Harper's, not
Harper's Bazaar.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty sure that if you pulled his head back, a Pez would
pop right out.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Rosie O'Donnell's description of New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, quoted in US News &AMP; World Report.
</P>
</TEXT>
