<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5718 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-PREVIEW-     11-01 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS CAUTIOUSLY OPTIMISTIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Imagine Cinderella with 240 glorious days to kill
before retreating to the bucket and sponge.
</P>
<P>
   Did you get there?
</P>
<P>
   OK ... with that imagery reconciled, let's introduce your
Y2Clippers, who lace up their glass Nikes tonight for the inaugural
regular season ballgame at Staples Center. Before we sabotage the
optimism, we must report that expectations finally are higher than
the curb.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers finished 5-3 in the recently completed Pumpkin
League, their best exhibition record since 1993, when 5-3 became
the preamble to a 27-55 season.
</P>
<P>
   But the prevailing Clippers may have enough talent and sass to
push their October run beyond the rank of aberration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made strides and I think we're ready,'' said power
forward Maurice Taylor, the incumbent go-to Clipper and the lead
variable in our insistence on icing down the glee over what should
be an entertaining season. ``It should be pretty exciting ... at
least for this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Why so cryptic?
</P>
<P>
   Well, 240 days from now, Taylor and new teammate Derek Anderson
will be storming into free agency. Matching their salary requests
against owner Donald T. Sterling's history for hoop investments
(the highest-paid Clipper in Sterling history was Stojko Vrankovic
at $4 million and change per season), it's safe to imagine ``Mo''
and ``DA'' taking what should be over 30 percent of the Clipper
offense to other teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as returning goes, that's over,'' Taylor said Saturday,
his 23rd birthday, and the day before the NBA deadline to sign his
vigorously requested, six-year, $70.9 million extension. ``I'm
playing my last year here.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, a 6-foot-5 guard who thus far seems like a bonanza
dividend in the sign-and-trade evacuation of Lamond Murray, has
less verbal leverage. Injuries limited his bargaining power after
two seasons in Cleveland, so he's deferring all contract talk to
his actions - until the contract-expiration emancipation of June
30, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   So now that we've chased off the enthusiasm, let's attempt to
drag it back.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, Rodney Rogers, Lorenzen Wright, Pooh Richardson and
Darrick Martin are not here.
</P>
<P>
   Lamar Odom is.
</P>
<P>
   While the dearly departed, aforementioned Clippers are decent
players, as well as fine fellows, they were afflicted with what
Taylor refers to as ``Clipper Syndrome.'' Their collective itch to
leave made Coach Chris Ford's first season in L.A. as warm and
fuzzy as a custody scrum.
</P>
<P>
   His second season could be defined by Odom, the 6-9 rookie from
Rhode Island, whose beguiling maneuvers and competitive spirit
should make these Clips superior to last season's 9-41 crew.
</P>
<P>
   In cahoots with Taylor, Anderson, and second-year center Michael
Olowokandi, Odom may be the front man in a promising quartet. They
will be abetted by the swashbuckling efforts of small forward
Tyrone Nesby, last season's CBA plum, who needs to fit his new
contract, refined perimeter touch and fortified ego into the
sixth-man role.
</P>
<P>
   Strongman Brian Skinner (6-9, 255 pounds) has emerged as a force
in the dawn of his second season, and appears capable of surpassing
Wright's contributions in low-post combat off the bench. He'll do
this without his predecessor's strategic pouting or superstar
delusions.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi has a bit more polish this season, to go with
healthier knees and a softer shooting touch (he made 71 percent of
his free-throw attempts in the exhibition spin after making just 48
percent last season).
</P>
<P>
   Veteran newcomer Eric Murdock and Troy Hudson, last year's
second CBA discovery, will swap time at point guard when Odom isn't
sliding into that spot.
</P>
<P>
   Could be about time to let the good times roll, right?
</P>
<P>
   Well, even though Odom turns 20 Saturday, he is wise enough to
recognize the burden of proof.
</P>
<P>
   ``Respect is something you earn,'' he said. ``We haven't done a
thing to switch that around.''
</P>
<P>
   No, but it should be fun watching Odom and the Clippers try.
</P>
<P>
   Odom played four positions during the exhibition trial, leading
the team in scoring (18 points per game) and rebounding (8) while
ranking third among Clippers in assists and blocked shots. He also
finished third among NBA employees in the Pumpkin League for
minutes played.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs the experience,'' said Ford, who maintains a posture
of cautious optimism when assessing the draft's fourth overall
pick. ``The entire season is going to be a learning experience for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Another interesting lesson could be taught when the Clippers'
almost maudlin declarations of team harmony are challenged by
adversity ... such as the typical rash of playing-time
confrontations. Or the twisted karma of shot distribution. Or the
reality of getting socked in the mouth by an elite team. Remember,
the Clippers' exhibition joy included an 0-2 finish against
contestants from last season's NBA playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't splinter at the first sign of failure,'' said Ford,
who spent October attempting to school the Clippers in the finer
points of up-tempo offense and aggressive, trapping defense.
``Twenty-eight days go by pretty quickly. We'll see what happens
when we start playing for real.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I feel good about this team. I like their work ethic. I
like the general tone.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the pricey acoustics at Staples, it all may sound pretty
good.
</P>
<P>
   At least until the clock strikes midnight in 240 days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
