<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-U.S.-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. BACKS EUROPEAN PLAN TO SEND HEATING OIL TO YUGOSLAVIA  
(EXCLUSIVE)
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-WINTER) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration, worried that it could
be blamed if Yugoslavs freeze to death in the winter, has decided
to support a European-run pilot program to send millions of dollars
worth of heating oil to Yugoslavia, senior administration officials
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   If the pilot program goes well, Washington will consider helping
to expand the oil deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be supportive of any proposal that meets
humanitarian requirements and can assist the opposition, so long as
we are not bolstering the regime,'' a spokesman for the State
Department, James Rubin, said. He added that the United States
already provided tens of millions of dollars to international
groups toward that end.
</P>
<P>
   At first the administration had opposed the European proposal,
fearing that President Slobodan Milosevic would divert the oil to
his business cronies or to the Yugoslav military. The
administration also feared that by alleviating the hardships of a
cold winter, the oil might diminish public protests about his
government.
</P>
<P>
   But American officials said they had decided to back the
European plan for humanitarian reasons, and with an understanding
that the oil would go to two cities in southeastern Serbia that are
governed by opponents of Milosevic's Socialist Party.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union agreed to supply $5 million in heating oil
and to pay to transport it to the cities, Nis and Pirot, beginning
this month.
</P>
<P>
   If the project is seen as a success, the officials said, the
United States will consider supporting _ and helping to pay for _
an expansion to other Yugoslav cities. Yugoslavia is faced with
devastating energy shortages after the destruction of petroleum
refineries during NATO's air war over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that the United States remains
firmly opposed to other proposals offered by European nations to
end the economic and diplomatic isolation of Yugoslavia, in
particular one to allow international airlines to resume flights to
Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
   A delegation of high-ranking Yugoslav opposition leaders now
visiting the United States has been pressing for American support
for the heating oil shipments. The opposition leaders are also
trying to display their solidarity to Washington and to portray
Milosevic as a wounded leader.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the group, which is expected to meet with Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright and White House officials later this
week, say the oil is needed to prevent a human disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without it, people will freeze to death,'' said Zoran
Zivkovic, the mayor of Nis and member of the opposition delegation.
``If the heating oil is not provided, it will be a great victory
for Milosevic, because it will just reinforce the position that the
West hates all Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   The delegation leader, Dragoslav Avramovic, a former central
bank governor and a candidate for prime minister in any
transitional government in Yugoslavia, said that Milosevic was far
weaker politically than was often portrayed in the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economic situation of Milosevic is desperate,'' he said.
``Prices are increasing 10 percent a week, which is 50 percent a
month, and it is difficult to see how the regime will survive. He
is now the obstacle to the recovery of Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   Zoran Djindjic, president of the Democratic Party, said he was
convinced that Milosevic would soon be ousted from office, despite
his willingness in recent weeks to use violence to put down
anti-government street demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic is history,'' he said, drawing comparisons with the
final days of President Nicolae Ceausescu of Romania and President
Suharto of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dictator must be strong or he doesn't exist,'' he said.
``Ceausescu was very strong until two days before his execution.
Suharto was strong a month before he was gone. Milosevic now is
like a fireman with five different fires, and with very little
water.''
</P>
<P>
   The delegation is also trying during its visit here to put an
end to the perception in Washington that the Yugoslav opposition is
fragmented, and that it is incapable of offering a serious
alternative to Milosevic and his loyalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The genuine opposition is not divided,'' said Vladan Batic,
coordinator of the Alliance for Change, an opposition group that
has organized many of the recent demonstrations that have drawn
tens of thousands of anti-government protesters to the streets of
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Djindjic, a philosopher who was imprisoned in the 1980s for
trying to establish an independent student organization, said it no
longer mattered if there were policy or personality disputes among
the opposition political parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parties are not important now,'' he said. ``The people on
the streets are now the opposition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
