<SLUG> BC-HAMP-NH-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BUSH BRACING FOR TOUGH FIGHT IN NEW HAMPSHIRE AGAINST McCAIN 
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush's advisers, acknowledging they
were caught off guard by Sen. John McCain's recent rise in the
polls in New Hampshire, say they are bracing for a hard-fought
contest in the state that holds the first presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is still the indisputable front-runner for the Republican
nomination, and his advisers do not seem especially panicky about
McCain. Even so, Bush's advisers said that McCain's inroads
underscored a new reality for the governor of Texas: He can no
longer expect a blissful glide to the general election. They said
that McCain could complicate Bush's strategy for wrapping up the
nomination quickly and, if McCain wins in New Hampshire, he could
threaten the entire Bush juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly didn't feel it was going to narrow this quickly,''
said Sen. Judd Gregg of New Hampshire, Bush's most influential
supporter in the state. ``But as John gets more visibility, some of
his warts are going to show.''
</P>
<P>
   Another person close to the Bush operation, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity, said, ``I don't want to say there was a
classic Texas arrogance, but their overall M.O. was not to directly
engage and stay above the fray. That now becomes an untenable
strategy because you're in a new world.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bush has embarked on an accelerated schedule in New
Hampshire. Last week, he opened his first television advertising
drive there (as did McCain), and on Monday he arrived in the state
for two days on the stump.
</P>
<P>
   His first stop will be Dixville Notch, a tiny enclave in the
north that incorporated years ago solely so it could cast the first
ballots in presidential campaigns. Bush will be the last major
candidate this year to pay homage to the voters in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Bush will deliver his third major education address
in New Hampshire. His first two speeches were in New York and Los
Angeles, with audiences that had a special connection to the
content of the speeches. The choice of New Hampshire appeared more
geared to Bush's need to shower more attention on the state.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers also said they hoped to pick up support in New
Hampshire by tailoring their television commercials to the local
audience. The campaign has begun running a commercial on the
governor's tax-cutting policies, which his advisers said was
popular in focus groups of New Hampshire voters. The advisers said
a Bush commercial about ``armies of compassion'' did not test as
well in the state, but was still popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has multiple messages,'' said Fred Steeper, Bush's
pollster. ``And what the research does is test which of those
multiple messages seem more relevant to the New Hampshire voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, after spurning two debates in New Hampshire _ and finding
himself under harsh attack by his opponents and local editorials _
Bush has agreed to take part in a forum on Dec. 2. Only weeks ago,
his campaign had said the governor would not debate until next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers say they are not overly concerned with McCain
because the senator is concentrating his limited resources on only
two states: New Hampshire and South Carolina. They also insist that
they had always intended to intensify their campaign schedule in
New Hampshire. Yet they also said they were moving more swiftly in
the state, not merely in reaction to McCain but to other realities
of this campaign.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the state has moved up the date of its primary to
Feb. 1, which put more pressure on Bush to get his campaign in gear
faster. In addition, no one expected that so many major candidates
would withdraw from the race so early, including Elizabeth Dole,
former Vice President Dan Quayle and Pat Buchanan, who won the New
Hampshire primary in 1996 and is now seeking the Reform Party
nomination. McCain has picked up support from the narrowed field as
has Bush.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is in a particularly enviable position because this state
has a history of rewarding mavericks, and of punishing front
runners. The senator has made this state a central focus of his
campaign. He has virtually ignored Iowa, where he is far less
popular, and has stumped in New Hampshire far more than Bush.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM STARTS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through some scares up there with President Bush,''
Steeper said. ``New Hampshire can always have upsets because it's a
small state and people react to retail campaigning. I take the
polls seriously: they probably reflect the state of the current
campaigns: There's a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Judd said people should not underestimate the harm from The
Union Leader of Manchester, whose conservative editorials have
attacked Bush for ignoring the state, among other things. ``The
Union Leader every day is pounding Bush,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In numerous interviews on the ground in New Hampshire in the
past several days, voters and strategists warned that Bush needs
more of a presence in the state. McCain has been attracting
exuberant, and large, crowds on his trips to the state.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very possible that McCain could outwork Bush and pull an
upset that would send shivers through the Republican
establishment,'' said Dave Carney, a veteran Republican strategist
here who is not affiliated with any campaign. ``He's got the
personality that would definitely appeal to New Hampshire voters.
But George Bush is an excellent retail politician, he can talk to
people in a warm and friendly way.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Bush could also run into trouble from Steve Forbes, the wealthy
publisher who is well organized in New Hampshire and is expected to
spend huge sums on television advertisements against Bush _
commercials that could presumably help McCain as well. Thus far,
Forbes lags both Bush and McCain in polls. But if he gains ground
in the state, he could also eat into Bush's support from
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM STARTS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain, Bush and Forbes right now are clearly in the first
tier,'' said Steve Duprey, the state Republican chairman. ``McCain
has the advantage in that he is focusing on far fewer states. And
Bush is truly campaigning nationally. They are very different
strategies suited to different budgets.'' He said that while the
Bush campaign was ``taking some hits'' for not appearing more
frequently in the state, the campaign ``was not unmindful of
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Dennehy, McCain's New England political director, said of
the Bush campaign, ``All they care about is spending and staying on
message. I think the people of New Hampshire are smart enough to
understand the difference between that and straight talk.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Several recent polls in New Hampshire show that while Bush has
not lost significant support, McCain has gained as other contenders
dropped out. Two polls, for example, found that he still trails
Bush, but the gap has narrowed from 35 points to 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone survey taken by Research 2000, Oct. 20-21, Bush
was the choice of 39 percent of Republican voters, McCain was the
favorite of 27 percent. The poll was conducted statewide with 413
Republican primary voters. A poll in August found that Bush had 45
percent; McCain, 10 percent. Both polls have a margin of sampling
error of plus or minus 5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Another poll, by Quinnipiac College, also found McCain within
striking distance of Bush, 41 percent to 28 percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mr. McCain also has more widespread appeal across party lines
than Bush. Though a sizeable number of New Hampshire voters still
have no opinion of McCain, polls show that majority of people who
have an opinion, like him. That is true not only for both
Republicans and Democrats, but also the crucial independent voters
who can vote in either the Republican or Democratic primary in New
Hampshire. Among those who have an opinion of Bush, polls show
Republicans like him, Democrats do not like him and independents
are evenly divided.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush needs to start coming to New Hampshire a little more
because New Hampshire does strange things in the primary,'' said
Jim Sullivan, a Republican who is chairman of the town budget
committee in Hooksett, N.H. ``I don't think we like to be told who
we have to vote for. We need to see the candidate. That's what
makes New Hampshire unique.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican, Reed Paige Clarke III, a retired consular
affairs officer from Londonderry, N.H., warned Bush not to take New
Hampshire for granted. New Hampshire voters, she said, were ``more
offended by his not showing up here than by his being the heir
apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke, who is 70, said that besides Bush, McCain was the most
viable contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talks rather straight and right from the hip,'' he said.
``He doesn't bother walking around the corner when he can go right
straight through.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren Mason of Meredith, N.H., a professor of business at
Plymouth State College who has followed the state's primaries for
years, said McCain was gaining steam because he was ``an antidote
to Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe how many Democrats I've heard say they're
going to vote for McCain,'' Mason said. ``It's definitely a Clinton
reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that former President George Bush was not wildly
popular in the state _ particularly when he reneged on his
no-new-taxes pledge _ and that that could hurt his son. ``The old
man always took a beating in this state,'' Mason said. ``In this
state, with the Bush family, they've not been liberal enough for
the liberals and not conservative enough for the conservatives.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that McCain was so aggressive in New Hampshire
``because he realizes if he doesn't do well here, he's done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
