<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-RESISTANT-TB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FIGHT AGAINST TUBERCULOSIS, EXPERTS LOOK FOR PRIVATE HELP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   International public health officials and scientists are trying
to enlist leading American philanthropists in plans to create a
$500 million to $600 million trust fund next spring to help stop
the spread of tuberculosis. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Dr. Gro Harlem Brundtland, executive director of the World
Health Organization, said in a recent interview that there is now a
consensus that a main obstacle to stopping the spread of TB is a
lack of drugs to treat the 8 million people who contract the
disease each year. She called the $100 million now being spent to
fight TB ``in no way sufficient'' to help poor countries stem the
disease that killed 2 million people last year.
</P>
<P>
   Brundtland said the director of organization's ``Stop TB''
initiative believes that with a fund of $500 million to $600
million, ``the problem of access to drugs would be solvable.''
</P>
<P>
   The health organization began the initiative _ a partnership
with leading scientific labs and nonprofit anti-TB groups in
Europe, Asia and the United States _ after a White House meeting
last year that reflected growing alarm about the disease, the
world's leading infectious cause of death among adults.
</P>
<P>
   Brundtland was in New York partly to attend a meeting last
Thursday on the rapid spread of TB strains resistant to various
drugs _ strains that have been detected in more than 100 countries.
The meeting was sponsored by the Open Society Institute, a
foundation financed by George Soros, who has committed more than
$15 million to tuberculosis-related programs.
</P>
<P>
   Soros' foundation also financed a report released last week that
documented the rapid spread of drug-resistant TB to more than 100
countries and called for a new treatment strategy.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Friday, Soros said governments must do more
to fight the disease, as must ``newer, younger foundations with
greater resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Soros nor Brundtland would identify which foundations
they had in mind, but several participants at last week's meeting
said they clearly included the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation,
which has assets exceeding $17 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, Gates, chairman of the Microsoft Corp., and his
wife committed $750 million over five years to speed the delivery
of vaccines against four childhood diseases to developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Foege, a physician who advises the Gates foundation
on medical giving, said that apart from already contributing $25
million to help fund research on TB vaccines, the foundation has
made no decision about what else it might do. But he said last
week's meeting highlighted the need both for more money and more
thought about how best to find it.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David L. Heymann, who heads the organization's division of
communicable diseases, said the partners in the TB initiatve would
work toward beginning a trust fund campaign or other programs by
next March, when public health and finance officials plan to gather
in Amsterdam to discuss the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   There is disagreement about how best to spend money to treat
tuberculosis. Some experts fear that expanding treatment for
patients with the drug-resistant strains _ which requires them to
take up to seven expensive drugs daily for 18 to 24 months _ would
divert resources from care for those who have strains that are not
drug-resistant. Only 20 percent of the latter group receive
adequate treatment.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Geneva Monday, Heymann said there
was a consensus at the New York meeting that action is needed to
contain the epidemic of drug-resistant strains, but not at the
expense of the other patients. Foege said the New York meeting
``moved the dialogue along so that people can stop fighting one
another and start fighting the disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln Chen, executive vice president of the Rockefeller
Foundation, cautioned that while the meeting stimulated greater
concern about TB's spread, some experts were still not convinced
that ``buying drugs through a trust fund is necessarily the best
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Major questions about how best to allocate money remained, he
said, such as what experts in those poorer countries with high TB
rates want and whether their public health systems can support the
distribution of more drugs to patients and can monitor them to
insure the drugs are taken.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Clinton administration official said the meeting also
emphasized that, despite substantial donor fatigue, ``TB is now on
our back door step. If we don't pay now, we'll pay later, and in
far greater amounts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
