<SLUG> BC-CURLS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIRLS WITH CURLS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 By JAIMEE ROSE 
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  We're really hurting for Elaine.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since the Seinfeld sign-off, we've been desperate to hear
``get out!,'' dying to see her dance (well, maybe not), aching for
the laughs that only a show supposedly about nothing can bring.
</P>
<P>
   We say supposedly because we've made a discovery. Seinfeld was
not a show about nothing. Seinfeld was a show about hair.
</P>
<P>
   George was all about baldness, Jer ry's 'do was the paramount of
neatness, Kramer's crop was fright ening, and Elaine was the girl.
</P>
<P>
   And she had curls.
</P>
<P>
   She was one in a million, if you think about it. Prime-time
curls have mostly been reserved for redheads (Lucy, Carol Burnett,
Melissa on thirtysomething), or for crazy women (Lucy, Carol
Burnett, Melissa on thirtysomething). Long, sexy ma nes of curls
were not the providence of Melrose, did not live in the 90210 zip
code, were not around when Peggy Lipton was mod.
</P>
<P>
   That Girl had smooth hair even in New York; Ginger had it even
on her island. Farrah had serious hair, but none of the Angels had
to deal with the frizzies. For that matter, neither did Laurie
Partridge, Samantha Ste phens, Marcia Brady or those little girls
who lived on the prairie. When Larry dreamed of Jeannie, naturally
she had long, straight blond hair.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, it seems like prime-time got a perm. We have
noticed _ and we've counted _ at least a dozen actresses with long
curls in the spotlight now.
</P>
<P>
   There's ER's Julianna Margulies. She's old hair, just like her
show. There's Providence's Melina Kanak aredes. She's new. There's
the blond locks of Sarah Jessica Parker on Sex and the City and the
brown locks of Debra Messing (Grace on Will &AMP; Grace). They've been
around.
</P>
<P>
   New this year, there' s Amy Bren neman on Judging Amy, Jean
Louisa Kelly on Cold Feet, and Rebecca Gayheart of Noxema fame, who
is sometimes curly, sometimes straight on Wasteland.
</P>
<P>
   We're up to seven. There's more: Suddenly Susan's Kathi Griffin,
Moesha's Brandy, Ally McBeal's Lisa Nicole Carson. Of course there
is Felicity's Keri Russell, who chopped her long locks (horror!)
this season and nearly was disqualified from our curl club. And
maybe the award for the true Elaine tribute goes to Ally McBeal's
curly-haired secretary, played by Jane Krakowski and named,
honorably, Elaine.
</P>
<P>
   And it gets better. The world's highest-paid actress, Ms. Julia
Rob erts, has curly hair. One of the world's most lusted-after men,
Tom Cruise, is married to Nicole Kidman and her curls. The
highest-grossing film of all time, Titanic, starred Kate Winslet in
her pre-Raphaelite glory.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, there's pop princess Jen nifer Lopez, movie star and
L'Oreal spokeslady Andie MacDowell, Chris tian pop artist Amy
Grant, even acclaimed actress Minnie Driver.
</P>
<P>
   Plus Ally McBeal's Judge Whipper, played by Dyan Cannon, which
makes three for Ally, so far.
</P>
<P>
   We've come a long way from the days when Jan's real problem with
Marcia, Marcia, Marcia, was the bitter hair envy shared by so many
real-life girls.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Hoyt, a 27-year-old curly-haired stylist at Salon
Phoenix, was one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried everything,'' she said. ``I would wash it and lay on
my pillow with it wet to try to make it flat, or I would take a
curling iron and try to make the curl soft.''
</P>
<P>
   It was hard having curls when the world was in pursuit of
Marcia. If nothing else, girls with curls always had to go home
after a trip to the salon for hair sculpture before the bathroom
mirror. Those straight-haired stlyists just never understand. Hoyt
would spend up to 90 minutes wrestling with her hair each day.
</P>
<P>
   `'I wanted it straight. I wanted her hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, she's more inclined to go for the Julianna, thanks to
loads of curl-control product on the market and her time at beauty
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in high school,'' she says, ``I didn't know how to
control it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, she's overwhelmed by options. On the shelves at beauty
supply shop Ulta 3, a national refuge for product junkies, there
are 13 curl control products in one section alone. Frizz-Ease. Bed
Head. Ultra-control gel for brunettes. Light control mousse for
greying blondes. You get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the products for curly girls who still,
despite the coolness of Elaine and company, want straight hair. And
that's OK. Elaine even went straight sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   For this, there is straightening balm. Glosser. Wax sticks. Bed
Head Con trol Freak Frizz Control &AMP; Straight ener Serum.
</P>
<P>
   The label of Bed Head, by the way, reads like a poem to any
curly girl gone straight: ``A Control Freak's final step - styling.
Restrain your unruly, freakin' hair without a strug gle. Become
sleek and smooth in seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of money to be made in curl control.
</P>
<P>
   Hoyt knows it; she does it. She still has clients who come in
for chemical hair straightening. These are the ladies who used to
roll their hair around juice cans, trying to flatten it out. These
are the girls who did backbends over the ironing board while their
mothers starched and pressed their hair into Marcia obliv ion.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, says Hoyt, people are leaving their curls
be these days (sometimes, herself in cluded).
</P>
<P>
   There are websites, with product testimonials (``gel, girls,
skip the mousse''), dedicated to living with curly locks. Actress
Rita Wilson is quoted in this month's In Style magazine on the
glories of being able to live with curls. Ally McBeal's new fall
season 'do makes the most of Calista Flockhart's natural wave.
(Which makes four for that show.)
</P>
<P>
   So maybe this is the new status hair. Maybe long curls will be
to the late '90s what Jennifer Aniston's layered Rachel 'do was to
the early '90s. (Aniston, by the way, straightens her naturally
curly hair.)
</P>
<P>
   Part of it may be that whole '90s ``simplify your life'' thing.
Part of it may be the products.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe we just really miss Elaine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
