r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-Q&AMP;A-LADN     11-01 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-Q&AMP;A-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Change coaches, change players, change buildings,
change the linens _ it really doesn't matter what the Lakers do
each offseason, the basic result will be the same: higher
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   They're considered an annual disappointment for not winning the
NBA championship, and every acquisition _ Shaquille O'Neal, Dennis
Rodman, Glen Rice _ raises hopes, fairly or not.
</P>
<P>
   Now they've done it again. The Lakers barely touched the
free-agent pool but still inspired championship predictions with a
single hire _ coach Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   A realistic expectation? Isn't that always the question?
</P>
<P>
   Here, an attempt at the answers in a brief conversation with
ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Q. So the Lakers got the best coach $30 million could buy. Are
they really any better than they were in that horrid playoff
collapse?
</P>
<P>
   A. On the premise that it's never too early to burst bubbles,
the simple answer is no. Kobe Bryant, O'Neal and Rice make the
Lakers an automatic playoff team, but the supporting cast is
largely unimproved.
</P>
<P>
   Power forward remains a glaring weakness, and the combination of
Robert Horry and A.C. Green won't make anyone forget the previous
combination of Horry and J.R. Reid.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, if Horry and Rick Fox don't rediscover their shooting
touch soon, the Lakers' bench will again be woefully lacking in
offensive punch.
</P>
<P>
   Q. So hiring a coach with six championship rings means nothing?
</P>
<P>
   A. Actually, it means the Lakers will pay attention to an
authority figure, which is an instant improvement. And Jackson will
in fact make this team better than the sum of its parts, but it
will take time.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, it took Michael Jordan and Co. months to get
comfortable in Jackson's offensive system, and by Jordan's account,
two years to truly thrive in it. Initially, the Lakers will
struggle no matter how much talent they have. But Jackson's
emphasis on the fundamentals will make O'Neal and Bryant better
team players. They respect his knowledge and are buying into his
team-first philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   The egalitarian triangle offense also will allow role players
like Derek Fisher and Ron Harper to make consistent contributions.
But it won't solve their need for rebounding and defense in the
frontcourt.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Hate to ask, but does that mean they're going to sign the
nutty guy with the tattoos and bad hair again?
</P>
<P>
   A. Don't expect it, largely because the front office is
absolutely opposed to the idea, and even owner Jerry Buss has
admitted misgivings about taking the plunge the first time. For
now, the Lakers will search the league for a saner alternative. But
if the Lakers don't have a solid starter by late January, brace
yourself, because Jackson won't stand pat.
</P>
<P>
   Q. So who are these ``saner'' alternatives?
</P>
<P>
   A. That depends on your definition. Another Jackson favorite,
the offbeat Bison Dele (formerly known as Brian Williams) has
retired from the Detroit Pistons, and is living in Santa Monica,
just close enough for Jackson to indirectly lobby him to return.
But getting Dele would require a trade.
</P>
<P>
   A less-complicated alternative would be to get Orlando veteran
Armon Gilliam. O'Neal is lobbying to acquire old friend Horace
Grant from Seattle (unlikely) or Antonio Davis from Toronto (more
likely).
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is Derek Fisher good enough to start for a championship
contender?
</P>
<P>
   A. Did anyone think Avery Johnson was before last season? Fisher
is an apt comparison, a younger version of the Spurs' point guard.
He's underrated and works his tail off, hustles on defense and
improves each season. He's also grasped Jackson's system well. Yes,
he's capable. In fact, he was the Lakers' most reliable shooter
throughout the exhibition season.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Glen Rice didn't seem too happy last season. Is he here to
stay?
</P>
<P>
   A. That may be up to him. He's a free agent next summer and
wants a huge new contract. If he can adapt to Jackson's offense, he
might earn a deal from the Lakers. But he's struggled so far, and
if he's still struggling in January, expect his name to appear in a
dozen trade rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Veteran teams like the Jazz, Pacers and Bulls have had the
edge in the playoffs in recent years. Aren't the Lakers too young
and immature?
</P>
<P>
   A. Two seasons ago, perhaps, when Bryant was still a teen-ager
and the core included O'Neal, Nick Van Exel and Eddie Jones. But
this is a much different, much older team. Their average age is now
28, and five Lakers have logged at least 10 years in the league.
Bryant's even legal drinking age now.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Speaking of those veterans, do John Salley, Ron Harper, Green
and Brian Shaw have anything left?
</P>
<P>
   A. In Harper's case, absolutely. His experience with Jackson's
Bulls will be invaluable, and he can start at either guard
position, provided his knees hold up. Salley and Green can add some
wisdom and, they hope, a few rebounds. But don't expect more than
10 to 15 minutes a game from Salley (who retired three years ago)
or more than 30 from Harper and Green. Shaw played just one game
last season but has performed well in his brief time with the
team. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
