u e BC-TV-GUMBEL-COX     11-01 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GUMBEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gumbel on `Today': Competing with his old pals `doesn't hurt'
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ As part of an 11-city tour to promote
The Early Show, Bryant Gumbel and Jane Clayson recently visited CBS
affiliate WPEC-Channel 12. Gumbel addressed, among other things,
his pompous image, competing with Today co-anchor Matt Lauer and
why he came back to morning TV.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You have a reputation for being arrogant. Does that bother
you?
</P>
<P>
   A: Because everyone writes about it, people think it's a
reality, but it's not a reality. I've been in this business almost
30 years, and life isn't always going to go perfectly, and not
everyone is going to write wonderful things. The only things I can
control are my own performance on the air and the way I conduct
myself with my co-workers and people I report to.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How much of your reputation has to do with your color?
</P>
<P>
   A: Nothing that happens in America is absent of color. So I
think it's naive to believe that judgments about me are absent of
that. I'm not baying at the moon, and I'm not crying about it; it's
just a reality.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Isn't it ironic that you're back on morning TV?
</P>
<P>
   A: This is a chance to build something from the ground up. This
is a chance to reverse a legacy of failure. . . . when I started
(on ``Today'') in 1982, there were concerns other correspondents
wouldn't talk to me, or that guests wouldn't come on the show, that
people would leave in droves and affiliates wouldn't take it. To
come from that point to this one is very gratifying.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happened with ``Public Eye''?
</P>
<P>
   A: I wasn't strong enough to force it to be what I wanted it to
be. I was too easily dissuaded of things as the new kid at the
corporation. I tried to be the good company guy . . . and it just
didn't work out. It was not a show I was very proud of, and, yes,
it was my fault. But having said all of that, the show was very
much numerically in line with what first-year newsmagazines do. It
was also very much in line with what new shows on CBS do. It wasn't
the Ishtar of television.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What did you learn from the experience?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's good to be hardheaded when you believe things should be
done a certain way. No man is an island. You can steal a star
quarterback, but if you don't surround him with a good running
game, wide receivers, an offense line, a defense, a coaching staff
and a scouting staff, he ain't going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you chafe at the fact that networks feel the need to build
amusement park-like studios to get people to watch?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah, I do. But you know what the reality is? If we were
going to start this program tomorrow, and we didn't have one of
those studios, you guys would write that CBS isn't making the
commitment. These studios are environments in which you think you
have the best chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will it be tough competing with your good buddy Matt (Lauer)?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's fine. It's not just my good buddy, Matt. It's my good
buddy (''Today'' executive producer) Jeff Zucker and my good buddy
Al Roker. Competition is fine. It doesn't hurt. In many instances,
it makes you better. We all said we're never going to say anything
personal about the other one, and I never will. They're very dear
friends of mine.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Thompson writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
