<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5729 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-TV-NEWSWARS-COX     11-01 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NEWSWARS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Growth of early morning audience raises stakes in ratings race
 &HT;    (EDS: Runs with TV-GUMBEL.)
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We greet them every morning with our first cup of coffee. Katie
and Matt on ``Today''. Charles and Diane on ``Good Morning
America''. We welcome them into our homes like long-lost friends.
But don't let the good cheer, sleek studios and waving tourists
fool you. Beneath the sunny surface and friendly chatter, there's a
high-stakes war for early morning TV dominance.
</P>
<P>
   At risk: millions of advertising dollars and precious morning
television viewers. The competition heats up Monday when ``The
Early Show,'' CBS' morning news program with former ``Today''
co-host Bryant Gumbel and onetime ABC News correspondent Jane
Clayson, elbows its way to the morning news breakfast buffet.
</P>
<P>
   The heated booking wars have already begun. Thorny permit
problems kept ``The Early Show'' from getting Mariah Carey to
perform live in Central Park for Monday's debut. She'll appear on
rival ``Today'' instead.
</P>
<P>
   That's nothing new. ``CBS This Morning'' has always lagged
dismally behind ``Today'' and GMA. During the week of Sept. 20, for
instance, ``Today'' averaged 5.6 million viewers, GMA 4.3 million
and ``CBS This Morning'' a paltry 2.7 million. ``CBS This Morning''
has lived in the basement primarily because the penny-pinching
network never devoted enough resources to it.
</P>
<P>
   But that's changed. CBS spent $30 million to build a
state-of-the-art indoor/outdoor studio on tony Fifth Avenue, it
tapped former ``Today'' executive producer Steve Friedman to
produce ``The Early Show'' and lured Gumbel back to the early
morning rat race.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest investment that CBS has ever made in this
time period,'' says Andrew Heyward, CBS News president. ``And it's
a terrific time to be making a big investment given the morning is
a hotly contested, lively arena with plenty of room for us to do
better than we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Early morning is the fastest growing segment on network
television. According to Nielsen Media Research, over the last five
years, the number of homes using television from 7 a.m. to 9 a.m.
has increased 11 percent. Growth from 5 a.m. to 7 a.m. has been
even greater _ up 18 percent over the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   The networks also make a lot of money in the morning. From 1995
to 1998, revenues for the shows grew 37 percent to a combined $450
million. And for the first half of 1999, ``Today'''s revenues
increased 26 percent to $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   Says GMA co-host Charles Gibson: ``It's not all altruism that
has brought the increased attention to morning television. This has
become a significant revenue source.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Gumbel: ``It's not likely someone is going to get up at 6
a.m. to watch a movie on HBO. There's isn't a ballgame on ESPN at 7
a.m. It's one of the few places where a network remains
preeminent.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks in large part to CNN, the Internet and the newsmagazine
explosion, viewers now expect to get a steady diet of hard news,
national news, global information, fashion tips and celebrity
gossip before they go to work or school. Since people are also
waking up earlier, the networks have been pressed to devote more
money to their morning shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of instant news anywhere, anytime has made morning
more valuable to the viewing public,'' says Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today'' upped the ante six years ago when it moved to a
glass-walled, street-level studio in Rockefeller Center. Six months
later, ``Today'' climbed into first place and hasn't looked back.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the once top-rated GMA was struggling. Long-time
anchors Joan Lunden and Gibson left. GMA sank even further after
Lisa McRee and Kevin Newman were hired. Then Gibson returned with
ABC powerhouse Diane Sawyer. Since then, GMA has seen its total
number of viewers increase 29 percent. The show's splashy Times
Square studio is also moving GMA up in the ratings, with viewership
rising from 3.8 million to 4.5 million in a month.
</P>
<P>
   But the question remains: How long will Gibson and Sawyer play
good solider and stick with GMA?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an open-ended thing,'' is all Gibson will say.
</P>
<P>
   Says Shelley Ross, GMA's executive producer: ``Charlie and Diane
aren't here under duress, pain and punishment. I guarantee, there
will be no radical changes. This is our show. This is who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   But what will ``The Early Show'' be?
</P>
<P>
   Expect to see a traditional morning show format packaged into a
glossy, high-tech studio package. Hard news segments combined with
feature pieces, celebrity interviews and consumer-oriented tips
will be the norm. Former MTV VJ Martha Quinn and best-selling
author Lisa Birnbach (''The Official Preppy Handbook'') will offer
parenting tips on a weekly segment, ``Yikes! I've Grown Up.''
Former GMA correspondent Laurie Hibberd will look at what's hot in
pop culture in her twice-a-month report called ``The Hib List.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to try and reinvent the wheel,'' says Heyward,
``but we're going to try to add some spokes of our own.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest spoke, of course, is Gumbel. Considered to be one of
the best live interviewers on television, Gumbel helped make
``Today'' a morning show giant during his 15 years as co-host. But
the often smug anchor has many detractors who don't like his cocky
image. And there's a lot of pressure riding on those $5
million-a-year shoulders. The 51-year-old Gumbel, however, says he
doesn't feel it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure how to gauge pressure,'' he said . ``There's
virtually pressure in everything you do, but most of it is
self-inflicted. The external stuff about what's going to happen
with the numbers, that's going to happen, period. We really can't
do anything about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry insiders expect ``The Early Show'' will enjoy
respectable numbers during the first week as the curiosity factor
remains high. After that, it's anyone's guess how successful the
program will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a restaurant,'' says Thomas DeCabia, an executive
vice president and general manager at Schulman/Advanswers, a New
York media buying company. ``A new one opens up and everyone wants
to try it out. But will they go back to being a loyal patron?
That's how these shows are.''
</P>
<P>
   The wild card in this whole war, however, is Clayson. Although
she has covered such high-profile stories as Bob Dole's 1996
presidential campaign and O.J. Simpson's civil trial, she's a
relative unknown. Her chemistry with Gumbel is key.
</P>
<P>
   Heyward says CBS looked at more than 300 tapes of potential
co-hosts and met with more than 100 hopefuls before hiring Clayson.
She also had ``a zillion and one'' conversations with Gumbel over
the phone. The network even dubbed the search Operation Glass
Slipper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget Operation Glass Slipper,'' says Clayson, a 32-year-old
devout Mormon, ``this Cinderella is going to need some running
shoes. And I've got those.''
</P>
<P>
   And CBS has a snazzy studio across the street from Central Park.
Friedman says the network had no choice but to build its own lavish
set. ``It's the price of admission to get into morning
television,'' he says. ``If somebody's in Times Square and
somebody's at Rockefeller Center, you can't do a competitive
morning show on 11th Avenue.''
</P>
<P>
   The real race to watch will be between long-running GMA and the
upstart ``Early Show''. Friedman believes his show can catch GMA
whenever Sawyer steps down.
</P>
<P>
   GMA's Shelley Ross says she's not concerned _ yet. ``I feel
confident we will thrive and there is room for all of us,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Let the war begin.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Thompson writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
