<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5732 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-PUMPKIN-RID-COX     11-01 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUMPKIN-RID-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pumpkins get the cannonball test
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Finding folks willing to creatively
dispatch of unwanted pumpkins in the name of good, messy fun is
more difficult than one might think.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, firing one from a cannon like they do at the
World Punkin' Chuckin' Championships in Delaware was out of the
question.
</P>
<P>
   We called 10 paving companies from Boca Raton to Fort Pierce
before one in Delray Beach agreed to steamroll our gourd. (And then
Hurricane Irene nixed that one.)
</P>
<P>
   We asked the Palm Beach County sheriff's bomb squad to blow one
up. They were amused, but cited the ``copycat'' issue.
</P>
<P>
   We begged the fire safety class at Indian River Community
College to ignite and extinguish one. It could qualify as a
training exercise for newly graduated firefighters, we bargained.
No dice. ``I wouldn't know how to light one on fire,'' an
instructor said. (Accelerant anyone?)
</P>
<P>
   We even badgered a tree-trimming business into letting us chuck
a punkin' into their tree shredder so we could hear it go SPLORK!
They weren't interested.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, we abandoned some really bad ideas. Like the
friend-of-a-friend who offered to put it on the tip of a Nike
surface-to-air missile he had purchased on Ebay's Web site _ and
had delivered via UPS. (Apparently, one can own a missile for
``display'' purposes.) We nixed the Nike, reasoning that flattening
Riviera Beach just to vaporize oversized fruit was certainly
crossing the line.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, we found some souls just off their gourd enough to take
the pumpkin challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Punkin' punchin'
</P>
<P>
   Tool of destruction: Right foot, fist of champion kickboxer
Steve Shepherd.
</P>
<P>
   Result: The 10-pound gourd was no match for the five-time world
champion junior-middleweight kickboxer. About four punches was all
it took to cave in the face of the challenger. Shepherd finished
the job with heel-first stabs with his foot. One nit: Shepherd, who
is retired from the sport at age 49 and now runs his own kickboxing
gym on Military Trail in West Palm Beach, asked that the pumpkin's
face first be weakened with knife punctures. ``Otherwise, I'll
break my ankle.''
</P>
<P>
   Smash rating: 5.5 out of 10. While not easily defeated, a
pumpkin does make a satisfying thud when struck with the human
foot.
</P>
<P>
   Mess rating: 4 out of 10. A pumpkin emits a nasty,
Frito-corn-chip-like odor when kicked apart.
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``This went so well, I may come out of retirement,''
Shepherd said.
</P>
<P>
   Punkin' shootin'
</P>
<P>
   Tool of destruction: Double-barrel .687 Baretta shotgun fired by
skeet shooting champion Kent Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Result: With optimistic visions of evaporating gourds, we
pitched bagel-sized pumpkins 20 feet into the air for Taylor to
blast at Palm Beach Trap and Skeet in Wellington. (Don't try this
at home, kids. Taylor's a professional.) We soon discovered pumpkin
skin has a rawhide quality. Even with Taylor's expert aim, the
shotgun spray barely penetrated, giving the pumpkins only an
acne-like abrasion. To remedy this, Taylor took to lobbing his own
pumpkins Bronco Billy-style at closer range while cradling the gun
and then firing double blasts. The result: Fourth of July in
October!
</P>
<P>
   Smash rating: 7.5 out of 10. The pumpkins took a bullet better
than John Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   Mess rating: 10 out of 10. Palm Beach Trap and Skeet wisely
anticipated a Mardi Gras-sized mess and put us at the farthest end
of the facility. While not nearly as goopy as a large pumpkin, the
mini-versions obliterated nicely when blasted up close. An
estimated 3 billion militant fire ants residing at the course won't
have to dine on a bare leg for at least three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``Without a doubt, this is the weirdest thing I've ever
shot,'' Taylor said, scratching his salt-and-pepper beard. But did
it qualify as skeet or trap shooting? ``It didn't really qualify as
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Punkin' truckin'
</P>
<P>
   Tool of destruction: The Brahma, the world's largest
street-legal pickup truck. The customized International Harvester
hauler runs close to 32 feet long, seats six comfortably and is
purchased at the Riviera Beach manufacturing garage by everyone
from cattlemen to Arab sheiks. Built by Jere Dixon, a 44-year-old
owner of a medical software company, the truck could haul 6,000
10-pound pumpkins without a struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Result: Punkin' pancake. Placing one 15-pound gourd in front of
the dual rear tires, Dixon peeled out. Pumpkin guts flew 30 feet
away. And the tires left a perfect souvenir treadmark on the orange
skin.
</P>
<P>
   Smash rating: 10 out of 10
</P>
<P>
   Mess rating: 9 out of 10. The devastation was total, but
surprisingly tidy. Except for some stray seeds and innards, the
pumpkin folded like a card table.
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``That was so cool,'' Dixon said. ``Want me to do it
again?''
</P>
<P>
   Punkin' forkin'
</P>
<P>
   Tool of destruction: A mini-forklift used. We first squashed a
5-pound pumpkin with the forks. Then we tried to run over the
remainder with the vehicle's 6-inch-tall wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Result: While not explosive, the results were impressive.
Pumpkins do not take well to the blunt trauma of a shop forklift.
Especially after a dozen downward whacks. The forklift did excel in
running over the pumpkin _ sort of. Its wheels were too small to
hurdle the heap, but they spun on the skin and melted the adjacent
asphalt to create an orange cloud of acrid smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Smash rating: 7 out of 10. The pumpkin's stem acted in its own
defense, becoming a preventive keystone.
</P>
<P>
   Mess rating: 10 out of 10. Where there's smoke, there's doomed
pumpkin.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Houck writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
