<HEADLINE>
BOEING UNION SAYS WORKER STRESS NOT FACTOR IN 767 CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The International Association of Machinists Monday
defended Boeing union members work in building two 767-300
airplanes that rolled off the same assembly line and later crashed,
saying overtime stress and a contract dispute didn't create
problems in the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Early Sunday morning, an EgyptAir jetliner plunged into the
Atlantic Ocean, apparently killing the 217 people on board. The
EgyptAir 767 rolled off Boeing's Everett assembly line in 1989,
right before a Lauda Air 767-300, which crashed eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing crafted the twin-engine airplanes in the weeks just
before a labor dispute with Machinists, who were also complaining
about stress tied to overtime. The two airplanes that crashed were
among the last produced before Machinists struck on Oct. 4, 1989,
for 48 days.
</P>
<P>
   Union leader Bill Johnson said the labor situation simply wasn't
a factor in the quality of the aircraft. Even if there was a flaw
in the workmanship of either airplane, Boeing has enough
safeguards, such as multiple inspections, to catch any fatal flaws
in its airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many checks...things can't slip through,''
Johnson, who is president of the International Association of
Machinists District Lodge 751, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is on a fishing trip right now,'' he said of the
search for clues as to the cause of the EgyptAir crash.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson pointed out the Lauda Air crash was tied to a design
flaw _ a thrust reverser fired during the flight sending the 767
into a fatal spiral and killing all 223 people aboard, according to
investigators _ not a manufacturing flaw.
</P>
<P>
   Some local financial experts echoed Johnson's assertion that
line workers weren't likely to shoulder the blame for the EgyptAir
accident. The airplane had been flying for a decade, according to
Bill Whitlow, a portfolio manager at Safeco Asset Management Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's a coincidence,'' Whitlow said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators, led by the National Transportation Safety
Board and the Federal Bureau of Investigation, have just begun
collecting the remains of the airplane from the waters off
Nantucket. The federal answers to the questions surrounding the
EgyptAir crash may be months or years away.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the government has yet to render its final
verdict on what caused the fatal crash of 1996 TWA Flight 800 over
Long Island. That verdict is expected next year.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also stressed that Machinists take great pride in their
work, even when they're fighting with their employer over wages and
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   He argued that everyone is simply searching for answers in the
wake of the tragedy. But, he warned they shouldn't seize on the
fact that two 767s that were produced consecutively crashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A plane went down and no one knows why it went down,'' Johnson
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
