<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5740 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-TV-GOODY-AZR &LR;      11-01 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EARLY SHOW' WITH GUMBEL: MORE OF THE SAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
Whither Mariah?
<TEXT>
<P>
   That was the big controversy going into the debut of CBS' The
Early Show on Nov. 1, a fact that tells you all you need to know
about the state of network morning ``news'' shows.
</P>
<P>
   Mariah Carey had been scheduled to belt out a couple of hits for
The Early Show, but when CBS couldn't come through with the
necessary permits in time for an outdoor concert, she took her
platinum pipes to NBC's Today show.
</P>
<P>
   CBS rebounded with a big star in a slightly different
demographic gal axy: Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   This blockbuster replaced last week's Big Morning Show Story, in
which Early Show host Bryant Gumbel did or didn't dis his former
Today co-host, Katie Couric. That's fitting. Because all of these
shows, ABC's Good Morning America included, are a little about
what's said and a lot about who's saying it.
</P>
<P>
   You don't pick a morning show based on the stories and entertain
ment they offer. You pick Matt Lauer and Katie over Diane Sawyer
and Charles Gibson, or vice versa. (Actually, in Phoenix, you pick
Good Morning Arizona most of the time.)
</P>
<P>
   And now Gumbel and co-host Jane Clayson are thrown into the
fray, giving CBS its strongest morning-show lineup since people
lived in log cabins and watched television on coal-powered sets, or
so it seems. Can they compete?
</P>
<P>
   Does it matter? is the better ques tion. Does The Early Show
offer anything different, a compelling rea son to change your
morning routine?
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, no. The EgyptAir crash forced Gumbel and
Clayson into a hard-news format at the start _ they couldn't very
well ignore so gigantic a tragedy, so it's impossible to know how
the debut would have kicked off on any other day.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, its competitors were covering the same story. And
like its competitors, The Early Show offers a set window for
gawkers to peer into, a jolly weatherman, an outdoor set for the
well-scrubbed talent to min gle with the unwashed, that kind of
thing.
</P>
<P>
   But what The Early Show gives us that the other shows don't is
Gum bel. Love him or hate him _ actually, does anyone love him? _
the guy is a fascinating television presence.
</P>
<P>
   His interview with Clinton in the Oval Office, for instance,
found Gumbel in fine form. It's like riding a bicycle for this guy
_ time passes, he hops aboard and he's right back in the race,
peddling furiously.
</P>
<P>
   Just like old times: Gumbel looked over Clinton's head, at the
ceiling or past the president while asking such questions as how
Clinton would summarize, in one sentence, his presidential legacy.
He let the presi dent weasel out of a few questions _ neither
Clinton's answer nor Gum bel's follow-up to the previous query
mentioned the words ``impeach ment'' or ``Monica,'' for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel did ask about the Mideast peace conference Clinton was to
attend, as well as how Clinton reacted to reports that Al Gore and
Clinton's wife, Hillary, might be harmed in their election
campaigns if the president campaigned for them.
</P>
<P>
   But the way he ended the interview was what made this classic
Bryant. He told the president that he under stood he would be
signing papers to finalize buying a new house in New York next
week. Did the president know where the nearest golf course was? No.
Gumbel informed him. And did the president know who was a member?
Uh, Bryant? Ding, ding, ding. Kudos to the chief executive in the
gray suit.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange was Gumbel in a nutshell _ the solid information
about buying the house nearly bur ied amid the smarmy, self-serving
boast, all in one segment. The man is fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   Clayson isn't, particularly. It's ri diculous to talk about
their ``chem istry'' after only one show. Likewise, it would be
unfair to describe news reader Julie Chen as anything other than
competent.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's not too early to say the whole gang could use a
little work on their man-on-the-street skills, the morning-show
burlesque routine that Couric and Lauer have developed into low
art. Despite a partial crowd, which included Clayson's parents and
a few guys from Bryant's alma mater, Bates College in Maine, nei
ther seemed comfortable; Gumbel, in particular, looked petrified
that someone might actually touch him.
</P>
<P>
   I'll bet no one in that crowd belongs to his country club.
</P>
<P>
   Oops _ had to take a quick timeout to catch Couric's interview
with Stephen King. A quick flip back and I've missed . . . nothing.
Which is the point of how these shows are struc tured, after all.
If you have to go fish a brown sock out of the dryer, you don't
want to miss anything.
</P>
<P>
   No matter which morning show you choose, believe me, you won't. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
