<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5747 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS &LR;      11-01 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The Cowboys have said all season that they don't know how good they
are. They should be more sure now.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Through two months they have proved they're good enough to beat
the second-worst defense in the league _ but few others.
</P>
<P>
   They are good enough to beat a former Super Bowl contender
without its quarterback. They can beat a one-shot wonder whose
quarterback is rated dead last in the league. And they can beat
that pitiful defense _ twice.
</P>
<P>
   The wins over the Washington Redskins were impressive. The
victories against Atlanta and Arizona don't exactly make the
Cowboys formidable.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cowboys haven't beaten anyone else. They failed against
the Philadelphia Eagles. They failed against the New York Giants.
And most recently, they failed against the Colts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just wasn't our day,'' safety Darren Woodson said after
Sunday's loss in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The victory over the Redskins a week earlier was a face-saver
for Dallas. But the Cowboys have lost three of their last four and
now enter a stretch that includes Minnesota, Green Bay, Miami and
New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not play well,'' Cowboys defensive tackle Chad Hennings
said. ``That's a shot at the players, coaches, everybody across the
board. We didn't make the adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be a theme of late. The Cowboys led in each of the
losses. In each instance, the offense came to life only after the
opponent began having success. And in each instance, it was too
late.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles, Giants and Colts outscored the Cowboys in the second
half 51-14.
</P>
<P>
   Also, how about their non-division road record? The Cowboys have
lost eight consecutive times on the road when playing outside the
division. They haven't beaten a non-NFC East team away from Texas
Stadium since a victory in Pittsburgh on Aug. 31, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bothersome,'' Woodson said. ``I don't see why we
shouldn't be able to win some of these games.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's because the Cowboys really aren't very good. On
cruise control they swept their division last year, but it was the
worst division in football. And while it's more competitive this
season, it's open to debate whether it's because of the East's
improvement or the parity that seems to have hit the league.
</P>
<P>
   And there have been excuses each time:
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, the Cowboys lost Michael Irvin to a neck injury
early and the offense never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, they were playing one of the top defenses in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   And in Indianapolis, well, Peyton Manning, Marvin Harrison and
Edgerrin James didn't play like the league's future superstars.
They played like current ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give them credit,'' Woodson said. ``They are a young,
explosive offense. In the second half, they made plays and we
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the offense _ which managed only two touchdowns in two
weeks _ that took the heat after losses to the Eagles and Giants.
The defense can hang its head this week.
</P>
<P>
   James, whom the Colts took instead of Ricky Williams with their
first-round pick, managed one of the most productive days of any
running back in franchise history, a record that dates to the
Baltimore days.
</P>
<P>
   James rushed for 113 yards and caught passes for another 92. No
Colts back has achieved 100 in both facets in a single game.
</P>
<P>
   ``To come back (from a 17-3 deficit) the way we did says a lot
about our team,'' Manning said.
</P>
<P>
   It may say more about the Cowboys. It wasn't long ago that the
Cowboys were the ones bubbling over with confidence even when
trailing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People talk about the mystique the Dallas Cowboys have, and
they've earned that because they're the team of the '90s,'' Manning
said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, by the time the playoffs roll around, the '90s will
be over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
