<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-MILITARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
28 EGYPTIAN MILITARY OFFICERS AMONG FLIGHT 990 VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY AND CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At least 28 Egyptian military officers, including
three brigadier generals, were among the 217 people aboard EgyptAir
Flight 990, according to US officials.
</P>
<P>
   The US Embassy in Cairo described the Egyptian officers as
``military trainers.'' Other Clinton administration officials,
speaking on the condition of anonymity, said most were pilots who
had just completed training in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A foreign diplomat in Washington, asking not to be identified,
said the Egyptians were almost all ``young officers receiving
training. They were going home on that flight. They had just
completed normal training. It is something that is going on all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   In Cairo, US Consul General Roger Pierce described the training
in similar terms. ``It's very common. Hundreds of Egyptian military
are trained in the United States every year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   US officials were careful to avoid any suggestion that the
presence of such a large Egyptian military contigent was connected
in any way to the EgyptAir crash.
</P>
<P>
   At the Cairo airport, several grieving families described many
of the presumed dead officers as communications workers in the
military.
</P>
<P>
   One officer aboard the flight was identified as Khalid Ibrahim
Saad, 45, who was from a small town about 50 miles outside Cairo.
Saad had been undergoing military training in Los Angeles, his
family said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He joined out of love for his country. He died for the state
of Egypt, said his brother, Mustafa Saad, 42.
</P>
<P>
   Nine pilots and engineers also had been in Alabama for two weeks
flying and examining AH-64 ``Apache'' attack helicopters and other
equipment purchased by Egypt from the United States, a US official
said, speaking on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt is one of the largest purchasers of military hardware,
buying billions of dollars worth of equipment over the years from
American companies. It also has one of the most extensive joint
training programs with he United States.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Defense Secretary William S. Cohen stopped
in Egypt as part of a swing through the Middle East to watch a
joint US-Egyptian war games exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Cohen called his Egyptian counterpart, Defense Minister
Field Marshal Mohammed Hussein Tantawi, to express his condolenses
over the loss of life of the Egyptian officers, the US official
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Egyptian Embassy in Washington declined to comment about the
reports.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Donnelly reported from Washington, Sennott from Cairo.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 2130EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
