<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-ANALYSIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS POSITION-BY-POSITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
GUARDS: Depth and consistency in the backcourt were understated
weaknesses for the Lakers last season. Neither should be a problem
now. Once Kobe Bryant recovers from a broken hand, he will pair
with either Derek Fisher or Ron Harper to form a solid guard
tandem. In the triangle offense, any two-man combination from among
that trio can play together, and each brings something to the
table: Bryant's athleticism, Harper's triangle experience, Fisher's
all-out hustle and an improving outside shot. All three are good
defenders, and Bryant and Fisher have been among the better
triangle students.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Veteran Brian Shaw will provide some added depth as the first or
second guard off the bench, and rookie Devean George impressed in
the exhibition season. Second-year players Tyronn Lue and Sam
Jacobson might be squeezed out of the picture. &QL; 
FORWARDS: The early returns are discouraging for the Lakers. At
power forward, the best they can hope for is to get a quality
quarter or two per night from some combination of Robert Horry,
A.C. Green, John Salley and Travis Knight, perhaps even Rick Fox.
That won't be good enough, so expect a trade for a legitimate
starter who can rebound and provide interior defense. Small forward
won't be a strength, either, if Glen Rice can't find his way in the
triangle offense. He shot 31.4 percent in the exhibition season and
rarely appeared comfortable. If he can't get untracked, he might be
traded.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, the Lakers have some depth at small forward,
with former starters Fox and Horry, plus George. &QL; 
CENTERS: Shaquille O'Neal is the most dominant big man in the NBA,
and he'll need every last bicep muscle to survive the season. Coach
Phil Jackson says O'Neal might play 40 minutes a game (it would be
a career-high) in lieu of any capable backups on the roster. Salley
and Knight will provide spot relief, but that will be insufficient
if O'Neal gets in foul trouble or has a flareup of his chronic
abdominal injury. By all appearances, O'Neal is ready for an
MVP-type season. He averaged 23.3 points, 12.5 rebounds and 2.5
blocked shots in the exhibition season. &QL; 
COACH: Jackson's .737 career winning percentage (656-234) is tops
in NBA history, and his six championships give him the locker-room
clout to cure much of what ailed the Lakers. They will not
underachieve under Jackson, or tune him out, but they will struggle
to learn his system. Jackson needs some more triangle-type players
and will scour the league for them over the course of the season.
Once he gets the right combination, and the current group gets
comfortable with the triangle, Jackson's mastery should become
apparent. &QL; 
BENCH: Improved over last season, but still a cause for concern.
Who's the energizing sixth man? Fox? Green? Harper? Fisher? Any of
them could be, but that remains to be seen. Fox and Horry struggled
as reserves last season, and Fisher has been far more productive as
a starter. Who provides rebounding off the bench? Who can anchor a
second unit? Where's the defensive stopper? Jackson's rotation will
be in flux for a while until at least a few of these questions are
answered. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
