<SLUG> BC-AIRCRASH-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGYPTAIR PLANE HAD STATE-OF-THE-ART BLACK BOX 
</HEADLINE>
  (With AIRCRASH-RDP and related stories) 
(mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ The EgyptAir Boeing 767 that crashed Sunday was
equipped with an unusually sophisticated black box, one that
recorded three times as many categories of data as the standard
required in the United States, Boeing said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, when Boeing delivered EgyptAir's 767, the United
States mandated that flight data recorders monitor 17 categories of
airplane operation. But EgyptAir ordered one with 55 data
categories, including monitors for fuel flow, autopilot status and
engine fires, according to Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy has already reported hearing pings from a flight
recorder, giving National Transportation Safety Board officials
cause for optimism that they can learn a great deal about the crash
without having to haul the whole plane from the water. But an
official of the safety board cautioned, ``We won't know till we
crack it open.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are also encouraged because the plane's automatic
radio system, or transponder, continued to respond to radar signals
at least 36 seconds into the sequence of events that doomed the
plane, and if the transponder had power, the boxes may have, too.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, TWA Flight 800, the Boeing 747 that exploded off
the shore of Long Island, N.Y., in 1996, had far more elementary
electronics than the EgyptAir plane. The two black boxes on that
plane, the flight data recorder and the cockpit voice recorder,
quit working within a fraction of a second of the explosion that
destroyed the aircraft. The lack of information from those devices
is one of the factors that has made that investigation so tedious
and long.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president for technical affairs of EgyptAir, Maged
el-Masri, told The Associated Press Monday that the flight data
recorder installed on the downed Boeing 767 could capture 200 to
300 types of data. A Boeing spokesman confirmed that the plane was
delivered with boxes that could record 55 types of data, but he
said he did not know if Egyptair had further updated its data
recorders, as many airlines have done over the years.
</P>
<P>
   One of the 17 data categories that were required by the Federal
Aviation Administration when EgyptAir ordered the 767 shows the
position of the ``thrust reversers,'' which are used on the runway
to redirect a plane's exhaust and slow it down. The reversers were
blamed in the crash of a 767 in Thailand in May 1991. The recorder
notes, for each engine, whether the reversers were deployed, stowed
or in between.
</P>
<P>
   The extra data categories added by EgyptAir show, among other
things, fuel flow and various engine functions, throttle positions,
status of the autopilot and navigation systems, hydraulic and oil
pressures and whether engines were vibrating or on fire.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators will need the data recorders because of a paucity
of other evidence. In TWA 800, for example, other pilots reported
having seen a fire or explosion. In the EgyptAir crash, James Hall,
the chairman of the National Transportation Safety Board, said
Monday, there had been no pilot reports so far of anything unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Searchers did not know if the ping they heard was from the
flight data recorder or the cockpit voice recorder, which is
supposed to capture the last 30 minutes of cockpit sound. The
search equipment on hand cannot detect the source, Hall said,
adding that the equipment to locate it probably will not be in
place until Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, please,'' he said, ``we are dealing with water 250
feet deep, and recovering and locating small objects like recorders
is a daunting effort.'' He cautioned that the investigation would
be lengthy.
</P>
<P>
   But the Navy has a good record for finding black boxes, and the
investigators have a good record in using them to determine the
causes of crashes. In February 1996, for example, the Navy
retrieved a flight data recorder from a Boeing 757 from 7,200 feet
of water, after a crash off the Dominican Republic, and the safety
board quickly found evidence of a maintenance problem that probably
caused the crash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
