<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-FAMILIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH DREAD, FAMILIES GATHER IN RHODE ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO _ Before EgyptAir flight 990 plunged into the waters off
Nantucket, Mass., life for sisters Rania and Suha El Shagie seemed
perfect.
</P>
<P>
   They had both been married the day before and their two
husbands, who were best friends and colleagues in EgyptAir, left
for work on the flight crew aboard the Boeing 767.
</P>
<P>
   Their honeymoons lasted one day.
</P>
<P>
   Hassan Sherif, 26, a flight attendant, called his wife, Rania,
23, on Sunday from New York just before he boarded the flight.
Their rushed conversation now haunts her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me before he left the hotel there was a long delay. He
said there was something wrong with the plane,'' said Rania with
tears welling in her eyes. ``He was very worried about the flight.
He told me that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rania and Suha were among the family members of the 62 Egyptian
victims of the aircrash preparing to take a chartered flight to
Rhode Island Tuesday to begin what will probably be a long,
torturous wait to identify the remains of their loved ones and, if
possible, bring them home for burial. The sisters' brown eyes were
reddened with sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   And as they sat in a large banquet hall in Cairo International
Airport waiting for the 1:30 a.m. flight, Rania kept going over the
final conversation with her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `I don't know why I am so worried this time. I
never feel this way,' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cairo-bound flight had been delayed by 90 minutes in Los
Angeles before stopping at John F. Kennedy International Airport in
New York. LA airport officials said a routine inspection resulted
in the discovery of a flat tire, which was repaired. It was unclear
whether that was the problem Sherif was referring to, or if he
meant a more significant problem.
</P>
<P>
   As Rania dissolved into tears once again, her sister Suha, 24,
reached out and touched her arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to eat something,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   An apple with one bite out of it and an unopened Pepsi sat in
front of Rania.
</P>
<P>
   The two sisters sat waiting for the flight, reflecting on the
joy they felt when they officially registered their marriages on
the day before their husbands left to work aboard the flight last
week. The registry of marriage is a Muslim custom which precedes
the actual wedding day but legally means the couples were married.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all seemed so perfect,'' said Suha, whose husband, Mohamad
Galal, 26, a flight attendant, is also believed to have been killed
in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sisters. Our husbands were best friends. What could be
more perfect?'' she asked, her eyes reddened from hours of crying.
``And then in one minute it is all taken away.''
</P>
<P>
   The families of the victims had all received specially expedited
visas from the US Embassy Monday, and were filled with questions
and a sense of dread at having to come to America to wait for naval
vessels to search the deep, murky waters off Nantucket.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the bereaved families gathered in clusters of grief.
They ate almost nothing, but they talked endlessly with each other.
They seemed to be bonding over their tragedy, realizing they were
in the company of perhaps the only people who could understand what
they were going through.
</P>
<P>
   The stories they shared were poignant, filled with the mystery
of fate.
</P>
<P>
   There was EgyptAir co-pilot Adel Anwar who was eager to return
home to prepare for his wedding, which was to take place on Friday.
He swapped shifts with a colleague and took a seat in the cockpit
of Flight 990, his brother Mohamed told reporters who swarmed the
airport here.
</P>
<P>
   The families of the 28 Egytian military officers who had been on
the flight huddled together. The military officers had been in the
United States for various training sessions. The surviving family
members shared the stories of their sons and brothers who are
believed dead in the crash. Although only one body had been
discovered by Monday, none of them seemed to hold out hope for
rescues. Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Emad Rahim, 37, lost his younger brother, Amer, 31, who was a
strategic communication expert in the military and had been at a US
military training facility in Los Angeles. He confided to another
man who had also lost a brother that he was nervous about the
EgyptAir flight aboard a Boeing 777.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to admit, I am not so easy about flying on EgyptAir,''
he said, the remark sparking a small bit of nervous laughter
between the men.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed to ease some tension.
</P>
<P>
   The families of the six executives of an Egyptian oil company
who were aboard the flight also gathered together.
</P>
<P>
   And amid these gatherings you could see people nodding and
listening and sharing conversations. But not everyone took part.
</P>
<P>
   One man sat with his head in his hands, crying. An unopened
Koran was on the table.
</P>
<P>
   Two men, Mohamed Rashad, a Muslim, and Magdy Mekahail, a Coptic
Christian, discovered that they had both lost their mothers-in-law
in the crash. Both of the men, as it turned out, were electrical
engineers. They pooled what little information they had about the
crash, trying to piece together all of the unanswered questions
they have. But mostly they talked about their mothers-in-law and
how much they meant to their grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I guess we all need each other,'' said Rashad. ``If
we can't find answers, at least we can find some comfort. Everyone
here has lost so much.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
