<SLUG> BC-AUTO-EXECS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERAL MOTORS DIRECTOR WHO LED MANAGEMENT SHAKE-UP TO RETIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Skedded earlier as AUTO-SALES)  
(ms) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ John G. Smale, the director who led a rare management
coup at the General Motors Corp. seven years ago this month, plans
to retire in May, a GM spokesman said Monay.
</P>
<P>
   The man Smale and the GM board installed as chief executive back
then, John F. Smith Jr., is likely to retire at the same time after
seven grueling years at the helm, according to board members and
others close to the company.
</P>
<P>
   While GM's board has not formally decided who would replace
Smith, its current thinking is that the changing of the guard could
be announced as soon as January, but would likely take effect in
May, according to board members and others.
</P>
<P>
   The next leaders of the company will likely come from GM's
current management team. The current thinking is that the board
will split the top job, giving Smith's title of chairman to Harry
J. Pearce, 57, who is vice chairman, and naming as chief executive
officer G. Richard Wagoner Jr., 46, GM's president and chief
operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Smith denied that his retirement was imminent. ``I don't have
any plans to retire,'' Smith said in a recent interview. He
nonetheless added that, ``we have a very strong lineup of
leadership executives and feel very comfortable with succession.''
</P>
<P>
   Smale, 72, who refused to comment on succession plans in a
recent interview, strongly suggested the board would not reach
outside the company. ``You can't really build an organization by
hiring everybody else's executives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The exits of Smith and Smale would in some ways mark the end of
an era at GM. As part of the shake-up, Smale served as GM's
chairman from November 1992 to January 1996, when he handed the
mantle to Smith.
</P>
<P>
   They have brought the company back from the brink of bankruptcy
in the early 1990s, turning massive losses to record profits as the
economy boomed.
</P>
<P>
   Together, Smale, Smith and their team have taken the company
apart and put it back together again. GM used to comprise seven
bureaucratic fiefdoms _ Chevrolet, Pontiac, Saturn, Oldsmobile,
GMC, Buick, Cadillac _ each operating almost independently but
sending profits into headquarters. GM now makes central decisions
about how to run seven similar businesses. It takes better
advantage of the economies of scale involved, both in North America
and in operations around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``GM has turned around,'' Smale said.
</P>
<P>
   Some auto industry experts give GM credit for the changes so far
but say that fixing the company is taking too long. ``In some ways,
they are getting it right, and I believe that they are slowly but
surely making real progress,'' said Robert A. Lutz, retired
president and vice chairman of the Chrysler Corporation. ``It is
grindingly slow.''
</P>
<P>
   For industry executives and experts who have watched in
wonderment as GM has failed to regain a shadow of its heyday in the
1960s when it sold more than half the vehicles in America, the
leadership change cannot come soon enough. Many believe the company
needs to bring in an outsider to shake things up and instill a
sense of urgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need some fresh blood,'' said Gerald P. Hirshberg,
Nissan's president of North American design who began his career at
GM.
</P>
<P>
   The company needs ``an outspoken, even controversial leader,''
said Gerald C. Meyers, the former chairman and chief executive of
the American Motors Corporation and a professor of organizational
behavior at the University of Michigan. He is critical of GM's
inability so far to build head-turning cars and trucks. ``Seven
years in the chair is long enough _ that is two product cycles.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 61, has the strong support of his management team and the
board that elevated him to the top job. ``Jack is a great CEO,''
said Pearce, who refused to discuss succession. ``In the history of
GM, he will go down as one of the great chairmen.''
</P>
<P>
   While Pearce would normally be next in line for both the
chairman and chief executive jobs, the succession became more
complicated when he was stricken with leukemia. He had a
bone-marrow transplant in September 1998. The board has been
delaying its formal decisions until it is clear whether Pearce is
well enough to take on the top jobs, and Smith has agreed to stay
until the board reaches a conclusion about Pearce's health, said a
person familiar with top-level discussions at the company.
</P>
<P>
   But in any case, GM's direction is unlikely to change because
its next leader will be someone who has been running the plays set
by Smale and Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Pearce, viewed in the industry as a charismatic leader, began
working for the company as a product litigation lawyer at a North
Dakota law firm and rose to vice-chairman. Many outsiders view him
as the best GM has. ``It is a disaster that he has come up sick,''
said Meyers, the former AMC leader.
</P>
<P>
   More than a year after his transplant, Pearce was given a clean
bill of health by his doctors, GM spokesmen said, and while he must
take temporary precautions while his immune system recovers _ like
avoiding large crowds _ he is back to a full-time schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Wagoner is regarded as a details-oriented young manager whose
claim to fame is turning around GM's Brazil operations then serving
as Smith's chief financial officer in the bleak, stop-the-bleeding
years of the early 1990's. While most who encounter Wagoner concur
he is extremely bright, some outsiders believe he is too green for
the top job.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the situation is reminiscent of the last time GM's
management turned over. The man Smale deposed, Roger Stempel, was
criticized for his go-slow approach to fixing the company's
problems and for a board that appeared to rubber-stamp management's
plans. To outsiders, the difference now is that after an
unprecedented economic expansion, GM is making money hand over
fist, and that a board member is coaching some of management's big
plays.
</P>
<P>
   Smale, the retired chairman and chief executive of Procter &AMP;
Gamble, has been the board's strong, steady voice for years. Unlike
any other G.M. director, he sits on all seven board committees, and
he is the chairman of the board's executive committee. Several
times a week, he is in contact with Smith, Pearce, Wagoner and
Ronald L. Zarrella, president of GM's North American operations and
marketing chief. And he keeps in touch with lower-level executives
too _ in a recent interview in his office at Procter &AMP; Gamble's
headquarters in Cincinnati, he ticked off a list of five of GM's
division leaders he had recently met with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smale runs this place,'' said one GM executive with some
exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Smale is behind some of GM's biggest changes. Several
years ago, he pushed for the auto company to adopt the brand
management marketing techniques common to companies like Procter &AMP;
Gamble that sell cheaper consumer goods. GM has since hired a
number of midlevel marketers experienced in hawking soft drinks,
diapers, and snack food who have had mixed success selling cars.
</P>
<P>
   And this year's reorganization of the system GM uses to get its
cars from factories to dealers is something that paid off for
Smale's company. The change has not gone smoothly _ dealers have
complained all year that GM can't get them cars their customers
want fast enough as a result of the organizational shuffle _ but
Wall Street analysts are convinced it will eventually prove to be a
smart move. So is Smale. ``We did this at Procter 10 or 11 years
ago,'' he said. ``It simply takes time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
