r s BC-FBN-PAYTON-COLUMN-LAD     11-01 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PAYTON-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYTON LEFT US WITH GREAT MEMORIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By DOUG SPOON 
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESPN's way of paying tribute to the century's greatest athletes
is to roll the videotape and provide some mood music.
</P>
<P>
   Real life isn't like that, of course. Our sports heroes aren't
frozen in time, forever replaying their finest moments.
</P>
<P>
   In real life, athletes win and lose, succeed and fail, prove
themselves mortal and only sometimes seem bigger than the games
they play.
</P>
<P>
   And then they die.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Walter Payton was the one who left us. The former
Chicago Bears running back, the NFL's all-time rushing leader, died
at age 45, after a nine-month wait for a liver transplant.
</P>
<P>
   His death was premature, unfair and only the latest in a long
line of sports figures -- from the young and promising to the old
and prominent -- who have passed away this year.
</P>
<P>
   It started with the death of Joe DiMaggio, whose passing in
March was long anticipated and much dreaded. DiMaggio's obituary
had been prepared for months; one television network reported his
death weeks before it actually happened.
</P>
<P>
   All that took none of the pain away. To a generation of baseball
fans yearning for the innocence of a bygone era, Joltin' Joe took a
little bit of us with him.
</P>
<P>
   Similar feelings were expressed last month when basketball great
Wilt Chamberlain died. Although his position among the game's
all-time greats will be debated forever, Wilt represented a
dominance and dedication many admired and find missing among
today's athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, neither DiMaggio nor Chamberlain was handed the tragic fate
of golfer Payne Stewart, who died in a private plane crash last
week. If there is anything in sports more sad than the death of a
legend, it is the passing of one who wasn't allowed the opportunity
to become one.
</P>
<P>
   Golfer Gene Sarazen's passing came last spring. Former Dodger
shortstop Pee Wee Reese, who lived a long, colorful life, passed on
this fall. Former Athletics and Yankees pitcher Jim ``Catfish''
Hunter suffered greatly before dying of the disease named for
another Yankees standout, Lou Gehrig.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty years ago this summer, Gehrig stood before a sellout crowd
at Yankee Stadium and called himself ``the luckiest man on the face
of the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Gehrig, well aware he was dying of a rare disease, had an
admirable perspective on his situation. At least he was prepared.
</P>
<P>
   For Stewart and several others who died tragically in accidents
this year, death came without warning.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Diemert, a young man trying to make a name for himself in
auto racing, died in a crash during a practice run on opening night
at Irwindale Speedway. J.C. Gonzalez, a promising young jockey,
died after falling from his mount on the first day of horse racing
at the Los Angeles County Fair.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Cowherd become Irwindale Speedway's second fatality in a
crash in September. Greg Moore, 24, was killed in a crash during
the Marlboro 500 in Fontana on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   And now, we have lost a football player whose amazing
combination of grace, strength and endurance will be remembered
well into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   Payton truly was a good guy, a man with honest intentions and
the dedication and ability to carry out his mission. In a 13-year
career, he rushed for 16,726 yards and led the Bears to a Super
Bowl victory in 1985. He avoided tacklers and churned out yardage
in ways many have displayed for short periods of time, but never
with his degree of longevity.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, when Payton appeared publicly last February to announce his
illness, he was quiet and frail, a man staring death in the face
unless a liver donor was found.
</P>
<P>
   That liver never came. In the meantime, Payton developed the
form of cancer that would eventually lead to his death. We
should've been prepared, but we chose to think of brighter days and
to hope.
</P>
<P>
   With Payton, as has happened so often in 1999, we are left with
the memories of a public figure who inspired us.
</P>
<P>
   Those they can never take away from us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
