<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTDOWN IN NORWAY: 100 DAYS TO END A 100-YEAR-OLD CONFLICT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSLO, Norway _ In the birthplace of the Israeli-Palestinian
peace effort, President Clinton presided Monday over a kind of
multinational homage to the original dream of a permanent peace as
both sides prepared for the thorny final round of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and Palestinian leaders, with sideline cheers from the
Norwegians, recommitted themselves to forging a framework agreement
by February. In a series of two-way meetings, with each other and
separately with Clinton, they began designing an approach to carry
forward at a quickened pace.
</P>
<P>
   Although a recent lull in the negotiations had concerned both
the Americans and the Palestinians, Clinton, in the first day of a
two-day summit meeting, said it was hardly time for hand-wringing.
Rather, he and the other leaders referred to this as a critical
juncture when both sides share a resolve to end a 100-year-old
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   In the context of the 100 years, Ehud Barak, the Israeli prime
minister, called the next 100 days a fateful period that could set
the stage for a resolution of a seemingly inexorable battle. Toward
midnight, he headed into a private meeting with Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian leader _ a couple of night owls from the Middle East in
a hotel suite by the fjords.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, looking unusually hale and hearty, Arafat said
he welcomed Barak to be his ``partner in the making of peace, of a
peace of the brave.'' Arafat, 70, was echoing his term of affection
for Yitzhak Rabin, the slain Israeli prime minister whom he
repeatedly refers to as ``my late partner.''
</P>
<P>
   The legacy of Rabin, who was assassinated on Nov. 4 four years
ago, hovers over this reunion in Oslo, with his widow, his
daughter, his two drivers, his foreign minister, Shimon Peres, and
his protege _ Barak _ all present. A memorial service on Tuesday is
meant to serve as the emotional centerpiece of this diplomatic
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis and the Palestinians did not devote any time to the
substance of the charged issues that will shape a future
Palestinian state and Israel's relation to it. Official two-way
talks between Israeli and Palestinian teams begin next week in the
Middle East. The members of the Israeli team were named Monday,
nearly two months after the Palestinian group was established.
</P>
<P>
   But in his meeting with Clinton, Barak revealed a part of his
negotiating strategy for the first time. He said he has divided the
issues _ from the division of water resources to future borders _
into three categories: non-negotiable; vital to Israel and worth
fighting hard for, and merely important.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave Clinton an idea of what are the red lines that cannot
be crossed, and what are the gray lines,'' a senior Israeli
official said. The official would not divulge which issues fell
into which categories.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Michael Melchior, an Israeli cabinet minister, said Barak
has made it clear to him that ``if we really have an overall deal,
he is willing to give deep compromises.'' He said that meant that
if serious issues like Jerusalem were resolved in a way that the
Israelis found favorable, they could do more on territory.
</P>
<P>
   A senior American official said Clinton's meeting with both
leaders focused on practical ways to ``get down to business.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the leaders were discussing, with each other and through
Clinton, whether to deal with all the issues at once or one at a
time, and whether to have single-issue committees. He also said
they would try to figure out their own relationship to the
negotiating teams given that both leaders understand that they will
ultimately make the tough calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the time for us to be focused on the substance,''
the American official said. ``It's a time for us to be focused on
structure, process and organization so that you have a reasonable
chance to get what they have established for themselves _ a
framework agreement on all the permanent-status issues by Feb.
13.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference with the Norwegian prime minister, Kjell
Magne Bondevik, Arafat said he considered the fate of Jerusalem and
of the Jewish settlements in the West Bank to be the most crucial
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to state that holy Jerusalem will be the capital
of the Palestinian state,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM STARTS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in his trademark fatigues and keffiyeh head scarf,
Arafat waved and smiled to the Norwegian crowds that had awaited
his arrival and clapped politely in greeting. He appeared in better
health, more focused and cheerier than he has in some time, with a
notably reduced tremor in his lip. Although he always speaks
publicly in Arabic, Monday he corrected his interpreter, Saeb
Erekat, the senior Palestinian negotiator, and for the first time
in a long time, he broke into English himself.
</P>
<P>
   After Erekat said that the Palestinian leader had called for all
agreements to be implemented as ``accurately and precisely as
signed,'' Arafat raised his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Accurately and honestly,'' Arafat said, smiling largely.
``That is what I said in the original Arabic.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying he would complain to Clinton about Israel's continued
building at settlements in the West Bank, Arafat added that
``Norway, the European Union, the United States and all the nations
of the earth consider settlement activity to be destructive to the
peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is perceived as both a friend of Israel and the first
American president to fully embrace the Palestinians, giving him
unusual sway over the peace effort, whether he is a midwife or a
mediator.
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance here Monday as the first American president to
pay an official visit to Norway, he said it was premature to
discuss a possible summit meeting at Camp David early next year.
But he added, ``There is nothing I would not do if I thought it
would genuinely help build a lasting peace in the Middle East.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For the Israeli and Palestinian peace teams, this city, with its
moody skies and damp streets, evokes vivid memories of their
breakthrough negotiations in 1993 and their return to collect the
Nobel Peace Prize the following year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The waste of three years was a catastrophe, but we are back
here,'' said Uri Savir, a key negotiator and now an Israeli
legislator, who took some of the famous secret walks in the
Norwegian woods that paved the way to the Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
   Savir said he believed strongly that if a deal were not struck
with the current Palestinian leaders, an opportunity would be lost.
Future Palestinian leaders, who grew up under the Israeli
occupation, would prove to be more hard-line, he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   At the Grand Hotel in the center of town, a kind of peace
reunion took place as some of the original players reconvened and
reminisced.
</P>
<P>
   Melchior, a Danish-born Israeli who took a leave as the chief
rabbi of Norway when he joined Barak's cabinet, gave daylong
television interviews Monday in fluent Norwegian.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has the old Oslo feeling here today,'' said Melchior, who
leads a dovish Orthodox movement called Meimad.
</P>
<P>
   During a visit to the Munch Museum, Barak's wife, Nava, who
rarely speaks publicly in Israel, lamented the fact that Rabin's
assassination still made Israel fearful. She referred to the secret
service's decision that her husband would not be allowed to speak
at a memorial service in Israel because there was not sufficient
time to plan proper security.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great shame that four years after the murder, someone
can't get up in public and give a speech without being worried
about his well-being,'' she said. ``It's not even worry about
terrorists from outside, God forbid, but about forces from
within.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
