<SLUG> BC-ANDERSEN-ONLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDERSEN CONSULTING'S CHIEF MAKES E-COMMERCE NEW GOAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Andersen Consulting announced Monday that Joe W.
Forehand, a high-ranking partner with 27 years of experience at the
firm, would be its new chief executive. Forehand said in an
interview that he planned to make e-commerce the central part of
the consulting firm and that the company intended to take stakes in
clients more frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Forehand, a native of Alabama who lives in Texas, most recently
led the firm's communications and high-technology practice, which
accounts for about 25 percent of the company's revenue. He replaces
George T. Shaheen _ who left in September to run Webvan Group, an
Internet grocery delivery company _ as the head of the $9 billion
firm that employs 65,000 people in 48 countries.
</P>
<P>
   The 51-year-old Forehand takes over at a crucial time for
Andersen, the world's largest consulting firm. Its 1999 growth rate
will fall below 20 percent for the first time since 1994 as its
strength of installing back-office systems has become less
lucrative and it has been embroiled in a nasty breakup with its
former parent, Arthur Andersen. After bringing in $8.3 billion in
revenue last year, Andersen Consulting will report a growth rate in
the mid-teens for 1999, Forehand said.
</P>
<P>
   Following in the footsteps of the dynamic Shaheen, the new chief
executive is little known outside of Andersen, where he has spent
his entire career, and one analyst said the appointment was a
surprise, though strategically sensible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andersen doesn't really need a dynamic, colorful leader
anymore,'' said Tim Bourgeois, the vice president of research at
Kennedy Information, a New Hampshire research firm that tracks
consulting. ``It makes sense to have a kinder, gentler person'' as
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Forehand said he envisioned an Andersen that has a consulting
practice at its core but increasingly invests in Internet ventures
that would then be aligned with the firm. It would also use its
consultants' ideas to start businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen, he said, should ``become a part of the fabric of this
new economy, not just watch it happen.'' Currently, 14,000 of
Andersen's consultants are taking internal classes to improve their
understanding of e-commerce, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The firm already holds about a dozen stakes, typically worth $2
million to $3 million each, in start-ups for which it has done
work, said Forehand, who  in engineering at Auburn
University. Forehand said he would aggressively expand such
projects, particularly in business-to-business ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Owning parts of other companies raises potential
conflict-of-interest problems for consulting firms, which have long
worked for more than one client in an industry. Clients could be
reluctant to hire a firm that owns parts of a rival.
</P>
<P>
   Forehand said he was confident that Andersen would be able to
resolve such issues.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he would not alter the firm's confrontational
strategy of seeking a divorce from Arthur Andersen, from which it
tried to break off almost two years ago. Andersen Consulting became
a separate unit of Arthur Andersen in 1989, and the two have spent
much of the 1990s arguing over how to co-exist.
</P>
<P>
   The firms began an arbitration hearing on Oct. 25 in New York.
It will wrap up at the end of next week, Forehand said, and he
expects a ruling early in 2000 on the future structure of the
firms.
</P>
<P>
   That could end a process that has kept some of Andersen's top
partners busy with internal business rather than on
revenue-producing work. ``It has been a distraction for them,''
said C. Scott Hartz, the managing partner for global consulting at
PricewaterhouseCoopers, a rival firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
