<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UKRAINE-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UKRAINE'S PRESIDENT WINS SPOT IN NOV. 14 RUNOFF  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By TOM WARNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIEV, Ukraine _ Leonid Kuchma overcame his own lackluster record
as leader of Ukraine for the past five years to win a commanding
first place in a preliminary round of presidential elections on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   According to nearly complete but unofficial results issued
Monday evening, Kuchma finished well out in front of the 12 other
candidates with 36.5 percent of the votes. He now faces a runoff on
Nov. 14 against the leader of the Communist Party, Petro Symonenko,
who placed second with 22.2 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
   International election observers said that some of the campaign
methods used by Kuchma and his supporters were unfair and even
illegal, but that they were generally pleased about the voting
process and said the count seemed to reflect how Ukrainians cast
their ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts said the result made Kuchma a virtual shoe-in in
the second round. The only candidate who was thought to have a
serious shot at beating Kuchma, the Socialist Party leader
Oleksandr Moroz, placed a distant third with only 11.3 percent of
the votes.
</P>
<P>
   Mykhailo Pohrebinsky, an analyst and one of Ukraine's leading
pollsters, said the greatest danger for Kuchma is that his
supporters will be so certain of his victory that they won't show
up at the polls for the final runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Symonenko beat out other would-be challengers by initially
focusing on gaining the support of the party faithful and then
reaching for broader support on the eve of the election with
newsmaking comments that seemed to show him breaking from his
reputation as a doctrinaire Marxist-Leninist.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Symonenko and his party had consistently called
for Ukraine to join Russia's union with Belarus as a first step
toward restoration of the Soviet Union. On Monday, however
Symonenko said he favored ``free trade'' with Russia and Belarus
but not necessarily political union.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
