<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE HOUSE SEEKS DEAL TO ALLOW CHINA INTO WTO
</P>
<P>
   After a series of secret exchanges with Beijing over the last
two weeks, the White House is racing to close a deal by the end of
this month that it hopes will pave China's way into the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Senior administration officials say there is a 50-50 chance they
will be able to close the huge deal, which President Clinton views
as his best shot at stabilizing American relations with China
during his last year in office.
</P>
<P>
   CHASE DISMISSES CURRENCY TRADER
</P>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan said that its fourth-quarter trading revenue
would be reduced by $60 million after the bank discovered that it
had booked nonexistent trading profits. The bank has dismissed a
currency trader involved in the matter. Chase's stock dropped
$3.6875, or 4 percent, to $83.5625.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE RETAILERS TURN TO TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that this Christmas season will be make-or-break,
online retailers are in a costly race to bring their names to
consumers through TV advertising.
</P>
<P>
   BELL ATLANTIC SYSTEM NOT QUITE OPEN
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department said that Bell Atlantic had come close to
fully opening its local networks in New York to competitors but had
not quite made it, a condition for entering the long-distance
market.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T argued before a federal appeals court that Portland, Ore.,
exceeded its authority when it sought to force AT&AMP;T to open its
cable lines to rival Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS MIXED; NASDAQ HITS RECORD
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices were mixed, but the NASDAQ composite index eked out
another record, rising 1.22 points, to 2,967.65. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index fell by 8.81 points, to 1,354.12, and the
Dow Jones industrial average slumped 81.35 points, or eight-tenths
of a percent, to 10,648.51.
</P>
<P>
   Yields of Treasury securities held near their four-week lows
amid hopes that the Federal Reserve would not need to raise
interest rates more than once in coming months to check inflation.
The yield on the 30-year issue rose to 6.18 percent from 6.16
percent on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   NEW CHIEF AT ANDERSEN CONSULTING
</P>
<P>
   Andersen Consulting announced that Joe Forehand, a high-ranking
partner with 27 years of experience at the firm, would be its new
chief executive. He replaces George Shaheen, who departed in
September to run Webvan Group, an Internet grocery delivery
company. Forehand said that he planned to make e-commerce the
central part of the consulting firm and that the company intended
to take stakes in clients more frequently.
</P>
<P>
   DAIMLER TO TEST NEW PLASTIC ROOFS
</P>
<P>
   Taking a big step forward in the development of automobiles with
plastic bodies, DaimlerChrysler announced that it would equip 5,000
of its Jeep Wranglers each year with lightweight, low-cost roofs
made from a new kind of specially hardened plastic.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAW PLANS TO INVEST IN ICO GLOBAL
</P>
<P>
   Craig McCaw, the cellular telephone pioneer, said that he had
agreed to raise at least $1.2 billion to take ICO Global
Communications, the struggling global satellite telephone business,
out of Chapter 11.
</P>
<P>
   CHAIRMAN OF DAEWOO OFFERS TO QUIT
</P>
<P>
   Disgraced by the collapse of the business empire he founded 32
years ago, the chairman of Daewoo Group, Kim Woo-choong, submitted
his resignation to the domestic creditors who are overseeing the
sale of the South Korean conglomerate's vast array of heavily
indebted businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
