<HEADER>
A5770 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-TULLIS-NYT &LR;      11-01 0328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-TULLIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICHARD TULLIS, EX-CHAIRMAN OF HARRIS CORP., DIES AT 86  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ill, Pa., N.J., Calif., Ohio)   By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richard B. Tullis, who guided the Harris Corp. from a small
printing press company to an electronic communications equipment
giant, died on Sunday at his home in Vero Beach, Fla., the company
said. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   Although Harris' early career predated the computer revolution
by decades, he was well primed to ride the electronic
communications wave. Tullis graduated from Principia College in
Elsah, Ill., in 1934, with a double major in mathematics and
physics. After short stints with the Dictograph Products Co. and
Schick Dry Shaver, he joined the Miller Printing Machinery Co. of
Pittsburgh as a salesman.
</P>
<P>
   Tullis moved to Cleveland in 1956 to become vice president of
what was then known as Harris-Seybold, a maker of printing presses
and paper cutters. Over the next 29 years, as Harris began changing
into a manufacturer of word processing systems and other
computerized communications devices, he rose through the company's
ranks, becoming president in 1961, chief executive in 1968 and
chairman in 1972. He remained on the Harris board until 1985.
</P>
<P>
   He also served on the boards of National City Bank, the
Cleveland Electric Illuminating Company, NACCO Industries and
GenCorp, and was chairman of Armada Funds Group for nine years.
</P>
<P>
   Tullis' role in Cleveland extended beyond Harris. He was among
the leaders of a movement to build low-income housing in the city's
downtrodden Hough area and was a longtime trustee of the Cleveland
Orchestra, where he and his wife, Chaille, endowed the principal
viola chair.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Tullis is survived by his daughter,
Mrs. Charles G.L. de Barcza of Bedminster, N.J.; twin sons, Barclay
of Palo Alto, Calif., and Garner of New York City; nine
grandchildren; and five great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 2143EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0450 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5772 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-EGYPTAIR02-COX     11-01 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPTAIR02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EgyptAir crash investigation: Too early to predict cause
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ While abandoning hope that they would find any
survivors from Sunday's crash of EgyptAir Flight 990, searchers
Monday recovered a large piece of the aircraft and heard a signal
believed to come from a flight recorder.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these discoveries, officials said they're baffled by the
crash. They cautioned that the investigation _ even the recovery of
submerged wreckage _ could take years.
</P>
<P>
   That haunting prospect awaits more than 180 relatives from Egypt
and across the United States arriving in this historic Navy town.
Grief counselors await them at a local hotel and investigators
promise twice-a-day updates.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon disclosed 30 Egyptian military officers were on
board the doomed flight. Among the officers was at least one
brigadier general, The Associated Press reported, citing unnamed
administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   But authorities said they have found no indications of sabotage
or terrorist activity.
</P>
<P>
   ''At this particular point in time, there is no indication of
criminal activity,'' FBI agent Barry Mawn said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He added, however, that FBI bomb technicians and lab specialists
will help in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   National Transportation Safety Board Chairman Jim Hall cautioned
that he's unwilling to rule out the possibility of sabotage because
of the investigation is in the ''very early stages.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The facts will lead us where they will lead us,'' said Hall,
flanked by officials of the NTSB, the FBI, the Coast Guard and the
Navy.
</P>
<P>
   The Egyptian military officers were mostly pilots who had been
training in the United States, the Pentagon said. The 199
passengers included 106 Americans _ 54 of them headed on a two-week
trip to Egypt and the Nile. Eighteen crew members were on board.
</P>
<P>
   The first group of victims' relatives arrived from New York on
Monday afternoon by chartered plane at T.F. Green Airport in
Warwick, where they were greeted on the tarmac by an Egyptian
priest. They were taken to a hotel and offered grief counseling
from the Red Cross and other organizations.
</P>
<P>
   George Arian, a friend of one of the victims, said some
passengers on the flight to Rhode Island panicked briefly as the
plane began flying over water soon after takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a shock. Some people were crying hard,'' Arian said.
``Every lady or every man was thinking of his loved one.''
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian investigators and the president of EgyptAir are
expected to arrive today to assist in the investigation, Hall said.
He estimated 500 to 1,000 investigators are at work.
</P>
<P>
   The Cairo-bound Boeing 767 suddenly plummeted 33,000 feet into
the Atlantic Ocean 50 miles south of Nantucket, Mass., early
Sunday, a half-hour after leaving New York's John F. Kennedy
Airport. The plane vanished from radar screens without making a
distress call or giving any other indication of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, searchers detected a pinging sound, which
investigators believe is coming from one of two ''black box''
recorders. If recovered, the flight data recorder or the cockpit
voice recorder may offer clues to the jetliner's plunge.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said it will be 36 to 48 hours before the USNS Mohawk,
equipped with sophisticated listening devices, will arrive at the
debris field to hone in on the pinging, presumably 250 feet under
water.
</P>
<P>
   ''Recovering small objects, including a recorder, is daunting,''
Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   The debris collected _ some of it by student sailors from the
U.S. Merchant Marine Academy _ includes shoes, purses and teddy
bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``It basically looked like somebody had emptied their trash
Dumpster,'' said one of the sailors, Chris Kincaid.
</P>
<P>
   None of the retrieved debris has any burn marks that might
indicate a fire or explosion, search officials said.
</P>
<P>
   All agencies are now focused on search and recovery, abandoning
rescue efforts 36 hours after the crash. A person could survive
five to six hours in the 59-degree water.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have far exceeded that,'' Coast Guard Rear Adm. Richard M.
Larrabee said. ''We believe at this point it is in everyone's best
interest to no longer expect we will find survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was nothing we needed or wanted that we did not have in
terms of searching for survivors,'' he said. ''There were no
limitations as far as our efforts for the last two days.''
</P>
<P>
   But until now, Larrabee said, ''One of the frustrations in this
case is we have not been able to communicate directly with the
families of the victims.''
</P>
<P>
   Airplanes and boats originally scoured a 9,000-square-mile zone,
but narrowed it to a 36-square-mile area after discovering floating
debris Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy and Coast Guard rushed to gather the debris _ small
pieces of the plane, cushions and seats, clothing and other
personal belongings _ in advance of wind, rain and cold weather
forecast today.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled to reach the search area today, a ship capable of
sonar detection and a second vessel equipped with sonar and a robot
will focus their search on underwater debris.
</P>
<P>
   It is going to be tough, despite the sophisticated technology.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not a good area,'' said former Coast Guard officer Brent
Spies, now a private boat captain. ''It is very deep. There are
conflicting currents. The weather can deteriorate real quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard cutter Monomoy transported human remains and
aircraft debris Monday from the search area to the former Quonset
Point naval base. The NTSB is staging its investigation at the
sprawling complex of airplane hangars, runways and deep-water
docks, northwest of Newport.
</P>
<P>
   The agency will gather wreckage and attempt to reassemble the
plane in one of the hangars. In conjunction with the local medical
examiner, the NTSB is setting up a temporary morgue in another
building.
</P>
<P>
   Searchers have recovered one body, grisly work in this scenic
stretch of New England. Deep-blue water dominates the rocky terrain
dotted by weather-beaten towns and brick houses perched over the
Narragansett Bay.
</P>
<P>
   In Newport, the Coast Guard has set up its search-and-recovery
operations at the Naval Yard where a ship delivered the wreckage of
John F. Kennedy Jr.'s private plane, recovered from nearby waters
in July.
</P>
<P>
   Relief agencies, including the American Red Cross and the
Salvation Army, are setting up operations in Newport and Quonset
Point. The agencies will feed emergency workers and provide
counseling for the grieving.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know the people of Rhode Island will open their hearts to
their families wherever they come from,'' Rhode Island Gov. Lincoln
Almond said.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burritt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
