<P>
   (NYT11) OFF NANTUCKET ISLAND, Mass. -- Nov. 1, 1999 --
AIRCRASH-1, 11-01 -- A Coast Guard Cutter and a smaller boat during
search operations on Monday for victims or debris from the crash of
Egypt Air Flight 990. Coast Guard search crews gave up hope Monday
of finding anyone alive from the doomed flight, but found a large
piece of wreckage and detected a signal believed to be from one of
the plane's ``black boxes.'' (Dominic Chavez/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) DENVER -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- SCI-ZUBRIN-MARS, 11-01 -- Dr.
Robert Zubrin, 47, founder of the Mars Society. His 1996 volume,
``The Case for Mars,'' made a sensation in astronautical circles
with an interesting notion for a cut-rate program for Mars
exploration known as the Mars Direct Plan. The proposed program
would use existing technology and would keep fuel weight at a
minimum by having the astronauts manufacture propellant for the
return trip from material on Mars. (Brian Payne/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- SCI-MUSICAL-INSTRUMENTS-3,
11-01 -- Dr. Joseph Markoff, an amateur musician, advocates an odd
technique: freezing. ``I believe that cryogenics stabilizes the
brass and reduces extraneous vibrations and harmonics,'' he says.
``But the bottom line is that it makes me sound better.'' (Michael
Branscom/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) ARLINGTON HEIGHTS, Ill. -- Nov. 1, 1999 --
SCI-MUSICAL-INSTRUMENTS-2, 11-01 -- Those who have tried to
deep-freeze their instruments say there is a difference in ease of
playing and in the range of ``color'' in the tone. Wayne Tanabe,
owner of the Brass Bow music shop in Arlington Heights, puts a tuba
into a freezer cooled with liquid nitrogen to 325 degrees below
zero. (Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) ARLINGTON HEIGHTS, Ill. -- Nov. 1, 1999 --
SCI-MUSICAL-INSTRUMENTS-1, 11-01 -- Deep-freezing musical
instruments may sound extreme, but it is just one example of how
brass and woodwind makers are wrestling with deciding just how much
to allow technology to remake their craft. Wayne Tanabe, owner of
the Brass Bow music shop in Arlington Heights, prepares a french
horn for freezing by rinsing it in a water bath. (Steve Kagan/New
York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NASHUA, N.H. -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- CAMPAIGN-MCCAIN-BOS,
11-01 -- Sen John McCain, R-Ariz., a candidate for the Republican
nomination for president, during a luncheon with the Software
Association Of New Hampshire last week. Weaving a history of
Vietnam War valor with details of a rambunctious youth, McCain is
presenting himself as a man of vigor and a political maverick, a
man of achievement who has made his share of mistakes. The style is
what his aides like to call ``the total candor campaign,'' a
strategy calibrated for the post-Clinton era. (Lane Turner/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BOSTON -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- SCI-TB-BOS, 11-01 -- Drs. Paul
Farmer, left, and Jim Yong Kim, of Harvard University's Deptartment
of Social Medicine, are the founders of Partners in Health, a group
which lobbies for equal access to health care in the poorest parts
of the world. (Wendy Maeda/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOSTON -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- SCI-GERMS-BOS, 11-01 -- Dr.
Stuart Levy, a Tufts University School of Medicine infectious
disease specialist, looks at bacteria which is resistant to
antibiotics in his laboratory. Levy has been sounding the alarm on
antibiotic resistance for years. (John tlumacki/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- TV-PUERTORICO-REVIEW-2, 10-31
-- The producer and creator of ``Taina,'' Maria Perez-Brown, and
the show's director, Chuck Vison, watch a montior during the
filming of a scene. The concept of this show, which focuses on a
teenager and her multigenerational family, is based on Ms.
Perez-Brown's own experiences growing up in Puerto Rico, in
Brooklyn and in Hartford and, she said, on ``my fantasy experiences
- the kind of childhood I would have liked to have had.'' It has
been in development for two years. (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- TV-PUERTORICO-REVIEW-1, 10-31
-- Diane Lozada, 17, will play Taina, in a prime-time television
series of the same name that Nickelodeon plans to try out with its
children's audience by next year. ``This is my first time in a
starring role and that I get to show all my abilities at once,''
she said sitting outside the School for Performing Arts. ``I get to
act, sing and dance.'' And, she added, ``I get to be the Puerto
Rican that I am.'' (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- GRUNWALD-BLINDNESS, 10-31 --
Henry Grunwald, the former editor in chief of Time Inc. and
ambassador to Austria, has written ``Twilight: Losing Sight,
Gaining Insight,'' which he calls ``an autobiography of my eyes,''
to be published on Wednesday by Alfred A. Knopf. Grunwald, 76, has
been slowly losing his sight since 1992 because of macular
degeneration (a disease of the central retina, which picks up the
finest details of what people see). It affects 15 million Americans
and is the biggest single cause of legal blindness among the
elderly. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
