New York Times Photo Package, moving Monday, 11/01/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) ABOARD MERCHANT MARINE TRAINING SHIP KINGS POINTER,
South of Nantucket Island -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- AIRCRASH-10, 11-01 --
Debris from EgyptAir Flight 990 lies aboard the Merchant Marine
training ship after it was recovered on Sunday from the ocean south
of Nantucket Island. Coast Guard search crews gave up hope on
Monday of finding anyone alive from the doomed flight, but found a
large piece of wreckage and detected a signal believed to be from
one of the plane's ``black boxes.'' (Troy Gosswiller/New York Times
Photo) MAGS OUT
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- AIRCRASH-9, 11-01 -- Tamer
Omar, brother of a co-pilot in training on Egyptair Flight 990,
Heshema Omar, is surounded by the press as he walks outside the
Ramada inn at John F. Kennedy airport. All over the world, families
and friends sifted through pictures - mental and sentimental ones
as well as photographs - of the passengers and crew members who
died Sunday when Egyptair Flight 990 fell into the Atlantic Ocean
off Nantucket. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- MUSEUM-SUIT, 11-01 -- From
left, Robert Rubin, charman of the board of the Brooklyn Museum of
Art, Arnold Lehman director of the museum and attorney Floyd Abrams
before a news conference on Monday. A federal judge ruled on Monday
that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York violated the First
Amendment when he cut city funding and began eviction proceedings
against the museum for mounting an art exhibition the mayor deemed
offensive and sacrilegious. (Dith Pran/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- SCI-FITNESS-WATER, 11-01 --
Doctors say too much water during endurance events like a long run
can be dangerous. Though athletes need to drink regularly during a
race to prevent dehydration, experts say that excess water can lead
to hyponatremia, a potentially fatal condition that is rare but
increasing among recreational athletes. (Steve Berman/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- LACHAPELLE-FASHION-3, 11-01
-- From left, Barry Diller, Diane Von Furstenberg and Miuccia Prada
showed up to be counted Interview magazine's 30th anniversary party
last Thursday night at the Kit Kat Club. Despite hints of
decadence, hardly any of the usual crew of guests seemed shocked by
the evening's proceedings. (Miles Ladin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- LACHAPELLE-FASHION-2, 11-01
-- The theme of the evening was the ``Hotel LaChapelle,'' for the
photographer David LaChapelle's new book. And what's a hotel
without topless bell boys and bell girls? (Miles Ladin/New York
Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- LACHAPELLE-FASHION-1, 11-01
-- The rapper Lil' Kim performing in a hip hugger (it hugged only
one hip) at Interview magazine's 30th anniversary party last
Thursday night at the Kit Kat Club. Lil' Kim is the real thing, an
invention, a performer whose body and obvious lack of inhibition
make you feel she is totally in control of the stage. (Miles
Ladin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) PAGOSA SPRINGS, Colo. -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- PARK-RESORTS,
11-01 -- Sierra Club activist Betty Feazel, right, and Mark
Pearson, chairman of the club's National Wildlands Committee,
oppose an exclusive club development planned for an as-yet
undeveloped valley that borders Feazel's ranch in the Rockies of
Southern Colorado. ``This is a cancer in the heart of a national
area,'' says Ms. Feazel, 83. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) PORTLAND, Ore. -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- PORTLAND-INTERNET,
11-01 -- City councilman Erik Sten speaks to reporters as David
Olson, director of the City Cable Office, looks on in Portland on
Monday. Seeking to stamp out a growing political brush fire that
started here, the AT&AMP;T Corp. argued before a federal appeals court
Monday that the city exceeded its authority last year when it
sought to force AT&AMP;T to open its cable lines to rival Internet
service providers. (John Gress/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK-- Nov. 1, 1999 -- AIRCRASH-8 11-01 -- Reporters
cover the arrival on Monday of relatives who lost loved-ones on
EgyptAir Flight 990 at JFK Airport. The Cairo-bound EgyptAir Boeing
767 was carrying 217 people when it plunged into the Atlantic from
33,000 feet early Sunday, a half-hour after leaving New York's
Kennedy Airport. The plane went down without a distress call or any
other indication of trouble from the pilots. (Ruby Washington/New
York Times Photo) MAGS OUT
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) BOSTON -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- BOSTON-CANCER-2, 11-01 -- Jose
Navarro, a 40-year-old Boston flea market vendor, is surprised by
what he learns from reading an anticancer pamphlet. The
quarter-million English-and-Spanish brochures, Boston's largest
public health mailing ever, are the flashiest element of the city's
``crusade against cancer.'' (Jared Leeds/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) BOSTON -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- BOSTON-CANCER-1, 11-01 --
Esther Ellis, 71, reads an anticancer pamphlet while waiting to
receive a mammogram. Over the last few days, every household in
Boston, in theory, has been mailed a brochure describing how to
prevent cancer and to detect it early if it develops. (Jared
Leeds/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) STUDENCANE, Yugoslavia -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- KOSOVO-WINTER,
11-01 -- Hanife Gega, an ethnic Albanian, prepares tea in the ruins
of her home last Friday. Her house, like many in the village in
southern Kosovo, was burned with such ferocity by Serb forces that
aid organizations have categorized it as irreparable and fit only
for demolition. Despite the United Nations' promises that every
family in Kosovo will have a dry room for the winter, many
families, the Gegas included, will be camping outside. (Andrew
Testa/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) ABOARD MERCHANT MARINE TRAINING SHIP KINGS POINTER,
South of Nantucket Island -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- AIRCRASH-7, 11-01 -- A
crewman recovers debris from EgyptAir Flight 990 on Sunday south of
Nantucket Island. The debris was found by crewmen aboard the
Merchant Marine training vessel and handed over to the Coast Guard
later Sunday. (Daniel Robson/New York Times Photo) MAGS OUT
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) KINGSTON, R.I. -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- AIRCRASH-6, 11-01 --
Government officials examining debris from EgyptAir Flight 990 on
Davisville Pier 2 in Kingston on Monday. Coast Guard search crews
gave up hope Monday of finding anyone alive from the flight, but
found a large piece of wreckage and detected a signal believed to
be from one of the plane's ``black boxes.'' (Chang W. Lee/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) - MAGS OUT ADVISORY
