   (NYT24) PAGOSA SPRINGS, Colo. -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- PARK-RESORTS,
11-01 -- Sierra Club activist Betty Feazel, right, and Mark
Pearson, chairman of the club's National Wildlands Committee,
oppose an exclusive club development planned for an as-yet
undeveloped valley that borders Feazel's ranch in the Rockies of
Southern Colorado. ``This is a cancer in the heart of a national
area,'' says Ms. Feazel, 83. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) PORTLAND, Ore. -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- PORTLAND-INTERNET,
11-01 -- City councilman Erik Sten speaks to reporters as David
Olson, director of the City Cable Office, looks on in Portland on
Monday. Seeking to stamp out a growing political brush fire that
started here, the AT&AMP;T Corp. argued before a federal appeals court
Monday that the city exceeded its authority last year when it
sought to force AT&AMP;T to open its cable lines to rival Internet
service providers. (John Gress/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK-- Nov. 1, 1999 -- AIRCRASH-8 11-01 -- Reporters
cover the arrival on Monday of relatives who lost loved-ones on
EgyptAir Flight 990 at JFK Airport. The Cairo-bound EgyptAir Boeing
767 was carrying 217 people when it plunged into the Atlantic from
33,000 feet early Sunday, a half-hour after leaving New York's
Kennedy Airport. The plane went down without a distress call or any
other indication of trouble from the pilots. (Ruby Washington/New
York Times Photo) MAGS OUT
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) BOSTON -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- BOSTON-CANCER-2, 11-01 -- Jose
Navarro, a 40-year-old Boston flea market vendor, is surprised by
what he learns from reading an anticancer pamphlet. The
quarter-million English-and-Spanish brochures, Boston's largest
public health mailing ever, are the flashiest element of the city's
``crusade against cancer.'' (Jared Leeds/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) BOSTON -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- BOSTON-CANCER-1, 11-01 --
Esther Ellis, 71, reads an anticancer pamphlet while waiting to
receive a mammogram. Over the last few days, every household in
Boston, in theory, has been mailed a brochure describing how to
prevent cancer and to detect it early if it develops. (Jared
Leeds/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) STUDENCANE, Yugoslavia -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- KOSOVO-WINTER,
11-01 -- Hanife Gega, an ethnic Albanian, prepares tea in the ruins
of her home last Friday. Her house, like many in the village in
southern Kosovo, was burned with such ferocity by Serb forces that
aid organizations have categorized it as irreparable and fit only
for demolition. Despite the United Nations' promises that every
family in Kosovo will have a dry room for the winter, many
families, the Gegas included, will be camping outside. (Andrew
Testa/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) ABOARD MERCHANT MARINE TRAINING SHIP KINGS POINTER,
South of Nantucket Island -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- AIRCRASH-7, 11-01 -- A
crewman recovers debris from EgyptAir Flight 990 on Sunday south of
Nantucket Island. The debris was found by crewmen aboard the
Merchant Marine training vessel and handed over to the Coast Guard
later Sunday. (Daniel Robson/New York Times Photo) MAGS OUT
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) KINGSTON, R.I. -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- AIRCRASH-6, 11-01 --
Government officials examining debris from EgyptAir Flight 990 on
Davisville Pier 2 in Kingston on Monday. Coast Guard search crews
gave up hope Monday of finding anyone alive from the flight, but
found a large piece of wreckage and detected a signal believed to
be from one of the plane's ``black boxes.'' (Chang W. Lee/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) - MAGS OUT ADVISORY
</P>
<P>
   The photos of debris from EgyptAir Flight 990 aboard the
Merchant Marine training ship Kings Pointer, NYT12, 13, 14, sent
Nov. 1, 1999, are MAGAZINES OUT. The New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) ABOARD MERCHANT MARINE TRAINING SHIP KINGS POINTER,
South of Nantucket Island -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- AIRCRASH-4, 11-01 --
Coast Guardsmen and crewmen aboard the Kings Pointer lower an
inflatable rescue slide, recovered from EgyptAir Flight 990, to a
Coast Guard boat on Sunday south of Nantucket Island. The debris
was found by crewmen aboard the Merchant Marine training vessel and
handed over to the Coast Guard later Sunday. (Cpt. Cynthia
Smith/New York Times) MAGS OUT
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) ABOARD MERCHANT MARINE TRAINING SHIP KINGS POINTER,
South of Nantucket Island -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- AIRCRASH-4, 11-01 --
Coast Guardsmen remove lines used to lower an inflatable rescue
slide from EgyptAir Flight 990 on Sunday south of Nantucket Island.
The debris was found by crewmen aboard Kings Pointer, a Merchant
Marine training vessel, and handed over to the Coast Guard later
Sunday. (Cpt. Cynthia Smith/New York Times) LITE MAGS OUT
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) ABOARD MERCHANT MARINE TRAINING SHIP KINGS POINTER,
South of Nantucket Island -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- AIRCRASH-3, 11-01 --
Debris from EgyptAir Flight 990 lies aboard a Merchant Marine
training ship after it was recovered on Sunday from the ocean south
of Nantucket Island. Coast Guard search crews gave up hope on
Monday of finding anyone alive from the doomed flight, but found a
large piece of wreckage and detected a signal believed to be from
one of the plane's ``black boxes.'' (Kevin Cronau/New York Times
Photo) MAGS OUT
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ABOARD MERCHANT MARINE TRAINING SHIP KINGS POINTER,
South of Nantucket Island -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- AIRCRASH-2, 11-01 --
Debris from EgyptAir Flight 990 lies aboard a Merchant Marine
training ship after it was recovered on Sunday from the ocean south
of Nantucket Island. Coast Guard search crews gave up hope on
Monday of finding anyone alive from the doomed flight, but found a
large piece of wreckage and detected a signal believed to be from
one of the plane's ``black boxes.'' (Kevin Cronau/New York Times
Photo) LITE MAGS OUT
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) OFF NANTUCKET ISLAND, Mass. -- Nov. 1, 1999 --
AIRCRASH-1, 11-01 -- A Coast Guard Cutter and a smaller boat during
search operations on Monday for victims or debris from the crash of
Egypt Air Flight 990. Coast Guard search crews gave up hope Monday
of finding anyone alive from the doomed flight, but found a large
piece of wreckage and detected a signal believed to be from one of
the plane's ``black boxes.'' (Dominic Chavez/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) DENVER -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- SCI-ZUBRIN-MARS, 11-01 -- Dr.
Robert Zubrin, 47, founder of the Mars Society. His 1996 volume,
``The Case for Mars,'' made a sensation in astronautical circles
with an interesting notion for a cut-rate program for Mars
exploration known as the Mars Direct Plan. The proposed program
would use existing technology and would keep fuel weight at a
minimum by having the astronauts manufacture propellant for the
return trip from material on Mars. (Brian Payne/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- SCI-MUSICAL-INSTRUMENTS-3,
11-01 -- Dr. Joseph Markoff, an amateur musician, advocates an odd
technique: freezing. ``I believe that cryogenics stabilizes the
brass and reduces extraneous vibrations and harmonics,'' he says.
``But the bottom line is that it makes me sound better.'' (Michael
Branscom/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) ARLINGTON HEIGHTS, Ill. -- Nov. 1, 1999 --
SCI-MUSICAL-INSTRUMENTS-2, 11-01 -- Those who have tried to
deep-freeze their instruments say there is a difference in ease of
playing and in the range of ``color'' in the tone. Wayne Tanabe,
owner of the Brass Bow music shop in Arlington Heights, puts a tuba
into a freezer cooled with liquid nitrogen to 325 degrees below
zero. (Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) ARLINGTON HEIGHTS, Ill. -- Nov. 1, 1999 --
SCI-MUSICAL-INSTRUMENTS-1, 11-01 -- Deep-freezing musical
instruments may sound extreme, but it is just one example of how
brass and woodwind makers are wrestling with deciding just how much
to allow technology to remake their craft. Wayne Tanabe, owner of
the Brass Bow music shop in Arlington Heights, prepares a french
horn for freezing by rinsing it in a water bath. (Steve Kagan/New
York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NASHUA, N.H. -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- CAMPAIGN-MCCAIN-BOS,
11-01 -- Sen John McCain, R-Ariz., a candidate for the Republican
nomination for president, during a luncheon with the Software
Association Of New Hampshire last week. Weaving a history of
Vietnam War valor with details of a rambunctious youth, McCain is
presenting himself as a man of vigor and a political maverick, a
man of achievement who has made his share of mistakes. The style is
what his aides like to call ``the total candor campaign,'' a
strategy calibrated for the post-Clinton era. (Lane Turner/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BOSTON -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- SCI-TB-BOS, 11-01 -- Drs. Paul
Farmer, left, and Jim Yong Kim, of Harvard University's Deptartment
of Social Medicine, are the founders of Partners in Health, a group
which lobbies for equal access to health care in the poorest parts
of the world. (Wendy Maeda/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOSTON -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- SCI-GERMS-BOS, 11-01 -- Dr.
Stuart Levy, a Tufts University School of Medicine infectious
disease specialist, looks at bacteria which is resistant to
antibiotics in his laboratory. Levy has been sounding the alarm on
antibiotic resistance for years. (John tlumacki/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- TV-PUERTORICO-REVIEW-2, 10-31
-- The producer and creator of ``Taina,'' Maria Perez-Brown, and
the show's director, Chuck Vison, watch a montior during the
filming of a scene. The concept of this show, which focuses on a
teenager and her multigenerational family, is based on Ms.
Perez-Brown's own experiences growing up in Puerto Rico, in
Brooklyn and in Hartford and, she said, on ``my fantasy experiences
- the kind of childhood I would have liked to have had.'' It has
been in development for two years. (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- TV-PUERTORICO-REVIEW-1, 10-31
-- Diane Lozada, 17, will play Taina, in a prime-time television
series of the same name that Nickelodeon plans to try out with its
children's audience by next year. ``This is my first time in a
starring role and that I get to show all my abilities at once,''
she said sitting outside the School for Performing Arts. ``I get to
act, sing and dance.'' And, she added, ``I get to be the Puerto
Rican that I am.'' (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Nov. 1, 1999 -- GRUNWALD-BLINDNESS, 10-31 --
Henry Grunwald, the former editor in chief of Time Inc. and
ambassador to Austria, has written ``Twilight: Losing Sight,
Gaining Insight,'' which he calls ``an autobiography of my eyes,''
to be published on Wednesday by Alfred A. Knopf. Grunwald, 76, has
been slowly losing his sight since 1992 because of macular
degeneration (a disease of the central retina, which picks up the
finest details of what people see). It affects 15 million Americans
and is the biggest single cause of legal blindness among the
elderly. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
