<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAEWOO-FOUNDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAEWOO FOUNDER AND 12 OTHER EXECUTIVES OFFER TO RESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SAMUEL LEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ Disgraced by the collapse of the business
empire he founded 32 years ago, the chairman of the Daewoo Group
submitted his resignation Monday to the domestic creditors who are
overseeing the sale of the South Korean conglomerate's vast array
of heavily indebted businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation offer by Kim Woo Choong, a modern-day Korean
business legend, was quickly followed by similar offers from the
presidents of Daewoo's 12 main affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear Monday night whether the creditors had accepted
the resignations. Kim had quietly left Seoul last week. Now in
Frankfurt, he called over the weekend and offered to quit, group
executives said.
</P>
<P>
   His move was not a complete surprise. The 62-year-old chairman
resigned last month as chairman of the nation's big business
lobbying group, the Federation of Korean Industries, leading to
speculation that he would leave Daewoo as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to step down from management in order to take full
responsibility for Daewoo Group's management problems,'' Kim and
the other executives said in a statement. ``Our decision is also
aimed at helping speed up the rehabilitation of the group's
affiliates.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim, who once personified South Korea's business success,
created Daewoo with a $10,000 loan in 1967, starting the company as
a one-room textile exporter. Over the years, Daewoo _ which means
``Great Universe'' in Korean _ grew into the nation's
second-largest conglomerate behind Hyundai, with businesses ranging
from shipbuilding to cars to securities brokerage. In the process,
it used vast amounts of borrowed money that it found increasingly
difficult to repay.
</P>
<P>
   Daewoo's heavy debts are thought to have contributed to South
Korea's economic crisis two years ago, and the company's own
financial problems grew so severe that it nearly fell into
bankruptcy in July, with $52 billion in loans.
</P>
<P>
   Creditors granted a reprieve from the most pressing loans, and
efforts to reorganize the group and sell many of its businesses
have been under way since then. But the process has been extremely
slow.
</P>
<P>
   Oh Ho Gen, executive chairman of the Corporate Restructuring
Committee, the group of domestic creditors overseeing the Daewoo
reorganization, said the resignation offers by Kim and his
subordinates came in response to concern that Daewoo's founder was
manipulating the reorganization process from behind the scenes.
``There's been a great deal of speculation that Chairman Kim is
scheming to come back,'' Oh said. ``It's nothing but a rumor, but
as long as it was perceived as a possibility, it was very difficult
to work out a restructuring for each of these companies.''
</P>
<P>
   South Korea's stock market rose more than 5 percent Monday on
the news, and amid optimism that Daewoo's reorganization might
proceed more smoothly. But some expressed skepticism that Kim would
no longer be involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows new control to start being established,'' said James
Rooney, president of the Templeton Investment Trust Management Co.
``But will the chairman really detach himself? Will he really let
the things necessary actually happen?''
</P>
<P>
   Rooney said while Kim had ``clearly been part of the problem
over the last few years,'' his undisputed leadership made him the
``only one who knows where everything is in the group'' _
information that is crucial to creditors and to the South Korean
government in unraveling the debt problems.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging Kim's knowledge of the inner workings of the vast
conglomerate, Oh at the Corporate Restructuring Committee said that
while the chairman and the company presidents had offered to
resign, creditors might decide to keep them aboard to help with the
overhaul of their businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Oh said Kim was not indispensable. He said creditors had made
substantial progress over the last few months in gaining knowledge
about the depth of Daewoo's financial crisis. ``The myth about
Chairman Kim being the only one who knows everything about Daewoo
is just that, a myth,'' Oh said.
</P>
<P>
   Creditor banks on Tuesday will review debt-rescheduling and
restructuring plans for the Daewoo Motor Co., Daewoo Heavy
Industries, the Daewoo Electronics Co. and the trading and
financing arm of the group, the Daewoo Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign creditors, who are exposed to around $5 billion of debt,
met last week in Japan and refused to freeze the group's debt,
demanding more consultation on the restructuring plans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
