<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW FALLS IN MIXED TRADING AS NASDAQ HITS NEW HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices were mixed Monday as traders and
investors took some profits after the big run-up in market gauges
over the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a consolidation-type day,'' said Bryan Piskorowski, a
market analyst at Prudential Securities. ``There was a little bit
of profit taking, and word of another earthquake in Taiwan got
people a little scared and took a little of the froth out of the
Nasdaq.''
</P>
<P>
   While some semiconductor stocks, including Intel, dropped after
news of the quake flashed across trading screens, the Nasdaq
composite index managed to eke out another record.
</P>
<P>
   At the close, the Nasdaq was up 1.22 points, or 0.04 percent, to
2,967.65. Early in the session, the index flirted with 3,000 and
got as high as 2,997.90.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, big declines in two conglomerates, General Electric
and Tyco International, helped to push the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index down by 8.81 points, or 0.7 percent, to 1,354.12.
Tyco fell 4 9/16, to 35 9/16, and GE dropped 6 1/8, to 129 3/8.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, which included four new stocks
_ Intel, Microsoft, Home Depot and SBC Communications _ for the
first time, slumped 81.35 points, or 0.8 percent, to 10,648.51.
Declines in GE, American Express, down 5 to 149, and DuPont, down 2
3/8 to 62 1/16, were largely responsible for the drop in the
blue-chip index.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the new Dow stocks _ Intel and Microsoft _ fell Monday,
with Intel down 1 7/16, to 76, and Microsoft dipping 3/16, to 92
3/8. SBC Communications and Home Depot gained, with SBC rising 2
1/8, to 53, and Home Depot rising {, to 76\.
</P>
<P>
   Small stocks had a solid session with the Russell 2000 index of
small-company shares gaining 3.18 points, or 0.7 percent, to
431.82.
</P>
<P>
   The pace of business was fairly brisk for a Monday, although
much reduced from the heavy traffic recorded at the end of last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Volume on the New York Stock Exchange was 861 million shares. On
the Nasdaq stock market, 1.07 billion shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said it was likely that business would not pick up
significantly until after the government releases October
employment numbers on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Monday's mixed performance, many participants and
analysts are coming to the view that the weeks and months of
uncertainty that have impeded a broad advance may be coming to an
end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tend to be biased toward being pretty positive,'' said
Michael Molnar, a managing director in sales and trading at Salomon
Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is a lot of risk to the market,'' he said.
``Interest-rate fears are largely overblown, and Y2K is the
ultimate one-time event. As a business issue, people will start to
look past it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebbing concern that interest rates will move higher prodded
Byron Wien, a U.S. equity strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter,
to commit some spare cash from his model stock portfolio to a
handful of financial service stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am still quite cautious on the overall market,'' Wien said
Monday. ``This was a tactical move because I think we are in a
benign interest-rate environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Several factors favor financial stocks at the moment, Wien said,
including the pending elimination of the Glass-Steagall Act, strong
economic growth with minimal inflation, and the sense that a
decision by Federal Reserve Board policy-makers to raise short-term
interest rates on Nov. 16 may be the last such increase for some
time.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, which have had a big run over the last two
weeks, retreated a bit on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Stock Exchange/KBW Bank Index, which had risen
nearly 25 percent in two weeks, fell 10.68 points Monday, or 1.2
percent, to 873.51.
</P>
<P>
   Software companies had a good day, as investors began to focus
on how they might help big companies transfer some of their
business to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle and Siebel Systems, which sell customer-service and
call-center software, were two big winners. Oracle gained 3 5/8, to
51 3/16. And Siebel jumped 7 7/8, to a record 117 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications companies posted mixed results.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint fell 2 5/16, to 72\, after The Financial Times of London
reported that the company faces seven lawsuits stemming from its
agreement to be bought by MCI Worldcom.
</P>
<P>
   But BellSouth, which lost the bidding war for Sprint, rose 2
3/16, to 47 3/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
