r f BC-EVERDREAM-EVERDREAM_S     11-01 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERDREAM-EVERDREAM </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Everdream Takes Hassles Out of Computing  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
A Silicon Valley startup today will become the latest vendor to
announce a plan to relieve small businesses of the risks and
hassles of buying, installing and supporting their own computers.
<P>
   Everdream Corp. will provide up-to-date PCs, an array of
standard software applications, unlimited Internet access and 24/7
tech support for the whole setup at a flat fee of no more than $150
per user per month.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-month-old Mountain View company is part of a growing
trend known in the industry as ``subscription computing.'' System
integrators such as MicroAge already offer hardware, software and
support to large corporate customers on a per-seat basis. In , &LR;  and
in  &LR; recent months two other companies _ CenterBeam, a Santa Clara
startup, and Micronpc, a direct-to-the-customer PC vendor based in
Nampa, Idaho _ have unveiled similar plans for small-to-medium
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But Everdream's service differs from the others in several ways.
</P>
<P>
   First, it's designed specifically for what CEO Gary Griffiths
called ``the low end of the small-business market'' _ companies
with just 10 or so employees. It will even contract with customers
who have only one PC.
</P>
<P>
   Second, instead of competing head-on with local dealers who
currently  &LR; supply PCs for many such businesses, Everdream aims to
enlist them as its front-line marketing arm. The theory is that
dealers will be glad to offload basic tasks such as building and
installing PCs, which don't generate much profit anyway, so they
can concentrate on offering more lucrative value-added services.
</P>
<P>
   As of last week, Everdream had already signed up 45 dealers in
the Bay Area alone, Griffiths said.
</P>
<P>
   For their $150 monthly fee, users will get Everdream-branded PCs
with Intel Pentium III microprocessors, 128 megabytes of memory,
13-gigabyte hard drives, Intel Ethernet network adapters and
17-inch monitors.
</P>
<P>
   That's a generous configuration by today's standards, but it
might not be when Everdream's standard 21/2-year contract expires.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Windows 98, Outlook 2000 and the Small Business
Edition of Microsoft's Office 2000 productivity-software suite will
be preloaded, along with Intuit's Quicken or QuickBooks accounting
software and Symantec's Act! &LR;  contact-management program. Web-based
- &LR; training courses on six major applications are also included.
</P>
<P>
   For Internet access, Everdream customers will use 56K modems or
high-speed digital subscriber lines to connect to Concentric, a
prominent local Internet service provider. At sites with 10 or more
customers, there will be no extra charge for DSL.
</P>
<P>
   Everdream, however, wants potential customers to focus not on
the hardware and software it will install, but on the service and
support it will provide. The company says it will function as a
single point of contact users can count on for live support when
they have a problem or question about any aspect of the system.
</P>
<P>
   To keep support costs down, Everdream is relying on some special
software it will preinstall, including open-source &LR;   &LR; programs that
allow its technicians to chat with the customer and observe or even
control the PC over the Internet. A ``dreambar'' floating above the
standard Windows taskbar will provide one-click access to major
applications and to Everdream's support services, as well as to a
Web portal where it will offer additional small business-oriented
information and services.
</P>
<P>
   The dreambar also has room for the customer's own business logo
and for system-status reports, such as ``backup completed 2:11
a.m.'' The package includes daily backup over the Internet to
www.connected.com, a Web site that specializes in data backup and
disaster recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond all that, Everdream has also developed proprietary,
patent-pending programs it hopes will keep its customers up and
running without extensive hand-holding.
</P>
<P>
   The software divides the PC's hard drive into two partitions,
each with its own copy of the Windows operating system. Users will
be free to install anything they want on one partition, but the
other will contain only software preinstalled by Everdream, which
users won't be able to modify.
</P>
<P>
   When starting up their PCs, users will be able to choose which
part of the disk to launch. When they boot up from Everdream's
partition, software for which the company is seeking a patent will
check the disk and make sure it contains all the files it's
supposed to and no others; if it detects any anomalies, they will
be fixed automatically before they can cause problems, according to
Russell Rive, the company's co-founder and chief technical officer.
That way customers will always have a system they can count on
working, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Smulders, principal analyst at Dataquest, called the
Everdream service ``a very interesting model.'' But he also noted
that the company faces some challenges: Some very small businesses
might consider the service pricey compared to ``free'' or nearly
- &LR; free PCs offered with Internet service contracts, and many local
resellers might be reluctant to share revenues and information
about customers with the company.
</P>
<P>
   He also pointed out that many small businesses require
specialized ``vertical-market'' software that Everdream isn't set
up to provide.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
