<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5794 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-EVOICE-EVOICE_SFCHRON     11-01 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVOICE-EVOICE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 EVoice Offers Nearly Free Phone Mail  &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Looking to save a few bucks a month on voice mail?
<P>
   A Menlo Park company is offering phone message service free to
customers in Northern California who are willing to listen to a 10-
to 15-second advertisement before picking up their messages.
</P>
<P>
   EVoice Inc., which launches its service tomorrow, said it plans
to compete with Pacific Bell by offering its customers free voice
mail on their home or business phones. Pac Bell offers voice mail
for $7.95 per month, plus a one-time installation fee of $19.95.
</P>
<P>
   While a handful of companies _ such as One Box, eFax and
ThinkLink _ have started offering free voice mail service in recent
months, most require that messages be sent to a separate phone
number that's different from a customer's home or work number.
Users of those services check their voice mail via the Internet or
telephone, as do eVoice users.
</P>
<P>
   But eVoice lets customers get the free voice mail on their
existing home or business phone, so users can have a single number
for all messages.
</P>
<P>
   Once they have signed up, users can access their messages via
the phone or by going to eVoice's Web site _ www.evoice.com. To
check their messages on the Web, customers must use a computer with
RealAudio so they can hear the advertisements and phone messages.
</P>
<P>
   However, to find out if they have a message waiting, the eVoice
service is a bit less convenient than traditional voice- &LR;  mail.
</P>
<P>
   Users must either call the eVoice service, go to the Web site,
check their e-mail or be notified via an alphanumeric pager. The
service does not provide users with a flashing light on their phone
or a fast dial tone indicating that a message is waiting.
</P>
<P>
   The company is testing a service that would inform customers of
a waiting message through a ``stutter'' dial tone.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Crair, president of eVoice, said the company plans to roll
out the service nationwide during the next year. For now, however,
it's only available from Fairfield to Watsonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason why customers should have to pay a monthly
fee to get voice mail,'' Crair said. ``Consumers and small
businesses can both save money by using eVoice.''
</P>
<P>
   That is, as long as they're willing to listen to advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Crair said several companies, such as the Fox Family Channel,
have signed up with eVoice to pitch their products to customers. He
said the ads will be targeted to users based on demographic
information eVoice collects about customers when they sign up.
However, no individual information will be given to advertisers,
Crair said.
</P>
<P>
   EVoice's business model is similar to other companies that have
begun giving customers free services for the price of listening to
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like BroadPoint Communications, based in Maryland,
offer free long-distance service to people willing to listen to
recorded ads. Some PC-makers are giving away computers to customers
who don't mind seeing ads on their screens.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Pac Bell said customers who sign up for voice
mail want a quick, efficient service and won't want to listen to
ads.
</P>
<P>
   John Britton, a spokesman for the phone company, said when Pac
Bell broadcast messages over its voice mail service a while back
customers were not happy.
</P>
<P>
   ```People get voice mail with us because they want it to be fast
and save them time. They don't like listening to ads,'' Britton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Britton added that the service lacks some of the functionality
of Pac Bell's voice mail system _ such as the ability to hear a
special dial tone indicating that a message is waiting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
