<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5797 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-LOBBYIST-PLEA-370&AMP;ADD     11-01 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOBBYIST-PLEA-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOBBYISTS PLEAD GUILTY IN CASE LINKED TO HOUSE MEMBER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two lobbyists pleaded guilty Monday to relatively
minor charges arising from a huge construction project in Boston,
thereby ending an investigation that had seemed to threaten the
powerful chairman of the House transportation committee.
</P>
<P>
   Ann M. Eppard of Alexandria, Va., and Vernon A. Clark of
Stateline, Nev., pleaded guilty in federal District Court in Boston
to misdemeanor charges that Ms. Eppard took illegal compensation
from Clark while she was chief of staff to Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Pa.,
who heads the House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Joseph L. Tauro fined each defendant $5,000. He fined
Clark an additional $5,000 on a separate guilty plea to filing
false tax documents related to his lobbying business.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ends the case against Ann Eppard and Vernon Clark, and it
ends the investigation,'' the U.S. Attorney in Boston, Donald K.
Stern, said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Stern said his office had decided to drop an earlier indictment
containing far more serious charges because a recent Supreme Court
decision made it more difficult to prosecute cases involving
government officials who accept favors.
</P>
<P>
   The original indictment, returned in April 1998, accused the
defendants of several felonies involving illegal gratuities and
influence-wielding that could have led to more than 30 years in
prison for each defendant. The indictment was handed down a year
before the Supreme Court case cited by Stern, who asserted that the
earlier charges were appropriate at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's action apparently ended any legal problems for Shuster.
It had been widely reported for months that a federal grand jury in
Boston was looking into whether he had used his influence to help
two campaign contributors in disputes regarding the
multibillion-dollar construction project in the case, a highway and
tunnel project through downtown Boston and under the city's harbor.
</P>
<P>
   The House ethics committee agreed last June to delay an inquiry
into Shuster's activities pending the outcome of the Boston
investigation. It was not apparent Monday evening what effect, if
any, the end of the Boston case would have on the ethics
committee's course.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The 1998 indictment asserted that Ms. Eppard had received more
than $200,000 from 1989 to 1995 by taking advantage of her position
as chief of staff to Shuster to gain favorable settlements for two
businessmen whose property was in the path of the construction
project. Both businessmen were represented by Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Eppard worked for Shuster from 1972, when he was elected to
Congress, until just after the election of 1994, when the
Republicans took over the House, and Shuster gained the influential
chairmanship of the transportation panel.
</P>
<P>
   She then left Shuster's office to form a lobbying firm, which
has prospered by representing transportation interests. She also
continued to raise money for Shuster's campaigns, partly by
soliciting contributions from those interests.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster's critics saw his friendship with Ms. Eppard, her
instant success as a lobbyist and her fund-raising on his behalf as
conflict of interest. But the chairman has consistently denied any
wrongdoing, and Monday night he issued a statement expressing
pleasure that the most serious charges against Ms. Eppard were
dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our trust and respect for Ann remain intact,'' Shuster said.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster's lawyer, Stephen Delinsky of Boston, said that the case
against Ms. Eppard and Clark was weak from the start and that the
result was ``a huge victory for Ann Eppard and Vernon Clark.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark's lawyer, Barry Simon of Washington, could not be reached
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Eppard's lawyer, Richard Egbert of Boston, called his client
``a dedicated person and a very decent human being.'' He said the
misdemeanor to which she pleaded involved technical violations _
accepting meals, lodging and entertainment from Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``She stands vindicated of any willful or intentional violation
of the law,'' he asserted.
</P>
<P>
   Stern disagreed. He said his office had been hobbled by a
Supreme Court ruling last April that simply giving gifts to an
official, without a demonstrated link between the gifts and an
official's actions, did not constitute illegal gratuities.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling involved an investigation into the actions of former
Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy, who had been accused of taking
illegal gifts from a California agricultural cooperative. The
Supreme Court agreed with a federal appeals court, which had
overturned a verdict against the cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   In a wider investigation, Espy was cleared of all charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 2201EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0474 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5798 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG_SFC     11-01 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 MONEYBAG/ARTHUR M. LOUIS  &HT;     Dividends Bedevil Retiree 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: I have a 401(k) plan with Wells Fargo, my former employer. All
the money is invested in a fund consisting entirely of Wells stock.
The quarterly dividends were automatically reinvested in more stock
until recently. Then I was surprised to receive a large check
representing my dividend, along with a note stating that this would
happen every quarter from now on. It said that I can't reinvest the
money in the plan and that the dividends are taxable income, but
that I will not be subject to the 10 percent penalty for early
withdrawal from a tax-deferred plan. I would have preferred to stay
with the tax-deferred dividend reinvestment plan. What are my
options?
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Paula Rowe, a benefits manager with Wells Fargo, says the change
was made to give Wells Fargo a `'very significant'' tax deduction.
</P>
<P>
   Under the tax code, she notes, dividend distributions to
retirees from an employee stock ownership plan _ which your 401(k)
is _ can be deducted from income in determining corporate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   By taking advantage of this deduction, Rowe says, Wells has been
able to set aside more money for matching-dollar contributions to
the plan. It now will match up to 6 percent of salary each year,
compared with 4 percent previously. As a result, future retirees
will wind up with more retirement money.
</P>
<P>
   But that is small consolation for you, because you already are
retired.
</P>
<P>
   Rowe points out that you can shift your assets to another Wells
fund if you are unhappy with the present arrangement. Wells
provides a dozen alternative funds that will reinvest your
dividends rather than send them to you.
</P>
<P>
   The catch is that these are diversified funds _ not invested
strictly in Wells Fargo stock. As a general rule, diversification
is good for investors. But if you think Wells, without reinvested
dividends, is going to perform significantly better than a
diversified portfolio with reinvested dividends, then you will want
to stick with your present fund. Also, bear in mind that you can
reinvest your Wells dividends yourself _ after taxes _ by
purchasing Wells stock from your broker.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; No Escaping Capital Gain
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I am a Canadian citizen. Many years ago, while living in the
United States as a resident alien, I invested in a U.S. mutual
fund. Later, I lived for seven years in Canada. I have returned to
the United States, again as a resident alien, and have just sold my
fund shares, realizing a capital gain. Do I have to pay U.S. income
tax on the portion of the gain that was achieved while I was living
in Canada? Also, does the fact that I lived in Canada affect my
acquisition date for tax purposes?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: The U.S. tax code requires people living in the United States to
pay tax on their income, regardless of the source. The fact that
you moved in and out of the country in years gone by doesn't affect
your liability for taxes on income received while you are living in
this country, according to Internal Revenue Service spokesman Jesse
Weller.
</P>
<P>
   Because you took the capital gain while living here, the gain is
subject to U.S. tax. Whatever portion of the gain accrued during
your stay in Canada is irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   Your acquisition date for tax purposes is simply the date on
which you purchased the shares. Whether you have been to Canada,
Nepal or the moon in the meantime doesn't change that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Retiring on $12 Million
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR; q  &LR;  Q: I am 45 years old and retired. I have no debt and my annual
expenses total $125,000. I am curious to know whether my asset
allocation seems adequate to sustain my lifestyle until age 90.
Here are my assets: a house, appraised at $3 million, with the
mortgage paid off; $5 million in a Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
fund; $2 million in a tax-free fund; $2 million in municipal bonds.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: I am flattered to receive your question. People with a
net worth of $12 million are likely to have dozens of high-powered
financial advisers and brokers camped on their lawn, waiting to
make a pitch. Have you looked out the window lately?
</P>
<P>
   Barring some catastrophe that decimates your holdings, your
fortune should be plenty large enough to tide you over for the next
45 years. Assuming that your annual expenses grow at an inflation
rate of 3 percent per year _ a reasonable expectation, though not
certain _ you would need a total of somewhat more than $11 million
to pay your bills from now to age 90. You already have more than
that _ including your house _ in today's dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Reckoning in tomorrow's dollars, you almost certainly have much
more than you need, because your investments should grow
considerably during the next 45 years.
</P>
<P>
   Consider your S&AMP;P 500 fund alone. If it were to grow at an
average annual rate of 10 percent per year, it would be worth more
than $300 million by 2044.
</P>
<P>
   If you were to withdraw 5 percent of the amount in your S&AMP;P fund
each year to meet expenses _ probably more than you will need _ you
would wind up with more thmillion in the fund at age 90,
again assuming a 10 percent annual growth rate.
</P>
<P>
   So relax and enjoy the next 45 years. Then, relax and enjoy 90
more years. You should be able to afford it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag &LR; sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
