<HEADER>
A5802 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-PREVIEW-LA     11-01 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS EXPECT SLOW START, HOPE FOR FAST FINISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Under Phil Jackson, the Los Angeles Lakers are all
about geometry, so grab a protractor, a compass and maybe the
nearest abacus and try to process this bit of mathematical reality:
The presumably improved Lakers could go .500 in the first month of
the season ... and be happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, they might not post a winning month until sometime after
Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   And if that doesn't sound logical _ the idea a perennially
dominant team can add the winningest coach in NBA history and
expect !ital!mediocrity!off! in the win-loss column _ then you can
empathize with all those contorted faces in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has brought credentials and expectations. But he has
also brought humility to a once-cocky team.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, all eyes are still on the championship. But for
once, the Lakers acknowledge just how much they need to do to get
there. The installation of Jackson's triangle offense has been
shaky, and that alone has forced everyone from Shaquille O'Neal to
Kobe Bryant to accept that becoming champions is a learning
process, and that they are but neophytes.
</P>
<P>
   In the New Laker Paradigm, suddenly ``patience'' is the
buzzword.
</P>
<P>
   And how about this? The Lakers actually admitting they can't
just steamroll through the league. That they might even lose more
games than they'll win in November and December.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be real rocky,'' said Lakers veteran Robert
Horry. ``There's going to be a lot of people booing. But they've
got to realize this offense, a lot of guys don't really have a hold
of it yet, and they're not really comfortable with it. And a lot of
times, you'll be second-guessing yourself and that takes away from
your game, and that carries over to the defensive end. It's just
like a big snowball effect, it just messes up your whole game.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who watched the Lakers go 3-5 in the exhibition season
could see that. For now, there's no reason to expect the first few
weeks of the real season will be much different. But Horry believes
that might be an odd sort of blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be different, but I think it will be good for
us. That way nobody has a lot of expectations put on them. Guys
just go out and play, and there's a lot of teams that are picked
before us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Teams like the Utah Jazz, which the Lakers face in tonight's
opener at Salt Lake City. And the Trail Blazers, who the Lakers
play in Portland on Saturday. In fact, six of their first nine
opponents are probable playoff teams, Houston and Phoenix among
them.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Lakers' challenge of assimilating a new offense,
a new coaching philosophy and a half-dozen new players will be
further exacerbated by the loss of Bryant, out another three weeks
or so because of a broken right hand.
</P>
<P>
   None of this, however, has caused panic in the ranks, and that's
a reflection of the Lakers' new coach. Jackson is intense but
cerebral, and a five-year contract gives him the latitude to be
relaxed about the prospect of losing games. He's also been through
this many times before, even with the Chicago Bulls, even during
their championship seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to struggle to start, and I figure if we're 5-5 in
November, I think we'll be happy at some point when we're at that
level,'' Jackson said. ``The idea is to build momentum during the
course of the season and finish really strong. And that's all that
matters to us, really. Whether we win 40, 50 or 60 games, if you
build the momentum at the end of the season, you're going to have
the type of team you want to go into the playoffs with. It really
doesn't matter beyond that, because you can still win championships
in this league just by making the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixty wins is still Jackson's goal, but a lot of things will
have to go right. O'Neal will have to stay healthy, because he has
no solid backup. An odd collection of less-than-ideal power
forwards will have to suffice until the Lakers can swing a trade,
probably for Detroit's Bison Dele. Glen Rice will have to find a
way to make jump shots in an offense that doesn't seem to suit him.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the rest of the West has only gotten better, and the
Lakers' path to the Finals will be tougher than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Two seasons ago, the Lakers won 61 games, reached the conference
finals and were swept by Utah. Last season, they were swept out of
the semifinals by San Antonio. Now, they start a season without
having added a significant talent, save for the gray-bearded man at
the end of the bench (Jackson, not John Salley).
</P>
<P>
   But they're arguably no better a team than the one embarrassed
by the Spurs. ``Not yet,'' O'Neal conceded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think guys are just still nervous and a little timid about
not making a mistake,'' O'Neal said. ``I think by January we should
be able to tell where we are as a team .... Patience is the best
virtue, but that word's not in my dictionary, so I don't know what
it means. But the reality of the situation is we are going to have
to have patience.''
</P>
<P>
   And if O'Neal sounds a bit more conservative than the
smack-talking ``Superman'' of the past few years, then maybe that's
the first sign of the new coach's influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think I'm going to panic,'' Jackson said. ``And I
think if I don't panic, the players will remain calm. They'll be
very comfortable that we have confidence in what we do, and we know
how to run this and we know how to get it done. If they stay matter
of fact about their business, which is learning the skills and
executing the things that have to be done, they'll do all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, that is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
