<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-TAXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT BRADLEY WOULD EARN FAR LESS THAN CITIZEN BRADLEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Bradley, author, lecturer and consultant,
would have to take a substantial pay cut if the American people
accepted his offer and elected him president.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, the former senator and basketball player, made more
than $5.3 million in 1997 and 1998. His federal income tax returns
for those two years reveal that he wasted little time after his
departure from the Senate in January 1997 in turning his celebrity
and 18 years of political contacts into lucrative speaking and
consulting income.
</P>
<P>
   His 1997 adjusted gross income was $2.7 million, more than half
of it from speeches and consulting fees. He earned $300,000 from
media appearances, book royalties and visiting professorships at
the University of Maryland, Stanford University and Montclair State
University.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Bradley reported gross income of $2.6 million from many
of the same sources, with the addition of $300,000 in consulting
fees from Morgan Guaranty Trust and J.P. Morgan and $131,000 from
the Gartner Group, a Connecticut telecommunications concern.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the information in the tax returns was disclosed in May,
when Bradley filed his personal financial statement with the
Federal Election Commission. But the Bradley campaign made the
complete returns available in the last week in response to
reporters' inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Hauser, Bradley's campaign press spokesman, said he would
allow the returns to speak for themselves. ``We're not interpreting
it,'' Hauser said. Congress last month doubled the president's
salary, to $400,000 a year. The increase takes effect after
President Clinton leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's incom both years included pension payments of about
$90,000 from the National Basketball Association and the U.S.
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and his wife, Ernestine Schlant Bradley, reported
charitable gifts of $39,462 in 1997 and $38,041 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Gifts in 1997 included $500 to Princeton University, Bradley's
alma mater; $1,500 to the public library in Montclair, N.J.; $1,000
to Barrios Unidos, a Latino community group, and $250 to the
National Civic League.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Bradleys contributed $1,000 to the Harlem
Educational Activity Fund ; $1,050 to the Newark Do Something Fund;
$900 to Give Kids the World and $1,025 to Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   In both years, by far the largest recipient of the Bradleys'
largess was the St. James African Methodist Episcopal Church in
Newark, N.J. In 1997, they gave the church 500 shares of
appreciated NationsBank stock worth $31,859; in 1998, they donated
500 shares of BankAmerica stock with a value of $28,016.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
