A5806 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-MEDIA-LIBERTY-LADN     11-01 0349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-LIBERTY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR MEDIA ACCEPTS BUYOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; BURBANK _ Post-production specialist Four Media Co., in a major
boost to its fortunes, announced Monday it has agreed to be
acquired by AT&AMP;T Corp. affiliate Liberty Media for $246.7 million
in stock.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, due to close in the first quarter of 2000, gives Four
Media stockholders a rich payout with shares valued at $12.48 _
more than double their price at the close of trading Friday. The
company's shares jumped $4.6925 to $10.75 on Monday, a 77 percent
gain.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Robert Walston, who founded
Burbank-based Four Media six years ago, said in a statement the
deal will be a catalyst for creation and delivery of new forms of
entertainment and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty, operated by cable mogul John Malone, has been on the
acquisition trail in recent months and agreed last week to buy
hotel pay-per-view programming specialist Ascent Entertainment for
more than $500 million. In late July, Liberty bought two other
major Hollywood ``post'' houses _ Todd-AO and Soundeluxe _ in
separate deals worth a combined $162 million.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty, which had 1998 revenue of $1.56 billion, also has
investments in QVC, Discovery Channel and USA Networks.
</P>
<P>
   Four Media, which grew partly through an aggressive acquisition
strategy of its own with the goal of becoming a ``one-stop shop''
for all post-production services, sold 51 percent of itself earlier
this year in an $80 million deal worth $7.85 a share to Wall Street
investment firm Warburg Pincus. Walston, Warburg Pincus and Fleming
Asset Management _ owners of 70 percent of Four Media's shares _
have endorsed the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Four Media, which has more than 1,300 employees, also reported
Monday a loss of $2 million for its fourth quarter ended Aug. 1 due
to the expense of a stock offering. Cash flow was off 4.2 percent
to $8.1 million compared with the 1998 period while revenues rose
40.7 percent to $48 million.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
