<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5809 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-FRONTROW-NYT &LR;      11-01 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRONTROW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GINIA BELLAFANTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Fashion Ads in National Geographic &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Flip through the November issue of National Geographic _ past
the images of a posthurricane Tegucigalpa, Honduras; a militia
march in Iraq; a mating dance of the Karo people of Ethiopia _ and
you will see a picture of a woman who seems as out of place in the
pages of this publication as she might at a Weight Watchers
meeting. She is the British model Stella Tennant, and she is
featured in an ad for Helmut Lang.
</P>
<P>
   Lang, who considers National Geographic his favorite
publication, has never taken a conventional approach to
advertising. When he opened his SoHo store in 1997, he bought ads
on the top of taxicabs, that most populist of venues. And he
prefers to buy ad pages in magazines like Vibe and Artforum rather
than Harper's Bazaar or Vogue. He has favored Robert Mapplethorpe
images in his campaigns rather than pictures of his clothes. Now,
Lang is the first fashion advertiser to appear in the U.S. edition
of National Geographic, which typically runs ads for cars and
flood-relief groups and might not attract more chic-minded factions
of the citizenry.
</P>
<P>
   One could argue that the sheer size of National Geographic's
readership _ there are eight million subscribers worldwide _ means
that among the many who want to read about African marriage
rituals, there must also be some who see the logic of spending
$1,200 on a simple wool coat. Richard Kirshenbaum, a co-founder of
the ad agency Kirshenbaum Bond &AMP; Partners, which does not handle
Lang's account, says National Geographic readers are an educated,
well-traveled lot who might easily fall into Lang's
``psychographic.'' Reaching them comes at no small cost, though. A
page in the magazine costs about $170,000, about four times what it
might be in Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``With National Geographic the great thing about it is it's so
not fashion,'' said Jonny Lichtenstein, Lang's advertising
director. Lichtenstein, who said there will be Lang ads in National
Geographic every month through 2000, enjoys the fact that Lang ads
stand out more there than they might otherwise. In a magazine
replete with fashion ads, ``you can get lost,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ex-Barneys Chief Is Now at Vanity Fair &LR;
</P>
<P>
   While readers may not be seeing an ad for Barneys New York in
National Geographic anytime soon, they might soon be feeling,
however faintly, the influence of its former chief, Gene Pressman,
in the pages of another magazine, Vanity Fair.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Vanity Fair named Pressman, who was the store's
co-chief executive until it filed for bankruptcy in 1996, a
contributing editor of the magazine. Like other celebrities and
quasi-celebrities on mastheads _ Shoshanna Lonstein at
Cosmopolitan, Gayfryd Steinberg at Vogue _ Pressman will not be
expected to go about town with a steno pad in search of scoops.
Instead, he will apparently share his thoughts on fashion and
society with the magazine's editors. ``I could be the eyes and ears
culturally for the magazine,'' he said. ``They have other people to
do that, too, obviously, but I can contribute. Magazines are like
think tanks.'' He added, ``A lot of it will be impromptu _ that's
how ideas are generated.''
</P>
<P>
   Graydon Carter, Vanity Fair's editor, said that he and Pressman
had been friends until they had a falling out over a critical story
that Vanity Fair ran about the financial troubles of Barneys. Then
a few years ago, they ran into each other at a party for Steven T.
Florio, Conde Nast's chief executive, and reconnected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire his eye, talent and passion,'' Carter said. ``Why not
bring him to the magazine and try him for a year?'' He added after
a pause, ``He's up on the Internet and all its possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Contributors like Pressman are ``good door openers,'' Carter
said. ``A lot of a magazine's success depends on access.'' But it
is unclear what kind of access Pressman can provide that other
nonwriting contributors cannot, like Diane Von Furstenberg, Anne
McNally and Rupert Everett. Still, Pressman, appears to have a good
deal of time on his hands with which to do some door opening.
Although he has a consulting contract with Barneys, he described
his relationship with the current management of the store, founded
by his grandfather, as ``mellow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been asked to do too much, and I haven't been doing
any complaining,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 2206EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
