<SLUG> BC-BKN-SEASON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA BEGINS A TRANSITION FROM PHYSICAL TO UP-TEMPO PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After various New York Knicks had been whistled for
holding, grabbing and chucking with their forearms, the referees
conducting a clinic on the new rules during training camp last
month asked whether the players had any more questions regarding
what the league expected of them from now on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we should be wearing tutus out there,'' one player said.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999-2000 National Basketball Association opens Tuesday at
about the same time the door on aggressive physical play is
closing.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner David Stern wants and needs a more balletic style
of play and more points to be scored to sell his product _ and
fewer bullies to depress television ratings.
</P>
<P>
   From rule changes to personnel shake-ups, the league is the
middle of a transformation. Losing ground is the plodding
half-court style, which is being replaced by an up-tempo,
end-to-end running game. And it is not just the Sacramento Kings
and the nouveau Knicks. The fast break, dormant for much of the
1990s, is experiencing a sudden rejuvenation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way everyone wants us to play, so I'll guess we'll
just have to deal with it,'' said Coach Pat Riley of the Heat,
whose brutish teams in New York and Miami were annually accused of
bringing down the league's quality of play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not who we are,'' Riley said. ``It's not our identity.
And it will take us a while to adjust. But maybe it will be good
for the league.''
</P>
<P>
   After a decade of declining scores and field-goal percentages,
and dramatically improved defense, something had to change. Michael
Jordan's former team, the Chicago Bulls, averaged a paltry 81.9
points a game last season, fewest in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Nine teams averaged fewer than 90 points a game, including the
Knicks and the Heat. Sacramento was the lone NBA team to average
more than 100 points. It is no coincidence that a former almost
invisible NBA outpost has become must-see television. The colorful
Kings of Jason Williams and Chris Webber have already secured 20
national television appearances, including nine on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining the network's decision-making process, Dick
Ebersol, NBC Sports' president, recalled sitting up late one night
in May and watching a playoff game on Turner Sports between the
upstart Kings and the Utah Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``College or pro, it was the most extraordinary basketball game
I'd seen all year,'' Ebersol said of Utah's last-second victory in
Game 4. ``It was a game we didn't even televise. People were making
baskets, scoring on both ends. The offense was startling. That game
was one of the reasons we made some of the scheduling decisions we
made.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the defending champion San Antonio Spurs, Allen
Iverson and the Philadelphia 76ers; Shaquille O'Neal, Kobe Bryant
and the Los Angeles Lakers, and Allan Houston, Latrell Sprewell and
the Knicks will be featured a maximum 11 times on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's what America wants to see,'' the Kings'
Williams said recently. ``We run. We have fun. We push it up the
court. Growing up, that's what attracted people to the game. If we
have anything to do with getting back to that, then that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   With many members of the original Dream Team closer to
retirement than their primes _ Charles Barkley, Patrick Ewing,
Scottie Pippen, John Stockton and Karl Malone among them _ it
appears the league and the network have made a conscious decision
to showcase rising young stars rather than fading, aging icons. The
Kings did not make an appearance on NBC during the regular season
in the nine previous years of the network's contract with the
league. An advertising campaign titled ``It's Our Turn Now'' aired
during the World Series, featuring Iverson and Williams. Bryant and
Kevin Garnett of Minnesota have also filmed commercial spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will always say a game that is centered at the very least on
offense as much it is defense makes for much better TV fare,''
Ebersol said. ``There's no question we cherish a wide-open game and
we believe in a lot of these young players.''
</P>
<P>
   After Magic Johnson and Larry Bird retired, Jordan's
transcendent popularity masked many of the league's quality-of-play
problems. Now that Jordan has been gone from the game since the
abbreviated season that began last January, the league seems to
understand the need to return to more free-flowing, fluid offenses
to increase fan interest. It is a marriage of simple economics and
aesthetically pleasing play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure it's right to say we've acted in concert or that
the game is going to dramatically change,'' Stern said. ``The
network's decisions are based on research and judgment. And our
owners have decided they'd like to return a less physical, more
open game.''
</P>
<P>
   The rule changes involving excessive contact were by far the
greatest indicator that the game had become too physical. But not
everyone is in agreement that they will help the quality of the
game.
   ``I'm not so sure that it's going to be the answer,'' said
Lakers Coach Phil Jackson, who also decried the adding of a timeout
in the second period, believing it will impede the flow of a game.
``We hope it is because we like to see more cutting and movement on
the floor, less physical holding, contact of bodies and physical
play being the dominant factor, rather than speed and mobility.
Some of the rules have been enforced very well. Some haven't
because it's a very difficult thing for the referees to make that
adjustment.''
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Petrie, the general manager of the Kings, was named
executive of the year last season by his peers for the foresight to
trade for Webber, draft Williams and acquire the offensive-minded
center, Vlade Divac. Putting together a team of entertaining
passers and scorers, Petrie seemed to also see the changing
landscape of a league literally in transition. ``The classic
example of the running game flourishing would be the Knicks of the
early 1970's,'' Petrie said recently. ``They had five or six really
skilled players, and each had the ability to do more than just one
thing. Now we have all these specialists, and suddenly the game has
drifted.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I can't say I or anybody else went out and decided
to build a running team. But I knew early on we were going to be
able to play up-tempo. Do I think the rule changes and getting back
to running are good for the game? Definitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the rules were called, it was hard to cut without
someone giving you a forearm shiver every time. I'm for anything
that allows more skill, more natural basketball ability than just
raw physical strength.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 2213EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0490 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5822 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MTV-MGM-AD-COLUMN-NYT     11-01 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MTV-MGM-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD COLUMN: MTV AND MGM JOIN IN 100-HOUR JAMES BOND PROMOTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the next three weeks, MTV viewers might feel as if they
have stumbled into one of those James Bond movie marathons _ only
this one will be celebrating just one film.
</P>
<P>
   ``The World Is Not Enough,'' the latest James Bond movie, will
be the centerpiece of as many as 100 hours of programming on MTV
channels worldwide. Among other things, there will be multiple
showings of the music video of the movie's theme song; a special on
the making of the video, which includes scenes from the movie; and
a contest to give away a $200,000 BMW featured in the movie, to be
conducted on MTV's highest-rated program.
</P>
<P>
   But what will not be apparent to MTV viewers is that much of the
programming will be part of a financially based arrangement between
MTV, a unit of Viacom Inc., and the studio behind the film,
Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer.
</P>
<P>
   The two entertainment companies have joined in a huge promotion
aimed at building a more youthful following for a Bond movie
franchise old enough to be the father of most MTV viewers. The
arrangement will not be overtly disclosed, even on MTV programs
like a special devoted exclusively to the movie that includes
interviews with its stars, whose production costs are paid for,
wholly or in part, by MGM.
</P>
<P>
   MTV and studio executives said that the Bond promotion, like
many other MTV movie promotions in recent years, is a hybrid: one
part programming maneuver, intended to appeal to the channel's
film-infatuated audience, and one part elaborately conceived and
externally financed promotional announcement _ with elements of
what is otherwise known in television as an infomercial.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the stakes are particularly high. MTV is calling
the campaign, pointing toward the opening on Nov. 19 of ``The World
Is Not Enough,'' the first global movie promotion. MGM, which is
controlled by the Tracinda Corp., has taken the unusual step of
releasing the film throughout the world within the same two-week
window and MTV, which has more viewers than ever before, is singing
the movie's praises in music videos and special programs on
affiliates reaching more than 300 million homes around the world.
</P>
<P>
   For MGM, the deal adds up to worldwide access to MTV's audience
of teenagers and college students. For MTV, it adds up to another
lucrative payday from its best customers, the movie studios.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as we are in television,'' said John Shea, a senior
MTV executive, ``we are also in business. To say anything else
would be naive. This campaign is an understanding between smart
marketing people.''
</P>
<P>
   The very title of Shea's job suggests how business
considerations go hand in hand with programming at the channel. He
is the senior vice president of franchise and sponsor development
for MTV.
</P>
<P>
   Shea described the process of promoting films as a
one-hand-washing-another kind of arrangement. He said that MTV had
a specific ``movie team'' that meets each week to assess upcoming
releases and identify ones likely to appeal to its young audience.
Some recent examples included ``Austin Powers,'' ``The Waterboy''
and both Scream movies.
</P>
<P>
   Once a film is deemed a likely favorite for MTV viewers, MTV
executives approach the studio that is distributing it about
participating in a promotion. If the studio agrees, it may be asked
to put up money to produce a ``movie special'' for the channel,
perhaps to supply the prizes for a giveaway and often to increase
its purchase of advertising time on MTV.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a studio deems us a promotional partner,'' Shea said,
``they also ought to deem us an appropriate media-buy partner.''
The studios, he said, were all already in business with MTV because
of the amount of advertising money they committed to the channel
before every TV season _ the so-called upfront market.
</P>
<P>
   Van Toffler, the general manager of MTV, said that the channel's
negotiations with movie studios as advertisers were no different
from the negotiations any network would hold with clients.
</P>
<P>
   But some studio executives complain that MTV's standing in the
youth market gives it enough leverage to let it to set a specific
figure that a studio must spend in advertising before any promotion
deal can be closed. One executive, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said that MTV was far from alone in this practice _ that
it had become widespread on cable television channels and even some
broadcast networks _ but that MTV was the most aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   A senior executive with another studio described MTV movie
promotions as ``basically paid political advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   This executive called MTV ``a very efficient monopoly'' on
youthful viewers and said of the channel's demands on advertisers
to go along with the promotions, ``They drive a hard bargain and it
doesn't matter how big you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea did not agree. ``It's not accurate to say there is a quid
pro quo'' for the studios to buy more advertising, he said.
``That's putting the cart before the horse.''
</P>
<P>
   First and foremost, he said, MTV's movie team, which includes
representatives of several departments _ advertising and promotion,
programming and even news _ must decide if the film will appeal to
the channel's viewers.
</P>
<P>
   And Toffler disputed the idea that MTV creates infomercials for
movies. ``The studios don't pay the whole costs of movie
specials,'' he said. ``We take on the decision to produce a
program. It's not as if they're paying us for air time.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the Bond project, Toffler was supported by Gerry Rich,
the president of worldwide marketing for MGM, who said his studio
had not been asked to increase its advertising budget despite the
elaborate promotion. He also said that while MGM had contributed
cash to some of the productions connected to the promotion, ``It
has been a harmonious arrangement; it felt balanced.''
</P>
<P>
   In finding a welcome at MTV, Shea said, the Bond film was aided
by its producers' decision to recruit the rock band Garbage to sing
its title song _ and to make the video that goes with it.
</P>
<P>
   MTV also came up with the idea of tying the film promotion to
its production of the MTV Europe Music Awards, the European version
of MTV's Video Music Awards. That event is set for Nov. 11 in
Dublin, and Pierce Brosnan, the current James Bond, and Denise
Richards, his co-star in ``The World Is Not Enough,'' will appear
as presenters.
</P>
<P>
   Before the show, MTV will give away one of the BMWs that Brosnan
drives in the film. Another will be given away by Ms. Richards on
``Total Request Live,'' a daily MTV show.
</P>
<P>
   Toffler contended that no promotion decision, whether for
advertising money or money for production, was ever made by MTV's
programming department. ``I don't know what our ad guys say when
they talk to the studios,'' he said, ``but none of that impacts any
programming decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited a number of independent films like ``The Blair Witch
Project'' and ``Go,'' which he said MTV had backed with programs
and other forms of coverage even though their production companies
could not afford much, if any, advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a slave to our audience,'' Toffler said. ``What our
audience is desirous of seeing is our priority.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
