<HEADLINE>
BUSH SLIGHTLY HURT DURING JOG WHEN A TRUCK SPILLS DEBRIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK BRUNI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas was slightly
injured while jogging in Austin, Texas, Monday when a truck trailer
overturned, scattering debris across a foot path, and Bush was
forced to dive out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Law-enforcement authorities and officials with the Bush campaign
said Bush, 53, the leading contender for the Republican
presidential nomination, suffered only minor scrapes and bruises to
his right leg and hip.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving medical treatment from paramedics on the scene,
he was able to proceed with his plans to fly to New Hampshire,
where he arrived Monday night and will campaign for the next two
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an old baseball term called a strawberry,'' Bush said
in a statement released by his campaign Monday night. ``You get a
strawberry when you slide hard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a strawberry on my hip and on my leg, but if I needed
to, I could go out now and run three miles,'' he said. ``The only
thing retarding that is the fact that I'm getting a little older
and I don't want to do that twice in one day.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was relieved to hear that Roscoe Hughey, a
bodyguard who had been riding behind him on a bicycle, was released
from the hospital Monday night. Hughey, 39, had been partly buried
in debris, mostly pieces of wood and concrete, that pressed hard
into his left side, law-enforcement officials said. But hospital
tests showed that he had not sustained any broken bones or serious
internal injuries, Bush's aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Law-enforcement officials said it was unclear what had caused
the trailer to overturn. Both they and Bush's aides said there was
no indication that the driver of the truck was singling out Bush or
was guilty of any criminal wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Bush usually runs at least 15 miles a week, in 3- or 4-mile
increments. When he is home in Austin, he often runs downtown along
Town Lake.
</P>
<P>
   That is where he was exercising shortly after noon Monday, his
aides said. The section of the path on which he was running abuts a
busy street, and aides said his fleeting visual impression was that
the truck and trailer were veering off the street and heading for
him. He hurled himself off the path before the debris tumbled
across it, hitting Hughey.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
