<SLUG> BC-BBO-MANAGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAYLOR NAMED MANAGER OF CHICAGO CUBS AND MANUEL GOES TO CLEVELAND
INDIANS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the day that Don Baylor rejoined the managerial
ranks from which he was inexplicably evicted a year ago, other
black and Latino candidates did not fare so well Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Chambliss and Cito Gaston were shut out in Cleveland,
where the Indians named Charlie Manuel as their new manager, and
Bob Watson and Omar Minaya finished as also-rans in Disney Land,
where the Anaheim Angels hired Bill Stoneman as their general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the first day that Leonard Coleman, the
highest-ranking black executive in baseball history, was no longer
president of the National League. With Major League Baseball moving
all league functions into the central office, Coleman resigned,
effective the end of October.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor, whom the Colorado Rockies fired as manager last year
only to have the owner subsequently acknowledge that the move was a
mistake, was named manager of the Chicago Cubs. He accepted a
four-year contract for $5.2 million dollars. The appointment had
been expected, even though Baylor was the person most sought by
clubs seeking a manager.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor served this season as the Atlanta Braves' hitting coach.
He rejected offers from the Angels (four years, $4.9 million) and
the Milwaukee Brewers (four years, $5.2 million). The Baltimore
Orioles received permission to talk to him, but never followed up.
</P>
<P>
   In becoming the Cubs' 46th manager and the first who is a member
of a minority group, Baylor said he liked the city, its fans and
the challenge presented by a team that has not won a World Series
since 1908.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody would love to be in Joe Torre's shoes,'' Baylor said
by telephone from Chicago, referring to the Yankees' manager.
``That doesn't happen. But with your second chance to manage, the
history of this club, the fans they have, they have a tremendous
following. They have to feel they want to win sometimes. That's
what we're going to try to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor's appointment restores to four the number of black and
Latino managers in the majors. Jerry Manuel of the White Sox,
Felipe Alou of Montreal and Dusty Baker of San Francisco are the
others. The Brewers are expected to raise the total to five when
they select their manager; the candidates are said to be Gaston,
Chambliss, Willie Randolph and Davey Lopes.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Manuel, the Indians' hitting coach, seemed to be that
club's choice as manager ever since Mike Hargrove was fired last
month for failing to win a World Series during the Indians'
five-year run as American League Central champions. Hargrove may
wind up managing the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday an Indians official indicated that none of the other
candidates had given the club reason not to hire Manuel, who in his
sixth season as hitting coach this year saw the Indians score the
most runs of any team in half a century. The Indians also
interviewed Gaston, who managed Toronto to World Series
championships in 1992 and 1993; Chambliss, the Yankees' hitting
coach, and Jim Riggleman, Baylor's predecessor as the Cubs'
manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a true baseball guy like Charlie is the right move and
the right fit,'' John Hart, the Indians' general manager, said.
``Today's announcement is going to be a big hit in our clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   The hiring of Baylor and Manuel left the Orioles and the Angels
seeking managers. The Orioles also do not have a general manager.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' hiring of Stoneman left the major leagues with 29
white general managers, including four hired recently. No black or
Latino executive has held that position since Watson resigned as
the Yankees' general manager two seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   Watson appeared to be a strong candidate for the Angels' job
after they interviewed him three times. The third interview came
last week, after their prospective hiring of Stoneman, the Montreal
Expos' vice president for baseball operations for 15 years,
appeared to have fallen through.
</P>
<P>
   According to an executive of another club, Stoneman was the
choice of Tony Tavares, the Angels' president, but Michael Eisner,
head of the Walt Disney Company, was not convinced after meeting
with Stoneman, whose role with the Expos had been largely
financial. The Angels then held additional interviews with Watson,
Minaya and Jim Duquette of the Mets and Dan Evans of the White Sox.
Watson declined to comment on the Angels' decision, but he was
clearly not happy that he had been interviewed three times and was
still not hired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want some time to pass before I go out and say how I really
feel about all this,'' he said by telephone from his home in
Houston. ``I don't want it to be construed as sour grapes. I'm
going to wait until I can really collect all my thoughts and also
see how the rest of this hiring process goes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
