<HEADLINE>
2 SYRACUSE PLAYERS REMAIN HOSPITALIZED AFTER STABBINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two Syracuse University football players and another man
remained hospitalized Monday with stab wounds following a melee
outside a downtown Syracuse bar early Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Five people were injured in what the police say they believe
started as a verbal altercation inside the bar, Sadie's Place, and
spilled onto the sidewalk. Three players and two of their friends
were set upon by an armed group of six or more men, the police
said.
</P>
<P>
   David Byrd, a starting cornerback for the Orangemen was upgraded
from critical to serious condition late Monday, but Myles Thomas of
Boston, a friend of one of the players, remained in critical
condition in the intensive care unit at University Hospital. Byrd,
who had surgery Sunday, was stabbed twice in the back, twice in the
neck and once in the leg. Thomas was stabbed in the chest.
</P>
<P>
   Giovanni DeLoatch, a backup tackle who was stabbed behind the
right ear, in the right thigh and several times in the back, was in
good condition at St. Joseph's Hospital. Maynard Pettijohn, a
starting defensive end who was stabbed in the head and in the ear,
was treated at St. Joseph's and released, and Daniel Moore of
Boston, a friend of one of the players, was treated for a stab
wound to the back and was released from St. Joseph's.
</P>
<P>
   Sadie's Place has a history of violent disturbances, including
fights, assaults, stabbings and shootings, said Sgt. David Sackett,
a spokesman for the Syracuse police. The bar is about two miles
from the campus and is owned by the wife of an Onondaga County
sheriff's deputy.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released by the university's athletic department,
Coach Paul Pasqualoni said the players had been warned about going
to places like Sadie's, although he did not say that it had been
singled out.
</P>
<P>
   The police arrested two Syracuse men on Sunday night and said
they planned to arrest more in connection with the stabbings,
Sackett said. Trequill Stackhouse and Cheiron Thomas, both 22, were
charged with assault, gang assault and criminal possession of a
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Sackett said a bouncer cleared the bar because he smelled
marijuana and feared a fight was about to break out. He said
witnesses told the police that 40 to 60 people were milling outside
the bar and that 6 or more men, some armed with knives, attacked
the players and their friends. Two knives were recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't know what precipitated the fight, but when it
all comes out we believe it will show that the players were singled
out,'' Sackett said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 2227EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0500 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5834 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-LACHAPELLE-FASHION-NY     11-01 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LACHAPELLE-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN INTERVIEW IS NOW OVER 30 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CATHY HORYN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The last thing the photographer David LaChapelle
wanted to be associated with was a party where, as he put it,
``Miuccia Prada would be staring at Helmut Lang.'' Those two were
indeed at Interview magazine's 30th anniversary party last Thursday
night at the Kit Kat Club. And so were Calvin Klein, Fran Lebowitz,
Barry Diller, Diane Von Furstenberg, Jon Bon Jovi, Tom Ford, Puff
Daddy and Elizabeth Hurley.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody was being stared at. Unless you counted the platinum
blonde who was wandering naked through the room looking as though
she had just slipped out of Marilyn Monroe's ``Happy Birthday''
dress. Or Lil' Kim, the diminutive rapper, who performed wearing
nothing more than a slinky top made of some gold chains and a pair
of pink satin pants that had only one leg.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the place was so crowded, with people filling the
balcony and the wings, that Ms. Hurley, for one, could never be
sure what the rap star was wearing. ``I could only see her from the
waist up, and she looked fabulous,'' she said, standing next to
Elton John, who also performed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite hints of decadence, hardly any of the usual crew of
guests seemed shocked when they arrived at the party, around 10:45
p.m., after a dinner given by Ingrid Sischy, Interview's editor in
chief, and Sandy Brant, its publisher. And while somebody had gone
to a lot of trouble to decorate 2,000 cupcakes with the magazine's
logo and to arrange for Amanda LaPore, the blonde, to pop naked out
of a big cake, LaChapelle was clearly the evening's presiding
genius.
</P>
<P>
   Since the party was also in his honor, he transformed the club
into ``Hotel LaChapelle,'' after his new book of photographs, being
published by Bulfinch Press. There were rows of twin beds on the
main floor, and night stands with Bibles and alarm clocks. As the
guests arrived, topless bell boys and bell girls wearing pasties,
suspenders and caps with chin straps served drinks. Andre Leon
Talley, Vogue's editor at large, flopped down on a bed next to Ms.
Lebowitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pastiche'' was Talley's pronouncement.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what she thought of the situation _ the beds, the go-go
dancers gyrating on the stage in white cotton underpants and boots
_ Ms. Lebowitz shook her head. ``I don't think it's really a
thinking situation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   LaChapelle, whose goggle-like glasses and floral-print shirt
gave him the appearance of an ecstatic tropical insect, said he
wanted the party to evoke what he called ``the energy of Studio
54.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't really, but there were moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted a mix,'' he said. ``So there are skateboarders
and Sean Puffy Combs. You've got Willem Dafoe and a transsexual
prostitute I know standing next to some women in a suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, it was Lil' Kim, more than the hysterical
decorations or the self-conscious attempts to be shocking, who
transformed the evening. She is the real thing, an invention, a
performer whose body and obvious lack of inhibition make you feel
she is totally in control of the stage. She sang with a couple of
young men she introduced as her ``little brothers,'' though they
didn't look very little.
</P>
<P>
   ``She uses her sexuality in a really aggressive way in her
music, but when you meet her she's disarmingly sweet, a living
Kewpie doll,'' said LaChapelle, who recently photographed Lil' Kim
naked except for some logos (``We were painting them right on her
skin,'' he said, ``like she was an expensive Louis Vuitton bag'').
</P>
<P>
   After her performance, Talley took Ms. Lebowitz backstage to
meet her. Lil' Kim was in a tiny dressing room with a couple of
friends, including Iman, the model who is married to David Bowie,
and Nija Battle, who designs furs for Lil' Kim and other rap
artists. There were a lot of squeals of ``No, you're beautiful!''
and ``Honey!'' Lil' Kim was saying she had her wardrobe designed by
someone named Misha or Melissa, when another person dropped by and
her little voice was drowned out by more squeals.
</P>
<P>
   LaChapelle came in and plopped down next to Lil' Kim. Someone
asked him if it was true he had auditioned all the go-go dancers.
``Oh, yeah,'' he said. ``They're professional go-go dancers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lebowitz shot him a look and said, ``They thought they were
going to clerk for Ruth Bader Ginsburg.''
</P>
<P>
   As someone who experienced enough of the so-called pop life _
the clubs, the underground happenings, the celebrities extending as
far as the limos stretch _ to qualify as a kind of senior citizen
of camp (even though she is only 49), Ms. Lebowitz had an
interesting take on things.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I like in this popular culture is the music,''
she said, lighting a cigarette. ``It's the only thing wholly
invented by these people. It's not taken from somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   She didn't think the party atmosphere had anything in common
with the club scene in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is nothing like it, nothing at all,'' she said, adding,
``Young people always come up to me and say, `Oh, I want to be like
you.' I don't want to be like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lebowitz frowned and went on: ``They always ask me what
restaurant I went to when I was their age. We didn't eat. We didn't
have any money. That's a difference _ kids have money now. I don't
think I ate dinner the first 12 years I was in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Lil' Kim was ready to go back out in the crowd and mingle. She
put on a white coat, seemed to roll around in it a moment, and left
surrounded by a posse of bodyguards. As Ms. Battle headed out
behind her, she was asked about Misha or Melissa, the stylist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Misa,'' she said. ``M-I-S-A.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lebowitz smiled mildly. ``You know,'' she said, ``like Misa
Sert.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course,  &UR; that &LR;  muse's name was Misia _ but what's an ``i''
among all these good friends?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
