<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICERS WHO KILLED HAMMER-WIELDING MAN WON'T FACE CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Brooklyn grand jury has decided not to bring any
charges against four police officers involved in the fatal shooting
of a mentally disturbed, hammer-wielding man, District Attorney
Charles J. Hynes announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The killing of Gidone Busch on Aug. 30 brought hundreds of
Hasidic protesters to the streets of the heavily Orthodox Borough
Park neighborhood and attracted widespread attention because of the
stark differences between Police Commissioner Howard Safir's first
description of what happened and the accounts of witnesses on the
street.
</P>
<P>
   Before releasing the findings, Hynes and other prosecutors met
with Busch's family for more than two hours Monday morning to
outline the results of the investigation for them.
</P>
<P>
   In an often emotional encounter, participants on both sides
said, the prosecutors presented a narrative sharply at odds with
Safir's original version. But the prosecutors concluded that, in
legal terms, the officers were justified in using deadly force
against Busch because they had a ``reasonable belief'' that he was
a threat to them and others. Busch's relatives and supporters, on
the other hand, remained bitterly critical of the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed,'' Busch's mother, Doris Busch-Boskey,
said later. ``I just hope we can learn from this, in how they
handle emotionally disturbed persons.''
</P>
<P>
   At a City Hall news conference the morning after the shooting,
flanked by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and a hastily assembled row of
Jewish community leaders, Safir said the police opened fire only as
Busch was beating a fallen police sergeant with a hammer, putting
the officer's life in danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seven independent witnesses who confirm everything I
am saying, nonpolice witnesses,'' Safir said that morning, ``and
each of those witnesses says at this point as he continued to hit
the sergeant with the claw hammer, the police fired 12 shots.''
</P>
<P>
   But according to participants on both sides of Monday's meeting,
the prosecutors gave a different account, based on the grand jury's
findings. Citing both police and civilian witnesses, they said
Busch was shot after he broke free of the police effort to contain
him. He ran up a narrow stairway from his basement apartment,
struck Sgt. Terrence O'Brien with his hammer, then rushed past the
officers.
</P>
<P>
   He stood on the sidewalk, they said, with the hammer raised over
his head as the six officers who responded to radio calls stood,
all on their feet, guns drawn, in a rough semicircle around him.
</P>
<P>
   They shouted at him _ one ``almost pleading,'' a law enforcement
official said _ to drop the hammer. There was a distinct single
shot, closely followed by a volley. Busch fell dead.
</P>
<P>
   This account is essentially the same as that in an article in
The New York Times last month that reconstructed the shooting from
accounts of witnesses and investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Although there had been speculation that the grand jury, which
voted on Thursday, might issue a report critical of police training
and tactics for dealing with emotionally disturbed persons, Hynes
said, ``That's a kind of second-guessing I don't want to engage
in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony of this case is that they followed every step of the
procedures,'' the district attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, the officers called for the specially
trained and equipped Emergency Services Unit.
</P>
<P>
   A few new details emerged Monday _ including a previously
undisclosed, frantic second radio call for the Emergency Services
Unit, underscoring both the strangeness of the fatal events and the
speed with which they unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   Busch first appeared holding not a hammer, but a flute,
according to Monday's account. Percy Freeman, a homeless man with
whom the prosecutors said Busch had been smoking marijuana, had
come up the stairs to tell the police, ``Don't worry about the
hammer; it's a religious object,'' when the officers wrestled him
to the ground to handcuff him.
</P>
<P>
   The newly disclosed radio calls indicated that only seven
seconds elapsed from the time Busch bolted past the police and his
death. At 6:48:20 that night, Sgt. Joseph Memoly, arriving on the
scene as Busch was breaking free, put in a second call for the
emergency unit ``forthwith'' _ police argot for as fast as
possible. At 6:48:27, O'Brien radioed: ``Perp down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
