<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5844 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-PARK-RESORTS-1STLD-WR     11-01 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARK-RESORTS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-795(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLES ERUPT OVER PRIVATE LAND IN NATIONAL PARKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Inserts 3 grafs, beginning ``Gettysburg ...'')  
 (ATTN: Colo., Md., Mont., Alaska, Pa., Utah, Ariz.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAGOSA SPRINGS, Colo. _ Nestled in the San Juan National Forest
in southwestern Colorado is a small rectangle of mountains and a
valley that straddles the meandering East Fork of the San Juan
River.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the rectangle's 2,780 acres are indistinguishable from
the surrounding landscape, a dream scene of 1.8 million pristine
acres at the Continental Divide, where the only sounds are the
water rushing over rocks, the wind and the occasional cry of birds
high overhead.
</P>
<P>
   But that is about to change.
</P>
<P>
   Like more than 50 million other acres inside the United States'
national parks and forests, only a fraction of the total, the
rectangle of acreage is privately owned. It was one of thousands of
land grants made available, in some cases almost 140 years ago, for
homesteading, mining operations and railroads.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the private tracts remain undeveloped, owners
of the rectangle here are planning to build a members-only resort
on 200 acres that they call Piano Creek Ranch, where membership
shares cost $385,000 to $535,000.
</P>
<P>
   Designed to accommodate 395 families, the resort would include
spacious houses, lodges, a golf course and an equestrian center. A
ski area would be built on another part of the rectangle. Already,
175 families have signed up, and ground breaking is scheduled for
next June, with completion planned in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Preservationists say developments like Piano Creek represent
only the beginning of a major problem throughout federal lands. It
is ``the undiscovered crisis,'' says the National Park Trust, a
nonprofit group that buys land and donates it to the park system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the results of the booming economy and a lot of
new disposable wealth,'' said Steve Thompson, senior vice president
of the Trust for Public Land, another nonprofit organization that
works to preserve national park lands and forests.
</P>
<P>
   ``With population pressures and beautiful places disappearing,
people of means are saying, `I'll get my little corner of
Paradise,' and they do what they want with it,'' Thompson said.
``They have the legal right to do it. But it's sad that resources
that are so spectacular, so beautiful would not be made available
to a broader audience, only to a limited group.''
</P>
<P>
   And with land prices soaring in areas within some of the
country's more popular parks and forests, the federal government
and nonprofit agencies that buy land for preservation may be unable
to compete with private investors. Paul Pritchard, president of the
National Park Trust, predicted, ``In five or 10 years, we'll be
priced out of the market in high-demand parks.''
</P>
<P>
   The private ownership rights were honored when Congress began
designating national parks and forests in the 1890s, and through
recent years most of the land owners have either kept their tracts
in a natural state or sold them to the federal government for
preservation.
</P>
<P>
   But in the San Juan forest, and with growing frequency
elsewhere, owners of ``inholdings,'' as they are known to the
federal government, are developing acreage for commercial gain,
setting off intense fights with preservation groups and community
organizations concerned that development could damage the ecology
by disturbing wildlife and scarring landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has become a major concern,'' Interior Secretary Bruce
Babbitt said of private development inside federally owned lands.
``We need the resources to buy them out before problems start, and
there are willing sellers for most of them. But we don't have the
money, so the willing seller decides to sell on the open commercial
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Each year, the major federal land management agencies _ the
National Forest Service, the National Park Service, the Bureau of
Fish and Wildlife and the Bureau of Land Management _ provide
Congress with a list of privately held property they want to buy.
</P>
<P>
   The park service list alone has a backlog of 10,184 private
tracts in 145 parks _ more than 1 million acres in all _ that
officials say would cost the government $1.35 billion to buy for
preservation. The National Park Trust estimates that 20 percent of
the privately held land within national parks and forests is ``in
imminent danger'' of development.
</P>
<P>
   But Congress never appropriates enough money to satisfy all the
needs, so which properties are bought depends on the threat of
development, the willingness of the owner to sell and the price.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Babbitt said, the four agencies have received a
combined $300 million to $400 million annually for the acquisition
of private land. As a result, conflicts are brewing throughout the
country as more developers build on their land inside national
parks and forests and market it for profit.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the Maryland suburbs outside Washington, the National Park
Service is trying to buy 88 acres within the Monocacy National
Battlefield, a major Civil War site, to prevent any development of
housing subdivisions and shopping centers.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of 11,000 acres within the Bitterroot National Forest
in western Montana resisted efforts to sell the land to the federal
government and, instead, sold recently to a company headed by Craig
Barrett, chief executive of Intel Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett said that his group did not intend to develop the land.
But preservationists are skeptical and they complain that because
the acreage is a patchwork of about 14 separate tracts, the private
ownership makes it difficult for the federal government to manage
the public lands around them.
</P>
<P>
   In the Denali National Park and Preserve in Alaska, developers
are planning to turn an old 20-acre mining site into a remote lodge
with 30 lodges. For access, which the federal government is
required to provide, the developers are asking the park service to
improve a 10-mile road through park land that would cross a valley
creek 27 times. Park officials fear that the improvement will
encourage other land holders to develop sites near the road.
</P>
<P>
   Gettysburg National Military park in south-central Pennsylvania
includes three privately held tracts, and park officials say that
proposed commercial development would destroy the integrity of one
of the most sacred battle sites of the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Cattle grazing on 532 acres of private land around the Golden
Spike National Historic Site in Utah, where rails from the east and
west linked for the first time in 1869, is speeding up erosion, a
process that officials say can be reversed only by buying the land.
</P>
<P>
   Population growth in Arizona, one of the fastest-growing states
in the country, is threatening the Saguaro National Park, where the
saguaro cactus has been known to grow as high as 50 feet and weigh
as much as 8 tons. But in recent years, encroaching development has
affected the cactus, and the park service wants to buy 250
surrounding acres as protection.
</P>
<P>
   Those fights are similar to the conflict here. Dan McCarthy, a
Chicago businessman and majority owner of the San Juan property,
once considered building a large ski resort on the land but said he
was persuaded by members of his family to abandon the plan because
of the potential impact of the traffic and people. More recently,
the 81-year-old McCarthy agreed to sell the tract to developers
whose idea for a country-club-like project more suited his
sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely sensitive to the environment,'' he said in an
interview. ``And I am concerned about what happens to the East Fork
after I die, whose hands it might be in. My kids like it the way it
is, but someone might come along and they might feel like selling.
I think this is the best practical answer.''
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of people disagree with him. While recognizing
that as a property owner, McCarthy can do whatever he wants with
his tract, a coalition of environmental groups, Friends of the East
Fork Valley, and residents of Pagosa Springs, the nearest town,
have vowed to fight the project as inappropriate for the site.
</P>
<P>
   They contend that the lavish resort would disrupt elk migration
routes, threaten lynx, deer and other wildlife and destroy
landscape that remains as it was when wagon trains rolled westward
across the same access road that would serve the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep thinking that every time you develop something,
wildlife can go over the next hill into the next valley,'' said
Mark Pearson, chairman of the Sierra Club's National Wildlands
Committee. ``Well, this is the last next valley. There is no other
place wildlife can go.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearson is helping lead a campaign to stop, or at least delay,
the Piano Ranch project by challenging developers as they seek
permits from federal, state and local governments for necessities
like road improvements, electric lines and sewage operations.
Opponents also say they intend to appeal any appy the Forest
Service, which is required for construction to begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a cancer in the heart of a national area,'' said Betty
Feazel, 83, who has lived on an 800-acre ranch at the foot of the
access road to the Piano Creek site since 1922 and remains a friend
of McCarthy despite the development plans. ``I don't think he
realizes how much impact this thing is going to have. People are
going to be crawling all over the whole area.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jo Bridges, a district ranger for the San Juan National
Forest, said that unless an environmental-impact study concluded
that development of Piano Creek posed insurmountable problems to
the forest, she would approve the project, as the first level of
review, and ``development will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearson said that opponents of the development would appeal her
approval to the Forest Service regional office and, if necessary,
to headquarters in Washington. Beyond that, either side could
appeal to the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Sanders, chairman of the development company that is
buying the land from McCarthy, said in an interview that if Pearson
and others would only listen, they might be convinced that the
impact of the project on the area would be small and certainly less
than the ski resort once under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said he thought the opponents' public campaign had been
disingenuous, filled with half-truths and overstatements to attract
more allies. He cited as an example assertions that the project
would cover all 2,780 acres of the rectangle. That was wrong, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's not easy to believe a developer, that I could have
good intentions,'' he said, pointing out that he could just as
easily have built residential subdivisions. ``But I am trying to
protect the environment. I'm attracted to this area for the same
reasons other people are. Environmentalists want to see the land
remain pristine, and so do our members.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
