<HEADLINE>
CANADIAN REGULATORS FILE COMPLAINT AGAINST YBM MAGNEX AND ITS
OFFICERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By TIMOTHY PRITCHARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Canada's top securities regulator filed a complaint
Monday against YBM Magnex International and its senior managers and
directors, including former Premier David Peterson of Ontario,
accusing them of failing to disclose negative information about the
industrial magnet maker's business in a share offering prospectus
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Ontario Securities Commissi the company and its
underwriters did not tell investors that the auditor Deloitte &AMP;
Touche had refused to sign YBM's 1997 accounts or undertake further
work until ``an in-depth forensic investigation'' had been
completed.
</P>
<P>
   The securities commission approved the prospectus after
discussions with company officials, despite concerns expressed by
the Royal Canadian Mounted Police about YBM's links to Russian
organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, YBM shares were listed on the Toronto Stock
Exchange and included in the TSE 300 index, but the company had no
Canadian operations. Its head office was in Pennsylvania, its
principal shareholding was in the Channel Islands, its
manufacturing plant was in Hungary and almost half its sales were
in Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The securities commission said it had initiated proceedings
against Harry Antes, YBM's chairman; Jacob Bogatin, president and
chief executive; Daniel Gatti, vice president of finance, as well
as Peterson and another independent director. Peterson was premier
of Ontario from 1985 to 1990. Also named by the securities
commission were First Marathon Securities and Griffiths McBurney &AMP;
Partners, two Toronto-based securities firms that underwrote YBM's
stock issue.
</P>
<P>
   The securities commission will seek a permanent order to end
trading in YBM shares, which are now temporarily banned from
trading.
</P>
<P>
   In June, YBM pleaded guilty to one count of conspiring to commit
mail fraud and securities fraud in the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
