<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTON-HOUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAPPAQUA PASSES A NEW LAW AS IT GETS READY TO WELCOME THE
CLINTONS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DEBRA WEST   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. _ President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton
closed on their $1.7 million house here Monday without attending
the closing, but their presence was felt in the neighborhood long
before they signed the papers and wrote the checks.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday, the Town Board of New Castle, which includes the
hamlet of Chappaqua, passed a law requiring that protesters get a
permit before demonstrating along its quiet woodsy roads. Last
month, officials from the Secret Service and the Federal Aviation
Administration met to discuss increasing the altitude at which
planes must fly over the Clintons' new house, which is under the
landing path to the busy Westchester County Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have to put up with the demonstrations but we won't
have the noise from the planes,'' said Clinton B. Smith, the New
Castle town supervisor. ``So I guess we'll take the good with the
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons' lawyers handled the details of the closing Monday
at the Manhattan law firm Battle Fowler. The loan, for $1.36
million, is a 30-year adjustable-rate mortgage, starting with an
annual interest rate of 7.5 percent for three years, said Jim
Kennedy, a White House spokesman. The loan, from the PNC Mortgage,
a subsidiary of PNC Bank Corp. of Pittsburgh, allowed the Clintons
to call off a much-criticized arrangement with a Democratic Party
fund-raiser, Terry McAuliffe, who had guaranteed an earlier loan
with $1.35 million of his money as collateral.
</P>
<P>
   In the new mortgage, the Clintons put up a 20 percent down
payment, or $340,000. Neither of the Clintons attended the closing,
and they made no announcement on when they planned to move in.
</P>
<P>
   But owning property does not necessarily a New Yorker make.
</P>
<P>
   Though she now officially owns about an acre in New York state,
Mrs. Clinton was not considered a New Yorker by 69 percent of the
people questioned between Oct. 23 and Oct. 28 for a New York
Times/CBS poll, and 43 percent thought she could not effectively
represent New York in the Senate without having lived here for many
years.
</P>
<P>
   But to some people in Chappaqua, however, the newcomers already
seem like a lingering headache.
</P>
<P>
   For months, the New Castle Town Board has considered creating a
law to regulate an onslaught of demonstrations they expect the
Clintons' presence to invite. The board began considering the law
in September after a small group of demonstrators marched in front
of the house, a white clapboard colonial on Old House Lane, to
protest mass killings in East Timor. The Clintons had not moved in
and the couple they bought the house from had not moved out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to know what's coming,'' Smith said of the need for
the new law, which requires organizers of demonstrations and
parades of more than 10 people to apply for a permit at least a
week in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make sure we don't have overlapping demonstrations.
Otherwise it could overwhelm the police and disrupt traffic.
Besides, if I'm a protester holding a sit-down demonstration in the
middle of Route 117, I'm going to hope that somebody's around the
bend telling cars to slow down.''
</P>
<P>
   When most people buy a house, they have to consider the impact
that a nearby airport might have on their lives. In the Clintons'
case, the airport has to worry. The house is about a mile from the
landing beacon that pilots follow to approach the Westchester
County Airport in bad weather. Depending on the altitude
requirement, the Clintons' presence could have a significant
impact, said Berl Brechner, president of the Westchester Aviation
Association, which represents 170 corporate and private plane
owners who use the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The Westchester County Airport handles 200,000 annual takeoffs
and landings and a million passengers a year on commercial
airlines, corporate jets and privately owned planes, Brechner said.
To land safely on Runway 16, which 90 percent of the planes use,
pilots have to fly about 2,000 feet above sea level or, because of
Chappaqua's hilly terrain, about 1,500 feet above the Clintons'
house, Brechner estimated. Any restriction requiring pilots to fly
higher would mean the approach to the airport would have to be
changed. Such a change would carry the risk of a plane's
encountering dangerous tailwinds, Brechner said.
</P>
<P>
   James Peters, a spokesman for the FAA, said the Secret Service
had not yet requested that the FAA study the potential impact a
flight restriction in the area. Given that the Clintons now own the
house, the Secret Service is expected to make that request shortly.
</P>
</TEXT>
