</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CATHOLIC-LEAGUE-860&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC LEAGUE CHIEF OFFENDS SOME BUT GETS RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WINNIE HU   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ William Donohue refuses to lunch with the rich and
powerful even though, he says, they come courting. He hardly ever
takes phone calls _ unless, of course, they are from people like
Cardinal John O'Connor _ and he never lets anyone tell him what to
do.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not so easy for others to dismiss Donohue, the
outspoken president of the Catholic League for Religious and Civil
Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue's scathing attacks on the blasphemous and the irreverent
in movies, magazines and art exhibitions have transformed his group
into one of the most visible defenders of the Roman Catholic
Church. The Catholic League, which is not officially part of the
church, gets $2.7 million a year in donations but its tactics have
drawn the ire of artists, community leaders and even some
Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday, Donohue spent $34,500 for a full-page ad in The
New York Times that assailed Vanity Fair and its publisher, Conde
Nast, for three stories that he said tried to discredit O'Connor,
Mother Teresa and Pope Pius XII. The headline trumpeted: ``Conde
Nast has a Problem with Catholicism.''
</P>
<P>
   Catholic League members also handed out ``vomit bags'' outside
the Brooklyn Museum of Art to protest the Oct. 2 opening of
``Sensation,'' which features a painting of the Virgin Mary adorned
with elephant dung. Donohue dispatched a flurry of letters urging
New York City Council members to cut off public funding. He called
on Catholic schoolteachers to boycott the museum for a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like the Marines who go in and clear the forest,''
Donohue said as he plunged a fork into the macaroni salad that he
had for lunch on Thursday in his rented office in the archdiocese
headquarters in Manhattan. He was eating at his desk, alone as
usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church has something to say,'' he said. ``People can agree
or disagree, but I would hope when they disagree, they can do it
respectfully. There's a cacophony of catcalls stopping that message
from getting out at the moment, and what I want to do is give it a
fair hearing _ and then walk away.''
</P>
<P>
   But others say the Catholic League _ whose symbol is a shield
and sword _ only worsens the din.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. James Martin, a Jesuit priest and associate editor of
America, a national Catholic magazine, said he disagreed as often
as he agreed with the Catholic League. He called the group a
``double-edged sword'' because of its eagerness to plunge into one
fray after another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often their criticism is right on target, but frequently they
speak without seeing or experiencing what they are critiquing, and
that undercuts their credibility,'' he said. ``Unfortunately, that
type of response gives people the idea that the Catholic Church is
unreflective.''
</P>
<P>
   Donohue, 52, a former sociology professor who lives in Mineola,
took over the 11,000-member Catholic League in 1993 and
reinvigorated it with his personal blend of religious pragmatism
and media savvy. Although he supports the church's teachings on
life-and-death issues like abortion and the death penalty, he
steers clear of divisive debates on theological doctrines and
secular politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not at all like the Christian Coalition, which, let's
face it, is the Christian arm of the Republican Party,'' said
Donohue, who is an independent voter. ``I don't care about the
Republicans, and I don't care about the Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Catholic League has grown to an estimated 350,000
members (Donohue multiplies the number of households that donate
money by 1.5 to include spouses and other family members).
</P>
<P>
   But he counts no Hyannisport Kennedys among them. He said Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani had never written the organization a check. And
the one time Donohue met with Peter Vallone, the City Council
speaker, was outside Yankee Stadium; Donohue introduced himself and
told Vallone he was wrong on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Donohue's support comes from rank-and-file Catholics
like Jodie Thompson, a real estate developer in Dallas, who has
given $50,000 in the last two years, making him the league's
biggest donor. ``I think a lot of Catholics are fed up with attacks
on Catholicism and Christianity, too,'' Thompson said. ``There
aren't attacks on Jews, Buddhists or Hindus. If someone attacks
other faiths, they would be severely criticized.''
</P>
<P>
   Donohue fans this simmering anger with inflammatory news
releases, a Web site and a newsletter, The Catalyst, which condemn
everything from Miramax movies to tasteless jokes about nuns. Every
other month, he requests donations for a large ad or some other
project. He writes personal notes to those who give more than $250.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic League receives no money from the church, but it
maintains close ties to the leadership. Several bishops make
personal donations. O'Connor spoke at the group's 25th-anniversary
reception in 1998 and vacated part of his suite for its expanding
operations, said Joseph Zwilling, a spokesman for the Archdiocese
of New York.
</P>
<P>
   But Donohue denies that he does O'Connor's bidding. ``I swear on
the Bible,'' he said. ``We are not a front group for the cardinal.
Nobody calls the shots here.''
</P>
<P>
   No one, that is, but Donohue.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He leads the crusade against anti-Catholicism from his tidy
corner office lined with religious awards and pictures of Christ,
the Virgin Mary and various saints. Unexpectedly, there is also a
silver-framed photo of Donohue with Norman Siegel, executive
director of the New York Civil Liberties Union, at a recent news
conference. ``People are surprised that Norm and I are friends,''
he said. ``You know why I like him? Because he's a straight
shooter.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Siegel said that he has come to respect Donohue's
aggressive leadership of the Catholic League _ and to view him as a
formidable opponent. He described Donohue as a ``populist'' who
frequently takes extreme ``bunker-type positions'' to appeal to
religious conservatives. ``He's a bright, well-read individual, but
he wants to be a kind of intellectual Archie Bunker,'' Siegel said.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue concedes that his tactics can be, well, uncharitable,
but he points to the results. When he calls for a protest or
boycott, he commands attention. ``My predecessors in the Catholic
League were losers who always took the softest approach possible,
and we saw where it got them,'' he said. ``I'm saying I want
results and fast results.''
</P>
</TEXT>
