<SLUG> BC-GORE-BLACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADING BLACK NEW YORKERS MEET PRIVATELY WITH GORE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two months after Bill Bradley delivered a speech on
race relations at a public hall in Harlem, Vice President Al Gore
met privately Monday with two dozen prominent black New Yorkers,
some of whom urged him to begin campaigning in black communities
across the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is obvious that he was dealt with on this,'' the
Rev. Al Sharpton, who was host to Bradley at the Harlem speech in
late August, said of the meeting with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly brought that up,'' Sharpton said. ``And we
certainly expect that he will do what his opponent has done _ and
what Bush has done.'' Sharpton was referring to a visit by Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas to a public school in Harlem since he began
his run for the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The session with Gore lasted just under an hour and was attended
by a cross-section of black New York religious and political
figures, including H. Carl McCall, the state comptroller; State
Assemblyman Clarence Norman, the Brooklyn Democratic leader, and
former Mayor David N. Dinkins.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's appearance was at the headquarters of Sharpton's
National Action Network, just off 125th Street, Gore's at the
elegant apartment of the lawyer Victor A. Kovner on a quiet block
on the Upper West Side.
</P>
<P>
   Gore did not stop to discuss the meeting with reporters
afterward, jumping into his limousine with a wave and heading off
for a dinner party arranged by Tina Brown, the editor of Talk
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was the latest in a number of private sessions Gore
has arranged to shore up his standing with essential segments of an
electorate that will determine the Democratic presidential
nomination. The meetings are taking place at a time when many
Democrats believe that the vice president is facing a particularly
fierce challenge in the New York primary by Bradley, former senator
from New Jersey and a onetime player for the New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times/CBS News poll conducted from Oct. 23 to Oct. 28
found that among registered New York Democrats, 42 percent said
they would prefer to see Gore as their party's nominee, compared
with 37 percent for Bradley. But that difference was within the
poll's margin of sampling error.
</P>
<P>
   McCall, the state's highest-ranking black official, said Gore
had called him and asked him to arrange the meeting that took place
Monday. McCall, who is supporting Gore, said the session had not
been arranged in response to Bradley's visit to Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a reaction to what anyone else has done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to Bradley's approach to his appearance in Harlem, Gore
did not seem to want public attention drawn to his meeting.
Although his aides alerted reporters to some events on the vice
president's schedule _ including a taping at ABC News _ they did
not mention the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But Kovner's apartment is across the street from the entrance to
ABC, and reporters who had gathered there in hopes of questioning
the vice president took note of the appearance of first Sharpton
and then Dinkins. Gore's aides and Secret Service agents kept
newspaper photographers across the street.
</P>
<P>
   Both Dinkins and McCall praised the vice president's
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the usual kind of issues _ a lot of concern about
education and the homeless,'' Dinkins said. ``The vice president
was forthright, responsive and tremendously articulate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
