<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6015 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-NYT &LR;      11-01 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE POLITICS OF IMPERFECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Nov. 2:
</P>
<P>
   Life would be simple for presidential candidates if they did not
have advisers. Vice President Gore is the latest to discover this,
thanks to the amusing report in Time magazine that he is being
urged to quit behaving like a ``beta male,'' to wear earth-toned
suits and to look for opportunities to bash President Clinton,
whose alpha maleness Gore has to conquer. It is, as we have been
saying, going to be a great campaign year.
</P>
<P>
   The above advice was urged on Gore by Naomi Wolf, the feminist
author who made her mark on the 1996 campaign by advising Clinton
to reshape his political persona into that of the reliable father.
No doubt he wishes he had listened. Her advice to Gore seems pretty
reasonable, except for the earth tones. It is a rule of American
politics that Ronald Reagan was the only president who could get
away with brown suits.
</P>
<P>
   But the real significance of this little flap is that of a
mileage marker in the campaign. We are entering that stage of the
contest when candidates' organizations, their histories and their
personalities start generating news. This happens because everyone
takes a closer look when the field is winnowed to a serious
handful, and the body politic and the press discover yet again that
each contender has his foibles.
</P>
<P>
   Gore may be lucky in taking his lumps early, for the spotlight
will swing to each candidate. Former Sen. Bill Bradley, praised
today for his Zen-like calm, will be examined tomorrow for signs of
remoteness.
</P>
<P>
   The testing process is already moving along smartly on the
Republican side, where the curiosity about Gov. George W. Bush's
alleged drug use ebbs and flows, but never quite disappears. Now
Sen. John McCain is threatening Bush's front-runner status in New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the subject of McCain's temper has been explored in a
recent New York Times article, which was cited in turn in a tough
editorial in The Arizona Republic. The editorial dismissed as
``hogwash'' McCain's contention that he does not fly off the
handle. Like Jimmy Carter and Bill Clinton before him, McCain may
discover that dark-horse candidates from smaller states find it
especially hard to convince their old neighbors that they are ready
for the big time.
</P>
<P>
   There is a natural tendency in each momentarily besieged
candidate to think that his or her opponents are getting a free
ride. But over time, just about everyone gets a chance to deal with
a campaign crisis. The responses help the public to measure the
guts and intelligence of the candidate and his staff.
</P>
<P>
   It is an imperfect process, to be sure. In 1996, for example,
campaign combat exposed the deep strain of sourness and pessimism
in Bob Dole's personality. But the skills at crisis management
demonstrated by Bill Clinton in his 1992 campaign did not transfer
into a disciplined performance in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Only one recent president has slipped through his campaigns and
the White House without revealing deep truths about himself. Ronald
Reagan was surrounded by aides who liked to maintain an air of
mystery about how much he knew and how engaged he was with his job.
The mystery endures to this day, and on the evidence of ``Dutch,''
it confounded even Reagan's official biographer, Edmund Morris.
</P>
<P>
   That alone should remind us not to look away from the messy or
silly moments on the campaign trail. Most candidates are not as
successfully opaque as Reagan, and in the hundreds of small
decisions that must be made between Iowa and the inauguration _
decisions as diverse as suit color and how to finance health care _
they reveal themselves. If the electorate is lucky, the winner
gathers the strength demanded by the office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
