<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: PROTESTS FALL OFF
</P>
<P>
   With the police patrolling Tiananmen Square in ever larger
numbers, fewer members of the banned Falun Gong spiritual movement
tried to protest, and witnesses reported seeing only a handful
detained. Fugitive group members vowed to carry on their campaign
to reverse the condemnation, but the government restated its intent
to root out and imprison leaders of what it called a ``malignant
tumor'' in society.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: ACTIVIST ON TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   A prominent democracy advocate had a two-hour trial in Beijing
on charges of conspiracy to subvert the government. His sentence
was not announced but a guilty verdict is certain for Jiang
Qisheng, who was previously imprisoned for two years after 1989,
when he was a key student leader, and has since made public calls
for democracy and commemorations for those killed in the June 1989
crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: TALKS IN NINTH WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. George Mitchell's mission to rescue the stalemated
peace agreement entered its ninth week with rival political parties
continuing negotiations but with no sure prospect of a
breakthrough. Progress remained deadlocked over the refusal of the
Ulster Unionists, the province's largest party, to share power with
Sinn Fein, the political wing of the IRA, in the absence of
disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA: SHEVARDNADZE SUCCESSFUL
</P>
<P>
   A pro-Western party headed by President Eduard Shevardnadze
finished first in a parliamentary election on Sunday. The
opposition charged vote-rigging, but Shevardnadze called the result
``a universal victory for all of our nation.'' It appeared to
improve his chances for re-election next year.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   URUGUAY: INCONCLUSIVE VOTE
</P>
<P>
   Tabare Vazquez, candidate of a leftist coalition that includes
former Tupamaro guerrillas, fell far short of the 50 percent vote
he needed to avert a second-round runoff in presidential elections
on Sunday. Vazquez will face Jorge Batlle of the ruling center-left
Colorado Party on Nov. 28. After winning 31.3 percent in the
first-round vote, Batlle must now run in a coalition with the
center-right National Party to avert a Vazquez victory.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: TIES TO BRITAIN IMPROVE
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that Buenos Aires and London continue to improve
relations, the British and Argentine navies began their first joint
exercise since the two countries went to war in 1982 over control
of the Falkland Islands. The four-day exercise is a search and
rescue operation after the hypothetical sinking of a fishing
trawler 260 miles southeast of the Falkland archipelago, which the
Argentines call the Malvinas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
