<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6019 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CHASE-MARKETPLACE-NYT     11-01 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHASE-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHASE REDUCES REVENUE AND FIRES TRADER FOR BOOKING NONEXISTENT
PROFITS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK MCGEEHAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Chase Manhattan Corp., the nation's third-largest
bank, said Monday that its fourth-quarter trading revenue would be
reduced by $60 million after the bank found it had booked
nonexistent trading profits. The bank has dismissed a currency
trader involved in the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Bank officials declined to identify the trader or to say why he
was fired. But people inside the bank said that a senior currency
trader named Christopher Goggins was dismissed last week after an
internal audit found that he had been exploiting a flaw in the
bank's trading systems to record gains on long-term trades that the
bank could not realize.
</P>
<P>
   They said the bank had not determined whether the breach was
deliberate or inadvertent. Traders are usually compensated based on
their annual trading performance.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who answered the phone at Goggins' home in New Jersey
said he was no longer employed at Chase. Goggins did not respond to
messages left at the home.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Chase said that no money was embezzled from the
bank and that no customer funds were affected. Chase also noted
that the $60 million cut in fourth-quarter revenue was barely
significant to a bank with trading revenue of $2.2 billion in the
first nine months of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, this is something that they're embarrassed about and
should be embarrassed about,'' said Lawrence Cohn, director of
research at Ryan, Beck &AMP; Co. in Livingston, N.J. ``It's a breakdown
in their internal control mechanisms.''
</P>
<P>
   The reversal of the paper gains will reduce the bank's net
income this quarter by about 5 cents a share, analysts said.
Chase's stock dropped $3.6875 a share Monday, or 4 percent, to
$83.5625 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   According to people inside Chase, the trader had taken advantage
of slight discrepancies in the bank's pricing of currency and
interest-rate contracts for about a year. The trades involved
currency forwards, or contracts to buy or sell currencies at a
predetermined price on a future date. To limit risk, such trades
typically involve the simultaneous purchase of one contract and
sale of another.
</P>
<P>
   These people said the trader was inflating the paper profits on
his trades by using inappropriate methods to measure their value.
The small differences in those pricing methods added up as the size
of the positions grew larger through the year, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was picking and choosing from two different cash streams on
the same contracts to make it look like profits were being made
that really weren't,'' one Chase executive said.
</P>
<P>
   Chase officials declined to say whether the bank planned to take
legal action against the trader.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who were briefed on the matter by a Chase executive
said they were persuaded that the bank had rooted out the problem
and repaired the flaw in its systems that allowed it to occur.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn said that as he heard about the problem, he was reminded of
Joseph Jett, a one-time star trader at Kidder, Peabody, the
now-defunct securities firm. Jett was dismissed from Kidder after
he was said to have exploited flaws in Kidder's risk-management
systems to book huge gains on trades that the firm never realized.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, an arbitration panel rejected Kidder's case seeking
$82.8 million in fraud claims from Jett, though it withheld
millions of dollars of his deferred compensation. Last year, Jett
was found guilty of false record-keeping, ordered to repay $8.2
million of bonuses, fined $200,000 and barred from the securities
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts played down the Chase incident, calling it so
minor that it would never have been noticed had the bank not
disclosed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sort of thing _ traders getting beyond their scope _
happens occasionally,'' Diane Glossman, an analyst at Lehman
Brothers, said. ``In all of the cases where it has happened to an
American bank, they've proven to be isolated cases rather than an
indication of faulty oversight.''
</P>
<P>
   Chemical Bank, one of the banks that merged to form Chase, had a
big loss from one person's trades in 1994. Victor Gomez, a currency
trader, lost $66 million in what his supervisors called
unauthorized trading of contracts on the Mexican peso. Gomez was
sentenced in 1997 to 37 months in jail for conspiring to defraud
the bank by falsifying records.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something like this happens to them every five years, with
as much currency trading as Chase does around the world,'' Ms.
Glossman said, ``that would indicate that their controls are pretty
good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 2319EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
