<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6021 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-PAYTON-COLUMN-COX     11-01 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PAYTON-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An epitome of overachievement
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There was something unusual about Walter Payton beyond
his ability to zig when defenders zagged. He wasn't O.J. Simpson.
He wasn't Jim Brown. He wasn't even Red Grange, Bronko Nagurski or
Gale Sayers, those other greats for the Chicago Bears who rushed
for fewer yards than Payton but caused more tingling at the
mentioning of their names.
</P>
<P>
   Payton was just Payton, and Payton was a 5-foot-10, 202-pound
miracle. Somehow, despite spending most of his 13 NFL years behind
invisible offensive lines, he became the league's all-time leading
rusher. He had two Most Valuable Player awards to complement his
nine Pro Bowl trips.
</P>
<P>
   Still, except for those who really knew the deal, Payton zagged
when others with such credentials zigged in the game of throwing
your legend around without saying a word.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just knew so much about him. That was the problem,'' said
Jeff Van Note, the former Falcons center, who retired a year before
Payton after the 1986 season. ``If you ask any player in the
league, they knew about his incredible workout regiment. That's all
I used to hear, about how he used to run these hills back in
Mississippi. You didn't think about him as having any sort of a
presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Note was referring to the Payton outside of his No. 34
jersey. As that miracle, nobody played harder. Nobody played wiser.
Nobody inspired so many around him to do both, and this was before
and after the Bears' renaissance under Mike Ditka. From Payton's
rookie season of 1975 through the early 1980s, the Bears were bad.
They were really bad, and except for those who really knew the
deal, they'd have been worse if not for Payton's desire to remain
that miracle each game no matter.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the culmination of the Bears' renaissance in 1985,
when they surged to a world championship. Although Payton was named
the NFL's MVP, he quickly became a footnote for historians because
of a Chicago defense that evolved into one for the ages. ``But,''
Ditka said, ``we wouldn't have won the Super Bowl without Walter
Payton. There were guys who ran with the ball better, faster. But I
don't think anyone ever ran with more determination than Walter.''
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Falcons free safety Eugene Robinson, a Payton fan as a
youth in Hartford, Conn. But business is business. In 1987, before
Robinson's Seahawks met Payton's Bears, Robinson developed a
strategy to handle the blistering forearm Payton used to shock
defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, OK, I know he's going to punch me in the face with
that forearm, so I'm going to grab his wrist and push down his
punch arm and kind of clothesline him on the sideline,'' Robinson
said, laughing. Robinson laughed some more, while recalling how he
nearly cried back then after he was surrounded by a bunch of
growling Bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Singletary. Richard Dent. Wilber Marshall. All those
dudes ran after me, saying, `Man, what's wrong with you? I better
not ever catch you doing that again to Walter,''' Robinson said.
``I told them it was legal, but I sort of moved out of their way,
saying, `My bad.'''
</P>
<P>
   Payton said nothing. Payton rarely did. Payton just let his legs
do his talking.
</P>
<P>
   The miracle died Monday, and he was 45. For those who really
knew the deal, the miracle will live forever.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Moore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
