<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jaguars looking at offensive line moves
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Jacksonville Jaguars might have to make at least one change
to their highly regarded offensive line when they face the Falcons
Sunday in the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Starting right guard Rich Tylski fractured his right foot in
last week's 41-10 victory over Cincinnati. He'll be out at least
four to six weeks. Also, Pro-Bowl left tackle Tony Boselli was
wearing a stabilizing boot for a sprained right ankle in the locker
room on Monday. Boselli's status is listed as day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only Monday,'' said Boselli, who forms the league's best
tackle tandem with Leon Searcy. ``There's no reason to start
speculating about what's going to happen. We still have a couple of
days. Hopefully, it will respond well.''
</P>
<P>
   Zach Wiegert will probably move into Tylski's spot. If Boselli
can't play, starting left guard Ben Coleman could move outside,
with Quentin Neujahr taking Coleman's place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't made a decision on how that will go,'' coach Tom
Coughlin said. ``There are some options, some flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the Jaguars' playmakers on offense also are battling
injuries. Quarterback Mark Brunell started against the Bengals,
completing 11 of 19 passes for 145 yards and two touchdowns, but he
aggravated a rib injury and didn't return after halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Brunell was injured in practice before an Oct. 17 game against
Cleveland. He says he felt about 80 to 90 percent against the
Bengals and could have played in the second half if needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were up enough where we could rest it a little bit,''
Brunell said. ``It was a smart thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, running back Fred Taylor, a second-year pro from
Florida, also sat out most of the second half. Taylor rushed for
128 yards on 15 carries against Cincinnati, after missing the
previous three games with a hamstring injury.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said he left after playing just over two quarters because
of leg cramps. Veteran James Stewart rushed for 32 yards and two
touchdowns in Taylor's absence against the Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until I'm able to play 60 minutes, I'm not quite back to my
old self yet,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are coming off their best defensive game of the
season. Atlanta sacked Carolina quarterback Steve Beurelein six
times in last week's 27-20 win. Defensive end Chuck Smith had three
of them and caused a fumble, which defensive tackle Shane Dronett
returned to the Panthers' five-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Smith sidelined
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Akili Smith, the third overall pick in this year's
draft by the Bengals, will miss as many as three games after
hurting the big toe on his right foot during the loss to the
Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who missed most of training camp because of a contract
dispute, was sacked four times during the first half in
Jacksonville. A magnetic resonance imaging test Monday found no
major injury, but the foot was badly swollen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said it will be two or three weeks before I even start
running,'' Smith said. ``It's depressing, it really is, but this
kind of stuff happens in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Blake, who opened the season as the Bengals' starter, will
replace Smith against Seattle Sunday. Blake completed 13 of 23
passes for 155 yards against the Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   Blake and other Bengals players believe the injury might be the
best thing for the former Oregon star.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go out and play against a defense (such as Jacksonville's)
with no training camp, it's tough for him,'' Blake said of Smith.
``He's struggling. I feel bad for him. He has no chance at all,
none whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last three games, Smith was sacked 13 times and threw
four interceptions with no touchdowns.Willie Anderson
</P>
<P>
   Said offensive tackle Willie AndersonRison supportAndre
RisonDerrick AlexanderJoe HornGunther CunninghamLonnie
JohnsonCoates wants outBen CoatesErnie ZampeseDrew Bledsoe.
</P>
