<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARATHON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN MARATHONERS IN U.S. HITTING THEIR STRIDE AT AGE 40 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MARC BLOOM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jean Chodnicki of Manhattan ran her fastest marathon,
2 hours 43 minutes, in 1980. She was 21. Now at 40 she hopes to run
close to that performance in Sunday's New York City Marathon and
join a growing number of women in their 40s in what was once
considered a young runner's pursuit: the Olympic marathon trials.
</P>
<P>
   Chodnicki, a manager in a printing plant, is part of a
phenomenon. When Joan Benoit Samuelson captured the first Olympic
marathon for women in Los Angeles in 1984, she was 27, and the
other top Americans in the burgeoning women's running movement were
in their 20s. Now 42, Samuelson is still running and, along with
midlife peers like Kim Jones and Lynn Jennings, is a contender to
make the United States Olympic marathon team for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine of the 195 women who have qualified for the women's
trial, to be held Feb. 26 in Columbia, S.C., are 40 or older or are
turning 40 in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 42, twice the runner-up at New York, whose competitive
edge has survived a year of running lost over the stress of a
divorce, said, ``I was talking with Joanie at a race and told her,
`Wouldn't it be great if you, me and Lynn Jennings all made the
Olympic team?'''
</P>
<P>
   Older women have succeeded in the marathon before _ Priscilla
Welch of England won at New York in 1987 at 42. But the tendency of
large numbers of women to sustain a running career and contend for
the Olympics is uniquely American. The five female marathoners on
the United States team at last summer's world track and field
championships in Seville, Spain, averaged 38. But most of the
world's best, like the world record-holder, Tegla Loroupe of Kenya,
a two-time New York City winner, are in their 20s or are just over
30.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for the Olympic trials, Chodnicki, who turned 40 in
June, has to run 2:50 or better, a pace of 6:28 a mile. ``I feel
fresher than ever,'' said Chodnicki, whose weekly 20-mile training
runs take her over the George Washington Bridge and back. ``As I've
gotten older, I've taken more rest days and cut my mileage. I used
to run 80 to 90 miles a week. Now I do 55 and have life in my
legs.''
</P>
<P>
   A more measured approach to the marathon shapes these women;
many of them balance careers and child-rearing with Olympic hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had two children in my 30s,'' said Marie Boyd, an
Albuquerque pathologist, who turns 40 in December and competed on
the United States team in Seville. ``My whole career has been a
juggling act. We settled in New Mexico because I found a position
in a hospital in which I work only 35 to 40 hours a week and can
fit in my training.''
</P>
<P>
   In February's trials, Boyd hopes to run under 2:35, which would
most likely put her in contention for one of the three berths on
the United States team. ``Women in their 40s understand their
bodies, make fewer training mistakes and get more out of
themselves,'' said Benji Durden, a 1980 Olympic marathoner who
coaches Boyd and Jones. ``But it's also the case that there has not
been a lot of new blood coming into the marathon.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one American, 34-year-old Libbie Hickman, who ran 2:28:34
at Chicago on Oct. 24, has broken 2:30 during the trials qualifying
period. Samuelson ran 2:24:52 to win the 1984 Olympics, and her
American record is 2:21:21 from 1985. Even with prize money readily
available, no marathon stars have succeeded her in the 1990s,
motivating older women still capable of running in the 2:30's and
2:40s to continue.
</P>
<P>
   While Samuelson, the winner in the masters division (40 and
over) at New York last year, and Jones are not running Sunday to
save themselves for the trials, Chodnicki is making her last
attempt at a qualifying spot. On Oct. 3, she ran the Twin Cities
Marathon in Minneapolis but said she ``fell asleep'' in the 18th
mile and ran 2:54. ``It only took me a week to recover,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Chodnicki, who represents the Warren Street Social and Athletic
Club of Jersey City, began running 26 years ago for Saddle Brook
High School in New Jersey. She has run more than 30 marathons but
with significant detours. After improving her best time by nine
minutes with a 2:43, achieved at New York in 1980, Chodnicki
developed anorexia and bulimia, eating disorders that plagued her
for years. ``It took a long time to heal,'' Chodnicki said. ``But
that's all gone.
</P>
<P>
   Physically fit, Chodnicki acquired mental focus from turning 40,
which has given her new life as a competitor. ``If you look at the
results of road races in New York,'' she said, ``most of the top
women are in their late 30s and into their 40s. Now I go into a
race asking, `Who are the masters?''' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
