<SLUG> BC-BELLATLANTIC-FCC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETBACK FOR BELL ATLANTIC IN DRIVE FOR LONG DISTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raising a speed bump in Bell Atlantic Corp.'s path toward
offering long-distance communications services, the Justice
Department on Monday said the company had come close to fully
opening its local networks in New York to competitors, but had not
quite made it.
</P>
<P>
   The department's comments to the Federal Communications
Commission, which is weighing whether to make Bell Atlantic the
first Bell company allowedhe long-distance market, were a
surprise to some analysts, who had expected the department to
endorse Bell Atlantic's application.
</P>
<P>
   But the department hardly rejected Bell Atlantic out of hand _
in contrast to the department's blunt dismissal of five previous
Bell applications _ and even said the commission could approve Bell
Atlantic's petition subject to conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am confident that Bell Atlantic can solve the few remaining
problems in New York, and I am pleased that they have already
started to do so,'' Joel Klein, the assistant attorney general in
charge of the antitrust division, said in a statement. ``But those
problems cannot be ignored and must be resolved if we want
consumers to receive the full benefits of competition.''
</P>
<P>
   A Bell company may enter the long-distance business on a
state-by-state business after convincing the FCC that it has opened
its local systems to competitors. But no Bell has yet passed that
test.
</P>
<P>
   The department's comments are not binding on the FCC, but the
two organizations have agreed on rejecting the past applications.
</P>
<P>
   The department's lukewarm comments were a surprise mainly
because the New York State Public Service Commission gave Bell
Atlantic its full support less than two weeks ago. The Justice
Department joined forces with the New York regulators last year in
a partnership to test the openness of Bell Atlantic's New York
network. That process delayed Bell Atlantic's long-distance
application for at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This entire New York process has in some ways been
disappointing because it's taken so long,'' James Young, Bell
Atlantic's general counsel, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Young said Bell Atlantic might be able to address the
department's concerns even before the FCC's review ends in late
December. The commission, however, has frowned on Bell companies'
amending their long-distance applications, preferring to take a
network ``snapshot'' at the time of the application in order to
avoid chasing a moving target. It is also unclear how any
conditional approval could be structured.
</P>
<P>
   But because Bell Atlantic is credited with doing more than the
other Bells to open its systems, the FCC might demonstrate some
flexibility. The commission is under political pressure to allow at
least one of the Bells into the long-distance market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 2323EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991101.0524 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-01 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6031 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-ATHLETE-DEATHS-NYT &LR;      11-01 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATHLETE-DEATHS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODEO AND AUTO RACING DEATHS CUT SHORT CAREERS OF TWO YOUNG
ATHLETES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By LENA WILLIAMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their names did not engender the public familiarity afforded
professional athletes like the golfer Payne Stewart, who died last
week in a plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Moore drove race cars for a living and the thrill of it.
Colby Goodwin supported a family by roping steers. Moore, 24, and
Goodwin, 32, were killed last week doing what they had done for
several years: Moore racing his Reynard-Mercedes at speeds up to
220 miles an hour; Goodwin lassoing 750-pound steers from atop a
horse.
</P>
<P>
   Although not yet in Stewart's vaunted realm, both Moore and
Goodwin were talented athletes on the rise in their respective
fields. Moore won five races over the last three years and finished
fifth in points last season on the CART FedEx series, one of auto
racing's toughest circuits. Goodwin finished among the top 15 steer
ropers in the country for the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin's death was only the second in National Finals history.
Brent Thurman, a bull rider, was killed in 1994. Moore was the
second driver in the CART FedEx series to die this year. Gonzalo
Rodriguez of Uruguay was killed in a crash Sept. 11. Before this
season, there have been only two driver fatalities in CART racing
(using Indianapolis-style cars) over the last 20 seasons, said Ron
Richards, vice president for communications for Championship Auto
Racing Teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go along week to week, month to month and don't have anyone
injured or killed,'' Richards said in a telephone interview from
Los Angeles, a few miles from the California Speedway in Fontana,
where the wreck occurred. ``At times, you sit back and look at it
and view it as being totally safe. This is a dangerous sport. With
cars going at 200 miles per hour, there is an element of risk. This
reinforces that.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin was critically injured Saturday when his horse tripped
on the slack portion of his rope after he had roped a steer and
fell sideways on him. The accident occurred during the National
Finals steer roping competition at the Lazy E arena in Guthrie,
Okla., with Goodwin's wife, Amy, and his parents watching from the
stands. The couple have a 10-day-old son, Gunner.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the real dangers in rodeo is traveling from rodeo to
rodeo,'' said Steve Fleming, director of communications for the
Professional Rodeo Cowboys Association, which has 11,000 members.
``Typically, we have one or two deaths per year in traffic
fatalities to and from rodeos.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleming said it is not uncommon for riders to compete on a
Saturday night and have another competition Sunday morning. Because
most riders travel with the horses, they usually drive to
competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin's traveling partner was Guy Allen, one of the most
successful steer ropers on the circuit. Allen, 41, won an
unprecedented 14th world title at the Nationals. Like Goodwin,
Allen is from Lovington, N.M., and the two ropers had formed a
close bond. Allen was the best man at Goodwin's wedding in August
1998 and became his mentor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't uncommon for a very accomplished rider to travel
with a younger guy like Goodwin and advise him on what to do and
what competitions to enter,'' Fleming said in a phone interview
from the association's headquarters in Colorado Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, who was born in Vancouver, British Columbia, was said by
his peers to embody what pro racing is all about. Single,
good-looking and fun-loving, Moore along with three of his closest
friends, Max Papis, Dario Franchitti and Tony Kanaan, were a
talented 20-something group of drivers known on the CART circuit as
the ``Brat Pack.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys had a great deal of fun,'' Richards said. ``You
have to be committed to do what these guys do week in and week out.
Greg was focused, courageous and committed. He loved racing and
going out on the track. But he also loved life away from the track,
and much of it centered around his friendship with Max, Toni and
Dario.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore almost missed Sunday's race. He broke his hand the day
before and was driving with a cast and brace approved by CART's
doctors. He wasn't cleared to drive until late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Steve Olvey, director of medical affairs for CART, said he
gave Moore the go-ahead. ``It really is not likely that the hand
injury had anything to do with this accident,'' Olvey told The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the Player's Forsythe team for the past two years,
Moore was scheduled to switch to Roger Penske's team next season.
</P>
<P>
   Services for Goodwin are scheduled for Thursday in Channing,
Texas. Memorial services were being planned for Moore. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
