<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFT, WET GRASS HURTS EUROPEAN CONTINGENT AT BREEDERS' CUP  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALLANDALE, Fla. _ Eleven of Europe's best race horses flew into
South Florida Monday for the Breeders' Cup, but, while the weather
seemed suitable for flying, racing officials were bedeviled by an
old problem: was it suitable for racing?
</P>
<P>
   The travelers found many of the 128 Breeders' Cup horses stabled
at Gulfstream Park, where the championships will be run Saturday,
and they also found the main track loaded with traffic during the
morning workouts. Bob Baffert alone had seven of his stars taking
their final dress rehearsals, including the undefeated juvenile
filly Chilukki, the great Silverbulletday and his leading candidate
for the $4 million Classic, General Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the horses were working on a dirt track labeled
fast. Most of the Europeans will run on the grass course, which has
been inundated with storm water and may not afford them much chance
of working out. The racing officials offered little assurance that
things would get better.
</P>
<P>
   The weather is a matter of huge importance to horses from
Europe. They customarily race on grass, and the weather back home
tends to be cool in autumn. But as they landed in Florida, they
were met with more of the heat and humidity that undermined their
two previous visits at Gulfstream: in 1989, when the European
horses went 0 for 11 in the Breeders' Cup, and in 1992, when they
went 0 for 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hurricane Irene dumped 18 inches on the track two weeks ago,''
said Pam Blatz-Murff, the director of racing for the Breeders' Cup.
``And since then, we've had two more inches of rain. We've had a
hard time getting on the turf course. In the 10 days that I've been
here, this morning was only the third time we'd been on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to sacrifice the turf course to workouts, not
with championship races coming up. Six horses went out at 9 o'clock
this morning. We're hoping things get better by the time the
European grass horses come out of quarantine tomorrow. But the
forecast is calling for more rain, and even a flood watch for
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The grass course was officially listed as soft when the six
horses were allowed to try it Monday morning. The grass tends to
retain water closer to the railing, so the horses are restricted to
running on the outer portion of the course. They are kept outside
by ``dogs,'' or rubber cones, placed on the ground to mark off the
restricted zones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make the decision on racing over the turf course at 4 in
the morning,'' Blatz-Murff said. ``We've been restricting the turf
course to certain hours and certain horses, mainly Breeders' Cup
starters. Today, we started at 9 and let the six horses work. But
the dogs were placed 50 feet out from the rail. The track is only
70 feet wide, so it meant the horses could use only the outside
lane or two.''
</P>
<P>
   To make the flooding worse, after Irene howled through Florida,
the infield lake at Gulfstream overflowed onto the grass course.
When the Breeders' Cup is run, three of the eight races may be
compromised _ the new $1 million Filly and Mare Turf, the $1
million Mile and the $2 million Turf. Those are the chief races the
Europeans have targeted.
</P>
<P>
   Where will all that leave grass racing on Friday, the opening
day of a gala three-day Breeders' Cup weekend?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about Friday's races yet,'' Blatz-Murff
said, sounding as though she wished the subject would go away.
``The fields are smaller, for one thing. Meanwhile, for workouts,
grass horses for Saturday will have the preference.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Baffert's dirt horses dominated the workouts Monday,
both in number and speed. The California trainer expects to enter
eight horses in six of the eight races, and he turned seven of them
loose by the dawn's early light. The eighth, River Keen, worked six
furlongs in 1:12 at Belmont Park in New York in preparation for the
Classic.
</P>
<P>
   General Challenge, who is Baffert's main horse in the Classic,
worked a snappy six furlongs at Gulfstream in 1:09 3/5, prompting
Baffert to say: ``I like to put an edge into my horses this close
to a race. This work puts him right into it. I was going to work
him tomorrow, but I kept seeing rain in the weather reports. When
the track came up in good shape this morning, I called an
audible.''
</P>
<P>
   Silverbulletday, the star filly in Baffert's barn and the
probable favorite in the $1 million Distaff, dazzled the clockers
by going five furlongs in 57 2/5 seconds. She did not like running
in the mud when she lost the Beldame to Beautiful Pleasure last
month at Belmont Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't like that surface,'' he said. ``But that's what
happens in this sport: horses beat horses. She's pitched 10 strong
innings for us this year. I just want her to give us one more
strong inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert also saw a smart workout Monday by his 2-year-old filly
Chilukki, who shot five furlongs in 59 seconds. He was thoroughly
impressed by Forest Camp, his star juvenile colt, who flew five
furlongs in 58 2/5 seconds in one of the morning's best
performances for the rich Baffert barn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
