A6040 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-WACO-EVIDENCE-COX     11-01 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-EVIDENCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Government asks for more time in Branch Davidian case
 &HT;    By Tommy Witherspoon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ For the second time in a month, the federal
government has asked U.S. District Judge Walter S. Smith Jr. of
Waco for more time to comply with his order to produce all evidence
related to events at Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence in the wrongful-death lawsuit filed by Branch
Davidian survivors against the government was due Monday. In a
motion filed then, Nina S. Pelletier, a U.S. Department of Justice
attorney, gave the judge a progress report of the government's
efforts, including some in the executive office of the president,
to comply with his discovery orders and then asked for an
additional month to complete the task.
</P>
<P>
   In August, the judge ordered, among other things, that the
government turn over all materials in the custody of any agency,
including audio and video tapes, that relate to the Branch Davidian
raid on Feb. 28, 1993, or the April 19, 1993, tear-gas assault and
fire in which David Koresh and 75 of his followers died.
</P>
<P>
   Houston attorney Mike Caddell, who represents a majority of the
plaintiffs, said he will not oppose the delay, adding that he
doesn't think it would, if granted, affect the May 15 trial date
set in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge initially ordered these documents produced in
August, and it is hard to understand how they can't get their act
together after four months,'' Caddell said. ``They should have been
doing this all along. They have organized these documents for
Congress twice now. The truth is that all this stuff has been
organized before. They make it sound like this is the first time
anybody from the government has gone through these documents.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Pelletier's notice of compliance, as of Oct. 29,
the Department of Treasury, excluding the Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms; the Department of Justice, with the exception
of the FBI; the Department of Commerce; the Department of State;
the office of Special Counsel; and the Department of Health and
Human Services had completed their searches for materials and will
produce all ``responsive, non-classified documents on or before
Nov. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   By Monday, the FBI had shipped 131 boxes of materials to the
court in Waco, including more than 100,000 pages of documents, 882
audio tapes, 121 video tapes, numerous computer disks, laptop
computers, photographs and more, the notice reports.
</P>
<P>
   Also by Monday, the ATF had shipped at least 66 boxes of
materials to the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``ATF continues to devote substantial resources to reviewing and
inventorying other materials, including computer drives and
computer diskettes, third-party documents and oversized
photographs,'' Pelletier writes.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney's office for the Western District of Texas,
which handled the criminal prosecutions of 11 Branch Davidians in
San Antonio, has submitted 111 boxes; the Department of Defense has
gathered about 30,000 pages of unclassified materials and 7,000
pages of classified documents and has forwarded about 12,000
unclassified pages to the court.
</P>
<P>
   The executive office of the president has produced documents,
too, and is in the process of completing its search of archived
e-mail messages, according to the notice. The office estimates that
it will have provided ``all responsive unprivileged material'' by
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Witherspoon writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-01-99 2331EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
