now everyday. His observation of the stages of infant development
today seem obvious to any observant parent: the oral stage,
dominated by feeding; the anal stage, with attention shifted to
endless diaper changes; and the genital stage, signalling the first
hints of sexual awareness. After the mindless destruction of World
War I seemed to deny the life force itself, Freud put forth the
idea, in ``Beyond the Pleasure Principle,'' that humans struggle
daily with two opposing forces: Eros, the life force, and Thanatos,
the death force. Whenever we talk about someone having a death
wish, Freud is there.
</P>
<P>
   He's also there when we say something sexual where a sexual
reference was not intended _ we call it a ``Freudian slip.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's there whenever his grossest generalization, the Oedipus
complex, is taken seriously. Generalizing from the results of his
own self-analysis, in which he found himself attracted to his own
mother in childhood, Freud asserted it to be true of all children,
male and female alike (which has recently found him favor in
lesbian circles). The actual story of Oedipus in Greek mythology
probably points to something far less sexually specific: that a man
is likely to follow the pattern set out for him in youth, to
attempt to duplicate the home he was raised in and to replace (to
``kill'') his father. But the myth is now so wrapped up with Freud
that it is hard to disentangle it.
</P>
<P>
   Freud's reputation crested sometime midcentury and has since
been under sustained attack. Where once Freud was a hero of popular
culture _ the 1962 Hollywood howler ``Freud'' cast Montgomery Clift
as the bearded cigar-smoker and featured the oracular tones of
director-narrator John Huston comparing Freud to Christ _ he is now
passe, a name with little resonance.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1970s, the scholarly world, too, has tended more to
Freud-bashing than to Freud hagiography. In ``The Memory Wars:
Freud's Legacy in Dispute (New York Review, 1995),'' author and
former Freudian Frederick Crews dismissed Freud as ``the discoverer
of vague general truths about human deviousness.'' E. Fuller
Torrey, in ``Freudian Fraud (Harper Collins, 1992),'' made a case
that there is no scientific basis whatsoever for Freud's theories.
</P>
<P>
   Long before either book was published, no less a figure than
Ludwig Wittgenstein, one of the century's greatest philosophers,
pointed out perhaps the single greatest flaw in Freudian theory. If
Freud had indeed discovered dark things in the unconscious, how
could he possibly prove they were things of meaning? A cause is not
a meaning. Event A may cause Behavior B without imbuing B with a
particular meaning.
</P>
<P>
   A child may learn to repress sexual urges that do not correspond
to parental expectations, but, well . . . so what? Nothing
scientific can be drawn from such an observation. An additional
element is needed, Wittgenstein observed, to give the event and its
repression meaning: the very unscientific one of mythology.
(Wittgenstein's observations about Freud, scattered throughout his
career in essays and lectures, are gathered in ``Wittgenstein Reads
Freud: The Myth of the Unconscious,'' by Jacques Bouveresse,
translated by Carol Cosman (Princeton University Press, 1995.)
</P>
<P>
   So, Freud's power depends, not on any factual, scientific
observation about humanity, but on the skills he had as a writer
and self-promoter to convince us that looking at life his way _ at
every neurosis as a repressed desire, at every dream as wish
fulfillment, etc. _ is the right way to look at it.
</P>
<P>
   Psychoanalysis is a myth without hard scientific basis.
Paradoxically, it's a myth that loses potency when stripped of its
supposed factual basis, becoming then just one possibility among
many others. Freud himself was adamant that his theories be
considered ``correct.'' In ``The Ego and the Id (1923)'' he wrote:
``The fact that in the technique of psychoanalysis a means has been
found by which the opposing force (repression) can be removed and
the ideas in question made conscious renders the theory
IRREFUTABLE.(ITAL)''
</P>
<P>
   The claim to irrefutability was part of Freud's myth.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Orpheus and Eurydice was a myth about the
exploration of the unconscious. Its moral was that knowing the dark
side of ourselves is not possible except in the symbols of art _
Orpheus' music.
</P>
<P>
   The myth of Freud was a modern version of same in which knowing
our unconscious selves in rational terms is not only possible, but
factually verifiable according to the theories of psychoanalysis.
</P>
<P>
   But what if the old myth, and not the new one, more accurately
represents the human condition? Not all myths are equal. Some got
there first because they state a truth that lies at the center of
our existence.
</P>
<P>
   If the story of Orpheus is truer than the story of Freud, then
our conscious and unconscious selves are not meant to communicate
in the way Freud wanted them to. In psychoanalysis, the language of
the conscious self dominates the unconscious; the unconscious is
invaded. The Orpheus myth would lead us rather to leave the
unconscious alone on its own terms, and content our conscious
selves with meditating on the symbols of art and spirituality that
are the universal language of the unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   In very general terms, this is what Carl Jung did. The Swiss
student of Freud trumped his teacher's belief in the unconscious by
giving the unconscious its due, developing a whole new branch of
psychology that diverged from Freud by dwelling not on repressed
sexual urges but on the meaning of symbols from the unconscious. He
let the unconscious speak in its own language.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of plumbing the darkness inside ourselves, sexual or
otherwise, may have begun to pale. The latest trend in therapy is
philosophical therapy, which is an exact denial of psychological
therapy.
</P>
<P>
   According to philosophical therapists, our duties as people are
to develop conscious discernment and leave what cannot be discerned
to dreams, art and religion. In a time when Freudian theories have
decayed to the point that respect is given to every smirking sexual
reference on daytime television talk shows, it's a refreshing
concept. &QL; 
Kenneth LaFave can be reached at (602) 444-8927 and at
ken.lafave(at)pni.com viae-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
