<SLUG> BC-BOEING-MOOD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING MOOD IS SOMBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It's a somber time for the owners and the workers of
The Boeing Co.
</P>
<P>
   Investors and workers are coping with a weekend that recorded
the tragic crash of an EgyptAir 767 airplane and an embrassing
report that the company didn't share data on fuel tank problems
with investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Investors expressed their concern by sending Boeing's stock down
3.1 percent in trading Monday, in part based on speculation that
the crash could create uncertaintity among the company's customers,
according to financial analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Those concerns were coupled with a general worry about the
fallout from a report that the company didn't share some findings
about its fuel tanks for nearly 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the events rattled investors and weighed on the minds
of Machinists as they reported for work at Boeing's Everett plant
after the eventful weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern is if there is some sort of implication that comes
back to Boeing or the manufacturing process making that aircraft
that could concern the airline customers and perhaps raise concerns
about future sales,'' said Peter Jacobs, an analyst who tracks
Boeing for the Ragen MacKenzie Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Only a day before the crash, Boeing was dealing with news
reports stating it didn't share a 1980 report on fuel tank problems
in one of its jumbo jets with federal investigators until June. The
investigators _ striving to determine what caused TWA Flight 800 to
explode in a ball of flame over Long Island in 1996 _ said the
report could have helped them.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's events also dampened the mood at lunch tables and
breakrooms at the Everett plant, where workers assembled the 767
that plunged into the Atlantic Ocean off Nantucket.
</P>
<P>
   Workers said they're always concerned when one of the airplanes
they craft is involved in an accident, according to John Scofield,
who works on the 777 airplane line at the Everett plant.
</P>
<P>
   It's ``a little somber,'' Scofield said. ``We are not happy
about it. We all fly those airplanes too.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Scofield and others say they don't expect investigators
to discover that a flaw in their craftsmanship or an oversight on
the assembly line led to Sunday morning's tragedy that appears to
have claimed 217 lives.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, employees say, they expect the National Transportation
Safety Board to discover that a mistake in maintaining the plane or
some other flaw caused the EgypytAir crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys, they take great pride in the product they build,''
said Bill Johnson, the president of International Association of
Machinists and Aerospace Workers District Lodge 751, based in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The union and Boeing are also dealing with the revelation that
the EgyptAir 767 that crashed rolled off the assembly line right
before another 767 plane, owned by Lauda Air, that crashed eight
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Employees and union leaders rejected any connection, citing the
quality of the work and the checks-and-balances built into the
airplane manufacturing system.
</P>
<P>
   News reports ``make it sound like some flaw (was) built into the
airplane, I just don't see it,'' said a Boeing employee, who works
on the 767 line and requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The two days of bad news are the latest clouds to gather over
the Seattle-based aerospace giant. Boeing has already fallen behind
rival Airbus Industrie in the fight for new airplane orders this
year. So far, Airbus has captured about 70 percent of the 1999 firm
orders.
</P>
<P>
   And only last week, El Al, Israel's state-owned airline,
announced it's planning to buy Airbus planes for the first time.
While it also announced plans to buy at least three Boeing 777
planes. Currently, the carrier has an all-Boeing fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the news coming out of Boeing is bad lately. The company
has reported a series of strong financial quarters, indicating that
its new campaign to cut costs is succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   And Chief Financial Officer Debbie Hopkins has received rave
reviews from Wall Street analysts for boosting the company's
financial performance.
</P>
<P>
   Information from Bloomberg News was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
